<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PUT 5 IN PRO BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Emmitt Smith and Erik Williams made a pledge to
each other during the off-season that they would be back _ together
_ representing the Cowboys in the 2000 Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We committed to each other: `We're going to get back \Rto the
Pro Bowl\S,' '' Smith said yesterday. ``And ... we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Williams, both voted in as reserves in the three-part
balloting of NFL players, coaches and fans (each counting
one-third), will join NFC Pro Bowl starters Larry Allen and Deion
Sanders for the Feb. 6 game in Honolulu. In all, the Cowboys had
five players selected
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker Dexter Coakley was the biggest surprise and
evoked the loudest ovation yesterday from the players gathered
around coach Chan Gailey on the field after practice when the
announcement was made.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, a third-year player/first-time Pro Bowler, goes to
Honolulu as a reserve behind New York Giants' Jessie Armstead and
Tampa Bay's Derrick Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, a restricted free agent after this season, has had a
Pro Bowl-type season, but without the Pro Bowl name recognition
that so often seems to be required in all-star selections in any
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lets me know that some effort goes into the choosing,''
Cowboys' Alonzo Spellman said, ``because Dexter definitely deserves
it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Coakley is short. He's listed at 5-foot-10, and that
probably (no pun intended) is a bit of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   When the skeptics questioned the Cowboys for drafting Coakley in
the third round out of tiny Appalachian State in 1997, Larry
Lacewell, the team's scouting guru, countered by saying, ``We're
not bringing the guy in to change light bulbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? He has done everything else this season.
</P>
<P>
   All four of Coakley's team-leading interceptions from the
weakside linebacker spot have come in national TV games, including
two against Miami's Dan Marino on Thanksgiving Day. Coakley
returned one 46 yards for a touchdown. He cleaned up on all the
NFL's major awards that week.
</P>
<P>
   His other two picks came in prime-time games against Atlanta in
September and New England this month. He ranks second on the team
to Randall Godfrey in tackles with 117 and is second to Charlie
Williams in passes defensed with nine. He also has one sack.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, never in his wildest dreams did Coakley envision himself
headed for Honolulu in six weeks
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge!'' Coakley said, ``Coming from a small school,
all through my career, you're dealing with the negatives: `He won't
be big enough. He won't be durable enough.' This is great. It
definitely came out of the blue for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a capsule summary of each of the Cowboys' other Pro
Bowlers for the 2000 game:
</P>
<P>
   Left guard Larry Allen, perennial All-Pro selection for the past
five years at guard or tackle, hasn't played since Nov. 14 when he
suffered a sprained right knee. ``I didn't think I'd make it this
year,'' said Allen, a Pro Bowl starter four years in a row. ``Not
to be out there \Rfive games\S and still make the Pro Bowl shows
the respect that the players have for me. This one means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders, who led the fan voting at both
cornerback and kick-return specialist, is headed for his eighth Pro
Bowl (fourth in five years with the Cowboys). The NFC kick-return
specialist will be Chicago's Glyn Milburn. Sanders missed the first
two games of the season (toe) and played hurt several more weeks
with hamstring and groin strains. He receives a $1.5 million bonus
by playing 70 percent of the plays ... and making the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith, with eight Pro Bowls in 10 seasons,
is fourth on the Cowboys' all-time list behind Bob Lilly (11 Pro
Bowls), Mel Renfro (10) and Randy White (9). ``I didn't expect to
make it this year, because over history the top three rushers from
each conference get in,'' said Smith, who ranks fourth among NFC
rushers with 1,165 yards and 10 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought \RPhiladelphia's\S Duce Staley (1,229 and four TDs)
would get in. To be honest, he probably should. But maybe \Rthe
voters\S took into consideration the Minnesota game.'' That night,
Smith had 140 yards rushing through the first 24 minutes before a
broken right hand forced him out of the game. Playing with a metal
plate in his hand now, Smith has missed 10 quarters this season
because of injuries, including a strained groin that shelved him
after the first play against Philadelphia two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis back Marshall Faulk of St. Louis (1,248 yards and six
touchdowns) is the NFC starter. Washington's Stephen Davis
(NFC-leading 1,405 yards and 17 TDs) and Smith will back him up.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Erik Williams, a reserve to the St. Louis Rams'
Orlando Pace and the New Orleans Saints' William Roaf, is headed
for Honolulu for the fourth time in a nine-year career. ``I thought
last year would be my comeback year, but apparently no one else saw
it that way,'' Williams said. ``This one makes me feel good because
I've struggled with my \Rright\S knee the past four or five years
since that \ROctober 1994\S car accident. But I know I deserve to
be over there this year. Nobody can tell me any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Darren Woodson, who said that he didn't have a
``Pro Bowl year,'' saw his string of consecutive trips to Hawaii
snapped at five.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of Cowboys being snubbed can be made for:
</P>
<P>
   Free safety George Teague, with two interception returns for
touchdowns, who lost out to San Francisco's Lance Schulters and
Philadelphia's Brian Dawkins;
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, who Coakley was sure would go to the Pro Bowl instead
of him, lost out to Detroit's Stephen Boyd, who will back up
perennial Pro Bowler Hardy Nickerson of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers at
middle linebacker;
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Greg Ellis, who led the Cowboys with 7 1/2 sacks
and two long-distance touchdown returns (87-yard interception and
98-yard fumble);
</P>
<P>
   Punter Toby Gowin, who lost out statistically to Minnesota's
Mitch Berger;
</P>
<P>
   Center Mark Stepnoski, who was the people's choice (along with
Woodson, Sanders and Allen) in the fan voting.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
