<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BELFOUR REMAINS AT TOP OF HIS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez realized playing
on what had quickly become a sore knee wasn't really an option not
too long into practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all he had to do was tell usual goalie Ed Belfour that he
would have to play.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe, that knee wasn't so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   But it was. So Fernandez went to Belfour, who had just played in
back-to-back games a couple of nights before, and explained the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `I'll go,''' Fernandez said. ``He's fired up. He knows
he's a big spark on this team and a big reason why we're winning.
He wants to take every challenge. He wants to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Belfour really wasn't even supposed to play in
the second of the back-to-back games. But the Stars were playing in
their first game since losing captain Derian Hatcher for six to
eight weeks with a lacerated calf muscle, and Belfour not only
figured he needed to be in the game, he ``wanted'' to be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you play back-to-back games, and we'd lost one of our
best players and captain, you want to have as many veteran players
in the lineup as you can,'' Belfour said. ``If I can help out that
way and play a great game, I wanted to try to do that. And I came
up with a good save at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   A good save?
</P>
<P>
   Try an unbelievable save. Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor watched
the replay later and said he doesn't know how Belfour managed to
make the stop. Belfour slid from one side to the other, stacked his
pads, and when he saw the shooter going upstairs, he kicked his top
leg up at the last second, getting the puck with the toe of his
skate.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing took maybe a second to transpire, a great save
made even better because the Stars were clinging to a 3-2 lead at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't stop it, it's a tie game,'' Sydor said. ``I
guess that's why Eddie is there to do that kind of stuff. With
Derian being out, he's the big-time closer.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked like Rollie Fingers against Calgary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour made 31 saves to preserve a scoreless tie, including a
superb stop on Flames forward Jarome Iginla in overtime. Belfour
had one of those nights, and they've been frequent this season,
where he made the amazing look ordinary and impossible look doable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of our team that has given us a chance to remain
in the race is goaltenders,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``Both the guys, him and Manny, and I don't want to leave Fernandez
out of this because he's been good too. These guys, every night,
they give us a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has also given them leadership. He will be in goal again
tonight against the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Not the rah-rah, locker room-speech-making kind of leadership
that we see so much of today, but the quiet leadership of going out
on the ice every night and doing his job and doing it well even
when those in front of him haven't returned the favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some frustration on his part in the way we've
played in front of him. I think that we haven't played as well in
front of him this year as we did last year, and we've had to rely
on him a little bit more,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think the
leadership is he's not carrying any burdens with him right now.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has a reputation for doing otherwise. ``You mean that
he's crusty, he's difficult,'' Stars forward Mike Keane said,
``when really, he's a teddy bear. Maybe, he just thinks he's a
toughie.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not. Just ask Stars forward Jamie Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has been bounced back and forth between the Stars'
minor-league affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich., and Dallas all season.
Players like him only rent an apartment when told to. Until then,
let's just say, Marriott points begin racking up.
</P>
<P>
   So guess who invited Wright to come and live with him? Yep,
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had plenty of room,'' Belfour said, adding that Adam
Creighton had done likewise for a young Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   A kinder, gentler Belfour and a Stanley Cup to boot. Many
predicted that to be the kiss of death. What would be his
motivation to play hard every night? What did he have left to
prove?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing what we did last year, he could've come back this year
and take it easy a little bit. But I think he wants to prove to
everybody that he's the goaltender he was last season,'' Stars
center Guy Carbonneau said. ``Without a doubt, he's been our best
player all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk-radio callers who predicted anything less didn't really
know Belfour. Not that a lot of people do, and Fernandez certainly
isn't claiming to have any deep insights. But Fernandez said he
sees a lot of himself in Belfour. They are both those rare
individuals that if all of the money were taken out of the game,
then they would continue to play as hard as they could, because
they can't deal with losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire that he has I see a lot of me in there, too,''
Fernandez said. ``We're both the same. We refuse to lose. I see
him. He gets fired up before a game.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the parts of Belfour that have remained unchanged
since he arrived in Dallas in July 1997. But he isn't the same
Belfour as then. During Tuesday's practice, the remark was made
that Belfour seemed to be settling into the golden years of his
career. He has a Cup, a new contract and he's finally developing
the reputation for being the goalie he always has been: One of the
best in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   He even looks, dare we say, happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've had a lot of success here in Dallas, and I'm happy
about that and fortunate. I'm just trying to continue that
success,'' Belfour said. ``And maybe all the years before that, all
the hard work, maybe not winning the Cup has made me more hungry
over the years, is starting to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no maybe about it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
