<SLUG> BC-FBN-DITKA-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINTS' DITKA STANDS BY DECISION TO DRAFT WILLIAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Saints' savior, running back Ricky Williams,
sat on the floor of the visitors' locker room curled up in his
cubicle. An empty stool served as a barricade between Williams'
position inside his locker and the rest of the world after the
Saints' 31-8 loss Sunday to the Ravens in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The hood from Williams' parka concealed the emotions and the
distinguished dreadlocks of a 22-year-old who has said he bears
multiple physical and emotional scars from his first NFL season.
The physical problems include injuries to his left ankle, right
elbow and a severe sprain to the big toe on his left foot, an
injury which has prevented Williams from playing the past four
weeks, although he's expected back in the lineup that Saints' coach
Mike Ditka gave up far too much (eight draft picks) to acquire
Williams in last spring's draft _ isn't obvious here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to back off of our decision,'' said Ditka, whose
tenure with the Saints beyond this season appears in jeopardy. ``I
didn't care what people said about it back in April, and I don't
care what they say about it now _ you included. You are not the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is the authority on what we do but us, and nobody has
to answer for what we do but us. That might sound harsh, but it's a
fact. If I have to answer, I will answer, by God, and it will
probably be in a way that will make everybody happy \Rby getting
fired\S. But right now, we made the right decision on Ricky
Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka traded the Saints' first-, third-, fourth-, fifth-, sixth-
and seventh-round selections from 1999 and first- and third-round
selections in 2000 to Washington for the Redskins' first-round
selection (fifth overall) to acquire Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism here surrounding Ditka's move is directed not so
much at Williams, who has had a solid season, but at trading away
so many premium draft picks for a team with so many needs.
Williams, even missing most of the past month, has rushed for 816
yards.
</P>
<P>
   As Saints' third-year linebacker Keith Mitchell said, ``Since
I've been here, we haven't had a 600-yard back. So, hey, he's
already made a big difference as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' rushing total is the most for a Saints running back
since Mario Bates rushed for 951 yards in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka remains stoic in the face of his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has never been predicated by what \Rothers\S think,''
he said. ``There are people in the league who I have tremendous
respect for. Then, there are people in the league that I really
don't care for _ just like they don't care for me. So, we made a
decision _ not based on what the league thinks and what's best for
the league. We did something we thought was best for the Saints.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, meanwhile, wasn't talking to the media early this
week, although he's expected to address the media today.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka said he expects Williams to get his first extended playing
time in more than a month against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to play,'' Ditka said. ``We want him to play. No,
he's not 100 percent, but he's probably no worse than when he
played with the ankle injury, so he's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The player chosen one spot ahead of him, running back Edgerrin
James, meanwhile, has had a dream season playing for a team with
the top young quarterback in football, Peyton Manning, and one of
the top young receivers, Marvin Harrison. That trio has helped
Indianapolis to a 12-2 record, already a nine-game improvement over
a year ago. James ranks second in the NFL behind only Marshall
Faulk of St. Louis in rushing (1,400 yards) and total yards from
scrimmage (1,935).
</P>
<P>
   While Williams might suffer by that comparison, he does not lack
supporters, especially in his own locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the real deal,'' Saints quarterback Billy Joe
Tolliver said. ``I think he's got it all. He's got the size and the
speed, and he's a smart kid on top of everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked up our system fast. He does the right things. I
think he's going to be a good back for a long time. Everybody talks
about trading your whole draft for a kid, but he'll be a
difference-maker before it's all said and done.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but it won't be this season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
