<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-INDICTMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALGERIAN CHARGED IN EXPLOSIVES CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A five-count federal indictment accusing an Algerian
man of trying to smuggle nitroglycerin and other bomb-making
materials into the United States was as notable for what it didn't
say as what it did.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, handed down Wednesday, charges Ahmed Ressam with
illegally carrying explosives and with making false statements to
U.S. Customs agents in Port Angeles after he drove off a ferry from
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no mention in the charges of any broader plot
linking Ressam, 32, to any terrorist network or planned attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a terrorism indictment,'' said U.S. Attorney
Katrina Pflaumer.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam's arrest _ and the arrest of a second Algerian at the
Canadian border in Vermont _ have stirred fears of terrorist
attacks during the holidays and prompted warnings from the State
Department that U.S. citizens abroad may be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy security, Ressam was led into the U.S. Courthouse in
Seattle, where he pleaded not guilty to each count.
</P>
<P>
   He listened intently as the proceedings were explained to him in
Arabic through a court translator. Ressam said nothing, except to
indicate that he understood the charges against him and the pleas
he was making.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jerry Diskin told Magistrate John
Weinberg that the materials found in Ressam's rental car _
including nitroglycerin, urea powder and timing devices _ could
``easily have taken down a building'' had they been assembled into
a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg ordered Ressam held without bail after his federal
public defender, Tom Hillier, raised no objection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the bomb components, Weinberg cited Ressam's
outstanding warrants in Canada for theft charges, his use of a fake
passport and Quebec driver's license, and the fact that he held
plane tickets to leave the United States after an overnight stay in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no conditions that can be set that would ensure his
appearance and the safety of the community,'' Weinberg concluded.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Ressam could face up to 40 years in prison and be
fined more than $1 million. He is being held in the federal
detention center at SeaTac.
</P>
<P>
   His trial was set for Feb. 22 before U.S. District Judge John
Coughenour. Federal prosecutors have to option may to try indicting
him on additional charges if they assemble evidence of a broader
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   After the detention hearing, Pflaumer issued an unusual plea to
anyone who might have been involved in such a plot to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now would be an excellent time for (a co-conspirator) to
disassociate himself and come forward,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian investigators say they are searching for a man who
recently shared a motel room with Ressam in Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   His hands shaking, Ressam was stopped by U.S. Customs officers
Dec. 14 after he drove off a ferry from Victoria at Port Angeles.
Several forms of false identification, including a passport and two
Canadian driver's licenses, were also found in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam tried to bolt from inspectors, but was stopped after a
five-block foot chase.
</P>
<P>
   Hillier said he has yet to see any of the prosecutors' evidence
against his client. He said Ressam speaks virtually no English,
save the words ``OK'' and ``Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's holding up,'' Hillier said. ``He's in a foreign country
in difficult circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillier stressed that no one from the U.S. Attorney's Office had
approached him about a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation in the press that prosecutors may be
forced to offer Ressam a deal to learn more about the targets of
the explosives, and about any terrorist organizations he was
involved with.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Wednesday that French officials
believe Ressam has links to an Algerian terrorist group responsible
for bombings in France. It also reported that American officials
have unconfirmed intelligence reports that Ressam was seen in
Islamic fundamentalist training camps during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials told The Associated Press they are
searching for as many as three other people who may have ties to
Ressam.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI Wednesday asked the public for help identifying everyone
who traveled on the ferry Coho the day Ressam was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Scott Sunde contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
