<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET WAS PRESSED INTO SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ If Andy Murray had his way, the Kings coach would
have held goaltender Stephane Fiset out of the team's three brutal
losses last week. Fiset was still coming back from missing five
weeks with an injured right hand.
</P>
<P>
   But with Jamie Storr playing poorly, and later placed on injured
reserve with a concussion, Fiset had no time to work his way back
gradually. One period after he was activated, Storr was pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset allowed three goals against New Jersey and two more
against the New York Rangers the next night. But his toughest
effort came last Saturday at Staples Center when he was replaced
after allowing six goals against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I need more time? That's a loaded question,'' Fiset said.
``I told the coach I was ready, so I was ready. But you can always
use another practice or two when you're coming back. But there are
no excuses. We all should have been ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, the Kings starting goaltender to open the season, allowed
just one goal in the first period Wednesday after a defensive
mix-up by defenseman Aki Berg and Frantisek Kaberle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good first period is important for all of us, but I think it
will be really important for Steph,'' Murray said. ``It is the best
way to rebuild confidence. You really can't get that back in
practice. He needed the work, but we couldn't get it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster move: After Jozef Stumpel was cleared to play after
missing five weeks (hernia surgery), defenseman Jere Karalahti was
assigned to the Long Beach Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti played in just one game after overcoming visa problems
last month in his native Finland. That was Dec. 11 against Montreal
and he was not sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough situation for him, conditioning-wise,''
Murray said. ``He was hurt for about a week and a half and when he
came back, the coaches knew he wasn't going to be around much
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to protect their own interests, but he really hadn't
played much and it showed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
