<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-CINCINNA     12-23 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-CINCINNATI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 4 CINCINNATI WALLOPS COLD-SHOOTING OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ In rolling to its best-ever start under Kelvin
Sampson, Oklahoma defeated respectable opponents like George
Washington, California, Mississippi and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   But even Sampson said that the No. 21 Sooners had not met a team
with the talent of No. 4 Cincinnati, most recently deposed from
five weeks as the nation's top-ranked team by a two-point loss to
cross-town rival Xavier on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And after last night's 72-57 loss to the Bearcats (9-1), Sampson
conceded the obvious difference between the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been exposed like that and we've played some good
teams,'' Sampson said. ``Cincinnati is a better team than us now.
But I'm not going to overreact to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cincinnati's kids needed the Xavier game to get their
focus back. I think our kids needed this game. Our inexperience
showed. But this was a good experience for us. Cincinnati is really
good. And Kenyon Martin is as good as advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a stocking load of reasons why the Bearcats dominated
OU (9-1).
</P>
<P>
   Center Kenyon Martin was only one, but he was almost enough.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-9 senior from Dallas Bryan Adams scored a game-high
23 points on 11-for-13 shooting and pulled down nine rebounds in
only 26 minutes. And had he played longer than six minutes in the
first half because he incurred his second foul six minutes into the
game, Cincinnati might have led more than 39-29.
</P>
<P>
   At that, the Bearcats scored the game's first nine points and
never let OU closer than four. They are 3-0 this season against
ranked teams and have won six consecutive regular-season games
against Top 25 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was most important that we got off to a good start coming
off a loss and we played good tonight,'' Martin said. ``They've got
to play without me sometime. Tonight I got into foul trouble early
and they adjusted. My hat's off to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had another half to play and I put the fouls behind
me. I just had that type of night, being ready to shoot and
knocking down shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit a variety of shots. And the Sooners had no answer to
Martin, especially when forward Eduardo Najera had his poorest game
of the season. Najera, who was hitting almost 47 percent of his
shots, made only 6-of-21 from the floor. He scored 16 points before
he fouled out with 4:29 to play and Cincinnati leading, 65-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played me like every other team,'' Najera said. ``My
shots were not falling, but I can't get caught up in that. I didn't
play good at all and I'm concerned about the team. Even though the
shots were not going in, we still have to play better
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's long-distance shooters also had a poor night. The
Sooners had been sinking 3-point shots at a Big 12-best 44.1
percent clip. Last night, they hit only seven of 32. And many of
those were uncontested. OU shot 30 percent overall, 20 percentage
points under its season average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a bad night to not shoot the ball well for sure,''
Sampson said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
