<SLUG> BC-HAWKS-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BURY HAWKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six straight losses taught the Celtics no late-game lead can be
too large. Not the way they play. Not with their recent tendency to
let games slip away with sloppy play. Not when they are plagued
with inopportune breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night at the FleetCenter, there were still breakdowns,
scoring droughts, and mistakes, but no fatal collapse. On the night
the parquet floor was retired, Boston defeated Atlanta in blowout
fashion, 98-81, in front of 15,973.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, who improved to 11-14, practically guaranteed by
halftime that their losing streak would not stretch into the
holiday break. The effort and positive attitude coach Rick Pitino
often applauded in defeat was finally handsomely rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a win and got off the slide,'' said Kenny Anderson, who
contributed 13 points and 10 assists in the Celtics' unselfish
display. ``We've just got to keep it up. With one game, we can't
get real overjoyed, but we executed, passed the ball well, and
everybody got involved. We played good aggressive defense. We had a
lot of energy. Lately, our problem has been that we cannot close
the door in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics set the tone and tempo early, determined not to make
the same mistakes that had cost them victory in Atlanta Nov. 27.
They knew better than to get stuck in a halfcourt game where
Atlanta's leading scorer Isaiah Rider (23.5 points per game) and
the NBA's leading rebounder Dikembe Mutombo (14.6 rebounds per
game) could become factors. The two Hawks showed their ability to
take over games together last month, leading the comeback victory
at the Philips Center.
</P>
<P>
   The game was knotted at 6 when the Celtics went on a 20-6 run
that absorbed eight minutes off the clock. A driving layup by
Adrian Griffin capped the spurt with 33.5 seconds left to play in
the opening frame. A last-second, 22-foot jumper by Dana Barros
allowed the Celtics to double up the Hawks, 28-14, at the end of
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Boston had pushed its lead to 18 points (50-32) as
scoring spurts expanded and contracted the gap. Atlanta mounted an
8-2 run midway through the second quarter, cutting Boston's lead to
14 points. Then, Antoine Walker made it his personal mission to
gain back lost ground. The forward followed his first 3-pointer
with a slam dunk and returned the Boston lead to 19. After an
Atlanta timeout, Pervis Ellison put back a Walker miss as the
Celtics' lead grew to 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   A 7-1 Atlanta run trimmed the visitors' deficit to 15 points
with 1:06 left to play before a layup and buzzer-beating 3-pointer
by Eric Williams pushed the Celtics lead to 50-32 by intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston knew from experience against Atlanta that no lead was
safe. As the Celtics pushed their lead to the point of
embarrassment in the third quarter, the Hawks played with little
energy or enthusiasm. Boston built its advantage to a game-high
28-points near the end of the third with a pair of Barros free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing as two different teams,'' said Atlanta's Bimbo
Coles, who along with LaPhonso Ellis, led the Hawks with 13 points.
``We play well in practice, but we're not taking this to the floor.
We're not playing defense. We have the talent, but that's not
carrying over into the game. We're working hard on our offense, but
we have to use set plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider finished with 11 points, marking only the ninth time this
season he has not led his team in scoring. Mutombo recorded a
below-average performance on the glass, grabbing just 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Vitaly Potapenko worked tirelessly over 28 minutes to keep
Mutombo as much of a non-factor as possible. Beneath the basket,
the 6-foot-10-inch Boston center kept his arms spread and
continually looked over his shoulder to monitor his Atlanta
counterpart. Meanwhile, Williams and Griffin often double-teamed
Rider, forcing him to take fadeaway shots and frustrating him.
</P>
<P>
   With the Celtics ahead by 24 points (96-72) and less than three
minutes remaining in the game, Walker could not help but smile
sheepishly and shake his head after he missed a wide-open slam
dunk. It was one of the rare occasions when a play did not go his
way. The Celtic forward finished with a game-high 24 points, while
Barros followed with 15. Griffin grabbed a team-high 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was definitely an important game for us, especially
before hitting the road,'' said Walker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
