<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HAWKS-CELTICS-BOS     12-23 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWKS-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PIECE OF PAST GONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Bob Ryan 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's just a bunch of wood, right?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure. And Bill Russell is just some old guy who used to play
a little basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Those 264 panels compose nothing less than the single most
famous athletic surface in the entire world. From Beijing to Buenos
Aires, and all the Belfasts, Barcelonas, and Boca Ratons in
between, people know the look of that famed parquet. They know that
on those 5-foot-by-5-foot slabs the absolute best basketball that
has ever been seen on this, or any other, planet has been played.
They know that this floor has been trod on by the greatest players
and greatest teams and has been the site of the greatest games.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why the Garden and Celtic pooh-bahs have decided that
the parquet floor is no longer suitable for NBA action has not been
adequately demonstrated. The Lakers didn't seem to have any trouble
playing decent ball on that floor Monday, and the Celtics weren't
so bad on it Wednesday night themselves. OK, there are a few
missing chunks here and there, and there have even occasional
rumors the floor might contain a few, shall we say, dead spots. But
that's part of the charm, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   How much better can a new floor be? One percent? Three percent?
Ten percent? Will a new floor bring back the 130-125 game? Is it
worth sacrificing what little is left of our precious basketball
tradition in order to have some new panels?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, geez, Bill Russell played every home game of his
majestic career on that floor. In fact, he played the first of
those games 33 years ago Wednesday, hauling in 16 rebounds as the
Celtics beat the St. Louis Hawks in the Old Garden. Bill Russell
was here to say goodbye to the parquet Wednesday night. How's that
for closure?
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But who wanted that closure? I doubt if Bob Cousy thought
it was such a hit idea. By the way, The Cooz says, ``Dead spots?
What dead spots?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of dead spots is pure, unadulterated crap,'' quoth
No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, and not to disparage the opinion of the man who
probably bounced the ball more often than anyone who ever played on
the floor in question, but his is a clear minority view. Just about
everyone else agrees that the parquet floor very often has a mind
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Take the simple act of dribbling. ``Sometimes it would come back
to you,'' explained Atlanta coach Lenny Wilkens, one of the great
guards ever to play this game. ``And sometimes it wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson had his first exposure to the vagaries of the
floor when he was barely out of diapers. Well, all right, that
might be a slight exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I played in the Boston Garden was in the Boston
Shootout,'' Anderson said. ``I had a few problems with the floor. I
remember a few times the ball didn't come back up.''
</P>
<P>
   That brings to mind the Quinn Buckner take. When colleague
Michael Madden asked him what it was like to dribble on the parquet
a few years back, Buckner replied, ``I don't know if you can call
it dribbling. I call it, `Putting it down and just hoping it comes
back up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming in here when I was a rookie,'' recalled
Celtics assistant coach Lester Conner. ``I was coming down against
Gerald Henderson and I forget who else, but what I do remember is
that I wound up going one way and the ball went another. I always
figured that's why Larry Bird was out here so early. He never
seemed to have any trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Gerald Henderson, The Man With The Washboard Stomach
was back here to pay his respects to the floor Wednesday evening.
It was, of course, on this floor that he had his greatest
professional moment, picking off an errant James Worthy pass and
turning it into a basket that saved the Celtics from going down,
0-2, in the 1984 Finals.
</P>
<P>
   How many other great moments have taken place on that floor? 10?
50? 100,000? Bill Russell (Havlicek stole the ball), John Havlicek
(His freaky leaner off the glass in the Phoenix triple OT), Tom
Heinsohn (Russell's miraculous block on Jack Coleman to save Game 7
against St. Louis in 1957), K.C. Jones (Bird's steal against
Detroit and Isiah Thomas in 1987) and Bob Cousy (``We Love Ya,
Cooz!'' on March 17, 1963) each talked about a great parquet
happening during a nice halftime ceremony. We could talk about our
own special parquet memories until the next millennium. My favorite
is Dave Cowens belly-flopping after a ball he had knocked it away
from Oscar Robertson in the famed double-OT Game 6 against
Milwaukee in 1974. What's yours?
</P>
<P>
   We once had it all in Boston. We had the greatest team and the
greatest place to play. There was no better atmosphere in
professional basketball history than the Boston Garden on a steamy
spring evening. Will you ever, ever, ever forget the surreal aura
of the Heat Game in 1984? Air conditioning? Who the hell needs air
conditioning? This is our house, pal. You can't take it, you don't
deserve to be playing for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what's left? The Garden is gone. We were told it was going
to be OK in the new building because they'd be taking the floor and
the flags with them. Well? What gives? They've taken the floor away
and the Fleet is now just another overpriced, sterile new building.
And it's not like there'll be a new flag being hung anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The floor was the last true link with the Celtics' great
history. ``It's like a part of me,'' said the inimitable Spider
Edwards, who was brought back to take one more walk down the floor
with his broom after the first period. ``I've spent half my life on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The parquet floor had a resonance that far transcended Boston.
With the floor now packed up forever, the old, sweet NBA of train
travel, doubleheaders, and three-to-make-two is now officially dead
and buried. It's naught but a Jumbotron, hey-ma-look-at-me world
now.
</P>
<P>
   So let the record show that at 9:19 on the 22d of December,
1999, in the last Boston Celtics home game of the century, Jamel
Thomas took a crisp feed from Doug Overton for the final basket on
the world's most famous floor _ a fast-break dunk. Be it known that
Walter McCarty air-balled the final shot from 3-point land. And
further let the record show that the last person to bounce a
basketball on the world's most famous basketball floor was
Atlanta's Chris Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to history. Say hello to . . . ?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
