<HEADLINE>
TCU HANDLES EAST CAROLINA IN MOBILE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ The future is now.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two seasons of history-making firsts for the TCU
football program. Bowl games, winning seasons, a conference title
and a rushing champion are just some of the chapters of a history
written and tradition recaptured with each game.
</P>
<P>
   Last night in this gulf port city in the backdrop of a
first-year bowl, the Horned Frogs slammed bookends on the school's
postseason chronicle. TCU's stunning 28-14 demolishing on No. 20
East Carolina in the inaugural Mobile Alabama Bowl marks the first
time TCU has won back-to-back bowl games since the 1936-37 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special what this team carved out for itself in TCU
football history, with back-to-back bowl victories and back-to-back
winning seasons,'' Frogs coach Dennis Franchione said. ``Eight wins
has happened once in the last 40 years, so it's pretty amazing what
we have been able to do in two years. I don't think I could have
ever envisioned this back in December, 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs finish the 1999 season 8-4 with their first five-game
winning streak since 1984. That's also the same year TCU last won
as many eight games, a number not reach previously since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione leaves Alabama today hoping the Frogs have convinced
a football world they belong among the nation's top 25 programs.
After falling behind 7-0 on the Pirates' second offensive play, TCU
dominated the proceedings, never giving ECU a chance to catch its
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that gives us national respect and some credibility,''
said Franchione, 15-9 in his two seasons at TCU. ``We beat a Top-20
team and I think we really beat them pretty convincingly. If we
don't mess it up offensively two times down there in the red zone,
it's going to be a 42-14 game.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman quarterback Casey Printers stamped his rookie year with
the bowl's player of the game honors. The DeSoto product surprised
the Pirates with a steady stream of bullet passes and timely runs.
Printers completed 13-of-19 pass attempts for 174 yards and a
touchdown with poise belying his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Casey was going to have to come in here and make some
plays,'' said Frogs tailback LaDainian Tomlinson, who rushed for a
game-high 124 yards. ``He didn't play like a freshman
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Printers: ``They left the middle of the field open. When I
went back in my drops, we attacked it, and we did a great job of
catching the ball and heading up field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs also regained their composure after a series of early
mistakes. LaTarence Dunbar fumbled on TCU's first drive, Mike
Scarborough dropped a Printers' long pass inside the ECU 10-yard
line and George Layne drew an unsportsmanlike penalty, knocking the
Frogs out of scoring position _ all in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept our focus,'' backup quarterback Patrick Batteaux said.
``We didn't let the weather or anything get us down. We had a
couple of penalties here and there, a couple mistakes, but we got
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Frogs did sustain three scoring drives in the first
half, giving TCU a 21-7 lead heading into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not stop us the first half; we stopped ourselves,''
Franchione said. ``Fortunately, we managed to get three of them in
the end zone in the first half. If we don't make a mistake or two,
maybe we have five in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Three touchdowns, five touchdowns, it didn't matter. TCU had an
answer for everything the Pirates did. Quarterback David Garrard
was sacked four times and never found a rhythm. ECU also lost 16
yards rushing on the night, the second consecutive year TCU held a
bowl opponent to negative yards rushing. Southern California lost
19 yards last year in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know where we was coming from,'' TCU linebacker
Shannon Brazzell said. ``They're a good team, give them some
credit, but when our team comes to play, we confuse everybody. We
bring funk.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU heads into the off-season with its future brighter than at
any time in the last half-century. The Frogs lose only four
starters and 11 seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot for our team,'' Franchione said. ``It means a
lot to our seniors, who two years ago at this time were 1-10. This
completes it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Batteaux: ``This team is going to be even better. I'm just
glad I was a part of it. The tradition and going to the bowls, I
wish this team well.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
