<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA UPSET IN HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAIE, Hawaii _ UCLA tried to impose its frenzied, fast-breaking
will on Colorado State on Wednesday. Instead, it was the Bruins who
wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kapono's 3-pointer from the left corner clanked off the
rim as the buzzer sounded, giving Colorado State a 55-54 upset
victory in the semifinals of the Pearl Harbor Classic.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which has not won an in-season tournament since 1990, will
play the loser of the South Florida-San Jose State in the
consolation game today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins trailed 54-47 with several minutes left, but Dan
Gadzuric's lay-up and Rico Hines' free throws narrowed the deficit
to 54-51. After Colorado State's Aki Palmer lost the ball, UCLA
guard Ray Young buried a 3-pointer from the right wing to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (5-2) had a chance to take the lead with a minute
remaining, but Kapono missed a difficult, left-handed shot from
close range. Colorado State center John Ford made one of two free
throws, setting up Kapono's last, errant chance.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended an inconsistent 24 hours for the No. 18 Bruins.
They played one of their best halves of the season Tuesday against
Maine, and one of their worst. After charging to a 20-point
halftime lead, they coasted through the final 20 minutes with
sloppy offense and lethargic defense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lavin was in no mood to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped them,'' Lavin said. ``I emphasized that we played
them even in the second half, and that's alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew a repeat performance against Colorado State would result
in UCLA's second loss of the season. The Rams are big, smart and
efficient. They play at a methodical pace, and they don't take bad
shots. In other words, they're a classic UCLA antagonist _ like
Princeton, Detroit Mercy and Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spread the floor and use the clock,'' Lavin said.
``They're more deliberate. It's a good opportunity, because we'll
have to face teams like that over the course of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged baskets for the first 11 minutes. But after
the Bruins pulled even on Gadzuric's lay-up, the Rams surged. Their
man-to-man defense forced several UCLA turnovers _ interrupted only
by several bad shots _ and the Bruins went seven minutes without a
basket.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two field goals by Colorado State forward Ceedric
Goodwyn gave the Rams a 24-17 lead and forced the Bruins to call
timeout. Much needed, it did little good. The mistakes continued,
and they shuffled to the lockerroom trailing 29-20 _ having scored
three points in the final eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams played with what can best be described as speedy
patience. They didn't sit back in a zone defense; they played a
tight man-to-man throughout. They pushed the fast break, but only
when opportunities existed. They moved the ball quickly, mostly by
passing, but they did not take bad shots.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they maintained superb court balance and limited
UCLA's fast break. The Bruins never got any easy baskets _ always a
bad sign for a team that struggles to execute its half-court
offense.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA shot 37.7 percent from the field in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The second half started much like the first ended: Young
committed a turnover on the first possession and was removed from
the game, then Ryan Bailey charged on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Bruins had no success with Goodwyn. At 6-8 and
230 pounds, he was too strong for their guards and too nimble for
their big men, and he scored six consecutive points to give the
Rams a 36-28 lead early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA gradually tightened its defense, which energized the Bruins
_ they were dazed by Colorado State's first-half success _ and
forced several errant shots. One Rams miss became a highlight play
as guard Earl Watson threw an off-the-backboard pass to Jerome
Moiso for a thunder dunk.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams maintained their composure in the face of UCLA's
chaos. Guard John Sivesand followed Moiso's dunk with a 3-pointer,
then center John Ford tipped home a miss. Soon, the Rams had
reclaimed a nine-point lead, and UCLA was forced to scramble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
