<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLE-FIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENDALE SURVIVES TRIAL BY FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Donna Huffaker  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE -- Nearly 600 firefighters battled on the ground and in
the air Wednesday to contain a fast-moving wildfire and save homes
perched on steep terrain in Glendale and La Canada-Flintridge.
</P>
<P>
   After consuming about 750 acres, the fire was 90percent
contained by Wednesday afternoon and no one was injured by the
blaze that broke out about 9:40 p.m. Tuesday, said Los Angeles
County Fire Capt. Steve Valenzuela.
</P>
<P>
   While winds gusting to 50 mph accelerated the flames, an
exceptionally bright full moon helped water-dropping helicopters
and ground crews battle the fire, which ultimately jumped the
Glendale Freeway and threatened homes less than a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   At sunrise, two water-laden SuperScooper planes joined the air
assault with six helicopters flying through thick smoke in an area
choked with obstacles, including power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air support for this fire was essential for containment,''
Valenzuela said. ``The operation worked like a well-orchestrated
play. Everyone had their part and everyone knew their lines.''
</P>
<P>
   As strong winds hit 50 mph on Wednesday, 25 residents fled their
homes, and staff members from Camp Max Straus in Glendale evacuated
60 children to the camp's offices in Los Angeles. The 112-acre camp
is located in the Glendale foothills.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, firefighters gained an upper hand on the wildfire,
but not before flames destroyed the Glendale Police Department
firing range and ignited some 24,000 rounds of ammunition, keeping
firefighters at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Glendale City Council ratified a declaration of a local
state of emergency and hopes to be reimbursed for costs of the fire
from federal and state funds.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began at Starland and Sugarloaf drives in La
Canada-Flintridge and spread southwest into Glendale. Within
minutes, the flames charred 25 acres, Valenzuela said. Wind gusts
fanned the flames across 100 more acres in the next 30 minutes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Around 3 a.m., flying embers sparked a flare-up and flames raced
up a hill on the east side of the Glendale Freeway, between the
Ventura and Foothill freeways, igniting a call box and engulfing
the guardrail, said Glendale Assistant Fire Chief Chris Gray.
Embers sailed to the freeway's west side but firefighters used
hoses to quash the fire immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost a home at this point, and I don't want to take
any chances. I don't want to jeopardize anything by withdrawing the
equipment early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 580 firefighters and 100 engines fought the fire
as Glendale stretched its resources to the limit and got help from
Burbank, Pasadena, South Bay, Santa Monica, Culver City, Alhambra,
Orange County and Los Angeles city and county fire departments,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With many roads closed, more than 100 Glendale police officers
directed traffic at every cross street of Canada Boulevard north to
Verdugo Road, said Sgt. Rick Young. The drive into Glendale from
the foothills Wednesday morning was sluggish, but no real problems
occurred, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and fire officials said multiple agencies cooperated
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also used bulldozers to churn brush under dirt and
thus remove potential beds of fuel where wafting embers would have
taken hold. Because rainfall levels have been low this season and
last, the brush is dangerously dry and flammable, Valenzuela said.
Fire danger is approaching critical levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
