<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORDEAL-FIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS SPEND NIGHT WORRIED ABOUT FIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Hamm  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alice Skenderian sat up in a hotel room until dawn
Wednesday, sleepless and exhausted, watching news reports and
wondering what her family would do if they lost their home to the
fire that roared through more than 750 acres during the night,
threatening scores of hillside homes in Glendale and La Canada
Flintridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a panic,'' said Skenderian, 46. ``It was
terrifying. Where would we go? How would we start from zero?''
</P>
<P>
   With daylight, the firefighters were able to deploy airborne
SuperScoopers, gaining control over the fire and eliminating the
threat to homes. Skenderian, like scores of residents who fled,
returned to find their houses intact.
</P>
<P>
   When the fire got close to the Skenderian house on Delisle Court
near the Glendale Freeway late Tuesday, the family was urged to
evacuate. Crying and distraught, Skenderian grabbed important legal
papers and valuable pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, Skenderian, her husband and their son jumped
into the car and headed into town, where they checked into a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't sleep,'' she said. ``We just watched the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Araxi Kousherian also spent the night in front of the
television, trying to see how close the fire was advancing toward
homes. She dozed off for a few minutes here and there, but the
early hours of Wednesday were filled with too much anxiety for
restful sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very bad night. It was terrible,'' said Kousherian,
52. ``I was thinking that my house would be black.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Red Cross Shelter set up in the Glendale High School
gymnasium, 17 people filled cots overnight. Families began arriving
just after 11 p.m. Tuesday, when the shelter opened.
</P>
<P>
   Some did manage to sleep, but most stayed awake and worried.
``They were anxious to know what was going on,'' said shelter
volunteer Mack Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Avakian and her husband, Leon, were in the middle of a
movie late Tuesday when they got a pager message informing them of
the fire. The couple rushed home, grabbed their wedding photographs
and a few documents and went to stay with family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I freaked out when I saw how close it was, but I was OK after
that,'' said A.J. Avakian, 28.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m. Wednesday, they decided to go home to check on the
house. They slept for a few hours, but decided to go back to their
relatives' house when the fire seemed too close.
</P>
<P>
   They were nervous and restless, she said, but not worried about
losing their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take things as they come,'' Avakian said. ``You get
yourself out of there and the rest is just material.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning home Wednesday, residents found their homes standing.
Many said they were thankful that the holidays would be spent at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thanked God,'' Kousherian said. ``Thank God nothing was
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The only damage to her home was black soot that had fallen into
the pool. But even the white house looked spotless.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sharp contrast to the blackened flora along the
mountainside just feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, everyone has done pretty good up here,'' said Jim
Cooper, an engineer for the Glendale Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Homes remained intact partly because of the high rate of
compliance with the city's weed abatement requirements, officials
said. Residents who live in high hazard areas are required to
annually eliminate all weeds within 100 feet of their property.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Department accounts for 12,000 parcels of land, which
are occupied by about 4,000 homes, said Doug Nickels, Glendale Fire
Department's urban fire forester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is in compliance,'' Nickels said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
