<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-SURGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLU PROMPTS PLEA TO CUT PARAMEDIC WAIT IN ER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Rick Orlov  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The annual flu outbreak has overwhelmed paramedic
services, prompting Los Angeles fire officials Wednesday to seek
approval for them to cut short the time they spend with patients in
hospitals so they can keep up with emergency calls.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing county Department of Health Services rules,
paramedics are required to stay with patients until they are
admitted to the hospital. City fire officials want county health
officials to relax those rules, allowing paramedics to return to
duty more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem isn't the number of calls we answer but the time
our people are spending in the hospitals to get people admitted,''
Battalion Chief Daryl Arbuthnott said. ``Because the hospitals are
jammed, our people have to spend more time there until a bed is
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Fire Chief Bill Bamattre has been meeting with
officials from the county health department over the past week to
try to relax regulations requiring paramedics to remain at the
hospital with a patient until a bed is available.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he has issued a special order canceling staff
training and taking other measures to keep more ambulances and
emergency medical personnel available to respond to calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The health officials might not call it this, but I think we
have a real epidemic on our hands and the hospitals are jammed,''
Fire Commissioner David Fleming said. ``It's times like this where
government has to be flexible. There is no reason for a paramedic
to stand around a hospital to wait for a bed to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Hastings, director of the Emergency Medical Services
Agency for county health, agreed the waiting creates a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of year when call volume is up
substantially,'' Hastings said. ``I've heard some stories of
extraordinary delays. There is one report of a paramedic unit
waiting for three hours. That should not happen. The normal time is
15 to 30 minutes. The problem is, everyone is backed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bamattre has told the county of his concern that the units are
out of service too long in some cases, resulting in delays in
responding to other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Dassey, deputy medical director for acute communicable
diseases for the county, said he and other medical professionals
are reluctant to call the latest influenza outbreak an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has identified about a dozen different strains, but
they are all included in our vaccine,'' Dassey said. ``But we are
seeing what we normally see in December and the winter months. Some
influenza, some other upper respiratory diseases. What we get
concerned with is pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Dassey said he believes the admitting delays are not so much a
function of more flu patients, but of fewer beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a dramatic reduction in the number of staffed
beds since 1991,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern to him is why people would call a paramedic
for the flu or any other respiratory disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need to use emergency medical services when we
have so many clinics around the county that offer primary care,''
Dassey said. ``There is no reason for people to use paramedics and
emergency rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with so many people demanding paramedic runs to emergency
rooms for the flu, Bamattre issued an order this week blocking the
assignment of the department's 25 ambulances with emergency medical
technicians to fire scenes so they are available to respond to
general calls.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure all 50 city paramedic units are in operation,
Bamattre canceled all special training programs. He also is giving
area commanders authority to move paramedics off fire engines to be
available to staff ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   Arbuthnott said the paramedics are being given more leeway to
call in private ambulance firms to transport patients as long as
they are not in any health danger and it appears it will take some
time for transport.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
