<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7340 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BRUSH-HAZARD-LADN     12-23 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSH-HAZARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGION'S ULTRA-DRY CONDITIONS RAISE RISK OF IGNITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Harrison Sheppard  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Massive wildfires that raged through Glendale nine
miles north of Los Angeles and Ventura County, also to the north,
Wednesday served as blazing reminders of the tinderbox conditions
created by the absence of almost any rainfall in the region for the
last six months.
</P>
<P>
   Despite gusting Santa Ana winds, firefighters lost only one
house during three wildfires that moved quickly over the parched
hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   And the end of fire season does not appear to be near, largely
because of the extreme dryness caused by La Nina. Although fire
season normally ends by early December with the arrival of rains,
this year's season is expected to last through January, if not into
February, firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really points to the fact we live in a very volatile
environment,'' said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Brian
Humphrey. ``Southern California by nature of its geography and
vegetation is incendiary.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how incendiary 1999 has been was demonstrated Tuesday night
and Wednesday when three separate blazes, in Glendale, Ojai and the
Rincon, tore through thousands of acres of brush, requiring efforts
from hundreds of firefighters from companies throughout the Los
Angeles region.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, almost 600 firefighters from a dozen departments
battled a blaze that blackened about 750 acres, reaching 90 percent
containment Wednesday. In Ojai, fire burned more than 3,000 acres,
with no prediction for containment, and a smaller one on the coast
near the Santa Barbara-Ventura county line burned 300 acres, which
firefighters expected to encircle by the end of the day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect of more blazes across the San Fernando Valley
area of Los Angeles, the city Fire Department has deployed 16
engines, carrying 64 firefighters, around the Valley and on the
other side of the Santa Monica Mountains on Wednesday night,
Humphrey said. The deployment could continue today, depending on
conditions. To keep adequate personnel levels, the LAFD's Bureau of
Fire Prevention shut down so fire inspectors could be drafted into
firefighting duty.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley has received virtually no rainfall at all this year
since July only 0.08 of an inch recorded in Burbank _ compared with
an average of 5.86 inches, most of it usually in November and
December, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Similar trends were seen throughout Southern California, where
wildfires burned almost three times as much land this year as in
1998. More than a quarter-million acres of brush have burned in
more than 5,000 brush fires in Southern California this year,
according to the National Inter-Agency Fire Coordination Center.
Last year, which was also dry due to La Nina, there were about
4,100 fires that burned 89,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The fires underscored the need for residents and businesses to
clear brush from their properties, although firefighters said brush
clearance was adequate in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale Assistant Fire Chief Chris Gray said most of the brush
had been cleared around high-tension power lines and the freeway,
over which the fire jumped. ``The issue of clearance or lack of
clearance did not affect the fire,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   County and city fire spokesmen said most property owners have
complied with brush clearance regulations by now. Those who didn't
received visits from fire department-hired contractors, along with
a fat bill in the mail afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a group that lags that you have to go after,''
said John Todd, assistant chief of county fire's forestry division,
who oversees the brush clearance unit.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, though, that group has diminished to
about one-third the size, he said. In 1995, the county had to chase
after 1,500 property owners, sending them additional letters or
hiring contractors directly to do the work. This year, 500 property
owners did not comply initially, but by now about 99 percent of
county property owners have complied, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey urged those who have not already done so to prepare
their homes by checking for dead vegetation or rubbish around their
properties. Even those who don't live near heavy brush areas or
receive notices should be cautious, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often find people becoming complacent, with the feeling
their homes won't be affected,'' Humphrey said. ``Even in the
middle of the Valley, in a tract, a fire could easily hopscotch
from roof to roof in the blink of an eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the massive aid sent to the Glendale and Ventura County
blazes, Los Angeles County and city firefighters said they had
enough personnel on duty to handle additional fires if needed.
County fire sent about 300 firefighters to Glendale out of 800
normally on duty, according to department spokesman Inspector
Edward Osorio. But many of them were called from home, so the
county had more than 500 firefighters available for other blazes.
</P>
<P>
   The city Fire Department sent a smaller response, only about 50
firefighters and 10 pieces of equipment, so plenty were on hand to
battle other conflagrations.
</P>
<P>
   When fire conditions are most hazardous, defined as sustained
winds at or above 25 mph and humidity of 15 percent or less, a red
flag warning is issued. Those warnings were issued for numerous
areas Wednesday, said Ron Hamilton, the U.S. Forest Service's fire
weather unit leader in Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton did not have an exact figure for how many were issued
this year, but said he believes it's more than any of the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   With no rain forecast any time soon, Todd said the hazardous
conditions are likely to remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get two or three inches of a good storm to really
soak everything down, we're at a high fire hazard,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BULLARD-H     12-23 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BULLARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Matt Bullard had a rather modest goal for the season _ to get off
the injured list.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of training camp, it seemed like his job was to thank
fans for coming out before preseason games. He figured to be most
valuable to the organization as the Comets' radio analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But if he was to play this season, Bullard knew exactly what his
role would be. There really wasn't much to know. Rehabilitate his
latest knee injury, be a good guy in the locker room and, should
the occasion arise, knock down a few 3-pointers. And that was
pretty much it.
</P>
<P>
   But less than a third of the way into the season, Bullard finds
himself in a different role _ that of starter and team captain. He
leads the league in 3-point shooting. Media members swarm him after
practice, hoping to find a replacement go-to talker. And strangest
of all, Bullard cannot even disparage his defense, which usually
serves as fodder for his one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard, 32, wraps his left knee in ice and describes how he
defended Scottie Pippen on Tuesday night or what he expects tonight
when he matches up with Washington's Juwan Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bullard remains a role player. While he has taken over
Charles Barkley's pre-game captain's handshake duties, he has not
supplanted him as the focal point of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But in his ninth NBA season, including eight with the Rockets,
Bullard might have a larger stake in his team's success than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally different,'' Bullard said of the sudden change in
job description. ``I'm enjoying it. It's rejuvenated me. I came
into the season, (and) my knee was really sore. I started the
season on the injured list. I thought I might be on the injured
list all year trying to get my knee better.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden our team is not making shots, and they bring
me in. Then Hakeem (Olajuwon) gets hurt and Charles gets hurt, and
all of a sudden I'm starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally different than what I thought my role would be
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard thought he had completed rehabilitation from the seventh
surgery on his left knee (and 11th knee surgery overall) in the
offseason. He began training camp on schedule, but when his knee
became increasingly sore, Bullard skipped almost all of the
preseason and started off the season on the injured list, hoping
the rehab time would allow him to strengthen the muscles around the
knee.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets' new-look offense bogged down, they went back
to posting up Barkley and Olajuwon inside, drawing double teams and
leaving the perimeter shooters open. That meant the Rockets needed
help, so with his knee ready, Bullard got the call.
</P>
<P>
   But when Olajuwon and Barkley went out, it might have seemed
that Bullard's usefulness went with them. Instead of being
misplaced in the revised offense, though, Bullard said he has
sought different scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a bigger challenge,'' Bullard said. ``I'm
enjoying the way we're playing. It's exciting to watch. It's
exciting to play. It's not what I expected, but all of a sudden we
turned into that. It's rejuvenating to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With forward Walt Williams struggling with his shot, Bullard has
moved into the starting lineup for the first time since the 1997-98
season, providing an outside option when defenders sag to help out
against the drives of guards Steve Francis and Cuttino Mobley.
Bullard's shooting touch keeps teams honest on pick-and-rolls.
Although he is averaging only 5.4 points per game, he is shooting
51.3 percent from the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always have to do things on scouting reports about
Bull,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``They don't play the
pick-and-roll the same way when Bull sets the pick. He will occupy
a guy. If they come off him, he's a good outside shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   With his knee flaring up, such as Saturday when he could play
only into the second quarter, Bullard has made only four of 18
shots since becoming a starter. He had made seven of 12 shots in
his previous three games.
</P>
<P>
   As a starter, however, Bullard likely plays a larger part in
opponents' game plans. Defenders are more likely to remain focused
on staying with Bullard at the 3-point line, so Bullard has found
himself forced to pump-fake and shoot off the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams have game plans to stop other teams' starters,'' he
said. ``I'm leading the league in 3-pointers, so they're not going
to let me get open shots. I have to try to find ways to get open or
hit different shots. That's interesting and fun to me, to try to
figure out other ways to hit shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Like defenses that have adjusted to him, Bullard has had to
adapt as well. After coming off the bench for so long, he has
learned to time his shooting touch for late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so used to watching the game, getting into the flow,
it's hard to really be ready to play at the beginning of the
game,'' Bullard said. ``We're still trying to find the right mix. I
don't think we've found the guys yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for a fact I'm better coming off the bench. That's how
I've been able to stay in this league. A lot of guys can't make
that adjustment to come off the bench ready to play. I know I can.
Right now, I'm starting so I'm trying to make that adjustment to be
ready to start at the beginning of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting thing about Bullard's three-game stint as a
starter might be the success he has had defensively.
</P>
<P>
   He has done surprisingly well on the end of the court where he
has long been considered a liability. He might not draw any
defensive comparisons to Bill Russell, but with back-to-back games
against Pippen and Howard, Tomjanovich was not forced to change his
lineup because Bullard was overpowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm playing pretty good defense,'' Bullard said.
``I'm not a real good defensive player. But I'm able to move my
feet quicker. I think the more years you play in the league, the
better you can become by using your mind, your old vet tricks. I
think I'm doing a decent job. I'll keep trying to not be a
liability out there on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even have two blocked shots this year. That's one more than
my yearly average.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not quite true. Bullard had 95 blocks coming into this
season. But if Bullard is not going to reject shots, he has forced
some misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a veteran,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He understands his
limitations. He's usually not going to overextend himself. He'll
make the guy (his opponent) have to do something that's not his
strong suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is playing more, he can offer some leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hakeem and Charles were playing, I had a secondary
leadership role,'' Bullard said. ``I feel like I'm still a
secondary leader. We're trying to find who our primary leader will
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve, Cuttino, Shandon (Anderson), guys like that who are
playing all the minutes, they can set the standard as primary
leaders. I feel like I've been around. This is my eighth year with
the Rockets. I know what Rudy wants. I can help guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   And if nothing else, he has found himself well-qualified for his
new pre-game duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just say hi to the other team's captains,'' Bullard said.
``You crack a few jokes for the refs, try to get them on your
side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
