<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-23 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YOU get a sense of how garbled this NFL season has been when you
note that the Dallas Cowboys, with a pedestrian 7-7 record, visit
New Orleans on Friday in a brave attempt to keep alive their Super
Bowl ``hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the field, the embattled Mike Ditka will make what may be
his last stand in the city where fans invented the custom of
wearing paper bags over their heads to conceal the fact that they
have spent the time, and money, to watch the Saints play.
</P>
<P>
   It just doesn't get any better than this, does it?
</P>
<P>
   A victory over the Cowboys, even this pale imitation of what was
once America's Team, may be enough to save Ditka's job, if he wants
it saved. Yet the Cowboys have sunk so low that a loss to the
Saints may not qualify as a big, big upset.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear the 'Boys belting out the lyrics, ``Good
mornin', America, how are ya? Say, don't you know me? I'm your
native son ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is one of the local anthems, about a choo-choo
train, but the lines seem to apply more neatly to the boys who wear
the star: ``And I'll be gone 500 miles when the day is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think about the complications that had to occur to
bring you this attraction on Christmas Eve, when the Superdome will
be packed with hostile fans, yelling for blood. Pumped up on egg
nog and other libations, the fans will want little else for
Christmas than to watch Dallas lose. The next-best thing would be
watching the Saints lose.
</P>
<P>
   The home team is not very popular at the moment, known once
again to its detractors as the Aints, the name used whenever their
wins total two or fewer. The fans have poured food and beer on the
players as they retreated to the locker room. Ditka has reacted in
predictable ways, and apologized for them, including a very obscene
gesture captured on television.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the weekly agonies of Iron Mike has become a sport in
New Orleans, a great town for curses, with all those exotic shops
featuring voodoo masks and vials of dragon's blood, incense,
stuffed bats, tarantulas and toads, and hex-removing sprays in
aerosol cans.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy to determine which football team inspires more
sympathy. Yeah, the Cowboys have been crippled by injuries, but the
Saints are the first team in the history of professional football
to have two quarterbacks named Billy Joe disabled in the same
season. They will be down to their fourth starter, Jake Delhomme,
who wasn't even on the depth chart in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys win Friday and at home against the Giants, they
can win the NFC East. The Saints have desperation on their side.
They need a victory to avoid edging out the rookie Cleveland Browns
for the title of worst team in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a Super Bowl in Chicago, Ditka has known little
but misery and criticism in New Orleans. He was admired for his
boldness when he traded his entire draft for Ricky Williams, the
Heisman Trophy winner from Texas. The publicity flowed like fine
French wine, but Ricky hasn't had a healthy body all year and isn't
expected to play Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tourists who plan to spend Christmas in New Orleans
cannot fail to enjoy themselves, unless they hibernate in their
hotel rooms and only go to the game.
</P>
<P>
   This is the home of the best black and white music in America,
from riverboat to rock. It is where the blues were born, and
Preservation Hall is still regarded as a shrine, where the
white-haired survivors of the funeral marching bands still play
jazz the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints would appear to have no weapons with which to beat
Dallas, unless you count Bourbon Street, where the action slows
down around 4 in the morning. After that there are only the
sad-eyed and solitary drinkers milling around, and some of the fun
has drained away. This is the hour for Morning Call, the famous old
coffee and cruller house down at the French Market.
</P>
<P>
   Comes daytime, and the French Quarter is transformed. When the
lights go out and the sun comes up, you can appreciate the graceful
lines of an ageless architecture _ if you can get your eyelids to
open. The balconies provide high, open spaces to catch the breeze
from the Mississippi; the streets are made narrow for shade. The
history begins to come through, too. Every street and almost every
building in the 10 square blocks of the Quarter has its own
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Custom House was once a Confederate prison. In the light of
day, you can see clearly the Old Absinthe House, once a tavern
where Andrew Jackson is said to have planned the defense of New
Orleans in 1815. Before that it was supposedly the haunt of the
pirate brothers, Pierre and Jean Lafitte.
</P>
<P>
   Now come the Cowboys and the Saints, living small among the
ruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
