<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-FINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC BELL HIT WITH HEFTY FINE FOR MISLEADING CUSTOMERS  
 
 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM ABATE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ A California Public Utilities Commission judge
fined Pacific Bell $20 million Wednesday for misleading customers
into buying extra phone services and ordered the phone company to
spend an additional $24 million on a consumer-education campaign.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On top of the fine, which will go into the state's general fund,
the judge also ordered Pacific Bell and the PUC to come up with a
plan to identify and provide refunds to consumers who may have been
misled.
</P>
<P>
   In her 96-page decision, PUC Judge Maribeth Bushey justified the
huge fine _ believed to be a record against a California phone
company _ because of Pacific Bell's ```recidivist'' behavior. The
company was fined $16.5 million for similar marketing abuses in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about recidivism in a criminal terms, it usually
means a habitual criminal,'' said Kelly Boyd, with the California
Public Utilities Commission's Office of Ratepayer Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell spokesman Doug Michelman said his company was
outraged by the decision and will appeal the order to the PUC
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings in the decision are unwarranted, irresponsible
and unfairly single out Pacific Bell for sales and service
practices that are common in our industry and many others,''
Michelman said. ``We do believe our sales and service practices are
appropriate, legal, ethical and designed to meet the needs of our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The case arises from complaints first filed before the PUC in
April 1998 by the Utility Consumer Action Network in San Diego and
other groups representing phone customers.
</P>
<P>
   After a weeklong hearing in January, the case was referred to a
PUC judge. Utility Consumer Action Network President Charles
Carbone said consumer groups ``have waited with bated breath''
since then for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer groups accused Pacific Bell salespeople of
misleading customers into thinking that it is difficult to block
caller ID, so that Pacific Bell could sell more caller ID equipment
and services. Caller ID boxes show the phone number of incoming
calls, but 44 percent of Californians have opted to block their
numbers, which has hindered the company's sales of the equipment
and service.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also charged that Pacific Bell sales representatives
duped customers into buying expensive options like call-forwarding
and three-way calling by bundling them into packages with such
names as ``The Basics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They put together packages with all the bells and whistles,
and they called them basic service,'' Carbone said. ``So, instead
of ordering basic service for $11.25, customers got socked with $30
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said she thinks the $20 million fine is the largest the PUC
has ever imposed on a phone company.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Bell may not have to pay the entire $20 million. In
her order, Bushey said the phone company might have to pay only $10
million, ``depending on Pacific Bell's cooperation with the
remedial steps ordered in this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Those steps include creating a $24 million advertising campaign
to inform consumers about basic phone services and the rules for
blocking caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   Bushey's decision could spur district attorneys for Alameda, San
Mateo and Monterey counties to reopen lawsuits that they filed in
September against Pacific Bell. The district attorneys charged that
the phone company was continuing to mislead consumers even as it
was awaiting a decision on the PUC action.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said a Superior Court judge essentially threw out that case
in October, saying the district attorneys had not shown that they
had standing to represent consumers in a matter regulated by the
state PUC. Boyd said Bushey's ruling would show the district
attorneys where they might have standing, should they desire to
revive their suits.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorneys could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chronicle staff writer Kelly Zito contributed to this &LR; 
 &LR; report. &LR;
</P>
<P>
