<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER23-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEESY THOUGHTS ON THE MOON  
  
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 
I never learn. I spent too much time marveling at last night's
lunar phenomenon and wound up with a nasty moonburn.
<TEXT>
<P>
   First aid for moonburn is to slather on a coating of cream
cheese, and just my luck, I was out of lox and bagels.
</P>
<P>
   But it was worth it. The moon hit my eye like a big pizza pie.
Why can't we write songs like that any more, songs that ask eternal
questions, like am I in love or did I eat too much pasta pazool?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's amazing to realize the moon is really only about 15
miles away, and getting dangerously closer. Using binoculars, I
could even make out the sign on the Sea of Tranquility: ``Coming
soon: Starbucks.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; THE WEATHER'S  &LR; so crazy, there have even been outbreaks of spring
fever.
</P>
<P>
   Jack the hack was pulling his cab into the Veterans company lot
one recent balmy midnight and noticed, on the ledge of an extremely
well-lit Ford billboard on 101 near the Mission Street off-ramp, a
young couple ... coupling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; IT'S AMAZING  &LR; what you see on signs. Barbara and Ken Small (yes, a
real-life Ken and Barbie!) spotted a large billboard for KGO radio
bragging of ``Non-stop 49ers action.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smalls ask, ``As an old sportswriter, don't you feel this is
an uncanny description of the 49ers' defense?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JUST IN CASE  &LR; you don't have enough to worry about with holiday
shopping, airport terrorism alerts, Y2K flop-sweats and the heat
melting your Frostie, add this: quake alert.
</P>
<P>
   Geologist James Berkland, who predicted the Loma Prieta quake,
says watch out. He discovered a strong correlation between extreme
tides (like now) and earthquakes, and says that between now and the
29th, there is an 85 percent chance of a 3.5-to-6 shaker within 140
miles of San Jose, and an 85 percent chance of a 7-plus somewhere
in the world, probably in the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of OSTLER23 (83394 ) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; KILLER KIDDIES  &LR; in Kansas, airline pilots who scoff at weather
warnings and kill 11 passengers, fatally careless doctors, cruel
parents, corporate toxic polluters, drivers who drive
drunk-mad-tired-stupid. ...
</P>
<P>
   Our government warns us to watch out for foreign terrorists, but
as of now, we're still our own worst terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RAISING CAEN,  &LR; or toasting memory of same, was the goal of the gang
at Moose's. The invitees: anyone who ever appeared in a Herb Caen
Christmas poem.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown delivered his annual lament that with Herb gone,
nobody's around to explain Willie's stupidity to the world. Herb's
son Christopher read his own poem about the agony and ecstasy
surrounding the old Herb holiday poem tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Hoover magically tinkled the Moose's ivories. The
still-inexplicable Strange de Jim snagged an appetizer and
commented, ``I love crab cakes. Especially the cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   And old Caen pal Harry de Wildt told of a luncheon at Le Central
when Caen was on his last legs. Stunning woman strolls past the
restaurant's window. Moment of silence, then De Wildt says, ``What
do you think of that, Herb?''
</P>
<P>
   Herb: ``Just remember, she's a pain in the neck to  &LR; some &LR;  guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STILL FLYING  &LR; limply from City Hall: the San Francisco election
flag _ a ballot box attached by cobwebs to the shell of a
sauntering snail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ``ANY GIVEN SUNDAY, &LR; '' Oliver Stone's gridiron epic now in theaters
near you, is a child of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Former 49ers star Jamie Williams wrote the story that inspired
the movie. And my Peninsula informant, Pal O'Alto, traces the
production of the movie back to a dinner at Stars in Palo Alto in
the summer of '95, where Stone picked the brain of former 49er
great Y.A. Tittle.
</P>
<P>
   Y.A., a big-time insurance exec, still has all his brain cells
intact, thanks to the fact that he played in the old days, before
the invention of the concussion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; I AM DONDER,  &LR; dammit!
</P>
<P>
   It's not Donner, OK? Sharon Rooney of the Donder Education
Society has her dander up and her dauber down. The society is
making little headway in efforts to educate folks that Clement
Clark Moore's seventh reindeer in the 1822 poem ``An Account of a
Visit from St. Nicholas'' is Donder.
</P>
<P>
   If folks start getting it right, the society will celebrate by
throwing a Donder Party, and venison will not be served.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE MAYOR  &LR; says you can't buy supermarket shopping carts. But Cost
Plus has 'em, tiny eight-inch tabletop models.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Wheeler suggests you might want to pick one up, in case
the brisk sales of Pokemon put the other dolls out of business and
Ken and Barbie wind up homeless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SLEEP-DEPRIVED  &LR; drivers more likely to crash, study says.
</P>
<P>
   Who does these studies? Sleep-deprived scientists? Maybe it
gives that info in the article, but I fell asleep while reading it
and got my nose stuck in my keyboard, between the bottom row of
keys and the spacebar.
</P>
<P>
   A few tips on staying alert while driving: Keep the gas needle
on E, the anxiety will help keep you peppy. ... If you have a
sunroof, put on the cruise control, sit on the roof and drive with
your feet (freeway driving only). ... Cell-phone late-night radio
talk shows and rant about idiots who refer to Donder as Donner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; IN CLOSING,  &LR; a word of advice: Moonscreen.
</P>
