<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7366 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-SWISSAIR-MOVE-2Takes-     12-23 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-MOVE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS ELATED BY MAINTENANCE DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM SKEEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ The arrival of a Swiss aircraft maintenance
operation, and the 3,000 to 5,000 jobs that come with it, will be a
massive shot in the arm to the Antelope Valley economy and will
help bring in more businesses, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As reported in the Los Angeles Daily News on Wednesday, Gov.
Gray Davis is scheduled to announce at 11 a.m. today that SR
Technics, a subsidiary of SAirGroup, will establish an aircraft
maintenance, repair and overhaul plant at Boeing's Site 9 adjoining
Air Force Plant 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Santa Claus exists, this is what he would bring,'' Palmdale
Mayor Jim Ledford said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Employment estimates range anywhere from 3,000 to 7,000 workers,
who will perform scheduled heavy maintenance, repairs, overhauls,
paint jobs avionics upgrades and other modifications for jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier interview with the Daily News, Michael Rodyniuk,
director of business alliances for SR Technics, said initial
employment will be in the hundreds and, by the year 2005, will
extend into the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   SR Technics is seeking to establish a global network of
maintenance, repair and overhaul facilities that will allow the
company to provide service for any airline worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to a massive impact on the economy,'' said David
Myers, regional manager for the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corporation. ``These will be high-wage, high-value jobs
that won't go away in three years. People are going to have the
confidence to invest in Palmdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said the SR Technics move will have a ripple effect,
causing the company's suppliers to consider moving to the region.
The move will also cause other companies planning relocation to
consider moving to the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Antelope Valley officials said officials from government and
industry came together to help make the deal happen, including the
governor, state Secretary of Trade and Commerce Lon Hatamiya and
representatives of Palmdale's economic development department, the
Antelope Valley Aerospace Alliance and Antelope Valley College.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman George Runner, R-Lancaster, described the SR
Technics decision as good news for the Antelope Valley and
California, but tempered his remarks with the proviso of ``if it
comes true.'' Runner noted Friday that the decision is still
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that 90 days ago this was nowhere,'' Runner
said. ``It's a great Christmas present for the Antelope Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner said he received a call last week from the state Trade
and Commerce Agency asking him to contact SR Technics regarding
air-quality issues. SR Technics officials were under the mistaken
belief that the Antelope Valley was still governed by the South
Coast Air Quality Management District, which, right or wrong, has a
reputation for being difficult to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The Antelope Valley is governed by its own air-quality control
district, split off from the South Coast AQMD in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Runner said the governor has been closely following the SR
Technics discussions and calling the Trade and Commerce Agency
secretary about it almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the governor was highly involved in this
issue,'' Runner said.
</P>
<P>
   If SR Technics opens a commercial aerospace operation in
California, it could help relieve the state's dependence on
military aerospace projects, Runner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can break the myth that California can't be
competitive,'' Runner said.
</P>
<P>
   SR Technics' site requirements include fair weather; hangars
large enough to accommodate jetliners such as the Boeing 747-400,
the Boeing 767, the Boeing 777 and the Airbus A-330 and A-340; an
available skilled work force; and a region where the population
appreciates the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   Site 9, where Rockwell International assembled 100 B-1B bombers,
offers 1.3 million square feet of office and manufacturing space,
including two high-bay hangars. The Antelope Valley also averages
345 days a year of clear flying weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Site 9 land is actually owned by Los Angeles World Airports,
the city of Los Angeles airports department. Boeing owns the
buildings, which it acquired when it took over Rockwell's space and
aircraft operations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been trying to sell Site 9 as part of a consolidation
plan announced several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other benefits for locating in the Antelope Valley include the
region's designation as an enterprise zone, where industry can get
state tax credits on equipment purchases and on wages for employees
hired through certain programs or from low-income areas; federal
tax breaks on imported items; and possible assistance through the
Antelope Valley Aerospace Alliance, a cooperative effort of the
region's major aerospace companies. Antelope Valley College
cooperates by offering help in creating training programs;
</P>
<P>
   There is also about $1.4million in state funding available for
job training, said Lancaster Mayor Frank Roberts, who serves as
chairman of the Antelope Valley's one-stop job training and
employment office.
</P>
<P>
   One major drawback for the Palmdale site was the lack of a
deluge system to protect against flash fires or fires from fueled
aircraft entering hangars.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials say the city would supply an $11 million
fire sprinkler system, according to sources.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another hurdle, according to sources familiar with the
negotiations, was a $5 million gap between what SR Technics was
willing to offer for a site and what Boeing was seeking for Site 9.
It was not immediately known how that was settled.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce B. Hailstone, president-elect for the Greater Antelope
Valley Association of Realtors, says he believes the new jobs will
help the valley's improving home market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an additional boost to the already
recovering market we see out there,'' Hailstone said.
</P>
<P>
   The valley market will benefit whether the jobs are taken by
Antelope Valley residents who now commute or work at lower paying
jobs, by newcomers or by a mixture.
</P>
<P>
   For those already living in the valley, new jobs for SR Technics
are likely to give them more income, making them prospects for
selling the homes they have and buying better ones, Hailstone said,
and newcomers are likely to buy houses rather than rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all win,'' Hailstone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
