<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS IMPROVE BUT STILL LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The Kings came back to life Wednesday night. They
just didn't do it with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing 23 goals in three consecutive meltdowns, the
Kings were respectable in a 2-1 loss to the San Jose Sharks in
front of 17,483 at the San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't euphoric in the post-game locker room, but they
weren't shellshocked either. The Kings know emotionally they have
regrouped, even though they face a potential fifth-consecutive loss
the day after Christmas against division-leading Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've played as bad as we've played the last three
games,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``There seems to be some sort of
penance that you've got to go through where you have to play a
couple of real solid games before you get your just rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was the return of center Jozef Stumpel, who had
missed almost six weeks after abdominal surgery. Stumpel gave the
Kings the defense they have been lacking in 7-1, 8-3 and 8-4 losses
that dropped them into last place in the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings had no answer for the league's leading goal
scorer, Owen Nolan, who got his 26th on the power play midway
through the second period to give the Sharks a 2-1 lead. Even
though they held San Jose to just three shots in the third period,
Nolan's goal was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why he is one of the top power forwards in the game,''
said Rob Blake, who had nine shots on Sharks goalie Steve Shields.
``He was in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Stumpel left the lineup Nov. 5, the Kings were 9-3-3 and
among the top teams in the Western Conference. Stumpel is the final
member of the Kings top line to return from injuries this season.
His mood was up even though he and linemates Luc Robitaille and
Ziggy Palffy were held without a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous at the beginning but after the first
shot I was fine,'' Stumpel said. ``Physically, I felt fine. I know
I'll even get sharper as time goes on and get even more into the
flow of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will need it if they want to pick up some ground in
the Pacific Division, which has hit a snag lately. All five teams
would qualify if the playoffs started today.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose came in with three consecutive losses. The Coyotes had
dropped five of six before routing the Mighty Ducks on Wednesday in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings knew keeping the game close in the first period would
be critical to overcoming their slump. They had been outscored 13-1
in the opening period the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sharks scored the first goal on a wrist shot by
Vincent Damphousse with 9:42 left in the first, the Kings had shown
enough grit to start rebuilding their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   They killed off two penalties, got their forwards to play
defense and even got a couple of shots in a short-handed situation
midway through the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear that the mental fatigue was gone,'' said Bryan
Smolinski, who scored the Kings only goal. ``That was just a mental
breakdown by an entire team. We showed we're through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was not all great. On the Sharks' first goal,
defensemen Aki Berg and Frantisek Kaberle collided in front of the
net, giving Damphousse an open look. He fired a 15-footer over the
right shoulder of Kings goal tender Stephane Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   But as they had done early in the season, the Kings sent a
message late in the period when Smolinski rebounded a blast by Glen
Murray with 1:03 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings caught a break at the other end when the Sharks' were
pressuring Fiset. Stephane Matteau took a shot from a bad angle
that struck Smolinski's skate and shot out to center ice.
</P>
<P>
   Murray picked up the puck, crossed the San Jose blue line and
let go a slap shot. Shields made the first stop, but Smolinski was
trailing the play and fired in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ninth goal of the season for Smolinski, who is among
the league leaders with 33 points in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a fluke I guess,'' Smolinski said. ``We haven't seen much
of that lately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
