<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 03:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LA     12-23 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA UPSET IN HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAIE, Hawaii _ It's a bit early in the season for teams to
establish identities, but UCLA's fingerprints are already
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Bruins run, and watch 'em have fun. Play them slow, and
watch 'em implode.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State became the latest team to exploit UCLA's
half-court woes, using a Gonzaga-esque game plan to upset the
Bruins 55-54 Wednesday night in the semifinals of the Pearl Harbor
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (5-2) trailed by nine points at halftime and seven
with three minutes left. But their frenzied rally fell short when
freshman forward Jason Kapono missed a 3-pointer from the left
corner at the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to play at a slower tempo,'' Colorado State coach
Ritchie McKay said. ``The higher the score against UCLA, the less
likely your chances of winning. We wanted to slow the tempo but
stay aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much of his strategy was culled from videotape of
UCLA's loss to Gonzaga, McKay said: ``A lot.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which has not won an in-season tournament since 1990, will
play the loser of the South Florida-San Jose State in the
consolation game today.
</P>
<P>
   The chaotic final minutes made the game seem closer than it was.
Colorado State dominated with a well-designed man-to-man defense
that forced UCLA into 37.7 percent shooting. The Rams also used
near-flawless judgment on offense. They refused to take bad shots,
and they forced the Bruins to play defense for 25-30 seconds per
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were well-coached,'' UCLA guard Earl Watson said. ``They
had a game plan, and they stuck to it. They played solid, and they
stayed within the team concept.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay liked his chances on the frontline with versatile forward
Ceedric Goodwyn (18 points) and athletic center John Ford (five
blocks). His perimeter defense was not designed to stop Watson _
UCLA's point guard and most experienced player _ but rather Kapono,
whose passing and decision-making are crucial to UCLA's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, as Kapono struggled (2 of 11 shooting, one assist)
so did the Bruins. They made one basket in the final eight minutes
of the first half as the Rams turned a 17-17 tie into a 29-20
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real discouraged, because we played some of our best
basketball of the season in the second half,'' Bruins coach Steve
Lavin said. ``But because we played so poorly in the first, we
weren't able to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played the first half against Colorado State like
they played the second against Maine on Tuesday night _ with a
mixture of lethargy and sloppiness. They played like they expected
to win, utterly confident they'd impose their frenetic,
fast-breaking will on Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Bruins who wilted.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were better coached, they were better prepared and, for
37 minutes, they were much the better team. They didn't sit back in
a zone defense; they played a tight man-to-man. They pushed the
fast break, but only when opportunities existed. They moved the
ball quickly, mostly by passing, but they did not take bad shots.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they maintained superb court balance and limited
UCLA's fast break. The Bruins rarely got easy baskets _ and that's
always a bad sign for a team that struggles to execute its
half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, UCLA tightened its defense as the second half
unfurled, and Colorado State briefly lost its composure. One errant
shot became a highlight play when Watson, leading the fast break,
threw an off-the-backboard pass to Jerome Moiso for a thunder dunk
that trimmed CSU's lead to 38-36.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best dunks I've ever seen,'' McKay said.
``I thought we were losing momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams quickly steadied themselves. Guard John Sivesand
followed Moiso's dunk with a 3-pointer, then Ford tipped home a
miss. Soon, the Rams had reclaimed a nine-point lead, and UCLA was
forced to scramble.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute rally began with Dan Gadzuric's lay-up. Rico
Hines' free throws narrowed the deficit to 54-51. After a Colorado
State turnover, UCLA guard Ray Young buried a 3-pointer from the
right wing to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had a chance to take the lead with a minute
remaining, but Kapono missed a difficult, left-handed shot from
close range. Ford made one of two free throws, setting up Kapono's
last, errant chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed our inconsistency,'' Watson said. ``We can't base
the game on the last play, because for the 39 minutes before, we
played terrible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
