<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NAPLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inn by the Sea a perfect fit for relaxing Naples
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ What I love about Naples is how people there
appreciate a good sunset. A half hour before the sun goes down the
march to the sea commences.
</P>
<P>
   Old folks lug tattered beach chairs and crystal wine glasses
from nearby homes.
</P>
<P>
   Young folks pedal bicycles across the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged fitness fans jog along the shoreline. A gaggle of
kids follow, pointing at birds and covering their eyes to avoid the
glare.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathers at the city pier and yet it's so quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Watching it reminds me of a scene in the Nicolas Cage-Meg Ryan
movie, City of Angels, where the angels meet at the beach at
sunrise to listen to the music of the spheres.
</P>
<P>
   No sphere music to be heard here. Clumsy-looking pelicans
crashing into the waves for fish provide what little noise there
is. You can't help but feel at peace.
</P>
<P>
   And peace is always a good feeling after a tiring afternoon of
gallery hopping and shopping on Fifth Avenue and Third Street
South.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that people in Naples would honor something as
beautiful as the setting sun. Clearly, they enjoy handsome artwork
_ there are no less than 31 art galleries in the city. Many are
around Fifth Avenue and Third Street South.
</P>
<P>
   Both tony shopping areas are within easy walking distance of Inn
by the Sea, the bed-and-breakfast my husband and I visited.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you be misled by its moniker, the inn isn't on the
shoreline, but three short blocks away _ close enough for a walk or
bike ride.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1937, the five-room inn, one of Naples' first guest
houses, is on the National Register of Historic Places. It has a
tin roof, wooden cove siding, ceiling fans and brass and iron beds
and yellow pine floors and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed in one of the two upstairs rooms, the Bokeelia Suite.
(Rooms are named after barrier islands. Others are Gasparilla,
Sanibel, Captiva and Keewaydin.) Painted pale yellow, the walls in
our suite had pink, blue and yellow floral wallpaper borders. There
were tropical watercolor prints on the walls, wooden blinds on the
windows, and several baskets of sea shells placed around the suite.
The sitting room had a day bed, wicker chair and coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   While cozy, we found the quarters a tad confining and we didn't
like having to go across the hall to use the bathroom, which was so
tiny we could barely close the door without scraping the sink.
</P>
<P>
   But we had a good time at the Inn by the Sea, partly because we
met some fun folks in the living room and talked for hours, and
partly because the place has plenty of old Florida charm. The
ceramic fish on the sidewalk at the house's entrance was cute and
we loved the backyard orange tree, ripe and ready for picking. The
citrus fragrance alone enchanted us.
</P>
<P>
   Engaging, too, were the inn's owners, Maas and Connie van den
Top, who bought the place a few months ago. Connie, a former art
dealer who lived in Paris for several years, and Maas, from
Holland, give the place a bit of international flair.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast, served in the dining room, included orange juice,
rolls, muffins, cereal, yogurt and fresh fruit. The only
disappointment was that with all those ripe oranges outside, the
juice came from a carton.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, this little B&AMP;B was a great place to get some
R&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Inn by the Sea, 287 11th Ave. S., Naples. Phone: (941) 649-4124.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: From West Palm Beach, go south on I-95 to I-75. Take
I-75 (Alligator Alley) west to exit 15. Bear left onto County Road
951 to Davis Boulevard (State Road 84) and turn right. When it
ends, turn right on U.S. 41. Follow signs to downtown. Take Fifth
Avenue to Third Street and turn left (south) to 11th Avenue South.
Inn is on the corner of Third Street and 11th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations: Five guest rooms, all with private baths,
although the upstairs rooms have detached bathrooms. Breakfast in
the dining room included.
</P>
<P>
   Rates: From Dec. 14-April 18, rooms range from $149-$189.
</P>
<P>
   Some good places to eat outdoors: Campiello, a fairly new
Italian eatery at 1177 Third St. S.; and Tommy Bahama's Tropical
Cafe, a fun place for lunch and shopping (there's a clothing store
attached)  Third St. S.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
