<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: What does an American look like?
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 26, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal authorities, concerned that this year-end will foment
worldwide (and domestic) terrorism against Americans, make this
suggestion: When overseas, try not to look too American.
</P>
<P>
   This is an interesting concept but one that is out of season.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, many Americans are easy to spot; usually, the men
wear Bermuda shorts, calf-length black socks and white sneakers _
along with a baseball-style cap.
</P>
<P>
   But in the winter? Say at this time? A good terrorist will have
to listen closely to people to hear an American accent, as the
tourists are bundled up just like the natives.
</P>
<P>
   Short of the guy in the Bermuda shorts and black socks,
Americans often are difficult to spot because the U.S. likely has
the most diverse population in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Americans look Hispanic, Americans look Italian, Americans look
African, Americans look Oriental, Americans look Semitic, Americans
look Nordic; you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Ugly American reputation that has followed us all
these decades of the 20th century is based more on activity rather
than attire. Maybe the suggestion should have been that we try to
not ACT like Americans overseas, because many do _ especially those
who plod on and off tour buses for the obligatory three-minute
visits to the Louvre, the Vatican or the Acropolis.
</P>
<P>
   There's a longstanding stereotyping wisecrack, to wit: How can
you tell the difference between a Japanese tourist and a Chinese
tourist? Answer: The Japanese tourist is the one with the camera
around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   I'm certain there is something similar about the American
tourist, likely an image of the guy in the black socks, but the
conundrum facing the would-be terrorist is whether the guy with the
camera around his neck is a Japanese Japanese or a
Japanese-American. Is the lady speaking French a French French
lady, or is she a French-American?
</P>
<P>
   We think we stick out as Americans wherever we go, yet if we
dress other than outlandishly and keep our voices down to a simple
shout, we should blend in fairly well with much of the world's
population. That's because most of us have hyphenated credentials,
as in Greek-American, or German-American.
</P>
<P>
   The detention of Japanese-Americans during our war with Japan
has had a history of infamy, in this case not because they looked
American but because they looked Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   And if an American is difficult to spot overseas, just think of
the confusion that goes on in this country where myriad languages
are spoken by U.S. citizens. The danger, beyond terrorism, is that
one kind of American becomes suspicious of another kind of American
simply because that person looks different; also a terrorism of a
kind. This stereotyping must be avoided in our quest to make our
own country safe from terrorism, lest we repeat what we did to
Japanese-Americans in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   In my morning jaunt in the park each day, I am passed by women
speaking Farsi (the language of Iran), by two couples going at it
in Chinese (I know this because I see them often in the
neighborhood Chinese restaurant), by many speaking Spanish. Rather
than the Tower of Babel, it is the Pathway of Babel.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, at a sports event, we were seated next to four
men who were speaking a language that I could not identify beyond
Eastern European. Finally, I asked one of them what language he was
speaking. Romanian, he responded. ``Where in Romania do you live?''
I asked just to appear interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Romania,'' he answered. ``Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, like so many of us, is a hyphenated American, a
Romanian-American. Is there something about that I should suspect?
</P>
<P>
   We are black, white and olive-skinned. Despite the few obnoxious
among us, if we act as ordinary as the natives of whatever country
we're in, we won't stick out as American.
</P>
<P>
   There is appropriate concern about terrorism, particularly
overseas. And there are cautions we must follow. But the idea that
any American can be singled out simply by ``looking'' American is a
stretch. We are too diversified.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep the camera in your pocket and the black calf-length
socks back in the hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
