<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HACKING INTO THE NEW MILLENNIUM
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's Y2K czar, John Koskinen, has
asked computer hackers to stand down around the first of the year
because ``we are going to have enough things going on that
weekend'' without their added input.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI and the Defense Department doubt that determined
intruders will honor Koskinen's request. Both agencies have warned
of potential New Year's cyber-attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Such warnings make news because the long-heralded ``network of
networks'' we know as the Internet has finally emerged as a true
mass communications medium. Upwards of 140 million people, 100
million of them in the United States, now have regular access to
online facilities. There are more than 4 million commercial sites
on the World Wide Web; their number grows at an exponential rate.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Internet will radically change how we shop, play and
work in the new millennium. What won't change is some people's
desire to challenge authority or to vent their curiosity along
illegal paths.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture of the Internet permits hackers to ``bomb''
selected sites. The sites fail in much the same way as an emergency
911 service would fail if a thousand calls were placed at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not hard for hackers to capture Internet addresses and
spoof them. A few years ago, after the home page of the Central
Intelligence Agency was hacked by a Swedish group, visitors were
greeted by a message that read: ``Welcome to the Central Stupidity
Agency.''
</P>
<P>
   But most cyber-cops aren't stupid. Within a day, the FBI tracked
down a Florida teenager who had sent threatening e-mail to a
student at Colorado's Columbine High School, still recovering from
a mass murder. The alleged offender, who faces serious federal
charges, would have been harder to find had he used an anonymous
remailer in, say, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, merely reading a New Year's e-mail message couldn't
spawn a computer virus, although that's recently changed with
``bubbleboy,'' a self-executing virus that does no serious harm. In
any event, the worst thing that can happen to you is a wholesale
loss of data on an infected computer, all of which can be recovered
so long as prudent backup procedures are in place.
</P>
<P>
   People who run espionage networks, nuclear missile sites and
electric power grids use another means to safeguard them against
cyberattacks: they decouple ``mission-critical'' computers from the
Internet. Meantime, other government agencies are busy devising
ways to wage cyber-warfare against future potential enemies who
might lack the sense to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   My employer bars all but a favored few from accessing e-mail
messages from beyond the closed corporate network. That rule
defeats a central tenet of the Internet: the ability to reach any
server from any other server.
</P>
<P>
   The company's security mavens fear that granting the staff
permission to use e-mail at, say, at an airport kiosk, might permit
a hacker to penetrate their firewall and thereby plant a phony news
story or mess up the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   It's a legitimate concern. But the risk would go way if the
``post office'' were moved outside the firewall. While that's easy
to do, it's not a high priority for cybergate guardians at the dawn
of a century with a full quota of both hi-tech risks and promises.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
