<SLUG> BC-FATHERXMAS-ESSAY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remembering Father at Christmas
 &HT;    By Mary Schulken
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ She learned to dance on Daddy's wingtip toes,
clutching gray wool pants, face buried in an itchy shirt that
smelled of woodsmoke, Skin Bracer and whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Around the hardwood floor they lurched, laughing, in the glow of
colored lights from the tree, while Mitch Miller sang about mommy
kissing Santa Claus, and Spike Jones wished for his two front
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   She a scrawny tomboy with ponytail and cowboy boots. He a
thick-middled man with a square jaw, glasses and day-old shadow on
his cheeks. The dancing would go on for a while. It was Christmas
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around they whirled, to the silly songs that were
their favorites. In the fireplace limbs from the big oak popped as
flames licked the lichens from dry bark. The dancing stopped only
when the record did and they paused to choose another. He was
breathless; she was eager to go on, and as happy as she can ever
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a Christmas moon turned fields and woods white against
the darkness. Soon they would walk, little hand and big hand, into
that night, under the big oak, and pause to examine odd marks in
the dirt he gravely said were made by hooves. When he pointed to
the sky, she could see it, the tiny dot across the moon, and hear
the tinkling of a bell.
</P>
<P>
   She could hear it later, too, from the foot of her bed, looking
out the window at an expectant sky, deaf to his footfalls one room
away as he put together swingsets and bicycles, and propped up baby
dolls.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost all she has of him now, those memories. That, and
the way the letters of his name are warm to the touch on a sunny
day where they are carved into granite. She was a girl when he went
away. She was a woman before she missed enough of what she lost to
grieve.
</P>
<P>
   The father, she knew. The man, she did not.
</P>
<P>
   The father rescued her kitten from the falling-down outhouse,
coaxing it to safety before the floor gave way and plunged him into
the heart of darkness in his shorty pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The man went to war instead of college, came home to parents who
needed him and a woman he had loved four years long distance. Some
nights, he pounded his fists on the kitchen table. Brown liquid
from a bottle carried him to a place it took her years to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   She wonders what he would think now about the grown woman whose
face so bears his likeness in cheekbone and expression. Whose hands
are like his. Whose mind carries the same hard edge that made him a
man whose opinions were sought, even without a college education.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been here for so much of her life.
</P>
<P>
   But he is here on brittle December nights, when a moon lights
each bare branch, and limbs clatter with a frosty breeze.
</P>
<P>
   He is here, in the latest rockabilly crooning about Santa, or in
the faintest jingle of a holiday bell.
</P>
<P>
   He is here every Christmas Eve, squiring her around the room
with his feet, and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ordinary thing for fathers to dance daughters on their
toes, to leave the print of reindeer hooves in the dust of a
driveway, to point at a moonlit sky, inspiring hopes as bright as
the star of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   But the memories of those things are not ordinary. They are not
like swingsets, baby dolls or bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   They do not wear out with use, or gather dust as time goes by.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Schulken is editorial page editor of The Daily Reflector in
Greenville, N.C. Her e-mail address is mschulken(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
