r k BC-LANE-COLUMN24-COX     12-23 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday tome still gives the answers
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The Encyclopaedia Britannica may have
moved from bicep-building bindings to airy blips of digital data
but a few reference works remain that can be aimlessly browsed by
the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   I speak here of ``The Big Book of Christmas and Christmaslike
Phenomena.'' Brought out of the Christmas box for another year of
reference, its duct-taped spine still supple, the book remains a
font of holiday lore.
</P>
<P>
   You'd look in vain to find such patient expositions of the
season's mysteries anywhere else. Consider these sample entries:
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL CAROLING _ Technological advances now allow mankind to
hear holiday songs performed in animal sounds. First barking dogs
singing ``Jingle Bells'' then cats, chirping birds and llamas (''A
Very Inca Christmas'' Fourth World Records, 1982). Legislative bans
found unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``BLUE CHRISTMAS'' _ ``The greatest song the mind of man has yet
composed'' _ M.R. ``Bob'' Carmellow, ``A Tear in the Eggnog:
Studies in Holiday Melancholia.''
</P>
<P>
   CASH REGISTER BELLS ARE JINGLING _ Still, the No. 1 Christmas
journalism cliche even though the last documented cash register
with a jingling bell was retired in 1992. See ``optimistic
merchants'' under ``Christmas Journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CHRISTIANS AND THE PAGANS'' _ Dar Williams' song is unique for
taking on the teeth-gritting tensions of holiday religious
differences. Wiccans and Christians manage dinner and family truce.
The editors prefer this even to John Prine's ``Christmas in
Prison,'' which remains the No. 1, penal-theme Christmas song.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS WREATH IN A CAN _ See ``Notable Holiday Marketing
Failures.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS HAIKU _ The winner of this year's Christmas Haiku
Contest:
</P>
<P>
   Who is Pokeman?
</P>
<P>
   And why am I fighting for
</P>
<P>
   Cards in Japanese?
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS TREE, PERFECTLY STRAIGHT _ See ``Christmas
Mythology.''
</P>
<P>
   ELECTO-TREE _ Although this product was a useful tool for
training cats to respect holiday decorations, civil-liability
issues halted its manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   FOURTH WISE MAN _ Variously identified as Zeppo, Pete Best and
Shemp. An oddly persistent Christmas legend, which, like the rubber
cigar, is without scriptural basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT IS IRONIC AT THIS TIME OF GOODWILL TOWARD MAN ...'' _ See
``Top 10 TV-News Lead-Ins'' under ``Christmas Journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   LANDSAT RULE _ The Landsat Rule states that outdoor Christmas
decorations are excessive if they show up in routine satellite
photos or confuse aircraft navigation.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT CHRISTMAS _ A mythical time when trees slip into their
stands and children are happy, clean and grateful. Teen-agers stay
home, children get their lines right in the pageant and everyone in
the photograph has his or her eyes open. Cards are mailed on time.
Credit is used responsibly. The last present is wrapped on Dec. 20
and everything is neatly boxed, labeled and stored by Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ORIENTAR (or-EE-en-TAR) _ When asked ``Where were the Three
Kings from?'' 80 percent of respondents say ``Orientar.'' Two
percent motion somewhere down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ORNAMENT-HOOK BALLS _ Nobody knows why metal Christmas ornament
hooks entwine themselves into balls while in storage. Mental health
professionals urge you to spend 98 cents on new hooks rather than
attempting to undo them. Spray-paint the mass and hang it on the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   REINDEER GAMES _ Their exact nature remains obscure. Lack of
opposable thumbs would seem to rule out ``Tomb Raider.''
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA _ The best-known newspaper editorial in the history of
journalism appeared in the New York Sun in 1897. It was not about
peace or justice. It did not expose corruption. It assured a little
girl named Virginia that Santa Claus lives. The public has received
editorial page assurances with a degree of skepticism ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
