<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ted Kennedy, senator of the century
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He is aging, rumpled and overweight. His family
has suffered hurts, embarrassments and cruel deaths. But Ted
Kennedy is still pushing hard for America's old, young, infirm and
downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, now 67, has been senator from Massachusetts since his
election in 1962 at the minimum constitutional age of 30. In the
years since, he has been trying incessantly to make the American
government help its people who cannot help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Lt. Gov. Ben Barnes introduced him at a recent
Austin fund-raiser as ``the senator of the century,'' who
``particularly in the area of human rights and equal opportunity
has had greater impact ... than even many presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America appreciates so much what you've done for those without
a voice,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, up for re-election next year, is also the target of
much venom from those who think he's the poster child for amoral,
baby-killing, tax-loving, big-government liberals who will destroy
the country. He's the bogeyman that conservative Republicans, and
particularly their direct-mail fund-raisers, love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   But the combination of his famous family history and his
longtime advocacy for liberal causes allows Kennedy to draw a
devoted crowd of Democrats anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand for education,'' Kennedy told 200 Democrats at a
fund-raiser Dec. 10 at Austin's Capitol Marriott Hotel. ``We stand
to try to include a fount of opportunity and hope for people in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Boston-Austin axis was created with the 1960 Democratic
ticket of John Kennedy and Texan Lyndon Johnson, it made access to
college a battleground against the GOP ticket headed by Richard
Nixon, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson believed that every young
person ought to be able to gain entrance to any college that they
were qualified to enter,'' Kennedy said. After the election, the
program was structured to have three-fourths of the aid in the form
of grants _ to avoid the ``very significant kinds of debts which
they have today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to any of the children at any of the (graduate) schools,
and you will find out that any time that they have a recess, that
they're talking about their debts, rather than talking about the
books that they're reading and should be learning about in their
classrooms,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who sponsored the Family and Medical Leave Act that
President Bush vetoed but President Clinton later signed, chaired
the Senate committee that oversees health and human services from
1987 until the Republicans took back the Senate in 1994. Since
then, he has largely played defense, trying to protect Medicare and
Medicaid and opposing Republican changes in labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   While crediting Texas with allowing remedies against health
maintenance organizations, Kennedy said the battle is still to be
fought nationally to ensure ``that we're going to have the doctors
and the trained personnel that are treating patients making the
medical decisions, and not accountants for the major industries in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, he said, ``stand for decent health care, quality
health care, expanding health care _ for working families in this
country, and for the senior citizens. ... And we're not going to
let the Republicans undermine that.''
</P>
<P>
   Texan Bob Mann, Kennedy's press secretary in the mid-1980s who
now teaches news writing at the University of Texas at Austin, was
impressed at Kennedy's stamina a dozen years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has enormous resilience,'' Mann said. ``Although he's now
pushing 70, he has maintained his idealism. He still gets to the
root of a problem and sees hypocrisy _ like senators who voted for
a $4,600-a-year pay raise for themselves, but against a 50-cent an
hour raise in the minimum wage for a single mother with three
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He continues to represent those nobody else does: the poor,
the elderly, the young, the minorities, the sick, those who do not
have people in Washington looking after them,'' Mann said. ``And
his resilience in doing that, in spite of the loss of family member
after family member, in spite of losing some political battles, is
just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
