<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This is the way world ends: Mad dash to next time zone
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Forget the computers.
</P>
<P>
   We should know the true significance of Y2K by watching Dibble
Glacier.
</P>
<P>
   If in fact the new year has any significance beyond a few coffee
makers spewing calve's blood, the glacier will tell us. For if the
world ends at the stroke of 2000, it ends starting right there.
</P>
<P>
   And if if does, a lot of people will be hurrying west and
rapidly praying.
</P>
<P>
   They'll have an hour, eight, 12, to make right with the heavenly
landlord, or buy time racing the sun before the sifter separates
wheat from chaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Father, who art in New Zealand. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Dibble Glacier is on the Antarctic rim. No computers, just ice.
It does have a sunrise, which is a distinction. Most of Antarctica
has no sunset in December.
</P>
<P>
   The permanently inhabited place that will have the first sunrise
of 2000 is Kahuitara Point on Pitt Island, one of New Zealand's
Chatham Islands.
</P>
<P>
   It will happen while Americans slumber on the morning of Dec.
31, 3:49 a.m. Texas time.
</P>
<P>
   The thing about the Y2K computer threat is that by the time it
reaches America the world will be half disrupted already.
</P>
<P>
   Or not.
</P>
<P>
   On even more pressing matters, if the sum of Earth's insisting
has convinced even God to believe the hype that millennia converge
on the stroke of 2000 (they don't) _ or if God decides to jettison
the whole party just to show us who's in charge ...
</P>
<P>
   The way Y2K arrives on the globe means that while we sleep the
morning before the big night, The End already will have begun in
some time zones.
</P>
<P>
   All of us will know when we awake on New Year's Eve morning. Al
Roker will be able to tell us.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us will be able to count on our fingers how many hours
we have left in paradise, without a convincing appeal for a grace
period.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most Americans will be playing down the risks.
They'll assume that any mass depopulation starting in the South
Pacific and sweeping across Asia and Europe is one of those El Nino
things. Or La Nina. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that will bring stark reality home would be
seeing Dick Clark wither under his top coat as the Times Square
ball drops.
</P>
<P>
   Bad example. Nothing withers Dick Clark. He will outlive all
planetary life.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a dangerously mortal president will be the coal-mine
canary, Armageddon-wise. If they see Bill Clinton deflate at the
stroke of 12 like a Bullwinkle float impaled on a street light,
Americans will know things are serious, state-side.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news is that except for those on the East Coast,
there will still be time to make things right. We just have to pray
real hard or run real fast.
</P>
<P>
   We've been hearing how monitoring the Y2K computer-time glitch,
time zone by time zone, will be like watching the Wave at your
local stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If Y2K is the end-of-time glitch, salvation-wise, it will be
played out in waves on west-bound interstates.
</P>
<P>
   West Texans in fear for their ever-afters will swarm New
Mexico's adobe chapels, where they'd have a whole extra hour to
save their souls.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush could use the time to dispatch Gideons to jammed
interstates to make futile flight fruitful. Or maybe he'll figure
he needs some chapel time for himself or a swift plane.
</P>
<P>
   When Y2K meets the West Coast, body surfers will be flailing
into the white caps to save their souls, literally.
</P>
<P>
   And in Hawaii, people will be frantic to catch the next flight
to Samoa. That's where the day will be done, the first day of 2000
on this planet. Or the last. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The glacier should tell us everything.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
