r e BC-BOOKS-MILNER24-COX     12-23 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More ideas on giving books as Christmas gifts
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Books for Christmas gifts deux:
</P>
<P>
   University presses are continuing to produce quality books of
the type and content that once came from regular trade publishing
houses. That was before just about every major and minor commercial
publisher was bitten by the Blockbuster Bug, meaning they decided
somewhere along the line to reject all books that they decided
would not be best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Not every book published by these commercial publishers meet
that mark, of course. It's still a matter of judgement, luck, fate,
and who-knows-what-all that pushes a novel or nonfiction volume
into the blockbuster category. But publishers keep trying to make
their allegedly educated guesses confined to the Big Bucks Books,
which they continue to find is not even as easy to do as choosing
which movie will make it big at the box office. Certain movie stars
will pull a certain number of fans into the movie theaters, at
least for the first few days until word-of-mouth has time to make
the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But we were talking about university presses, and books for
Christmas gifts to good friends and relatives. Here are a few
samples of what we mean:
</P>
<P>
   One discussed here not long ago is Larry L. King's hefty book of
letters titled ``A Life in Letters, or Reflections From a Bloodshot
Eye,'' (Texas Christian University Press). This one is a lot of fun
to read and is informative about the life and times of a writer.
</P>
<P>
   King, the one who writes for a living, not the guy on TV, is a
West Texas native who moved to Washington, D.C., some years ago to
tub thump for a West Texas congressman but sometime in the 1960s
decided to chuck all the benefits and safety nets provided a
congressional assistant and devote full time to writing. Friends
called him crazy, for that and other reasons, but the husky,
aggressive rascal made a go of it and then some.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote several books but his greatest success was, and is, the
Broadway hit he co-wrote called ``The Best Little Whorehouse in
Texas.'' He has made millions from that effort.
</P>
<P>
   But one doesn't have to be a writer or even interested in
writing and writers to enjoy King's book of letters, written to
friends, relatives, business associates and enemies over the years.
(There are even several to yours truly and other names you will no
doubt recognize, some are celebrities and some aren't.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have friends or relatives living in West Texas, or once
lived out there in what used to be call The Great American Desert,
a fine gift might be a new release by the Texas Tech Press titled
``West Texas: A Portrait of its People and Their Raw and Wondrous
Land'' by Mike Cochran and John Lumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is one of those coffee table books with plenty
of gorgeous photographs to go with the text written by two veteran
newspapermen _ Cochran covered West Texas for The Associated Press
for nearly 40 years and Lumpkin is currently AP Bureau Chief for
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A foreword is written by John T. Montford, president of Texas
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a really dandy University of North Texas reprint in
hardback by the creator of the popular series, ``Hank, the
Cowdog,'' about life as a cowboy titled ``Panhandle Cowboy,'' with
a foreword by Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist Larry McMurtry, who,
by the way, has a new book of essays out that would make a fine
Christmas gift titled ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen.''
McMurtry, the author of ``Lonesome Dove'' and other best-selling
novels, chats informally about his life growing up in Archer City,
Texas, growing famous as a writer and learning to cope with a heart
attack, among other human things. This is one of my favorite books
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And we mustn't forget that fascinating nonfiction ``Confessions
of Mad Dog'' by Jay Dunston Milner. It's a University of North
Texas Press release.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
