<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX     12-23 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home for the holidays and a spot of cash
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My daughters came home from college last
week, eager for a break from the rigors of studying, attending
University of Texas football games, and staying up far too late on
weekends doing . . . well, I don't want to know. Let's not go
there, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   Being a father, the first question out of my mouth is, ``So, how
did you do this semester?'' Kasey, the oldest, proudly proclaimed
she had once again made all A's, which means she's headed into her
final semester of undergraduate work with a 3.96 or so average. Two
B's in three-and-half-years, the rest A's. She's such an
overachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Kasey has a terrific work ethic, which she inherited from her
mother (who graduated in three years), and she has the ability to
work long hours, party too late, and then get up and study for a
test, a talent she got from me.
</P>
<P>
   OK, she didn't get the last part from me. I would work long
hours and stay up way too late discussing philosophy over a case of
generic beer. Remember generic beer? You could buy it at Kroger. It
just said ``BEER'' in black type on a white background and cost
$1.39 a six pack. Generic beer was brewed by Pearl, meaning I guess
that it was the bottom of the vat, down where the sediment sinks _
Pearl beer not exactly being a premium brew anyway. After the first
half-dozen cans, it really wasn't that bad, at least from the
perspective of a dirt-poor college student who used to sell plasma
for gas money.
</P>
<P>
   My trouble was, I could work long hours and party late, but I
generally didn't follow through on the studying part. I remember
more than a few classes in which my attendance was spotty enough
that the professor didn't recognize me when I showed at office
hours to try to catch up. I didn't make bad grades, graduating in
four-and-a-half years with a GPA a tad over a `B' average, the
beneficiary of laid-back instructors and friends who took good
notes. But there wasn't any ``cum laude'' written after my name,
not that it mattered much since I always knew I'd end up
newspapering anyhow. What mattered in that line of work was, well,
the ability to work long hours and party late.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Goose, the youngest daughter, who is finishing her
first semester at UT. Goose looks just like her mother but has the
same scholastic willpower I had _ in other words, not much. She
took a rugged course load her first semester of four courses and no
job, and finally confessed that best-case scenario was one A, two
B's and a C. Worst-case scenario, meaning what likely will happen,
is two B's and two C's.
</P>
<P>
   I asked what happened. She shrugged and said, ``I partied too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to ``The dog ate my homework,'' or, ``I
couldn't take the stress,'' or ``I'm dealing with some anxiety
issues right now?'' The child took a disarmingly honest approach
that left me a bit nonplussed. Kasey said she's going to enroll
Goose in a remedial course in how to deceive your parents, a course
in which Kasey graduated as valedictorian.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Kasey reports that Goose told her mother and stepfather
that she skipped too many classes. What's wrong with the child? Has
she not learned to lie? Good lord, she's in college, for pete's
sake, a time to stretch the boundaries, explore new frontiers _ and
make danged sure your parents never find out about it, at least as
long as you're still on their payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Her honesty forced me to deliver the stern-father lecture,
complete with the requisite threat about paying for one's own
college if things didn't improve. She promised to do better and
said this was all part of a master plan. She figured, she said,
that she could blow off the first semester and get it all out of
her system, then get serious the next go-round. Good story. Maybe
she is learning how to snow the parents.
</P>
<P>
   At least I had the advantage in my college career of being
solely in charge of paying for my own education, which meant I only
had to answer to myself for my slacker attitude.
</P>
<P>
   There's a thought. Maybe I'll offer to never bother her again
about her grades if she agrees to pay her own way through.
</P>
<P>
   What are the odds? She may not have the college-student parental
deception routine down quite right just yet, but she's no dummy.
Take the check, take the lecture, and take her chances that she'll
do better. I'm sure she will. If not, she can always go into the
newspaper business.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail; gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
