<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, December 24, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   FATHERXMAS-ESSAY _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ She learned to dance on
Daddy's wingtip toes, clutching gray wool pants, face buried in an
itchy shirt that smelled of woodsmoke, Skin Bracer and whiskey. A
Christmas essay from the editorial page editor of the Greenville
Daily Reflector. (Schulken, Greenville Daily Reflector) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The Encyclopaedia Britannica
may have moved from bicep-building bindings to airy blips of
digital data but a few reference works remain that can be aimlessly
browsed by the fireplace. I speak here of ``The Big Book of
Christmas and Christmaslike Phenomena.'' Brought out of the
Christmas box for another year of reference, its duct-taped spine
still supple, the book remains a font of holiday lore. You'd look
in vain to find such patient expositions of the season's mysteries
anywhere else. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Do you believe everything you
read? After perusing this list of ``little known facts'' e-mailed
to me by a friend, I have to admit some of these items are a little
far-fetched. But then again, the same can be said about astrology
and wrestling. (Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin
Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My daughters came home
from college last week, eager for a break from the rigors of
studying, attending University of Texas football games, and staying
up far too late on weekends doing . . . well, I don't want to know.
Let's not go there, as they say. (Gary Borders is editor and
publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He is aging, rumpled and
overweight. His family has suffered hurts, embarrassments and cruel
deaths. But Ted Kennedy is still pushing hard for America's old,
young, infirm and downtrodden. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Forget the computers. We should
know the true significance of Y2K by watching Dibble Glacier. If in
fact the new year has any significance beyond a few coffee makers
spewing calve's blood, the glacier will tell us. For if the world
ends at the stroke of 2000, it ends starting right there. And if if
does, a lot of people will be hurrying west and rapidly praying.
(John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
