<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, December
24, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WALKER _ ATLANTA _ Emory University professor Vanessa Siddle
Walker is a rising star in academia. She recently was awarded the
prestigious Grawemeyer prize _ it comes with $200,000 _ for a book
she authored that details the success of a black school in the
segregated south. We take a look at her life and explore her
controversial views on education. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-LAUDER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Evelyn Lauder is a woman
of diverse passions. Dubbed ``America's First Lady of Beauty,''
she's the senior corporate vice president of the Estee Lauder
companies, the cosmetics empire founded by her mother-in-law. She's
the founder and president of the Breast Cancer Research Foundation,
which has handed out more than $13.5 million in grants since 1993.
(Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CAROLEE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Carolee Friedlander's journey
from struggling homemaker to super CEO is the stuff of which
entrepreneurial legends are made. Back in 1972, the young mother of
three started stringing necklaces at her kitchen table. From those
humble beginnings sprang an eponymous jewelry empire. (Sturrock,
Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   HOLY LAND PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Holy Land will be bursting with milennium
tourists and celebrants. But where better to be than following the
footsteps of Jesus. Special Israel section. Lots of art. Lede-in to
package. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBARS
</P>
<P>
   GALILEE _ MOUNT OF BEATITUDES, Israel _ A tour bus stopped on
the slope of the Mount of the Beatitudes to let passengers watch a
shepherd herding his sheep. Except for his leather jacket and khaki
pants, he could have stepped from a scene 2,000 years ago. These
are the images that bring the Bible to life for many people and the
reason they make the long trip to Israel. More than the churches
and monuments, it is the gentle hills, the silver-blue beauty of
the Sea of Galilee and the rushing water of the River Jordan that
draw people to Galilee. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEGIDDO _ MEGIDDO, Israel _ When the final battle between good
and evil is fought, the book of Revelation tells us, it will be
fought here at a mountain at the entrance to the Jezreel Valley.
The mountain is called, in Hebrew, Har Megiddo, the Hill of
Megiddo. Bastardized by the Greeks, this battlefield became known
as Harmagedon. Today, Armageddon. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAALULA _ MAALULA, Syria _ If you want to travel 2,000 years
back in time, to hear words like those spoken by Jesus and his
contemporaries in Jerusalem farther to the south, this stunning
oasis is the place to do it. (Salome, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1221 -- The millennium is prompting millions of
pilgrims to trace Jesus' life through the Holy Land. (Belkin, Palm
Beach Post) Art includes 3-column color photo of Church of the
Nativity, an 18-pica color photo of tourists along the River Jordan
and a 1-column color photo of a mosaic at the huch of the
Multiplication of the Loaves.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CHRIST'S JOURNEY -- Touring the landmarks of Jesus' life
proves an exhilarating journey. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) Art
includes 3-column color photo of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AFRICAN EXHIBIT -- The Smithsonian's new exhibit,
``African Voices,'' tells the complete story of a continent often
misunderstood. (Dart, Cox Washington Bureau) Art includes a
2-column color photo museum director standing beside an African
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Timekeeping is the centerpiece of a
museum in Columbia, Pa. Now that museum has more space to devote to
time. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ HELEN, Ga. _ Helen, the Bavarian-style town 90 minutes
north of Atlanta, isn't just a great place to gorge yourself on
beer and bratwurst and boogie to an oompah beat. The village _
straight out of a child's storybook _ boasts more than 200 stores,
many stocked with unusual imports and toys even Santa's elves might
envy. (Laughinghouse, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not
for use by NYTNS clients). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-YEARSBEST _ Steve Murray analyzes this year's movies and
names the Top 10 (in alphabetical order), including ``Magnolia''
and ``American Beauty.'' (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GALAXY _ ``Galaxy Quest.'' Sci-fi spoof as aliens kidnap
cast of popular Star Trek-like vehicle. Opens Christmas Day. Grade:
C+ (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-MANSFIELD _ ``Mansfield Park,'' based on Jane Austen's
book and supposedly featuring sex scenes. Opens Christmas Day.
Grade: C. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-RIPLEY _ ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' with Matt Damon,
Gwyneth Paltrow and Jude Law. Pretty to look at but not as gripping
as the book or the ealier version ``Purple Noon.'' Opens Christmas
Day. Grade: B. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-CIDER _ ``Cider House Rules.'' B-. (Larsen, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BOYS _ ``Boys Don't Cry.'' Dramatizes the real-life murder
of Teena Brandon (a k a Brandon Teena), a cross-dressing young
woman. 3 stars. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-LIBERTY _ ``Liberty Heights.'' Director Barry Levinson
returns to Baltimore for another hometown reminiscence, with Bebe
Neuwirth and Joe Mantegna. 2 stars. (Salamon, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-YEARSBEST _ Year end music wrap package -- the best of
1999. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 1223 _ Here are 10 programs that defined
the decade in television. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 2-column color photo of a gavel, a 1-column color photo of
Judge Judy and a 3-column color photo of Bart Simpson, and 2-column
color photos from ``America's Funniest Home Videos,'' Larry King,
``Friends,'' ``The X-Files,'' ``Biography,'' ``ER,'' ``Today,''
Oprah Winfrey, Jerry Springer and ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ A pyrotechnic celebration of style over
substance, this knetic German film ``Run, Lola, Run,'' is the
cinematic love child of every video game and MTV quick-cut editing
trick of the past 10 years.''Also reviews of ``Summer of Sam,'' and
``American Pie.'' (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes an 18-pica
color photo from ``Run, Lola, Run.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Reviews of the latest releases by Buddy Miller,
Susan Ibarra, Goodie Mob. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE _ After a year of heavy emotions, the Indigo Girls
look forward to the coming new year. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes one 1-column color photo of the
Indigo Girls.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-IN-REVIEW _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was not the worst of
times, but it certainly wasn't the best of times. 1999 was a pretty
good year for books, although it seemed to me that the bigger they
were, the less they lived up to expectations. (Eyman, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MIDNIGHT-CAROL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``A Midnight Carol'' is
a novel about the writing of ``A Christmas Carol,'' but Patricia
Davis is smart enough not to make it a gloss on that great story.
Instead, it's essentially a rewrite of ``It's a Wonderful Life,''
without the divine intervention. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 1221 -- Author James Redfield, writer of ``The
Celestine Prophecy,'' offers up some more spiritual enlightenment
in his latest book (Salamon, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 2-column color photo of Redman and a 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW STERN -- Isaac Stern recalls his life as a musician
and his efforts as a global citizen. (Passy, Palm Beach Post) Art
includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket and a 1-column color
photo of Stern.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW MCMURTY -- Pulitzer-winning author Larry McMurty
has put together the closest thing you'll see to his autobiograhy.
(Milner, Longview News-Journal ) Art includes 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Author Joseph Heller's work captured the
dark mood of a nation. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 1-column color photo of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES: Cameraman Freddie Young has put together
his memoirs and the results are wonderfully in focus. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Don O'Briant's book notes. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Books for Christmas gifts deux: University presses
are continuing to produce quality books of the type and content
that once came from regular trade publishing houses. That was
before just about every major and minor commercial publisher was
bitten by the Blockbuster Bug, meaning they decided somewhere along
the line to reject all books that they decided would not be best
sellers. (Milner, Lufkin Daily News). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TV-YEARSBEST _ From ``The Sopranos'' to ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' our TV writers name their top 10 shows of the year.
(Kloer/Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
