<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAM' A GEM FROM LEE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SUMMER OF SAM'
</P>
<P>
   If Spike Lee directed glossy films with A-list stars like
Gwyneth Paltrow and strategic year-end release dates, perhaps he'd
be getting Oscar buzz now.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   He does the right thing: He makes films for himself, not
tunnel-visioned Oscar voters, and his ``Summer of Sam'' is the
latest in a line of personal triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the Bronx, N.Y., in the sizzling summer of '77 _ when Lee
was coming of age in Brooklyn _ ``Sam'' recounts the grisly
lovers'-lane murders of David Berkowitz, who used the nickname
``Son of Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's more about a vivid sense of time and place than serial
killings, a cliched movie device that in this rare case happens to
be based on fact.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz (played by ``The Practice's'' Michael Badalucco) is
simply another incendiary spark in the interlocked lives of
tumultuous young adults driven by the debauchery of the disco era.
Chief among them are a philandering hairdresser (John Leguizamo)
and his sweet waitress wife (Mira Sorvino).
</P>
<P>
   We also meet a crime lord (Ben Gazzara), a punk rocker (Adrien
Brody) and other neighborhood poseurs and toughs immersed in drugs,
sex and profane belligerence.
</P>
<P>
   As deaths mount, vigilante justice rears its head, with neighbor
suspecting neighbor, and with relationships already strained by
reckless hedonism nearing the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   This is Lee's first film that does not address the black
experience; he plays the only prominent black character, an
amusingly deliberate TV reporter.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Sam'' does consider issues involving prejudice,
intolerance and being an outsider or scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Be wary. This is not for everyone. It's a raw, harrowing,
gripping film that can be perversely amusing and brutally
sensational.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a film with a strikingly original vision, an
indifference to Hollywood formula and a resounding sense of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for sales, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PIE'
</P>
<P>
   What's the fuss? Even the unrated version of this notorious teen
comedy is about as daring as a routine ``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head''
episode _ and about as stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The premise involves randy teens looking for love in all the
wrong places on the eve of high school graduation. Four guys are
especially desperate to lose their virginity, though they just
might learn there's more to life.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, do you think? Stop me if you've heard this.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of largely unknowns tries mightily to elevate the
material above its witless self-gratification, yet they wallow in
cliches and gross-out gags.
</P>
<P>
   But give the film this: It refreshingly avoids the
mean-spiritedness _ if not hatefulness _ afflicting so many teen
tales. Its characters may be misguided, but they aren't wicked or
spiteful.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for all their sexual adventurism, they have a certain
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Is such a thing still allowed in high school?
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R and unrated versions available, Universal, CC, VHS
priced for rental, DVD $29.98 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RUN LOLA RUN'
</P>
<P>
   This boldly stylized German film hurls the alternate-path
premise of ``Sliding Doors'' in wildly divergent directions.
</P>
<P>
   Lola (Franka Potente), a young woman in Berlin, gets a frantic
call from her lover (Moritz Bleibtreu). He ran an errand for a
crime boss but lost the cash. He'll be dead in 20 minutes if he or
Lola don't find a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   This sends Lola racing to help,2and we see three drastically
different turns in her life, each hinging on slight variations on
her trip (a moment's delay can change everything).
</P>
<P>
   The film seems to cheer on its criminals, but Lola and her lover
are humanized in flashbacks, and her dedication is redeeming in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It's also fun piecing together the plot, like a puzzle that
interlocks in different ways to form different visions. Methodical
in its bedQ%Qions yet bracingly accelerated in snap-shot narrative
moments, ``Lola'' is a harrowing yet rewarding ride.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Columbia TriStar, in German with English subtitles, VHS
priced for rental, DVD $27.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CITY' ROCKS ON DVD
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit Rock City'' is a rarity, if not a first: It arrives
this week on DVD three weeks before its Jan. 11 debut on VHS.
</P>
<P>
   Since the latter format remains home video's dominant medium,
the film's review in this space will wait until that time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT SPIRIT
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the independent spirit of ``American Movie'' _
the documentary about a struggling director of a no-budget horror
film _ fans will get to choose its video box art.
</P>
<P>
   The choices are shown at www.americanmovie.com.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we checked, the leading vote-getter was the art
already used in the posters and print ads.
</P>
