<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-KALEIDOSCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KALEIDOSCAPE: IT'S BACK TO THE BIG TOP FOR NEWEST SHOW ON EARTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Step through the giant O that serves as entry to Barnum's
Kaleidoscape and discover a world gone glad.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the luxurious lobby tent, a street urchin in a
patchwork dress and bright red boots teaches children how to
Hula-Hoop. Watching the lessons is a tuxedo-clad man, who holds his
petite partner in the palm of his hand, high above the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, tumblers amaze all with their flips and flops
as a zany British band belts out an energetic rendition of ``Has
Anybody Seen My Girl?''
</P>
<P>
   Onlookers wander from wonder to wonder, munching on gourmet
veggie wraps and Wolfgang Puck pizza bought from old-fashioned
circus wagons that circle the performers. A few settle into red
velvet sofas to gaze up at the kaleidoscope images dancing on the
tent's ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   And this is just the pre-show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A RETURN TO TENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kaleidoscape made its world premiere last April in Los Angeles
and is on a 50-week tour.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million production features 62 performers and unfolds
under tents, the first Ringling Bros. circus to do so since 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Feld, chairman and chief executive officer of Feld
Entertainment, is the creative force behind Kaleidoscape.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Irvin Feld _ who revitalized Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus in the late '50s by moving the shows from
tents to more profitable venues such as arenas _ Feld envisioned a
one-ring, upscale circus that would appeal not only to traditional
circus lovers but to the theater-going crowd as well. Montreal's
Cirque du Soleil and others like it have proved that hybrid
audience exists.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaleidoscape is no mere Cirque wannabe. Critics across the
country have raved about the new show, and in many cities, runs
have been extended. The diverse audience includes the obvious
toddlers, parents and grandparents, plus teens, twentysomethings
and others who have heard about the show through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LET THE FUN BEGIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fun actually begins one hour prior to show time. As
circusgoers approach the striking white-and-red tents, a group of
dancers welcomes them with fancy footwork and Moroccan music.
Inside, the elaborate pre-show is under way. Ticket-holders can
mingle with performers, have dinner or check out Kaleidoscape
merchandise that's for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Feld designed the circus to flow like a party. The pre-show, he
says, is a vital part of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I invited somebody over to my house for a party, they'd
come to the front door and knock. They'd enter the living room,
have a drink and hors d'oeuvres, and get to know everybody,'' Feld
explains. ``The pre-show is the cocktail hour.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of their instruction, the Hula-Hooping children have
learned their colorfully dressed instructor's name _ Fanny _ and
that she's a ninth-generation circus performer from France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE MAIN EVENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As show time nears, Feld's party guests begin to file through
the lighted tunnel that leads to the performance tent. The intimate
setting holds 1,850, and there's not a bad seat in the house. Red
velvet covers each chair, and those in the back row are only 52feet away from the middle of the ring. There are even VIP couches
scattered throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The lights dim to signal the start of the show. When they come
up, a bed sits at the center of the ring with award-winning clown
David Larible tucked inside. He awakens and begins preparing for
his day.
</P>
<P>
   Kaleidoscape has no ringmaster, and almost no dialogue. Instead,
Larible serves as host, ushering the show along with comedic bits
between acts.
</P>
<P>
   The curly-haired Italian became the first clown ever to headline
a Ringling Bros. circus, in 1991. He did so until 1998, when Feld
asked him to help create Kaleidoscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really the glue that holds the show together,'' Feld
says. ``I don't know if I would have done it at this time without
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Larible sits at an empty makeup table, each of the show's
performers arrives onstage to help with his transformation.
Acrobats from the Hassani and the Bogino troupes juggle his tubes
of makeup before handing them off. The beautiful Vanessa Fisher, a
California girl who plays cello in the circus, climbs a rope to
rescue his big floppy shoes. And so on, until Pipo, a classic
European harlequin who plays Abbott to Larible's Costello, joins
him onstage. He hands Larible his red nose, and the show begins.
</P>
<P>
   The main performance is two hours and 10 minutes long, with a
20-minute intermission, and is accompanied by a live orchestra
performing an original score. The acts fly by.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Zerbini, a ninth-generation circus performer from
Florida, commands six white Arabian horses. Her cues are almost
invisible as the steeds change direction, stand on their hind legs
and race around the ring.
</P>
<P>
   After the animals exit, Sylvia the horse whisperer becomes
Sylvia the trapeze artist. She whips off her cape to reveal a sheer
costume with strategically placed sequins. She dazzles the audience
again with the second part of her act.
</P>
<P>
   Olga Rogacheva's time in the spotlight features the only other
animals in Kaleidoscape _ a flock of geese. A Siberian who has
performed throughout Europe for the past 10 years, Rogacheva
directs the geese here and there with help from Istvan Toth, her
27-inch-tall Hungarian sidekick. Audience members can't help but
fear for the diminutive man as the geese surround him at eye level.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can juggle using his hands. Picasso Jr. uses his mouth.
He spits pingpong balls 20 feet into the air one after the other,
catching them in his mouth only to send them flying back out.
</P>
<P>
   The circus' strongmen come in the form of the Golden Statues.
These Moroccan-born performers _ painted head to toe in gold paint,
their muscles bulging, and wearing the briefest of briefs _ bend in
unbelievable ways, forming human pyramids that leave audience
members with their jaws dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the stress level in the tent is what perch artists Lucy
Kirilova and Alex Petrov of Bulgaria do best. On his forehead,
Petrov balances a 13-foot pole _ atop which Kirilova sits. Petrov
then walks across an inclined tightrope, never wavering despite his
load.
</P>
<P>
   Crossbow marksman Guy Tell can clip a long-stemmed rose from the
mouth of his partner, fellow Parisian Regina Bouglione, with his
arrow. His finale _ a 16-bow stunt that ends with him splitting an
apple that sits on top of his own head _ is the stunner, though.
</P>
<P>
   The other acts amaze, as well. Aerial swing artists the Kabanovs
wow the crowd with the greatest of ease. The tumbling troupes, the
Hassani and the Bogino, have every cheerleader in the room taking
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts &AMP; Bolts, the wacky musical group heard in the lobby tent,
performs a silly set using a variety of instruments _ from watering
cans to the exhaust of a 1937 Rolls Royce.
</P>
<P>
   Larible returns to the ring between acts with Pipo to provide
comedic breaks from the artistic tension. He pulls audience members
into the ring for plate-throwing games or to act out operas only he
knows the plots to.
</P>
<P>
   The show ends with a grand finale, but we won't spill the
details here. Just expect all the small children in the audience to
run away and join the circus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
