<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-LARIBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST CLOWNING AROUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Larible understands why some people don't like clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clown is very mistreated,'' says the Italian performer.
``There are some people who do it right. Americans can be excellent
clowns. Buster Keaton was a clown. The Marx Brothers were clowns.
They were artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But suddenly, it turned. There is not professionalism. Anybody
can put makeup on, a wig, learn three or four tricks and say, `I'm
a clown.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Bozo, Ronald McDonald, the guy who comes to your
birthday party. That's not a clown. That's like saying a painter is
the guy who paints your walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who hate clowns. They are frightened of them,
because of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Larible studied mime, ballet and music at the Verona
Conservatory of Music and has the awards to prove he's the real
deal. He recently took home the Golden Clown Award, top prize at
the 1999 International Circus Festival in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing that bothers Larible almost as much as those
who clown around without the proper credentials _ the assumption
that Kaleidoscape is just like Cirque du Soleil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the last thing we want to be. Cirque is New Age,
everybody is dressed the same way, they move the same way, and it's
beautiful. You're going to be blown away, but at the end, tell me
one person that you remember or the name of a guy in the show. You
can't. We want to do the opposite. We want different personalities
to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is a big element of improvisation with our circus.
In Cirque, you see one show today and you see exactly the same show
tomorrow. Kaleidoscape ... It's always changing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
