<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUNDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAST LEADS CHEERS FOR `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To hear Cameron Diaz talk, you'd think ``Any Given
Sunday'' is as much of a chick flick as ``Waiting to Exhale'' or
``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't expect the reality of the movie: a three-hour melee
of testosterone-driven sex, drugs, violence and chaos _ of
hedonistic jocks, salacious women and ear-blasting near-carnage on
the gridiron.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no. Not with Diaz talking.
</P>
<P>
   And not with the man who hired her _ writer-director Oliver
Stone _ within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday'' is ``actually interesting for women to
see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, second-billed to Al Pacino, plays the merciless, fiercely
driven young owner of the fictional Miami Sharks, a pro team she
inherits from her father.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino plays its workaholic but struggling head coach, who needs
Diaz's advice like he needs two injured quarterbacks, which he gets
in the first scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different women in it,'' Diaz points out.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yeah. There are prostitutes (``Showgirls''' Elizabeth
Berkley plays one), a quarterback's harshly demanding wife (Lauren
Holly), and a wide array of groupies, bimbos, cheerleaders and
miniskirted predators.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to mention Diaz's screaming meanie, who attacks her
loyal coach for failing to win championships annually, or her
pathetic, alcoholic mother, played by Ann-Margret.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs Nora Ephron when you've got Oliver Stone?
</P>
<P>
   Diaz sees all these women as part of ``a very human story of
people in conflict, with football as the backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can appreciate this story. For women, it's certainly a
film they can go and take something from.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Stone also defends the film, pointing out that pro
players attract ``a lot of party girls and groupies. You have to
deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also insists he's an ``equal-opportunity employer'' and no
sexist _ when it comes to flashing nudity. In one scene, Diaz
confronts a player in a locker room filled with naked gladiators (a
scene she wincingly recounts).
</P>
<P>
   Full-frontal? A frontal lobotomy? You decide what was needed.
</P>
<P>
   As for Stone, 52, he asserts, ``Hey, I love women. I have no
problem with women. I'm very close to my ex-wives.''
</P>
<P>
   He admiringly calls Berkley's character ``a pro.'' (Well, yes,
by definition.) And as for Holly's harpy, he says, ``You'd be
surprised, but with three or four major quarterbacks, their wives
run the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't love grand?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Dennis Quaid, who plays the Sharks' aging and injured
star quarterback _ a man who'd love to retire if his
status-obsessed wife (Holly) would just let him.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to stand by her man _ at least until he winds up in
traction.
</P>
<P>
   But that was on-screen. Making the movie was a different story.
Then, masculinity ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent months on sets with manly men doing manly things with
men,'' Quaid said. ``There were a lot of guys.'' (Teams were
comprised mostly of players from the World Football League and
Arena Football League.)
</P>
<P>
   Quaid, who'd played a quarterback in 1988's ``Everybody's All
American'' but never played football as a youth, practiced with the
San Francisco 49ers' Steve Young and the Miami Dolphins' Dan Marino
before rolling for Stone.
</P>
<P>
   But that's as far as the real thing went. The National Football
League wouldn't sanction Stone's script, forcing him to create a
fictional league.
</P>
<P>
   This refusal to play ball didn't surprise Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I blame them,'' he said. ``If I were a corporation
with that much money involved _ you'd want to have it portrayed the
way you want, not with a loose cannon like Oliver Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's stars use such terms admiringly. Yet in some ways they
apply painfully.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed writer-director of ``Platoon'' and ``Born on the
Fourth of July'' _ war movies that both won him Oscars as best
director _ has had a rough ride recently.
</P>
<P>
   His last film, 1997's ``U Turn,'' made $6 million domestically,
and 1995's ``Nixon,'' costing $50 million, made $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, artistry shouldn't be measured merely by profits. But
Stone also has had personal detours stemming from a history of drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer he was arrested and later pleaded no contest to
charges of drunken driving and drug possession. As part of his plea
bargain, he entered drug rehab.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs also are a part of pro football's tableau, and Stone
didn't flinch from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday'' has any number of drug scenes, from glowing
swirls of liquor in icy glasses to the pain-killers injected into
suffering players, to the cocaine they snort at parties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all Stone's sensationalism about the rigors and hedonism
of the sport, he ultimately embraces a rah-rah philosophy of
teamwork first, individuality second.
</P>
<P>
   Stone believes a ``big problem'' in the NFL now is ``not only
the length of games and the bloodiness, but that people are really
playing for themselves because the money is so big.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime NFL fan, he sees pro football as ``the American
religion. It's ritualized violence, but it's allowable.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stone made war movies, he drew upon his own experiences
serving in Vietnam. He didn't play football, but he sees its
violent conquests of territory as a metaphor for war.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's the ideal director for such a film _ until
someone can find a way to merge ``Titanic's'' sensitivity with
football's savagery.
</P>
<P>
   As an outsider, Stone tried to ``be humble and make it
authentic.'' He cast former players such as Jim Brown and Lawrence
Taylor and relied on them and others as advisers (though even
casual fans will note many errors).
</P>
<P>
   One big hurdle was filmmaking's repetition.
</P>
<P>
   The ``highly skilled testosterone animals'' Stone hired weren't
playing a three-hour game once a week. They had to hit each other
daily for long hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``A war film is pure chaos,'' Stone said. ``But this was very
rigorous, orchestrated chaos. Chaos can be fertile or destructive.
You just can't let it get out of hand. But chaos is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the coach Pacino plays, Stone is ``a driven man,'' Diaz
said. ``In fact, he's the most driven person I've ever seen. But
he's so in control and knows exactly where he's going.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stone, that direction was crystalized by his impressions as
a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing comes easy in football,'' he said. ``It's hard, it's
fast, and every play is tough. It's also up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, perhaps sensing a parallel to his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you're a hero,'' Stone said with a small smile, ``you
can be a bum on the next play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
