<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-FANNY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWINGING INTO COMEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fanny Kerwich swung from her first trapeze just a few years
after she learned to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 6, I started to work with the trapeze in the ring,'' she
says. ``It was lots of fun. At that age, I didn't know it was
dangerous. Then I fell down. After that I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   When the 31-year-old performer falls now, she does so on
purpose. Kerwich was born into a circus family and grew up in
France. She learned acrobatics, too, but her dream was to be a
clown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy was my first love. My brother was a clown. At that
time, in Europe, to be a girl clown was not allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   But when her brother became ill when she was 14, the circus
needed a sub, and her street-urchin character was a hit. Kerwich
went on to perform in cabarets, variety shows and circuses in
Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character is still just like me when I was 12. I was
always wearing boots with dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kaleidoscape, she helps David Larible keep the show flowing
and entertains children in the pre-show, her favorite part of the
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I love. I think for that time, all those people
think life is beautiful. In the beginning, children are thinking,
`What does she want from me?' In the show, they watch me, and when
they leave, they leave as friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
