<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-PICASSO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A SPIN ON THINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Picasso Jr. had followed his original plan he would be behind
a desk, assessing taxes, instead of performing with Kaleidoscape.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish juggler earned an economics degree and was serving
in the military when a family circus rolled into the African city
where he was stationed.
</P>
<P>
   He had learned to juggle from his father, El Gran Picasso, but
the son considered it a hobby, not a career option.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always told me I could be a good juggler. He always
wanted me to be one, but I was really shy. I didn't like to perform
at all,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   Then the circus arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 years, no circus went through this area. The year I'm
doing my military service, the circus comes through. So I go over
there, and the family knew my father. I showed them what I could
do, saying I needed to practice more. They said, `What? No
practice. You need to act.'
</P>
<P>
   After his military duty ended, Picasso Jr. returned to Spain.
His father convinced him to perform a series of casino dates with
him. He did, and he was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Now 30, Picasso Jr.'s plate-throwing act keeps Kaleidoscape
audiences ducking. The dishes he whips to each corner of the tent
magically fly back to his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make it look so easy. But you have to spin it just the right
way.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
