<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-LYNCH-TV-LADN &LR;      12-23 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LYNCH-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LYNCH WHO STOLE CHRISTMAS' ON INDEPENDENT FILM CHANNEL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Times below are PST) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All alone for Christmas and feeling blue? Maybe ``Blue Velvet''
is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a daylong David Lynch marathon Saturday on the
Independent Film Channel, dubbed ``The Lynch Who Stole Christmas.''
The program kicks off at 6 a.m. Christmas morning, about the time
wide-eyed little ones will be scampering out to the tree _ at
someone else's house.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup includes: ``Lost Highway,'' starring Bill Pullman as
a jazz musician suspected of killing his wife (Patricia Arquette);
``Pretty as a Picture: The Art of David Lynch,'' with Pullman,
Arquette, Mel Brooks and others offering insights and anecdotes
about their experiences working with Lynch; Terry Zwigoff's
documentary ``Crumb,'' about '70s artist Robert Crumb, which was
executive produced by Lynch; and ``Independent Focus: David
Lynch,'' in which the filmmaker fielded questions from a live
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The IFC also is screening the rarely shown 1995 project
``Lumiere &AMP; Co.,'' for which Lynch and 39 other directors were
asked to make a short film apiece using the original Cinematographe
invented by the Lumiere Brothers 100 years earlier. Spike Lee, Wim
Wenders, Liv Ullman and other directors were given three rules to
follow: The film could be no longer than 52 seconds, it could not
have synchronized sound, and it had to be shot in a maximum of
three takes. Lynch's contribution has been described as ``a bizarre
mini-epic.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no Lynch-ing would be complete without ``Blue
Velvet,'' one of the most talked-about films of 1986. It deals with
a quirky small-town mystery involving a kinky nightclub singer
(Isabella Rossellini), a sadistic drug dealer (Dennis Hopper) and
other odd types.
</P>
<P>
   Check your local listings for the IFC channel on your cable
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
