</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SHAKESPEARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IN DOUBT, CONSULT THE BARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coca-Cola Co.'s recent troubles might not have been so bad
if executives there had paid more attention to a classic.
</P>
<P>
   No, not Classic Coke, but classic Shakespeare. Namely,
``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally mishandled the crisis in Belgium on the health
scare,'' said Kenneth Adelman, coauthor of ``Shakespeare in Charge:
The Bard's Guide to Leading and Succeeding on the Business Stage.''
He said Coca-Cola tried to downplay the tainted Coke rather than
being open with the public, and now M. Douglas Ivester, Coke's
chief executive, is stepping down as the company continues to
sputter.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester would have done better to follow the lead of Claudius in
``Hamlet,'' who was open with Laertes about how Hamlet killed
Laertes' father, Polonius.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that Claudius did not do was establish a crisis
center Web page,'' Adelman joked. He and coauthor Norman Augustine
have set up such a Web page at www.shakespeareincharge.com.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Adelman and Augustine use five plays by William
Shakespeare to illustrate key concepts about management, such as
how Petruchio effected change in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' how
Mark Antony seized opportunity in ``Julius Caesar'' and how
Claudius handled crises in ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Their book also points to modern examples to make crucial
points. When the beverage maker Odwalla had problems with E. coli
bacteria in its organic juice drinks in 1996, the authors write,
President Greg Steltenpohl handled the problem swiftly and limited
the damage _ which otherwise could have wiped out the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty minutes after learning of the contamination, Odwalla
held a press conference to announce that it was recalling all its
products containing unpasteurized apple juice, the culprit in this
case,'' they write. ``But, as the bad news spread, Steltenpohl
realized that wasn't enough. The newly formed crisis-management
team decided to use the Internet to reach the public. It flew in
Matthew Harrington, a public-relations specialist from Edelman
Public Relations in San Francisco, to create a crisis Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The savvy publicity firm had already reserved a Web site for
potential crisis communications by its clients. By late afternoon
the same day, they had posted a letter to the public on the Web
site that explained what they were doing to ensure that their
consumers were safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelman said in an interview that he has seen many leaders who
are more concerned with getting and keeping their jobs than they
are with managing effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find in a lot of leaders, like a lot of leaders in
Shakespeare, that they don't know what to do with their
leadership,'' said Adelman, a former U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations. ``I see that a lot of times with politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors use Petruchio's treatment of Katherine in ``The
Taming of the Shrew'' as an example of how managers can deal with
change. ``Aside from overall leadership, that is the most important
topic,'' Adelman said. ``The consequences of error are far greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you anticipate change and force change in your
organization, you'll be ruined very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelman and Augustine write that Petruchio tries one approach to
change Katherine, but is ready with a backup plan when that fails.
Petruchio keeps his eye on his goal _ marrying Katherine _ and
comes up with a different strategy that eventually works.
</P>
<P>
   Adelman said that Petruchio's dramatic actions are in stark
contrast with what usually happens in companies during mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a merger or acquisition, the natural inclination
is to go slow,'' he said. ``By and large, that's the wrong
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that moving slowly just prolongs the stress for
workers and sometimes customers. ``People can adjust to almost
anything. It's the uncertainty that'll kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
