<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-ASC-BOS &LR;      12-23 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-ASC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW INVESTOR HELPS OTTEN BUILD MOUNTAINS OF CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he was forming the American Skiing Company in recent years,
Les Otten, who holds a private pilot's license, saw the
organization grow so fast that he said he felt like he was trying
to land an F-15 on a carrier deck but suddenly realized he hadn't
learned to fly.
</P>
<P>
   But reports after last year's miserable ski season that Otten
had crashed and burned, are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while this season's lack of natural snow has prompted
ASC to cobble together an arcane ``guaranteed skiing'' deal to
visitors, Otten's empire has been given a major infusion of new
capital _ $150 million invested by the Texas-based firm of Oak Hill
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stabilized our company,'' says Otten, who still works
out of an office at the base of Sunday River in Bethel, Maine.
``Oak Hill's cash was a pretty important investment. I feel very
secure in the company's position and our ability to perform in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many new companies, ASC has yet to turn a profit, and since
going public two years ago, the company's stock has taken a
beating. Last year's snowless winter resulted in a $32.3 million
loss and employee layoffs across the resort holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Otten pressed on, developing ever more slopeside real
estate, acquiring new holdings and upgrading almost all the
properties. ASC owns Sunday River and Sugarloaf in Maine;
Killington/Pico, Sugarbush, and Snow/Haystack in Vermont;
Attitash/Bear Peak in New Hampshire; Heavenly in California,
Steamboat in Colorado, and The Canyons in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown so large so fast, then suffering the worst ski
seasons in a generation in the East _ and no great shakes in the
Rockies _ Otten's could be forgiven a case of the nerves about now.
But, he says, ``This time of year, the pressures are all positive.
We're getting psyched for a new season, the adrenline's flowing. If
I had that faint a heart, I shouldn't have gotten into the ski
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ever since his college days in New Jersey more than 30
years ago when he tried to buy a small ski area near home, Otten
has worked fulltime on buying and developing ski areas. And ski
seasons, he has come to know, tend to average out. Financial
analysts have assessed ASC's situation as stable enough to survive,
even through subpar winters. Still, says Otten, ASC needs a decent
winter to resume working toward its longer-range goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we're entering this year so much stronger
financially,'' says Otten.
</P>
<P>
   But surviving a season or two is far from what Otten _ or his
investors _ had in mind. Known for over 25 years as one of the best
snowmakers in the industry, ASC is staying technologically current
in snowmaking at all areas, according to Otten, and the company is
moving ahead with several projects, some of which were shelved last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The largest single challenge has been the development of The
Canyons in time for the 2002 Winter Olympics. With 3,300 skiable
acres and a vertical rise of 3,200 feet, The Canyons is currently
the seventh largest ski area in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area currently has the approvals to become the largest ski
in the United States,'' says Otten. ``We're just putting the
finishing touches on about 1,500 new beds that will all be
available by the first of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remarkable opportunity to get it. If you could have
been at Aspen in the 1950s or Vail in the 1960s or Beaver Creek in
the 1980s, that's kind of the opportunity that The Canyons is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of skiers seem to agree. Early in the New Year a 350-room
Grand Summit _ largest and fanciest of the ASC slopeside hotels _
will be pened. It already is 60 percent sold out. The familiar
quarter share (giving owners one-fourth of the time in a season,
with option trades around the resort world) sells for $115,000 for
a two-bedroom. Total net is $460,000. Another lodge, the Sundial,
opened with an offering of two-bedroom condos at $400,000 each and
sold out in 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy and optimistic about the fact that young
families are making investments in ski areas at a record pace,''
says Otten, whose new Jordan Grand Hotel at Sunday River is 70
percent sold.
</P>
<P>
   Otten's story is as well known and oft-told as any folk tale in
ski literature _ how a young cast-off executive from the Killington
Ski Company inside of two decades owned that area and eight others,
making him the largest single entrepeneur in skiing.
</P>
<P>
   So meteoric was his rise that as big as the company grew, so did
his status as a target. ``Sure I was up there for people to take
shots at,'' says Otten, who is quick to add that ASC is ``now in a
position to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term questions, such as the flat number of skier visits
for several years and the aging of the boomer generation do not
worry him. ``Luckily,'' he says, ``Jake Burton invented snowboards.
I'm optimistic. Taking a longer view, we have a record number of
young people entering the sport. We have a record number of people
buying real estate in our company, and the pace they're buying is a
record. It far exceeds anything we saw in the '70s and '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite getaways is still to take off for five-plus
days with family and friends to ski areas outside ASC property
(``Every day skiing at your own area is a work day,'' he says). He
skis all over the world, and even has a snowboard in his office
that he uses ``maybe 10 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still enjoy skiing,'' says Otten, whose wife, Chris, has
been in the retail skiwear business at Sunday River and other Otten
holdings. ``I started with those feelings for the sport, and I
still have a passion for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
