<HEADER>
A7571 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      12-23 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULTRASOUND ISN'T A `BETTER MOUSETRAP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I really have to get rid of my mice. I am not too wild about
traps, or D-Con, although a man used D-Con eight years ago and got
rid of them. I saw on TV something called Rid-A-Pest, an electronic
ultrasound machine that claims to get rid of mice. Do those things
work?
</P>
<P>
   P.G., Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Mice often come into the house in the autumn when it gets
cold, but higher-than-normal temperatures this fall have probably
delayed the process. At any rate, there is an old saying that if
you see one mouse, you have 20. That is not a very nice thought,
but it does mean that you should do something about it. Here is
what an authoritative book on pesticides says about ultrasound
machines:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no studies indicating (ultrasonic devices) are
effective at significantly reducing or eliminating rats or other
rodents from an area. . . . Until such studies are available, we do
not recommend the use of these products. There are reports showing
that certain ultrasonic devices are helpful when used in
combination with other methods, but this still does not mean they
alone will `eliminate' an infestation.''
</P>
<P>
   So, you pay your money and take your chances. Since D-Con worked
in the past, it will work again. Generally, mice killed by D-Con
and other poisons do not necessarily wind up in walls and other
sites to decay and smell up the house.
</P>
<P>
   Short of D-Con, then, it's back to the old snap traps, which are
instant death, not the slow, cruel death of sticky traps.
</P>
<P>
   And, while you are at it, inspect the foundation and exterior
walls for openings that a mouse could get through, then seal them.
Remember, a mouse's body is designed to get through surprisingly
small holes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I stained a nice table for my den, then put on three coats of
an oil-based polyurethane varnish. After two coats, I sanded
lightly and recoated. Now it looks dusty. When I wipe a wet sponge
on it, it looks great, but when it dries it looks dusty again. What
went wrong? One other thing: When I cleaned my brushes with
turpentine, they did not clean up at all well.
</P>
<P>
   DONALD FATZINGER, Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Join the club. The same thing happened to the handyman, and
he knew he was using water-based polyurethane varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite your calling it oil-based varnish, it was indeed water
based. And therein lies the problem. The brushes not cleaning up
well with turpentine (or paint thinner) was the clue that the
varnish is water based. Water will clean them up nicely; paint
thinner or turpentine will clean up oil-based varnish.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here is what happened. Everything was just perfect,
up to the third coat. The first coat soaked in, sealing the
surface; the second did the same, only less so; the third coat
stayed on the surface as a nice, smooth, consistent finish, except
that it was put on too thickly, and being water-based varnish, it
clouded up, creating that dusty look.
</P>
<P>
   When I wrote about my experience, a paint consultant called to
tell me that I had applied the third coat too thickly, but I
really, truly thought I did very thin coats, which I preach about
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you have to redo the table that looks dusty, by sanding
to the bare wood, restaining, and applying two or three coats of an
oil-based polyurethane varnish. And, thin coats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I clean a wood cabinet that has been polyurethaned?
The same goes for a polyurethaned floor.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID PEARSON, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Varnished finishes, and in your case and most other cases,
poluyrethane-varnished finishes, are pretty tough, stand up to wear
and tear, and look good for decades. The only weakness of such a
finish, on furniture and floors, is that it is easily scratched.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it clean by dusting with a dry cloth (dry mop or broom for
the floor). Occasionally, on both, wash with paint thinner, which
dissolves the dirt so it can be wiped up. This will dull the
finish, which can be restored by buffing with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   A mild solution of a good detergent and water will also clean
furniture and floors, but water should be used sparingly; in other
words, squeeze out your sponge when you use water.
</P>
<P>
   A floor does not have to be treated with anything else, except
area rugs. As for furniture, it is the handyman's opinion that
polish should not be used because it is not needed. Repeated
polishing results in a built-up finish that is dull and collects
dirt, then has to be removed. So why bother? If you insist, use as
little as possible and not more than two or three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some short ends of pressure-treated boards were left over
from a building project. Can I burn them to get rid of them? If
not, how can I get rid of them? What about scraps of siding that
have been treated with Cuprinol?
</P>
<P>
   MARY POLSONETTI, Wenham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Pressure-treated wood should not be burned, especially not in
a stove or fireplace; its chemicals become harmful air pollutants.
You can dispose of your boards in the trash collection. The
Cuprinol-treated siding can be burned a few scraps at a time _ but
no more than a few; make sure the fireplace draws properly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
