<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KRUGMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIST KRUGMAN CRUNCHES MORE THAN NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ Academic economics is widely construed to be a
clannish, genteel profession, a world of arcane mathematical
formulas, macro-something theories, and politely warring egos
debating the nuances of International Monetary Fund policy. It's
not supposed to be about fame, clout, rivalry, revenge. However,
that view could undergo serious revision before Paul Krugman is
through.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, 46, is an MIT economist whose specialties include
international trade and international finance. He is among the
profession's young superstars, a recipient (in 1991) of the Clark
Medal, signifying youthful excellence in the field. Often mentioned
as a Nobel Prize candidate, Krugman commands five-figure speaking
fees to enlighten corporate leaders and was rumored to be a
finalist for a Clinton administration job, an appointment he now
concedes would have been ``a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he is a prolific, lively writer who communicates
complex ideas with a feel for vox-pop vernacular, so much so that
The New York Times recently asked Krugman to join its op-ed page
lineup. At this stage of his career, having taught at Yale and
Stanford before returning to MIT in 1996, Krugman can pretty much
punch his own institutional ticket. It's when he starts trading
punches with opponents on the left and right that the IMF sometimes
gets confused with the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this scrap, in the pages of Mother Jones, between
Krugman, a liberal columnist whose nonacademic work has, up until
recently, appeared regularly in Fortune and Slate, and Jude
Wanniski, a noted conservative supply-sider.
</P>
<P>
   Wanniski: ``Unsuspecting editors continue to pay (Krugman) for
plagiarizing his own material . . . the most elaborate Ponzi scheme
in American journalism . . . a charlatan. . . . If Krugman had to
predict to make a living, he would starve to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Krugman: ``If you plan to engage in character assassination, it
pays to do some homework. . . . Wanniski's consulting firm employs
followers of cultist Lyndon LaRouche. . . . We should be grateful
to Wanniski for writing this letter, which tells us all that we
need to know about his ideas, and more than we need to know about
his character. . . . What's a nice guy like (Jack) Kemp doing with
a guru like this?''
</P>
<P>
   Mercy. And that grudge match does not even touch liberal icons
like Lester Thurow, Laura Tyson, and Robert Reich, each of whom has
been similarly Krugmanned in print. If he does win a Nobel, here's
a safe prediction: It will not be the peace prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' says Krugman. ``I certainly was not known as
being a disputatious guy before the early '90s. But then this whole
ideology emerged around American declinism and the superiority of
the Japanese economic model, and I came out swinging, for reasons
that still surprise me. I guess I was mad as hell and wasn't going
to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a loaner office at Princeton University _ Krugman is
on unpaid leave this year from MIT while finishing an economics
textbook _ he looks more Woody Allen than Woody Harrelson, a
bearded, unthreateningly gnomish figure dressed in rumpled khaki
trousers and a pastel-green sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are serious guys in the economics profession who I think
are dead wrong about a lot of things,'' he continues. ``For
example, I disagree with Robert Barro a lot. But I would never take
him on the way I'd take on Robert Reich, because I regard Barro as
serious. Unlike Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   One eye fixed on his laptop screen, Krugman shrugs off a
question about feuds with other high-profile economists. The
French, he says, have a phrase for their nuclear deterrence policy,
one he finds particularly relevant to his own situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it an all-azimuths policy, as in facing in all
directions,'' says Krugman with a thin smile. ``Well, I like to
think that I have all-azimuths enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, look out. Because Krugman, also known as ``the Bad
Boy of Economics'' (The Washington Post) and ``America's most
controversial economist'' (Newsweek), is about to acquire his most
formidable weapons system yet: a semiweekly forum in the Times,
beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   The move is an unusual one for the newspaper, which seldom taps
a nonstaffer (William Safire being the exception) for an op-ed job.
Krugman will keep his teaching post but give up other lucrative
pursuits. In exchange _ a Nobel for a Pulitzer? _ he will be handed
one of the premier seats in American journalism, and with it a rare
opportunity to influence public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was and am a bit nervous about this,'' Krugman admits. ``I
worry that friends and colleagues will end up defining me as a
journalist. But in the end this was just too interesting to pass
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting for the Times, too. Times editorial-page editor
Howell Raines, who in partnership with publisher Arthur Sulzberger
Jr. courted Krugman for the job, said he ``felt intuitively'' that
Krugman was the right fit for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we looked outside for somebody to do economics and
finance, Paul's was the only name on our list,'' said Raines, in a
recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a strong recommendation from Times columnist Thomas L.
Friedman, Raines added, he held several discussions with Krugman
over the summer, culminating with a long dinner in New York with
Sulzberger and a job offer the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed him most about Krugman, Raines said, was ``the
combination of an obviously powerful knowledge base, the ability to
think adventurously, and the bonus of being able to write with wit
and clarity. In a specialized field like economics, you can't get
by on style alone. But Paul is able to come up with the clarifying
example that's accessible to our readers without being overly
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines laughed when told that Krugman had expressed nervousness
about producing two columns a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be so,'' said the Times editor. ``But Paul never
struck me as someone who's lacking in self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, Krugman, who grew up on Long Island as the only
child of an insurance executive, is about to go boldly where no
full-time academic economist has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Passionate about history and science fiction as a youth, Krugman
spent what he describes as ``four uneventful years'' at Yale, where
he majored in economics yet evinced little interest in campus, or
national, politics. A protege of the economist William Nordhaus,
Krugman did graduate work at MIT _ not terribly distinguished work,
he concedes _ before delivering a well-received paper at a national
economics conference in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   What followed, Krugman writes in one of several essays posted on
his Web page, was a series of ups and downs. Work on global trade
and credit exchange models helped make Krugman a budding star in
the early '80s. In 1982, he joined President Reagan's Council of
Economic Advisors for a year, where his writing skills sharpened
noticeably. Returning to MIT in 1983, however, Krugman suffered
through a fallow period and wondered if he had what it took to make
a lasting mark in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Krugman put those doubts to rest with a series
of brilliant papers challenging conventional dogma on free trade
and industrial policy. He also wrote his first book for popular
consumption, ``The Age of Diminished Expectations,'' a
media-friendly primer on economic theory. The Clark Medal followed,
along with interest from the Clinton team related to his work on
economic inequality. He and the Clinton camp disagreed over the
competitiveness issue, however _ Krugman thought US concerns over
foreign competition were overblown _ and there was little love lost
personally between Krugman and key Clinton insiders like Reich,
Tyson, and Ira Magaziner.
</P>
<P>
   Reich, now teaching at Brandeis, says that while Krugman is
``extremely bright,'' he has not always demonstrated what might be
called exceptional people skills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
