<HEADLINE>
DON'T THROW OUT THAT TOOTHBRUSH!
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Dec. 25) 
 
 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a prescription for dental and environmental health _ a
toothbrush subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Somerville, Mass.-based Recycline is marketing the first-ever
toothbrush with a handle made entirely from recycled plastics. And,
to further court environment-conscious consumers, the company sells
its ``Preserve'' brush with a postage-paid mailer so it can be sent
back to the company for recycling.
</P>
<P>
   The old brushes will become plastic lumber that is used in park
benches.
</P>
<P>
   A one-year ``subscription'' of four Preserve toothbrushes and
mailers costs $17.95, which makes it a little more expensive than
standard brushes. But it's also doing your bit to cut back on the
50 millions pounds of plastic waste dumped annually in the United
States. The brush is available in seven colors with soft, medium or
firm bristles. A new brush arrives every three months, which is
what the American Dental Association recommends for use of a brush.
For more information, contact Recycline at (888) 354-7296 or check
it out on the Internet at www.recycline.com on the Web. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
