<HEADER>
A7581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-CHRISTMAS-BOS &LR;      12-23 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CHRISTMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUINTESSENTIAL CHRISTMAS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, Vt. _ Picture a Christmas card showing the most
traditional New England home you can imagine. To be really
Christmasy, the house would be antique and white, of course, with
green shutters, and have a beautiful old front door covered in
greens with a classic green wreath in its center.
</P>
<P>
   This ideal Christmas-card house would be sitting on a
picturesque town green, and from the glow of its windows you could
make out an interior filled with beautiful antiques, Christmas
trees glistening with tiny white lights, and the hint of several
generations of an old and close family gathering there for the
holiday. It is, in short, the quintessential Christmas house.
</P>
<P>
   And it exists. Richard DiFrummolo and Donald Winter can go home
again; they call the Federal-style home they own here the
``Christmas House'' not only because it looks like what everyone
thinks of as the epitome of this holiday, but because, with all
their travels and their two other homes in Boston and Provincetown,
Christmas is the only time they are sure to be here.
</P>
<P>
   While the Provincetown house on the beach is the center of their
summer activities and is all light and clean contemporary
furniture, this 1810 clapboard home, which sits next door to the
town hall in the center of ski country, filled with old family
photos, odd nooks and crannies, and dark and beautiful antique
furniture, is where their extended family and many friends have
gathered for the Christmas holidays ever since they purchased it 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Christmas tree in practically every room of the
house, including one in the gigantic kitchen and a 16-foot one in
the huge room over the barn. DiFrummolo, a former owner of more
than a dozen hair salons and now the official family Christmas
decorating CEO, decorates everything in the house for the holiday,
and it is all subtle and tasteful and in perfect keeping with the
house. The trees _ green and living _ have tiny white lights and
red berries for decoration, the mantel of the front ``green room''
holds birch logs, natural greens, more red berries, and interesting
plant material from the area, and the front hall table, which was
designed by the two to just cover the radiator and yet leave room
for people to move through the hallway, holds two giant antique
glass urns filled with red ball ornaments. The urns, a gift for
DiFrummolo from Winter, came from an Ellis Memorial Antiques Show.
Winter, who is president of the Ellis Memorial and Eldredge House
Inc., says that ``at one time a gentleman kept whiskey in the urns
and probably poured a little more out for himself every time he
passed them.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A house on the green'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the two men began looking for a place in Woodstock, they
told the real estate company they wanted a house on the town green;
that's the only place they considered for their front yard. For one
thing, Winter wanted a ski house for his three sons, who were then
teenagers. Two houses came available, and the other one was
purchased by Laurence Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrummolo and Winter's original plan was to live in the
enormous attached barn, originally a carriage house with horse
stalls and tack rooms on its lower floors and a large apartment on
the top floor, and sell the main house. ``Richard didn't even go
upstairs when we came to buy it, because we were supposedly living
in the barn,'' says Winter. To that end, they furnished the main
house sparsely at first, putting an antique chair here and there
when they found one at auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it grew on us; it evolved,'' says DiFrummolo. Originally
boasting a simple Federal style, the house was ``modernized'' with
what were considered up-to-date enhancements in the 1860s. Thus it
now sports elaborate gingerbread cornices just under the roof,
marble fireplaces, and red cabbage-rose wallpaper and carpeting,
some of which has been preserved. The most formal room, the right
front parlor, started out with the cabbage-rose wallpaper, but the
couple had it painted green and finally a pale yellow, to
complement the morning sunshine it receives. The room has a card
table bought at auction and an American corner cupboard from New
Orleans, in addition to a rose silk Chippendale rolled-arm
serpentine-back settee and a table made in this town. Family photos
fill the corner cupboard, and a floral painting hangs on the wall,
a thank-you gift from Jill Goldweitz of Boston to DiFrummolo for
decorating her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the house one finds art from local painters,
including a primitive of Lake Champlain and paintings from
Vermonters Clead Enders, William B. Hoyt, and Janet Fredericks. In
a niche between the parlor and the library is a collection of
handblown glass from Winter's family. His grandmother's brothers
lived in Sweden and blew glass for Kosta, the well-known company
that made glass for Steuben, Dorflinger's, and both the Lincoln and
Wilson White Houses. There are vases that have been blown, then cut
and etched; a pair of gigantic Mercury glass candlesticks; a vase
of papier-mache and mother-of-pearl; and green and blue art-glass
vases that were made from leftover glass from the Kosta factory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Interior renovations &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The library was made from an old kitchen and painted in a shade
that Winter calls ``cinnamon bear.'' The dining room has been
painted in the antique gold of Tuscany by a trompe l'oeil painter
the gentlemen discovered painting scenes in a local deli. The same
painter painted the dining room fireplace to look like stone, and
the wood floor to resemble tiles.
</P>
<P>
   A series of tiny, dark rooms was opened up to make one huge,
slightly more modern kitchen. By tearing down walls of back
hallways, the pantry, the original carriage shed, and the second
kitchen, and adding butcher block counters, a brick fireplace,
bookshelves, two dishwashers, and two sinks, DiFrummolo and Winter
ensured that the resulting space is big enough for Winter's dinners
for 40, for another Christmas tree piled high with gifts, and a
full dining table for family holiday breakfasts and brunches. In
another slightly contemporary touch to the holiday decor, the
kitchen tabletop is covered with a line of bowls, graduating from
small to large, each filled with red Christmas balls. The first
year they owned the house they had a Christmas party for all the
workers who helped restore the kitchen and other parts of the
house. Winter, who is adept at plumbing and electrical wiring, was
able to do much of that work on the house himself.
</P>
<P>
   They have left touches of the former kitchen, such as the three
bins that used to hold wheat, flour, and oats but now open out to
hold kitchen materials for recycling. And on the steps of the tiny
back staircase they had pictures of Vermont cows painted as a
whimsical afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   The four-bedrooms upstairs gradually became the master bedroom
and one for each of the Winter boys, which they have kept as their
own to this day, though each of them now brings a wife to those
rooms, and two little grandsons come with them. There is one tiny
bedroom left empty, and Winter optimistically put a flowery border
along the ceiling of the all-white room, which holds some of his
own baby toys from the '40s. ``It's for a future granddaughter,''
he explains, adding, ``They have to have a little girl at some
point, don't they?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barn room's special guests &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they gradually moved into the large house and each son
considered one bedroom his own, the couple rented the barn room, to
which they had added many windows, to a series of artists,
screenwriters, and people going through divorces. When actor
Michael J. Fox got married, he and his wife Traci hid out here from
the media during their honeymoon. Three years ago on a perfect June
day, Winter's son Tony (whose ribbons from his childhood years of
competing with the Green Mountain Horse Association decorate the
barn) married Courtney Bent in St. James Episcopal Church across
the green from the house. They then took a few turns around the
green in a surrey, and retired to the tented backyard of the house,
which rolls gently down to the Ottaquechee River, for a reception
for hundreds of friends. The caterer, an old friend of Martha
Stewart's, had told the home-economics superstar about the wedding
plans, and, DiFrummolo said, ``Martha asked if she could come to
photograph the reception for one of her books.'' Telling Stewart
this was a personal family event, they turned her down. ``She would
have gone around restyling everything,'' scoffed DiFrummolo, who
added that Stewart was also not asked to the rehearsal dinner,
which took place in the barn room.
</P>
<P>
   While in the past the couple have invited guests here for as
many weekends as they could in the fall, Winter always had to rush
back to his job as partner at the law firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge during
the week. But since his retirement a month ago, he's looking
forward to spending most of every fall, not to mention the holidays
of the future, ensconced right here with DiFrummolo in the
Christmas House.
</P>
</TEXT>
