<SLUG> BC-HOT-TIP-FIESTAWARE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA DISHES IT OUT FOR NEW MILLENNIUM
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: EMBARGOED until Saturday, Dec. 25) 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fiesta, which introduced its first solid-color tableware in
1936, has come up with a new design just in time for the new
century: Fiestaware 2000. In bright, jewel-toned colors of cobalt
blue, pearl gray, persimmon and juniper, the new dinnerware is
described by Jonathan Parry, creative director of the Homer
Laughlin China Co., as ``stylish, contemporary, irreverent,
casually modern ... architecturally more aggressive than
traditional Fiesta ... dinnerware with an attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   A new color will be introduced for a limited run every other
year.
</P>
<P>
   Made to mix and match with traditional Fiesta dinnerware, the
new dishes feature bold, right-angle designs that could be likened
to bamboo or lightning strikes. With a vitrified glaze that won't
absorb bacteria, Fiestaware 2000 is chip-resistant, retains heat
and cold, and is safe for use in the oven, refrigerator and
microwave.
</P>
<P>
   At varying prices, pieces _ including dinner, salad, fruit and
soup plates, oversized mugs, cereal bowls, water pitchers and
all-purpose utility plates _ the new dinnerware is available at
department and housewares stores. For more information about Fiesta
or Fiestaware 2000, check out www.hlchina.com on the Web. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
