<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2TAK     12-23 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR HOLIDAY HEADACHES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ    
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Child Caring's gift to parents this season is an expanded Q&AMP;A
devoted entirely to problems that can arise during the holidays.
Hopefully, there's a nugget or two here that will reduce your
seasonal stress. Of course, Child Caring also welcomes questions
throughout the year. Send yours to Barbara F. Meltz, Boston Globe,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378 or Meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do I teach my 2.9-year-old son to graciously accept a
Christmas gift even if it is something he already has or does not
like? I want him to show respect for the gift giver's feelings and
appreciation for the gift no matter what it is. I dread him saying
``Is that all there is?'' as he did on his second birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A. Practice what you want him to say and make a game out of it:
``What do you say when you get a present?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, I like it soooooooo much!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What if you already have the very same thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still say `Thannk youuuu!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Steel yourself, nonetheless, for the fact that he's only 2.
There will be times when he'll say, ``Thank you sooo much but I
hate this,'' and times when he'll dig his heels in and just say,
``No!'' In those moments, remind him of the rule: ``Remember how we
practiced saying thank you?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if that doesn't prompt a thank-you, it reinforces your
expectation. Perhaps equally important for family peace, it shows
Aunt Mary that you are trying to teach good manners. Keep in mind
also that young children easily get overwhelmed and overstimulated
during the holidays. Getting into a power struggle over thank-you
will only make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. New Year's Eve parties for teens make me nervous, this year
especially. What are some reasonable guidelines for parents whose
teens want to do it up big for the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   A. Kate Kelly, author of ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to
Parenting a Teenager'' (Alpha Books), has three teens herself.
Here's how she's coping:
</P>
<P>
   --Her college-age daughter has permission to go to a party at
the home of a family Kelly knows well, with kids she also knows and
guidelines clearly established: no alcohol (not even champagne), no
driving around to pick up kids who live two suburbs away. The
parents will be home and in evidence, and most kids will spend the
night. ``This group is a bunch of pals, and they've been through
overnights at proms together. I'm totally comfortable with this,''
says Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   --Her 15-year-old wants to do something ``special'' but so far
has no plan. ``I told her I'll remain open until the last minute,
but the plan needs to be very specific and safe, not a bunch of
kids roaming around looking for something,'' says Kelly. ``She
knows I'll pull rank because I've told her her safety is more
important than her being able to remember she was at some
questionable event on the millennium New Year.'' Will this be an
issue? ``Down to the wire,'' she predicts. But she's providing an
alternative: ``She can invite a friend to our house, where we will
have a few friends in to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   --The 11-year-old so far is the most unhappy. ``She's been
invited to a party and she has permission to stay until 10:30. I've
told her that even on the millennium, 11-year-olds should not be at
a party until midnight,'' says Kelly. This daughter is also welcome
to invite a friend over.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's general advice is to be tighter with the reins, not
looser: ``Don't let them do anything this night that they couldn't
do any other night.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This year, Christmas is not a happy time for our family: My
father is dying. Do we try to make it a normal Christmas for all
the grandchildren _ seven of them, ages 3 through 13 _ or do we say
we're really sad and basically ignore it? My two siblings and I
can't agree.
</P>
<P>
   A. Canceling Christmas would be unnatural and too sad for the
grandchildren. On the other hand, it's not fair or appropriate for
grief-stricken adults to act as if nothing is wrong. The operative
term is ``scale back,'' says grief therapist Maria Trozzi, founder
and director of the Good Grief Program at Boston Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her recommendation is for parents to acknowledge to their
children that although they're looking forward to Christmas because
it's so wonderful, it will also be sad this year because Grandpa is
dying. If you haven't already been this honest with the children,
it will be a hard conversation, but don't avoid it, even with the
youngest child. ``Honesty within an age-appropriate framework is
what most enables children to cope,'' says Trozzi, who is the
author of ``Talking With Children About Loss'' (Perigee Books.)
</P>
<P>
   While you don't want to cancel Christmas, do cancel your annual
holiday open house for 200; focus instead on being together as an
extended family. By all means, decorate your houses; you could
offer to help Grandma decorate hers too, if she seems interested.
Honor the traditions, songs, and foods Grandpa loves; if it's
possible, visit him on Christmas with small gifts and letters of
love.
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi followed her own advice 10 years ago when her father died
on Christmas morning. She had canceled a traditional Christmas Eve
party, and the extended family spent the evening at her father's
bedside, where he supervised distribution of mementos to the
grandchildren. Trozzi's son, who was 5 at the time, received a box
of World War II medals. That grandson is 15 now, and the box still
holds a place of honor on his bureau. ``He always refers to it as
his grandfather's last Christmas gift,'' Trozzi says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do we keep our 2-year-old from destroying the Christmas
tree? Half the ornaments look like toys; others are fragile. I hate
the thought of not using them.
</P>
<P>
   A. Some families are able to get away with putting fragile
ornaments out of reach, at the top of the tree, and nonfragile ones
within reach. For some kids, though, that will still be too much
temptation. Bite the bullet and put your best ones away for a year
or two. Instead, have fun together creating a totally
child-friendly tree by making and hanging decorations. Better
still, put control of the tree in his hands. If you don't own a
remote-control switch for the tree lights, consider splurging on
one. It'll be worth it to see the joy on his face at being in
charge of turning the tree on and off. (Hopefully, you won't have
to splurge for a video camera to capture the moment!)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two boys, ages 7 and 10. For three years in a row the
older one has asked for PlayStation or Nintendo for Christmas. He
could manage this gift. However, his younger brother has ADHD
(attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder) and has a sensory
integration problem. He would be addicted to this sort of toy, and
I am not willing to take on more battles with this or spend the
energy trying to limit usage. My older son does not know that this
is the real reason behind this issue. I know he'll be greatly
disappointed once again, although I have told him not to get his
hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if you've made a good decision for good reasons,
but your older son deserves to know your reasoning too; lack of
honesty will only build resentment toward you and/or his brother,
since siblings typically are far more aware of the issues that we
realize.
</P>
<P>
   Parent educator Linda Braun, excecutive director of Families
First Parenting Programs in Cambridge, suggests taking him aside
for a conversation that goes something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is something you really want. I've been trying to
figure out how we could make it work in our family, but as you
know, your brother struggles with limits. Your dad and I feel this
would just cause too many problems in our home.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND &LR;      12-23 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... our home.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that this lays blame on the brother,
``but this is also the reality of your family,'' says Braun. ``A
child can learn to cope as long as his needs are getting met. Not
that he gets everything he wants, but that his feelings and wishes
are acknowledged.'' She says you can go on to say ``This is a
difficult thing to explain to you, because we don't want you to be
angry with your brother. But we know that you are an understanding
person and that you know this would be too hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are you opening up channels of communication and
empathy, but you are also conveying an important value: ``Being a
family sometimes means that one person's needs take precedence over
another's.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My daughter is turning 9 and asking if Santa is real or not.
The way she puts it makes us feel as if she's accusing us of having
lied to her (arms akimbo, belligerent tone), so we're not sure how
to answer. It is a lie, but it never felt that way to us. Plus, we
have a younger child who still believes.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are typically two ways children approach the ``is Santa
real'' issue. One is to ask skeptical questions: How can he deliver
so many presents in one night? How does he fit through a chimney?
If she's easily satisfied with a
``He's-magical-he-can-do-all-that'' answer, she's testing but
wanting to believe just a little bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if your daughter has moved beyond this stage to the
next, where she is more confrontational and where keeping the truth
from her is disrespectful. As for whether it's a lie, don't even go
there; the fantasy of Santa serves many purposes for young
children, including being a source of comfort and security.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some openings for a conversation:
</P>
<P>
   --Acknowledge that he isn't real but talk about how you still
enjoy the fun and fantasy of Santa, even as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   --Do you remember how you felt when you realized Santa wasn't
real? Sharing that will help her see this as a rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about Santa as a symbol of the spirit of giving.
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about being respectful of younger siblings: ``Your sister
still believes. We don't want to spoil it for her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do I respond when my preschooler receives a gift I feel
is inappropriate, like a toy gun?
</P>
<P>
   A. The best response is a proactive one: Tell friends and
relatives how you feel. Also tell your child, says early childhood
educator and author Diane Levin of Wheelock College, who researches
children's toys.
</P>
<P>
   You can begin with a toddler, even if you do it for the first
time the day before Christmas, as an insurance policy: ``Do you
know that in our family, we don't believe in playing with toy guns?
Some children and some adults don't like toy guns because they make
people think you might want to hurt them for real.'' Then, if he
unwraps a toy Uzi on Christmas morning and looks at you with wide
eyes, you have a context for talking about it: ``I bet you're
remembering that we don't like toy guns in our family. Why don't we
put this toy aside for now? Tomorrow, we'll talk about what we can
do about the gun so everybody is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Levin opposes violent toys, she's also a realist.
When tomorrow comes (or if he doesn't want to put the gun away
now), her position is to compromise, partly because the gun has
made it into your home and partly because you can't cut a child off
forever from the culture. However, she urges talking about the
reasons you don't like toy guns, including not only that they make
you think about real guns, which can kill people, but also that
they are boring toys because there are so few ways to play with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has written several books about children's play, including
``The War Play Dilemma'' with co-author Nancy Carlsson-Paige
(Teachers' College Press) and ``Remote Control Childhood?'' (NAEYC
Press).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. For a while I thought it was my imagination that every time
the subject of Y2K came up, my preschooler would get anxious. But
now my in-laws and others have noticed it too. Is this possible,
and if it is, what can I do about it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Kids pick up on all sorts of things we say, but because they
don't have the cognitive equipment to deal with the information,
they react to our tone and emotion. Even if you haven't talked
about possible Y2K problems, a preschooler might have heard the
worried tones of a radio or TV announcer. The best way to help is
to get the issue on the table: ``I noticed when Uncle John talked
about Y2K, you seemed anxious. Do you know what Y2K is?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he says yes, ask him what it means and then clarify; for
instance, ``Well, Y2K is something people are talking about. It's a
birthday party for the world, which is moving from 1,999 years on
our calendar to 2,000 years. That's a long time!'' Be concrete:
Show on a calendar how it is 1999 now and it will soon be 2000.
Some other coping mechanisms: Plan a Y2K breakfast together, make
``2000'' place cards and decorations.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is giving him too much information. If he seems
interested, keep going: ``It's a happy celebration, but some people
are worried that computers will crash in the new year. Have you
heard that? It means they might break. In our family, we've fixed
our computers so that won't happen.'' When he's had enough, he'll
turn away, but be prepared for him to come back to it at another
time: You've made the topic talkable. For most kids, the answer
they want to hear is that you're taking care of your family, and
that they are safe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My child's best friend is getting a horse for Christmas and a
Millennium Barbie. We have far less to spend, but our child is very
conscious of the discrepancy. How do we talk about it in a way that
won't make her feel awful, not to mention poor?
</P>
<P>
   A. If what she wants most in the world is a horse, there's no
answer that will make her happy. Nonetheless, this is as an
opportunity to talk about your family values for the holidays, says
child psychologist Roni Leiderman, associate dean of the Family and
School Center at Nova Southeastern University in Fort Lauderdale.
She offers this approach:
</P>
<P>
   --Reflect her wish: ``I know you really want a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   --Acknowledge the reality of the situation _ ``A horse just
isn't something we can afford'' _ but don't dwell on the money and
stop short of apologizing: ``I'm sorry we can't get you one''; that
only makes your gifts seem inferior.
</P>
<P>
   --Model generosity of spirit _ ``Isn't that wonderful that Mary
is getting a horse? She must be so excited!'' _ but don't expect
her to necessarily buy into it.
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about the special presents she will get _ ``There are
some presents we hope you will really like'' _ and the true meaning
of Christmas: ``It's about sharing what we have, and being with
family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiderman stresses that this is not a one-shot conversation.
``It's a process,'' she says. ``This is a life lesson that takes a
long time to teach and to learn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
