<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     12-23 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL BUSINESS SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are all venture capitalists now.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's an exaggeration. But not much of one. The venture
capital business is booming. An estimated $30 billion will be
invested nationally in new ventures this year, a tenfold increase
since the start of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   More remarkable than the growth in dollars is the growth in the
number and nature of the investors. Simply put, corporate America
is jumping into the venture business in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steven Galante, publisher of Venture Capital and
Information Technology, a Wellesley, Mass. newsletter, 160
companies now have venture capital operations, up from 70 two years
ago. Technology companies and consulting firms are leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting recently announced the creation of a $1
billion venture capital fund. A few days later, rival consulting
firm EDS said it was setting up a $1.5 billion venture fund.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, EMC, the Hopkinton data storage firm, is
making venture investments. So are Cognex, RSA Security, Breakaway
Solutions, and Cambridge Technology Partners, a mix of small and
medium-size companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to see McDonald's establish a venture capital fund
any day now, with Ronald McDonald handing out money to
entrepreneurs,'' said Todd Dagres, a venture capitalist with
Battery Ventures in Wellesley, only half in jest.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't hard to figure out why everyone and his brother wants
to get into Dagres's business. Like bank robber Willie Sutton, they
want to be where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   Dagres's firm made an early investment in Akamai Technologies, a
Cambridge Internet company. That original $5 million investment
today is worth close to $3 billion, a 600-fold increase. The Akamai
deal is amazing even by venture standards, but there have been
plenty of other success stories.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, based in Andover, has achieved a market value of more than
$30 billion, largely because of its venture investments in dozens
of start-ups. Internet Capital Group, a Pennsylvania company with a
similar business model, is now worth more than $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't want a piece of the action?
</P>
<P>
   But the new players in the venture business say they are after
more than just money. What is it they want?
</P>
<P>
   --Access to cutting-edge technology. ``Our investments give us a
window into some of the new things happening in our field,'' said
Charles Stuckey, chief executive of RSA Security, a Bedford company
that specializes in computer security.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, RSA made a small investment in a start-up called
VeriSign. VeriSign works with digital certificates, a piece of the
security business in which RSA had no experience. RSA has since
produced its own digital certificate product, in part, by licensing
VeriSign technology.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't hurt that VeriSign has become a very hot company
and RSA's original investment is now worth nearly $700 million. RSA
since has invested in half a dozen security start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   For technology companies like RSA, venture investing is a
relatively cheap form of research and development. For a modest
price they get a chance to see what the rest of the world is up to.
Cisco Systems, one of the nation's most successful high-tech
companies, has made a large number of venture investments; in some
cases, Cisco subsequently has acquired companies whose technology
looked especially promising.
</P>
<P>
   --Sales to new customers. Breakaway Solutions, a Boston
e-consulting firm, just this week announced the creation of a
venture fund that will put money into fledgling dot-com companies
that also happen to be Breakaway clients. ``It is a way of aligning
our goals with our customers,'' said Gordon Brooks, Breakaway's
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In short, if the customer does well, Breakaway should do well,
too.
</P>
<P>
   EMC had adopted the same strategy on a small scale. The data
storage giant has made some selected investments in dot-com
companies ``that have the potential to be large users of storage,''
said EMC spokesman Mark Fredrickson.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the venture-capital business are not surprised to
see the flood of new entrants into their industry. ``This is all
part of the cycle,'' said Tim Barrows, a top executive at Matrix
Partners, a Waltham venture firm with an excellent track record.
``Returns have been high and that attracts a lot of new capital.
We've got too much capital in the system right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, too many players and too much capital leads to
high prices and eventually, poor returns. ``Obviously, the returns
that venture capitalists are earning are not sustainable,'' said
Steven Gallante, the newsletter publisher. ``They will come down.
How far? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Charles Stein and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
