<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 CHRYSLER LHS: BIG, STYLISH AND POWERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to pay for the gas (it's getting expensive if you
haven't noticed), but opinions are still dispensed for free at
Irving's Service Center in Stoneham.
</P>
<P>
   For example, we'll take today's subject: a 2000 Chrysler LHS.
</P>
<P>
   I pull up to the pumps and walk inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's a nice-looking car,'' says Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's the sound system?'' asks son Matt, looking up from the
study guide for his upcoming test on the new auto inspection
equipment. ``I hear it's really something special.''
</P>
<P>
   I flip Matt the key and watch him crank up the windows and sound
on the four-disc, in-dash CD changer that's part of a 360-watt
system with Infinity speakers in nine locations. As I walk out to
finish gassing up, the smile on his face tells all as he leans back
in the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got it right,'' he says as he relinquishes the car in
exchange for gas money.
</P>
<P>
   That applies to more than the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   This is the big car your father always wanted to drive, except
it's only been built for the last two years. And it is right.
</P>
<P>
   It's also big. And stylish. And comfortable. And powerful. And
luxurious. And built in America.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, and it's fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   And for you, the son or daughter? All of the above holds true,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The LHS, a sibling of Chrysler's performance-oriented 300M, has
plenty of strong selling points of its own. Under the hood, they
share the same 3.5-liter, 24-valve V6 that puts out 253 horsepower,
enough to get an LHS from 0-60 in 7.7 seconds with good economy (18
m.p.g. city and 27 highway).
</P>
<P>
   The LHS is a little longer than the 300M, offers a softer (but
not spongy) ride, has more interior and trunk space and comes at a
decent price: $28,090 (ours added the CD changer at $515 and
17-inch chrome wheels at $750).
</P>
<P>
   The styling _ as it is across the Chrysler line _ is stunning,
and the reliability in these big cars is encouraging. The black
(heated) mirrors and a black trim strip between the hood and
windshield offset the bright silver of our test car. The LHS shares
the retro-look, airplane-styled dash instrumentation of the 300M,
including an analog clock (we won't argue with Chrysler's claim
that the cluster is reminiscent of Swiss-made watches).
</P>
<P>
   On the road, a trip with four aboard to Worcester saw the LHS
cruise easily at 80 and hold the road just fine. In town, where the
Central Artery is a tougher test, a late-night drive home on a
rainy night saw the suspension hop through the ruts a bit but
perform nicely overall.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't cold enough that week for the wet roads to turn to
black ice that would test the traction control, but, returning home
from the Globe in the wee hours one Sunday night, I got to give the
four-wheel disc brakes and antilock braking system a real-life
test.
</P>
<P>
   As I came onto the Expressway North at Columbia Road, an Acura
and Honda raced past, door handle to door handle in excess of 90
mph, rapidly disappearing from sight. A mile or so down the road,
they came a cropper in the South Station Tunnel, leaving a trail of
metal, plastic, glass and vital (automotive) fluids all over the
road with one car against each wall. The young lady driving the
Honda already had crossed over and was ``communicating'' with the
Acura driver who seemed OK but was unable to open the well-battered
driver's side door.
</P>
<P>
   The LHS made a quick, straight, pedal-pulsating stop, then
gingerly followed an 18-wheeler through the mess. A call to 911
went unanswered, leaving the conclusion that the trucker already
had officialdom on the phone. Ten minutes later, WBZ's traffic
report relayed news of a multicar crash in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the LHS seemed removed from the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends who came along during the week commented
favorably on the ride, the styling and the roominess of the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The leather seats were comfortable and heated. Heated seats
always sounded like a ``Who needs 'em?'' amenity _ until I tried
them. They're one of life's welcome luxuries, and just this week I
heard of a driver who uses his all year to ease a chronically
aching back.
</P>
<P>
   The obligatory cupholder report: Hit a bar on the front of the
center armrest and a double cupholder pops out. It was fine for our
various test beverages: a medium cardboard coffee cup, a soda can,
and an insulated travel mug, keeping them safely within reach and
out of the way of all controls.
</P>
<P>
   The equally-obligatory owner's manual report: You'll need to
read it to fully understand the many features of the
climate-control and audio-CD systems. Only a true gadget-person
will figure them out completely without help.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --Power, styling, spaciousness, combination of ride and
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --No easy place to put a turnpike toll ticket (the CD changer
took care of any in-dash cubbyhole spaces).
</P>
<P>
   --It took time to get the seat/mirror adjustments just right.
And rearview mirror visibility was somewhat limited.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
Base price: $28,090 &QL; 
Price as tested: $29,355 &QL; 
Horsepower: 253 (at 6400 rpm)/Torque: 255 lb-ft. at 3950 rpm &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 113 in./ 207.7 in. &QL; 
Width/Height: 74.4 in./ 56 in. &QL; 
Curb weight: 3564 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
