<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-23 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF '99 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With thousands of miles logged in many cars, trucks, and SUVs
from when this journey began and my first calendar year as auto
writer closing, this is a good time to look back at what I liked
most in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When I test a car, I always ask myself what sort of driver the
car is intended for and if it will suit that person.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-expensive vehicles exclude lots of readers since most of
us can't afford them, but the vicarious sharing we get to do makes
for interesting columns, as your e-mail and letters tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles priced in the mid-range raise lots of questions these
days because picking among those from $23,000 to $40,000 can be
tricky. Quality, comfort, and performance can be found across this
entire price spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   At the lower end of the cost scale, cheap doesn't necessarily
mean badly built and unreliable anymore. In fact, almost no one is
building a bad vehicle these days.
</P>
<P>
   So, these are my favorites from the past year _ in no particular
order but saving my top choice for last:
</P>
<P>
   Ford Focus _ Finally, an American car to compete with the Honda
Civic and Toyota Corolla _ and maybe do them one better. The Focus,
in three basic models (three-door, four-door sedan and station
wagon) is roomy, economical, and sporty. Its sharp lines give it an
edgy European look; its interior is surprisingly large; and, with a
130-horsepower engine coupled with a five-speed standard
transmission, it was downright snappy. Cost: $12,000-$16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Maxima _ Right now, the best bang-for-the-buck on the
market. At less than $25,000, it is bigger, more powerful, and
handles better than ever. It's got a great 222 horsepower V-6, a
sporty feel when driving, and is in a league of its own at this
price.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen Jetta GLS VR6 _ A solid car: solid suspension, solid
braking, solid acceleration, solid seats. Aimed at young drivers,
it's not quite a pocket rocket and not quite a sports sedan, but
that's its appeal. It too is snappy, tight in turns, roomy, and fun
to drive. Cost: $19,950-$24,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar XKR _ Supercharged, powerful, stunning on the straights,
and catlike on the curves. It's a sports car that seats four, and
if you can afford a Porsche 911, the Mercedes SL500, or the Acura
NSX, this classic Jaguar, powered by 370 horses, should be on your
comparison list. Cost: $76,800.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes E55 AMG _ My favorite Mercedes, this sports sedan is
specially prepared by AMG with a 349-horsepower engine that propels
it from 0-60 in 5.7 seconds and, at high revs, sounds like a big
ol' muscle car. It's got sophisticted suspension _ gas shocks, coil
springs, antidive devices, stabilizer bars, antisquat devices _ and
supersmart Automatic Slip Control and Electronic Stability Control
that lets it handle all that power. Cost: about $73,000.
</P>
<P>
   Audi TT _ This crouched bug drew more attention than anything
else I drove all year. Kinda retro, kinda airplane-like, lots of
fun. Its 1.3-liter turbocharged engine (with no turbo lag) zips it
from 0-60 in 6.9 seconds. The car clings to corners as if it's on a
railroad track. It's a tight fit inside _ a car you wear _ but when
you're in there, you are in charge of your domain. Cost: $32,900.
</P>
<P>
   Porsche C4 _ Subtle, as a Porsche can be. Wicked quick, as a
Porsche can be. Wicked fast, as a Porsche can be. Tiptronic
transmission that really let's you feel like you are shifting
(using buttons on the steering wheel, no less) and a Porsche
Stability Management system that will not let you cause the car to
fishtail _ unless you turn it off, and let the real fun begin.
Cost: $83,822.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Tundra _ For quality, comfort, quiet, and power, this is
the best pickup truck being built today. It doesn't have the raw
rumble of the Fords, Chevys, or Dodges, but its Lexus-based engine
will last longer than any plant in any of those rigs. Get it with
four doors and seating for five or six and you've got the perfect
combo for today's living: an SUV with a rear pickup truck bed.
Cost: $29,693.
</P>
<P>
   Ford SVT F-150 Lightning _ Forget common sense. Let's return to
the wonder years of big block American steel with a supercharger
strapped on for brute power. It rumbles, it roars, it burns rubber
with the flick of a foot. For truck enthusiasts who would like to
leave yuppies and their whining foreign performance cars in the
rearview mirror, this is just the beast. Cost: $30,450.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Xterra _ And speaking of returning, let's return to those
thrilling days of yesteryear when SUVs actually went off-road. When
they were spartan, utilitarian, and affordable. The Xterra takes
you there in an angular box that's meant to be ridden hard and put
away wet. Racks, bins, and tie-down spots for equipment abound.
Perfect for those who want an SUV they'll really use. Cost:
$21,499-23,297.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln LS/Chyrsler 300M _ OK, so it's two cars, but what they
represent is important: classy, comfortable, high-performance
American luxury sedans that can give the Europeans a run for their
money. The LS (full review coming next week) is the more luxurious
of the two, the 300M the car with the greatest sense of sportiness.
Costs: Lincoln, $39,105; 300M, $30,560.
</P>
<P>
   Acura NSXT _ And now it comes to this . . . of all the cars I
have driven this year, which would I like to find sitting, free of
charge, in my driveway tomorrow morning? It's got to be this
crouched aluminum rocket. Is it as fine a car as the Porsche C4? In
most folk's eyes, probably not. But is it more fun to drive? Can
you feel the road _ as in every crack in pavement or stray pebble _
through the wheel? Do you feel, once you are lowered into the
driver's seat, that you could gas it up and head for the West Coast
at high speed? Yes, to all of these questions, and that's why it's
my favorite. Cost: $88,814.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1408EST &QL; 
