<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS IS A STATE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; mere 24 hours until Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   How do you want to spend them?
</P>
<P>
   Some of us will follow the tradition of Last Minute Shopping,
taking this one last day to fight the crowds, looking for the
perfect gift. We'll tell ourselves we haven't done enough, remind
ourselves how much everyone expects from us, convince ourselves
each object we purchase as a token of our love will prove how much
we care.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the choice you've made, admire your own perseverance.
Celebrate this remarkable display of effort so close to the finish
line. Don't scatter your energies feeling angry, or sorry for
yourself, or put upon by all those folks demanding this sacrifice
of time and money. The secret of perfect happiness is never to
allow the way you feel to countermand the actions you take. Honor
the part of you that consciously made this decision, the part that
revels in an extravaganza of gifts. To give with a recalcitrant
heart is to sow the seeds of misery.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us learn this the hard way, by seeing how we taint
everything we touch when we refuse to take responsibility for our
own choice of action. The people on whose behalf we say we act
resent the false smiles we muster while radiating victimhood. Only
when we say yes with our own voices and accept that we do so of our
own volition does the joy of the season have a chance to enter us.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us will follow the tradition of Do It Yourself, having
taken this holiday as an opportunity to transform oranges into
ribboned candlesticks and make elaborate gingerbread houses. We'll
have baked cookies, draped the stairs with evergreens, sent out
family photographs, and put the ornaments we made on the tree we
cut down ourselves. Still to go _ finishing a handmade sweater and
Christmas dinner from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the choice you've made, give yourself credit for
fighting the materialistic spirit of our age. Be impressed by your
refusal to accept commercial substitutes for your own creative
energy. Don't scatter your energy, trying to complete the list
you've constructed in your head. The secret of perfect happiness is
to place what you want to do within the reasonable limits of your
time and energy. Remember, it isn't how much you do; it's the
ability to radiate loving-kindness as you do it. To compress too
much into too little space is asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us learn this the hard way, by making too many promises,
and starting too many projects. The people for whom we say we're
doing this feel marginalized by our preoccupations and upset by our
agitation. Only when we take one breath at a time and focus on
being centered rather than productive does the spirit of the season
have a chance to fill us.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the '90s tradition of No Big Deal, which means that
some of us pull out the old aluminum tree and hang the standard red
balls on it. We'll have ordered boxes of oranges for everyone over
50 on our Christmas list and bought a book for everyone else. Our
kids are getting gift certificates, our mates a kiss under
imaginary mistletoe. All that's left now is to order Chinese food
and watch a seasonal video.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the choice you've made, enjoy every minute of leisure
you can gather. Pat yourself on the back for escaping the frenzy,
for rejecting the conventional, for refusing to accept the shame
heaped on those who refuse to play the game according to the rules
of commerce and religion. Don't waste your energy cursing the way
others have yielded to the excesses of the season. The secret of
perfect happiness is to focus on the patterns of living that bring
you satisfaction and let the rest become background, like a distant
aurora borealis.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us learn this the hard way, by letting our attention
wander to the past or focusing on disturbing examples of capitalism
run amok. The people for whom we care will happily do without
ceremony if we are attentive, attuned to the present moment, and
available to them. Only by shutting out the noise of the
marketplace can we make space for the cultivation of our own souls.
</P>
<P>
   With only 24 hours to go, it's important to remember that, in
the midst of all our preparation, the only goal worth pursuing is a
state of mind _ that is, to arrive at Christmas Eve with a heart
overflowing with anticipation. There can be no magic without the
cultivation of inner delight, no pleasure without inner
peacefulness, no treasured moments to remember without an inner
eye, gazing out from the silence within at the splendor of the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
