<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MOUNTAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC MOVES THE `MOUNTAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Most people who read ``Cold Mountain'' saw it as a
great epic set in the Civil War. But Tim O'Brien and Dirk Powell
were thrilled by the references to the traditional Southern music
that the author Charles Frazier had scattered throughout it.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing notes at a Folk Alliance conference last winter in
Memphis, O'Brien and Powell found that they were both thinking
about recording the old ballads and dance tunes found in the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who plays this music, and knows the book, is going to
be interested'' in the CD that O'Brien (on guitar) and Powell (on
fiddle) made this year with banjo player John Herrmann, O'Brien
said in an interview at his home here.
</P>
<P>
   But recording the music inspired by the book proved to be more
challenging that they had thought: Their CD, ``Songs from the
Mountain,'' got hung up by legal wrangling and distribution
miscues, and it remains in the hard-to-find category.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a comedy,'' O'Brien said. His wife, Kit Swaggert,
who serves as CEO of Howdy Skies Records, the company O'Brien and
Powell formed to record the music, was blunter: ``It got really
messy when we started dealing with Hollywood lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was despite the fact that Frazier was fully behind the
project, having spent years listening to traditional musicians as
he researched the book _ and knowing full well the use he was
making of music in the novel.
</P>
<P>
   What Frazier had planted _ and what had struck a chord with
O'Brien and Powell _ were a major character who is a fiddler,
important scenes built around music, and brief phrases taken from
traditional ballads.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful scene finds the fiddler Stobrod, and a young boy who
plays the banjo, captured by a Confederate vigilante unit whose
commander asks them to ``pick me something'' before they are
executed. They play _ and O'Brien, Powell, and Herrmann record _ a
rousing version of ``Bonaparte's Retreat'' and then ``Washington's
March,'' a tune, Frazier writes, ``grim as death.''
</P>
<P>
   But even more intriguing for O'Brien and Powell were the lines
from traditional ballads that appear frequently in the thoughts of
Inman, the book's central character.
</P>
<P>
   From the song ``The Drunkard's Hiccups'' comes the line: ``If I
could sprout wings and fly.'' The line ``You can tramp down those
flowers all around my grave but they'll rise and bloom again''
comes from ``Raleigh and Spencer,'' a rousing piece that Frazier
had heard played by a North Carolina fiddler, Tommy Jarrell, whom
he has identified as one of his models for the character of
Stobrod.
</P>
<P>
   What Frazier did _ in addition to going to fiddlers' conventions
_ was to listen to the oldest available recordings from long-gone
performers as a way to echo as much as possible the speech patterns
of Southerners at the time of the Civil War. Music, he has said,
provided ``the straightest line of accessibility to that old
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting that music out of the book and onto a CD ``was a
textbook of how things can go wrong,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The Howdy Skies team quickly learned that all rights to ``Cold
Mountain'' had been sold to MGM-UA for a projected motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that was finally struck after lengthy negotiations was
that Howdy Skies could not use the title ``Cold Mountain'' on the
CD album cover _ hence ``Songs from the Mountain'' _ although that
title could be used in the liner notes.
</P>
<P>
   But a larger obstacle was the stipulation that the CD could be
sold only as a package with the paperback edition of the novel,
which had just been released. ``I think they saw that as a way to
sell more books,'' O'Brien said, ``because we had to buy 2,500
copies to package with the first pressing of the CD.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem there was that when the book-CD package arrived in
record stores, the obvious customers for the CD had already read
the book in hardcover, and thus they balked at buying the
paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Even after that obstacle was overcome and Howdy Skies was able
to market the CD separately, a glitch at the distributor prevented
many record stores from getting their orders filled.
</P>
<P>
   Things have now been straightened out sufficiently to encourage
a new pressing, Swaggert said. But Howdy Skies can sell its ``Songs
from the Mountain'' only through the end of 2000, because that was
the expected release date for the projected motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Brien and his fellow musicians dream of being
invited to do the soundtrack, pinning their hopes on an endorsement
from the author.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Swaggert said, Frazier took director Anthony
Minghella for a drive through the mountains of western North
Carolina and played a cassette of Dirk Powell performing
traditional Appachian music on the car's tape deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Frazier told Minghella, ``is what I want the music in
the film to sound like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1411EST &QL; 
