<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7596 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-KRUGMAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-23 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KRUGMAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PRINCETON, N.J.: ... people skills.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think he's actually become less pugilistic in recent
years,'' says Reich, who declined to talk about Krugman's fallout
with the Clinton team. ``Paul seems more interested in going after
ideas than people, which is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what I now know about myself, no. I would not have
given me a job in the early Clinton administration,'' says Krugman.
``I would have been too much at odds with people whose views I
didn't respect, like Reich and Magaziner.''
</P>
<P>
   Economist Lawrence Summers, who now runs the Treasury
Department, is so famously contemptuous of other economists that
``he makes me look like sweet forgiveness,'' says Krugman. ``But
Larry wants the position in a way I never did. I would have been a
disaster. Listen, you have to know who you are. My most important
collaborator, Elhanan Helpman, just turned down the Bank of Israel
job. Not for lack of intellect, but because he knew it was wrong
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, who has no children, is married to Robin Wells, an
economist hired by MIT in 1996 as part of a package deal that
brought Krugman back east from Stanford. His first marriage, to
Robin Bergman, a clothing designer, ended in divorce. He and Wells
live in North Cambridge, at least for now. Krugman acknowledges
that one purpose of the Princeton sojourn was to explore job
possibilities. ``There might be a good fit there; they have some
needs,'' he says. ``We're just talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Off campus, he and Wells enjoy what Krugman calls ``fairly small
vices'' such as gourmet cooking and summer bicycle trips to Europe.
For relaxation, he turns to pulp fiction and popular science books
_ and tries to enforce a rule against any economics after 6 p.m. at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Krugman began a new career phase by writing articles
for Foreign Affairs. In the six years since, he says, his focus has
gradually shifted away from pure research, in specialized fields
like economic geography, toward more of a synthesis of the
scholarly and the popular, now culminating in the Times
appointment. Krugman concedes it is a trade-off that sparks envy in
some, scorn in others, and conflict within himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be what they're not,'' he avers.
``Academics want real influence, policy makers are interested in
what they're going to do after they leave office, and businessmen
want to be respected for their minds. Obviously there are great
research economists out there who wonder why they can't get into
The New York Times. On the other hand, there are people like me who
wake up in the wee hours of the morning thinking, `Gosh, what
insights have I missed while I've been busy meeting deadlines?'
It's good not to get too complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems obvious to bring up the example of John Kenneth
Galbraith, the protean Harvard economist with the famously popular
touch. Obvious, perhaps, until Krugman dismisses it with the same
contempt he has heaped upon peers like Lester Thurow, Krugman's
colleague in the MIT economics department.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith is ``an interestingly funny example, because he was
never taken seriously by professional economists as a professional
economist,'' says Krugman. ``Like it or not, you wouldn't find
Galbraith on a graduate-student reading list. There's no Galbraith
Model still out there that people need to learn. So I did not
detect a lot of yearning to become the next Galbraith among PhD
economists. There are probably more wanting to become the next Paul
Krugman now, because they've seen that someone who is actually on
the grad school reading list can do that sort of thing too.''
</P>
<P>
   It is comments such as these that prompt others to paint Krugman
as ``arrogant'' and ``smug,'' even while conceding his talent and
writing ability. In 1996, Robert Kuttner wrote a scolding essay in
The American Prospect titled ``Peddling Krugman.'' In the piece,
Kuttner called Krugman _ a onetime contributor to the Prospect _
``the conservative's ideal liberal'' and accused him of, among
other sins, hypocrisy, lack of commitment to teaching duties, and
making the world safer for political and fiscal conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Krugman's world,'' wrote Kuttner, ``if bizarre arguments
are dressed up in formal models, they pass muster as economic
science, even if they turn out to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuttner says he had more fun deconstructing Krugman than with
any other piece he's written. And he is disappointed the Times did
not make a more unconventional choice to fill its op-ed slot. With
Krugman appearing on the same page as Friedman, says Kuttner, ``The
Times' op-ed page will now run the gamut from A to B in its
diversity of views on political economics. Paul's clever, and he
writes well. But so much of his career has been spent as an
enforcer of boundaries, of who's mainstream and who's
conventional.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is late afternoon, and Krugman is addressing an overflow
crowd in a seminar room upstairs from his Fisher Hall office. The
subject is recession-racked Japan and its so-called (thanks to
Krugman) ``liquidity trap,'' a condition brought on, he explains,
by the country's banking system having too much savings and not
enough demand for capital investment. As outlined by Krugman, the
result is interest rates hovering at zero and persistent economic
stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``credibility problem'' for Japan, Krugman admits
he failed to take the crisis seriously before, an admission his
detractors would no doubt cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me to see what I got wrong,'' he tells an
audience of grad students. His advice to Japanese policy makers?
``Throw everything plus the rice cooker at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the talk are many equations that surely make more
sense to PhD candidates in economics than to visiting reporters.
Times readers will soon make their own assessment of Krugman's
handiwork. Told by one visitor that he had ``learned something''
during the lecture, though, Krugman looks skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?'' he says. ``And what would that be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1412EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
