<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER EDITOR SEEKS TO RENEW THE NEW REPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Beinart is not only trying to revive the fading fortunes
of The New Republic, where the primary story in recent years has
been the messy editor exodus. He's trying to prove he's the right
man for one of journalism's real high-wire acts.
</P>
<P>
   Beinart _ a five-year New Republic staffer who became editor of
the 85-year-old opinion journal on Nov. 1 _ has a tough sell with
the skeptics. The New York Observer snidely announced his ascension
by characterizing him as ``a self-effacing 28-year-old former
intern.'' And the media world is watching, waiting to see if he can
give the 92,000-circulation magazine a coherent identity, forge a
workable relationship with owner Marty Peretz, and avoid the fate
of his recent predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that his task is daunting. The good news is that
everyone is rooting for him. ``God knows the magazine needs a
period of stability and success,'' says new Atlantic Monthly editor
Michael Kelly, who was fired by Peretz in 1997 after a turbulent
nine months as editor. ``And Peter Beinart is a very good bet to
provide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his odds of success, Beinart _ a Cambridge, Mass.
native and Buckingham, Browne &AMP; Nichols alum (his stepfather is
American Repertory Theatre artistic director and New Republic
contributor Robert Brustein) _ takes over a magazine in need of
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   One big problem has been the revolving door in the editor's
office. Andrew Sullivan departed in 1996 with Peretz grumbling that
he had softened the magazine with ``uncontextualized froth.''
Kelly, a vocal Clinton critic, left after clashing with his boss
over the magazine's treatment of Peretz favorite Al Gore. In
September, Chuck Lane resigned suddenly after apparently getting
wind that his days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   This turnover has occurred in the larger context of a gradual
brain drain. A decade ago, The New Republic featured an all-star
lineup of people like Hendrik Hertzberg, Fred Barnes, Sidney
Blumenthal, Michael Kinsley, Robert Kuttner, and Morton Kondracke _
one that hasn't since been replicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, it was serendipity,'' says Beinart. ``It was a
remarkable collection of people. . . . Part of it was the time.''
Ronald Reagan's presidency may have marked The New Republic's last
great burst of energy, when the once liberal magazine tacked to the
center and in Beinart's words, was ``ruthless about taking people
on in our own camp.'' (A landmark was the 1986 editorial ``The Case
for the Contras'').
</P>
<P>
   Peretz, who simply responds ``yeah'' when asked if his magazine
has lost some altitude, says that ``politics has not focused on big
ideas, and Bill Clinton's presidency was in a certain sense . . . a
great titillating diversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor working against The New Republic is the
proliferation of faster, newer media like cable news networks and
the Internet. ``They can jump on the news cycle. And the weekly
opinion magazines are just struggling to get a voice in the
wilderness,'' says Hotline newsletter editor Craig Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   But Beinart, likeable, bright, and mildly hyper, has a
three-point plan of attack. First ``it's a magazine that's out
there to take risks . . . willing to take on sacred cows,'' he
says. Exhibit A: a clever Dec. 20 cover package called ``Why
America Loves Stupid Candidates,'' featuring George W. Bush in a
dunce cap and a piece by Andrew Sullivan comparing him to another
party boy pol, John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second thing is the magazine has to be a lot more on the
news,'' he adds. ``The stuff has to be ruthlessly reported.'' So
Beinart dispatched a reporter to Decatur, Ill. to write a Dec. 6
story on the racial wounds opened by the expulsion of six black
students after a football game brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing is the magazine really has to have a sense of
fun,'' continues Beinart. A Jan. 3 parody issue devoted to the
millennium doesn't quite hit the mark. But an upcoming satirical
presidential campaign feature written by Doug McGrath called ``Dear
Village'' holds promise.
</P>
<P>
   One subject Beinart is no doubt tired of discussing is Al Gore.
Given Peretz's well-known fondness for the vice president, the
issue isn't so much about the magazine's politics as it is about
the editor's independence. The matter reared its head in October,
when The Washington Post reported that Beinart killed a piece on
Bill Bradley by Salon.com Washington correspondent Jake Tapper.
``Maybe it didn't fit in with their agenda,'' Tapper told the Post.
``Clearly, a fair and unbiased analysis of Bill Bradley's Senate
career . . . does not belong in Peter Beinart's New Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception (of favoritism toward Gore) has been a
problem,'' responds Beinart, who says that anyone who reads The New
Republic under his watch ``would not see the magazine as shilling
for anybody and I've gotten no pressure to shill for anybody.''
Arguing his case, he cites a Dec. 20 Notebook item critical of
Gore's pandering and a Dec. 13 story essentially lauding Bradley's
health care proposal over Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we're going to endorse Al Gore in the
primary,'' he insists, perhaps bravely. ``That's very much up in
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his challenges, Beinart's biggest asset is a substantial
reservoir of good will. Kelly, his ex-colleague at The New
Republic, calls him ``first rate in every way.'' Says Peretz, who's
known to change his mind on editors: ``I have such an exhilarated
feeling about Peter. . . . He's going to restore, I hope, (the
magazine's) primacy in big political and historical ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Tapper, who's waiting to be paid for his aborted Bradley
piece, wishes Beinart well. ``Quite frankly, I hope he turns The
New Republic around,'' he says. ``Just send me my kill fee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
