<HEADLINE>
SANTA'S LITTLE HELPER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 (For release: Dec. 26 or thereafter)  
 By SUSAN DOMINUS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    I'm always a bit cranky the day after Christmas, when I promptly
take down those flattering white lights and toss the remaining
gingerbread limbs that would just go stale anyway.
 &HT;    I might try to cheer myself up with my ``Acoustic Christmas''
CD, but the Hooters' cover of ``Silent Night'' has no charm now
that the moment has passed. This morning-after dejection, I
realize, would be a common response to a favorite holiday's end _
except that I'm Jewish.
 &HT;    Yiddishe grandmother Jewish. Years-of-Hebrew-school Jewish.
Know-it-to-look-at-me Jewish.
 &HT;    My attachment to the holiday isn't one born of nostalgia, at
least not for an experience of my own. Growing up, we weren't the
kind of Jews who had a Christmas tree with a Star of David on top,
nor even a so-called Hanukkah bush.
 &HT;    My Hebrew-school teachers dismissed such seasonal trappings as
``goyishe narrishkeit'' (though my parents promised that if I
really wanted a tree, I could have one in March). For their
generation, Christmas was yet another locus of exclusion, a party
to which they had not been invited.
 &HT;    And Hanukkah made a poor substitute, a minor event in the annual
calendar _ not even a High Holy Day _ dressed up and retrofitted to
satisfy third-generation children.
 &HT;    What's more, we all knew it. Smirking my way through Hanukkah
circa 1982 may well have been My First Ironic Experience. By the
fourth night of candle-lighting, I was itching to get back to the
``Benson'' rerun I was watching.
 &HT;    My appreciation for Christmas, on the other hand, developed
completely without irony. That affection, I should clarify, does
not include the holy stillness of midnight Mass or the simple
truths of Scripture _ I don't know from those, as my grandmother
would say.
 &HT;    I'm talking about the bells and whistles that differentiated the
holiday from Hanukkah: the hand-painted, faux-antique ornaments and
rooftop reindeer and mail-order gourmet fruitcakes. Precisely the
sorts of things that serious Christians sometimes deplore as
crassly commercial, a tacky, insipid betrayal of the holiday's true
meaning.
 &HT;    But that's their issue, not mine. It's hard to worry about
maintaining the purity of a holiday that isn't really yours to
begin with. And much easier to enjoy its light side when you don't
have to deal with tough questions of faith or responsibility, or
with all those magical-realist plot lines.
 &HT;    And so, not normally a booster for rampant materialism, I
forgive all in the season of giving and gaze at the windows of
F.A.O. Schwarz, cheeks rosy, eyes brimming. I make an annual
pilgrimage to the tree at Rockefeller Center. I've actually crashed
groups of carolers. And I've barely forgiven my older brother for
quitting his high school gig as a mallside Santa because he was
allergic (weakling!) to the glue of the beard.
 &HT;    Furthermore, I'm not alone in my taste for tinsel. Even some of
my most jaded Jewish friends share my delight in the indulgent
excesses of Christmas treacle. I invite them over for eggnog. They
drag me out to see their favorite manger. I'm not proud to admit
this, but we have even watched the stop-action ``Rudolph'' special,
year after year after year. Can gift boxes of Russell Stover candy
be far off?
 &HT;    Indeed, American Jews in general have proved themselves such
eager Christmas enthusiasts that they've actually contributed a
startling number of the images that now define the holiday.
 &HT;    The pretty picture of fair-haired gamins in dressy tartans,
gathered about the hearth with their hunting dogs, is practically a
trademark of Ralph Lauren, ne Lifschitz. And of course it was a
Jew, Irving Berlin, who first wrote longingly of a white Christmas
_ just like the ones he used to know.
 &HT;    In recent years, it seems that Jews have started turning that
kitschy exuberance toward their own rituals. Whereas Hanukkah was a
fairly casual affair during my childhood, it's now a full-scale
production, with its own fetish objects _ hand-painted,
faux-antique Stars of David, Winnie the Pooh dreidels, mail-order
gourmet latkes, strings of foil stars with which to bedeck your
haimishe halls.
 &HT;    If my parents felt excluded from Christmas, and I embraced it, I
suspect my 2-year-old niece _ who spent those eight days listening
to a Hebrew Hanukkah music soundtrack, surrounded by a set of
sparkly menorah and candle decorations _ will grow up indifferent
to it.
 &HT;    For all my devotion to the spirit of another religion's holiday,
though, there's one line I've never crossed. I've never bought a
Christmas tree. As every kid knows, you can't celebrate Christmas
without one, and I don't.
 &HT;    Come Dec. 25, I fall on the side of tradition _ my own, that is
_ and spend the day doing laundry. I can comfortably visit the
holiday, take in the lovely sights and sounds, but I have no real
interest in laying claim to it or to its central symbol, and I
suspect I never will.
 &HT;    But if I did, I know just how I'd decorate it.
 &HT;     c.1999 Susan Dominus  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan Dominus is the executive editor of Nerve.com.) &LR;
</P>
