<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-MILLENNIUM-BOS     12-23 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MILLENNIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, RELUCTANT HOSTS TO PILGRIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Imagine having to host a party that is not your own.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Rabbi Donniel Hartman, a prominent interfaith
scholar, describes the Jewish state's awkward position as it
prepares for millions of Christian visitors, including Pope John
Paul II, to celebrate 2000 years of Christianity in the land of its
birth.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasy position accounts for what Hartman calls a ``polite
silence'' in Israeli society on the eve of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of happening. But it's happening under the surface,
you don't sense any excitement,'' says Hartman, of the Shalom
Hartman Institute, where he is an Orthodox rabbi and avid proponent
of interfaith dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, allegations are flying from leaders of
Israel's own tourism industry that the Jewish state has failed to
prepare adequately for the millennium and may squander a valuable
opportunity for Israel graciously to host Christians from all over
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers say a unique opportunity for the coming holidays
to be an occasion for dialogue between the two faiths has been
largely reduced to a security threat. Secular Israeli police
officials are focused on fringe Christian sects filled with
apocalyptic fantasies that 2000 marks ``the end of days,'' as it is
referred to in the Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   And in some corners of Israel, the throng of Christian visitors
and celebrations often stirs bitter memories of Christianity's long
history of persecuting Jews. To many ultra-Orthodox Jews, the
occasion is seen as an affront to Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article in the Haredi newspaper Yated Neeman said
Christians are preparing for ``a great crusade in our holy land.''
It emphasizes the ``profanity and apostasy of the Christians'' and
depicts them as ``enemies of Judaism from time immemorial.''
</P>
<P>
   It also calls on the Haredi, or ``God fearing,'' community to
refuse Christians apartment rentals or hotel rooms in Haredi
neighborhoods, advises readers ``to stop them from holding
processions and ceremonies in public places,'' and to ``bar them
from visiting our holy places.''
</P>
<P>
   But such Israeli references to ``our holy places'' and even
Hartman's notion of a party in ``our home'' deeply offends
Christian leaders, who counter that Christianity was born in the
land and that many Palestinian Christians who live in the Galilee,
West Bank, and Jerusalem can trace their roots to the earliest
followers of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank town of Bethlehem, where Jesus was born and which
will be the focus of Christmas celebrations, is also under
Palestinian rule as a result of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Peter Vasco, director of the Holy Land Foundation and a
liaison between the US Embassy and the Franciscan Order, which
holds custody of some Christian holy sites, says, ``It is nice that
they think of it as an invitation to their home, but we like to
think of it as our home as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is Israel that is assuming the responsibility of the
influx of tourists at Ben Gurion International Airport and
coordinating the arrival of a host of world dignitaries and church
leaders to holy sites in Jerusalem, Nazareth, and the Galilee
region. And it is Israel that will shoulder the enormous burden of
security for the Holy Land's millennial visitors.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a country built on the ashes of the Holocaust and a
history of suffering under Christendom deal with such a
celebration?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to host this event with the greatest respect,''
says Jerusalem's mayor, Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
   Respect perhaps, but not necessarily a sense of festivity,
according to Jonathan Harpz, director of the Jerusalem Hotel
Association.
</P>
<P>
   He was quoted in Friday's Jerusalem Post as saying, ``Jerusalem
is filthy, simply disgusting. The city isn't lit and it doesn't
feel festive. . . . The city isn't decorated. And the mayor should
have made these things his priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Meron Benvenisti, former deputy mayor of Jerusalem, has been
publicly warning Israelis about what he sees as a lack of
generosity of spirit toward the coming Christian celebrations,
saying that ``Israelis are flinching at the idea of the Christian
attachment to the Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, director of the Anti-Defamation League's
office in Israel, says the focus by Israeli authorities and news
media on the small fringe of apocalyptic Christians reveals an
ignorance about Christianity and of the vast majority who come here
as religious pilgrims or perhaps just tourists who wish to see the
land where their faith has its origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of focus on the fringe misses the great opportunity
we have here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As Hartman puts it, ``A lot of the silence that is taking place
is because we don't know how to take advantage of that
opprotunity.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll commissioned by the Chicago-based International
Fellowship of Christians and Jews revealed widespread ignorance
about Christianity in Israel. The poll of 479 Israelis, with a
margin of error of 4 percent, revealed that 75 percent could not
identify the date of Christmas. Some 65 percent do not have a
single Christian friend and only slightly fewer said they have
never been personally aquainted with a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   The ignorance reflected in the poll can be traced to the lack of
substantive education about Christianity in Israeli schools,
according to Ron Kronish, director of the Interreligious
Coordinating Council in Israel, a prominent Jerusalem-based
organization promoting interfaith dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Kronish, who presented a research paper last year to the Vatican
on the issue and has recently published its findings in Israel,
says: ``There is virtually no education about Christianity in
Israeli schools'' other than a very brief skimming of its history
in junior high grades. What little is taught about Christianity, he
says, leaves students with ``a very dark, medieval view of
Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes up through the Crusades to the Holocaust, and then it
just stops without any discussion of changes in the last three
decades,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Kronish has recommended that Israeli schools adopt a special
curriculum in the coming year to learn more about Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity ahead of us,'' he says. ``And it
remains to be seen if we are going to take it more seriously. We
still have time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
