<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ The shuttle astronauts take a second
space walk to fix the Hubble Telescope, from 1 to 8 p.m. EST. By
Warren E. Leary. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-VENTURE-CAPITAL (Undated) _ For venture capitalists, times
have never been richer. Now big banks want a piece of the action.
Since 1996, major commercial banks like Chase Manhattan have
tripled the money they devote to venture capital, the high-risk,
high-return world of financing startup companies. The appeal is
obvious. Chase and its kin are happy to get 8 percent interest on a
typical loan, while the average venture capital investment in a new
company almost doubled this year. And bank stocks have been weak
this year, while stocks in publicly traded venture capital
companies like CMGI have soared. But as banks move deeper into
venture capital, they face some risks of their own. A few banks,
notably Chase and Wells Fargo, have had successful venture arms for
years, but others have little experience with the hyper-competition
of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-INDUSTRY (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The German government
says it plans to repeal taxes on capital gains from the sale of
industrial holdings inside the country, a move that could reshape
the country's corporate landscape. The large stakes in industrial
companies held by big banks and financial companies have helped
preserve ``fortress Germany'' at a time when the rest of Europe is
undergoing sweeping consolidation. German stocks surge more than 4
percent, led by Allianz, Deutsche Bank and other financial
companies. Allianz alone holds industrial stakes worth $30 billion,
while Deutsche Bank owns stakes worth about $25 billion. The
proposal, however, is vague on many details and in any case must be
approved by both houses of Germany's Parliament. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks surge. At 2:15 p.m., the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 205 points to 11408, a record. The S&AMP;P
500 was up 23 points, and the Nasdaq composite index up 47 points.
Treasury prices were little changed. European markets were also
higher, with London up 0.85 percent and Frankfurt up 4.17 percent.
The Tokyo market was closed for the Emperor's birthday. Hong Kong's
Hang Seng index ended up 0.64 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
