<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     12-23 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY ODYSSEY OF `I KISS YOU' CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Mahir Cagri was just an unwitting Web
celebrity, a regular guy who woke up one morning to discover he had
been transformed into an international cult figure. He was
impossible to contact, a mysterious figure, an image without a
voice. But after weeks of ignoring my pleas (written in fractured
Turk-glish), he finally called the other day to tell his version of
the story. And guess what? Now that he is a close personal friend,
I can tell you that Mahir Cagri is famous for all the wrong
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like sex, but that is not something I would tell the whole
world,'' he says. ``I would rather ask the world to think about the
children who are dying of hunger. We need to share.''
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, Cagri is the Turkish fellow whose earnest
home page _ ``I kiss you!!!!'' _ was stolen by a hacker who spiced
up the Web page with such comments as ``I like sex.'' The doctored
page was transmitted all over the world, and jokesters posted
dozens of parody sites, featuring animated songs, games, and films
showing Cagri in compromising positions. Folks had a great time
chuckling at Cagri's English, noting his affection for ``music
enstrumans'' and his desire to ``invitate peoples'' to visit him in
Izmir. Some entrepreneurs even sold his image on coffee mugs and
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me happy if they are having fun and getting away from
their problems,'' Cagri says of his new fans and ``friends.'' He
adds that he has even forgiven the hacker. He also has no interest
in going after journalists who have misrepresented him, including a
British writer who claimed that Cagri was demanding $50,000 to do
an interview with CNN. (Not true.) ``I don't have time to run after
those articles,'' he says through a translator during a telephone
interview from New York. ``I have other things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Cagri is on a US media tour sponsored by a Web
company called eTour.com, a free member-based guide to the
Internet. The company brought Cagri over as the guest of honor at
its recent publicity party. ``Here you have a guy whose whole world
has been turned upside down, and he's really Mr. Cool,'' says Jim
Lanzone, eTour's vice president of marketing. ``He wants to visit
every single person who wrote to him. He keeps saying, `I must go
to Buffalo. I must go to Tacoma.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cagri received offers from many US firms, but he says that eTour
extended the ``warmest of invitations.'' He says a film company,
which he will not name, traveled to Turkey and offered him $25,000
to shoot a film about his life. ``When they first came over, they
thought we didn't know anything about the world, and they were
shocked when they met us,'' he recalls. ``In five days, they were
up to $250,000, but I did not accept because I don't like those
people. Money is not everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cagri realizes that folks are eager to capitalize on his image
as some rube who _ perish the thought! _ can't speak the Queen's
English. ``They are the ones who don't know the world,'' he says.
``They are the ones who are living in their own tower. They are the
ones who have lost love. I am Turkish. Why do I have to speak
English? They can't say a word in Turkish, but I can say what I
need in English.''
</P>
<P>
   He says if he makes any money out of this Kafkaesque brush with
fame, he wants to use it to build a school for children from
war-torn areas. He has already convinced one West Coast
entrepreneur selling ``I kiss you!!!'' merchandise to donate the
proceeds to a nonprofit organization that supports refugees in the
Caucasus. ``It wasn't a considerable amount, but he did give me
some money,'' Cagri says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a rich man,'' he continues. ``I am a regular man. But
I would like to find a lawyer soon to stop those people from doing
what they are doing. Everybody that uses me in a bad way, I am
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun is fine, but Cagri would appreciate it if his fans would
help him save the world. ``I think I can use this in a positive way
if I can get help from people like you who are journalists,'' he
says. ``I am thinking of setting up the Mahir Friendship, Love, and
Peace Fan Club. Of course, it will be fun, but we will work on
world problems as well.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's off to visit his new best friends on his whirlwind
tour. He's terribly sorry that he can't invite every one of them to
stay at his house, but it seems he does have time to entertain
certain members of the Fourth Estate. ``I invite you,'' he says,
before racing off to the next interview. And my husband? ``Yes. I
invite him. You can come.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I spent some quality time watching ``The Donny and
Marie Show'' at work. A celebrity dentist was revealing toothsome
secrets. Riveting, it wasn't. But it was the only thing I could get
on my desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. A Canadian company called ICraveTV.com is
rebroadcasting programming from 17 television stations in Canada
and the United States live on the Internet. The broadcast quality
is awful, but the very fact that this upstart company is doing this
has TV stations and the National Football League up in arms. The
company is testing the limits of laws about broadcasting
programming on line and has already received cease and desist
demands from the NFL and a consortium of local stations in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is imperative that this illegal behavior be nipped in the
bud,'' says Tom Davidson, the counsel for WKBW-TV in Buffalo who is
working with a group of broadcasters. According to US law, only
cable and satellite companies may retransmit copyrighted
programming provided that they pay royalties into a pool that is
redistributed to the original programmers. ``Web site operators
don't qualify under US law, and Canada has a similar law,'' says
Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   But William Craig, president and founder of ICraveTV, claims
that it is legal to retransmit programming over the Internet in
Canada. The Web site asks users to enter a Canadian area code
before receiving access to the programs. Anyone can simply look up
a number in the phone book and gain instant access to such fare as
``Donny and Marie.'' ``You could also go down to the store and
steal a shirt, but does that mean those stores shouldn't be selling
shirts?'' says Craig. ``In a free marketplace, you have to rely on
people not committing fraud.'' Craig is selling ads on the site;
the more folks who view the site _ from New Brunswick, Canada, or
New Brunswick, N.J. _ the more money he makes.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the case raises intriguing questions about what can
be broadcast on line, and it's not going away. Both Davidson and an
NFL spokesperson say they plan to take further legal action soon.
Stay tuned _ but not on ICraveTV.com. That would be fraud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have way too much time on their hands, the
latest Net craze is a little game called Elf Bowling. The
dreamchild of a Dallas company called NVision Design, the game
features Santa's helpers, who get sick of working for the Clauses
and go on strike. Santa retaliates by turning them into pins in a
bowling game. It's dumb, but it's hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems that there's an urban legend surrounding the game.
A message is circulating via e-mail warning that the game is
infected with a delayed virus that will be activated Dec. 25. Not
true, says Dan Ferguson, president of NVision Design. ``There is a
virus scare every two weeks, but this is only a hoax,'' he says.
The Symantec Virus Research Center, in fact, has issued an alert
that the rumors are false; Elf Bowling is clean. You can download
it from NVisiondesign.com. But think of the poor squeaking elves
during this holiday season: After all, elves are people, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to cyberlinks(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
