<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-McCAIN-$ADV26     12-23 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-McCAIN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 McCAIN, BRADLEY ATTRACT THE SAME KIND OF VOTERS  
 (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``P'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they surge upward in the New Hampshire polls,
Democratic contender Bill Bradley and Republican hopeful Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., find themselves facing unlikely competitors _ each
other.
</P>
<P>
   With less than six weeks before the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary
_ the nation's first _ these two anti-party mavericks are racing to
attract the same kind of voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 139 Republican-leaning New Hampshire independents
earlier this month by Utica, N.Y.-based pollster John Zogby, 28.7
percent of the independents said McCain was their first choice,
with 21.7 percent preferring the national GOP front-runner, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. Independents represent about 37 percent of
the iconoclastic Granite State's electorate, one percentage point
ahead of Republicans and 10 points ahead of Democrats. Swaying
independents has enabled McCain to pull even or go ahead of Bush in
most New Hampshire polls, as has Bradley in his race against Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the surprise.
</P>
<P>
   When asked their second choice for president, more of the
Republican-leaning independents selected Democrat Bradley over any
of the Republican candidates. The former senator from New Jersey
and New York Knicks basketball star got 15.5 percent, ahead of
publishing magnate Steve Forbes with 14.3 percent and Bush with 9.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern shows up for Democratic-leaning independent
voters who favor Bradley. Asked their second choice, 31.1 percent
picked Republican McCain, while 24.6 percent picked Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dynamic worth watching in the New Hampshire primary
and elsewhere,'' Zogby said. The race for the independent vote ``is
kind of a second-level primary ... A late surge for McCain may be
based on Bradley voters defecting, or vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Some party regulars discount the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polling data is (from) New Hampshire, which is obviously
different than the country as a whole,'' said Democratic National
Committee chairman Joe Andrew. ``I don't see that (as a broad
trend) at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But other polling data suggests supporters of McCain and Bradley
share an important characteristic: They care more about personality
than politics.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide poll of 1,073 adults last week by the
Washington-based Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press
showed that Bradley's support is based more on his reputation as a
star basketball player than on his liberal political leanings or
18-year record in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, McCain's record as a U.S. Navy pilot in Vietnam who
spent five-and-a-half years as a prisoner of war is more important
to his supporters than his conservative leanings or 12 years in the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genuineness and outsider-ism are things that draw people to
these candidates,'' said Andrew Kohut, the Pew Center's director.
``It's a good thing for them, but independents could be drawn from
one to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The twinning of McCain and Bradley is surprising because they
are far apart in ideology and voting records.
</P>
<P>
   True, they appeared together in New Hampshire Dec. 16 to stump
for campaign finance reform. And both have expressed support in
varying degrees for vouchers to help parents pay private school
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain opposes legal abortion while Bradley favors it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain opposes banning guns while Bradley favors banning
inexpensive handguns, ``Saturday night specials.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain supports greater defense spending to improve military
battle readiness. Bradley says eliminating pork-barrel military
weapons programs can yield savings.
</P>
<P>
   Why are independent voters willing to leap the ideological fence
so easily?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with (McCain's and Bradley's) anti-party,
anti-establishment attitude toward politics,'' said Linda Fowler, a
political scientist at Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., who
oversees the Dartmouth-Associated Press Poll in New Hampshire.
``Partly that's the culture of the state. Independent voters make
up their minds late, and they're less tied to philosophy than
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this pattern repeats itself in other states may depend
on whether primaries are open or closed. New Hampshire is an open
primary state, meaning any voter may vote in either party primary
regardless of party membership or lack of it. Twenty other states
have open primaries, including Michigan and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, four states (including Washington and California)
have ``blanket'' primaries. In these states, primary voters get a
combined ballot and vote for one candidate for each office,
regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   Both the open and blanket primary systems give added strength to
independent candidates because independent voters can cast ballots
in those system, whereas they are prohibited from voting in
primaries in states that require party membership to participate in
primary voting.
</P>
<P>
   The primaries in the remaining 25 states are closed, meaning a
party primary is open only to voters who are registered with that
party. Among these are New York. Closed primaries by definition
encourage party loyalists and diminish the potential of
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain and Bradley will do better in any state that allows
independents, and less well in states that don't allow them,'' said
Larry Sabato, government professor at the University of Virginia.
``This is the point where independents have influence, but after
New Hampshire the partisans will reassert control.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain led Bush by 9 points, 39 percent to 30
percent, in a poll earlier this month by the American Research
Group. On the Democratic side, the same polling organization found
44 percent for Bradley and 40 percent for Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
