<P>
   INTERNATIONAL-STYLE (New York) _ The Met Life (formerly Pan Am)
Building at the foot of Park Avenue is one of the worst disasters
ever to befall the New York cityscape. All New Yorkers acknowledge
the universal truth of this belief. But Kivi Sotamaa, a young
Finnish architect, likes the building very much. Most startling of
all, Satamaa appreciates the closure that the building brings to
the southern end of Park Avenue, and to the grand boulevard of
International Style office towers leading toward it. To him, and to
a surprising number of other architects and city-lovers, the
so-called Park Avenue Corridor is the architectural heart of the
20th century. The corridor is the crystallization of the New York
myth, the soaring city of work and ambition, where the sky is the
limit and dreams are fulfilled. It symbolizes New York's
displacement of Paris as the century's most vibrant City of Light.
By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-PAST (Undated) _ There has never been any doubt that
in the spectral trinity Dickens created to preside over the yule
holiday, the Ghost of Christmas Past reigns as first among equals _
the Prime Mover of mood and spirit. Christmas might, in fact, be
characterized as a holiday in continual, necessary decline, a
celebration whose emotional center is our insistence upon the
superiority of Christmases gone by. White Christmases are, by
definition, the ones you used to know. A look back at Christmas
1899. By Thomas Mallon.
</P>
