<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-CRADLE-SPI &LR;      12-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRADLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `CRADLE' IS JUST TOO CROWDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Depression year of 1937, the 22-year-old, pre-``Citizen
Kane'' Orson Welles directed a pro-labor musical for Roosevelt's
Federal Theater Project called ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' which was
written by Marc Blitzstein and set in the midst of a steel strike.
</P>
<P>
   But the day of its opening, the government (possibly because it
feared the play's communist sympathies, possibly for more benign
reasons) canceled the opening, closed the Maxine Elliott Theater
and forced the company to perform the play illegally in another
venue _ making it a great succes de scandale.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Welles himself was involved with a movie project based
on this incident and wrote a screenplay (which has been published
as ``The Cradle Will Rock: An Original Screenplay''). But after the
film was cast (with Rupert Everett as Welles) and all the sets had
been constructed, the financing fell through and the project died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cradle Will Rock'' (missing its article) is a new version
written and directed by Tim Robbins. It apparently bears no
relationship to the Welles project and fans out to not only
chronicle the famous theatrical incident but to be a broadly
comedic cross-section of the Manhattan cultural scene of the time.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it's an interesting and likably ambitious movie
with an ensemble of mostly engaging character vignettes, but,
sadly, it misses its mark.
</P>
<P>
   At times it resembles a low-budget television docudrama, and its
efforts to be an analogy _ and a warning _ to our own time fall
flat.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set during three periods _ conception, first
rehearsals and opening night _ and weaves in and out of a tapestry
of real and fictional characters, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Composer Blitzstein, (Hank Azaria) who struggles to compose the
piece at his piano and sell it to the theater arm of the Works
Progress Administration.
</P>
<P>
   _Olive Stanton (Emily Watson), a homeless actress-singer who
wangles herself an audition and the play's prostitute lead role.
</P>
<P>
   _Nelson Rockefeller (John Cusack), a capitalist who becomes
locked in a battle of wills with left-wing Mexican muralist Diego
Rivera (Ruben Blades).
</P>
<P>
   _Margherita Sarfatti (Susan Sarandon), a Jewish Italian envoy
who is trading her country's art treasures for U.S. industrial
support for Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   _Tommy Crickshaw (Bill Murray), a vaudeville ventriloquist who
joins a right-wing WPA employee (Joan Cusack) to rid its theater
arm of ``red'' control.
</P>
<P>
   _Aldo Silvano (John Turturro), a poor Italian American cast
member obviously based on the great left-wing character actor
Howard DaSilva.
</P>
<P>
   _Countess La Grange (Vanessa Redgrave), a silly New York society
matron and patron of the arts married to a thick-headed steel
magnate (Phillip Baker Hall).
</P>
<P>
   Also in the mix are Welles (Angus Macfadyen), his producer John
Houseman (Cary Elwes), Theater Project director Hallie Flanagan
(Cherry Jones) and such important cultural and political figures of
the time as William Randolph Hearst (John Carpenter), Marion Davies
(Gretchen Mol), Frida Kahlo (Corina Katt), Congressman Martin Dies
(Harris Yulin) and Harry Hopkins (Bob Balaban).
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Robbins tosses all these ingredients into his
pot, mixes them together with rapid cross-cutting to give the
proceedings a lightning-fast, screwball comedy pace, and hopes his
souffle will rise. It doesn't, at least not as high as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several good performances (Murray, Blades, John Cusack
and Jones, in particular), the blessings are unevenly distributed.
The film fails so consistently as knockabout comedy that it makes
one wonder if it might have worked better with a more serious
approach (as in the Welles screenplay).
</P>
<P>
   It also ends with little satisfaction. First it fails to tell us
that the play went on to many other performances and a successful
tour, and it closes with an enigmatic coda that seems to be warning
us about the dangers of corporate ownership of art. Unfortunately,
it is so vague it doesn't make its point.
</P>
<P>
   Cradle Will Rock. Directed and written by Tim Robbins. Cast:
Hank Azaria, Ruben Blades, Joan Cusack, John Cusack, Cherry Jones,
Bill Murray, Vanessa Redgrave, Susan Sarandon, John Turturro, Emily
Watson. Touchstone. 125 minutes. Rated R for some brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
