<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-AFFAIR-SPI &LR;      12-23 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFAIR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFFAIR' FOLLOWS NOVEL MORE CLOSELY THAN 1955 FILM, BUT STILL
STRAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publicists for the new film version of Graham Greene's 1951
novel, ``The End of the Affair,'' sent a copy of the book to movie
critics, which is a good thing because I don't think I would know
what was going on in the movie if I hadn't read it.
</P>
<P>
   When Neil Jordan announced the film last year, he was openly
contemptuous of the 1955 version directed by Edward Dmytryk and
starring Van Johnson and Deborah Kerr _ saying he didn't consider
his film a remake because the first film was ``not even close'' to
the novel.
</P>
<P>
   But, though Jordan's movie is very stylish and well-acted and
follows the first half of the novel faithfully, it takes a big
swing away from fidelity in the last act and misses the intense
religious struggle of both main characters that is the heart of the
story. The result is an engaging but essentially routine tragic
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the novel, it opens in 1946 postwar London, as successful
novelist Maurice Bendrix (Ralph Fiennes) has a chance meeting with
Sarah Miles (Julianne Moore), a beautiful but somewhat troubled
married woman with whom he had a long, torrid, wartime affair that
ended abruptly two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   What happened, we soon learn, is that while he and Sarah were in
the afterglow of making love at his flat on that fateful day in
1944, a German V1 buzz bomb landed nearby and nearly killed him.
When the smoke cleared, Sarah would have nothing more to do with
him. And not knowing why, it's been eating him up ever since.
</P>
<P>
   When Sarah's clueless and dull husband, Henry (Stephen Rea),
privately tells Bendrix that he suspects Sarah is having an affair,
the writer is consumed by jealousy, hires a private detective (Ian
Hart) to watch her and plunges into a quest to find out why their
own affair ended, and how he might get her back.
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, he finds _ mostly from reading Sarah's stolen
journal _ that Sarah is still deeply in love with him, but has made
a deal with God, and, though she went into the deal as an agnostic,
it sent her on a difficult, almost saintly, mystical-religious
quest that precludes a love affair with Bendrix or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   And as he learns all this and desperately tries to pull her back
down to earth, and she resists his efforts, the total-atheist
Bendrix is brought into an internal struggle with the Supreme Being
he doesn't believe exists _ and the strange love triangle
ultimately affirms the existence of God.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's a story with a very religious subtext: It's
completely autobiographical _ based on Greene's own affair with an
American woman in the same period, and more or less following the
story of his own intellectual and religious struggles.
</P>
<P>
   The film hits the few high points of this internal conflict in
some of Bendrix's narration and in one last-act miracle; but Jordan
_ obviously not wanting to make a ``religious'' movie _ has tossed
most of it out, combined characters, and twisted the plot into a
rather conventional tragic love story with perhaps the box-office
appeal of ``The English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The four performances (especially Moore and Hart) are strong,
and the visual evocation of wartime London in numerous flashbacks
has a moody beauty. But, as good as it is in all these departments,
it doesn't really work. It seems to have a hole in the center of
it: a love triangle in which one of the participants is missing.
</P>
<P>
   The End of the Affair. Directed and written by Neil Jordan.
Cast: Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore, Stephen Rea, Ian Hart.
Columbia Pictures. 105 minutes. Rated R for nudity and sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
