<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENUFLECTING AT THE ALTAR OF ADVERTISING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The green-and-white tags, secured to the towering Giving Tree
with pieces of red yarn, gently fluttered like scores of butterfly
wings in the indoor breeze made as mall shoppers hurriedly passed
by.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens upon dozens of tags hung there, each with a mini-profile
of a boy or girl who hoped that strangers would find it in their
hearts to supply a little bit of Christmas for children who might
otherwise not have any.
</P>
<P>
   Perusing the tags provided an instant snapshot of the
consumerization of Christmas and the corporatization of America's
youth _ an alphabet soup of desire.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with the generic requests for TVs, CDs and VCRs
were appeals for the retail icons of the late 1990s. Gameboy.
Discman. Nintendo. PlayStation. Nike. Air Jordan. Tommy. DKNY.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing masterminds must be as gleeful as Scrooge on the
morning after the Ghost of Christmas Future visited to know their
efforts are paying off.
</P>
<P>
   America's youth are worshipping at the altar of advertising
hype, bolstered by the ``synergy'' between companies and spin-off
products that puts a Pokemon in your face at the movie theater, on
TV, and in toy stores, fast-food restaurants _ even the check-out
line at the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper cannot escape culpability here. A quick scan of
the Tuesday Family Day! section revealed a PokeWatch column for the
``gotta-buy-it-all'' shopper. How adolescent or adult can get
jazzed by that insipid yellow pillow of a monster named Pikachu and
his less-than-inspired friends is beyond me. But then, I didn't get
the whole Beanie Baby thing, either.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only a bahhing humbug would begrudge the youngsters whose
names adorned the fluttering green-and-white tags for wanting the
same things as children whose parents are more than eager and
financially able to indulge such wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the repetitive petitions for electronic gadgets and color
TVs and apparel labeled with the names of anorexic designers or
obscenely paid professional athletes were enough to make your head
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Christmas, a time to celebrate the birth of the one who
came to save us all from our sins, perhaps it is too much to expect
requests for a crucifix or a Bible to mingle with the CD games and
high-dollar running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happened to kids who just wanted a bike, or a doll,
or a sweater?
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw it. The tag that simply bore the name ``Christine''
and her clothing sizes. No special requests. No demands for
electronic gizmos or brand-name merchandise. Just small sizes _ can
anyone really have size 2 1/2 feet? _ and a statement of fact:
Favorite color is purple.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm reading too much into it, looking for meaning when
perhaps the child just couldn't make up her mind, but what was
unwritten on that green-and-white tag secured by a piece of red
yarn to a giant artificial tree summoned like the angels who
announced His birth: I will be grateful for whatever you can give.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite color is purple, the color of kings.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is a feminine derivative of Christ, the King of Kings.
</P>
<P>
   And she asked for nothing beyond whatever someone felt moved to
give.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for her made my Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
