<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-GALAXY-SPI &LR;      12-23 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GALAXY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GALAXY QUEST' GOES FORTH AND PROSPERS BY MOCKING SCI-FI TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' doesn't exactly go boldly where no man has gone
before, but it does contain several formidable laughs and some
silly spoofing of ``Star Trek'' and the die-hard contingent of fans
who refuse to let the show rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Most sci-fi spoofs _ think Mel Brooks' 1987 debacle
``Spaceballs'' _ that have tried to do parodies of the ``Star
Wars'' or ``Star Trek'' phenomena have fallen flat on their
interstellar faces.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of making fun of the series' fans and their
lifestyle, ``Galaxy Quest'' targets actors and how an onscreen
image can forever lock a performer in a particular role. And that
proves to be its saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   The movie almost pays tribute to the people who slavishly
worship the genre and it pokes fun with mostly good-hearted, if
goofy, affection.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen plays Jason Nesmith, who starred as Commander Peter
Quincy Taggert, the popular, self-absorbed leader of the Galaxy
Quest crew. Nesmith makes his living signing autographs at sci-fi
conventions around the country and he revels in the adoration of
the show's followers, who refuse to think of him as anything other
than Commander Taggert.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the crew is not so happy with the way life has
turned out after their long run on television.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen DeMarco (Sigourney Weaver) is forever hounded by blond
girls in revealing uniforms who want to be just like her ``Galaxy
Quest'' character, Lt. Tawny Madison. Shakespearean actor Alexander
Dane (Alan Rickman) played ``Richard III'' on the London stage but
he's doomed to a seedy life repeating the role of the
half-humanoid, half-reptilian Dr. Lazarus from the planet Tev'Meck
at Burbank shopping mall appearances.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Fred Kwan (Tony Shalhoub), the TV show's Tech Sgt.
Chen; Tommy Webber (Daryl Mitchell), who was only a kid when he
played the ship's expert navigator, Lt. Laredo; and Guy Fleegman
(Sam Rockwell), whose one-episode character was instantly killed
off.
</P>
<P>
   The bickering bunch is pulled back into action by a dying race
of aliens who think the show was for real and need the cast's help
in a battle with their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the stellar cast _ Rickman, Shalhoub and Rockwell are
terrific _ the film has a streak of offbeat, dark humor that
propels the one-note joke at the core of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Director Dean Parisot, who has directed TV movies and shows
prior to his feature film debut with ``Home Fries,'' is familiar
with the small-screen format and its quirks. He humorously captures
the cheesiness of the sets and the idiosyncrasies that are part of
TV science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy Quest. Directed by Dean Parisot. Written by David Howard,
Robert Gordon. Cast: Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver, Alan Rickman,
Tony Shalhoub, Sam Rockwell. DreamWorks Pictures. 102 minutes.
Rated PG for mild violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1509EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PIG-PARABLE-BOS &LR;      12-23 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIG-PARABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LITTLE PIGGY ... WENT TO HARVARD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some readers are charmed. Others rev up a mild huff. Most,
though, are just puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet's latest work tells the story of a self-educated and
persistent pig named Henrietta who, after being rejected from a
certain esteemed law school in Cambridge, Mass., ultimately gains
entry, becomes valedictorian, goes on to the Supreme Court, and
speaks loftily about social justice and the disenfranchised
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Like one of Franz Kafka's parables, Mamet's ``Henrietta'' seems
to be a simple children's tale about defeating the odds. But the
31-page illustrated book is being snapped up in Cambridge book
stores and has provoked speculation at Harvard Law School about the
playwright and filmmaker, and about the author's deeper meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Some see the tale of the Shakespeare-savvy swine as a thinly
veiled jab at elitism. Others view the book as an attack on what
they perceive as Harvard's legacy of discriminating against
minorities. And some believe it's just a story about making it on
your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an anti-elitism lesson for kids,'' said Alan
Dershowitz, the outspoken Harvard Law School professor who added a
blurb on the jacket praising the fable's ``truth.'' ``No matter
what you are, no matter what people perceive you as, you can make
it to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hulings, a 24-year-old law student, gleaned a different
meaning: ``The moral to me is that finding value in what other
people hold in esteem is ultimately a shallow endeavor,'' referring
to the pig's lack of success before Harvard was affixed to her
resume.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the book's illustrator knows Mamet's meaning. Elizabeth
Dahlie, a Wellesley artist who jazzed up Henrietta with a red
ribbon on her squiggle of a tail, glasses perched low on the sow's
snout, and a crimson-striped muffler to help her brave the cold,
said: ``Really, I'm not sure. I just drew the pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamet did not clear up the confusion. He declined an interview
through his agent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But if the book is chiding Harvard Law School for the period in
its history when it excluded almost everyone except white males,
officials at the nation's oldest law school are quick to come to
its defense.
</P>
<P>
   About 47 percent of the students in the class that entered this
fall are women and more than 25 percent are minorities, said Mike
Chmura, a Harvard spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for people who provide some difference, who have made
good use of their opportunities, who have overcome disadvantage _
just like Henrietta,'' said Joyce Curll, the law school's
admissions director. ``We have probably the most diverse law
school. If Mr. Mamet really looked around at this institution, he
would see that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the student population has grown more diverse in the past
decade, the law school's faculty has been slow to change. Of 79
professors, only 13 are women and eight are minorities, Chmura
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet, known for his black-humor plays including the Pulitzer
Prize-winning ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' and provocative movies such
as ``Wag the Dog'' and ``The Spanish Prisoner,'' named his heroine
after a pig once owned by his friend, the wealthy Boston developer
and presidential host on Martha's Vineyard, Dick Friedman. The
developer named the restaurant in his Charles Hotel in Cambridge
Henrietta's Table, after his departed sow.
</P>
<P>
   And while Mamet never comes out and calls the ``Great
University'' by name, illustrations clearly depict Cambridge's
Charles Square and the Weeks Memorial Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts with the learned pig leaving her solitude and
studies on some ``Eastern Isle'' to follow her dream of addressing
juries. ``Having seen the barriers to the Professions crumble
before now this and that disadvantaged group,'' Mamet writes, ``she
presented herself at the institution of her choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But without credentials or an undergraduate degree, the law
school rejects her. Later, after ``she haunted the libraries and
folded herself into the backs of the lecture halls,'' the school
banned her. Dahlie, the illustrator, paints a sign hanging from a
door: ``No pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   After living like a bum in the streets of Cambridge, things
change for the better for Henrietta. She meets the ``Old
Vagabond,'' who turns out to be the Great University's president.
But the president misplaces his glasses and doesn't realize she's a
pig. He's so impressed with her knowledge of Hamlet, Oedipus, and
Henry Fielding, that, even after he discovers she's a pig, he
invites her to attend the law school.
</P>
<P>
   Henrietta marches onward from there. And so have sales of
Mamet's book.
</P>
<P>
   But while many may be reading it, they are often left shrugging
quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning over his thick textbooks and cramming for his final at
the Harvard Law School's imposing library earlier this week, a
25-year-old law student shook his head after reading ``Henrietta''
several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's driving at something,'' Jake Erhard said. ``But
I'm not quite sure what it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      12-23 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 CHRYSLER LHS: BIG, STYLISH AND POWERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to pay for the gas (it's getting expensive if you
haven't noticed), but opinions are still dispensed for free at
Irving's Service Center in Stoneham.
</P>
<P>
   For example, we'll take today's subject: a 2000 Chrysler LHS.
</P>
<P>
   I pull up to the pumps and walk inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's a nice-looking car,'' says Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's the sound system?'' asks son Matt, looking up from the
study guide for his upcoming test on the new auto inspection
equipment. ``I hear it's really something special.''
</P>
<P>
   I flip Matt the key and watch him crank up the windows and sound
on the four-disc, in-dash CD changer that's part of a 360-watt
system with Infinity speakers in nine locations. As I walk out to
finish gassing up, the smile on his face tells all as he leans back
in the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got it right,'' he says as he relinquishes the car in
exchange for gas money.
</P>
<P>
   That applies to more than the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   This is the big car your father always wanted to drive, except
it's only been built for the last two years. And it is right.
</P>
<P>
   It's also big. And stylish. And comfortable. And powerful. And
luxurious. And built in America.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, and it's fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   And for you, the son or daughter? All of the above holds true,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The LHS, a sibling of Chrysler's performance-oriented 300M, has
plenty of strong selling points of its own. Under the hood, they
share the same 3.5-liter, 24-valve V6 that puts out 253 horsepower,
enough to get an LHS from 0-60 in 7.7 seconds with good economy (18
m.p.g. city and 27 highway).
</P>
<P>
   The LHS is a little longer than the 300M, offers a softer (but
not spongy) ride, has more interior and trunk space and comes at a
decent price: $28,090 (ours added the CD changer at $515 and
17-inch chrome wheels at $750).
</P>
<P>
   The styling _ as it is across the Chrysler line _ is stunning,
and the reliability in these big cars is encouraging. The black
(heated) mirrors and a black trim strip between the hood and
windshield offset the bright silver of our test car. The LHS shares
the retro-look, airplane-styled dash instrumentation of the 300M,
including an analog clock (we won't argue with Chrysler's claim
that the cluster is reminiscent of Swiss-made watches).
</P>
<P>
   On the road, a trip with four aboard to Worcester saw the LHS
cruise easily at 80 and hold the road just fine. In town, where the
Central Artery is a tougher test, a late-night drive home on a
rainy night saw the suspension hop through the ruts a bit but
perform nicely overall.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't cold enough that week for the wet roads to turn to
black ice that would test the traction control, but, returning home
from the Globe in the wee hours one Sunday night, I got to give the
four-wheel disc brakes and antilock braking system a real-life
test.
</P>
<P>
   As I came onto the Expressway North at Columbia Road, an Acura
and Honda raced past, door handle to door handle in excess of 90
mph, rapidly disappearing from sight. A mile or so down the road,
they came a cropper in the South Station Tunnel, leaving a trail of
metal, plastic, glass and vital (automotive) fluids all over the
road with one car against each wall. The young lady driving the
Honda already had crossed over and was ``communicating'' with the
Acura driver who seemed OK but was unable to open the well-battered
driver's side door.
</P>
<P>
   The LHS made a quick, straight, pedal-pulsating stop, then
gingerly followed an 18-wheeler through the mess. A call to 911
went unanswered, leaving the conclusion that the trucker already
had officialdom on the phone. Ten minutes later, WBZ's traffic
report relayed news of a multicar crash in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the LHS seemed removed from the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends who came along during the week commented
favorably on the ride, the styling and the roominess of the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The leather seats were comfortable and heated. Heated seats
always sounded like a ``Who needs 'em?'' amenity _ until I tried
them. They're one of life's welcome luxuries, and just this week I
heard of a driver who uses his all year to ease a chronically
aching back.
</P>
<P>
   The obligatory cupholder report: Hit a bar on the front of the
center armrest and a double cupholder pops out. It was fine for our
various test beverages: a medium cardboard coffee cup, a soda can,
and an insulated travel mug, keeping them safely within reach and
out of the way of all controls.
</P>
<P>
   The equally-obligatory owner's manual report: You'll need to
read it to fully understand the many features of the
climate-control and audio-CD systems. Only a true gadget-person
will figure them out completely without help.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --Power, styling, spaciousness, combination of ride and
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --No easy place to put a turnpike toll ticket (the CD changer
took care of any in-dash cubbyhole spaces).
</P>
<P>
   --It took time to get the seat/mirror adjustments just right.
And rearview mirror visibility was somewhat limited.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
