<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-BICENTENNIAL-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CAPITOL TO CELEBRATE ITS BICENTENNIAL  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JUDY HOLLAND   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Congress first moved into the new Capitol on
the Potomac nearly 200 years ago, lawmakers viewed the classical
white marble building in the wilderness as a symbol of balance,
stability and harmony for the rapidly growing nation.
</P>
<P>
   They never envisioned that the British would stack Library of
Congress books on members' desks in 1814, sprinkle them with gun
powder and set the House and Senate wings ablaze until only the
walls were left standing.
</P>
<P>
   They never expected the Capitol would become a barracks for the
first Union troops at the start of the Civil War in 1861 and that
the famous 19th century poet Walt Whitman would nurse wounded
soldiers in the Rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   And no one imagined these halls would become the scene of a
murder in 1889, when Louisville Times reporter Charles E. Kincaid
fatally shot former Congressman William Preston, a Kentucky
Democrat, who had threatened him for writing an unfavorable story.
</P>
<P>
   To capture these historical jewels and others, the U.S. Capitol
Historical Society is celebrating the Capitol's 200th anniversary
by sponsoring a traveling exhibit of the history, art and
architecture of the building. The exhibit will visit the capitals
of all 50 states starting next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to take the Capitol to the public,'' says
Clarence J. Brown, a former Republican congressman from Ohio and
retiring president of the historical group. ``We are not educated
today in the civic history of our country as well as we should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the bicentennial, the society will sell a replica of the
gavel that George Washington used to lay the cornerstone of the
Capitol in a Masonic ceremony in 1793.
</P>
<P>
   Despite long-standing efforts to identify the cornerstone,
historians remain divided over exactly where it is located in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask anyone in the Capitol where the cornerstone is and you
get a fight,'' says Brown. Brown says he believes the cornerstone
was accidentally carried out of the Capitol when the East Front was
expanded in 1959. He suggests that the silver plate it was laid
upon has disintegrated over time.
</P>
<P>
   But George M. White, architect of the Capitol from 1971 to 1995,
scoffs at Brown's theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind'' that the cornerstone lies in
the corridor of the East Front of the Capitol, near a carryout
cafeteria, White says. A stone at that site is unusually large and
matches descriptions in early newspaper accounts, he notes.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wolanin, the curator of the Capitol, says the federal
building deserves more study as ``the symbol of democracy both in
our country and in the entire world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people understand about the history of the art and
the building itself, the more they'll get out of the experience of
being in the building,'' Wolanin says. ``Hopefully more people will
want to understand it and to take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit will explain how the states decided which of their
famous residents would be portrayed in the Capitol's Statuary Hall.
Two statues of people prominent in the state's history represent
each state.
</P>
<P>
   One panel of the exhibit will show how the Capitol's classical
Greek and Roman architecture is reflected in state capitals across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The display will explain that the Capitol's classical lines were
intended to symbolize that America's political system was designed
like the democratic republics in Greece and Rome, instead of like
the British monarchy that the settlers had left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The group is also extending its reach into cyberspace next
spring by launching The Web Site of the History of Congress, a
guide that eventually will include biographies of more than 12,000
federal lawmakers who have served since the First Continental
Congress in 1774.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are also underway for educational forums for high school
students, which are ``intended to bring kids into contact with
people who are public servants and inspire them to want to become
active in their communities,'' says Matt Wasniewski, the society's
associate historian.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail:
Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
