r a BC-CALIF-GOVERNOR-Y2K-HN     12-23 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOVERNOR-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR EXPECTS SOME PROBLEMS WITH DATE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The state command center is ready. The
National Guard is prepared. High-tech telecommunication devices are
being installed in Gov. Grady Davis' Los Angeles condominium and
downtown office. His staff is working overtime. Yet the
always-cautious governor still expects problems next week related
to the millennium date change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure something will go wrong,'' Davis said Wednesday,
sounding a little like Eeyore, the gloomy donkey from ``Winnie the
Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some streetlights won't work, some ATM machines won't
work, but we can live with these things,'' he said. ``As long as
the prison doors don't open and the water projects don't stop
functioning and the major systems keep functioning, we'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he would attend three parties in Los Angeles on New
Year's Eve, then ``probably be home by 12:20 to check in with the
Office of Emergency Services,'' which has set up an elaborate state
command center at its headquarters outside Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Y2K team is convinced absolutely nothing will go wrong.
Having lived almost 57 years, I am sure something will go wrong,''
Davis said again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have a host of contingency plans in the ready,'' the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Information Technology says 100 percent
of California's essential computer systems are prepared for the
date change. The state has spent about $100 million making sure its
computers will work.
</P>
<P>
   Because earlier software and some models of computers were
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year _ the
``99'' in 1999, for example _ computer experts say it is possible
that equipment that has not been updated may think 2000 is 1900.
That could result, these experts theorize, in breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   If there are widespread problems, the governor has the power to
call out the 22,000-member Army and Air National Guard and declare
states of emergency. About 1,700 National Guard soldiers will be
training New Year's weekend. The training exercises will allow the
Guard to deploy troops on a few hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   All state activities will be coordinated through the Office of
Emergency Services in suburban Sacramento. Three other regional
offices _ in Oakland, Southern California and Sacramento _ will
filter information to the command center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that the computer systems are reliable; those seem to
be OK,'' said Tom Mullins, a spokesman for the Office of Emergency
Services.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Emergency Services has prepared a Y2K booklet in
eight languages, available on the agency's Web site,
www.oes.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet advises people to store one gallon of water for each
family member for each day. Residents should have enough
non-perishable food to last each person three to seven days, it
says, and keep extra supplies of medication, a first aid kit and
critical medical records. Have some extra cash on hand and keep
your gas tank at least half-full, the Office of Emergency Services
also advises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1533EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
