<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-PANTHERS-CARRUTH-     12-23 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PANTHERS-CARRUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T FORGET THE VICTIMS IN THE CARRUTH CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The body of Cherica Adams was honored and buried
in Charlotte, N.C., Saturday. Let's hope her memory won't fade any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Misfortune has struck the Southeast. A young woman is dead. Her
infant son entered the world three months before his time. An NFL
player stands charged with a crime so heinous that death may be the
consequence of his alleged actions.
</P>
<P>
   But as we begin to sort through the details of how former
Carolina Panthers wide receiver Rae Carruth wound up facing a
first-degree murder charge for conspiring to kill Adams, his
girlfriend and supposedly the mother of his recently born son
Chancellor Lee Adams, let's be sure to not become so consumed with
Carruth that Cherica and Chancellor become bit players in his
plight.
</P>
<P>
   If Carruth is indeed a victim himself, the courts will determine
that. But Adams and her child are the most significant victims now
and we can't ignore the possibility that as this story builds
steam, it may become more about Carruth and less about them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a scary topic already, both for the sketchy details
already supplied and the interest it has generated. True, Carruth
isn't O.J. Simpson and Adams isn't Nicole Brown Simpson. We're
talking about a subpar receiver (who was recently waived by
Carolina) and his unknown girlfriend he dated for more than year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even without the Juice's juice, this crime should appall and
not bore us. An NFL player stands accused of murder and if he is
found guilty, he will almost certainly face the death penalty. When
was the last time that happened?
</P>
<P>
   We live in a sports culture where Lawrence Phillips' return to
the NFL generates ethical debates, where Latrell Sprewell chokes
his former head coach and winds up telling his story on ``60
Minutes.'' Now we have a pregnant woman slain as she sat in her
car, and the level of outrage just doesn't fit the crime. This is
why we should worry about Adams and Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If their story doesn't appeal to us much now, it's unlikely that
it will in the midst of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The overall coverage of this incident already has been sparse.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks have passed between the time of Adams' shooting and
her funeral in Charlotte, and few details about either the victim,
the crime or the alleged perpetrators have leaked out of North
Carolina. This much we do know:
</P>
<P>
   That the 24-year-old Adams and Carruth, who is 25, had dated for
about a year; that on the night of Nov. 16, she was sitting in her
black BMW when someone opened fire on her, hitting her four times
in the neck and abdomen; that Chancellor Lee was delivered by
Caesarean section and is believed to be the son of Carruth; that
Carruth had already fathered another child and had financial
problems; and finally, that after the police arrested three other
men along with Carruth, two fingered Carruth as the chief
conspirator and within days of Adams' death, Carruth stashed
himself in the back of a friend's Toyota and fled to Tennessee,
where the police eventually caught him.
</P>
<P>
   Within the media, that should be enough to open some eyes and
turn a few heads. But there is a feeling that we've been down this
road, with the Simpsons most notably. Their drama clearly had
theatrical appeal long before it swelled out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Most people had opinions, theories and agendas concerning the
subject, and as a result that story probably jaded the response to
a situation like that of Carruth and Adams. Or is there more to
this than that?
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, that Adams was an exotic dancer when she met
Carruth was unearthed along with information of a relationship she
had with former Charlotte Hornet and current New York Knick Larry
Johnson. Though these elements of the story shouldn't be viewed
suspiciously, they do make Adams more real to those who didn't know
her, which also means that people are starting to take time to
discover who she was.
</P>
<P>
   One concern here is that she will wind up portrayed as just
another woman about to bear a child to a wealthy athlete, that
because she performed lap dances for a living, she didn't merit the
kind of sympathy or outrage generated by the death of a Nicole
Simpson. Even worse would be to overlook the long-term effects on
Chancellor, who was born fighting for his own life, and both the
Adams and Carruth families.
</P>
<P>
   The boy faces a world of potential custody battles and his
mother will only come alive through the memories of others.
</P>
<P>
   The Adams family is just learning about an existence without
their daughter, and the Carruths may have to do the same if their
son is found guilty and receives the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the predictable story will be how Carruth declined
from a first-round pick into a murder suspect. He is about to start
fighting for his freedom. But once this legal process starts
rolling, let's pay special attention to the woman who died too
young and a child whose innocence was robbed at birth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1537EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
