<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7715 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-BOOKS-HNS &LR;      12-23 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT-SO-PERFECT BOOKS OFFER GOOD CAREER LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I get dozens of career books each year. A handful are so
wonderful that I write about them right away; most of the rest get
discarded in a hurry. But there is a third group: Some books are
intriguing enough to be useful to some people, but have one flaw or
another that keeps me from wholeheartedly recommending them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they are too good to ignore. Some could be perfect gifts,
if you know someone who fits into a particular book's niche
audience. Here are four such books, ones I was able to put down,
but couldn't throw away:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Who Moved My Cheese?'' by Spencer Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   If this book would just come out in paperback for $9.95 or so, I
would recommend it without hesitation. But it is only the size of a
long magazine article and sells for $19.95, which would buy a heck
of a lot of Gorgonzola.
</P>
<P>
   The main part of the book is a parable about four mice who live
in a maze and survive by eating cheese. One day the cheese
disappears from its usual place, confounding a couple of the mice.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, co-author of ``The One Minute Manager,'' uses the
parable to illustrate how difficult it can be to deal with change,
and what people need to do not only to survive, but to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   The people who struggle most in their careers these days are
those uncomfortable with change. They had a job that was at least
reasonable, then the company merged or they got laid off or their
duties changed dramatically. They dwell on what used to be rather
than moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's book can help them. It also can be useful when life
gives you a nasty twist, like a serious illness or divorce or the
death of a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Clarity Quest,'' by Pamela Ammondson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most valuable things you can do in your career is
take a sabbatical, giving yourself some time to think about how
things are going and whether you need to go in a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   But many jobs don't let you take a break, and some workers can't
afford any unpaid time off because they live from paycheck to
paycheck. Ammondson's book tries to help, describing how you can
take a sabbatical of sorts while using up only one week of vacation
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarity Quest'' outlines an eight-week process, but only the
eighth week involves taking time off from work. During the first
seven weeks, Ammondson guides you through various exercises
designed to help you relax and focus on the things that really
matter in your life.
</P>
<P>
   The book is too touchy-feely for my tastes, and I think a lot of
people could achieve the same results on their own, if they just
took the time to focus on their careers and their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But many people simply don't know how to begin. Even if they
take a sabbatical, the only insight they will gain is from watching
``Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   If you know something needs to change in your career or your
life and you are not sure how to approach it, ``Clarity Quest''
could help.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Power of Positive Criticism,'' by Hendrie Weisinger.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the advice in this book ought to be superfluous;
managers with a few street smarts ought to know how to criticize
employees constructively, and rank-and-filers ought to appreciate
the need for criticism to help the company function better.
</P>
<P>
   But often they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Weisinger's book offers insights into why criticism is valuable
and how it is often abused. He explains how bosses need to use
careful timing and just the right words to correct employees
without making them feel hurt or bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-filers can benefit from the book as well. The book
explains how to handle touchy situations, such as criticizing your
boss or dealing with co-workers who are constantly negative.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The 75 Greatest Management Decisions Ever Made ... and 21 of
the worst,'' by Stuart Crainer.
</P>
<P>
   There are some classic lessons in here, such as Henry Ford's
innovations in automobile manufacturing, and how Walt Disney
listened to his wife, Lillian. He wanted to call his cartoon
character Mortimer Mouse, but she thought that was a Mickey Mouse
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 bad decisions are also useful, particularly because some
of them were made by people like Ford (who decided to build
submarines during World War I) and some of the leaders of Silicon
Valley. Even brilliant people can screw up royally.
</P>
<P>
   The book's biggest flaw is that it is overly ambitious. Having
75 decisions makes it seem too much like a laundry list rather than
offering much insight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Crainer's book could be a good reference for a lot of
managers, and a reminder of how fine the line can be between
brilliance and stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
