<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7716 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOTHER-HN     12-23 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOTHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DIRECTOR EXAMINES THE NATURE OF FACADES IN `MOTHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until ``All About My Mother,'' there were two faces to Pedro
Almodovar. The angular, style-is-substance one and the downy-soft
one that feels increasingly touched by an angel.
</P>
<P>
   (It should be noted that even the angels in an Almodovar film
wear leopard-print miniskirts and Gucci shades.)
</P>
<P>
   But since ``The Flower of My Secret'' in 1996, and most
alarmingly with ``Live Flesh'' in 1997, he's been experimenting
with a formalism that felt conventional, like someone was standing
over him saying, ``Oh, behave!''
</P>
<P>
   How does a man ostensibly fed up with being the Agnes (``All My
Children'') Nixon of Spanish cinema satisfy fuddy-duddy critics who
have derided him for his lack of maturity and emotional sincerity?
He gets introspective and makes a movie about sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   For Almodovar, looking inward is unusual therapy that is as much
to do with his artistic loves as his deepest self. Soul
searchingly, he's dedicated ``All About My Mother'' to ``all
actresses who have played actresses, to men who act and become
women, to all the people who want to be mothers.'' It's a
romantically labyrinthine tribute that piles layers of intertextual
shout-outs to ``All About Eve,'' Tennessee Williams, Truman Capote
and Alfred Hitchcock, and beautifully assesses the nature of
facades. Once you peel away the performance, what is left is the
emotion it masks.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerity was not something Almodovar's films needed  &Cx1f; _ there is
no more sincere and smitten a socio-sexual gamesman.
</P>
<P>
   His mothers were never just mommies, they were Madonnas of the
highest, most glamorously neurotic order. To see him flirting with
conventions like the flaccid noir in ``Live Flesh'' was upsetting
because you could see him struggling to ``grow up'' by trying to
keep a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``All About My Mother,'' Almodovar imbues his
Harlequin-novel-meets-Marvel-comic-book melodramas with something
more than a wink and a smile, and it's beguiling.
</P>
<P>
   His expressionism and his screenwriting have always had fun
together, but now there is a kind of faith and spirituality that
sexcapades like ``Laws of Desire'' and ``Kika'' only laughed at.
</P>
<P>
   The film is about Manuela (Cecilia Roth), a Madrid nurse
dedicated to her teen-age son Esteban (Eloy Alzorin), who is
writing a story about her. Her birthday presents to him are
perfectly thematic _ Capote's ``Music for Chameleons'' and a
production of ``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' In a shatteringly shot
and performed sequence, Esteban is killed chasing Huma Rojo (Marisa
Parades), the show's Blanche du Bois, in her limo one rainy night.
If there is a difference between the Almodovar of old and the one
working here, it has been the replacement of irony with a more
astral, less literary idea of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Before, with Almodovar, a sudden tragedy like Esteban's death
would have weakened Manuela, depraved her. But here and in Roth's
delicate hands, Manuela is an emblem of sacrifice, nearly crippled
by grief.
</P>
<P>
   She sets out to fulfill her son's birthday wish: to know his
father. As Manuela heads to Barcelona to find Esteban's father,
``All About My Mother'' unfurls into a journey film, the breadth of
which makes for Almodovar's most profound writing. Where he was
once an iconographer and cartographer of a woman's identity, he has
now forsaken sex, per se, for gender, eroticism for sensuality.
While other aging directors (Almodovar is only 48) from Scorsese
(``Bringing Out the Dead'') to Lynch (``The Straight Story'') are
looking for humanism, Almodovar is merely plumbing the depths of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Every soul Manuela encounters in Barcelona _ from Huma and her
co-star (and lover) Nina (Candela Pena) to the philosophically
narcissistic transsexual Agrado (Antonia San Juan) and the
pregnant, AIDS-struck nun (Penelope Cruz) _ is cosmically,
symbiotically stitched into her quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All About My Mother'' is Almodovar's 14th feature, but it
contains a host of superlative firsts: a handful of the only truly
moving scenes he has filmed, the most gorgeous dialogue he has
composed, his most dimensional performances of his most dimensional
characters and perhaps his most dynamic photography and elaborate
production design.
</P>
<P>
   That haunting super-size billboard of Huma's face that Manuela
stands in front of at one point is like a live, humanized
Lichtenstein painting. It is the type of alluring pop scenery
Almodovar has always used to beautify his melodramatic operas, only
now the soap has been left at home beside the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
