r l BC-KIDS-SLEEPING-NORVILL     12-23 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-SLEEPING-NORVILLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBORAH NORVILLE SAYS NO TV BEFORE BED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sunday, Dec. 26) 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids watching a little too much TV? Are you concerned that
images of bad guys in video games just before bedtime make for a
restless night? Snuggle up together with ``I Don't Want to Sleep
Tonight,'' a new children's book about the perils of television
viewing written by Deborah Norville.
</P>
<P>
   That's Deborah Norville, an Emmy-winning reporter who anchors
the TV magazine ``Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   She's well aware of the irony in someone who has made a career
in broadcasting telling children and their parents that there
sometimes are better things to do than be a couch potato.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who better to say turn off the tube?'' Norville said. ``I've
been very blessed to work on TV and, Lord willing, I'll continue to
do so. But I don't think there's anybody who works on `Inside
Edition' that thinks kids should watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the rhyming, lift-the-flap book (Golden Books;
$12.99) came from Norville's experience with her 8-year-old son
Niki, big brother to Kyle, 5, and daughter Mikiela, 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote this as a poem for my little boy who tended to watch
more TV and play more video games than he should, and those tended
to be the same nights when he had what we call the `scaries,' those
middle-of-the-night, calling-for-help (nightmares).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell a child something and it goes right past them,
but if they make the discovery themselves there's a greater chance
that it's going to stick. So I thought, `How can I help him make
that connection?' and I thought of making up a rhyme.''
</P>
<P>
   Norville is in the habit of composing little bits of poetry for
her children for different occasions, so her message flowed easily
in that form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The verse that came to me was,' ... and one thing I have
noticed about these visits from these creatures, they only come on
nights when I've seen some TV features,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So using that as the center point, I worked my way back to the
annoying monsters that were bugging you when you were trying to
sleep, and then going forward to dreamland, which is a really cool
and wonderful place if you hadn't been glued to the tube before you
tried to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Norville and her husband, Karl Wellner, have set limits on
their children's TV watching and video game time: No TV or video
games Mondays through Thursdays, and none Friday until after
school. During the weekends, they are allowed to watch television,
but Norville and Wellner try to steer them away from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become much more proactive about offering alternatives
to television,'' she said. ``If it's a Saturday and our son says,
`Hey, Mom, can I go play Nintendo,' we don't say, `No,' flat out.
What we try to do instead is say, `Yeah, but you know what, we've
got that new football, and you asked me the other day to go play
football and now would be a great time.' We try to offer
alternatives. Often if you get engaged in another activity with
your children, they forget they wanted to play Nintendo or watch
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times they're making that choice out of boredom _
`There's nothing else that seems intriguing so I'll watch TV or
I'll play video games.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Norville said she recently learned that Golden Books wants her
to do a series of books along the same lines, possibly illustrated
by Rachael O'Neill, who did the vivid crayonlike drawings in ``I
Don't Want to Sleep Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Norville said if the book does become a series, the next entry
might be based on a poem she wrote for Niki when he was dealing
with a bully: ``Today I feel sick. I will not go to school/My
stomach feels wiggly, my hands clammy and cool./I squeezed shut my
eyes, tried hard to sleep./I saw nothing but visions of Ricky the
creep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a dream I've had, but it's been one of the most
fulfilling professional experiences I've ever had,'' Norville said
of her first children's book, now in its second printing just six
weeks after hitting the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the book is television is a great thing and it
can open horizons, but great things should be enjoyed in moderation
and there are just wonderful worlds that can be opened in a
book.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
