<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7718 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-STONE-FEATURE-LA     12-23 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STONE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER STONE TACKLES FOOTBALL IN `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sunday, Dec. 26) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, word was out that Oliver Stone was going to make
a football movie. The National Football League did not consider
this to be good news. Stone would show up at games, and league
officials would warily watch him out of the corners of their eyes,
trying to see just what the maverick filmmaker was up to, in the
same way, say, a dog peers at his owner who has a bottle of shampoo
and garden hose in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you blame them?'' asks Dennis Quaid, who plays an aging
quarterback in Stone's movie, ``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is a corporation, just like Disney, and corporations
like that have a thing about their image. And if you have a loose
cannon like Oliver roaming around, you'd have every right to be a
little concerned about what he's going to do to that image.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a whole lot, it turns out. Sure, ``Any Given Sunday'' is
filled with drugs, prostitutes and violence _ the staples of an
Oliver Stone movie _ but in the end, the film plays almost as a
loving homage to football, a sport Stone calls both a ``pagan
rite'' and ``the religion of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's America's version of the gladiator games of Rome, taking
place on Sunday, the day people used to go to church,'' Stone says.
``It's ritualized violence. But it's allowable. It's legal _
unlike, say, marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Stone's pointed way of pooh-poohing (and perhaps calling
your attention to) his recent arrest for hashish possession, his
second such offense. At 53, Stone may be a little old to be playing
the rebel, particularly for someone who has made so much money
making commercial films for Hollywood studios. But he still likes
to provoke _ both with his movies and his personality _ even if he
has moved away (although not by choice) from chronicling his own
fevered version of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect Oliver to be out there on the edge,'' Quaid
says. ``They not only expect it, but they seem to like it. It's
like, `Oh, look what he's doing now.' I find people's reaction to
him a curious mix of envy and disdain.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's reaction to Stone's script, not surprisingly, was one
of outright dismissal. Stone was thus compelled to create a
fictional football league (the Association of Football Franchises
of America), complete with made-up teams (the Miami Sharks are the
featured franchise), uniforms, logos and a championship game for
the ``Pantheon Cup.'' (The name is another nod to the
football-as-gladiators concept, as is the footage from ``Ben-Hur''
that Stone inserts into the film during one of the coach's big
speeches.)
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' coach, Tony D'Amato, is, appropriately enough,
played by Al Pacino, no stranger to screaming or vein-bulging
speech-making. Tony is a for-love-of-the-game guy, disconcerted by
the way corporate money has transformed football into a business
instead of a sport. Quaid plays the old-school quarterback; TV's
Jamie Foxx is the up-and-comer who spends more time making
commercials than studying the playbook. And that's OK with the
team's owner (Cameron Diaz!), who has a pragmatic, market-oriented
approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday'' also features a host of football players, past and
present, including Hall of Famers Lawrence Taylor and Jim Brown in
featured roles, and five other legends (Y.A. Tittle, Dick Butkus,
Bob Sinclair, Warren Moon and Johnny Unitas) in cameos as coaches.
Former Dallas Cowboys coach Barry Switzer also shows up, playing a
sportscaster paired with Stone himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's movie doesn't exactly call any audibles in its depiction
of the win-at-all-costs mentality prevalent in professional
football. ``North Dallas Forty'' got there 20 years before, and did
a much better job in showing the various abuses football players
must endure for the team. Where ``Sunday'' breaks new ground is in
portraying the ways the sport has become less a game than a weekly
pageant run by and for large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football today is all about the spectacle and the show,'' says
Brown, the former Cleveland Browns star, generally considered to be
the greatest running back who ever played. ``Now, there's nothing
wrong with the hoopla and the dancers. It makes for a good show.
But it doesn't make for a good sport. Everything today is motivated
by money. Owners want it; players want it. It dilutes the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this being an Oliver Stone movie, the purity of the
game ultimately becomes secondary to the bone-rattling violence
(``in six-track Dolby stereo!'' Stone enthuses) and the indelicate
extracurricular activities. (``Tell me something,'' Stone asks.
``Have you seen more beautiful women in a movie per cubic feet?
Have you? I love women!'')
</P>
<P>
   These twin obsessions often had a way of turning the ``Sunday''
set into a giant locker room, a place where, Quaid says, ``chaos
reigned supreme'' and ``your manhood was challenged on almost a
daily basis.'' Actors learned to be football players; football
players learned to be actors. The football players had an easier
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of a lot of days, I needed a Tylenol IV,'' says
Foxx, who played quarterback in high school. ``The problem was that
you'd get hit and there would be something wrong with the camera
angle, so they'd have to film it again ... and again ... and again.
They gave me the option of using a stunt double, but in the same
breath they told me I'd be a pansy if I did so. You heard the
`pansy' word a lot during those football scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor, who played linebacker for 13 years with the New York
Giants, hitting people didn't pose much of a problem. Remaining
patient did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I don't mind contact,'' Taylor, now 40, says. ``But
in a movie, you've got to do the same thing so many times that it
gets old. I wanted to ask: `Aren't you professional? Can't you get
it right the first time?' But seeing as it was my first movie, I
thought it best to keep my mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   During the down time, Taylor took notice of some striking
similarities between Stone and his old Giants coach, Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that make Bill Parcells a great coach _ his
personality, his attitude, his ability to see things other people
don't see _ are the same things that make Oliver a great
director,'' Taylor says. ``Oliver will say something to you and you
won't understand a word of what he's talking about, but then you do
it, and you say, `Wow. That's why he makes all those great, weird
movies.'''
</P>
<P>
   When told of the compliment, Stone laughs, and admits there are
some similarities between himself and another coach _ ``Sunday's''
fictional leader of men, Tony D'Amato. For one, both are men who
are more comfortable among men. For another, both wonder if they
are perhaps past their prime. Self-pity colors their worlds. And
then there's the shared propensity for screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is D'Amato,'' says Jamie Williams, a former tight end for
the San Francisco 49ers, who had a hand in developing the movie's
script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have a life,'' Stone counters. ``But, yeah, we share
the same intensity, the same appetites. And I love football.
There's something about sports that brings men together and excites
their passions. The players get to be savages out on the field, and
we live vicariously through that. To me, that's a beautiful
thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1539EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-2000-BEST-THINGS-L     12-23 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-2000-BEST-THINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 2,000 BEST THINGS ABOUT TELEVISION, ACCORDING TO TV LAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Monday, Dec. 27) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are lists that serve as uncanny mirrors of our society _
Time magazine's People of the Year, for example, or the Beatitudes
as delivered by Jesus during the Sermon on the Mount, or David
Letterman's Top 10 lists. Then there are lists that are patently
and risibly pointless, a waste of everyone's time and energy _ the
American Film Institute's 100 best films of all time, Joe
McCarthy's Hollywood 10 during the Red Scare of the '50s, or
anything compiled in Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the lists that are so patently and risibly
pointless that they serve as uncanny mirrors of our society. Which
brings us to TV Land's recent declaration essaying the 2,000 Best
Things About Television.
</P>
<P>
   Folks at the cable outfit worked long, but apparently not too
hard, to concoct this list. The point seems to be to get media
pundits across the country opining over what morons in their right
mind would rate the Pocket Fisherman (671) above the Skipper from
``Gilligan's Island'' (686), who for some unknown reason ranks
higher than Richard Pryor (1,305) !ital!and!off! ``Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' (1,034).
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to disappoint anyone, here are my observations.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the list is aimed at the imbecile in all of us. MTV is
in the top 30 _ of a full 2,000 things, remember _ while HBO didn't
crack the top 100. Edward R. Murrow barely makes the top 200, a few
notches above ``Athletes mouthing the words `Hi, Mom.''' ``The
Sopranos,'' gaining steam as the best TV series ever, barely makes
the top 700, while special compilations of TV commercials comes in
150 slots higher! Tony Danza is considered better by 60 positions!
``The Brady Bunch'' gets 15 separate mentions! The outrage!
</P>
<P>
   ``The rerun'' is No. 9 _ remember, all TV Land does is show
reruns _ while ``Saturday Night Live,'' which has been excruciating
a heck of a lot longer than it was ever actually funny, is No. 14,
with at least 34 other separate entries, like Mr. Bill (227) or
``Deep Thoughts'' (1,205), most of them from the early, funny days.
``Wayne's World'' ranks 278, while Wayne himself is a lowly 1,043 _
did the people compiling the list even bother to pay attention to
what they were up to? If so, they might have wondered where,
besides the phone book, Jon Lovitz (1,561) could possibly come
before Eddie Murphy (an astonishing No. 1,880, just one slot ahead
of Jack Carter).
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a smidgen of the inconsistencies within the
small subset of ``SNL'' listings (which inexplicably accounts for
1.5 percent of !ital!all!off! that is good about television). We
have a full 50 years of logical lapses to pick apart here.
</P>
<P>
   Relax _ we don't have the stomach for it, either. Let's look at
some pointed choices.
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman (No. 23) ranks !ital!waaay!off! ahead of Jay
Leno (312); Letterman comedy bits rate eight other slots, while I
couldn't find one other reference to Leno _ even Conan O'Brien, who
at 485 follows Leno, has at least three routines elsewhere on the
list. Johnny Carson, of course, blows them all away: He's No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple Emmy winner and incredibly prolific guy David E. Kelley
only rates a lowly 1,485 on the list, below ``Battle of the Network
Stars'' and just above ``Two Fat Ladies.'' (Someone must've
!ital!really!off! hated ``Snoops.'') Steven Bochco, on the other
hand, is at 359. The highest-ranked person who actually wrote and
created a show is James L. Brooks (34), followed by Rod Serling
(70) and Carl Reiner (196).
</P>
<P>
   Only ``The West Wing'' (608) and ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (1,839) ranked from the latest TV season.
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting if unlikely calls: the skier's crash landing
opening ``Wide World of Sports'' (No. 57), episodes in which
characters get amnesia (79) or get discovered by Hollywood (850),
Emergency Broadcast System tests (244), the spit-take (588), TV
show board games (1,009), lunch boxes (1,208) and novelizations
(1,363), when a fading show adds a strange new character, often a
child (1,712).
</P>
<P>
   What were they thinking?: Soap operas (No. 87), Billy Jean King
vs. Bobby Riggs (101), Fonzie's leather jacket (261, while the
wimpy blue cotton one from the first season doesn't rate at all),
``I'd like to buy a vowel'' (543), the E! channel (1,148),
``Lancelot Link, Secret Chimp'' (1,626), !ital!two!off! Bob Uecker
references (1,184, 1,344).
</P>
<P>
   Overrated: Live news coverage (No. 5), the Super Bowl (12),
weather reports (31), Fonzie (93), Mr. Haney on ``Green Acres''
(379), Richard Dawson (787), Horshack from ``Welcome Back, Kotter''
(792), technical difficulty cards (908), plate-spinning acts
(1636), ``Arli$$'' (967), ``The Flintstones''' Bamm-Bamm (1,470),
Donny Osmond (1,358), the Osmonds (1,805), ``Seinfeld's'' music
sting (1,634), ``America's Funniest Home Videos'' (1,686), Screech
on ``Saved by the Bell'' (1,999), Charo (2,000) and ABC (1,533).
</P>
<P>
   Underrated: Monty Python's Flying Circus (No. 55), Ernie Kovacs
(167), Bill Murray (343), ``The Larry Sanders Show'' (376),
``Mystery Science Theatre 3000'' (1,912), Mr. Rogers changing his
shoes (675, though it outranks the whole show, at 680), ``Space
Ghost: Coast to Coast'' (718), Dr. McCoy's ``I'm a doctor, not a
...'' line on ``Star Trek'' (1,060), ``Watching the White Bronco''
(1,207), Darren McGavin (1,818), the episode where Mr. Ed plays
baseball (1,268), Emma Peel's leather jump suit (1,275).
</P>
<P>
   Odd juxtapositions: Ellen's coming out (128) is considered just
slightly better than TV commercials (129). ``The Munsters'' bests,
barely, Sarah Michelle Gellar, 1,176 to 1,177. Stuart Margolin
(1,786) and Jesse ``Maytag Repairman'' White (1,790) rank higher
than Katie Couric (1,793). Sally Field's Oscar acceptance speech
(354) rates higher than she does (484). The Pillsbury Doughboy
(363) rates higher than ``The Prisoner'' (364). The ``60 Minutes''
ticking watch (477) barely edges out ``Casper, the Friendly
Ghost's'' theme song (478). ``Wessonality'' outranks ``Everybody
Loves Raymond,'' 1,097 to 1,101.
</P>
<P>
   It's all relative: ``The Simpsons'' episode ``Who Shot
Montgomery Burns'' ranks significantly higher (297) than the
``Dallas'' episode it parodied (1,129). Farrah Fawcett's hair (496)
outranks Farrah herself (573), a fairly crucial distinction. David
Duchovny ranks 638, and his character Fox Mulder weighs in at 723,
while ``The X-Files'' itself is only 752; Duchovny's crush on Larry
Sanders comes in at 1,656.
</P>
<P>
   TV Land somewhat modestly places itself at No. 239. TV critics
rank No. 1,939, which strikes me as somewhat generous _ whoever
compiled this list clearly has never attended TV press tour, or
they wouldn't have made the list at all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
