<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TITUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     12-23 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITUS ANDRONICUS': CRUELTY HATH A HUMAN FACE, A HUMAN HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A director seeking a path into Shakespeare's goriest play,
``Titus Andronicus,'' basically has two choices.
</P>
<P>
   One is to keep a safe distance from a repellent story that many
regard as one of Shakespeare's lesser efforts by treating it as a
slice of stylized Grand Guignol and staging its chain of murders
and mutilations as the blackest of comedies.
</P>
<P>
   The other, riskier way, which the director Julie Taymor has
adopted in her shattering screen adaptation, renamed simply
``Titus,'' is to shoot the moon and take the play extremely
seriously. In peering into the raging hearts of characters
hell-bent on destroying one another and inflicting maximum pain and
humiliation, Ms. Taymor discovers many unsettling contemporary
resonances.
</P>
<P>
   This splashy elaboration of Ms. Taymor's 1994 Off Broadway
production turns ``Titus Andronicus'' into a fluid time-traveling
fantasia on violence and revenge that has the look and feel of a
sophisticated video game.
</P>
<P>
   One minute we are in ancient Rome, the next in Mussolini's
Italy, the next in an ``Alice in Wonderland'' world of life-size
toy soldiers, the next in a video-game arcade.
</P>
<P>
   As these environments collide and merge, we find ourselves in a
surreal, time-collapsed dream world, a murderously supercharged
virtual reality where the characters loom as recurrent historical
archetypes.
</P>
<P>
   Playing this fast and loose with Shakespeare, of course, carries
a price. Ian McKellen's 1930s fascist ``Richard III,'' for
instance, came off as a glibly streamlined, if entertaining, gloss
on Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Titus'' is quite faithful to Shakespeare's text, the
mixture of the ancient and the contemporary and of British
theatrical and American film acting styles can be jarring. Alan
Cumming's flamboyantly prancing, leering, insecure boy emperor,
Saturnius, seems to belong in a different movie from Jessica
Lange's quietly seething Empress Tamora.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Taymor's floating the play through shifting time zones
and locations also pays dividends. It's impossible to watch
``Titus'' without considering the mass slaughters in the Balkans
and Rwanda, and even the Columbine High School killings. What was
then, she forcefully reminds us, is also now.
</P>
<P>
   In connecting these recent horrors to the characters in
``Titus'' Ms. Taymor made the audacious editorial decision to begin
and end the movie with images of children.
</P>
<P>
   The story is prefaced by a scene of a little boy gleefully
stirring up imaginary carnage on a kitchen table with toy soldiers
and ketchup. His private little war game builds to an imaginary
explosion that magically plunges him Alice-like through a tunnel
under the floor into the world of the play.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the film, after most of the major characters have
finished one another off, we see the child, presumably wiser after
all he has been through, leading another child (the illegitimate
son of two of the story's revenge-crazed butchers) into the future.
If this ambiguous ending suggests the possibility of healing, we
also shudder to imagine the legacy of hatred the orphan might be
harboring.
</P>
<P>
   From its opening images, ``Titus'' portrays violence as an
escalating fever, an addictive mass hysteria that consumes the
characters and turns them into bloodthirsty fiends. That notion
seems to be borne out by what we know of the killing fields in
Rwanda and Cambodia, to name two countries where mass slaughter
became commonplace in recent times.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the film, in one of its most indelible and
grotesque images, the title character (Anthony Hopkins), who has
gone mad, throws a cannibalistic banquet of revenge in which he
dons a contemporary chef's uniform to serve meat pies to the
Empress Tamora and her husband made from the bodies of her two
sons.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins got it right in a recent interview when he described his
Titus as a mixture of King Lear and Hannibal Lecter. His
performance, one of his finest, is ghoulishly funny and emotionally
devastating all at once.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of this great actor in a chef's hat, cackling
grotesquely while serving up human carnage, is a coup de cinema by
the director celebrated for her transfixing theatrical images in
shows like ``The Lion King'' and ``Juan Darien.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Titus,'' Ms. Taymor's background as a gifted
puppeteer whose inanimate creations convey a primal psychological
charge is evident. The film's most searing image finds Titus'
daughter, Lavinia, who has been raped and mutilated by Tamora's
sons, reduced into a human scarecrow with branches planted in the
stumps of her severed hands and red ribbons streaming from a mouth
from which the tongue has been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Those murderous sons, Chiron (Jonathan Rhys Meyers) and
Demetrius (Matthew Rhys), are punkish speed-freak sociopaths
straight out of ``A Clockwork Orange.'' Their mother, who ascends
from captured slave to empress, is an elaborately tattooed pagan
goddess for all seasons clad in gold lame and matching gold
breastplates.
</P>
<P>
   The revenge cycle begins when Titus, a popular Roman general,
victoriously returning with his Goth prisoners of war, refuses to
spare the life of Tamora's eldest son and slays him before her
eyes. Ascending to power as the wife of Saturnius, Tamora plots
revenge with Aaron (Harry Lennix), her black servant and lover, who
engineers much of the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Seething from a lifetime of racial humiliation, Aaron is the
play's (and the movie's) ultimate symbol of the hate that begets
hate. Lennix's cool, wily Aaron stands as the ultimate, vengeful
product of a toxic racism.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Ms. Taymor has said she wants to help lift
``Titus Andronicus'' from its relatively low regard in
Shakespeare's canon. And her fine, provocative film makes a strong
case for ``Titus Andronicus'' to be taken much more seriously than
it has been.
</P>
<P>
   But any play in which revenge is the single guiding motivation
for most of the characters most of the time inevitably lacks other
human dimensions. In any case, ``Titus'' makes the best possible
argument for a cautionary drama that contemplates the absolute
worst in us.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `TITUS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Julie Taymor; adapted from Shakespeare's
``Titus Andronicus''; director of photography, Luciano Tovoli;
edited by Francoise Bonnot; music by Elliot Goldenthal; production
designer, Dante Ferretti; produced by Jody Patton, Conchita Airoldi
and Ms. Taymor; released by Fox Searchlight Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Anthony Hopkins (Titus), Jessica Lange (Tamora), Alan
Cumming (Saturnius), Harry Lennix (Aaron), Jonathan Rhys Meyers
(Chiron), Matthew Rhys (Demetrius), Angus Macfadyen (Lucius) and
Colm Feore (Marcus).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 160 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Titus'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has gory violence, nudity and an orgy
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
