<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: ROCK CRYSTAL FOR KINGS AND GODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WENDY MOONAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christmastime is just the season for rock crystal,
which has long been revered for its purity, its lucidity and its
magical play of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Christians, light penetrating rock crystal is
traditionally symbolic of the Immaculate Conception,'' Sylvie
Raulet writes in ``Rock Crystal Treasures From Antiquity to Today''
(Vendome Press, 1999). ``The Virgin Mary is the crystal and her
son, Jesus Christ, the celestial light.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian church has always used rock crystal, an especially
colorless form of quartz and the symbol of purity. Angels are often
seen wearing rock crystal pendants in paintings, like Piero della
Francesca's ``Madonna of Sengallia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Middle Ages, rock crystal was mostly used for religious
objects,'' said Tony Blumka, the owner of Blumka Gallery, at 209 E.
72nd St. in Manhattan, which specializes in medieval, Renaissance
and Baroque art. ``It was considered very precious. It was even
used just to take the place of glass.'' The Metropolitan Museum of
Art has a 14th-century faceted rock crystal beaker from Germany
with gilded silver mounts and cover that came from his gallery and
is on display at the Cloisters.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Barnet, the Met's curator of Medieval art and the
Cloisters, said that ``hundreds of thousands of pieces of rock
crystal from the Middle Ages have been lost.'' The Met has a church
monile, or necklace, of silver gilt and rock crystal from the early
16th century. ``It would be kissed by the priest during the
celebration of the Mass,'' Barnet said. ``Ours has rubies set into
it and a hexagonal piece of rock crystal at the center with the IHS
monogram of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1500s Pope Clement VII commissioned a small rock
crystal casket to give to King Francis I of France on the occasion
of his son's marriage to Caterina de Medici. It was decorated with
gold, enamel rondels and intricately carved rock crystal panels
with scenes from the life of Jesus. It was created about 1530 by a
master craftsman from Vicenza, Italy, named Valerio Belli, who is
mentioned in Vasari's ``Lives of the Most Eminent Italian
Architects, Painters and Sculptors.'' It took two years to make and
cost 2 million florins. It is now in the collection of the Museo
degli Argenti in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Francis I must have loved rock crystal. He built a royal
treasury in a tower of his chateau in Fontainbleau to display his
most sumptuous objects, including a silver-gilt and rock crystal
ciborium (which holds the eucharistic bread) and a pair of
magnificent rock crystal candlesticks festooned with gold, pearls
and garnets that were made about 1530 and later presented to the
Treasury of the Order of the Holy Ghost. They are now in the
Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Monstrances on church altars were made of imperfect rock
crystals whose fissures were meant to symbolize the ``tears of
Christ.'' Rock crystal reliquaries containing the precious bones of
saints are often encrusted with pearls and jewels. Clement VII
alone commissioned 41, and they were shown to the public only twice
a year, on the Saturday of Holy Week and Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It seems amazing that bejeweled rock crystal reliquaries have
survived from the Middle Ages and the Renaissance. But as Ms.
Raulet put it, ``Anyone who dared steal or damage these treasures _
consecrated because of the relics they contained _ would be
excommunicated.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more antique rock crystal is coming on view now. The
Gilbert Collection, which will go on display at Somerset House in
London in May, for example, includes a splendid tankard from
Strasbourg. ``Rock crystal was much prized in the Renaissance
because it was supposed to be able to detect poison,'' said Timothy
Schroder, the curator.
</P>
<P>
   Rock crystal has been worked since the third millennium before
Christ and carries different meanings for different cultures. The
Egyptians used it in their jewelry and in the eyes of sculptures.
The word is derived from the Greek word for ice, krystallos,
because the Greeks thought rock crystal was formed by water frozen
on mountaintops at such extreme temperatures that it could no
longer melt. In many cultures it was considered a divining stone,
and mediums still use a crystal ball to communicate with the forces
of nature.
</P>
<P>
   In China, rock crystal is said to symbolize victory. ``Rock
crystal was not used much in China,'' said crystal dealer Jim
Lally. ``It's rare.'' He has a rock crystal bear from a late
Warring States or Han burial site in Shandong Province and is
asking $40,000 for it.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of rock crystal carving seems to have deteriorated
in Europe from the 18th century to the 20th. The Paris dealer
Nicolas Kugel sells only rock crystal carved in the 16th and 17th
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gem-cutting tradition initiated by the Medicis faded out
after Louis XIV,'' he said. He is particularly proud to have
17th-century gold-mounted rock crystal cups carved by the Milanese
artist Miseroni, he said, adding, ``He worked for most of the
courts of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kugel was the underbidder for the famous Moor's Head cup that
Sotheby's sold in London on Dec. 17 for $2,859,580, a record for a
silver object sold at auction in Britain. It was a marriage cup
belonging to the Royal House of Saxony. The head, with a rock
crystal feathered headdress set with precious stones, was made by
the goldsmith Christoph Jamnitzer (1563-1618).
</P>
<P>
   The cup was the top lot in the 143-lot sale of the Moritzburg
treasure, which was buried in wood crates in the forest of the
family estate outside Dresden during World War II as the Soviet
army approached. It lay there undiscovered until 1996, when it was
found by an amateur treasure hunter who called the authorities. It
was displayed in a museum in Dresden in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, rock crystal has been a popular mineral for
jewelry designers, especially Faberge, who single-handedly revived
the princely tradition of rock crystal works meant to be displayed
as status symbols. Cartier, which made Gloria Swanson's
diamond-studded rock crystal cuffs, continues to use rock crystal
in jewelry and clocks similar to those designed in the 1920s and
'30s.
</P>
<P>
   Paris jeweler Alain Boucheron began to reintroduce rock crystal
years ago. A true enthusiast, he uses it for objets d'art, clocks,
jewelry, even chess sets. He has created a bestiary of animal
motifs in rock crystal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rock crystal represents at once both turbulence and
limpidity, and its dual, even ambiguous nature is the very essence
of the mineral's magic,'' he wrote in the preface to Ms. Raulet's
new book. ``It conjures up all that is finite yet never-ending,
instantaneous though eternal; both heat and cold, immobile yet
changeable. This explains why Georges Sand said that it represented
the limit between `the visible and the invisible.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
