<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHRISTMAS-PAST-2TAKES     12-23 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-PAST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS 1899, JUST LIKE THE ONES I NEVER KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
Thomas Mallon's novels include ``Dewey Defeats Truman'' and ``Henry
and Clara.'' His latest novel, ``Two Moons,'' will be published in
February. 
 By THOMAS MALLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There has never been any doubt that in the spectral
trinity Dickens created to preside over the Yule holiday, the Ghost
of Christmas Past reigns as first among equals _ the prime mover of
mood and spirit. Christmas might, in fact, be characterized as a
holiday in continual, necessary decline, a celebration whose
emotional center is our insistence upon the superiority of
Christmases gone by. White Christmases are, by definition, the ones
you used to know.
</P>
<P>
   The impulse to see yesterday's Yuletides through a glowing,
fir-scented mist of nostalgia is hardly a modern one. A glance at
the pages of The New York Times for Christmas week 1899 shows our
late-Victorian ancestors indulging in the same sentiments we feel
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day had not been especially favored by the fickle weather
clerk,'' The Times reported on Dec. 26, 1899. After a stretch of
unseasonable warmth, Christmas turned out ``cloudy for the most
part, with intervals of sunshine, and a brisk, cold breeze, lacking
both the cheer of continuous brightness and the appropriate gift of
a snowstorm.'' The ``two trifling flurries of snow'' only teased
``the spirits of the youngsters to whom Santa Claus had brought
sleds.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper had been braced for disappointment for days. On
Dec. 23, the lead article in its Saturday Review of Books and Art
raised the cultural question: ``Is the Christmas Spirit Decaying?''
It appeared to the essayist that ``into this beautiful custom there
has crept a sort of materialism _ a commercial spirit.'' The author
had less objection to the amount of money being spent than to the
automatic, cheerless way in which the till was jingling: ``There is
too much of the give-and-take feeling, the balancing of virtues,
and the idea that gifts must be sent because received.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there had been ``a great apparent decrease in the number of
jolly-looking people, with tired but happy faces, and arms full to
overflowing with bundles.'' Couldn't everyone remember how, not so
long ago, ``one package-laden individual looked at others who were
equally burdened; the whole scene, the shops, the streets, the
people, producing a certain friendly feeling _ the real Christmas
spirit of love and good will toward all men''?
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years later, as we do our online shopping, filling the
virtual basket with one more point and click, we are equally
tempted to recall yesteryear's sharp elbows and stolen cabs as
having been one long pink-cheeked festival of urban cheer. But it
is memory, and the elaborate tricks played upon it by Christmas,
that turns every crotchet into a Cratchit, each fuhgedaboudit into
a fa-la-la-la-la.
</P>
<P>
   The Times writer, who knew his complaint was already ``an old,
old one,'' wondered if the trouble comes ``simply because we are
growing older and losing our capacity for illusions.'' Actually,
our capacity for nostalgia, the grandest illusion of all, is the
single faculty that expands as we get older, with Christmas the
evergreen herbal firing its big annual growth spurt.
</P>
<P>
   At Christmastime in 1899, New York City seemed to keep its mind
more on the holiday than the approaching turn of the century, and
when the future did force itself upon the mind, there was the
comforting possibility that things might not change so much after
all. E.S. Nadal, writing for the paper on Dec. 24, predicted that
even with the advent of the bicycle and trolley and automobile,
``it does not follow that the use of horses will be superseded or
even very greatly circumscribed by them.'' There is not, alas, much
comfort here for those now counting on the survival of the printed
book and retail store.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of 1899, the nation was generally in a mood to
count its blessings. With the Spanish-American War well over, the
bodies of sailors blown up on the Maine 22 months earlier were at
last returning for home burial: President William McKinley would
preside over ceremonies at Arlington on Dec. 28. Those New Yorkers
who found the warmer-than-usual weather still too cold for comfort
could let themselves be tempted by an advertisement in The Times
for Puerto Rico, ``Uncle Sam's new possession, this charming
island.''
</P>
<P>
   Things across the Atlantic were not nearly so sunny. France
remained riven by the Dreyfus case, and England had just suffered
unexpected reverses in the Boer War. Queen Victoria, spending her
life's second-to-last Christmas at Windsor Castle, wished only for
a stiff upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported, ``It was ... her express desire that the
grandchildren who assembled about her today should not have their
Christmas marred by the events which have saddened her own heart.''
</P>
<P>
   If the United States was enjoying peace and the beginnings of
its own little empire, Christmas nonetheless magnified the
country's two-nations problem of rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' lead story for Dec. 26, 1899, concerned the previous
day's feeding of 20,000 needy New Yorkers by the Salvation Army in
Madison Square Garden. The practice had begun only the year before,
and the newspaper's account paid attention to not only those
serving and being fed, but also to an upper crust of spectators who
had come to watch a show:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the boxes and gallery of the great building during the
evening, when the feast was at its height, sat many thousands of
well-fed and prosperous people, among them many women who had come
in carriages and were gorgeously gowned and wore many diamonds, who
looked on in happy sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The modern reader may think the reporter's tone is meant to
convey revulsion, or at least irony, but two column inches down one
encounters a heartfelt description of ``the splendid bridge that
yesterday spanned for one brief day at least the chasm that yawns
between the rich and the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Battle for Christmas,'' historian Stephen
Nissenbaum surveys press coverage of this event and finds how
``only a single report, in The New York World, suggested that what
had happened was more a matter of voyeurism than of class
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rich were beset with some anxieties of their own.
The stock market had recently taken a sharp dip, and ``one
prominent jewelry house had had over 300 orders canceled since the
panic.'' Keene's, on Fulton Street, placed a sizable ad in The
Times promising that it would be open on Christmas Day ``owing to a
large number of articles reserved and not called for.''
</P>
<P>
   If the rich no longer gawk quite so crassly at the feeding of
the poor, the city's vast middle class, after its own big dinner,
still indulges in the slightly pharisaical pleasure of watching
television news crews invade New York homeless shelters to film
celebrity servers and embarrassed diners.
</P>
<P>
   One more easily counts one's own surfeit of blessings by toting
up the scarcity of others, which is why stories of Christmas crime
and catastrophe pack an especially hard punch. 'Tis the season when
fire seems made not just for the hearth, but for the tenement and
crib as well. Two days before Christmas 1899, readers of The Times
found a lengthy front-page story from Quincy, Ill., concerning 11
children killed in a Nativity pageant rehearsal:
</P>
<P>
   ``Laurena Menke, aged 9 years, who was to impersonate a lamb in
a tableaux of the birth of Christ, came in contact with the
gaslight, and the cotton batting from her costume was at once
enveloped in flames, which by running about in her wild frenzy, she
communicated to the costumes of other girls, who, in turn, spread
it still further among the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The details of this lamb-to-the-slaughter tale jump out, however
horrifically, in the spirit of the season, which is wondrously,
cosmically ironic: the world's Savior born in a stable; the last
ready to be made first. Forever after, the promise of redemption
has shimmered more brightly, more mysteriously, beside sudden,
terrible doom.
</P>
<P>
   Calamities that might seem only squalid at another time of year
take on greater pathos and, we're somehow sure, significance.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Dec. 23, 1899, Willis Clark, an unemployed variety
actor who had lost faith in his prospects, shot at his wife,
missed, and then succeeded in killing himself amid ``holiday crowds
surging past the always busy corner of Fifth Avenue and 23rd
Street, in the continuous kaleidoscopic, cosmopolitan parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers could take a guilty, debonair pleasure in the high-life
crime drama of the ``young clubman'' Roland B. Molineux, who was
spending this Christmas in the Tombs while on trial for a Christmas
crime from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Molineux stood accused of having mailed a present _ a bottle of
Bromo Seltzer with a silver holder _ to one Harry Cornish. Not
knowing that cyanide was mixed into the bottle, Cornish allowed his
landlady to partake of the contents with fatal results.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper audience for the continuing story was not yet
aware of another man spending Christmas 1899 in prison for
embezzlement partway across the country in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   There, William Sydney Porter, who would become better known as
O. Henry, passed away the time in jail by writing stories. ``The
Gift of the Magi,'' even now the ultimate tale of New York
gift-giving, was only several years off, and knowledge of its
imminence might have eased the disappointment of our ``Christmas
Spirit'' essayist, whose nostalgic complaints included the decline
in those ``simple stories which used to fill the Christmas
numbers'' of the magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers, then as now, were crammed with advertisements
for after-Christmas bargains. Abraham &AMP; Straus beckoned readers to
its ``Annual Event in Muslin Underwear,'' and the Siegel Cooper
department store, disposing of the Yule as if it were a nuisance,
offered ``a clean sweep of all our Holiday Toys,'' including some
``Handsomely Dressed Dolls'' for 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   One imagines that avid young newspaper reader Virginia O'Hanlon
awakening on West 95th Street to scan the ads in search of
something to make up for yesterday's letdown. Now 10 _ two years
past The New York Sun's famous letter reassuring her that yes,
there is a Santa Claus, and probably more skeptical about the
matter _ she, too, had surely concluded that Christmas isn't what
it used to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
