<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-MALL-$ADV26-COX     12-23 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-MALL-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WASHINGTON'S MALL-ENNIUM: FIREWORKS, MUSIC AND ANXIETY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories for
release Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Champagne, music, a spectacular fireworks display _
and a touch of anxiety _ will set the tone of the ``America's
Millennium'' celebration on the Washington Mall on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The White House office of the first lady, which is coordinating
plans for ringing in the first year that starts with a ``2'' _
calendar purists say the next millennium won't start until Jan. 1,
2001 _ was predicting last week that 100,000 people would show up
for the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a drop from the 600,000 originally expected.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is likely the result of continuous cautions from
President Clinton and other officials for Americans to be
``vigilant'' about possible terrorist acts during the holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the customary ``lost kids'' tent, a new
37-foot-long mobile command center has been stationed on the Mall
for use by police, fire and other emergency officials _ another
reminder of the vague but real concern about Y2K terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, a daylong celebration will climax with a
pyrotechnic extravaganza described by its producer as a
once-in-a-millennium cascade of brilliant white ``stars'' raining
down from the 555-foot Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   From the Lincoln Memorial several hundred yards away, Clinton
will light a fuse 20 seconds before midnight to set off the finale.
</P>
<P>
   It will take 10 seconds for the fuse to burn its way to the base
of the Washington Monument, currently surrounded by an elaborate
scaffold because of refurbishing work.
</P>
<P>
   Then, starting at 11:59:50, 10 successive bursts of brilliant
white stars will rain down the sides of the monument, each 55 feet
above the one before it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, beginning at precisely midnight, the entire monument
will be covered with ``a stunningly beautiful waterfall'' of white
pyrotechnics, said Philip Butler, who is producing the show for
Fireworks by Grucci, a venerable Long Island company.
</P>
<P>
   For a period of 20 seconds, all 10 segments of the fireworks
display will burn simultaneously. Then, beginning again at the
bottom, they will start shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monument is a national icon which is held in great
reverence,'' Butler said in an interview last week, ``and we could
never use it as a fireworks stage, except for the scaffolding being
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through a lot of effort on everybody's part, including the
National Park Service, we worked out a way to use the scaffolds and
not the monument itself for our spectacular. This will never be
done again _ unless maybe in the year 3000.''
</P>
<P>
   An ``America's Millennium Gala'' show preceding the fireworks
will be televised by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But the millennium events are to take up most of the day,
beginning at 11 a.m. with performances on the Mall by youth choirs,
the U.S. Marine Corps Band and other performers. The president and
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will unveil a ``National
Millennium Time Capsule,'' containing artifacts representing
America at the end of the 20th century, at the 11 a.m. event.
</P>
<P>
   Four Smithsonian Mall museums _ the National Air and Space
Museum, the National Museum of Natural History, the Hirshhorn
Museum and the National Museum of American History _ will operate
at their normal 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m. hours throughout the New Year's
weekend, Dec. 31 through Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, auditoriums in the Hirshhorn and the museums of
American history and national history will present a continuous
series of 33 hour-long lectures on subjects ranging from bluegrass
music to the future of sports in America.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are free, but have all been given out on a
first-come-first-served basis, a Smithsonian spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   Beer, wine and champagne will be sold at the Mall celebration,
but alcohol consumption will be monitored with a wristband
accounting system, and limited to a four-block area east of the
Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   Streets immediately around the Mall will be closed, and city
officials have urged persons attending the celebration to use the
Metro subway system. Subways will operate until 3 a.m. and buses
until 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons will host a dinner for 1,000 invited guests at the
White House. A select 320, including Muhammad Ali and Elizabeth
Taylor, will actually sit down with the first couple inside the
White House. The rest, members of Congress and others, will dine in
a heated tent in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, the Clintons and 500 of their guests will go to
the Lincoln Memorial for a splashy ``America's Millennium Gala,''
hosted by actor-rapper Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The gala will include entertainment by Robert Duvall, Diane
Keaton, Kathy Mattea, Bobby McFerrin, Don McLean, Brian Stokes
Mitchell, Kenny Rogers, Luther Vandross, Tricia Yearwood, Sam
Waterston, BeBe Winans and Luke Cresswell accompanied by
</P>
<P>
   the 25-member company of the Broadway production ``Stomp.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last half-hour of the year, large projection screens
erected beside the Lincoln Memorial will show an 18-minute movie,
``The Unfinished Journey,'' by Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   The president will speak briefly, then light the fuse.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
