<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHICH WAY THE WIND BLOWS
</P>
<P>
   D.A. Pennebaker gave a literary feeling to ``Don't Look Back,''
his 1967 documentary about Bob Dylan. ``The songs had a Kerouac
quality,'' he said in an interview the other day. ``They
continually surprised you: always the pig who flew through the
window. He took you into literature, whether he intended it or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, to be released on DVD and in a new tape edition on
Jan. 4, travels along on a three-week concert tour of England in
1965. Heard regularly in Britain on Radio Caroline, a pirate
station, Dylan was in the early throes of fame and about to play
the Royal Albert Hall. ``Take that girl off our car,'' a member of
his entourage cries as the limousine edges into the mob after a
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is playful, sort of. ``You had to take part in their
lives in a way that was natural or they'd throw you out of their
room,'' Pennebaker says in a film-length commentary he shares on
the disk with Bob Neuwirth, Dylan's road manager. The director put
his camera on his shoulder and hung out on the fringes. Biography
didn't matter. ``I liked not getting a lot of facts down,'' he
said. ``Because my sense was that he was making it up all along,
inventing himself before our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Baez was also on the tour and is prominent in the film.
Life consists of managers and arrangements, small rooms crowded
with friends and their friends. On the disc the two commentators
are always delighted by what they see, which can be infectious.
``Isn't that Allen Ginsberg?'' Neuwirth asks. Dylan is forever
smoking, writing songs and mischievously sparring with the latest
journalist sent to interview him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes The Manchester Guardian, in over its head,''
Pennebaker comments on the disc. No one from the press understands
Dylan's songs. He teases them like children. ``If we didn't not
like you, we could put you on,'' he tells one earnest young
reporter who has made the mistake of suggesting that Dylan wasn't
treating him with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Pennebaker said in the interview, most of the
resulting articles bore Dylan no grudge. ``He was kind in a
sense,'' he said. ``He always pulled back. In literature there are
writers who can't get enough blood on the floor. But he realized
reporters weren't fair contestants. They were just sent out as part
of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The disc includes new audio performances of ``It's All Over Now,
Baby Blue,'' ``The Lonesome Death of Hattie Carroll'' and ``It
Ain't Me, Babe'' and, of course, bits of many other songs. In the
film, a reporter from Time magazine tells Dylan that he is going to
attend a concert. ``It's going to happen fast, and you're not going
to get it,'' the singer tells him.
</P>
<P>
   As a film star Dylan was somewhat puzzled himself. ``He was
trying to see what he looked like to people from a more normal
world,'' Pennebaker said. ``He kind of lost track of the film
because it took so little effort and was like a home movie. He had
no thought about how revealing it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   MICKEY BLUE EYES
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fugate (Hugh Grant) works hard at getting himself into
proper cultural alignment to marry the daughter (Jeanne
Tripplehorn) of a genial Mafia chieftain (James Caan). An
Englishman with Grant's brittle manner, slight stammer and
practiced helplessness is bound to make an awkward fit with
raucous, wear-it-on-your-sleeve future in-laws who are lovable one
minute and deadly the next. With plenty of suave comic timing,
Grant's Mickey negotiates the gangsterish shoals in, Stephen Holden
wrote in The New York Times, ``a lightweight comedy that has more
than enough laughs to justify its silly, scatterbrained premise.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 103 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   THE HARMONISTS
</P>
<P>
   In telling the story of the Comedian Harmonists, a German
singing group popular in the days when the Weimar Republic gave way
to Nazi control, a handsome and thought-provoking film raises
questions about how the same people could cherish culture and
embrace barbarity. Full of lively, funny and sentimental song, the
group gains in popularity and earns a trip to New York. But three
of its members are Jewish, and on their return they are forced to
disband in a film that approaches Germany's past with ``a
compelling gravity'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $75.41. 124 minutes. Closed captioned. German
with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   DROP DEAD GORGEOUS
</P>
<P>
   About as funny as making fun of maimed characters in
wheelchairs, Michael Patrick Jann's film gives the overworked realm
of beauty pageants a scorched-earth treatment that just may finish
the subject forever. (Fat chance.) At a high school in Minnesota, a
pushy pageant organizer (Kirstie Alley) bullies a ragtag field of
entrants through their paces in preparation for a contest that, if
all goes right, will culminate in the coronation of her nasty
daughter (Denise Richards). For viewers all that's left is to
``wince through what may be a record number of miserably unfunny
jokes'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 98 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   THE RED VIOLIN
</P>
<P>
   The discovery by an unscrupulous New York violin restorer
(Samuel L. Jackson) that an instrument he has been assigned to work
on is a legendary violin made in 1681 sets off a fanciful and gaudy
string of tales. Over three centuries the instrument makes its way
from 17th-century Italy to 18th-century Austria, to a tribe of
Gypsies, then to 19th-century England, 20th-century China and
finally to contemporary Montreal. The fiddle experiences a lot over
that stretch, but the intended grand statement about the mystical
power of great music becomes ``too kitschy to let that vision catch
fire'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.98. 131 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW TITLES OF INTEREST, SOME OF WHICH MAY HAVE HAD A
THEATER RELEASE, APPEARED ON TELEVISION OR BEEN ON VIDEOCASSETTE IN
EARLIER EDITIONS.
</P>
<P>
   BABAR: KING OF THE ELEPHANTS. An animated film made for video
follows the elephant king from his early travails in the forest to
his stay in the city with the sweet old lady who teaches him the
way of the humans and back to the jungle for his coronation. 1999.
HBO. $19.96. 85 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITNESS TO THE MOB. The NBC mini-series stars Nicholas Turturro
as Salvatore (Sammy the Bull) Gravano, onetime underboss of the
Gambino crime family, who testified against his boss, John Gotti,
and helped send him to prison for life. Here, Caryn James wrote in
The New York Times, ``is a rare example of a smart, sophisticated,
fact-based television drama, one that combines the blare of
headlines with the heft of the best fiction.''1998. Trimark.
$79.99. 172 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   HOGARTH'S `MARRIAGE A LA MODE.' A documentary from the National
Gallery in Britain examines the moral tale _ and a harrowing one it
is _ that unfolds in a series of six Hogarth paintings, beginning
with the marriage between the son of a bankrupt nobleman and the
stubborn daughter of a London alderman and proceeding through
adultery, venereal disease, murder and suicide. 1997. Home Vision.
$19.95. 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   VAUDEVILLE. An American Masters production includes performance
clips of Bob Hope, George Burns and Gracie Allen, Eddie Cantor,
Bert Lahr, W.C. Fields and others. 1999. Winstar. $19.98; DVD,
$24.98. 112 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
