<HEADLINE>
SOLVE THIS PUZZLE, WIN A BUNDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: Where can I find the Eternity Puzzle, which is popular
in Europe and has supposedly been available in the United States
since October?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.H., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: Eternity, a 209-piece jigsaw puzzle that will pay 1
million British pounds to the person who solves it first, is
available by mail from the Evers Toy Store. The prize is worth more
than $1.6 million at present exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle sells for $29.95 plus $6 shipping and handling. To
order, call (800) 962-9481; write to Evers Toy Store, Box 241,
Dyersville, IA 52040; or visit the Web site www.everstoystore.com.
</P>
<P>
   All puzzle pieces are the same color on both sides, no two are
identical in shape, and there's no way to distinguish an edge
piece. They must be placed onto a 12-sided board with no gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite common to fill most of the board, only to discover
that the last 20 or so pieces just cannot be placed,'' Eternity
enthusiast Mark Pursey writes on his Web site at
homepages.tig.com.au/~snark/eternity.
</P>
<P>
   You also can win the money without purchasing the puzzle. For
rules, write to Eternity, Ertl/Racing Champions, Box 500,
Dyersville, IA 52040.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I send get-well cards to Robert Urich (synovial
sarcoma), Charles Schulz (colon cancer) and Jim Varney (lung
cancer)?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.M., Mansfield, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Urich in care of Baker Winokur Ryder Public
Relations, 405 S. Beverly Drive, Fifth Floor, Beverly Hills, Calif.
90212l; Schulz at Number One Snoopy Place, Santa Rosa, Calif.
95403; and Varney in care of William W. Gibson, Wyatt Tarrant and
Combs, 518 Union St., Nashville, TN 37219-1750.
</P>
<P>
   Urich, who turned 53 on Dec. 19, said a year ago that he has a
clean bill of health. Chemotherapy and radiation treatments were
used to fight the rare soft-tissue cancer he was found to have in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, 77, was found to have cancer in November. He will be
retiring from his ``Peanuts'' comic strip early next year, ending
new daily strips Jan. 3 and Sunday strips on Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Varney, 50, recently made public his illness. He had part of his
right lung removed in September 1998 and has had radiation
treatments.
</P>
