<HEADLINE>
`IRVING BERLIN': A SMARTLY PRODUCED BIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review. Time is for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The silence at the center of ``Irving Berlin: An American Song''
is the program's subject himself. Berlin utters scarcely a word in
Sunday's two-hour tribute on A&AMP;E to his prodigious career. When we
hear directly from him, it is his famous rendition of ``Oh! How I
Hate to Get Up in the Morning,'' from ``This Is the Army.'' His
reticence offstage can be taken as his way of telling the world
that what he had to say he said in his music and lyrics, and that
there was nothing he could add to that, so why bother?
</P>
<P>
   This smartly produced and edited biography makes a good case
that the sentimentality, the patriotism, the connection to his
country and his audience that we hear in Berlin's songs were real.
In work that some critics, favoring the spirit of a Porter or a
Hart or a Sondheim, dismissed as unsophisticated, an enormous
audience found an expression of its own feelings, whether for
America or Christmas or true love. Berlin was a show-business
natural, but his songs were from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   When he tapped into his audience, he was tapping into himself.
``Always'' was for Ellin Mackay, the love of his life; ``Blue
Skies'' was for their first baby. It didn't matter that he couldn't
read music; the magic was in how he heard it and brought it to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the immigrant boy who became America's best-loved
composer began on the Lower East Side of Manhattan in the early
years of the century. After his inauspicious start as a singing
waiter (32 cents in royalties for his first song, ``Marie From
Sunny Italy,'' which rhymed ``queen'' with ``mand-o-leen''),
``Alexander's Ragtime Band'' swept the nation, and except for the
rare lapse he kept turning out hits for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's career ended in the 1950s with the advent of rock 'n'
roll. For all his versatility through the decades, the new pop
music did not come naturally to him, and after a couple of failed
efforts he withdrew from show business. He lived on to 1989, but
with bouts of depression. The program doesn't get very deeply into
the reclusive man, but it does justice to the tunes.
</P>
<P>
   It's still easy to get caught up in Berlin's songs and their
spirit, whether it's a scratchy version of ``A Pretty Girl Is Like
a Melody'' from the Ziegfeld Follies, or Fred Astaire doing ``Cheek
to Cheek'' with Ginger Rogers, or Judy Garland in the Easter
Parade, or Rudy Vallee introducing a radio audience to ``Say It
Isn't So,'' or Ethel Waters having a heat wave, or Bing Crosby
crooning ``White Christmas,'' or Kate Smith rousing the nation with
``God Bless America,'' or Ethel Merman doin' what comes natur'lly.
Berlin stopped writing a half-century ago, but the snatches heard
here of his astounding array of hits can start you humming all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY SPECIAL' Irving Berlin: An American Song
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at 8 p.m. ET on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Written and produced by Michael Epstein; Josie Peltz,
coordinating producer; Genevieve Standing, production coordinator;
Alison Guss, senior producer. Produced by History Television
Productions for A&AMP;E. Carol Anne Dolan and Susan E. Leventhal,
executive producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
