NYT-12-23-99 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JESUS-APPEARANCE-COX     12-23 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-APPEARANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Face of Jesus a 2,000-year-old mystery
 &HT;    (Eds: The following package on the facts behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today. The
package includes JESUS-LIFE, JESUS-APPEARANCE, JESUS-CRUCIFY,
JESUS-MISTLETOE and JESUS-GIFTS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jesus Christ is worshiped as the human
incarnation of the son of God, and his likeness has been reproduced
for hundreds of years by thousands of artists.
</P>
<P>
   But they've all been making it up.
</P>
<P>
   The Apostles were assiduous in copying down Jesus' message, but
no one bothered to write about his appearance. We know some things
he said, but not at all how he sounded.
</P>
<P>
   And though Bible readers are given vague hints about the visage
of the Prince of Peace, even those are contradictory. It was
written that Jesus was handsome, and it was written that he was
not.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries European Renaissance painters gave him the benefit
of the doubt. Jesus was portrayed as tall and fair and, well,
angelic, but archeologists and historians say the evidence points
otherwise. By the standards of white America today, the son of God
was probably short, dark and lithe. ``He was probably about
5-feet-4, and 135 pounds with tanned olive skin,'' said the Rev J.
Brabban, chairman of the religion and philosophy department at Palm
Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jesus was a carpenter and a construction worker he
probably had calluses on his hands. In all likelihood he had brown
or black hair, perhaps curly, and an aquiline, Semitic nose. In
short, Jesus looked like a Middle Eastern Jew who worked hard for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   But did he have a beard and long hair like he did on Broadway in
``Jesus Christ Superstar?'' Maybe. Men of that day wore their hair
both long and short, but most of the styles archeologists are
familiar with from the first century come from portraits of rich
people who lived in big cities, hardly a category Jesus fell into.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition of Jesus having long hair and a beard is from
the Middle Ages,'' said Michael White, a professor of religious
studies at the University of Texas at Austin. ``They romanticized
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make things up and then they get passed down as fact.
It's like the camels in the story of the Magi. There is no evidence
that there were camels and they were not typical domestic animals,
but everybody thinks they were there because that's how the story
is presented.''
</P>
<P>
   What historians are confident of is that Jesus was probably
familiar with four languages. His native tongue would have been
Aramaic, a cousin to Hebrew; the language spoken at the marketplace
was Greek; the formal language of the government was Latin. Jesus
would have both read and written ancient Hebrew, the language of
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   By our standards, Jesus would have been considered, materially
at least, dirt poor. He might have eaten meat _ lamb or goat _ once
every two weeks but he survived largely on grains. Except for the
time he spent near the Sea of Galilee, all the fish he ate was
probably salted.
</P>
<P>
   And he was not well-traveled. With the exception of his family's
exile to Egypt after his birth, he probably never ventured more
than 100 miles away from his hometown of Nazareth. But because he
lived in the Middle East, the crossroads of the world, he probably
saw people from several different countries who came through the
Holy Land to trade their merchandise, and their slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Besides persecution, he probably feared leprosy and knew a few
people with tuberculosis. Since even rudimentary dental care or
optometry was still centuries away, most of the people around him
were missing teeth and suffered from poor vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's all speculation,'' said White. ``From all we know he
looked like any ordinary Jewish person of the first century. But we
can't really be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: douglasbelkin(at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
