<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JESUS-CRUCIFY-COX     12-23 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-CRUCIFY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jesus' death quick by Roman standards
 &HT;    (Eds: The following package on the facts behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today. The
package includes JESUS-LIFE, JESUS-APPEARANCE, JESUS-CRUCIFY,
JESUS-MISTLETOE and JESUS-GIFTS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spikes nailed through Jesus' wrists and ankles did not kill
him. The crown of thorns that cut into his brow was little more
than a nuisance, and the whipping he endured before he was
crucified was almost an act of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Christ, like the tens of thousands who were crucified
before and after him, died because he could not breathe.
</P>
<P>
   By hanging someone by their arms, a crucifix forced a victim's
diaphragm to lift the weight of their torso and lower body in order
to raise the abdominal wall and give the lungs room to expand. With
the added weight, that diaphragm slowly exhausts. When it can no
longer expand, the lungs have no room to inflate. Jesus was able to
take in less and less air until he suffocated.
</P>
<P>
   As sadistic as the physics of a basic crucifixion sound, the
Romans had engineered methods to make it worse. By placing a small
hump on the vertical post of the crucifix at the small of the
victim's back, the condemned could save himself, for awhile, by
raising himself onto the hump and taking some weight off his
diaphragm. Eventually, his arms would exhaust and he would sink
back down and start the process of suffocation again.
</P>
<P>
   Christ didn't have this opportunity, and in some small way the
Romans were merciful to him. The nails they pounded through his
ankles would have made it impossible for him to raise himself, and
the whipping, the crown of thorns and the spikes through his wrists
_ pounded not through the delicate tissue of the hands, but between
the sturdier bones that run between the elbow and wrist _ would
also bleed every time he shifted his weight. Taken together, all
these things would have weakened him further and hastened his
death.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it could have been worse. By the time Christ was hung on
the cross, the Romans had plenty of practice honing the science of
crucifixion. They had inherited the method from the Persians, who
had pioneered it about 500 years earlier, according to the Rev. J.
Brabban, chairman of the religion and philosophy department at Palm
Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach, Fla. But instead of a
cross, the Persians lashed the wrists and ankles of the condemned
to the four corners of a device that looked like the letter X.
</P>
<P>
   The Romans raised the crucifix onto a post a few feet above the
ground to better expose the condemned. The point, after all, was
not just to execute, but to torture and to set an example for
others who were considering breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   It was, no doubt, effective. It could take almost a week to die.
But in Jesus' case, ``it was probably over in six hours,'' said
Brabban.
</P>
<P>
   Crucifixion continued as a form of execution through the fourth
century, Brabban said. But by then, with Christianity spreading, it
stopped being used because anyone crucified would appear
Christlike. And the point of an execution, after all, is to kill
people, not to martyr them.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: douglasbelkin(at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
