<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JESUS-GIFTS-COX     12-23 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-GIFTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frankincense and myrrh were like gold in their time
 &HT;    (Eds: The following package on the facts behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today. The
package includes JESUS-LIFE, JESUS-APPEARANCE, JESUS-CRUCIFY,
JESUS-MISTLETOE and JESUS-GIFTS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a little of the magic away from the Magi to be able to
buy frankincense and myrrh for $2.95 in the incense department at
just about any New Age bookstore. But in their day, the Three Wise
Men had a different set of circumstances with which to deal.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, frankincense and myrrh _ not to mention gold _ were
among the most precious commodities in the world. The resins were
collected from trees in Arabia and Africa and carried over land for
hundreds of miles to reach the Middle East. Merchants had to deal
with bandits and, during the Roman empire, very high taxes to get
them to market.
</P>
<P>
   But the trade flourished for more than 2,000 years because the
resins drew fantastically high prices, largely because of the
powers they were said to possess. Frankincense was associated with
divinity and myrrh with suffering. When inhaled, they could help
men get in touch with the divine.
</P>
<P>
   Both scents were used during religious rituals, but they were
also prized as perfumes for courtship. At times they were banned
from non-religious use.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptians would burn frankincense and use the charcoal to
make their black eyeliner. And frankincense was found in the tomb
of Tutankhamen. Queen Sheba and King Solomon both used it and it
was even exported to China during the Ming Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Myrrh, which was often burnt along with frankincense, was used
in the embalming process of the ancient Egyptians. The crude resin
was typically placed inside the hollowed-out body cavity of the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   To harvest frankincense and myrrh, collectors cut the tree
trunks from which they came. From the cuts, resin drips out and
dries under the sun into hard, knobby masses called tears. The oils
from the resins are distilled by steaming the tears.
</P>
<P>
   Today, frankincense and myrrh are used in aromatherapy.
According to promotional literature, the scents can ``evoke
emotional balance in cases of anxiety or stress and are best used
when seeking emotional insight. ... The curling tendrils of burning
frankincense and myrrh have measured the passage of history, and
facilitate the navigation of inner and outer spiritual realms.''
Might make a nice present ...
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: douglasbelkin(at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
