<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JESUS-LIFE-COX     12-23 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-LIFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nazareth of Jesus' time was primitive, perilous
 &HT;    (Eds: The following package on the facts behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today. The
package includes JESUS-LIFE, JESUS-APPEARANCE, JESUS-CRUCIFY,
JESUS-MISTLETOE and JESUS-GIFTS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesus may have been the Prince of Peace, but if his life was at
all typical of his fellow Nazarenes in the first century, he didn't
live like royalty while he was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, he would have lived under the same roof with a
few goats and, maybe, a cow and a couple of sheep. He would have
shared his bedroom with several members of his extended family. And
in the middle of the night, in winter, he probably used the same
chamber pot as the rest of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in first-century Galilee meant working around the
house from the time you were 4 or 5, grinding flour from wheat
grown on your own land and collecting animal dung to burn in the
family fire. It meant bathing weekly and rubbing yourself with
lemon rinds as a deodorant. It meant keeping an eye out for wild
boars when traveling and probably knowing a few people who had been
gored to death.
</P>
<P>
   It meant lugging water from central cisterns shared by everyone
in the community. It meant that if you broke your leg as a child,
you'd probably walk with a limp for the rest of your life.
</P>
<P>
   And according to Eric Meyers, a professor of Judaic studies at
Duke University who has worked on digs around Nazareth for 20
years, it might have meant commuting to work.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jesus was born, Nazareth was rapidly becoming the
bedroom community of Sepphoris, which Herod Antipas _ the Jewish
ruler of Galilee _ declared his capital about the time Jesus was
born. That declaration set off a building boom that continued
throughout Jesus' life.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus and Joseph, along with dozens of other local craftsmen,
probably walked the three miles to Sepphoris to help construct the
homes, many for the wealthy, as well as public theaters and
government centers that were being erected.
</P>
<P>
   While Nazareth had a population of a few hundred and was more of
a hamlet than a town, Sepphoris was probably home to about 15,000
by the middle of the first century, Meyers said. In the last 20
years, archeologists have discovered a theater and about 50
mikvahs, or Jewish ritual baths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very religious community,'' Meyers said. ``Nazareth
was poor to middle class, but Sepphoris would have been a lot
wealthier, maybe middle class to upper class, with a lot more going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Artisans from out of town who were trained in working with
stucco or masonry would likely have lived in Sepphoris to take
advantage of the building boom. And since the city was at the
intersection of several trade routes, foreigners likely passed
through regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Sepphoris eventually grew into a major city and learning center:
The Mishnah, a well-known collection of Jewish laws, was edited
there in the third century. By the eighth century, the city was
taken over by Muslims. And in the 12th century, a decisive battle
that sent the Christians packing and ended the last of the Crusades
took place a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The city was taken over by Israel in 1948 and today is a
national park and one of the most popular tourist sites in Israel.
A replica of a first-century household in Nazareth is under
construction and may open this summer, Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: douglasbelkin(at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
