<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JESUS-MISTLETOE-COX     12-23 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-MISTLETOE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Folk tale says mistletoe, once a full-fledged tree, was used for
Christ's cross
 &HT;    (Eds: The following package on the facts behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today. The
package includes JESUS-LIFE, JESUS-APPEARANCE, JESUS-CRUCIFY,
JESUS-MISTLETOE and JESUS-GIFTS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mistletoe you're trying to get caught under this Christmas
season wasn't always the semi-parasitic plant it is today.
According to an old French folk story, mistletoe used to be a tree
in its own right until it was caught in the wrong place at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   The French folk tale has it that mistletoe was used to make
Christ's cross, and thereafter it was cursed and forced to become a
parasite in order to survive.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the myriad myths that surround this storied
plant. All heal, Birdlime, Devil's Fuge, Golden Bough, Holy wood,
Witches' Broom, Wood of the Cross _ they're all names for
mistletoe, or Phoradendron serotinum, if you prefer the Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Norse mythology has it that mistletoe became associated with
love when an arrow made from its branches was used to kill Balder,
the Norse god of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Balder, the son of Odin and Frigga, had a premonition that he
would die. When he told the other gods about his fears, Frigga, the
goddess of love, exacted an oath from fire, water, metals, stones,
trees, diseases and even poisons not to do any harm to Balder.
</P>
<P>
   The other gods _ being gods _ heard about this pact and began to
slash at Balder with their swords as a tribute to his
imperviousness. Then they fired arrows at him only to watch them
bounce harmlessly away.
</P>
<P>
   But Balder's enemy, Loki, found out from Frigga that she had not
exacted an oath from one plant: mistletoe. She considered the plant
too feeble to hurt Balder.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing this, Loki tricked a blind man into shooting an arrow of
mistletoe at the god of peace. The arrow struck Balder in the heart
and killed him. His death saddened the rest of the gods so greatly
that they restored Balder's life. The plant was then given to
Frigga who dedicated it as a symbol of peace between enemies and
love between friends.
</P>
<P>
   Frigga, legend has it, decreed that anyone passing beneath a
sprig of mistletoe must seal that love with a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: douglasbelkin(at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
