NYT-12-23-99 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHRISTIAN-MUSIC24-COX     12-23 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-MUSIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 Christian artists who made a difference in the '90s
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The '90s brought unprecedented growth in
contemporary Christian music, with more artists than ever finding
mainstream success.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of the names: Amy Grant, Kirk Franklin, BeBe and
CeCe Winans, Michael W. Smith, Jars of Clay, Sixpence None the
Richer. Thanks to a sentimental song he wrote for his daughter's
high-school graduation, Bob Carlisle became the first contemporary
Christian artist to hit No. 1 with an album, ``Butterfly Kisses
(Shades of Grace).''
</P>
<P>
   According to SoundScan Inc. figures reported by the Gospel Music
Association in July, sales of Christian music the first six months
of 1999 showed a 21 percent increase over 1998. SoundScan numbers
place Christian music fifth in size in '98, with 6.8 percent of the
market, behind R&AMP;B, rap, country and soundtracks and bigger than
metal, jazz, classical, Latin and new age.
</P>
<P>
   As the decade winds down, it seems the right time to look at
some of the personalities who helped stimulate the growth.
</P>
<P>
   When you choose any top 10, you set yourself up for second
guessing. (How dare you leave out Lawrence Welk from the best TV
hosts of the 20th century?) But in the spirit of VH1's ``The
List,'' we will press on, offering three criteria:
</P>
<P>
   _ Each had to be someone you might have heard about, so the
movers and shakers who stayed behind the scenes were mostly
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's not only influence, but how you use it. Sales of records
couldn't be enough. Artists had to have something else to earn the
title ``influential.''
</P>
<P>
   _ They still had to be having an impact on music at the end of
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   1. dc Talk: Toby McKeehan, Kevin Max and Michael Tait have
changed the face of Christian music, while growing musically and
constantly broadening their fan base. Recently specializing in
densely layered melodies that lyrically address issues where faith
confronts lifestyle, dc Talk's existence as a group _ two whites
and an African-American, sharing equal billing _ spoke volumes in
their early days as a rap group in the late '80s, when contemporary
Christian music tended to be pretty white and bland. They have
taken the push for racial equality into their lyrics _ ``Colored
People'' was a Beatlesque plea for harmony and one of the
most-played songs of the late '90s. It doesn't hurt that Max and
Tait have two of the best voices in any genre. dc Talk may not have
the highest sales in the decade, but these Jesus freaks, probably
more than anyone else, made it possible for eclectic voices to be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   2. Michael W. Smith: This blue-eyed dynamo turned out four gold
and one platinum album in the '90s, and his November release,
``This Is Your Time,'' sold more than 120,000 units in its first
week _ a record for contemporary Christian music. But Smith also
penned music for a bunch of other projects, this year becoming the
first Christian artist to receive the ASCAP Golden Note Award for
lifetime achievement in songwriting. He also began his own record
company, Rocketown, that seeks to re-create the early familylike
Christian music atmosphere for singer/songwriters. The first artist
signed, Chris Rice, already has had two hit albums and remains
committed to his own youth ministry. Still, this year's Gospel
Music Association's artist of the year seems very rooted as a
husband, father and friend. Kids retain a special place in his
heart. In Dayton early this month for the Amy Grant Christmas
concert, he met with pastors, youth workers and Christian music
promoters to discuss his Rocketown outreach, which, according to
its mission statement, seeks to meet ``the social, spiritual and
physical needs of disenfranchised adolescents.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Kirk Franklin: Whether it's with the Family, God's Property
or ``The Nu Nation Project,'' this diminutive man stomps the
competition and breaks down barriers every time he releases a CD.
With a past that shows he understands the temptations an urban kid
undergoes _ abandoned by his teen-age mother and raised by an aunt
_ he's become, according to no less an authority than Rolling Stone
(on its Web site, www.rollingstone.com), ``the most popular gospel
singer of the 1990s, responsible for selling millions of albums
through his talent and charisma, while almost single-handedly
bringing inspirational African-American music to the masses.'' One
way he's done that is to invite guest artists, from energetic kids
to Bono to Mary J. Blige to Crystal Lewis, to join him. Only about
30, he's shown himself to be someone worth leaning on.
</P>
<P>
   4. Amy Grant: What is it about Amy Grant that has kept her in
the limelight for more than two decades? It's not her musical
ability, though her voice is as easy to take as her beauty. Nor is
it her songwriting, which is often underrated. Her '91 release,
``Heart in Motion,'' went five times platinum, thanks to the first
monster crossover hit of the decade, ``Baby Baby,'' about her
daughter Millie. Perhaps her main appeal is her humanity and her
ability to both receive grace and extend it to others. On a good
night on stage, she seems to make eye contact with every person in
the room, to make each feel important. The vulnerability shown on
'97's ``Behind the Eyes'' was courageously uncommon in Christian
music, and it was almost painful to listen to. Even after her
well-publicized divorce from singer/songwriter Gary Chapman, many
remain fiercely protective of Grant, an uncommon occurrence in the
Christian music community.
</P>
<P>
   5. Steven Curtis Chapman: SCC may well be the artist of the
decade in Christian music. With 39, he has practically owned the
Gospel Music Association's Dove Awards, being recognized by his
contemporaries virtually every time he sneezes. According to the
Dec. 20 CCM Update trade publication, Chapman finished with 11 of
the top 100 songs on the end-of-decade Christian adult contemporary
airplay chart, including No. 1, 1992's ``The Great Adventure.'' He
also scored the top two on the '99 AC airplay chart with ``Dive''
and ``Speechless.'' He's a singer/songwriter with a knack for
finding the perfect hook and for writing songs the Christian
community can identify with. He makes it seem so simple, he may be
sold short. Only in his 30s, Chapman is unlikely to go out quietly
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   6. Steve Taylor: Sometimes called ``the clown prince of
Christian music,'' this tall, lanky dude knows how to offend
Christian ``clones'' as well as spark laughs. But hardly anybody
can argue with the results of his Squint label, which he started a
couple of years ago in connection with the Word Music Group. His
label specializes in those groups that don't easily fit the
Christian music stereotype. But it's the success of Sixpence None
the Richer, named Breakthrough Group of 1999 by R&AMP;R magazine, that
shows Taylor's ability to identify artists that can be marketed far
and wide. Thanks to a little love song called ``Kiss Me,''
Billboard's No. 6 pop song of the year, in coming months you'll see
lead singer Leigh Nash's mug all over TV and magazines, which, come
to think of it, is preferable to seeing Taylor's.
</P>
<P>
   7. Point of Grace: This group has had unprecedented success
since its self-titled 1995 debut release. With at least 20
consecutive No. 1 radio singles, gold and platinum albums and three
books, the four women of Point of Grace began perfecting their
airtight harmonies and easy-listening sound in 1991 while on an
Arkansas college campus. They have all married now and started
having kids, but their music continues to encourage people to stay
the spiritual course. They also helped take the message that
abstinence is an option to thousands of teen-age girls early on.
Though some in the mainstream laughed, look how the movement has
caught on. Girl power? Oh, yeah.
</P>
<P>
   8. Rich Mullins: Like Keith Green and Mark Heard before him,
this Ragamuffin left this world much too soon, dying in an
automobile accident in September 1997. Like Green and Heard, he
made no attempt to hide his discomfort with the modern Church's
focus on self-indulgence. He left Nashville, Tenn., eventually
settling on a Navajo reservation to teach reading. Mullins had an
understanding of God's grace only a forgiven sinner could gain, and
that the same man who could worship an ``Awesome God'' could also
accuse God of playing ``Hard to Get'' is what drew troubled souls
to him _ and through him to Christ. His best work, ``The Jesus
Record,'' was released posthumously, and completing that project
birthed A Raggamuffin Band, which releases its first CD without
him, ``Prayers of a Ragamuffin,'' Tuesday. The group seems
determined to carry on his mission and his message.
</P>
<P>
   9. Jars of Clay: Nobody could have predicted the flood of
publicity that would attend the unexpected mainstream success of
the group's single, ``Flood,'' off its '95 debut project. dc Talk
may have paved the way for other rock and hip-hop groups, but Jars
opened a modern-rock superhighway. With unprecedented access to a
young audience and with a message that may have seemed alien to it,
Jars of Clay handled the pressure without cracking. The band's
third effort, ``If I Left the Zoo,'' recently released to critical
acclaim. If the dc boys go their separate ways early in the new
millennium, as is widely expected, Jars of Clay are the heirs
apparent to the male-group throne in Christian music.
</P>
<P>
   10. CeCe Winans: The voice would be enough. But besides
communicating heaven every time she opens her mouth, Winans has
been an influential good friend to the likes of Whitney Houston,
and she's started her own label, Wellspring Gospel, for artists _
like her _ who don't fit easily into a marketing niche (R&AMP;B, pop,
rock). According to an interview in this month's CCM magazine, she
also wants to use the label as a platform for positive urban music
for young people. BeBe's sister may just be getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
