   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DAVIES (Undated) _ John Paton Davies, a leading diplomat
who was among the ``old China hands'' driven from the State
Department after Sen. Joseph McCarthy questioned their loyalty and
labeled them Communist sympathizers in the 1950s, died Thursday at
his home in Ashville, N.C. He was 91. Davies and about a dozen of
the country's most eminent China scholars and diplomats found
themselves accused of having ``lost China'' after Mao Zedong's
Communist forces defeated Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists, who
enjoyed the support of the American government. By Michael T.
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-BABIES (Houston) _ They found the first baby in a
hospital bathroom, a crying newborn whose mother had disappeared.
Five days later a family awoke to find another newborn, still
bloody from birth, placed on their front porch. A third baby turned
up a month later, and then a fourth was found abandoned on a city
street. The cases kept coming until the number reached 13. Without
any apparent pattern, the Houston metropolitan area has experienced
an unprecedented rash of abandoned babies in the past year. The
problem has baffled local officials, who say an ordinary year might
bring two or three cases. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CREW-EDUC (New York) _ A sharply-divided Board of Education
voted Thursday not to extend the contract of Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew, heralding the end of Crew's sometimes rocky tenure as
the head of the nation's largest public school system. (Summary
from wires) By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-INDUSTRY (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The German government
endorsed plans on Thursday that would allow banks and insurers to
sell their holdings in other German companies without paying taxes
on the profits. The proposal strikes at the very heart of Germany's
impenetrable corporate structure, which has been built around a web
of cross-ownership between banks, insurers and industrial
conglomerates. German banking and insurance stocks soared on the
news. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
