<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Bush's silence on census draws fire from right, left
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The controversy over how to count the population
for the 2000 Census is threatening to ensnare Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the next president will give the states
population figures that have been adjusted by the Census Bureau
after the traditional head count. Proponents say that the figures,
adjusted using a process called statistical sampling, will give a
truer picture of the population and particularly of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of sampling say that only an actual count of the
population should be used to draw electoral districts and
distribute federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's response has so far been silence, which has angered
people on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to have it both ways,'' said Matt Glavin,
president of the Atlanta-based Southeastern Legal Foundation. The
public interest law firm has successfully sued the government to
prevent the adjusted numbers from being used to determine how many
seats in the U.S. House of Representatives go to each state.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic members of congressional caucuses representing
African-Americans, Hispanics and Asian-Americans also asked Bush to
take a position. ``We ask you to end your silence on this issue,''
said a letter that was signed by Democratic Reps. Carrie Meek of
Florida and Charles Gonzalez of Texas and Delegate Eni Faleomavaega
of American Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you stand with those who would deny minorities, children
and the poor fair representation and economic benefits for purely
partisan political reasons?'' the letter added.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma for Bush is that he is making a determined effort to
attract Hispanic support and yet not alienate his Republican base.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic groups, like other advocates for minorities, support
the use of sampling because they believe it will correct the
massive undercount that plagued the 1990 Census.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans, including the majority of Republicans in the
U.S. House who support Bush, oppose sampling on philosophical and
political grounds. They argue that sampling is unconstitutional and
fear that Democrats would gain from its use since sampling would
likely increase the numbers of traditionally Democratic minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is going ahead with sampling all
purposes other than apportionment, including redrawing electoral
boundaries and population-based formulas for federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   The data, however, will not be sent until April 1, 2001, or
three months after the next president takes office.
</P>
<P>
   This explains the emergence of this issue in the GOP campaign.
Bush's refusal to answer is ``unconscionable,'' Glavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker repeated the governor's standard
line on the issue when she was asked specifically whether he would
allow the use of the adjusted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes everybody should be counted,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other Republican candidates have taken a stand. Gary
Bauer, Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes said they would not send the
adjusted numbers to the states. John McCain has said that he would.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. BALLOT BATTLE MOVES INTO COURT
</P>
<P>
   McCain filed a lawsuit in New York last week to make it easier
for candidates to get on the ballot for the state's March 7
primary. New York is legendary for its arcane ballot requirements,
which favor well-funded candidates and those who are backed by the
party leadership. Bush is the choice of most of New York's top
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who want to be on the ballot across the state have to
obtain signatures on petitions in each of New York's 31
congressional districts. The petitions often are challenged, and
disqualifications are frequent. A registered voter can sign only
one petition, and the signature must be witnessed by the person
circulating the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a daunting process, and you never know where a mine is
going to go off,'' said Staten Island borough President Guy
Molinari, McCain's leading supporter in New York. ``We're doing our
damnedest, but we're also hoping for some help.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's lawsuit seeks to make it easier for candidates with
``legitimate statewide'' support to appear on the ballot and to
reduce the potential for challenges. As evidence of McCain's
support, his campaign pointed to a new Quinnipiac College poll,
which shows that McCain is the choice of 24 percent of likely
Republican primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said he doubts that McCain can qualify in all 31
districts. In some districts, the campaign has not yet begun
circulating petitions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
