<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7770 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-ADVOCACY-NAT     12-23 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ADVOCACY-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        Small business has many voices in Washington 
 &HT;     By Tania Anderson  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- When a small business owner gets fed up enough to
put money into a Washington advocacy group, they have plenty of
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is notorious for having different kinds of voices to
fight for certain issues on Capitol Hill. And the small business
community is not lacking. Almost every piece of legislation going
through the hands of Capitol Hill politicos affects small business
in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups are preparing the battleground for the proposed
ergonomics rule, health care issues, the death tax and other
regulatory restrictions on small business.
</P>
<P>
   With annual membership dues ranging from $100 to $2,500, why
would a small business owner invest in one of these groups? The
lure is dictated by three factors - the fear of adverse action on
Capitol Hill; an ideological affinity with the group; or some
economic incentive to join.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on the Senate and House small business committees
recognize certain players in Washington when it comes to small
business interests - The National Federation of Independent
Business, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the Small Business Survival
Committee and the National Small Business Union. The leaders of
these groups often get tapped to offer congressional testimony on
certain issues facing the committees.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Tied with the National Rifle Association as the second most
powerful lobbying group in Washington by Fortune magazine, NFIB
lobbies for its 600,000 small business members on a variety of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Its victories include deductions on self-employed health care, a
reduction in the death tax and a cut in the capital gains rate.
</P>
<P>
   NFIB has been lead by Jack Ferris for the last seven years and
has made his mark fighting against government-mandated health care
coverage. Dubbed by the press as ``silver-haired and
``acid-tongued,'' Ferris lead a fight to repeal the death tax and
convinced Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich that greater estate
tax relief was a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris' ability to build up a financially powerful lobbying
organization comes from his days as the campaign finance director
for former presidential candidate Lamar Alexander's gubernatorial
campaign in 1978. Ferris also worked as executive director of the
Republican National Finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   NFIB's $4.2 million budget is one of the largest in Washington
association groups. The 1998 budget - the latest numbers available
- is almost double from the previous year. The group also makes
$1.2 million in political campaign contributions, 93 percent going
to Republican candidates, according to the Center for Responsive
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   NFIB celebrates the small business owner on its website by
sprinkling it with small business success stories and anecdotes.
Each day's home page features a large color picture of one of its
members.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce has always had the reputation of
being a big-business advocacy group, but 96 percent of its members
are businesses with 100 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber represents 3 million companies, 3,000 state and
local chambers, 850 business associations and 87 American Chambers
of Commerce abroad. The organization, lead by Thomas Donohue, has
been working to stop Y2K lawsuits, helping companies to find
workers and expanding American exports.
</P>
<P>
   Victories for the last year include putting caps on punitive
damages on Y2K lawsuits for businesses with fewer than 50
employees, stopping Democratic Sen. Ted Kennedy's amendment to
raise the minimum wage by $1 over two years and restoring Medicare
funding to service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, the chamber's president and chief executive since 1997,
is credited with putting some life back into an organization that
lost its spark in the early 1990s. He expanded the organization
from three lobbyists to 17 and increased the chamber's annual
budget from $60 million to $90 million in the last two years. The
chamber also reports $31,151 in political campaign contributions,
98 percent going to Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's lobbying command started as the head of the American
Trucking Associations. The New York City native also worked as
deputy assistant postmaster general in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber recently secured $24 million from a Washington area
venture capitalist to start an Internet portal for small business
owners.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Survival Committee may sound like some
militant activist group, but the SBSC is regarded as a serious
Washington player among advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   The group, established five years ago, has more than 50,000
members representing both entrepreneurs and small business owners.
The main focus on its two leaders is to fight against ``unchecked
regulation and burdensome taxes imposed on America's small business
sector and workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   The group is often called to Capitol Hill to testify before the
Senate and House small business committees. The latest testimonials
from its chairman, Karen Kerrigan, range from pushing for small
business start-up accounts to electricity deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   SBSC was one of the only small business interests represented at
the most recent Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce meeting
in San Francisco. The commission is mandated by Congress to find a
solution to the issue of taxing Internet commerce by April 2000.
Chris Wysocki, the newly-appointed president of SBSC, gave one of
13 presentations and pushed for a permanent ban on taxes on
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan's name appeared on National Journal's 1995 short list
of Washington's conservative lobbyists under age 40 who will most
likely make a difference on Capitol Hill soon after she started
SBSC in 1994. Kerrigan previously worked as the national field
director of the Council for Citizens Against Government Waste and
headed the Taxpayer's Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   Wysocki joined SBSC four months ago to increase the membership
base by establishing cross-marketing agreements with other
companies that provide discounts on goods and services like
shipping and pre-paid legal insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The group's 1998 expenditures hit $600,000, a significant
increase from the $100,000 it spent in lobbying the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   National Small Business United, started in 1937, helped initiate
the White House Conference on Small Business, where 20,000 small
business owners crafted 60 recommendations designed to address
issues facing small business and forwarded to Congress and
President Clinton in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   NSBU's priorities include tax reform, entitlement reform and
payroll tax relief and improving pension options for small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is represented by a board of 32 small business
owners and lead by NSBU's president, Todd McCracken, who has
testified on Capitol Hill on the Small Business Year 2000 Readiness
Act.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways the group raises money is through the Small
Business Victory Fund, which endorses candidates with a record of
support for small business or are former small business owners
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
