<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Dec. 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A powerful jet stream disturbance, driven by winds over 170 mph,
will cross the Appalachians Friday. This will induce low pressure
over the Carolinas, which will bring a bit of light snow to the
Smokey Mountains and parts of the North Carolina piedmont.
Meanwhile, high clouds and cooler winds will follow a cool front in
Florida as morning showers depart southern sections.
</P>
<P>
   An exceptionally cold air mass both aloft and at the surface
will swing eastward from the Ohio Valley into the Northeastern
states. As a result, snow showers will be common near the eastern
Great Lakes and over the higher terrain of New England.
Temperatures will average about 10 degrees lower than Thursday, and
a brisk breeze will raise the risk of frostbite during lengthy
exposure outside.
</P>
<P>
   In the central states, milder air will push eastward from the
upper Plains, but cold air will be stubborn to depart the upper
Midwest. Clouds will be abundant from the eastern Dakotas to the
western Great Lakes. Sunshine and light winds will mark a warming
trend in the central Plains. A disturbance over northern Mexico
should keep low clouds and drizzle over the Rio Grande Valley. Some
clouds will advance into southern New Mexico and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure, crested over Idaho with a central
pressure of nearly 31 inches of mercury, will dominate conditions
over the western half of the nation. Very mild air will circulate
from the Southwest into the northern Rockies. Gusty canyon winds
will persist in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Jet Stream
</P>
<P>
   Weather balloons launched in the Ohio Valley on Wednesday
measured winds over 200 mph at 35,000 feet. A wide river of very
fast moving air was located from the southern Plains to New
England. This jet stream was driven by a huge temperature contrast
between arctic air in the Midwest and the remnants of autumn warmth
off the East Coast. The density difference between these air masses
causes air pressure to decrease more rapidly with height in the
colder air mass. This leads to strong pressure differences at high
altitudes. These strong pressure differences produced the fierce
winds.
</P>
</TEXT>
