<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SHOPLIFTING25-COX     12-23 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPLIFTING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Saturday, Dec. 25
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Holidays busy season for shoplifters
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a gangbuster holiday season for retailers, but
it's also one for shoplifters.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves, including store employees, are lifting everything from
athletic shoes to CDs, which rank among the nation's most stolen
items, according to a study conducted by Loss Prevention
Specialists Inc., a consulting group in Winter Park, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   And they're doing it at a time when stores are struggling to
find enough personnel to staff their aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are less vigilant (in spotting shoplifters) because
they're busy,'' said Read Hayes, president of Loss Prevention
Specialists. ``Many are temporary help and may not be well-trained
or motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Murphy, vice president of loss prevention for Wolf Camera,
added, ``As the traffic and volume increases, so does the
shoplifting.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. businesses lose $17 billion to shoplifting and employee
theft each year, Loss Prevention Specialists' 1998-1999 Retail
Theft Trends Report says. The average theft amount per incident was
$60.74, up from $58.43 in the 1997-1998 survey. The thefts account
for about 2 percent of retailers' gross sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``That adds up to lost profits to the retailer,'' said Don
Taylor, a marketing vice president of the Boca Raton, Fla.-based
Sensormatic Electronics Corp. ``And it ends up costing consumers.''
Sensormatic makes store surveillance and merchandise theft devices.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers pass along their increased costs to patrons, Taylor
said. Among the hardest hit during the holidays are department
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoplifting is a problem,'' said J.C. Penney spokeswoman
Stephanie Brown in Plano, Texas. ``During the holidays, we do beef
up security, but we don't disclose as to what extent. We don't want
to give any hints (to shoplifters).''
</P>
<P>
   To combat the problem, retailers install theft sensors on
merchandise and at doors, hire security guards and use mystery
shoppers. Some businesses are fighting back by installing more
sophisticated surveillance cameras and placing more guards inside
and outside their stores.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the theft, 43 percent, is committed by
employees, according to Sensormatic. That's where mystery shoppers
come into play, said Mark Michelson, president of the Chicago-based
Mystery Shopping Providers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mystery shopper is commonly used to do a cash transaction at
a store and observe what happens to the receipts,'' said Michelson,
who is also president and chief executive of Michelson &AMP; Associates
in Atlanta. Mystery shoppers often wear tiny cameras to record
employee actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more technology we have, the more safeguards we have,''
Michelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 deterrent, Murphy said, is customer service, which he
says lets patrons know salespersons are aware of their presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When retailers do that correctly, that's the best thing to
prevent shoplifters.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
