<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-NYT &LR;      12-23 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY,' starring Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz, Dennis
Quaid, James Woods and Jamie Foxx. Directed by Oliver Stone (R, 160
minutes). Stone's brawling, hyper-macho professional football film
has enough in-the-thick-of-it playing-field action to satisfy the
fantasies of most armchair players. In the style of Stone's ``Wall
Street,'' the movie is also a crude morality play that pits the old
ways versus the new with the veteran coach Tony D'Amato (Pacino)
embodying tradition and a young hot-shot quarterback Willie Beamen
(Foxx) the new. Although the acting is uneven (Ms. Diaz is
disappointing as a tough team owner), and the final scenes are
shamelessly ``Rocky''-ish, the movie delivers a credible,
action-charged vision of the frenzied world of professional sports
as a metaphor for the volatility of American culture (Stephen
Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY,' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Chris
Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan Ball. Directed
by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly finesse Spacey plays
a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who flips his lid for a
teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back on. The midlife
crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director Sam Mendes brings
terrific visual flair and dry humor to this barbecuing of the
bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert timing,
especially Ms. Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the
story spreads itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces
for a devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN MOVIE,' featuring Mark Borchardt and friends.
Directed by Chris Smith (R, 104 minutes). An insightful, funny,
not-to-be-missed documentary about a no-budget Wisconsin filmmaker
who makes a horror film as if his life depended on it. And as Smith
so affectingly reveals, Borchardt's hopes really do hang in the
balance. This knowing and often hilarious look at try-anything
indie filmmaking becomes a moving portrait of one man's uphill
struggle and finds Borchardt often describing success and
prosperity as his goals. Meanwhile, his own life is eloquently
presented as a very different, no less authentic kind of American
Dream (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANNA AND THE KING,' starring Jodie Foster and Chow Yun-Fat.
Directed by Andy Tennant (PG-13, 140 minutes). The same story that
inspired the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical ``The King and I'' is
the basis for this movie about the British schoolteacher Anna
Leonowens (Ms. Foster) who travels to Bangkok in 1862 to educate
the 58 children of King Mongkut (Chow). Although the story has been
given a contemporary multicultural perspective that's critical of
British imperialism, the picturesque film tells essentially the
same story but without the beloved songs, which are badly missed.
Ms. Foster's Anna is another of her nobler-than-thou ice queens,
and Chow's king is authoritative but less than thunderous
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BEING JOHN MALKOVICH,' starring John Cusack, Catherine Keener,
Cameron Diaz and (of course) John Malkovich. Written by Charlie
Kaufman and directed by Spike Jonze (R, 112 minutes). Welcome to
the fun house: in this exhilaratingly quirky first feature by a
stellar video director, the reigning fears and obsessions of a
technology-crazed, voyeuristic culture are given an even wilder
workout than they got from ``The Truman Show.'' Cusack plays a
discouraged puppeteer who accidentally finds a way into Malkovich's
mind. While the ordinary science-fiction plot might go downhill
after revealing its gimmick, this one's inspired craziness goes on
and on. Originality and cleverness abound (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BICENTENNIAL MAN,' starring Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz, Sam
Neill and Oliver Platt. Directed by Chris Columbus (PG, 132
minutes). This year's gushy Christmas card from Robin Williams
follows the 200-year quest of a household robot named Andrew to
become human. Directed by the schmaltzmeister Chris Columbus, who
steered this star through ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' the movie is a
joke-strewn sentimental man-machine allegory determined to make us
feel good about being human and is punctuated by corny speeches
exalting freedom, the joys of sex and the mystery of mortality.
Except for Williams, the acting is strictly of sitcom caliber
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY,' starring Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny.
Directed by Kimberly Peirce (R, 114 minutes). This stunning debut
feature tells the strange and resonant story of Brandon Teena, who
despite being born Teena Brandon went on to create a charismatic
identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately wrenching tale may
sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into Theodore Dreiser's
idea of American tragedy. The film makes it hauntingly real and
even tenderly romantic, with the astonishing acting needed to make
it work. One of the year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES,' starring Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron
and Delroy Lindo. Directed by Lasse Halstrom (PG-13, 125 minutes).
Radically downsized in scope, and its examination of the issue of
abortion greatly softened, John Irving's sixth novel (with a
Dickensian screenplay by the author) has been turned into a lovely
World War II-era fable about a young man venturing out into the
world. Maguire is Homer Wells, a doleful innocent raised in an
orphanage by Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who performs
abortions. Fleeing the institution with a golden young couple (Ms.
Theron and Paul Rudd), he becomes an apple picker. Sentimental but
smart, the movie has the sweetness and narrative drive of a '40s
``David Copperfield'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `CRADLE WILL ROCK,' starring Emily Watson, John Turturro, Ruben
Blades, John Cusack, Joan Cusack, Bill Murray and Vanessa Redgrave.
Written and directed by Tim Robbins (R, 132 minutes). This huge
Depression-era story features well-known figures from Orson Welles
to Nelson Rockefeller to Diego Rivera, and it works them into an
ambitious ``Ragtime''-like tableau. Though too many figures in this
landscape are reduced to naive caricature, Robbins and his
impressive cast bring strong passions to bear upon this (mostly)
true story of a legendary event: the trouble-fraught production of
the banner-waving 1936 agitprop musical ``The Cradle Will Rock'' by
Welles and John Houseman. Robbins and his cast play out all sides
of this event with the certitude that its importance lives on
(Maslin).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     12-23 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: lives on (Maslin).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE END OF THE AFFAIR,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore,
Stephen Rea and Ian Hart. Directed by Neil Jordan (R, 105 minutes).
Jordan's intoxicating version of Graham Greene's 1951 novel, in
which an illicit affair becomes a far greater gamble than either
lover could have imagined. For this fearlessly eclectic filmmaker,
this is one more intelligent, brooding love story with a secret
twist. Fiennes and Ms. Moore breathe life into this story with a
dreamy, erotic intensity that in no way trivializes the film's
underlying ideas about religious faith. Period detail (the setting
is London in the mid-1940s) is sumptuously heightened by the
inspired costume designer Sandy Powell (``Shakespeare in Love'')
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `END OF DAYS,' starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, Robin Tunney,
Gabriel Byrne and Kevin Pollak. Directed by Peter Hyams (R, 118
minutes). The star modestly tackles the role of a new savior who
may just keep mankind free of Satan for the next thousand years.
And that's not even the worst thing about this pointlessly nasty
would-be thriller. The material is so derivative that it amounts to
a tag sale of used parts from better apocalyptic films, with
special credit owed to ``The Exorcist'' for grisly sacrilegious
tricks. Hyams favors a jack-in-the-box approach to delivering shock
value. The star dutifully protects a nice young woman from demonic
forces. But Byrne plays the swaggering embodiment of pure evil and
has the better role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `GIRL, INTERRUPTED,' starring Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie.
Directed by James Mangold (R, 120 minutes). Except for being
several years too old for the role, Winona Ryder, an actress who
oozes high-strung intelligence, is ideally cast as Susanna Kaysen,
a pre-college-age girl who lands in a Cambridge mental institution
in 1967 after a halfhearted suicide attempt. (The movie is based on
Ms. Kaysen's memoir.) The period details are perfect, and Ms. Ryder
has the courage to make her character a pain in the neck. But the
small, introspective movie is nearly stolen by Ms. Jolie as a
charismatic, brutally truth-telling sociopath who becomes Susanna's
best friend (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEN MILE,' starring Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan,
David Morse, Doug Hutchison, Sam Rockwell and Bonnie Hunt. Written
and directed by Frank Darabont (R, 180 minutes). In adapting the
death row drama that Stephen King wrote in multiple installments,
the director of ``The Shawshank Redemption'' could have managed
more economy and fewer talky bits of business around the cell
block. Still, this lengthy film is vivid and well played. Smooth
ensemble acting builds up to the discovery that a gigantic
condemned man (Duncan) is a prisoner with very special abilities,
which gives the film its mixture of religious overtones and mild
horror. Hanks, as a wry Southern prison guard, is so unaffectedly
good that it's redundant to say so (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER,' starring Al Pacino, Russell Crowe and Christopher
Plummer. Directed by Michael Mann (R, 155 minutes). Mann directs
this taut thriller about the tobacco industry whistle-blower
Jeffrey Wigand with pulse-quickening panache. And he illustrates
why, in the corporate climate of the 90s, truth-telling is a
riskier business than it was circa ``All the President's Men.''
While Pacino delivers galvanizing moral outrage as a producer for
``60 Minutes,'' and Plummer wickedly mimics Mike Wallace, Crowe
movingly captures the complexity of Wigand's situation. Shaky
docudrama ethics cloud the film's take on ``60 Minutes.'' But this
is an inordinately well-played thriller, with Mann's stylistic brio
at its best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LIBERTY HEIGHTS,' starring Adrien Brody, Joe Mantegna and Ben
Foster. Directed and written by Barry Levinson (R, 134 minutes).
This semiautobiographical comedy-drama remembering teen-age life,
anti-Semitism and racism in mid-1950s Baltimore is the fourth movie
by Levinson to be set in his native city. A deeply felt nostalgia
trip, the movie adroitly captures the look and social attitudes of
the city 45 years ago. But the screenplay and performances are too
muted for the movie to come to terms with growing pains cushioned
in the nostalgic haze (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MAGNOLIA,' starring Tom Cruise, Melinda Dillon, Philip Seymour
Hoffman, William H. Macy, Julianne Moore, John C. Reilly and Jason
Robards. Written and directed by Paul Thomas Anderson (R, 180
minutes). In ``Magnolia'' the colossally talented Anderson has set
up an artfully orchestrated symphony of intersecting L.A. stories,
with many of the cast members from his ``Boogie Nights'' assembled
to form a charismatic ensemble. The movie is saved from its own
worst ideas by the intimacy of the performances. Its single biggest
surprise is Tom Cruise in the role of a strutting,
obscenity-spouting cult figure named Frank Mackey (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MAN ON THE MOON,' starring Jim Carrey and Danny DeVito.
Directed by Milos Forman (R, 118 minutes). Carrey delivers an
electrifying homage in Forman's vivid re-creation of Andy Kaufman's
too-short and enduringly strange career. In a film that summons its
subject's most memorable creative inventions as a series of
greatest hits, Carrey makes a flawless, uncanny impersonator. But
what is missing here, though it might have been the first thing
expected from an ostensible film biography, is an answer to the
simplest question: Who was Andy Kaufman, and how did he get that
way? (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MANSFIELD PARK,' starring Frances O'Connor and Jonny Lee
Miller. Written and directed by Patricia Rozema (PG-13, 105
minutes). In Ms. Rozema's skillful screen adaptation of Jane
Austen's third novel, the protagonist Fanny Price (Ms. O'Connor)
has been sharpened into a proto-feminist heroine who triumphs over
the materialist, patriarchal values of her wealthy relatives
through a combination of wit, beauty and daring. Without bearing
down too heavily, the screenplay (which incorporates fragments of
Austen's letters and diaries) equates early 19th-century slave
trading with the oppression of women. The message is leavened with
smart humor and warm three-dimensional performances (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ONEGIN,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Liv Tyler and Martin Donovan.
Directed by Martha Fiennes (not rated, 106 minutes). As the
directorial debut of Fiennes' sister Martha, ``Onegin'' diminishes
Alexander Pushkin's epic 19th-century novel ``Evgeny Onegin'' into
a cramped little soap opera whose two stars are painfully
mismatched. While Fiennes acts up a fine storm as the arrogant,
cynical title character who doesn't believe in love, Ms. Tyler, who
plays his romantic nemesis, is an inert cipher. Somehow, even the
grand ballrooms of 1820s St. Petersburg look drab and chintzy
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTA     12-23 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: chintzy (Holden).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SLEEPY HOLLOW,' starring Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci, Miranda
Richardson, Michael Gambon, Jeffrey Jones, Michael Gough and
Christopher Walken. Written by Andrew Kevin Walker and directed by
Tim Burton (R, 110 minutes). This ornate visual fantasy, artfully
concocted using a palette that suggests nuclear winter, has little
to do with Washington Irving's story and everything to do with
Burton's macabre vision. Depp makes a dashing hero as the film's
shy detective, but the story (by the writer of ``Seven'' and
``Fight Club'') is determined to put the ick into Ichabod Crane. A
first-rate cast and extraordinary technical talents are
attention-getting here, but so is the film's penchant for sardonic
beheadings. It's possible to admire Burton immensely for the secret
tenderness and rich imagination of his work without wanting to peer
at the exposed brain stems of his characters (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS,' starring Ethan Hawke, James Cromwell
and Max Von Sydow. Directed by Scott Hicks (PG-13, 130 minutes).
This director's follow-up to ``Shine'' is the cinematic equivalent
of an arty coffee-table book. It is so busy illustrating the story
(with elaborate flashbacks and montage sequences) that it forgets
to be dramatic. Set in the Pacific Northwest in 1950, the movie
looks back to World War II and the charged relationships between
Japanese-Americans and whites on an island north of the Puget
Sound. Hawke is the brooding reporter covering the trial and Von
Sydow the defense lawyer who is the film's official conscience.
Robert Richardson is responsible for the gorgeous cinematography
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `STUART LITTLE,' starring Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie and Jonathan
Lipnicki. Directed by Rob Minkoff (PG, 92 minutes). E.B. White's
1945 children's classic has been adapted into a lovely family film
about a little mouse (the voice of Michael J. Fox) who is adopted
by humans but runs afoul of their fluffy white Persian house cat,
Snowbell (Nathan Lane). The movie creates an enchanted storybook
version of New York and has what may be the most exciting toy boat
race (in Central Park) ever filmed. Thanks to Lane's sly, wise-guy
vocal impersonation, Snowbell nearly steals a movie that is funny
and sweet but never cloying (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SWEET AND LOWDOWN,' starring Sean Penn, Samantha Morton and Uma
Thurman. Directed by Woody Allen (PG-13, 95 minutes). In homage to
the kind of jaunty 1930s jazz that has been heard on many of his
other films' soundtracks, Allen imagines a consummate jazz
character: Emmet Ray (played with gusto by Penn), who can play the
guitar as gorgeously as Django Reinhardt but lacks certain
interpersonal skills when it comes to his private life. Borrowing
attributes of various real musicians, the film turns Emmet into
another one of Allen's cad-geniuses and gives him a long-suffering
mute laundress as a sweetheart. (Ms. Morton works miracles in her
wordless role.) But on the storytelling level, the film remains
flimsy. It's the musical interludes, frequent and lovingly
presented, that keep it alive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TOPSY-TURVY,' starring Allan Corduner and Jim Broadbent.
Directed by Mike Leigh (R, 161 minutes). Leigh's grandly
entertaining ``Topsy-Turvy'' is one of those films that create a
mix of erudition, pageantry and delectable acting opportunities,
much as ``Shakespeare in Love'' did last year. Instead of a
love-struck young playwright, it presents the curiously matched
personalities of the librettist William Schwenk Gilbert and the
composer Arthur Sullivan in the midst of a robust, knowing,
frequently hilarious look at the musical theater over which they
held sway (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TOY STORY 2,' with the voices of Tom Hanks and Tim Allen.
Directed by John Lasseter; a Pixar Animated Studios film (G, 98
minutes). A wonderfully playful sequel, sustaining the first film's
wit and novelty while bringing new sophistication to
computer-generated animation. And here is welcome proof that
Hollywood can still make movies to please audiences of any age or
persuasion. From its opening (a perfectly adorable ``Star Wars''
parody) to its Capraesque conclusion, this is seamless work with
more metaphorical cleverness than that usually found in the toy
bin. Colorful new characters and more adventurous action enhance
the story of how Woody falls into the clutches of a sleazy toy
dealer, experiences new-found celebrity and needs to be rescued by
his fabulous old friends (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TUMBLEWEEDS,' starring Janet McTeer and Kimberly J. Brown.
Directed by Gavin O'Connor (PG-13, 100 minutes). An astoundingly
vital performance by the British actress Janet McTeer makes this
small, beautifully acted slice of contemporary Americana a must-see
film. Ms. McTeer is Mary Jo Walker, a sexy, free-spirited woman
with four marriages behind her who travels across the country with
her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Ms. Brown). Like few other films,
this one captures an intimately loving (though not conflict-free)
relationship between a parent and child without becoming
saccharine. The director plays Mary Jo's trucker boyfriend, who is
only the latest in a series of romantic disasters (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WAR ZONE,' starring Freddie Cunliffe, Ray Winstone, Tilda
Swinton and Lara Belmont. Directed by Tim Roth (not rated, 99
minutes). Roth is an actor known for roles in tough films, but
never for anything quite as raw as this. In this searing first
feature, the title battlefield is a rural English home where a
teen-age boy looks upon his own family with helpless rage and
astonishment. Sensing the incestuous relationship between his
father and older sister, the film's wordless, baleful young hero
struggles to come to terms with this household horror. Understated
but extremely graphic at times, and shot with mournfully expressive
simplicity by Seamus McGarvey (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH,' starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie
Marceau, Dame Judi Dench, Robert Carlyle and Denise Richards.
Directed by Michael Apted (PG-13, 128 minutes). This director is
much admired for his ``Up'' series chronicling the lives of former
schoolchildren as they mature. And he has managed to make James
Bond grow up a little, too. Brosnan has grown much more comfortable
with the role of Bond, and most of the other characters are also
more interesting than might have been expected. Ms. Marceau slinks
memorably through the role of a treacherous oil heiress. Ms.
Richards seemed a lot smarter playing high school vixens than she
does as a brilliant scientist here. The itinerary roams from
Scotland to Central Asia. And Apted handles the action as well as
he does the talk (Maslin). Film Series
</P>
<P>
   `COLUMBIA 75.' With more than a month behind it and three weeks
still to go, Film Forum is past the midpoint of its 75-film
festival celebrating the 75th anniversary of Columbia Pictures. But
there are still plenty of cinematic riches to come. Friday's double
feature consists of two Kim Novak starring vehicles, Joshua Logan's
``Picnic'' (1955), with William Holden, and Richard Quine's ``Bell,
Book and Candle'' (1958), with James Stewart, Ernie Kovacs and Jack
Lemmon. For Saturday and Sunday the attractions are George Sidney's
``Bye Bye Birdie'' (1965) with Ann-Margret and Dick Van Dyke, and
Elliot Silverstein's ``Cat Ballou,'' with Jane Fonda as an outlaw
and Lee Marvin in an Academy Award-winning dual role as a drunken
gunslinger and his tin-nosed evil twin. The series continues
through Jan. 13 at Film Forum, 209 W. Houston St.t, in the South
Village. Admission is $9; $5 for members. Screening schedule and
information: (212) 727-8110 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
