<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REBELLION-BOOK-REVIEW     12-23 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REBELLION-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REBELLION': A WEIMAR-ERA ANTIHERO, CRUSHED BY NAIVETE AND
IMPERSONAL FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disillusionment that followed World War I and was felt all
over Europe saturates ``Rebellion,'' a spare, brooding novel by
Joseph Roth and the last of this brilliantly allegorical writer's
books to be translated into English. Serialized in the German
socialist newspaper Vorwarts in 1924, ``Rebellion'' was the third
of Roth's 15 novels, published after the similarly disillusioned
``Hotel Savoy'' but a decade before his masterpiece of the fallen
Austro-Hungarian Empire, ``The Radetzky March.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebellion'' is reminiscent of Chekhov in its uncluttered,
melancholy simplicity, while its sense of the larger, crushing
incomprehensibility of things echoes Roth's older contemporary,
Franz Kafka. It provides brief, crisscrossing lives of several
characters, though mostly it tells of the short, afflicted span of
Andreas Pum, a war amputee who enjoys a few brief weeks of
happiness before he is crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Crushed by what? That is the question. ``Rebellion'' was written
during what is seen as Roth's leftist period (he later became a
monarchist nostalgic for the defunct Austro-Hungarian Empire), and
so it is reasonable to see this novel as an allegory of the
brutality of capitalist power.
</P>
<P>
   It is in some ways. Roth's Andreas is an unschooled
working-class man ignorant of the means of self-advancement known
to the more privileged castes. He is therefore defenseless against
the middle class' unreasoning fear of the workers, the brutality of
the police, the indifference of the courts and the lurking
anti-Semitism that conflates Jews with Bolsheviks.
</P>
<P>
   But what destroys Andreas Pum is something subtle and mysterious
and not obviously political. It is Andreas' own passivity, for one
thing, his very obedience to the institutions that roll over him
without even noticing him. ``Rebellion'' in this sense is a satire
on a kind of Candidean naivete, a misplaced trust. Andreas' fate is
very different from that of another working-class down-and-out,
Willi, who hustles his way to the top of the heap by virtue of a
criminal aptitude that Andreas doesn't possess.
</P>
<P>
   But what gives ``Rebellion'' its mystifying power is its
depiction of personal fate as governed by the blind, casual
workings of a machine controlled by no one and for which no one is
responsible. Roth's novel in this sense can be read as a
theological statement about the capriciousness of a universe devoid
of a benevolent God. Or it can be read more philosophically, with
Andreas Pum representing one of the first alienated antiheroes of
European literature.
</P>
<P>
   The reader first encounters Andreas in a military hospital at
the end of World War I. His leg has been amputated and he has been
awarded a medal. Far from being emotionally stricken, he feels
proud and superior to the other wounded soldiers, those with ``no
God, no Emperor, no Fatherland,'' whom Andreas calls heathens.
</P>
<P>
   When he is released from the hospital, Andreas' chest decoration
provides him with a certain honor, and he has papers that give him
the right to operate a barrel organ on the street. One day he meets
a widow, Frau Blumich, and he immediately decides that ``there was
no one in the world who meant more to him.'' The widow, stout and
amply endowed, has other suitors, but she chooses Andreas as her
husband not in spite of his war wound but because of it. ``Reason
counseled a bird whose wings had already been clipped, because that
would be easier to keep and required less in the way of strenuous
training.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Andreas' cup becomes full, it is abruptly emptied
because of a capricious chain of circumstance. A certain Herr
Arnold, a well-off businessman, makes a clumsy pass at his
secretary, and the awkward consequences of this gesture put him
into a foul and aggressive mood. Arnold's troubles have nothing to
do with Andreas. But the two of them encounter each other on a
tram, and, as a consequence, Andreas is dragged off to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``But such is the treacherous way of Fate: we are doomed not by
our own fault, and sometimes without our even perceiving a
connection; we are doomed by the blind rage of a stranger with
whose story we are unfamiliar, to whose misfortune we are
unconnected, and with whose opinions we are even in agreement. He
and no other is the instrument in the casually devastating hand of
Destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The terrifying misadventure that befalls Andreas is mirrored and
intensified by Roth's narrative detachment, which is an essential
part of this writer's genius. As Michael Hofmann, the novel's
translator, puts it in a helpful introduction, Roth's sensibility
resembles that of other figures of early Weimar culture, for
example the caricaturist George Grosz, who took ordinary subjects
from ordinary life and gave them monstrous forms.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Grosz, Roth is understated. Yet his simple
narrative sentences tread like jackboots over the reader's
consciousness. When Andreas' wife repudiates him with the words
``wretched cripple,'' she knocks over a plaster vase. ``The water
drained out of it, gurgling, and fell in single melancholy drops
from the edge of the oilcloth cover onto the floor.'' With that
image, one sees the spilling of Andreas' very existence and the
utter absence of redeeming love.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas, in his shock and disillusionment, transforms himself
from a dutiful subject of God and Empire into one of the heathens
he used to scorn, expressing his new awareness in a furious
how-could-You-have-abandoned-me complaint shouted directly to the
Divinity. But while he achieves a kind of enlightenment, it is the
bitter epiphany of philosophical nihilism, one that seems eerily
appropriate in light of what subsequently happened to Roth himself.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he wrote his early novels, Roth was a successful and
well-paid journalist with no evident reason for pessimism. But in
1926, we learn from Hofmann's introduction, he visited the Soviet
Union and soured on the idea of the radiant revolutionary future.
When the Nazis came to power in Germany in 1933, he moved to Paris,
where he turned to drink and died in 1939. The biting pessimism of
``Rebellion'' spookily prefigures Roth's own fate in a Europe that
would crush many more worldly figures than Andreas Pum, and with
far greater savagery and evil purpose.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `REBELLION'
</P>
<P>
   By Joseph Roth
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Michael Hofmann
</P>
<P>
   148 pages. St. Martin's Press. $21.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
