<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANGELA-FILM-REVIEW-NY     12-23 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANGELA'S ASHES': A NEW GLOSS ON POVERTY IN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks poverty is not pretty would think twice after
watching the film version of Frank McCourt's best-selling boyhood
memoir. Not since Walker Evans distilled the mournful beauty of
Appalachia, or at least not since the latest fashion layout flirted
with arty desolation, has misery looked this fabulously pristine.
</P>
<P>
   As reverently directed by Alan Parker, ``Angela's Ashes''
presents the tough tales of McCourt's upbringing while harking back
to a quaintly romantic view of deprivation. So in the Irish setting
where the McCourt family wanted for food, coal and decent housing,
it also happens that graffiti, clutter and nonbiodegradable junk
were also in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' thus unfolds against fading wallpaper
backdrops that coordinate with the characters' tattered clothing;
alongside clotheslines where the prop department has worked wonders
with the laundry; and on rain-slick streets where sewage looks a
handsome shade of midnight blue. The actors radiate health even
when made up to look pallid. Nobody has indoor plumbing. Everybody
has clean hair.
</P>
<P>
   This emphasis on aesthetic niceties, in a film whose tidily
controlled palette keeps any sense of real suffering at bay, allows
``Angela's Ashes'' to offer a cathartic tsk-tsk for the holiday
season. Just as McCourt's readers could laugh and weep vicariously
at his silver-tongued storytelling, so the film invites empathy
from a comfy distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turns toward Mam,'' McCourt wrote of his chronically
unreliable father, ``and she says `You're not sleeping in this bed
tonight.' He makes his way downstairs with the candle, sleeps on a
chair, misses work in the morning, loses the job at the cement
factory and we're back on the dole again.'' There's as much craft
as hardship to a recollection like that.
</P>
<P>
   While readers who made the memoir so popular will miss some of
its grit, they are sure to find the material's essential glossiness
familiar. McCourt summoned his anecdotes with indefatigable charm,
no matter how dire the circumstances, to the point where his
autobiographical story became an exemplary pilgrim's progress.
</P>
<P>
   As adapted by Laura Jones and Parker, the film parades a
succession of trials and milestones for young Frank (played
successively by Joe Breen, Ciaran Owens and Michael Legge) like so
many picture postcards. From young Frank's first confession to the
first shilling he earns to support his family, the film's narrative
is as neat as its look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' follows the McCourt family from New York
City, where they are out of place, back to Limerick, Ireland, where
they find themselves even more so. The stalwart, long-suffering
Angela, played with patience and backbone by Emily Watson, comes
from a family that has no use for her husband Malachy (Robert
Carlyle, making the best of a more problematically written role).
</P>
<P>
   Malachy comes from Northern Ireland, which makes him a virtual
foreigner in Limerick, and Angela's family would in any case not
welcome more mouths to feed. In the first part of this lengthy
film, the family suffers ill will and unspeakable hardship,
including the loss of three young children. The kind of detail that
McCourt so memorably provided, and that the film dutifully
reiterates, is that Malachy committed the ultimate offense by
resting a pint of beer on the tiny coffin of one of his sons.
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to the pain that is described here, the film
isn't wrenching enough to do it justice. The family's suffering,
like the carefully mottled paint on supposedly run-down walls, is
curiously unreal.
</P>
<P>
   For all the scenes in which Angela, with her children in tow,
endures shame and humiliation (``Beggars can't be choosers, Mrs.
McCourt,'' she is literally told when trying to find furniture),
there is a safe and even self-congratulatory predictability in the
film's idea of hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Even the father's drunkenness is somehow sugar-coated, with a
lot of reproachful lines of dialogue (``You drank the money, didn't
you?'' Angela asks while peeling potatoes) and little of the angry,
erratic behavior that goes with this territory.
</P>
<P>
   If Carlyle seems tepid at such times, perhaps that's because
Stephen Rea played nearly the same role with such frightening,
mercurial brilliance for Neil Jordan in ``The Butcher Boy.'' In a
nutshell, the prodigiously talented Jordan (``The End of the
Affair''), with his ability to fuse enchantment and tragedy, is
what ``Angela's Ashes'' is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the scenes recreated here with varying degrees of
authenticity are young Frank's experiences with Roman Catholic
clergymen and teachers (believably captured) to his sexual
coming-of-age at the absolute insistence of a beautiful, available
young woman (preposterous as filmed, even if it really happened).
</P>
<P>
   Details like a sheep's head for Christmas dinner, or the McCourt
family's being forced to live downwind of the neighborhood
outhouse, are among those that prompt ``Angela's Ashes'' to make
the deplorable and the sentimental one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `ANGELA'S ASHES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alan Parker; written by Laura Jones and Parker,
based on the book by Frank McCourt; director of photography,
Michael Seresin; edited by Gerry Hambling; music by John Williams;
production designer, Geoffrey Kirkland; produced by Scott Rudin,
David Brown and Parker; released by Paramount Pictures/Universal
Pictures International.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Emily Watson (Angela), Robert Carlyle (Dad), Joe Breen
(Young Frank), Ciaran Owens (Middle Frank) and Michael Legge (Older
Frank) and Shane Murray Corcoran (Young Malachy).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Angela's Ashes'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity,
traumatic moments and brief, occasional nudity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
