<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., N.Y.)  (bl) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 C.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN A RECTORY ATTIC, A DEL SARTO
</P>
<P>
   In the early decades of this century, Clara Winthrop, a
parishioner at All Saints Episcopal Church in West Newbury, Mass.,
bequeathed a painting of a Madonna and Child to the church. Until
recently, officials at All Saints thought it was a copy of a work
by Andrea del Sarto, the Italian old master painter and draftsman,
and that it dated from around 1800.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, an oil on panel, hung in the choir stall until
about 20 years ago, when it was stored in the rectory attic.
Curious to know exactly what they had, church officials called in
Christopher Apostle, senior vice president in the old master
paintings department at Sotheby's, to examine the painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the old documents said it was a copy, when I saw the
painting I realized it was high-quality and from the 16th
century,'' Apostle said.
</P>
<P>
   He called in scholars, and together they examined the painting
with infrared reflectography, a method that reveals the drawing
beneath the painting's surface. All the experts agreed ``Madonna
and Child'' was painted by del Sarto.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sotheby's in New York plans to auction the ``Madonna and
Child'' on Jan. 28. The painting is expected to bring $1 million to
$1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Del Sarto was a great proponent of drawing, and the
underdrawings were typical of the way he worked,'' Apostle said.
Examining the painting with infrared equipment, the experts saw
evidence of del Sarto's method. He was known for first making a
detailed, full-size drawing, then blackening the back of it with
carbon. He pinned the drawing to a panel as if were like tracing
paper, then used a stylus to trace the design onto the panel before
painting.
</P>
<P>
   A preparatory drawing for the head of the Madonna is in the
National Gallery of Art in Washington. The painting's composition,
Apostle said, is similar to several versions by the artist, of
which the best-known is in the permanent collection of the National
Gallery of Canada in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   In the work Sotheby's is selling, the Virgin stands behind a
parapet holding a book in her right hand and supporting the infant
Christ with the other. As in the version in Ottawa, the viewer can
see where the artist changed his mind. The position of the child's
fingers, for example, has been visibly altered. ``This discovery is
significant in the old master world,'' Apostle said. ``Del Sartos
don't come up every day.''
</P>
<P>
   SHISEIDO GIFT TO NYU
</P>
<P>
   The Grey Art Gallery at New York University has received a
$500,000 gift from Shiseido, the Japanese cosmetics company, for
its endowment. At the same time the gallery is planning ``Face to
Face: Shiseido Japan 1900-2000,'' an exhibition of the company's
collection of posters, products and package designs, along with its
fine and decorative arts holdings, that explores how the history of
makeup reflects cultural and societal changes in Japan. In addition
to its $500,000 gift, Shiseido is paying for the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics of museum fund-raising have been a sensitive issue
lately, especially with the debate surrounding the Brooklyn Museum
of Art's ``Sensations'' show, which involves art owned by a single
collector, Charles Saatchi. He contributed $160,000 toward the
exhibition, and many people say the show will increase the value of
his art.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum announced that it
would mount a major retrospective of fashions by Giorgio Armani
that is to be sponsored by In Style, a magazine in which Armani
advertises. Eight months earlier the Guggenheim had reached what it
calls a ``global partner sponsorship arrangement'' with Armani,
something it did not mention when the show was announced. The
fashion company is reported to have given the museum $5 million and
promised $10 million more over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing comments by Guggenheim officials, Lynn Gumpert, director
of the Grey Art Gallery, says she would have organized the Shiseido
show regardless of the company's donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with experts who say you have to be extremely careful
because you don't want to compromise the integrity of the programs
at the Grey or mission of the institution,'' she said. ``But I am
convinced this is not the case. The material from Shiseido is
fantastic. It traces the history of how Western culture and art was
imported to Japan, bringing up issues of gender and of how one
perceives beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gumpert said the budget for the show had yet to be
determined. ``They did a similar show at the Musee des Arts
Decoratifs in Paris three years ago, which Shiseido also paid
for,'' she added. The money for the gallery's endowment is the
``first really sizable gift we've had for the endowment in 25
years,'' she said. ``It was given to celebrate Shiseido's 10th
anniversary in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW CURATOR AT MOMA
</P>
<P>
   For months there have been rumors that Gary Garrels, the chief
curator and curator of painting and sculpture at the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art, was trying to choose between job offers from
the Whitney Museum of American Art and Museum of Modern Art, both
in New York. Last week the Modern announced his appointment: in
April, Garrels is to become the Modern's chief curator of drawings
and a curator of painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in San Francisco said they planned an international
search for his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW LEAVES ARMORY
</P>
<P>
   A so-called armory show will no longer be held at an armory. The
International Fair of New Art, which was first held in February at
the 69th Regiment Armory at Lexington Avenue and 26th Street in
Manhattan, has grown so big that its second version will be held at
the North Pavilion, at 11th Avenue and 39th Street, a new structure
at the north end of the Javits Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the dealers wanted big booths to best show off the
works,'' said Tom Delavan, director of the fair, who added that the
pavilion's proximity to Chelsea was a big factor in choosing the
new site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
