<HEADER>
A7796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     12-23 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUM OF THE WEEK: RODNEY WHITAKER QUINTET'S `BALLADS AND BLUES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Album of the Week &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RODNEY WHITAKER QUINTET: ``Ballads and Blues: The Brooklyn
Session'' (Criss Cross).
</P>
<P>
   The first two albums by Rodney Whitaker, the bassist for the
Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, were valentines to his hometown,
Detroit; he surrounded himself with players he had known before
moving to New York, mixing them in with his new colleagues. The
albums were ambitious and a little unwieldy and often lost focus
and balance with so many different kinds of players.
</P>
<P>
   But his third, ``Ballads and Blues,'' has a streamlined,
economized sound, the benefit of players who know one another. It
includes some of the best young musicians in jazz: the saxophonist
Ron Blake, the vibraphonist Stefon Harris, the pianist Eric Reed
and the drummer Carl Allen. Although Whitaker has included a number
of songs by bassists _ three by Paul Chambers, one by George
Duvivier _ it's not a thematic record. The album has the ring of
the late '50s and early '60s, when great jazz musicians were under
contract to produce several albums a year, and a huge number of
high-quality records that weren't particularly high-concept were
recorded, thus creating the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The jazz mainstream has two aspects: there's the flat and the
dull, and then there's a form of comfort within traditional
language that allows musicians to let themselves go, which is what
happens here. Allen fills his sound with cymbal-heavy swing; Blake
plays long, connected, rapid lines that accrue an intellectual
weight as they go along; Harris steps out of rhythm to play dots of
sound in strange intervals; and Reed, an alert player, gets into
tumbling waves of rolled chords.
</P>
<P>
   The trombonist Wycliffe Gordon shows up on a few tracks, too,
chattering his solos and using a mute to sound like a singer. The
current anxiety emanating from jazz records _ the need to make a
new sound stick, the dips into stylized retro, the nervous desire
to connect with pop _ is, to our pleasure, nowhere to be found
here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
