</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TALKING WILL CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no end to ``The Vagina Monologues,'' and come
February the lone voice of Eve Ensler may be replaced by a
star-filled ensemble of some her biggest fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monologues,'' the provocative show about the majesty and
mystery of that eponymous body part, was tentatively scheduled to
close at the Westside Theater on Jan. 23, when Ms. Ensler, its
creator and sole performer, leaves to work on a new play. But a
production member, who has been part of negotiations, said the show
would continue, assisted by a roster of actresses including Winona
Ryder, Rosie Perez and Gillian Anderson, of ``X-Files'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   David Stone, the producer, would not comment on specific plans
for the show, but he confirmed that several options _ and actors _
were being considered. The production member said the show would
probably reopen, appropriately, around Valentine's Day, and would
feature sets of three women. Each woman will perform a handful of
the piece's 14 monologues. Each group will stay in the show for two
weeks. Twenty percent of the proceeds are to go to V-Day, a charity
that contributes to a variety of women's causes.
</P>
<P>
   The new undertaking will be heavy on feminine star power,
attracted by the show's popularity among women as well as the
relative ease of a two-week commitment (a form of commitment long
popular with the male of the species). Other actresses who have
been in discussions for two-week stints include Marisa Tomei, Kathy
Najimy, Marlo Thomas, Amy Irving, Andrea Martin, Gina Gershon,
Shirley Knight, Ricki Lake and Kristen Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT RUN IN `INCH'
</P>
<P>
   The post-mortem was continuing this week on the short, troubled
tenure of Ally Sheedy in the musical ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch.''
Ms. Sheedy left the show after Saturday's performance, roughly six
weeks before her contract was to expire. Producers said the
decision was mutual; but reached at her home on Tuesday, Ms. Sheedy
seemed upset by the experience. But she had little comment on the
circumstances. ``I'm just trying to get through all of this,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In September Ms. Sheedy took on the part of Hedwig, a catty
transvestite and overlooked East German rock star. The move was
risky for the show, as Ms. Sheedy had little singing experience and
was the first woman to try a role written for a man. Those fears
were confirmed when she received mixed reviews, and ticket sales
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Her manager, Neil Koenigsberg, said later that Ms. Sheedy had
enjoyed her stay with the show. ``They hired her, and she went
onstage,'' he said. ``She had fun.'' Matt McGrath, who was an
understudy for the role in Los Angeles, has taken it over in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   As for the show itself, at the Jane Street Theater, there are
reports that it may soon wind down its nearly two-year run, perhaps
by February. (The Los Angeles production closed last week.) Susanne
Brinkley, a producer of ``Hedwig,'' denied that any date had been
set but cautioned that ``like any show that's been running for a
long time, we're always looking at the show's sales and health.''
</P>
<P>
   THAT BUSY NATHAN LANE
</P>
<P>
   With plans for a springtime production of ``Wise Guys,'' the new
Stephen Sondheim musical, postponed indefinitely, the cast has been
looking for work. But when you're Nathan Lane, that doesn't take
long.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in June Lane will be appearing at the newly
refurbished Selwyn Theater in the Roundabout Theater Co.'s
production of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner,'' the wicked 1939
comedy by Moss Hart and George S. Kaufman. Lane, who has been known
to inspire a giggle or two, will be playing Sheridan Whiteside, the
irascible New York writer and critic (of all things) who fractures
his hip on the front steps of an Ohio family's home and proceeds to
make the family miserable for the rest of the play. (His opening
line? ``I may vomit.'') Monty Woolley originated the role.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said that after the disappointment of ``Wise Guys'' he
needed a little comedy. ``It's the perfect job,'' he said of his
new role. ``I just sit in a wheelchair and yell at people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Zaks will direct.
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP SHAKESPEARE
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare wasn't the first choice for the gang of student
rappers behind ``Bomb-itty of Errors,'' a hip-hop adaptation of
``Comedy of Errors.'' They originally thought of doing Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought in `The Trial,''' said Jordan Allen-Dutton, 22. ``It
didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was Shakespeare who got bomb-ittyed instead. The idea was
Gregory J. Qaiyum's. He started the enterprise as an independent
project at New York University's Experimental Theater Wing. Qaiyum,
23, gathered four collaborators: Allen-Dutton, Jason Catalano, Erik
Weiner and Jeffrey Qaiyum, his brother, all of whom were students
at New York University. (Jeffrey, 20, still is.)
</P>
<P>
   Working on a slapdash schedule of midnight-to-dawn rehearsals,
they translated the iambic vernacular into modern language and set
it to hip-hop's rhyming couplets. (A suitor to his love: ``I'll
serenade ya in Spanish, woo you in Swahili,/Ask you in German,
``Was ist die dealy?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The first full run-through was opening night,'' said Weiner,
22. ``It was rough. But our teachers said, `You're on to
something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since that first showing in May 1998 ``Bomb-itty'' has traveled
north to a developmental production in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., picked
up a bushel of prominent producers (including Daryl Roth, Hal
Luftig and Michael Lynne) and has leapt to a full off-Broadway run
at the Salon, a spanking new theater at 45 Bleecker St. in the East
Village.
</P>
<P>
   And while the reviews have been mixed, the show has been drawing
large audiences of young theatergoers. ``We get generally two sets
of audience members,'' said Mr. Catalano. ``Those that expect a
play, and those that expect a concert. We try to please both.''
</P>
<P>
   No word, or word up, on the group's next project, but
Shakespeare may be in for it again. ``Maybe `M.C. Beth,''' Weiner
said with a laugh. ``Or `Jamlet.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
