<HEADER>
A7798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RETURNS25-COX     12-23 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETURNS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mad dash begins to exchange those less-than-perfect gifts
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The blue cardigan sweater from Aunt Martha is:
</P>
<P>
   _ The wrong size.
</P>
<P>
   _ Identical to the one she gave you last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Definitely not your style.
</P>
<P>
   _ All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   So chances are you'll be heading to the store, package in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Returns and exchanges aren't the most exciting part of the
holiday season, but there are ways to make the transactions go more
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a return speedier if tags are attached to the
garment,'' says Susie Tokasey, assistant store manager at Stein
Mart. ``Once they've been removed, we'll have to verify the ticket
with the merchandise, which means calling the department.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the price tag has been removed, the identifying
merchandise number may still be intact.
</P>
<P>
   Tokasey says many of today's gift-givers include receipts with
their gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot more receipts coming back,'' she says.
``Customers realize if you don't have the receipt you'll receive
the current selling price and after Christmas most things are
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that those who feel awkward including a receipt
offer to return the gift themselves.
</P>
<P>
   During the holidays, most stores will take back items _ even if
they haven't been purchased locally _ as long as its merchandise
sold in the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we own it in our inventory, we will take it back,'' says
Dan Bukey, vice president and regional director of stores for
Elder-Beerman, who adds that sales staff is increased in the weeks
before and after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who aren't exchanging a size may want to postpone
their returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most stores have a 30-day return policy, so if you're not in a
rush, why put yourself through the headache of waiting in line?''
asks one toy store sales manager. At a toy store, he explains, it's
especially important for all boxes and packaging to be returned
with the item.
</P>
<P>
   Tokasey says most stores view returns as an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times people will bring things back to exchange or
return and find more things and spend more money,'' she says.
``It's an opportunity for us to increase sales.''
</P>
<P>
   For some customers, the return experience can turn out to be a
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably, someone might get two of the same Pokemon thing
and bring one back,'' he says. ``Perhaps it's something that
someone else couldn't find before Christmas!''
</P>
<P>
   TO MAKE EXCHANGES LESS FRUSTRATING:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep all tags, packaging and instructions and return them with
the merchandise. When possible, have the receipt as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the return policy of the store. Most allow 30 days for
returns and exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you don't have a receipt, expect to receive the current
selling value of the merchandise. Without the receipt, you'll
probably receive a store credit. Be certain to note the expiration
date of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be patient. Remember that store clerks are weary, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
