<HEADER>
A7799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-23 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ROYAL HAIRCUT
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Bai Ling walked into the Urth Cafe, a trendy coffee
shop on Melrose Avenue, and lifted her dark eyes and improbable
cheekbones into the air as if savoring the scents of chai tea and
cappuccino. But it was her hair that was on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to cut it all off; it was very difficult,'' said Ms.
Ling, the Chinese-born actress who plays a crucial supporting role
as the king's youngest and unfaithful wife in the recently released
``Anna and the King.'' She patted her head every few seconds,
feeling for the curls that wrapped around her ears and almost
willing the four-inch locks to grow faster. ``Before the movie I
had hair so long that I could sit on it,'' she said. ``Down to
here. I like to look beautiful and sexy. But for the movie it had
to all come off. I never felt so naked.''
</P>
<P>
   It is never easy for actors whose native language is not English
to carve careers for themselves in Hollywood, where they are often
relegated to villain or femme fatale roles. For every Arnold
Schwarzenegger who pulls it off, there are a dozen Gerard
Depardieus who give it a go and then head back home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ling, who lives on the water at Marina Del Rey (``I must be
near the ocean,'' she said), described her unlikely journey from an
impoverished urban upbringing in southwest China through a stint in
the army in Tibet to movie stardom in China, then a move to New
York University and several years of working as a hostess in
restaurants or as a newscaster on Chinese-language cable stations.
</P>
<P>
   It was her casting as a Chinese lawyer in ``Red Corner,'' a
Richard Gere thriller about an American businessman framed for
murder, that brought her to Hollywood and eventually led to the
current role.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Anna and the King'' her character chops off all her hair
and tries to pass as a monk to be near the young man she loves, who
ran off to the monastery when she was forcibly married to the king.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my agent told me that I would need to cut off my hair for
the movie, I thought: `What? Why?''' she remembered. ``Do they want
me to play the Yul Brynner part?'' But she agreed to do it, she
said, when the role was described to her. And it turned out to be a
wonderful experience, outside of the hair thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do no preparation for my acting, none for my scenes,'' she
said. ``I just keep this very peaceful and calm place inside of me
that I can go to and the emotions come through my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Tennant, who directed ``Anna and the King,'' vividly
remembered the struggle to have the movie's massive sets completed
in the Malaysian countryside after the government of Thailand
decided not to allow the company to film in the country where the
story is set. For the director of such relatively smaller films as
``Ever After,'' starring Drew Barrymore, this movie multiplied
complications by a factor of 10, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first day's shoot was a parade down the main street as Anna
and her son are taken by carriage to the Siamese royal palace.
``The call sheet was 20 pages long,'' Tennant said. ``I mean, the
elephants had a 3 a.m. call.'' And when local children spooked one
of the elephants, it bolted, was cornered and eventually sat down
on a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first day,'' Tennant said. ``I thought, `Uh-oh,
what have I gotten myself into?' But fortunately, it went fine
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The sets were so massive that work continued even as the movie
was shooting; the royal palace was not completed until the film was
practically finished. People hired to fix up the gardens were
simply dressed up as 19th-century Thai gardeners and sent to work
in the background of other shots. ``Otherwise we never would have
gotten done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also vividly recalled the scorching day he filmed one of the
movie's most difficult scenes, in which Ms. Ling and her young
lover are tied to posts before an angry crowd. That's the scene
that stands out in Ms. Ling's memory, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hot,'' she said. ``The sun was making me woozy,
and the wooden platform was burning my feet and my legs. It was
like sunburn: the skin was coming off.'' One of her major
close-ups, she said, was filmed in just one take. ``I said to Andy:
`Are you sure? Do you not want one more take? What if the film is
not right?' But he said, no, it was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ling rubbed her head for the 50th time, making sure that her
hair was actually growing back.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was a good scene in the movie,'' she said. ``In my face
you could see the misery. This is because I was feeling misery.''
</P>
<P>
   SWAGGER IS A MUST
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Foxx was taking a leisurely final run-through of a
forthcoming episode of his eponymous television series. The series'
main sets _ a hotel lobby, an office, an apartment _ are lined up
before a half-dozen rows of seats where the studio audience will
eventually sit. Foxx and his fellow actors go through the episode
scene by scene, moving back and forth among the sets as their
producers, writers and assorted crew members follow them, forth,
carting stools and canvas chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Foxx sat back in one of the greenrooms on the Warner
Brothers lot, where his series is taped, and talked about football
and his hopes for an acting career that extends beyond the sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver Stone, you know, is a diabolical genius,'' Foxx said
with a knowing glance. ``He was always coming up and feeding ideas
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx, best known as a comic actor, was delighted when he was
chosen by Stone to play an important role in the director's
football drama ``Any Given Sunday.'' In a star-heavy ensemble cast
that includes James Woods, Dennis Quaid, Cameron Diaz, Ann-Margret,
James Brown, Matthew Modine and Charlton Heston, Foxx is a standout
as a brash young quarterback who forges an angry relationship with
the movie's central character, a down-on-his-luck coach played by
Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little intimidating sometimes to play scenes with
actors with the intensity that Pacino, Brown and the others bring
to a scene. ``But that was only while we were shooting,'' Foxx
said. ``After the scene, Al would be so nice and calm. He really
went out of his way. It felt like this generational thing to me,
teaching the young guy how to do it, and I really appreciated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx had been a quarterback in high school in northern Texas, so
he knew a little bit about the swagger and the leadership needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I had to do was to work out and get in shape and put some
attitude with the moves,'' he said. ``I needed to change those high
school moves into professional moves.''
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH WARD
</P>
<P>
   James Mangold said he was interested in directing the movie
adaptation of Susanna Kaysen's memoir, ``Girl, Interrupted,''
because its setting, a mental hospital ward, and its ensemble cast
would allow him to ``return to some of the intimate energy of my
first film.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangold moved from his first film, the critically praised
``Heavy,'' to a somewhat larger canvas with ``Copland,'' which had
a cast that included Sylvester Stallone, Harvey Keitel and Ray
Liotta. In all of his films, he said, he insists on having the
actors, even the top stars, in as many shots as possible, even if
they are just standing in the background. He describes it as
``shooting stars in ways that aren't starlike.'' It gives the movie
a more truthful flavor, Mangold said.
</P>
<P>
   This was one reason that Winona Ryder approached him to direct
``Girl, Interrupted,'' he said. ``I felt that she was interested in
me for the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   He was intent on shooting the movie on location somewhere,
rather than building a hospital set at the studio and having the
actors all go home at the end of the day. Finally he located an
empty hospital in Harrisburg, Pa., which was transformed into the
institution where Ms. Ryder's character goes in the late 1960s
after a suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shot on an actual ward,'' he said. ``When they were not
in a scene, the actresses could go back to their own character's
room to rest and read. And there is something to be said for
looking out the window and seeing the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change from the book was the expansion of the role
of a cunning sociopath, played by Angelina Jolie. In the movie she
becomes first the idol and then the nemesis of Ms. Ryder's
seemingly more fragile character. The interplay between the two
became the key to the movie's dramatic arc, Mangold said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wish we could be that gutsy and insane and get away
with it,'' he said. ``And we know people _ we all have come across
people in life _ who do seem to be able to get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
