<HEADLINE>
NEWS FLASH! BIG FOOT SPOTTED IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, Dec. 24) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if China didn't have enough problems already, what with all
those human-rights protesters gumming up its tank-treads and
everything, an 8-foot-tall, red-haired, corn-loving Big Foot was
recently spotted in the province of Hubei.
</P>
<P>
   The story comes from Chinese ``state media,'' so when I say
``recently,'' I am actually talking about something that happened
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two months is a long time when you're talking about a hairy
8-foot creature with 16-inch footprints that goes through cobs of
corn they way the rest of us go through salted peanuts. The Chinese
Big Foot might be running the country now, for all we Westerners
know, or at the very least started a corn-fritter franchise or a
chain of hair salons catering to women seeking that stringy, matted
look.
</P>
<P>
   I worry about the Chinese Big Foot, not so much because he (she?
it?) doesn't speak the language (Big-Foot speech, from what I've
read, basically consists of hooting the letter ``u'' over and over
again), but because the Chinese are not as likely to elevate a
stinky, 8-foot ape with corn-breath to the same celebrity status
that we Americans would.
</P>
<P>
   In America, Big Foot, better known as ``Sasquatch'' (literally:
hairy giant creature that's failed to master consonants), is
immensely popular, especially for something that almost surely
doesn't exist. Sasquatch not only enjoys better name-recognition
than most of the presidential candidates, it is also
better-regarded, which is rather sad given the fact that Sasquatch
is said to enjoy a little leg-o'-human every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds, if not thousands, of articles have been written about
Sasquatch, one of the more comprehensive being an article by David
Brewster that ran in Seattle Magazine in 1970. (The same year I
graduated from high school; it has been all downhill for me ever
since but Sasquatch's career has really taken off.)
</P>
<P>
   I learned many interesting things about Sasquatch from
Brewster's article, over and above the fact that Big Foot (Big
Feet?) speaks in the kind of monosyllabic slur one normally
associates with teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I didn't know is that Sasquatches can live to be 200
years old, possibly due to their largely vegetarian diet.
(Leg-o'-humans are reserved for special occasions, such as the
occasion where a human wanders close enough to be grabbed.)
</P>
<P>
   Sasquatches also aren't real big in the personal-hygiene
department (another thing they have in common with teen-age boys).
</P>
<P>
   Brewster recounts the story of Warren Scott, a 37-year-old
Seattle man who was camping (alone, of course) near Vancouver in
1961:
</P>
<P>
   ``Late at night, a Sasquatch kidnapped (Scott) and carried him
70 miles. During the journey, Scott was almost suffocated by the
creature's vise-like grip and uremic odor. Eventually, he was
carried through a long tunnel and dumped in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of Scott's ordeal was spent in this hot, fire-lit
enclosure. The mother (Sasquatch) took care of him, bringing him
food (greens and inedible chunks of raw meat); the old man
(Sasquatch) was seldom around.
</P>
<P>
   ```I was treated like a pet,' Scott recalled. He endured some
good-natured whacking on the rump, he was watched intently when
passing wastes, and he engaged in some rock-rolling with the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests to me that Sasquatches are really nothing
more than overgrown frat boys, the kind that John Belushi (rest his
soul) played to perfection in ``Animal House.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Chinese find out that their Sasquatch enjoys peeping in
coed's windows, dragging dead horses into the dean's office and
stuffing it's face full of corn until it resembles a giant zit,
they may wish it had stayed in the decadent West, where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
