<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARSHALL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Saturday, Dec. 25
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Marshall tragedy now a triumph
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON, W.Va. _ Marshall University football coach Bob
Pruett fought back tears of sadness and joy as he addressed the
crowd of more than 500 people in front of the Memorial Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those guys are looking down and sayin, `Way to go,' to
those who stuck it out and made Marshall what it is now,'' Pruett
said on a breezy Sunday afternoon last month. ``From the ashes of
the plane crash to where we are today is a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbeaten and ranked No. 11, Marshall is the improbable winner of
a college-best 113 football games this decade. On Monday, the
Thundering Herd plays No. 25 Brigham Young in the Motor City Bowl
in Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But as important as that game is to Marshall as it tries to
complete a 13-0 season and move into the Top 10 for the first time,
the defining date in the school's football history always will be
Nov. 14, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   On that dreary Saturday night, the chartered plane carrying a
3-6 Marshall football team home from a 17-14 loss at East Carolina
crashed into a hillside as it approached Tri-State Airport outside
Huntington. All aboard were killed in what remains the worst air
tragedy in American team sports.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall football didn't die in that crash, although it was
on life support during more than a decade of losing seasons. Today,
tragedy has been turned into triumph, ashes have been turned into
glory.
</P>
<P>
   In Huntington, an aging city of about 50,000 on the Ohio River,
each victory is to be cherished more because of what came before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came here, we really didn't understand the
significance,'' quarterback Chad Pennington said. Pennington, who
finished fourth in the Heisman Trophy voting, is expected to be the
first quarterback taken in the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after awhile, you do (understand),'' Pennington said.
``Every time we go out on the field, we're not only doing it for
ourselves, we're doing it for the community and everyone who died
on that plane.''
</P>
<P>
   The 75 iron prongs on the 13-foot high Memorial Fountain
represent the number of players, coaches and Marshall supporters
who died. As the memorial service closes each Nov. 14th, the water
is shut off _ not to be turned on again until the start of the next
school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about death; it's what can come from death,'' said
Andre O'Neal, senior linebacker and co-captain and one of six
Marshall players from metro Atlanta. ``We are celebrating the lives
of those who died. Our success has come from their loss.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that sense of purpose and commitment that helped Marshall
overcome a 23-point deficit against Western Michigan in the
Mid-American Conference title game and prompted Pruett to turn down
a lucrative job offer from the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one person in America who would have turned down
that money,'' Pennington said about the six-year Houston deal worth
a reported $8.9 million. ``That's coach Pruett. He loves Marshall
and West Virginia that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, 56, was born in Beckley, W.Va., and graduated in 1965
from Marshall, also the alma mater of his wife, Elsie. He said he
seriously considered the Houston offer but couldn't tear himself
away from Marshall. At least not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of you will be asking me for financial
advice,'' Pruett joked as he and Pennington were greeted by about
300 fans when they returned home from the Heisman ceremonies in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people talk about loyalty, but coach Pruett stood up
for it when he turned down all that money,'' Marshall fan Barry
Brownfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, a former University of Florida defensive coordinator who
was named Marshall coach after Jim Donnan left for the University
of Georgia, has a base salary of $132,000 per year, plus a $1
million annuity. Recently, a $1,000-a-plate dinner was held to pay
off his house mortgage, and Coach Bobby Pruett's Steakhouse opened
this year in Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshall needs to show its appreciation to coach Pruett,''
Pennington said. ``Coaches like him don't grow on trees. If he
left, it would be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan was 64-21 in six seasons at Marshall, leading the
Thundering Herd to the NCAA Division I-AA national title in 1992
and making the title game two other times.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall has been even better since Donnan left. It made the
jump to Division I without a hitch after going 15-0 and winning the
I-AA title in 1996 _ the first season for Pruett and Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is 34-4 in Division I and has won three Mid-American
Conference titles in a row. Marshall, 12-1 last season, has won 16
consecutive games and hasn't lost at home in 31 games, both
national bests. Moss, now a star with the Minnesota Vikings,
finished fifth in the Heisman Trophy voting in 1997, and Pennington
was a finalist this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall _ one of three unbeaten major-college teams this
season _ has had trouble getting national respect. Like unbeaten
Tulane last season, Marshall is not part of the Bowl Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State and Virginia Tech, the other unbeaten teams, will
battle for the national title in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4. Marshall
had to settle for its third-straight trip to the low-paying Motor
City Bowl. And it would have been left out of a bowl all together
if it had not rallied to win the Mid-American Conference title
game. Pennington threw a short touchdown pass with four seconds
left to beat Western Michigan 34-30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think we should be ranked in the Top 10?'' Pruett asked.
``Yes. Do I think we deserve to be in a bigger bowl? Sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all we are thinking about is beating BYU. They are ranked
and have a great tradition. Beating them should get us in the Top
10 and help make people take us more seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 25 BYU is the first ranked team Marshall has played this
season. But the Herd did beat Peach Bowl-bound Clemson 10-7 in the
season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson also lost to Florida State (17-14) and to Virginia Tech
(31-11).
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshall has more good players than some people think,'' said
Clemson's Tommy Bowden, who coached Tulane to its unbeaten season
last year. ``Do they have the depth to beat FSU or Virginia Tech? I
don't know, but it would be fun to see them play and find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that won't happen. Not this year. Not without a
playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trapped in the world of the BCS,'' Marshall defensive
tackle Giradie Mercer said. ``Sure, I think we could play with FSU
and Virginia Tech. But where we're ranked bothers our fans more
than it does us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Summers, a Marshall fan who lives in Atlanta, was so
outraged when the Herd didn't crack the Top 10 polls released Nov.
14 _ the crash anniversary _ that he sent e-mails across the United
States calling for a boycott of sponsors of the BCS bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Herd deserves better and those who died on that plane
deserve better,'' he wrote. ``Stand up and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   It is because of that fierce loyalty that Marshall's 30,000-seat
stadium is packed for most games. For next season, the capacity
will be increased to about 40,000. Pruett hopes the increase will
enable Marshall to upgrade its home schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Marshall opens at Michigan State, then plays at
North Carolina. Trips to Virginia Tech and Georgia are on future
schedules. But what Pruett and Marshall fans really want is a
home-and-home series with state rival West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Marshall will have to be content with home games
against Mid-American Conference teams Bowling Green, Toledo and
Miami of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Before the homecoming game this season, a candlelight march was
held from Spring Hill Cemetery to the stadium. From the monument
honoring the crash victims on the top of the hill, you can see the
campus below. Six players whose bodies could not be identified are
buried under the marker in a communal grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very moving,'' Marshall fan Mike Captain said about the
candlelight march. ``Those who died will never be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain was a reserve on the 1971 team that won Marshall's first
home game after the crash. The Herd beat Xavier 15-13 on a
last-second pass play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Lord had to be looking out for Marshall that day, and
he still is now,'' Pruett said, thinking about Pennington's
game-winning pass against Western Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall television play-by-play announcer Keith Morehouse lost
his father in the crash. Gene Morehouse was the Herd's radio
announcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who haven't been through the crash don't understand why
it's such an emotional thing to see this team succeed,'' Morehouse
said. ``When my father was here, Marshall was so bad. This kind of
allows me to finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennington, born to Marshall alumni six years after the crash,
said, ``There's no doubt that this is a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
