<P>
   Eds: The following package on the truth behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today:
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-APPEARANCE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jesus Christ is
worshiped as the human incarnation of the son of God, and his
likeness has been reproduced for hundreds of years by thousands of
artists. But they've all been making it up. The Apostles were
assiduous in copying down Jesus' message, but no one bothered to
write about his appearance. We know some things he said, but not at
all how he sounded. And though Bible readers are given vague hints
about the visage of the Prince of Peace, even those are
contradictory. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-CRUCIFY _ The spikes nailed through Jesus' wrists and
ankles did not kill him. The crown of thorns that cut into his brow
was little more than a nuisance, and the whipping he endured before
he was crucified was almost an act of mercy. (Belkin, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-LIFE _ Jesus may have been the Prince of Peace, but if his
life was at all typical of his fellow Nazarenes in the first
century, he didn't live like royalty while he was growing up.
(Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-MISTLETOE _ The mistletoe you're trying to get caught
under this Christmas season wasn't always the semi-parasitic plant
it is today. According to an old French folk story, mistletoe used
to be a tree in its own right until it was caught in the wrong
place at the wrong time. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-GIFTS _ It takes a little of the magic away from the Magi
to be able to buy frankincense and myrrh for $2.95 in the incense
department at just about any New Age bookstore. But in their day,
the Three Wise Men had a different set of circumstances with which
to deal. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
