<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: love these people.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she started working with the homeless 13 years ago, mental
illness was not part of the equation. ``We used to laugh and say
you don't have to be mentally ill to get to the Night Shelter, you
end up that way once you get there,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed. A national study on homelessness published
recently found that not only are the homeless deeply impoverished,
but 39 percent also have symptoms of mental illness, as Ruth
McClain does. Two-thirds are suffering from chronic or infectious
diseases, not including AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   That mirrors the situation here, said Guinn, who estimates tha
about 30 percent of the homeless population in Tarrant County is
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The new Safe Haven, Suggs said, ``will allow us to give them a
better place to stay than the shelter. It's designed to draw those
who we think can be treated and enticed into accepting treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the only thing to do is wait and hope.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if Ruth would remember me when I visited her again
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kinda do and I kinda don't,'' she says, then asks me to move
out of the sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   I move and try to jog her memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came by a few months ago with John Suggs from the
Presbyterian Night Shelter,'' I say. ``And Lettie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah. You're the reporter from the Star-Telegram.''
</P>
<P>
   I am surprised. ``Yes, how are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth reaches over and shuts off Bennie Goodman playing on KLTY
radio. She spits on two fingers to tidy her hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked like a million dollars yesterday,'' she says, her
smile giving way to embarrassment. ``And you show up today?''
</P>
<P>
   This is on Tuesday, Dec. 6, and the weather has turned colder,
the temperature hovering close to 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The ``camp'' has changed from the time of our first visit in
September. A piece of plywood stands guard against the brisk winter
wind at one end and two pieces of dirty white and gray tarp pieced
together with safety pins provide a partial roof. Ruth sits where
she was the first time I saw her, on a dirty blue twin mattress
facing University Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Her clothes are layered to keep her warm, a striped
ramie-and-cotton sweater over a green T-shirt, and navy blue cotton
pants. A green sleeping bag is pulled around her shoulders. A
propane stove burns on the ground between her and the six cats.
</P>
<P>
   It is a gift from her younger sister, Bonnie, Ruth says.
``Patty,'' however, is scribbled on a store receipt she shows me
later. It is one of many such entries she has tucked into a thick
notebook describing the people who have visited her and the gifts
they bring.
</P>
<P>
   On one page, she has scribbled my name with the day and date of
our first visit: Tuesday, Sept. 28, 1999. There is a notation that
Suggs brought coffee and doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth's story hasn't changed much since then. She still insists
that God sent her here, that President Clinton is part of a
conspiracy to kill her, and that she has the power to fend off evil
by simply looking at a person and crossing her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They run, I'm so full of the anointing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   I'm resigned to accepting Ruth as she is.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, though, has since written me again. His words seem
more frantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady is still living under the bridge,'' he writes.
``Pretty soon it will get very cold. What do you think will happen
to her then? I wonder what would happen to her if someone did force
her to leave? Would it really mess her up more than she already
is?''
</P>
<P>
   I don't have the answers. But I would like to believe that if I
were in Ruth's shoes, someone would try to help me and insist I go
to a better place. Even against my will.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruth insists she is fine. She isn't. Ruth McClain is the
shadow of another woman who I imagine is smart and funny and full
of life and love.
</P>
<P>
   When Top Cat paws at a withered sunflower on the ground, Ruth
scolds him, and I think that she loves flowers, cares about things
pretty. Watching her with her cat, I wonder if she has children, if
her sister Bonnie is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``An angel planted flowers just yesterday,'' she says. ``You
should've seen this place. I had it looking real nice.''
</P>
<P>
   When I say goodbye, she yells, ``Come back when I've got things
set up looking nice again.''
</P>
<P>
   I tell her I will, but I'm worried now, like Dickerson. There
are more cold fronts now; it's finally raining again. I wonder if
Ruth and her cats will survive.
</P>
<P>
   People say that this is the season for miracles. I hope there's
one left for Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
