<HEADER>
A7811 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-1000(2     12-23 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING RUTH MIGHT REQUIRE A HOLIDAY MIRACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been nearly three months since John Suggs, executive
director of the Presbyterian Night Shelter, Lettie Zeweldemariam,
manager of the new Safe Haven, and I met Ruth McClain.
</P>
<P>
   The makeshift ``missionary camp'' tucked between two brick posts
under the Rosedale overpass in Fort Worth isn't the sort of place
anyone would want to visit, let alone live. The stench last summer
was almost unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the place McClain has called home for more than a
year. This place, on a small patch of ground between Rogers Road
and South University Drive, is where she says God told her to set
up camp, to build the World Global Mission Ministry for those who
are homeless like her. This is where she is safe from those who
want her dead, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to shut down the Union Gospel Mission and
Salvation Army, but now I'm just going to help them,'' she says.
``I'm waiting on the $200 million now.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I returned to visit McClain, who was still waiting for
her millions. This time, afraid that her family of six cats might
die in the cold, she was expecting a Winnebago to be delivered as
well.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tony Guinn, director of specialized services for
Tarrant County Mental Health Mental Retardation, as many as 2,000
people in Tarrant County are like Ruth, homeless and suffering from
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing can get them off the street and on medication except
gentle persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   I had passed Ruth's camp many times in the past year, en route
to my daughter's piano class or the shops in University Village.
Each time, I'd look to see if she was still there. I wondered how
she ended up in such a place. Because of my fears, I never stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late September, I received an e-mail from Doug
Dickerson, a former member of the board at the Presbyterian Night
Shelter, telling me about ``a lady'' under the Rosedale Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a miracle she has not been killed or injured,''
Dickerson wrote. ``She is very neat and tidy, and apparently there
are a number of people bringing her food, water, ice, etc., but she
obviously needs help.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said that the Presbyterian Night Shelter had tried to
intervene, but that she refused to accept help. He said he thought
a story about her might help.
</P>
<P>
   I soon learned, though, that unless Ruth proved to be a threat
to herself or someone else, she was simply exercising her right to
do as she pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The woman I met that day didn't seem capable of harm. I could
see that by the way she cared for her cats. She was a large woman
with a quick smile. She talked nonstop, moving in and out of
reality as quickly as she batted her eyelashes, thick with black
mascara. She talked about the mission God told her to build and the
``plot by the FBI and President Clinton'' to have her killed.
</P>
<P>
   We talked for the first time in September. Although the camp was
cluttered, everything was in its place. It was a perfect rectangle,
bordered by a twin-size mattress, bridge posts and plastic crates
that made a 4-foot wall facing University. Top Cat and the other
cats made their home in one crate on the ground. On top was a Bible
opened to the book of Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth said she was a computer operator at Texas Christian
University when the Lord called her to the street in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she said, he has saved her from tuberculosis,
ovarian cancer and brain cancer and, at that very moment, was
healing her of breast cancer. She told me the freckles on her body
represent the anointing of the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nuts,'' Ruth said, laughing. ``I'm an apostle, and an
apostle is called to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Since I first met Ruth, I've visited with Guinn at the county
mental health offices. I met Carol Sweeney, a board member at the
Presbyterian Night Shelter and a longtime advocate for the
homeless. I visited the shelter, where Sweeney introduced me to
some residents, told me their stories.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, a homeless woman had given birth on the
railroad tracks nearby. As Sweeney described a day in her life at
the shelter, I watched a woman they call Mama Sun.
</P>
<P>
   She looked like a little girl in a red-and-white dress, red
stockings and red shoes. A red bow held her hair in place, and red
lipstick was smudged on her cheeks, forehead and lips.
</P>
<P>
   One moment she was busy tidying an already made bunk, and the
next she was yelling over her shoulder to an imaginary person.
</P>
<P>
   This happens here on a regular basis, Sweeney said. Most of the
people are ``as crazy as loons,'' as she puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney is always watching. When she's lucky, she sees one of
them make a threat and acts quickly. It is the only chance she has
to get them committed, to get help for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was what Jesus told us to do ... take care of these
people,'' she said. ``Besides that, I love these people.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
