<HEADER>
A7813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-BETHLEHEM-122     12-23 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BETHLEHEM-1224-1stLD-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BETHLEHEM MIXES CHRISTMAS SPIRIT AND POLITICAL ASPIRATIONS
 &HT;    EDS: Corrects grammar in 10th graf 
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM _ Almost 2000 years later, people in the city where
Christ was born are hoping for a lot more than just a Merry
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem is not a ``little town'' any more. It's a crowded
Palestinian city trying to rebuild after decades of neglect and
Israeli occupation. Christmas and the millennial year 2000 are
opportunities for Bethlehem to emerge anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, one-third of the world is looking toward Bethlehem. The
burden is very heavy but we are prepared,'' Bethlehem Mayor Hanna
Nasser said recently. ``We know very well this is a religious
occasion, but we should never forget that it has more than one
dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   The other dimensions, he stressed, are ``political, tourism and
development.''
</P>
<P>
   This week around Manger Square, the plaza in front of the Church
of the Nativity, work was going full speed on all three fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Workers polished the tile road markers on Star Street, where new
stone walkways, sewage systems and electrical wiring are still
being completed between the crowded homes.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeepers opened the doors on new stores along an area _ long
ignored by visitors _ remade into a ``Christmas Market.''
</P>
<P>
   And across the base of the large stage where choirs will sing on
Christmas Eve, Arabic letters make the political point: ``From
Bethlehem 2000 to the independence and building of the Palestinian
state, with its capital of holy Jerusalem and under the leadership
of President Yasser Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   Raja Zacharia, 38, recently converted his grocery store to a
shop for the olive wood Christmas ornaments he makes. A Roman
Catholic, his father was killed by Israeli shelling in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need peace here in the land of peace,'' Zacharia said,
adding that he is skeptical that the city will ever find
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The city, just five miles south of Jerusalem, was under British
and then Jordanian control until Israel captured it in 1967. The
following years saw it beset by tens of thousands of Palestinian
refugees. Road work, sewers and water systems were overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   The town joined the rest of the West Bank during the Palestinian
Intifada uprising of the late 1980s, and was for years the scene of
stone throwing, rubber bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Israel transferred control of the city to the
Palestinian Authority, run by Arafat. Still bracketed by Israeli
roadblocks, Bethlehem is one of more than 100 sectors of the West
Bank that have been turned over. But, the Palestinians' dream _ of
their own state with a capital in Israeli-controlled Jerusalem _ is
still subject to the hard haggling of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem has a population of about 50,000 and is the center of
a district with about 150,000. With the influx of mostly Muslim
refugees, the Christian majority in the city has fallen to a
30-percent minority. Many Christians say they feel pushed aside by
the Muslims when it comes to jobs and other levers of power. Neon
crosses atop some homes and businesses are seen by some as an
assertion of their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser, however, the mayor appointed by Arafat, is a Christian
and Christianity is acknowledged as the city's claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   Each Christmas eve is marked by a Manger Square block party,
culminating with the midnight mass in the church. This year more
than 60,000 are expected there and more than 900 journalists have
credentials to attend.
</P>
<P>
   With foreign donations of more than $86 million, overseen by the
Palestinian Authority agency called Bethlehem 2000, Manger Square
has been converted from a noisy bus parking lot to a tree-lined
piazza.
</P>
<P>
   A museum and cultural center was built in place of a former
British and Israeli prison on the square. A five-star
Inter-Continental Hotel is being built around a former sultan's
palace on the edge of downtown. It will overlook the block houses
and dirt streets of a refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   City officials hope to shave off a greater percentage of the
tourist money spent by pilgrims coming from Israel next door. Signs
in the Christmas market proclaim, ``Come do your Christmas shopping
in the real capital of Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, a Muslim, has been an enthusiastic booster of the year
2000 effort, in contrast to his subdued Israeli rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians have put the Israelis in the shade,'' said
Israeli Rabbi David Rosen, Israel director of the Anti-Defamation
League. He faults Israelis for late millennium preparation and says
they might miss a chance to improve relations between Jews and
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, residents see it as an opportunity they cannot
afford to miss.
</P>
<P>
   If the year 2000 is a success, Mayor Nasser said, people around
the world will ``consider Bethlehem as a spiritual capital and not
think of Bethlehem only on the 24th and 25th days of December.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
