<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-RAISE26-COX     12-23 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAISE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Raise, anyone? Big ones may be scarce in 2000
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you want a fat raise to bring in the new
millennium, you are going to work really hard to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a strong economy and tight labor market, consultants are
predicting raises will be moderate for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing around a 4 percent merit increase budget'' from
companies responding to the annual Hewitt Associates Salary
Increase Survey, says Jane Romweber, a principal in the Atlanta
office.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bullish economy continues without a clear sign of
slowing down, employers are worried that higher labor costs can
have a compounding effect. Employees have to overcome those fears
and make their pitch on a personal level, career consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start talking about raises, everyone gets nervous.
They envision a price spiral,'' says Marilyn Moats Kennedy,
managing partner at Career Strategies, a management consulting firm
in Wilmette, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to overpay for an employee. They're going to
pay just what they have to pay to get an employee to work for them
and not a penny more.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, projections or not, nothing is promised. ``The
(projections) are averages, theoretically,'' Romweber advises.
``Your better performers get more, and your worse performers get
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even the better performers might have to labor for a
much-deserved raise. ``If you think they're going to recognize you
and give you money just because you're there, get over yourself,''
warns Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   So, how can you be the one to get the big bucks?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to show that you returned more value to (your)
company this year than last year,'' says Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the economy plays in your favor. With unemployment
levels at record lows and the supply of skilled workers extremely
tight, companies don't want good employees leaving in a market with
scarce replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers want continuity, so they have every reason to be
reasonable,'' says Romweber.
</P>
<P>
   A company that systematically underpays workers won't be
competitive for long. As a result, ``They have every reason to pay
you because in this full-employment marketplace, everybody's a free
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the raise you deserve, try the ``sandwich technique.''
That's when you ``sandwich'' the request for more cash between
compelling, preferably quantitative support for your case,
according to Emory W. Mulling, president and founder of The Mulling
Group, an Atlanta-based outplacement and executive coaching
consulting firm that teaches this negotiation technique to its
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   _ Note all your accomplishments from the past 12 months to
``cost-justify'' your worth to the company, Mulling says. ``Try to
quantify as much as you can. You increased sales by a certain
percentage, you lowered overhead by a certain percentage, or you
implemented a program or system that saved the company this much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for the raise, using your accomplishments as leverage.
``What you say is, `Since I saved the company X number of dollars,'
or `I added to productivity,' whatever you can quantify,'' says
Mulling. You can check with your industry association or a trade
group for salary ranges to see how you're faring compared with your
peers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seal the raise request with additional details about what you
accomplished last year, as well as an indication of what you plan
to do in the coming year. ``You try to demonstrate your value to
the company for next year as well,'' says Mulling.
</P>
<P>
   What if they say no?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have three options: Do nothing and accept it. Go look for
another job and possibly leave. Or, go back at a later time and ask
for reconsideration,'' says Mulling.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, don't threaten to leave, warned Mulling.
</P>
<P>
   If you get the raise, you don't want to be on the
prove-you're-worth-it side of an ultimatum. ``Sometimes the
employer gives the raise, their expectations go way up and they
say, `OK, kid. We're watching. If you're worth that much money,
you'd better deliver,''' says Romweber.
</P>
<P>
   If you do eventually leave the company, you don't want threats
to come back to haunt you. ``If you burn your bridges before you
leave, you may not get positive references,'' Mulling adds.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to stay, ``You need to learn to be happy,'' says
Mulling. ``Don't let a bad attitude destroy your reputation and all
the hard work you've done,'' the consultant adds.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you may have to ask again to receive. ``A lot of
people, when we go into the next recession, will not have asked for
a raise,'' says Kennedy. ``Then, they will go through another long
period and not get a raise. They'll never get it. They think it's
too awful to even broach the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   If last year wasn't your best for work performance, don't fret.
It's not too early to start strategizing for your 2001 increase _
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to sit down with your boss and find out what
high performance looks like, says Romweber. Find out how you're
viewed currently compared to that standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be straightforward,'' she says. ``I'm trying to manage my
career. I'd like to establish what my potential is and what plans
you have for the future. What are your performance expectations
going out?''
</P>
<P>
   With that information in hand, you can begin to shoot for the
top-level performance and start working to bag that big raise for
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
