<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wacky `Quest' for intergalactic fun
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest,'' opening Saturday, is a sci-fi spoof that looks
great on paper.
</P>
<P>
   It's got all the goods: a beloved old TV show as over the top as
``Star Trek.'' Geeky fans _ let's call them Questers _ who take the
show way too seriously. And wacky aliens from far, far away who
lure the has-been ``Quest'' actors into helping rescue their
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   On the big screen, however, it clicks only some of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver and Alan Rickman head the small band
of ex-``Galaxy Quest'' actors whisked off into space by the alien
Thermians to help them save Klatu Nebula from a particularly
nasty-looking race of warrior bug-lizards led by the evil Sarris
(Robin Sachs). The Thermians have latched on to the Earthlings
because they've intercepted transmissions of the TV show and
treated them like the discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' takes eons to take off. The opening, set at a
fan convention for the TV show, is so stilted and off-pace that
you'll probably think you're in for a long night at the movies. But
with decent special effects, an absurd sense of humor and the
Thermians' truly bizarre speech pattern, some fun finally kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   As Jason Nesmith (the TV show's Commander Peter Quincy Taggart),
Allen is as straightforward and oddly likable as he was for years
on TV's ``Home Improvement.'' Weaver's one-note jokes consist of
toting around big breasts and repeating everything the spaceship's
computer says.
</P>
<P>
   But the performances really worth seeing here belong to Tony
Shalhoub, who does an inspired, deadpan routine that's the exact
opposite of ``Star Trek's'' hepped-up, brogue-enriched engineer
Scotty, and Enrico Colantoni (TV's ``Just Shoot Me''), who plays
Thermian leader Mathesar with inventive childlike wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Many children will enjoy ``Galaxy Quest.'' Trekkies might even
fall to their knees. Others may resist falling for the movie's
cornball charm.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain. ``Galaxy Quest'' is a bona fide
antidote to holiday stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver and Alan Rickman. Rated PG
for mild violence and sensuality. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It'll beam you way, way up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
