<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-YEARSBEST26-CO     12-23 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-YEARSBEST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The straight story? A year filled with good pictures
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's pleasantly difficult to winnow down the best titles in a
year that was unexpectedly bursting with good to great movies. Many
of them were made by young directors, including Paul Thomas
Anderson (``Magnolia'') and first-time feature directors Spike
Jonze (``Being John Malkovich'') and Kimberly Peirce (``Boys Don't
Cry''). Meanwhile, the older masters turned in work that was
disappointingly familiar (Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the
Dead''), borderline bad (Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'') or
just peculiarly out-of-character (David Lynch's ``The Straight
Story,'' which many critics loved but for me was a condescending
bore).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best of the year's movies shared themes, though they
explored them in very different ways. The focus was often on people
coming to a crisis point, causing them to change or rebuild their
lives (``All About My Mother,'' ``American Beauty''). Other movies
tweaked the notion of personal identity (``Boys Don't Cry,''
``Being John Malkovich,'' ``Fight Club,'' ``Man on the Moon'').
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the occasional popcorn-ready crowd-pleasers that
reveled in the thrill of telling a good story, whether made with a
huge budget (``The Matrix'') or almost none (``The Blair Witch
Project'').
</P>
<P>
   Here, in alphabetical order, is a very subjective list of my
faves of 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All About My Mother.'' Spanish filmmaker Pedro Almodovar's
hymn to strong women is his most mature movie, even while retaining
his usual gallery of drag queens, junkies and other outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Beauty.'' One moment a suburban black comedy, the
next a transcendent glimpse of the eternal, this out-of-nowhere
original from screenwriter Alan Ball is a breathtaking look at the
miraculous aspects of the everyday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Being John Malkovich.'' So maybe you'd rather spend 15
minutes in the mind of Brad Pitt, but writer Charlie Kaufman and
director Spike Jonze created one of the wittiest, weirdest
explorations of identity of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Blair Witch Project.'' Yes, it was overhyped. But this
no-budget horror movie brilliantly reinvented campfire ghost
stories for the camcorder age and reminded Hollywood filmmakers
that a good yarn is more important than special effects.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Boys Don't Cry.'' Hilary Swank amazes as a woman
masquerading as a man; a thrilling debut from writer-director
Kimberly Peirce, who locates a tragic lyricism in the quick-mart
wastelands of Middle America.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Election.'' Alexander Payne's wicked comedy about the battle
of wills between a perky student and an ethics teacher is a
terrific indictment of the ways we all rationalize our bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fight Club.'' Though it plots itself into a corner, David
Fincher's hyperkinetic flick delivers bracing social satire about
the loss of masculinity in the age of IKEA.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Magnolia.'' A kaleidoscopic meditation on love, estranged
parents and children, and the need for forgiveness; a huge leap
forward from ``Boogie Nights'' writer-director Paul Thomas
Anderson. (Opens Jan. 7 in metro Atlanta.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Man on the Moon.'' Jim Carrey gives the performance of his
life as comic Andy Kaufman in a movie that makes explicit the
latent hostility between a performer and his audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Matrix.'' Finally, a sci-fi adventure with a plot as
accomplished and witty as its special effects; a visual triumph
headlined by Keanu Reeves in a comeback no one could have
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other best movies of 1999: ``The End of the Affair''
(opening Jan. 7 in metro Atlanta), ``The Insider,'' ``The Iron
Giant,'' ``Cookie's Fortune,'' ``The Limey,'' ``October Sky,''
``Ride With the Devil,'' ``The Sixth Sense,'' ``South Park: Bigger,
Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' ``The Winslow Boy,'' ``American Movie'' and
``Topsy-Turvy'' (the last two open here Jan. 21).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
