<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We laughed, cried, dreamed of big bucks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer and Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many shows, so little to watch. So ran the 1999 viewer
lament, the same as in years past. But even as ratings fell for the
big networks, there were some bright spots to be found as we
clicked around. Here are 10 of the most intriguing shows of the
year:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Sopranos'' (HBO) _ It sang, and will again. Returning in
January, the exquisitely layered mob-family drama made rival TV
executives drool with envy, made a sex symbol (sort of) of a fat,
midlife-muddled New Jersey gangster and made every other treatment
of organized crime on TV and most movies seem like concrete shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The West Wing'' (NBC) and ``Sports Night'' (ABC) _ Call it
``Sorkin TV'': Creator Aaron Sorkin provided the networks with a
comic drama and dramatic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``ER'' (NBC) _ Still the top doc after some past wobbling.
Crash-cart editing, guest star Alan Alda and millions of viewers
wishing someone would take a proctoscope to that nasty Dr. Romano.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Once and Again'' (ABC) _ Who said TV's just for kids? This
smart, sexy prime-time soap for baby boomers stars Sela Ward and
Billy Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Now and Again'' (CBS) _ Wacky idea _ a middle-aged man's
brain is transplanted into a young superman's body _ but it turned
out to be an utterly beguiling and unpredictable romance. With Eric
Close and Dennis Haysbert.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Daily Show'' (Comedy Central) _ Host Jon Stewart has
made this nightly news spoof late night's only appointment TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS) _ The family-based
anti-``Friends'': A ``Honeymooners'' for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Iron Chef'' (The Food Channel) _ A Japanese cooking
competition, dubbed and subtitled, in which kitchen warriors made
weird dishes of octopus and yogurt while the announcer made it
sound like professional wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Simpsons'' (Fox) _ Just say D'oh! Homer and Co.
celebrate 10 years of nuclear family meltdown in January, and
they're sharper than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Who Wants to Be
</P>
<P>
   a Millionaire'' (ABC) _ The season's guiltiest pleasure. And
that's our final assessment.
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer and Drew Jubera write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
