<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHRISTMAS-TODAY25-COX     12-23 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-TODAY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The reason for the season stays the same, times reshape
celebration for everybody
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Saturday, Dec. 25.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Christmas is changing. Just ask Santa.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lee has played the role for six years at a metro Atlanta
mall, and has grown accustomed to kids asking for the same gifts _
Barbie dolls, toy soldiers, bikes and video games.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, he says, kids have been coming to Santa with some
strange requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``One little girl came up last year and said, `I want to live
with my man,''' Lee said. ``I told her, `Your daddy is your man. At
your age, that's the only man in your life.'''
</P>
<P>
   The kids' wish lists don't stop there. Some ask Santa's help in
reuniting divorced parents or springing a relative from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some teenagers come up to me and say, `Santa, I'm
having trouble at home and I need someone to talk to,''' said Lee,
51, who has spent the past month in a candy-cane red uniform at
South DeKalb Mall in Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   When Santa starts giving therapy instead of toys, something is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans will greet a Rockwellian scene this
morning _ a warm, comfortable room filled with glittering
decoration and presents offered by loving family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But this picture has become blurred, a victim of the frenzied
nature of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Critics lament the growing commercialization of the season, but
people like Lee notice more subtle changes. Traditions of
Christmases past _ homemade gifts, singing Christmas carols under
street lamplights and lavish home decorations _ are being squeezed
out by the pressures of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gerald Durley, pastor of Providence Missionary Baptist
Church in Atlanta, says the Christmas season, like the pace of life
in general, has become more frenzied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find a certain tension in the worship service, with people
shopping around at the last minute and then flopping into church,''
says Durley, 57. ``It's become a part of the daily grind rather
than a time to reflect on the birth of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Durley says he's noticed a decline in many familiar Christmas
touches. Even traditional songs have changed, he says, forcing him
to call a local disc jockey, Frank Ski, to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Frank, I gotta turn your show off because I've
never heard anyone rap `O Silent Night,''' Durley recalls.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly dismayed by a new rap version of ``Jingle
Bells'' that goes: ``Jingle bells, your dad's in jail, pay his bail
and get out all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between that and `dashing through the
snow,''' Durley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Rasor suggests that all was not wonderful in
Christmases past.
</P>
<P>
   People tend to romanticize those years, says Rasor, a professor
of sociology at Atlanta's Interdenominational Theological Center, a
consortium of six seminaries near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``As life becomes more complex and more hurried, we probably
exaggerate what may have been in the past,'' Rasor says. But he
doesn't argue that earlier generations had some advantages for
celebrating the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier part of the century, families lived closer
together and were able to spend more time with one another, Rasor
says. That's no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   Generosity also required more imagination. Homemade cards and
handcrafted items, which often took painstaking work, were more
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gift-giving was more personal and meaningful. People were
forced to make things. They could not get on the Internet and order
something or go to the mall,'' Rasor says.
</P>
<P>
   People had less money but they had more compassion for needy
strangers who approached them during the holiday, said Joe Burton,
who was born in Atlanta shortly before the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to be more generous in the old days,'' said
Burton, 76, a state senator from Atlanta. ``If you were hungry,
people would share what they had. Nowadays, if a stranger knocked
on your door, if you're smart, you wouldn't open the door.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some good news, however. Not all recent holiday changes
have been bad.
</P>
<P>
   Burton says corporations, churches and shelters offer a holiday
safety net for the needy that didn't exist before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now things like the Empty Stocking Fund; the
churches are getting out and working. You can see it, you can feel
it,'' says Burton, who volunteers as a Salvation Army bell ringer
during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Philip Bray, who operates SafeHouse Outreach Ministries
in Atlanta, says people seem more caring today, but he also thinks
there is a growing need.
</P>
<P>
   Bray says that he sees more women and children at homeless
shelters during the holiday and that homeless youngsters represent
a special problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are bombarded with commercials about the newest toys,
and the fact that they might not be able to get those toys _ the
despair, the hopelessness _ it just seems to be compounded at this
time of the year,'' Bray says. ``My message is that we are rich
when we have joy, peace and loved ones in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the same message that Lee tried to spread this year.
</P>
<P>
   He sees his Santa role as a personal ministry and is convinced
that he's able to help the troubled youngsters who seek him out.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas may change but the need for compassion never does, he
says. ``I ask the Lord to speak for me, and he does.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
