<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7835 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MUSIC-YEARSBEST26-COX     12-23 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YEARSBEST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding rare, refined ways to subvert the mainstream
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar, Sonia Murray, Kathy Janich, Doug Hamilton,
Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all you knew of pop music in 1999 was the video hit parade on
MTV's ``Total Request Live,'' you could easily assume that the year
was one of the shallowest ever: boy bands and Tommy
Hilfiger-approved Lolitas, surly rap-rockers and one-hit-wonder
acts milking the same watery formula for all it's worth. That's a
deceptive image, however, as inventive artists found new ways to
subvert the mainstream _ making complex but thoroughly entertaining
albums _ while refining the musical approaches that made their
names.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at 10 of those performers, whose CDs were rated by
staff music critics as the best of 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fiona Apple, ``When the Pawn ... '' (Clean Slate/Epic). Yeah,
the full 90-word title scans like flaky 10th-grade poetry, but the
22-year-old phenom has the musicianly goods most of her peers lack.
Snazzy piano chops and jazzy vocalese give Apple's self-absorbed
relationship rants and reveries a seductive sparkle. Vent, baby,
vent. (Steve Dollar)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Basement Jaxx, ``Remedy'' (Astralwerks). British duo
deconstructs the history of dance music, throwing it all back
together in unexpected ways. What's really impressive, though, is
that the twosome does it without sacrificing niceties such as hooks
and melodies. (Shane Harrison)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beck, ``Midnite Vultures'' (DGC). A schizophrenic, funked-up
masterpiece, Beck Hansen's latest starts out as the phat soundtrack
to a throwdown at George Clinton's place, goes FM rock in the
middle and slinks to a close with the funniest falsetto-fueled
makeout song Prince never recorded. Think ``Odelay'' in a red
velvet suit and platform shoes. (Doug Hamilton)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dixie Chicks, ``Fly'' (Monument). The Texas threesome proves
yet again that it is possible to pluck a banjo like Earl Scruggs,
stomp the stage like Sly Stone and be commercially successful on
country radio. (Miriam Longino)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Magnetic Fields, ``69 Love Songs'' (Merge). Underground pop
auteur Stephin Merritt's three-CD opus rivals the Artist for
voluminous indulgence, but there's little filler here. For Merritt,
the love song is a mutable concept, encompassing titles as
disparate as ``Nothing Matters When We're Dancing,'' ``Underwear''
and ``Chicken With Its Head Cut Off.'' (SH)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Meshell Ndegeocello, ``Bitter'' (Maverick/Warner Bros.).
Stripped of prominent bass guitar (``Rush Over'') and sass (``If
That's Your Boyfriend''), this still underappreciated R&AMP;B talent
stands bare and beautiful on her third album. It's our hearts she
exposes. (Sonia Murray)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mos Def, ``Black on Both Sides'' (Rawkus). As casual observers
of rap watched mainstream favorites Master P go pop and Puffy's
sales go poof, the genre's best combination of smart lyrics and
creative production out this year gurgled almost unnoticed
underground. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  John Prine, ``In Spite of Ourselves'' (Oh Boy). Duets with
some of country/Americana's top female vocalists make this
collection of retro-country tunes burn like a naked light bulb.
``Back Street Affair'' with Patty Loveless is Porter and Dolly gone
bad. (ML)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tom Waits, ``Mule Variations'' (Epitaph). A busted-down
troubadour from the twilight zone of American myth, Waits is like a
hobo Stephen Foster stranded on Bourbon Street with a bullhorn and
a hip flask full of inspired jive. When he boasts, ``I got the
powder, but not the gun / I got the dog, but not the bun,'' you
know exactly what he means _ even if, really, you don't at all.
(SD)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wilco, ``Summer Teeth'' (Reprise/Warner Bros.). The year's
most gloriously indulged pop album, in which a great Middle
American rock band transcends its niche, with glances back at the
Beach Boys and the Kinks. (SD)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar, Sonia Murray, Kathy Janich, Doug Hamilton, Miriam
Longino and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution..
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
