<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WALKER24-COX     12-23 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An award-winning book by Emory University professor makes case
for segregated education in the Jim Crow South
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before she became a Harvard grad and a celebrated
professor, Vanessa Siddle Walker grew up on a 90-acre farm, where
she learned to pick tobacco and feed hogs.
</P>
<P>
   She also learned another skill _ paying attention to people's
stories.
</P>
<P>
   It's a skill she easily mastered. After all, she comes from a
family of storytellers.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers jumping onto her grandmother's lap as a
2-year-old, saying ``Mama Emily, tell about that time when. . . .
`` And for her curiosity, Walker would be rewarded with grand
family tales that mixed joy, poetry and humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a sense of self and place and where I belonged in
history,'' said Walker. She eventually compiled many of the stories
and placed them in a family Bible she keeps in her Tucker, Ga.,
home.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is now getting attention for a story of her own. She was
recently named the winner of one of the nation's most prestigious
awards in higher education, the Grawemeyer Award, for a book that
challenges the belief that most black schools in the segregated
South had little worth.
</P>
<P>
   The award is administered by the University of Louisville (Ky.)
and comes with a whopping $200,000 prize.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's book, ``Their Highest Potential'' (University of North
Carolina Press, 258 pages, $15.95), examines a black school in
rural North Carolina that thrived before schools were racially
integrated.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, 42, an associate professor at Emory University, offers a
bold argument in her book that, in some ways, black students were
better off in segregated schools than they are now.
</P>
<P>
   She comes to this conclusion by chronicling the story of the
Caswell County Training School (CCTS), which operated in the
Piedmont area of North Carolina from 1934 to 1969. She focuses her
tale on the school's principal, N.L. Dillard, a leader who made his
students rich in learning though they were poor in just about
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dillard's leadership, CCTS became one of the few fully
accredited schools in the region (none of the white schools in the
area achieved this distinction). And CCTS students regularly won
academic honors.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Dittmer, chairman of the selection committee for the
Grawemeyer Award, said Walker's book was rigorously researched but
is also an inspirational page turner. He said it holds lessons for
today's educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the theories that's typical in education is that we
think if you throw money at the problem, it'll go away,'' Dittmer
said. ``Her book is a testimonial that there's something far more
fundamental than economics or resources.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called caring. Caswell's teachers _ and many parents _
routinely spent their own money to help students or to improve the
school. Walker observed such altruism personally. Her mother,
Helen, taught at CCTS and her father, the Rev. Theodore Siddle, was
a PTA president.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said she was shocked when she received news of the award.
She celebrated by sharing pizza and carrot cake with her Emory
colleagues and later pledged to donate some of the prize money to a
scholarship fund for Caswell County students.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with the honor, Walker says, comes a measure of anxiety.
She fears that some people will misuse her book in an effort to
justify a return to segregated schools, something she does not
support.
</P>
<P>
   What Walker said she is attempting to correct in her book is a
historical distortion _ that black schools in the segregated South
had nothing to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Common belief suggests that under Jim Crow laws,
African-Americans were forced to go to inferior schools lacking in
resources and instruction. The landmark 1954 U.S. Supreme Court
case, Brown vs. Board of Education, abolished the doctrine of
``separate but equal'' schools, paving the way for school
integration nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   It also paved the way for the demolition of nurturing schools
like CCTS, Walker said. Under integration, the black educational
infrastructure _ black teachers, principals and schools _ was
``subsumed'' into the white school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had white superintendents, white school boards, white
teachers _ they fired many of the African-American teachers,'' she
said. ``So where African-Americans had power over how their
children were going to be educated in the segregated schools, they
lost much of that. People were making decisions about
African-American children who did not know them and perhaps did not
believe in what they were capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has its critics. Harvard University's Gary Orfield, one
of the nation's leading advocates for school integration, says
Walker's book waxes nostalgic over a period that brutalized black
folks. Walker insists that Orfield ignores the academic research
that supports her claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are looking back at that time are seeing things
that were there, but they're not describing the whole picture,''
Orfield said. ``They remember the best of segregation and the worst
of desegregation.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Walker _ a tall, animated woman who switches
easily from academic jargon to down-home stories that reveal her
gift for mimicry _ say she is grounded enough to handle any
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in Tucker, Ga., with her husband, Melford, an
attorney, and their 6-year-old daughter, Sarah. Her home, like her
work, points to the past. An organ that sits in her foyer belonged
to her late mother. Her dining room set belonged to a great-aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Jordan Irvine, a friend and Emory University
colleague, said Walker's rural upbringing stays with her in another
way. In the town of Yanceyville, N.C., where Walker was born, it
was considered taboo to brag. Walker explains much of her
accomplishments with a simple, ``I've been blessed,'' Irvine said.
``She went from rural North Carolina to Harvard, but she
understands that she didn't get there on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's humble nature also helped her while researching her
book, said Anthony Dillard, son of N.L. Dillard, Caswell's
principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came from well-respected people, so she inspired trust,''
said Dillard, whose father died in 1969. ``She has a very warm and
engaging personality. She could talk to anyone.'' Walker decided to
write the book a decade ago after hearing Caswell County residents
lamenting the news that the old county school was to be closed.
Their fond recollections stunned her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally remember being on 158 (U.S. 158 in Greensboro)
having this double take,'' Walker said. ``It hit me: `Nothing about
what they're saying matches with anything I know to be true in
academia.' My worlds collided.''
</P>
<P>
   Now those worlds have come full circle. Two pictures tacked on
Walker's office at Emory symbolize her journey. One is a poster
that celebrates the Brown decision. The other is a picture of
Dillard, standing nobly in front of the Caswell County Training
School with his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brown decision was right,'' Walker said. ``I'm not
advocating a return to pre-Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she pointed to the picture of Dillard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the story that hasn't been told,'' she said.
``This picture can exist beside the other without contradiction.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
