<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING DIFFERENT SLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Lewiston and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some drifting flakes:
</P>
<P>
   --Why is it that guys driving 6,000-pound cars on icy roads
think they are exempt from the laws of physics?
</P>
<P>
   --Why is it that 98 percent of the pictures in ski magazines
depict about 2 percent of the skiers?
</P>
<P>
   --The best thing about snowboarding is that your feet don't
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   --Skiing Magazine's top 10 ski towns, Jackson Hole (Wyo.),
Whitefish (Mont.), Steamboat (Colo.), Vail (Colo.), Taos (N.M.),
Stateline (Nev.), Truckee (Calif.), Park City (Utah), Stowe (Vt.),
North Conway (N.H.) overlap only slightly with the Globe Ski
Section's.
</P>
<P>
   --How about these: Montreal, Quebec, Lake Placid (N.Y.), Bolton
Valley (Vt.), Ludlow (Vt.), Warren (Vt.), Jackson (N.H.), Lincoln
(N.H.), Waterville Valley (N.H.), Carrabassett Valley (Maine),
Greenville (Maine), Lennox, and Stockbridge?
</P>
<P>
   --Quiz: Which state in the union has the most ski areas? Answer
below.
</P>
<P>
   --Wise husbands do not play mixed doubles tennis with their
wives, nor should they under any circumstances act as their wives'
ski teachers or trail guides.
</P>
<P>
   --By mathmatical measure, today's skier can get in more than
twice the skiing on a typical day than he could 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Why is it skiers spend much of their winter talking about
sailing, and sailors spend as much time in summer talking about
skiing?
</P>
<P>
   --Notice who calls the skier's fashion shots these days? Yup,
snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   --Does it seem to you that many ski areas are morphing into
amusement parks?
</P>
<P>
   --Salt Lake City may be the best all-around Winter Olympic site
since it all began 75 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Do you also have a hard time imagining Hannes Schneider, Stein
Erikson, Penny Pitou, and Andrea Mead Lawrence wearing ski helmets?
</P>
<P>
   --Ever wonder how much environmental extremism adds to the price
of your lift ticket? All those lawsuits feed a lot of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   --A Ski Magazine observation: ``Ten years ago, no one would have
dreamed that wintersports would be cast in the same light as timber
and mining, rather than as a socially-beneficial form of
recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   --Want your kids to be top ski racers? Get them off the groomed
slopes in their formative years.
</P>
<P>
   --The biggest waste of money in ski country? Now, as always:
lodge cafeteria food.
</P>
<P>
   --This winter's not a bummer; it's the ever-earlier-expectation
hype that makes it seem that way.
</P>
<P>
   --Which reminds me, a warm winter is way worse than a cool
summer.
</P>
<P>
   --The least important ski area statistic? Vertical drop.
</P>
<P>
   --How to experience the downhiller's edge? Says former US Ski
Team member Doug Lewis: sit in a chair in the middle of the floor
and lean back, farther and farther until you're right at the
toppling point. Go back too far, you crash. Not far enough, you're
not even in the race.
</P>
<P>
   --How time schusses: It will be 15 years this winter since Billy
``Red Sleds'' Johnson became the first US skier to win an Olympic
gold medal in downhill.
</P>
<P>
   --Does our ski scene ever miss Picabo Street or what?
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of ski racing, it was America's winningest male,
Phil Mahre, who said if he had weighed more than 135 pounds in high
school he would have played football rather than ski.
</P>
<P>
   --Who cares if people talk on cell phones on the chairlift?
</P>
<P>
   --Lycra may have taken over the winter sports scene, but there's
still no replacing those pretty Norwegian wool sweaters with the
peuter buttons.
</P>
<P>
   --But will someone please tell me the point of an altimeter
watch?
</P>
<P>
   --When I was a kid I'd have hated to have one of those little
skiing walkie-talkies to stay in touch with the rents.
</P>
<P>
   --Unless my pal had the other one.
</P>
<P>
   --And until I needed money for food and video games.
</P>
<P>
   --Quiz answer: New York State, with 56 ski areas.
</P>
<P>
   --Snowmobiles: winter's equivalent of jetskis.
</P>
<P>
   --I'd really like to have Emeril Lagasse over to the apres ski
dinner. He'd kick it up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   --Cross-country skiing in this country could really use another
Bill Koch about now. It's been 23 years since he won Olympic
silver, 17 since he won the overall World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   --And don't forget: The best day of the year to be on the slopes
is New Year's Day, the earlier the better.
</P>
<P>
   --Which raises a further point: If New Year's Eve is for
amateurs, what manner of yahoos are getting all worked up about the
``millennium'' New Year's celebration? One place I know I don't
want to be is the Killington access road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
