<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7838 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV30-     12-23 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV30-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTESSORI WOULD BE PROUD OF HER LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, Dec. 30) 
(Eds: this is the next-to-last Mary Loftus column.) 
(lh) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've had an education this year about a century-old, yet often
misunderstood, legacy: Schools based on the works of Dr. Maria
Montessori.
</P>
<P>
   Both my children are in Montessori schools for the first time:
My 3-year-old in an at-home preschool, and my 8-year-old son in an
elementary program for 6- to 10-year-olds. His second-grade teacher
recommended private school for him this year, sensing his need for
smaller classes, more independent projects and a creative
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's school has a garden planted and harvested by the
students, a wide porch and sun-filled classrooms. But the small
touches are what make it stand apart: the chess set always in use,
the small kitchen where students wash and rinse their lunch plates
and silverware, the list of housekeeping chores. There are no
assigned seats, no grades and no standardized tests. Cooperation is
encouraged _ students often break up into groups to create a book
of nouns, or into pairs to quiz each other on spelling words. It's
such a stimulating environment, almost every parent who sits in on
a lesson says, ``Why couldn't my elementary school have been like
this?''
</P>
<P>
   At the fall harvest celebration, the children had pulled sweet
potatoes from the ground to make muffins and casseroles, and picked
plums from the tree in the corner of the play yard for jam. We
spread blankets on the ground and had homemade lemonade while the
children pulled each other around in a wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe this?'' I kept saying to my mother, who was
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled and said, ``It's like the old one-room school house
your grandmother used to teach in. The older kids help the younger
ones, and you learn life skills as well as academics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Montessori method, developed almost a century ago by the
Italian educator, prides itself on respect for young students and
their innate desire for purposeful work. A common misconception is
that in Montessori schools the child can do anything he wants.
</P>
<P>
   As Adam says: ``Yes, I can do anything I want to, as long as
it's work.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sarah's preschool, she is one of five children taught by Ms.
Sharon in her home, a comforting, orderly place where morning
circle time often involves her playing guitar for a sing-along. The
students learn to wash the table, to pour water, to sound out
letters, and to name, in order, the planets, the days of the week,
the months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the students put on an impromptu puppet show from
behind a quilt thrown over the coffee table. There is quite a bit
of emphasis placed on outside play, manners, helping others and
moving gently.
</P>
<P>
   For Christmas, my children brought home bags from school filled
with apples and tangerines, walnuts and hazelnuts, homemade
cinnamon ornaments and paper chains, hand-painted pots with herbs
for the kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is SO Montessori,'' I said, grinning at my husband.
</P>
<P>
   That long-dead Italian psychiatrist would be proud. In her
words: ``There must be provision for the child to have contact with
Nature, to understand and appreciate the order, the harmony, and
the beauty which are the basis of all sciences and arts.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
