<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Dec. 24 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   NY-CREW-EDUC (New York) _ A sharply-divided Board of Education
voted Thursday not to extend the contract of Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew, heralding the end of Crew's sometimes rocky tenure as
the head of the nation's largest public school system. (Summary
from wires) By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   With: NY-CREW-MAYOR by Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-TALBOTT (Moscow) _ As Russian forces continue to pound
rebel positions in the breakaway region of Chechnya on Thursday,
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott accused Russia of
violating ``international norms'' by treating civilians as
``terrorists.'' Stepping up U.S. criticism of Russia's three-month
war, Talbott wound up two days of meetings with top officials in
Moscow by saying that ``substantial differences, even
disagreements'' remain between the two countries, including over
modifications to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-TRENDS (Undated) _ Online holiday shopping is
increasingly gnawing at the business of traditional retailers this
year, with preliminary indications that seasonal Internet sales may
nearly triple over last year. A New York Times/CBS poll Dec. 17-19
found that 17 percent of Americans said they have bought gifts over
the Internet this holiday season or planned to do so. Only 7
percent said they had shopped for holiday gifts online last year.
By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-SUBURBS (Mayville, South Africa) _ The modest one-room
houses in this fledgling black suburb are the most tangible symbol
of the post-apartheid government's commitment to redressing South
Africa's stark inequalities. And the changing lives within the
brick walls offer an intimate view of the hopes and hardships of
ordinary black people still struggling to climb the economic and
social ladder. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-WORKERS (Miami) _ These are boom times for the cruise
industry. Record numbers of passengers are packing bigger and
grander ships, providing record profits for the dominant lines.
Miami-based Carnival Corp., with 45 ships the world's largest
cruise company, is averaging $2.8 million a day in profits this
year, almost all tax-free because the company is registered in
Panama. But the benefits have been slow to trickle down to the
70,000 or so workers who keep the fleets running and passengers
dining and dancing. Though living conditions have improved, pay for
most has risen little, and some workers say their work has become
more grueling as ships have grown into floating cities bustling
with activity 24 hours a day. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report.
</P>
</TEXT>
