<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT     12-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``STUART LITTLE''
</P>
<P>
   Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie, Jonathan Lipnicki and with the voices
of Michael J. Fox, Nathan Lane, Chazz Palminteri, Steve Zahn
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Minkoff
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, a white digital mouse, gets sprung from a mouse
orphanage and, in Minkoff's adaptation of the E.B. White children's
classic, goes to live with the Little family in their comfy
Manhattan brownstone. Mr. Little ( Laurie) and Mrs. Little (Ms.
Davis) regard Stuart as one of the family, but their young son,
George (Lipnicki), has trouble with the concept. ``He's not my
brother: he's a mouse,'' George tells relatives at a party to
introduce the newest Little, who is neatly dressed, mannerly and
three inches high.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, Stuart wins the boy over with his antics and
friendliness. Then during a model-sailboat race in Central Park, he
grabs the helm of George's craft, named the Wasp (one of several
nice little touches in this film), and guides it to victory.
``That's no mouse, that's my brother,'' George proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   But dissatisfactions remain. The Littles' cat, Snowbell (Lane),
doesn't want it spread around that technically speaking he's now
owned by a mouse. Feeling an empty place within him, Stuart wants
to find his real parents. Eventually these elements combine to work
against him when some street cats, drafted by Snowbell to do away
with Stuart, come up with a phony mother and father to get him away
from the Littles and set up a final game of cat and mouse.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Some very small viewers could be bothered that Stuart
is usually but a gulp away from a cat.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Listen very hard for one mild epithet.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5: Most children will be aware that the story is a
fantasy, but they will feel Stuart's sadness at being separated
from the Littles. In the end, though, they should weather all
tribulations nicely.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-8: Family values will play nicely.
</P>
<P>
   OVER AGE 8: Some viewers will find the film corny, but many
children through the age of 10 or so will be caught by the family
drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANNA AND THE KING''
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Foster, Chow Yun-Fat, Bai Ling, Tom Felton, Keith Chin,
Syed Alwi, Randall Duk Kim
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andy Tennant
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 _ 140 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's 1862 on the Bangkok docks, and riffling through her Siamese
phrase book Anna Leonowens (Ms. Foster) is annoyed not to find a
carriage waiting to carry her and her young son (Tom Felton) to the
palace of King Mongkut (Chow). Soon thereafter his majesty presents
a bigger inconvenience. Instead of one royal son to teach, Anna
will instruct a class full of his children. (He has 58, with 10 on
the way.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you punish me with imperialist schoolteacher?'' the
king's son (Keith Chin) asks his father. In Tennant's film, Anna,
the widow of a British officer, and Mongkut are in territory
claimed in 1956 by Deborah Kerr and Yul Brynner in ``The King and
I.'' What's more, they are without ``Shall We Dance?'' and the rest
of the Rodgers and Hammerstein score.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, adapting itself from Margaret Landon's novel ``Anna and
the King of Siam,'' the film relies on grand settings and a
multicultural sensitivity that allows the pair to spar over customs
and viewpoints in a more worldly fashion as they build their mutual
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   A prim, severe woman with attitude, Anna confronts the king's
repressiveness and the racism and deceitfulness of her own
countrymen. Dabbling in regional affairs, the British are
encouraging murderous incursions along the Burmese border to secure
their commercial interests. Aware of this, Mongkut finds himself in
tight political quarters and facing a coup attempt. No cause for
singing.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Considerable and realistic. A young woman, having run
back to her lover after being taken as a royal wife, is caned
bloody. Later she and the young man are beheaded in a ritualistic
execution that spares viewers the actual sword swipes and in some
ways is the more chilling for it.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 8: A bad idea. The violence and complexity will upset
and bore them.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-10: Again, remember that this is no musical. Given that,
many children will relate to such issues as parental control and
forces crowding the family from outside.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-14: Reactions will vary, but generally teen-agers take
to stories of rebellion. Political and moral issues will be of
interest, though the arguments are pedantic. Many viewers will want
Ms. Foster to lighten up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``BICENTENNIAL MAN''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz, Sam Neill, Oliver Platt,
Kiersten Warren, Wendy Crewson
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Chris Columbus
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 132 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew, a cheerful and industrious robot working as a
household servant, makes an intricate little wooden carving it
occurs to his master, called Sir (Neill), that Andrew has creative
impulses that go beyond the robotic.
</P>
<P>
   In a story adapted from Isaac Asimov's novel, the robot's
manufacturer says it's an anomaly and wants it back. But Sir
insists on keeping it to see what develops. Andrew, who looks
something like Williams, is particularly fond of Sir's 7-year-old
daughter, Little Miss (Hallie Kate Eisenberg). Years pass. Little
Miss has a crush on Andrew, now a clockmaker, but says she can't
invest her emotions in a machine and marries a mortal.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew wants his thoughts and feelings to show on his face so he
finds a genius (Platt) who mixes a batch of glop that when spread
across robotic facial wiring looks exactly like Williams. Andrew,
financially well-off from clock sales, becomes independent but
always yearns to be even more human.
</P>
<P>
   Generations pass into a science-fiction future. Andrew meets
Portia (Ms. Davidtz), Little Miss' granddaughter, and thanks to
regular upgrades he now has all the emotions to fall in love. But
to marry he needs to be recognized as human, so he petitions a kind
of United Nations to grant him certification. That raises several
interesting bioengineering issues (one elderly judge has as many
mechanical parts inside him as Andrew has human). Is there hope for
this couple?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: When they are children, Little Miss' sister tries to
destroy Andrew by ordering him to jump out a window.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Sir teaches Andrew the facts of life. ``People actually do
this, Sir?'' the robot asks. Years later he embraces the practice
enthusiastically and talks about it frankly. While he and Portia go
to bed, his performance is not recorded.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: A little.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6: Too much for the very young.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-9: They should begin to understand Andrew's development,
which is not unlike what they are beginning to experience.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12: Ditto only more so.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP: Not one to spare the sentimentality, Williams
waxes strong near the end of the film. By then, though, many
teen-agers (not all) will be hooked by other questions and
developments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
