<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CARPET26-COX     12-23 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARPET26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Commercial carpet market looking brighter
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The anemic commercial carpet market is showing signs
of a comeback as it heads into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   An upswing in office projects coupled with a wave of new
floor-covering products are pumping more life into the sector.
Sales of residential carpet have been strong, thanks to a healthy
housing market, but demand for commercial floor covering has been
soft this year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said fear of a possible recession earlier this year put
a dent in corporate demand. And corporate pocketbooks were
stretched thin because of Y2K preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercial (carpet) market has been constantly looking
over its shoulder,'' said analyst Lorraine Miller of SunTrust
Equitable Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The sector, however, can look forward to a brighter 2000.
Corporate projects have picked up in the past two months, and that
translates into higher sales next year, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are forecasting a 5 percent increase in sales of
commercial floor coverings next year. Commercial sales this year
are projected at about $3.5 billion, a 1 percent decrease from
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sluggish market for commercial flooring, Georgia's
carpet companies are wrapping up their strongest year ever. Total
sales are projected to rise 4 percent over last year's $15.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street is concerned that the industry will not be able
to maintain the momentum. Share prices have plunged 40 percent this
year for the top two manufacturers, Dalton, Ga.-based Shaw
Industries and Calhoun-based Mohawk Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the market is bothered by rising interest rates,''
said analyst John Baugh of First Union Securities. Rising interest
rates could put a damper on homebuilding and commercial
development.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has pushed rates higher this year to temper
the overheating economy. But investors fear the effect will be a
damper on home-buying, which would take a bite out of demand for
floor covering.
</P>
<P>
   Given the size and breadth of the carpet giants, Wall Street may
be overreacting, Baugh said. Still, manufacturers have been
steadily diversifying to rely less on one sector, a trend that's
most prevalent among commercial floor-covering products.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the commercial carpet industry has been dominated by
broadloom carpet and carpet tiles sold to corporate office
customers. But a new wave of products outside the traditional
carpet realm has emerged. Schools, health care and retail offer new
opportunities for growth, manufacturers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of surfaces out there that aren't carpeted,
and the industry is going after them in a big way,'' said Baugh.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Interface contends it has created a product that
will compete with vinyl tiles and hard flooring prevalent in
hospitals and schools. Both markets have shunned carpet because of
its tendency to harbor bodily fluids and germs.
</P>
<P>
   Solenium, which hit the market in the summer, features a new
type of synthetic fiber that resists stains and odor. It's
extremely easy to clean, Interface says, and it muffles noise
better than hard surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concentrating on the health care market first, but after
that we'll go after schools and retailers,'' said John Wells,
president and chief executive of Interface Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high in those markets. For example, health care
facilities and schools spend $1.5 billion a year in floor
coverings, according to Interface. The company estimates that
Solenium could become a $100 million business for over the next
five years. First-year sales will reach nearly $5 million for 1999,
Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Interface will continue to market its core
carpet-tile products to office buildings and other commercial
customers. Almost half of Interface's revenue comes from
modular-tile sales. The rest comes mainly from broadloom carpet,
interior fabrics and raised flooring.
</P>
<P>
   Modular tiles, which are popular because companies can replace a
section of the carpet instead of the entire room, are taking market
share from broadloom carpet.
</P>
<P>
   With a focus on carpet tiles, Dalton-based Collins &AMP; Aikman
Floorcoverings has grown from a small niche player to one of
Georgia's leading commercial carpet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Collins &AMP; Aikman, which built its business on recycled carpet,
has been targeting education and health care customers for years.
The manufacturer has recently entered the retail and high-end
corporate market.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Collins &AMP; Aikman bought two companies to expand its
product line. The acquisitions of Santa Ana, Calif.-based Monterey
Carpets and Nova Scotia-based Crossley Carpet Mills gave Collins &AMP;
Aikman a line of high-end products. The new broadloom offerings
mean the company can get a bigger share of corporate projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In executive offices and boardrooms, companies want stylish
carpet,'' said Mac Bridger, president and chief executive at
Collins &AMP; Aikman. ``They would typically go to another manufacturer
for that. Now, we can fill a broad range of needs, from the
boardroom to the mailroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohawk has added both high-end and lower-price products. Mohawk
recently started making carpet tiles at a new mill in Dublin to
beef up its midpriced products. The tiles are being marketed to
schools, hospitals, airports and some retailers, said Frank
Procopio, president of Mohawk Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Like smaller manufacturers, Mohawk and Dalton-based Shaw have
been beefing up fashion products to target the high-end corporate
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always tried to improve performance and value, but in
the past few years we've also concentrated on style and design,''
said Hal Long, executive vice president of Shaw Contract.
</P>
<P>
   A spate of hotel renovation and casino construction is spurring
demand for high-fashion carpet. The hotel sector is one of the
fastest-growing for Shaw's commercial business, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   The carpet industry has become more complex with the new
emphasis on design and fashion, noted Procopio. Unlike the
residential side of the business, in which the manufacturers strike
alliances with retailers, the commercial sales force has to
continually court interior designers and architects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a project-by-project business. You can do a great job,
and the designers will remember that, but that doesn't mean you're
going to land the next project,'' Procopio said. ``You've got to
convince each team that you've got what they need on each job. A
lot of what we do comes down to relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
