<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WEB-CHURCHES-COX     12-23 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CHURCHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet church sites help believers extend religion's reach
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _About two years ago, Pastor Mac Richard started
up a church in much the same way that houses of spirituality have
begun for millennia. Fifteen people joined in Richard's living
room. On that day, a gathering became a congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Lake Hills Church has grown to several hundred
members who attend Sunday services, where live music and Pastor
Richard's up-tempo sermons cater to a tech-savvy audience of teens
and twenty-somethings. Richard, an intense and friendly presence
with close-cropped blond hair and a wide grin, says Lake Hills
Church is going for something a little post-modern in its search to
attract new members to the flock. There is the clean, well-designed
Web site that looks like it could be a portal for an up-and-coming
startup. There is the Sunday service itself, playfully called
``Church 2.0.'' Glossy leaflets for the service invite would-be
parishioners to ``plug and play into meaningful worship.''
</P>
<P>
   The church has no brick-and-mortar foundation. Richard and two
other pastors work in a small office off Mopac and Loop 360. The
services take place at Westlake High School's Fine Arts Facility.
And increasingly, Pastor Richard's message is being delivered on
the Internet, where members stay in touch through an e-mail
newsletter and a continually updated Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically a virtual church,'' Richard said. ``We saw the
Web as a way to get the word out about what God is doing through
our church.''
</P>
<P>
   In the increasingly crowded din of the Internet, religious Web
sites are becoming nearly as popular as the mainstays of Web
traffic _ pornography and finance sites. Using nearly any search
engine, typing ``God'' will bring up nearly as many Web sites as
the word ``sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that religious organizations have flocked to the
Internet zealously, seeing it as a cheap, fast and extremely
effective way to educate members of their churches as well as bring
in new people curious to begin a spiritual journey that starts
online.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Schultze, a researcher who for decades has studied the
link between religion and the media, said religion and the Internet
grew together with the explosion of the Net. ``If you look at the
history of film and television, you see that religious groups
tended to stay out of those media early. However, if you look at
the Web, you see just the opposite. It was the Web that really
launched the Gutenbergian revolution on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as Lake Hills Church say they can reach many
more people on the Net and provide services like posting sermons
soon after they happen or even streaming video to those who are
disabled and can't make it to church every week.
</P>
<P>
   But, Schultze said, the danger to organized religion is that the
online evangelization of religion may further fragment major
religions. ``The Web tends to undermine existing religious
authority and institutions. In fact, a lot of what is happening
with the use of the Web is dissidents within a denomination who are
organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Little churches, big Web sites
</P>
<P>
   Max Virdell, a large man with long brown hair, a full beard and
a minister's collar, entered the ranks of the ordained one day
after reading an article in Yahoo Internet Life magazine that told
him he could become a priest online.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, with divinity degrees from the World Christianship
Ministry and the Universal Life Church, he started up The Little
Church on the Web. Like the Lake Hills Church, Virdell has no
physical walls to his church. He maintains the site on a Sony
computer in his small North Austin apartment. He invites users to
pray, learn about his beliefs, and read sermons he may type up at 3
a.m. and post whenever the mood strikes him. Members of the Little
Church don't physically meet _ Virdell may speak in his site's chat
room or e-mail directly with those in need.
</P>
<P>
   Virdell, who is a great admirer of Billy Graham, fought and won
to get tax-exempt status for his virtual church from the state
comptroller's office. He also enjoys tax exemption from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The low-tech site, with its pictures of cherubs and multicolored
typefaces, is every bit as legitimate as the established churches
with the niceties of pews, stained glass and formal gathering,
Virdell says.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Virdell says he's always had a hard time finding the
right niche for his beliefs and he believes there are many like him
out there who may come away with a positive experience after
visiting the Little Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in a great need of a spiritual revival in this
country,'' Virdell said. ``This is about having a relationship with
God. I think you can have that without getting dressed up on Sunday
and going to church.''
</P>
<P>
   For the small church, the Internet has opened up a way to
compete with churches that traditionally have had much larger
congregations and, consequently, larger budgets for promotion,
events and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ethical Society of Austin, a 5-year-old group that
meets regularly to discuss ethics across different religious
persuasions, started its Web site, it got the help of some IBM
workers who are part of the group. Gordon Fossum, the Webmaster of
the Ethical Society's site, said he posts information about
upcoming events and meetings and uses the site to educate people on
the little-known group. ``The Web site is an integrated effort to
reach out to folks. We're just a small group trying to explain to
people that you can exist in our society and act in an ethical
manner without God at the rudder of your moral sailboat.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard said Lake Hills Church has been able to reach a large
audience by spending a fraction of the cost for traditional
mail-outs. ``If you direct-mail 32,000 people, it can cost up to
$10,000. For a Web site, we spent about $750 to $1,000'' to set up
lhc.org. For that price, he said, his church has the potential to
reach an unlimited number of people.
</P>
<P>
   The site, Richard said, promotes the idea that church doesn't
have to be a once-a-week experience. ``We send out an e-mail letter
called `The Connection.' It's another way for people to feel
connected Monday through Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   IN Rome
</P>
<P>
   Several floors below the place where Pope John Paul II sleeps,
the Vatican's Web site is housed. It is run on machines called
Raphael, Michael and Gabriel. The woman who has run the site,
Sister Judith Zoebelein, is an American who sees it a mission to
evangelize via the Net. The organization she answers to even sounds
like a tech firm _ the Vatican Information Service.
</P>
<P>
   If you look around the Vatican's site, which appears with a
parchment-style background and is available in six languages, you
can find video, audio, archives, news and information about the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Internet started as a haven for pornography and arcane
information for tech-heads and researchers, Mark Kellner, author of
the book ``God on the Internet,'' says organized religions have
found they have to brave the Internet, and in the next century they
won't have a choice. ``If there's a church or church leadership
that isn't in step with what's going on online, I can't see how
they'll survive much beyond the next 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner, who also writes for the Washington Times, said
organizations such as the Vatican expect to combat the negative
influences of the Internet by beating it with their own technology.
</P>
<P>
   He compares it to William Booth's use of drinking songs to
promote virtue. ``Booth says, `Why should the Devil have the best
music?''' Kellner said. ``I think the most perceptive people in
religion today should raise the question, `Why should the Devil
have the best Web sites?'''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fostering communication, the Internet is also a
way to reinforce ``brand loyalty'' to a particular sect and to
evangelize on a scale that not even Billy Graham could physically
match. Kellner foresees the rise of ``cafeteria-style religion,''
in which many people will be able to wander through a spiritual
journey online, finding the pieces that will reinforce or enlighten
them on particular sets of beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Kellner hopes the sheer amount of information
available will create a better environment for religious dialogue.
``The biggest reason for religious prejudice is fear of the
unknown,'' he said. ``I hope it will create a world where we
understand each other a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
