<HEADER>
A7850 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BALLOT-COX     12-23 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP luring voters with school prayer initiative
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Republican Party leaders are adding to the
March 14 primary ballot a question they figure could draw more GOP
voters to the polls: Should student-initiated prayer be allowed
before school sporting events?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since a New Orleans federal appeals court answered no to
that question earlier this year, and with the U.S. Supreme Court
scheduled to consider the issue next spring, the issue has become a
hot-button topic among Republican conservatives and the religious
right.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting earlier this month, the State Republican Executive
Committee voted to include the nonbinding ballot referendum _
called the Texas Religious Freedom Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, both parties have used such referendums to try
and boost turnout at their primaries _ on issues ranging from
gambling to term limits to concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that goes to the very heart of the rights and
freedoms of Texas students guaranteed in the United States
Constitution,'' said Susan Weddington, head of the Republican Party
of Texas. ``We cannot allow an out-of-control, activist judiciary
to sacrifice our freedoms at the altar of politically correct,
modern-day liberalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Black, the Republican Party spokesman, said the
referendum is an opportunity for GOP voters to express their
opinion about a Feb. 26 decision by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals to ban voluntary, student-initiated prayer at school
sporting events. ``This is basic, basic freedom ... and this is an
opportunity for the public to have a voice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are two court decisions that grew out of complaints by
two families about prayers before football games in Santa Fe, Texas
_ a small town outside Houston. In May 1995, a federal judge
restricted voluntary student-initiated prayer and ruled that prayer
at athletic events and graduation ceremonies was permissible with
court-ordered restrictions on the content of those prayers.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the New Orleans-based appeals court banned
student-initiated prayer altogether at football games. An appeal of
that decision is before the U.S. Supreme Court. Tim Turner, a
Houston member of the State Republican Executive Committee, said
the referendum is intended only as a straw poll, and not to
influence the Supreme Court which is to hear the case within weeks
after the primary. ``It is an issue I think most Texans can relate
to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other GOP officials, Turner predicts the referendum will
pass.
</P>
<P>
   While Tom Moon, a Houston member of the State Republican
Executive Committee who presented the referendum proposal with
Turner, has predicted the ballot question could draw additional
voter turnout, Travis County Republican Chair Becky Motal says she
has heard little discussion about it so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are focused on the presidential race and the other
races that will be on the ballot,'' she said. ``We will have
probably 30 people on the ballot (in Travis County). It will be a
very active ballot.'' Texas Democratic party Chair Molly Beth
Malcolm on Thursday denounced the GOP referendum as ``a slap in the
face of religious freedom and spirituality.'' While most Democrats
support the right of students to initiate prayer at school
activities, she said, the referendum insinuates that Republicans
have a monopoly on religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cheap advertising ploy to rally right-wing
supporters.'' Malcolm said. ``Many Texans are deeply committed to
their religious faith and spiritual convictions, but they do not
condone the exploitation of religion for cheap political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
