<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-SECURITY24-COX     12-23 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SECURITY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security officers at premium for New
 &HT;    Year's jobs
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Companies that haven't secured extra security guards
for New Year's duty by now can forget it. Those that do have extra
help are paying dearly for it.
</P>
<P>
   The double threats of possible Y2K computer glitches and fears
of terrorism have boosted business for security firms this year.
With the new year a week away, many of them are booked solid. Some
have even had to turn away business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking any more work for Y2K,'' said Randy
Blackwell, a scheduler for Wackenhut Security Corp. in DeKalb
County, Ga. ``Between now and the end of the year, it's going to be
hard to find enough (people) or get them trained in time. We're at
ground zero now in terms of hiring any extras to help us for Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law requires five to eight days of training before a
person can become a security guard and a month of training and
several days of background checks for those who carry firearms.
</P>
<P>
   For security guards already on the job, Y2K work is a bonanza.
Many will be ringing in the New Year making overtime and double
time. Wackenhut's 500 Atlanta-area guards will get an average of
$20 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incentive to get them to work,'' Blackwell said.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Wackenhut will be billing its customers, which range
from high-tech firms to convenience stores, at a rate of $34 an
hour, double the normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   The hectic holiday in the security business is the latest
example of a region bulging with jobs and few people to fill them.
Security firms, retailers and other employers in the service
industries hired extra seasonal workers, triggering a drop to
record low of 2.8 percent unemployment in November for the metro
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest problems is with the unemployment rate so
low, we can't find many people. There's so many (competing) jobs
out there,'' said Kelly Davison, office manager for Pro-Tec
Security Services Inc. in Norcross. ``We've had to turn down a lot
of requests for service because we don't have the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 25 guards, Davison said the company is focusing on
providing extra help to its longtime clients, which include car
dealers, churches, banks and a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Guardian Security, on Powers Ferry Road in Atlanta,
expects to pay a lot of overtime to its 240 guards to secure banks,
plants and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year, the wages are outrageous,'' says Paul
Santana, Guardian's vice president of operations. ``In order to get
people, we're paying $15 to $16. We're not finding enough people.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency doesn't end with security guards.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hot pursuit for all sorts of workers: caterers, sales
clerks, waiters and waitresses. In downtown Atlanta, Mick's
restaurant and Wherehouse Music have help-wanted signs posted.
</P>
<P>
   Even baby sitters in metro Atlanta are commanding anywhere from
$20 to $50 an hour to work New Year's Eve. In other parts of the
country, the going rate for baby sitters on New Year's Eve has
reached the-unheard-of sum of $300 for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that use our service have children and want to make
this a big event,'' said Terri Durshimer of TLC Sitters of Atlanta
in Smyrna.
</P>
<P>
   TLC is charging $20 an hour, double its normal rate. ``Some of
the caregivers are not willing to give up the night for family or
sentimental reasons,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who will be working will be in homes where
families are hosting parties and need someone to watch a group of
children, Durshimer said.
</P>
<P>
   One metro area couple said they are paying five times the normal
rate for a private sitter in their home.
</P>
<P>
   _Staff writer Derrick Henry contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
