<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-23 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K FRENZY A TEST OF COMMON SENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of wild speculation, outrageous predictions of a
global silicon meltdown and dire warnings of a digital apocalypse,
the end of the 1999 is finally here. In a week, the world's
computers face the daunting task of figuring out what 00 means.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 bug, better known as Y2K, has been squashed, at
least in the United States, according to most experts who've been
bird-dogging the situation. What happens overseas remains a
question, but it appears that the nation most reliant on high tech
has wrestled the problem to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   We hope, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Although calamities are unlikely, irritations are almost
certain. Chances are, someone's going to get billed for goods or
services dating back to 1900 _ with interest. The older PCs of many
home users will default to 1980 _ Year One in the internal clock
for the IBM-compatible computer _ which could play havoc with all
those old copies of Quicken that cheapskates have refused to
upgrade since, oh, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But most of these glitches will be found and dealt with in short
order, and life will go on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PROBLEM HAS BEEN ADDRESSED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's important to remember that most businesses and governments
have been coping with 2000 dates for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Reach into your wallet and pull out some credit cards. Note the
expiration dates that end in 00 or later. The banks and businesses
that issued them already are billing for 2000 dates. Some
businesses, the federal and some local governments currently are in
their 2000 fiscal years, so their computers also have been working
with double-aughts for some time.
</P>
<P>
   What is of most concern to those who've been watching Y2K play
out is the idea that people may overreact to something that's not
Y2K-related, but assume that it is.
</P>
<P>
   This is known as ``background noise'' _ the concept that there
are system failures happening to computers and the infrastructure
of everyday life all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, that a little after midnight on Jan. 1, a
car skids off an icy road somewhere and knocks down a power pole. A
neighborhood's power goes out, and residents there panic, thinking
power is out to the whole city.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Y2K had nothing to do with that accident _ unless the
driver is a computer technician who had one too many eggnogs while
celebrating a successful Y2K fix of his system _ but the folks left
in the dark don't know that. All they figure is, after months of
scare stories in the press and talking to that loony neighbor down
the street who's stockpiled water, guns and a year's worth of
canned peaches, the end obviously must be near.
</P>
<P>
   This whole problem could be aggravated by broadcasters who,
itching for some sexy Y2K news to report, decide to break into
regular programming to announce that power is failing everywhere
because of the Millennium Bug.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PERCEPTION CLOUDS REALITY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem related to Y2K, in other words, is likely to
be one of perception rather than reality. Grocery stores are not
likely to be out of food because their computers couldn't place
orders for them. Instead, they're more likely to be low on food
because people began hoarding.
</P>
<P>
   (Notice that financial analysts who cover the grocery industry
have quit talking about Y2K problems and now are talking about the
profits stores will make if the public goes bonkers. That should
tell you something ... )
</P>
<P>
   And the phone company, rather than warning that the telephone
network might not work, is urging people not to pick up the phone
at midnight to test it. The reason: Every time you get a dial tone,
even if you don't make a call, you use up a switch in the network.
There are a finite number of switches _ far fewer than the number
of actual phone lines _ and if too many people pick up the phone
out of curiosity at midnight, some will not hear dial tones.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing to keep in mind about Y2K is a key
phrase in Douglas Adams' classic novel ``The Hitchhiker's Guide to
the Galaxy'': Don't panic. Think about what's going on and what the
other causes may be before you decide that the world is coming to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, there's another phrase you should keep in mind:
Be smart.
</P>
<P>
   There are some simple things you can do to shield yourself
against the irritating little things that are more likely to happen
as a result of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read the main feature story on this page and use it to get
your own personal computer up to Y2K speed if you have not already.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have records of your own that are tied to
electronically held records elsewhere, then make physical copies of
them. For example, if you do electronic banking, then print out a
statement to have in case there are disputes with your bank.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many ATMs will print out a bank statement for you, and if you
don't do electronic banking, this is a quick, simple way to get the
paperwork you may need.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the receipts for every credit card transaction that may
show up on your January bill. And keep copies of all your December
credit card statements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay close attention to any legal or governmental documents
sent to you, such as license renewals, land records, tax bills and
so on. Keep an eye out for strange numbers or dates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay out of the yard of your nutty neighbor with the
guns-and-peaches stockpile for a few weeks. He's apt to be testy,
no matter what happens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
