<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-Y2K-HNS &LR;      12-23 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CARE OF THAT TURN-OF-THE-CENTURY BUG SHOULDN'T BE TOO
DIFFICULT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the bad news: If you have not yet tackled the issue of
making your home or small-business personal computer ready for
2000, your time is almost up.
</P>
<P>
   This is one deadline that's hard and fast.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good news: Fixing Y2K problems in a personal
computer is not difficult. It just takes a little time and an
organized approach.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry experts say that when it comes to the PC the
Y2K bug is more of an annoyance than anything else. A personal
computer is not going to become a nonfunctioning block of metal,
glass and plastic Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it may report dates oddly. Programs that rely heavily
on dates, if they are not Y2K-compliant, may alter important data.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, however, should be rare. Experts estimate that 90
percent of PCs can handle 2000 as a date. In some older computers,
users may have to correct the date manually every time they boot
up, rather than having the system handle it for them.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Y2K bug has been a reality for personal computers
since the creation of the original IBM PC in 1981, the PC industry
only began tackling the problem in earnest in the mid-1990s. Most
computer companies say that products purchased in 1997 and on
should be considered Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in a personal computer begins in the interaction
between two components _ the BIOS and the real-time clock.
</P>
<P>
   The BIOS, which stands for Basic Input Output System, handles
the simplest functions of the computer. It is the BIOS, for
example, that starts the process of launching operating systems
such as Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The real-time clock's function is to keep track of the time and
date. The root of the Y2K problem in a PC lies in the fact that the
year is only expressed as two digits in the real-time clock.
</P>
<P>
   When the computer is turned on, the BIOS gets the time and date
information from the clock. When software programs need to know the
date for some function, they ask the BIOS, which then supplies the
century information.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest PCs, BIOSes didn't ``know'' about the 21st
century. For these systems, the real-time clock's turnover to the
year 2000 made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike bigger computers, PCs usually don't interpret 00 as
1900. On those machines that can't handle 2000 as a year, users
likely will see Jan. 1, 1980, which is considered ``Year Zero'' for
personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem does not affect Apple Computer's Macintosh per se,
but some Macintosh software may have Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, computer makers have come up with fixes for the
BIOS problems, and they are making use of the Internet and its
World Wide Web to deliver those fixes. Most of what you need you
can find online at specific vendors' Web sites _ nearly all have a
special Y2K area set up to discuss the readiness of their products.
</P>
<P>
   Software and hardware manufacturers say there is a series of
steps PC owners can take to make sure 2000 rolls around smoothly:
</P>
<P>
   Begin by determining whether your personal computer's hardware
is capable of handling 2000 as a valid year.
</P>
<P>
   Check first with the maker of your PC. Many computer makers have
posted on their Web sites Y2K-compliance information about their
products. In some cases, every machine they've ever made is listed.
</P>
<P>
   If you own an off-brand PC, or one that was home-built,
determine who made the motherboard _ the main system board in the
computer _ and contact that vendor. Many clone systems come with a
manual for the motherboard that should provide contact information.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't determine who made the motherboard, you can at
least find out the maker of the BIOS. When your PC is first turned
on, the brand and model number of the BIOS appear briefly.
</P>
<P>
   You can always try to determine on your own if your PC is
Y2K-compliant with a simple and obvious test. Advance the system
clock to 11:55 p.m. on Dec. 31, 1999, then shut down the computer.
Turn it back on 15 minutes later. If the date is shown as Jan. 1,
2000, then the hardware is ready for the new century.
</P>
<P>
   There also are software programs that will test a PC. One of
them is available as a free download from the National Software
Testing Laboratory at www.nstl.com/html/nstly2k.html.
</P>
<P>
   Computers that won't handle 2000 don't necessarily have to be
doorstops. Some BIOSes can be upgraded to make them compliant _
manufacturers make these patches available online or through
technical support services.
</P>
<P>
   For computers that have BIOSes that can't be upgraded, there are
software drivers that can be inserted into a system's config.sys
file. These patches can be used with very old PCs _ in some cases,
they will work with computers that use the Intel 80286 processor,
circa 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A generic version of the driver is available from some
commercial software publishers. Symantec's Norton 2000 program
includes one, for example, and it's also available as a free
download at www.symantec.com/sabu/n2000/n2000ret/.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do the same kind of research on your operating system. All of
Microsoft's operating systems have some problems _ mostly minor _
with 2000 as a year.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes Windows 98, the company's newest. In fact, one
of the marketing draws for the release earlier this year of Windows
98 Second Edition was that it included Y2K patches that have been
issued for Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also has released stand-alone Y2K patches for Windows
95, 98 and NT, as well as including them in larger updates known as
service packs. But MS-DOS and Windows 3.1 are considered legacy
operating systems and Microsoft has released only limited fixes for
them. Consider upgrading to one of the newer versions if you are
still using DOS or Windows 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it's important to make sure you have the latest patches
for your operating system. Several fixes in the latest service pack
for Windows NT 4.0 are required to bring it into Y2K compliance,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Year 2000 Web site is at www.microsoft.com/year2000.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent versions of IBM's OS/2 operating system, Warp 3
and 4, also require available patches to be Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Most versions of Unix either are or can be made Y2K compliant,
including Linux, the increasingly popular Unix-like operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a list of your frequently used software, starting with
the ones that are most important to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a home-PC owner, that might include your personal
finance program, your e-mail software and any productivity titles
you use, such as a word processor or a spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   A small business owner would look at accounting and inventory
packages, spreadsheets and databases, word processors and
communications software.
</P>
<P>
   Most up-to-date software applications are Y2K-compliant. Some
companies have issued software patches to make older versions of
their titles compliant, but others require users to upgrade to the
latest version.
</P>
<P>
   Check the Web site of the software publishers in question, or
contact the companies' phone technical support. As with operating
systems, make sure you have the most recent upgrades to your
current applications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the documents you've made with those applications.
</P>
<P>
   Are you using two digits to indicate the year in your
spreadsheets and word processing documents? Better change those to
four digits. And if you exchanged spreadsheet or other data-file
information with other businesses, alert them to your changes as
well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be wary of any Y2K ``fixes'' that may be sent unsolicited to
you via e-mail. Anti-virus experts warn users to expect a flurry of
malicious software masquerading as Year 2000 patches.
</P>
<P>
   In general, it's a good idea to delete any executable files that
you didn't request, even if they come from people you know. Many
viruses replicate by attachments sent by e-mail in a way that the
sender doesn't know it's happened.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of unsolicited Microsoft Word documents, which
can contain macro viruses. If you receive an unsolicited Word
document, delete it and ask the sender to re-transmit the
information in text-only format.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
