A7861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CIDER24-COX     12-23 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CIDER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pruning of story for big screen reduces `Cider' appeal
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ John Irving so despised last year's adaptation of
``A Prayer for Owen Meany'' that he refused to allow the filmmakers
to use his name or that of the book and its characters, resulting
in the rechristened ``Simon Birch.''
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed novelist took a much more active role in
translating ``The Cider House Rules'' to the screen. Irving wrote
the screenplay himself and reportedly demanded director and cast
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Academy Award-nominee Lasse Hallstrom, the film is
the most successful adaptation of one of Irving's works since
1982's ``The World According to Garp.'' However, the 500-page-plus
historical novel proves to be an unwieldy subject even for its
author.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet, touching drama is very much a surface reading of the
epic coming-of-age tale about an orphan, Homer Wells (Tobey
Maguire), who is searching to find his place and purpose in the
world. The 1985 novel's time frame has been condensed, and a number
of subplots were trimmed because of the demands of cinematic
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``The Cider House Rules'' retains the central story
but lacks a strong narrative structure. The plot doesn't really
kick in until the second half of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Homer has been raised in pre-World War II-era Maine by Dr.
Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who heads the St. Cloud's orphanage.
Trained as a doctor by Larch, who treats Homer like a son, the
young man helps deliver unwanted babies and looks after the
abandoned children. However, moral qualms prevent Homer from
helping Larch with the illegal abortions that he performs, despite
the latter's reasoning that he is saving lives by preventing women
from being butchered by back-alley abortionists.
</P>
<P>
   When a young pilot, Wally Worthington (Paul Rudd), and his
pregnant girlfriend, Candy Kendall (Charlize Theron), visit St.
Cloud's for an abortion, Homer seizes the chance to leave with the
couple. He happily finds work in the apple orchard owned by Wally's
family, producing cider with Mr. Rose (Delroy Lindo) and his crew
of migrant workers after Wally goes off to war.
</P>
<P>
   Larch discovers he is to be ousted from the orphanage and wants
Homer to return and take his place. Having found love and
acceptance, Homer refuses _ until a series of difficult situations
force him to make tough decisions about the direction his life will
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' is classic Irving, featuring the
colorful characters and tragic twists of fate that are hallmarks of
the author's work. The story is warm and gentle, but conservative
viewers may be turned off by its pro-choice stance on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire (``Pleasantville''), one of Hollywood's best young
actors, does a fine job as Irving's wide-eyed hero. British actor
Caine adopts a convincing American dialect, and the lovely Theron
(``The Astronaut's Wife'') delivers her most appealing performance
to date.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the novel may still be disappointed. The story has lost
much of its flavor by being reduced to its core.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
