<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BOYS24-COX     12-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOYS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dreams of a new life turn tragic in `Boys'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If Matt Damon dropped 50 pounds, he would look a
lot like Hilary Swank. In the redneck horror story ``Boys Don't
Cry,'' the gamine Swank plays a 21-year-old man-boy who's full of
sweet swagger and has a mouth that stops traffic. Her Brandon Teena
is cadaver-thin, marking a powerful jawline that accommodates
water-balloon lips. When he smiles, those lips part like soft
curtains to reveal a toothy colonnade a mile wide. She, er, he, is
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   In this true story that unfolded in Nebraska in 1993, the
``man'' Brandon Teena (who was born the woman Teena Brandon; stick
with me) racked up an unlikely streak of female paramours, bundled
together with a string of brazen lies. Teena, we're told, wrestled
with a sexual identity crisis. At one point in the film she insists
she's a he-- maphrodite; at another she says she wants a sex-change
operation.
</P>
<P>
   She's complicated, but ``Boys Don't Cry'' unfortunately makes no
effort to suss out this unisex question mark. We have to take her
issues for whatever they may be (was she gay? bi? abused as a
child? dying to see what the men's room looks like?) without
motivational signposts.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed and co-written with studied compassion by
Kimberly Peirce, hews closely to the story told in last year's
documentary ``The Brandon Teena Story,'' though it telescopes
chronology and twiddles some facts. This may annoy viewers,
especially the lesbian overtones Peirce fastens to her version.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Boys Don't Cry'' so compelling _ makes you want to
take the journey wherever it may go no matter how horrible _ is a
uniformly magnetic cast that animates the grungy real-life
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a linear body shy on contours, Teena accomplished her
subterfuge with a transformation into a beguiling androgyne. She
cut her hair, strapped down her breasts, stuffed a sock in her
Levi's, and put some schwing in her step. (She becomes a bird-size
Damon.) Brandon's absolute lack of five o'clock stubble evidently
raised no flags with the smitten young women with whom he rubbed
cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need for our suspension of disbelief; Brandon's
conquests really happened, with the girls none the wiser. Swank's
remarkable De Niro-esque metamorphosis, which has been trailing
Oscar buzz for months, erases your incredulity. You can see why
these girls fell for Brandon. Knowing what we know, it's
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys'' doesn't show us Brandon's early chain of girlfriends.
It focuses on his last relationship with a girl named Lana, played
by druggy-faced Chloe Sevigny with a tough, languid fervency.
Sevigny gives a terrific performance, so cool and organically
nuanced, its impact registers as an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' would be a stronger movie had the filmmakers
walked us up to the point that Teena decided to become Brandon.
Instead it begins with her leaving Omaha for rural Falls City,
where she plans to escape a lie-littered past and start fresh. The
excitement in her eyes portends the euphoria and danger that awaits
her. She glows with the high of liberation. She has lived her life
in parentheses, and now, at last, she's going to live out loud.
</P>
<P>
   In Falls City Brandon befriends a rough group of partiers that
includes Lana, belligerent ex-convict John (a frightening Peter
Sarsgaard) and dim-witted Tom (Brendan Sexton III in his best
performance). These are bored people, marking their time with fast
driving and heavy drinking (having these Nebraskans drink Austin's
Celis beer is a gaffe, even if the film was shot in Dallas). Not
until Brandon's past catches up to him do they suspect his sexual
orientation is a hoax. The results are explosive and sickening.
</P>
<P>
   Peirce tells the story with quiet understanding and empathy,
avoiding the misstep of making Brandon a martyr, even if he is
destined for martyrdom in the name of intolerance, small-mindedness
and hate.
</P>
<P>
   Peirce has style. She uses visual motifs, such as time-exposure
tricks and persistent shots of open rural highways speeding past,
to conjure the idea of escape. Her voluptuous evocation of place _
the dusty farm roads, T-shirts and flannel, large American cars _
is on par with Gus Van Sant's knack for rural tableaux.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a complaint it's that the movie offers no narrative
surprises you wouldn't anticipate given the well-publicized case
facts. Its power is built-in. The facts alone will leave you
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
