<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LIBERTY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Liberty' glosses over travails of Jewish life
 &HT;    By Jeff Salamon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If there was resistance to the 1954 integration
of the Baltimore public schools _ and there was _ Barry Levinson's
``Liberty Heights,'' which opened Wednesday at the Arbor, doesn't
have the heart to show it to us. Levinson is so eager to please,
his camera would avert its gaze if a pigtail got dunked in an
inkwell that year.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe Levinson was too busy juggling his other
storylines to pay attention to such details. ``Liberty Heights,''
the fourth film in his ``Baltimore Quartet'' (``Diner,'' ``Tin
Men'' and ``Avalon'' came before) boasts a busy, tripartite
structure, centered on the Kurtzmans, a middle-class Jewish family.
Van Kurtzman (Adrien Brody), law student, pines for a blonde shiksa
goddess he meets at a Halloween party. His brother Ben (Ben
Foster), high school senior, pines for the black girl who sits near
him in homeroom. Their dad, Nate (Joe Mantegna), numbers runner and
burlesque theater owner, pines for a legit line of work.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson tries to lend these strivers depth by hitching an irony
to every subplot. The WASP elite Van is trying to infiltrate turns
out to be full of drunks with sexual hangups; Sylvia (Rebekah
Johnson), the black girl Ben falls for, is the daughter of a
well-to-do surgeon; Nate, who surrounds himself with henchmen and
flunkies, has a sense of fair play incompatible with the gangster
life.
</P>
<P>
   None of these wan turnabouts, however, compensates for the hole
at the center of ``Liberty Heights'': the sentimentalized portrait
of mid-century Jewish culture. Levinson etches a trio of Jews
looking for vitality, soul and success outside the confines of
their tribe, without hinting that American Jews were, at that very
moment, on the verge of a cultural takeover. Philip Roth, Lenny
Bruce and Allen Ginsberg, among others, were about to radically
transform the American popscape. But Levinson is so busy
sentimentalizing his childhood he can't see Judaism as anything but
a source of rectitude and accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Levinson sentimentalizes everything. The preppies
who beat up Van's friend Yussel for being Jewish turn out to be
alrightniks after all. Scribbles, the small-time pimp Nate is in
hock to, is never allowed to work up a sense of menace, which
simply deflates the kidnapping subplot at the film's climax.
</P>
<P>
   When Boogie, in ``Diner,'' got in trouble with a loan shark, his
panic was palpable. Here, Levinson is too concerned with warming
the heart to let that happen. That's what you get, I suppose, from
making too many movies with Robin Williams. (How many movies with
Robin Williams is too many? If the movie in question is ``Toys,''
the answer is one.)
</P>
<P>
   There are a few amusing scenes here and there, especially those
between Foster and Johnson (who is simply beguiling), but they only
point up how slack the rest of the script is. When he has nothing
else to do, Levinson tries to recreate the sort of mesmerizing
chatter Paul Reiser, Steve Guttenberg and Daniel Stern passed back
and forth in ``Diner.'' But now that Quentin Tarantino has elevated
this shtick into a full-blown aesthetic, Levinson's lost the spark.
These days, Paul Reiser gets handed better material when he's
shilling for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
