<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 16 
</HEADLINE>
  (A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (13-1) vs. Tennessee (11-3)
</P>
<P>
   The lone blemish on Jacksonville's record is a 20-19 loss at
home to Tennessee in September. In the rain-swept game, the Titans
ensured the victory when Samari Rolle intercepted Mark Brunell in
the final seconds. The result was friction between Jaguars Coach
Tom Coughlin _ ``It was a bad pass,'' he said of the play _ and
Brunell, who replied, ``I only run the plays that are called.'' The
Jaguars are a happy bunch now, especially with 11 consecutive
victories and with the league's best record. Watch Jevon Kearse,
the Pro Bowl rookie defensive end, chase Brunell, two fleet players
who should dance in a cat-and-mouse tango all day long. Fred
Taylor's running is the key. If Tennessee contains Taylor _ and it
will _ The Titans gain the winning edge.
</P>
<P>
   Titans, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRIDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (7-7) vs. New Orleans (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   It has been a frustrating season for Dallas, one of lost
opportunities mixed with infrequent gains. But Dallas remains alive
for a playoff berth, and this is a game it should not lose in any
fashion _ offense, defense or special teams. The Saints are reeling
and cannot wait for the season to end so they can get rid of Coach
Mike Ditka and more than a few malcontent players who have ruined
the atmosphere and any chance of success. Look for Dallas to
compile a bushel of big plays in both the passing and return games.
This Dallas victory sets up a heated clash next week in a season
finale between Dallas and the Giants in Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys, 31-16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRISTMAS DAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Denver (5-9) vs. Detroit (8-6)
</P>
<P>
   These teams have not met since 1990. Thus, they know little
about each other but familiarity will come quickly. For Denver, the
season was lost from the start with quarterback controversy and
critical injuries. Detroit's season looked like a wash from its
first kickoff, but the Lions surprised and roared to a quick start
before melting in recent weeks. Charlie Batch (thumb injury)
returns at quarterback for Detroit in hopes of jolting the team's
sputtering playoff drive. Batch gives the Lions something extra in
mobility, decision-making and spirit. Detroit owns a +8 turnover
differential, much better than Denver's turnover-laden team, and
this is how the game is won early and late.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 1 P.M. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (6-8) vs. Atlanta (3-11)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons blew up long ago, suffering through injuries and
giving the ball away at an alarming rate, nothing like their Super
Bowl team from a year ago. Now that they have hit rock bottom, it
is time to show a little life. And it is easier to do against a
team that last week in its 31-21 loss to Buffalo ruined its slim
playoff chances and now falls flat in despair. Watch Falcons
receivers Terance Mathis and Tim Dwight against Pro-Bowl cornerback
Aeneas Williams. Despite the records, that is a top-flight matchup
that will be full of tricky strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (9-5) vs. New England (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo is bubbly about its playoff chances, New England is
sour. What happened to the Patriots? They have collapsed,
especially on offense, and this game will be a reminder of why. The
New England fans will be booing from start to finish, and after the
game, the Patriot players will have to prevent their emotions from
spilling into an locker-room ugly scene. New England is in need of
a makeover, one that will happen likely sooner rather than later.
Buffalo, however, moves one step closer to the post-season. Doug
Flutie has passed for touchdowns in 12 straight games. With 41
yards, he will earn his first 3,000-yard passing season in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Bills, 23-20.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (7-7) vs. Pittsburgh (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh is another team that will likely change its
leadership and lineup dramatically after this season. It will not
make the playoffs this year, but Carolina still can with plenty of
help from other teams. First, the Panthers must win their final two
games. They cannot because they slip here. Pittsburgh is primed for
a turnaround game. It is a team that has more pride than it has
shown of late, especially last week in getting trounced at Kansas
City, 35-19. The Steelers have committed a league-low four fumbles.
They are plus 2 in turnover differential. Their pass defense ranks
third in the AFC. They should be better than 5-9, but inconsistent
play at quarterback has crushed their chances. For a game,
quarterback Mike Tomczak gets it right.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers, 31-20.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (6-8) vs. Rams (12-2)
</P>
<P>
   Bears' receiver Marcus Robinson did not make the Pro Bowl this
year but he should have. He is a big, tall, athletic receiver who
exhibits no fear. He leads the NFC in receiving yards and has
caught 71 balls, 9 for touchdowns. With another 79 receiving yards
he will own the Bears' career single-season record. He has a new
quarterback, the rookie Cade McNown, throwing him passes for an
entire game now, and this duo looks promising. The pair, however,
are no match for the Rams' quarterback, Kurt Warner, and his
quartet of dynamic receivers led by Isaac Bruce. Warner has tossed
36 touchdown passes, tops in the league, and Bruce has caught 11 of
them. The Rams also won the league's best rushing defense, allowing
an average of only 76.4 yards per game. The Bears are overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 28-10.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati (4-10) vs. Baltimore (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the Bengals and Ravens waited too late to begin
exploding on offense and winning games. The Ravens still own a
slight chance of making the playoffs, but more likely, it is
wait-till-next-year again for the Ravens. This victory gives them
more hope for a playoff-caliber team next year. For the Bengals,
Corey Dillon is a fluid and fun back to watch. The Ravens can earn
their first-ever 4-game winning streak and will behind quarterback
Tony Banks. These are his numbers in his last five games: 1,386
passing yards and 14 passing touchdowns. This is a shootout that
fits Baltimore best.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 38-33.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (12-2) vs. Cleveland (2-13)
</P>
<P>
   The Colts can match a club record with their 11th straight
victory. They can also match their club record with their 13th
victory of the season. They can win their sixth straight road game.
The Browns can look across the field and see a team they can
emulate. They can hope for a turnaround next year like the Colts,
who last year were a 3-13 team. Indianapolis has plenty to play
for, including a shot at gaining home-field advantage throughout
the AFC playoffs. Once again, they will be led by Peyton Manning,
who has thrown at least one touchdown pass in 27 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 30-16.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (8-6) vs. Giants (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams enter with high playoff hopes, the Vikings off a
victory (24-20 at home against Green Bay), the Giants off a loss
(31-10 at the Rams). The Vikings' victory was emotional, but so was
the Giants' loss. The Giants entered cocky and confident against
the Rams and left completely deflated. But the Giants are a team
that rebounds with vigor, and now their season is a two-game
season. Two victories and they are playoff bound. What a breakout
year for Giants receiver Amani Toomer (68 catches, 1,049 yards,
15.4 average yards gained per catch and 6 touchdowns). Last week
against the Rams, Toomer caught 9 passes and could have caught 9
more; he was that open. He will be again against the Vikings, but a
healthy dose of the rookie running back Joe Montgomery topples the
Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 21-19.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (9-5) vs. Seattle (8-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs have won four in a row and are sizzling, while
Seattle, which once owned a dominating lead in the AFC West, have
sunk. This game will likely decide the division, and the Chiefs
look prepared _ even on the road, even in the noisy Kingdome.
Chiefs tight end Tony Gonzalez, who earned his first Pro Bowl berth
this week, is finishing the season with flair _ he has six
touchdown catches in his last four games. Defenders are marvelling
over his body control in his pass routes, his soft hands and his
determination. Few tight ends affect the game the way Gonzalez can.
This game will be extremely hard-fought, but Kansas City wins it in
the end on a Pete Stoyanovich field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 19-16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (7-7) vs. San Diego (6-8)
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are the league's best rushing team, and the Chargers
allow the AFC's fewest rushing yards per carry. Brick meets brick.
Few teams want to see the Raiders make the playoffs. They are
dangerous because of their running game, led by a robust offensive
line and backs Tyrone Wheatley and Napolean Kauffman. Oakland's
45-0 mauling of Tampa Bay, the NFC Central Division leader, last
week was another reminder of how special the Raiders can be. They
are point here and there from being a 12-4 team. After this game,
they are an 8-7 team still hoping for a miracle playoff finish.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (7-7) vs. Tampa Bay (9-5)
</P>
<P>
   Last week Tampa Bay could have clinched a playoff spot with a
victory. Instead, they collapsed against the Raiders. This week
Tampa Bay can clinch a playoff spot. Green Bay, however, will not
allow it. The Packers are underachievers and have struggled through
an inconsistent year. But this is a team that will rise in this
moment. It is Packers' quarterback Brett Favre vs. the Buccaneers'
rookie quarterback, Shaun King. Favre will simply not allow his
team to lose this game and kill its playoff chances.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Washington (8-6) vs. San Francisco (4-10)
</P>
<P>
   Playing the 49ers in December used to mean meeting a team
playing its prime football in an awfully tough place. Now the 49ers
are a shell of that that team, powerless against good teams and
pitiful against elite teams. Washington is a good team. There are
reasons to believe the 49ers will put up a fight _ pride, unbeaten
record against Washington Coach Norv Turner, the strong pass rush
of tackle Bryant Young. However, go with the Redskins. The
Washington offense is so much better than the 49ers' offense that
the game is won when Washington has the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins, 30-24.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jets (6-8) vs. Miami (9-5)
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have beaten Miami in three straight games. The Jets are
plus 11 in turnover differential, and Miami stands at 0. Bill
Parcells is 7-7 vs. the Dolphins; Jimmy Johnson is 5-4 vs. the
Jets. But the Jets cannot make the playoffs, and Miami still can.
That's the difference. Under the national glare, Miami will regroup
and focus on a playoff sprint that includes winning this game. Look
for a big game from Dolphins' receiver Tony Martin, who with 65
receiving yards gains 1,000 for the season and becomes the second
player in league history to gain 1,000 with three different teams
(Irving Fryar is the other). Miami's Pro Bowl kicker, Olindo Mare,
needs one field goal for his 38th of the season, which would be a
league record.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 24-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
