<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-tech BellSouth team eases CARE's Y2K worries
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes it is the ``high-touch'' people who need
help from high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   And, recently, with the millennium just months away, one of the
world's premier humanitarian organizations (CARE, based in downtown
Atlanta offices) went to the region's largest telecommunications
company in an effort to head off any potential Y2K computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Without the help from BellSouth Corp., CARE would have spent
about $1.5 million to make sure its technology didn't get in the
way of its mission _ if it could have even been done without
outside assistance, said Pavan Rai, the organization's chief
information officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the high-tech guys helping high-touch people. They
have done just an outstanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   From the summer until this week, CARE relied on a BellSouth team
led by Robert Schwartz to get it ready. The group did an inventory
of CARE's processes, identifying all the places where a Y2K bug
might hide. A list was made of all software and hardware.
Contingency plans were written _ just in case things went wrong.
And then BellSouth helped set up a ``war room'' for CARE to monitor
its offices around the world during the first few days of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   CARE, which has a budget of $400 million and about 10,000
workers, last year provided emergency assistance to more than 6.5
million people in 28 countries. While most of that aid was
fundamental _ food or clothing _ the delivery systems often include
devices that are vulnerable to the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are ships and cranes that rely on computers.
If they can't be operated properly, food cannot be smoothly
unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have Y2K compliance around the world if we are
going to continue helping the poorest of the poor,'' Rai said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE also uses computers to keep track of its work. Computer
databases update warehouse contents and shipments. Other databases
manage the financing that pays for the work. Thousands of workers
depend on communications systems _ wireless and otherwise _ to make
the work happen.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Ackerman, BellSouth's chairman and chief executive, said
he was glad that BellSouth was approached. ``By working closely
with CARE, we're able to give locally while affecting millions
globally. There is no better investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
