u f BC-MEDIAMETRIX24-COX     12-23 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAMETRIX24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online stores see boom during holidays
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was the best of times and the worst of times for
online retailers this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Web measurement firm Media Metrix, the number of
online shoppers ordering gifts this year increased 33 percent from
last year during the last week before Christmas. But an equal
number were nervously following the delivery process with repeated
visits to the Web sites for UPS and Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days before Christmas, traffic to e-commerce sites
decreased by 6 percent. Media Metrix said the decline was due to
the shrinking number of days left to order gifts in time for the
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   However, part of the slowdown could be due to the e-commerce
backlash, as some popular e-commerce sites including Toysrus.com
and others announced they could not fulfill the orders they
received.
</P>
<P>
   Toysrus.com began e-mailing shoppers late Tuesday that their
purchases would not arrive but said they would be compensated for
the inconvenience with $100 coupons that can be used in its stores.
</P>
<P>
   Customer concerns may also have led to an increase in the number
of visits to both UPS.com and FedEx.com. Customers looking to see
whether packages had been dispatched and/or delivered increased
visits to the two sites by 57 percent and 94 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the holiday shopping season, the
flowers/gifts/greetings category was up by 10 percent as shoppers
looked for last-minute gifts. An advertising campaign by Web site
ProFlowers.com said that customers could order as late as Thursday
and be assured of Christmas delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers also spent more time shopping online, according to
the measurement service. Visitors aged 12-17 were up 89 percent
over last year.
</P>
<P>
   This could be due in part to the many efforts this year to bring
teen shoppers online, including wish lists, gift registries and
sites targeted at teens, such as RocketCash, Delias and FastFrog.
Teen-agers now make up 5 percent of total online shoppers, up from
3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, led by Time magazine Person of the year Jeff Bezos,
was the top e-commerce site for the week ending Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The online retailer had 6,967 unique visitors to the site _ up a
whopping 94 percent from the same time last year. EBay, eToys,
Barnesandnoble.com, Toysrus.com, CDNow, Buy.com, Egreetings,
Expedia travel services and Egghead software and electronics sites
rounded out Media Metrix's list of the top e-commerce sites for the
week.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Barnesandnoble and CDNow, all the sites in
the top 10 more than doubled their online holiday business this
year compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
