<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-SUBURBS-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S NEW BLACK HOMEOWNERS TAKE PRIDE IN HUMBLE
SURROUNDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYVILLE, South Africa _ The lacy curtains from the secondhand
shop flutter over the bedroom window. The white tiles salvaged from
the garbage dump gleam on the kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white people, they threw this away, too!'' exclaimed
Patrick Mbatha, 38, chuckling over his good-as-new wicker sofa and
the inexplicable ways of wealthy white people. ``You can see the
quality! It's a good cane. I saw it and right away I put it in the
boot of my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbatha is a hard-driving taxicab driver, a doting father of four
and a proud new member of this country's swelling class of
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   He is a leader of his block association, which meets under a
shady tree on Sundays, and he reminds his neighbors to keep their
grass cropped and their garbage bagged. He grimaces over
electricity bills, counts pennies for school uniforms and grows
corn in his garden for lean times.
</P>
<P>
   And on slow days, when his cab stalls or customers lag, he
marvels at his family's journey from a mud shack into this
fledgling suburb of frilly curtains, vegetable gardens and
strivers' dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, the South African government has put 3
million poor people in brick houses for the very first time,
spending $6 billion to shelter a population bigger than Chicago's.
</P>
<P>
   The modest one-room houses are the most tangible symbol of the
post-apartheid government's commitment to redressing this country's
stark inequalities. And the changing lives within the brick walls
offer an intimate view of the hopes and hardships of ordinary black
people still struggling to climb the economic and social ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed it could happen,'' said Mbatha, proudly
displaying his tiny house, his flush toilet, his two-room extension
and the mailbox that he built when postal delivery started in
September.
</P>
<P>
   He stood quietly when a visitor asked how three years of home
ownership had changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a man,'' he said finally. ``I'm proud. We may not
always have enough food. But here no rain will get you.''
</P>
<P>
   If the houses impart a new sense of dignity, it is also true
that Mbatha's sturdy roof cannot shield his family from the
problems that continue to bedevil this new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa still has one of the highest crime rates in the
world. Unemployment stands at nearly 40 percent, by some estimates.
And these social ills infect nearly every house on Mbatha's narrow
street, which is still so new that it has no name.
</P>
<P>
   Mandla Ngwane, 50, a father of three, is jobless. Bongiwe
Mkhize, 30, a single mother, worries about the increasing number of
rapes of young girls.
</P>
<P>
   Mbatha's wife, Anna, who was laid off as a clerk in a clothing
store in 1997, worries about feeding her family. Sometimes the
family runs so low on cash that the electricity is cut off, and
they spend a night or two in darkness, Mrs. Mbatha said. Other
times, the secondhand refrigerator goes empty, and the children go
to sleep hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mbatha loves her house and her new life in it. It is the
first time, she confides, that she has ever really enjoyed daily
chores. After all, it is much nicer to mop a tile floor than to
sweep a dirt one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a white lady now,'' she laughed. ``Madam of my own
house.''
</P>
<P>
   But at night, when the guns sing in the nearby squatter camp,
she and her husband lie in bed wide-eyed and frightened.
``Sometimes,'' Mrs. Mbatha said, ``I think about moving.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether the new communities will sustain themselves
as sought-after first stops on the road into the tiny black middle
class or whether they will deteriorate into crime-ridden slums that
lead nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, shoddy developers have already left people stuck
with crumbling houses that are quickly declining in value. In other
areas, homeowners cannot pay for basic services like water and
electricity, forcing city councils to abandon plans to improve or
maintain the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out on whether we've created new vibrant
suburbs or new ghettos on the peripheries of our cities,'' said
David Porteous, an expert on low-income housing and the managing
director of Gateway Home Loans, a lending agency that works with
the government to provide loans for poor homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the demand for houses in Mayville, 15 minutes
outside Durban on the eastern coast, is enormous, despite its
problems. Nationwide, three million people are on a waiting list
for housing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
