<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-SUBURBS-ART-N     12-23 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-SUBURBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MAYVILLE , South Africa : for housing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It only takes a look down the hill, a glimpse at the teeming
squatter camp that her family left behind, for Mrs. Mbatha to
remember how lucky she is. So she builds a fence to deter potential
robbers and plants corn while her neighbors make their own
adjustments to suburban life.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mkhize had to become used to the quiet. In the squatter
camp where she grew up, music blared, drunks wailed and chatty
neighbors passed easily from shack to shack. Here, neighbors lock
their doors and radios fall silent at night.
</P>
<P>
   Ngwane had to figure out how to expand his house without any
cash, a problem that he solved by slapping together an illegal
shack in the backyard, much to the dismay of the block association.
</P>
<P>
   And the local drug dealer had to adjust to angry neighbors who
threatened to have him evicted if he continued to use his house as
the headquarters for his bustling marijuana business. He now hawks
his wares in town, the neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Mbatha grumbled about some neighbors, the one who drinks
too much and the one who lets the grass grow two feet high. But he
said he loves his new life.
</P>
<P>
   While his wife reminds the children to turn off the lights to
keep the bills low, Mbatha dreams about expanding even further,
about building a living room and a sitting room with views of the
tall skyscrapers that glitter on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are back in the land of our fathers,'' said Mbatha, whose
relatives lived on this land for generations until 1960, when the
white government forced them to move to make room for Indian
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family will never leave this place again.''
</P>
<P>
   But his 10-year-old daughter, Sindy, wrinkles her nose at his
plans. She attends a multiracial school, speaks English with an
ease that astonishes her Zulu-speaking parents and dreams of buying
a big house with a Jacuzzi where the white people live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to live in town,'' Sindy said. ``Not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbatha laughs at his pretty, precocious daughter. But in truth,
he fears that none of his children will choose to live in this
community as adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they don't belong to this society,'' he said sadly.
``They interact with children from better areas. Their eyes, they
start to see. They tell us, `My friends live in better places.'
They will not stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he has considered moving to the white suburbs that
his daughter dreams about, Mbatha said, ``I don't even want to
dream about something I cannot achieve.'' And he slumped for a
moment, ashamed.
</P>
<P>
   But then his wife called his name, and he was the proud
homeowner again, bustling about the house, pointing out the newly
laid foundation for the living room and the battered phone that he
had just bought at a secondhand shop.
</P>
<P>
   There are no telephones lines in Mayville yet, and the Mbatha
family has no money to pay an extra bill. But the phone sits on a
shelf of honor in the wood china cabinet, a silent symbol of one
man's faith in a better future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telephone lines will come,'' Mbatha said. ``And when they
come, we will be ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
