<SLUG> BC-BORDER-TERRORISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAFFIC FLOWS SMOOTHLY ALONG BORDER DESPITE SECURITY ALERT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Heightened security along the Mexican
border has not slowed international traffic at the many bridges and
ports of entry into the United States, according to officials and
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took about 20 minutes, which is normal,'' said Sylvia
Silva, a Matamoros resident who drove across the Gateway
International Bridge to Brownsville early Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents reported a 40- to 45-minute wait to cross any of
the three international bridges at Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell they are checking more, and asking more
questions,'' Silva said. ``They didn't ask us, but you can tell
they were asking other people.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States increased security personnel at U.S. airports,
ports and border crossings this week to keep an eye out for
terrorists in response to the Dec. 14 arrest of suspected terrorist
Ahmed Ressam in Washington state. Authorities said Ressam, 32, was
smuggling explosives into the United States from Canada and has
ties to an Islamic fundamentalist group.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gateway bridge in Brownsville, passenger cars, buses and
trucks crept across the two northbound lanes and were routed to
four inspection booths. U.S. Customs officers and immigration
inspectors at the booths seemed to check most vehicles in a few
minutes, and only a few of the cars were sent to more intensive
secondary inspections or pulled over for looks under their hoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any problems so far,'' said Maria Reba,
director of field operations for the U.S. Customs Service in South
Texas. ``You should expect the same long lines you have every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500 inspectors in the district from Brownsville to Del
Rio, and at the Austin and San Antonio airports, are working
overtime in an effort to avoid lengthening the traditionally long
lines caused by holiday traffic, Reba said. A number of inspectors
normally assigned to administrative duties have been pulled from
their desks and sent to border crossings, she said. But no
additional personnel from outside the district has been needed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the heightened security measures were implemented, nothing
suspicious had occurred in Reba's district or anywhere along the
southern border, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is not disturb that too much,'' Reba
said of normal Christmas congestion. ``We're doing additional work.
We're doing more examinations, talking to more people, talking
longer and spending a little more time to be satisfied there is
nothing out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
