DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PANTHERS-CARRUTH (San Francisco) _ As we begin to sort
through the details of how former Carolina Panthers wide receiver
Rae Carruth wound up facing a first-degree murder charge for
conspiring to kill Cherica Adams, his girlfriend and supposedly the
mother of his recently born son Chancellor Lee Adams, let's be sure
to not become so consumed with Carruth that Cherica and Chancellor
become bit players in his plight. By JEFFRI CHADIHA. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-FEDERAL-RESERVE (Washington) _ Although the Federal Reserve
Board isn't expected widespread Y2K problems in the U.S. economy,
the Fed will operate a special around-the-clock command post that
will monitor banks and financial markets beginning Dec. 31. Federal
Reserve Board Governors Roger W. Ferguson and Edward W. Kelley will
share the weekend duty at the Fed and help oversee the 100 people
working at the command center. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Filed
Thursday in the ``w'' and ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-BICENTENNIAL (Washington) _ The 200th anniversary of the
U.S. Capitol will be commemorated with a traveling exhibit of
history, art and architecture that will visit the capitals of all
50 states, starting in April. ``We are trying to take the Capitol
to them,'' says Clarence J. Brown, a former Republican congressman
from Ohio and committed student of the history of the building. By
JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-McCAIN (Washington) _ As they surge upward in the New
Hampshire polls, Democratic contender Bill Bradley and Republican
hopeful Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., find themselves facing unlikely
competitors _ each other. With less than six weeks before the Feb.
1 New Hampshire primary _ the nation's first _ these two anti-party
mavericks are racing to attract the same kind of voters. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday in the ``p'' and ``w'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   MRS.CLINTON-VIEQUES (New York) _ If Hillary Rodham Clinton wants
to gauge the political fallout of the Vieques controversy on her
burgeoning New York Senate campaign, all she has to do is stop for
lunch at La Fonda Boricua, a chummy walk-in luncheonette in the
heart of the Spanish-speaking neighborhoods of East Harlem known as
``El Barrio.'' ``Everybody's talking about Vieques,'' says Jorge
Ayala, the easy-going, Puerto Rico-born owner of the bustling
restaurant. By STEWART M. POWELL. (1STLD-WRITETHRU filed Wednesday
in the ``a'' and ``p'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (''k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore and Bill Bradley will
continue into the new year sparring over their opposing education
and health-care initiatives, each trying to convict voters that his
proposals would be best for the American people. But while they are
jockeying for position on those issues, two others _ taxes and
trade _ pose real dangers to the candidates as they race toward the
Iowa caucuses. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
