A7878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW24-COX     12-23 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indexes set records as Santa rallies on Wall Street
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Santa Claus paid an early visit to the stock market
Thursday. The Nasdaq composite topped 4,000 for the first time and
the Nasdaq, Dow Jones industrial average and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
closed at record levels.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic case of the so-called Santa Claus rally,
according to analysts, as seasonal trading pushed stocks higher
despite a holiday-related drop in volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a seasonal upside bias at this time of the year based
on money flows accelerating and liquidity becoming thinner as some
institutions close their books for the year,'' said Prudential
Securities strategist Larry Wachtel.
</P>
<P>
   Volume diminishes as traders and investors leave their desks
before the Christmas holiday weekend, which means the market rises
on weaker than usual demand.
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange volume totaled 726.9 million shares,
down from 844.2 million Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On average, U.S. stock markets have gained on seven of the 10
trading sessions before the Christmas holidays since 1989, said
Wachtel.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, continuing its torrid climb on the strength of
strong demand for technology stocks, briefly moved above 4,000
shortly after noon, when it peaked at 4,001.63. Although it pulled
back, it still rose almost 1 percent for the day, to a new high of
3,969.53.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq closed above 3,000 for the first time Nov. 3 en route
to a year-to-date gain of 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose 1.8 percent to a record 11,405.76, the first since
Aug. 25. The S&AMP;P-500 gained 1.6 percent to 1,458.34, also a record.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller stocks rose to within 9 points
of its all-time high of 491.41, reached April 21, 1998. Analysts
said the index's rise reflected the wider breadth of market demand
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market was also buoyed by fresh evidence that
the U.S. economy is still growing at a moderate rate. The Commerce
Department said personal income, which includes wages, interest and
government benefits, rose 0.4 percent in November. It was the
smallest increase since August, although the gain was twice what
analysts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket
manufactured goods rose 1.2 percent in November, the first gain
since August.
</P>
<P>
   That means manufacturing industries will continue to improve in
the coming year, but analysts said it also suggests inflation will
still be a potential threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monthly economic numbers, many of which track the factory
sector, will remain strong and that will keep the heat on the bond
market and the (Federal Reserve),'' said First Union economist Mark
Vitner.
</P>
<P>
   After raising short-term rates three times earlier in the year,
the Fed declined to raise them again at its December meeting this
week _ the last of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes of the Fed's November meeting, released Thursday, show
policy-makers decided to bump up interest rates in November because
the century date change would make such a move less attractive in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts continue to be wary about interest rates, knowing
of Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's commitment to keeping inflation
down even if it means putting the brakes on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As for bonds, prices have continued to fall as concern about the
inflation outlook in that market grows.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in bond prices has had the effect of pushing 30-year
Treasury yields to their highest levels in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   The yield is just shy of 6.5 percent, a level that analysts
regard as a threat to stocks by providing investors with an
attractive return offered by a relatively risk-free security.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rising bond yields, many analysts remain bullish on
January, when buying historically picks up as investors enter the
market with year-end bonuses, pension fund payouts and the
repurchase of stocks they sold for tax purposes late in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting Jan. 3, 2000, we see a good rally from normal
first-of-year buying,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market
strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. ``By year-end, we look for the
(30-year) bond to start trending down, to a yield of 5.7 percent by
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also said the market is likely to get a boost from
pent-up demand caused by the year 2000 concern threat.
</P>
<P>
   There's a widely held belief that investors unwilling to buy
stocks in December from fear of a computer glitch will rush back
into the market in January after the year 2000 threat has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
