<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-KAPLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELICIA KAPLAN; POLITICAL SATIRIST, WRITER OF LIGHT VERSE; AT 83 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Felicia Kaplan, who, writing under her maiden name,
Felicia Lamport, earned a reputation as one of America's best-known
writers of light verse and most distinctive political satirists,
died Thursday at her Cambridge home. She was 83. The cause of death
was pneumonia. She had been in increasingly frail health for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word for Felicia is `unquenchable,' '' New York Times
columnist Anthony Lewis said Thursday of Mrs. Kaplan, a friend of
many years' standing. ``I can't think of anyone who could have
survived what she did for so many years with such fire of wit and
love unquenched.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, the Globe's Focus section had run Mrs. Kaplan's
``Muse of the Week in Review,'' in which she deployed her intricate
wordplay to skewer the latest folly in Washington or on Beacon
Hill. Her work also appeared in The New Yorker, The New York Times,
The Atlantic Monthly, Harper's, McCall's, The New Republic,
Saturday Review, Look, and the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   As such an eclectic list of publications might suggest, Mrs.
Kaplan's work ranged far and wide. She was as comfortable parodying
T. S. Eliot, in ``The Love Song of R. Milhous Nixon, 1973'' (``Let
us go then, in my plane/For a weekend of repose in Key Biscayne'')
as she was sounding like a latter-day Edward Lear, in ``Lines on an
Aching Brow,'' which in its entirety reads, ``I hereby confess/That
of all I possess/I'd most gladly be minus/The sinus'').
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kaplan's verse was collected in four volumes: ``Scrap
Irony'' (1961), ``Cultural Slag'' (1966), ``Light Metres'' (1982),
and ``Political Plumlines'' (1984). Her first book was a novel, the
best-selling ``Mink on Weekdays'' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kaplan was born and raised in New York, the daughter of
Samuel C. Lamport and Miriam (Dworsky) Lamport. The antic milieu in
which she was raised provided material she would later use in her
novel. She graduated from Vassar College in 1937 and went to work
as a writer for MGM.
</P>
<P>
   She married Benjamin Kaplan, a lawyer, in 1942. They moved to
Cambridge in 1947 when he joined the faculty of Harvard Law School.
At both their Bond Street home and on Martha's Vineyard, where the
Kaplans summered for many years, they entertained a lively and
eclectic mix of guests from the worlds of academe, law, politics,
and media.
</P>
<P>
   ``She suffered fools politely, but not gladly,'' Robert Manning,
the former editor of The Atlantic Monthly and a longtime friend,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Felicia as a friend protected you from enemies on all
sides: She was so loyal, in addition to being so entertaining and
ingenious.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kaplan taught expository writing at Harvard from 1980 to
1988 and then creative writing at the Harvard Extension School. She
was a past member of the board of the MacDowell Colony and the
American Chess Foundation. Chess was a great passion of Mrs.
Kaplan's, as were bridge and gardening. She was a member the
Author's Guild, and the National Writers Union.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her husband, she leaves a son, James L. of
Northampton; a daughter, Nancy Mansbach, of Newton; and four
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be private. A memorial service will be
held at a later date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
