<SLUG> BC-FLA-CENTURY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Celebrating the New Year in Century
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTURY, Fla. _ They'll ring in the New Year here with minature
pony rides, a pie eating contest, ugliest man competition,
fireworks and horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Why not welcome the new year, organizer's figure, in a place
named for the last turn of the century?
</P>
<P>
   No one's quite seen anything like it in this former lumber town
of 2,500 people, which has been in an economic coma since the mill
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it would be more
</P>
<P>
   well-received this year given the name of the town,'' said
Century CPA Ann Brooks, who's helped organize the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   When Michigan businessman Russell Alger needed to expand his
timber empire in 1900, he purchased 250,000 acres of forest in a
black community of Northwest Florida called Teaspoon. The Escambia
River flowed past. A train station took the name of the community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1901, Alger _ a former Michigan governor and Secretary of War
under President McKinley until he resigned after being criticized
for the lack of military preparation prior to the Spanish-American
War _ rejected naming the remote Florida station after himself. But
he agreed to a later suggestion, brought on by the change in the
calendar: Century.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the town's historical society today brag they haven't
been able to find another town in the nation named Century.
</P>
<P>
   Remnants of the old Alger-Sullivan Lumber Company are scattered
throughout Century's historic district, where Spanish Moss cascades
down the branches of towering oak trees. Just a few generations
ago, moonshiners and honky-tonks pervaded the dense woods and
flatlands along the Escambia River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whiskey was rampant and I was right in the middle of it,''
recalled Jerry Fischer, 60, a local photographer and city
councilman. In pockets of town, poverty lingers. Crack cocaine
dealing has replaced bootlegging.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an economic boom throughout the South, Century's
unemployment rate soars near 20 percent. Many residents are on
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the lumber company left town, they left behind a whole
lot of people who depended on them for everything,'' said Century
Mayor Benny Barnes. ``When they left, they took a whole lot of the
leaders with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, Alger-Sullivan sold its timberlands to a group of paper
companies. In 1967, Jim Walters Corp. added a door manufacturing
factory to the plant and slowly phased out the sawmill.
</P>
<P>
   There's been some resurgence. A state prison built about 10
years ago has provided jobs. A nearby industrial park has attracted
medical companies. The city offers financial incentives to
businesses that locate here. In the 1970s, the Florida town of
South Flomaton annexed the community of Century then changed its
name to Century. U.S. 29, which cuts through town and is a familiar
route to Atlantans who travel south to Pensacola, is four-laned.
CVS has replaced the Big B. Still, the Piggly Wiggly remains the
only grocery store in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just not lots here,'' said Daniel Moore, Piggly Wiggly
manager. ``So you have to go other places if you want to get a job
and you're going to be a professional.'' Chicken crackled as Barnes
dropped freshly floured pieces in a black kettle of boiling oil
fired by a propane burner set up behind the police station. As he
does every year, the mayor cooked for the annual city hall
Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: The town is Y2K complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fret whether the town's 7-year-old computers would
survive New Year's Day, Century spent $20,000 on new ones. A
generator is hooked up to city hall to keep them running.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think the lights might go off,'' Barnes said.
There will be a generator hooked up to the lights at the city park
_ named for Century native and Arizona Diamondbacks manager Buck
Showalter _ Dec. 31, when the town's celebration begins. A crowd of
7,000 is expected.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-minute fireworks display will bring the New Year in with a
bang. The city kicked in $5,000 for the celebration and was matched
by the county. Billboards promote the event all along U.S. 29.
``There are people that would not be happy here,'' said resident
Margaret Collier, 73. ``We are not a sophisticated town. But if you
want good, hearty people, then they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
