u i BC-VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES-5     12-23 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISASTER DEEPENS UNCERTAINTY ABOUT VENEZUELA'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ A week of immense landslides and floods has
done more than destroy lives, homes and public works here. The
country's worst natural disaster of modern times has also left an
institutional vacuum and deepened uncertainty about how the
government and economy are to be run over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   The torrential rains that brought on the calamity began on Dec.
15, the same day that Venezuelans overwhelmingly approved a new
Constitution that confers broad new powers on President Hugo Chavez
and his allies in the military. Chavez, a former Army colonel, was
elected to office a year ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new charter has already been promulgated, the
measures putting it into effect have not been taken, and they are
not likely to be under current conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In a hurried effort to fill the gap, the Constitutional
Assembly, dominated by followers of Chavez, formally dissolved
Congress late Wednesday, replacing it with an appointed 21-member
body drawn mostly from its own ranks. The assembly itself is to go
out of existence on Feb. 3, and the interim council, to be led by
former Interior Minister Luis Miquilena, will take over all
legislative functions until new elections can be held.
</P>
<P>
   Before the referendum on Dec. 15, Chavez had said that he wanted
elections for all public offices, including his own, to be held
``as soon as possible'' or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the disaster and the devastation that it has inflicted on
the economy and the schools, hospitals and other government
buildings that would be polling places have led to speculation that
elections may have to be postponed until later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The decree on Wednesday also appointed a new Supreme Court and
dismissed Comptroller General Eduardo Roche Lander, an independent
who had been aggressively investigating what he describes as
corruption in the military and mishandling of public funds by the
Chavez government.
</P>
<P>
   A result is to give the president virtually unlimited authority,
leading newspapers here to predict that a dictatorial ``war
economy'' could soon be declared.
</P>
<P>
   Already there have been complaints that the military is seeking
to exclude any other group, including elected civilian officials,
from meaningful participation in relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people in the Armed Forces wanted to impose a single
authority,'' Pablo Medina, a pro-Chavez member of the Constituent
Assembly, complained in a speech on Wednesday in which he also
warned that during ``great tragedies, great fortunes are made, and
we must avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar objections have been made by police officers, some of
whom have found themselves barred from entering areas they usually
patrol, even though victims are clamoring for protection from
robbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army is acting like they are the only ones in charge, and
there is no role for anyone else,'' said Inspector Jose Contreras
of the Caracas metropolitan police who is working in Blandin, the
neighborhood of the capital most damaged by the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   As for Chavez, the crisis appears to have intensified the
populace's feelings, both positive and negative, about him. Those
who admired him before blame previous administrations for creating
the conditions that led to the catastrophe and are even more
solidly behind him. Critics, who accuse him of mismanaging the
disaster, now have more reason than ever to dislike him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the disaster began, Chavez has been everywhere, wearing
camouflage fatigues and a red military beret as he personally
supervises relief efforts. He has also halted his attacks on what
he calls a ``rancid oligarchy'' of politicians, business executives
and church leaders, instead praising them for making supplies,
transportation and money available to victims of the floods.
</P>
<P>
   That display of good will has not been universally returned,
however. The archbishop of Caracas has said Chavez's arrogance
``attracted the wrath of God'' and brought down the floods. In the
heavily damaged coastal area of Los Corales, an angry painting on a
wall proclaims, ``Thanks to Chavez, the world has ended.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement would appear to be a reference to long and
sharply critical reports in two newspapers, El Nacional and El
Mundo, that accused the Chavez administration of ignoring weather
reports and warnings from community leaders that waters were rising
and that a disaster was on the way. Instead, the reports contend,
the government chose to focus its attention on the constitutional
referendum in an effort to assure a big turnout and a resounding
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, former Planning Minister Teodoro Petkoff,
who became editor of El Mundo when Chavez came to power,
unexpectedly announced his resignation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Petkoff complained that a ``cynical'' and ``unscrupulous''
government was exerting ``tremendous pressure'' and ``blackmail''
on the paper's owners to have him soften its reporting by falsely
claiming that the paper had not paid taxes that it owed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can say it openly,'' Petkoff wrote in a farewell
statement, ``the government has been extorting the Capriles Lopez
family in order to force a change of policy at El Mundo.''
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesmen declined to comment on the case. But a
foreign political analyst here described El Mundo's disaster
coverage of recent days as ``the straw that broke the camel's
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
