<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-VENTURE-CAPITAL (Undated) _ Since 1996, major commercial
banks have tripled the money they devote to venture capital, the
high-risk, high-return world of financing companies before they go
public. The appeal of venture capital is obvious. Banks are happy
to get 8 percent interest on a typical loan, while the average
venture capital investment in a new company almost doubled this
year. But as banks move deeper into venture capital, they face some
risks. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Middle Right)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A year-end buying spree drove the three main
stock gauges to new peaks, with the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index surging briefly above the 4,000 mark before falling
back. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
