<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HHS-QNA26-COX     12-23 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HHS-QNA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Southern health chief has children on her mind
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ann Rosewater, a chief adviser to U.S. Health and
Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, this month was appointed
regional director of HHS in the South. Her Atlanta office serves
Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina,
South Carolina and Tennessee. Rosewater has developed an expertise
on protection of children. She recently shared some of her opinions
on health and social issues with staff writer Marlon Manuel. Some
excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sen. Mike DeWine, a Republican from Ohio considered an expert
on children's issues, has been quoted as saying that foster care
really isn't on the radar screen with a lot of folks in Congress.
As a former congressional aide, what do you think it's going to
take to make that topic an issue in the 2000 elections?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think, actually, issues around children are on the minds of
a lot of people, though not enough. Never enough. And issues about
the most vulnerable children are more challenging to get on
people's screens as an issue, if only because they're less visible
and there are fewer of them. .. This week the president signed a
new piece of legislation ... that will double the independent
living program, which is a foster care transition program for those
kids who are aging out and can help them get on their feet and not
fall back without work or becoming homeless. That's a very big and
exciting change and improvement in the foster care system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With foster care, should emphasis be placed on family
preservation, on adoption or on some other mechanism to take care
of these children?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a continuum of support that has to be provided. But
I'd like to step back and learn what's going on in this particular
region. . .. I know it's particularly on the minds of people in
this state, and I certainly would like to be helpful, and I think
there's a continuing role for the federal government in trying to
help states and communities help ensure safety for all children and
families. ... I'm excited there's going to be a new (Georgia
Department of Family and Children Services) director. I know some
steps have been taken and that's very positive, and we're looking
forward to working together and helping out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Based on what you know about the region, do you have a
priority or goal as you step into this role?
</P>
<P>
   A: I certainly want to listen and learn from the people around
the eight states that are part of this region before I pick a
specific target for myself. ... The demographics of the region are
changing. There are more Latinos, and not just in Florida, but in
Georgia and North Carolina as you look at the Census projections.
One of the things I want is to help people get adjusted to this
diversity and change ... protecting people who may have a harder
time benefiting from the growth, make sure people get work and
opportunities, and of course, give kids a healthy and positive
opportunity to get started. One other thing, of course, is lots of
these changes, lots of these issues through the region have huge
implications for health and for health care. So HHS has huge
responsibilities, obviously, for making sure not only that people
have health insurance but that the quality of care that people get
_ whether it's a nursing home or at home or at whatever level _ is
good.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Picking up on some of that, for instance in Tennessee, Gov.
Sundquist and the General Assembly have been working very hard to
overhaul TennCare. How critical is that issue for that state?
</P>
<P>
   A: TennCare has been an important experiment, and we care deeply
about ensuring that people have continued health care and health
coverage. The state has the challenge to make sure that it can keep
all these folks insured with quality care. Of course, that's a
significant issue ... I have had the opportunity just recently to
meet the governor, and so I'm certainly available as they go
through this process, trying to figure out what they're going to
do. I know they have some serious challenges. It's really an
important state responsibility to figure out how to make TennCare
work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You mention the growth of the region. Still, there are
pockets of the South that have not experienced the same kind of
boom. This summer, President Clinton went to some of the poorest
areas, Appalachia in Kentucky, the Mississippi Delta. How prevalent
is poverty still in pockets of the South and what type of a threat
is it for children in the region?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the issues we're seeing _ and it's not only an issue
for the South but the nation _ is while there's economic growth,
some people are really benefiting but, as you're saying, others are
left behind, both in areas of the South and particular groups of
families and children. And that income gap is actually increasing.
What I think is critical is to figure out how we can take the kind
of responsibility as good partners with states and communities and
families, to make sure that people who might be vulnerable _ and I
think kids are in particularly vulnerable situations _ how we can
make sure we create pathways to opportunity. I think the sort of
impression of disparity, as opposed to the reality of disparity, to
the extent that's out there, is something we need to address.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You talked about ``pathways to opportunity.'' Do you have
specific ideas?
</P>
<P>
   A: Again, I'm hoping I'm going to learn a lot about what's going
on state by state. ... Three states in this region just received
what are called high-performance bonuses for some of the good work
they've done in getting people into jobs, helping them retain jobs,
helping them improve their earnings. We're eager to build on that
and get all the states up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's been a moratorium in place the last six years that
keeps HHS from auditing how states spend federal dollars that have
been earmarked for foster care. Do you foresee an end to that
moratorium, and while that moratorium is in effect, how can
taxpayers be sure their money is being spent on the purposes it was
intended?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was imposed by Congress because Congress perceived that
the basis on which monitoring was being done of states' compliance
was not very meaningful. What HHS has done, which I think has been
quite important and is reflected in a lot of pieces of legislation
that have been enacted regarding foster care and child welfare, is
that we have key goals for the resources that are shared with
states: Safety, permanency and well-being for children. These goals
need to be embedded in the monitoring that we do, and the
monitoring should be designed in a way that we can work with
states. We're not interested in playing ``gotcha,'' we're
interested in getting good service, good care and good movement
toward permanency for these kids. We've been in the process of
redesigning that approach to accountability, and I think we're
eager to get on with that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
