<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     12-23 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright San Francisco Chronicle 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHATEVER IT IS, GO AHEAD AND TRY IT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To pierce or not to pierce? That is the question.  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Elliott &LR;  forwards a report from the Humanities and Sciences
Quarterly of Stanford University on a forum discussion conducted by
biological sciences Professor  &UR; Robert Sapolsky &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Sapolsky's talk, ``Sushi &AMP; Middle Age,'' explored why humans
become less interested in new things as they get older. The
professor used three ``measures of openness'':
</P>
<P>
   Musical tastes; willingness to try new foods (sushi, for
example); and acceptance of certain forms of body piercing, such as
studded tongues.
</P>
<P>
   The professor urged members of the audience to try to hold on to
the passion of youth and, ``like the younger generation, to explore
for exploration's sake.'' The averages, if you're gazing into the
mirror contemplating a pristine nostril or eyebrow: ``windows'' to
novelty in music close at 35; to new foods at 39; and to body
piercing at 23.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``The future was and remains the quintessential American
art form,'' says Yale computer science Professor  &UR; David Gelernter &LR; 
in Wired magazine. ``Other nations sit back and let their futures
happen; we construct ours.'' Also on the Wired horizon: ``San
Diego-based EPIcyte is cooking up contraceptive corn on the cob.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDANGERED BARBIE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Grass Valley Union reports that officials of the Echo Ridge
Seventh Day Adventist school found a pile of mutilated Barbie dolls
in the parking lot of the school, upon which the cops were called.
School principal  &UR; Vickie Altman &LR;  said the dolls had been set on
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that a deputy of the Nevada County
Sheriff's Department ``suspected it was mere mischief,'' which was
a relief to other Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RATING THE SEATS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The proprietors of Big Pagoda, a Fillmore Street gallery/ store
that features Asian-design furniture, have begun publishing a
newsletter, the first issue of which launches ``Sitting Out, Dining
Out.'' The editors will visit restaurants, the newsletter explains,
and rate their chairs, &LR;  on the bases of ``sitability, scootability,
base solidity, squirm index'' and ``seat height.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue gives the highest rating to Shanghai 1930,
citing its ``fat leather pews,'' and the same to McDonald's, where
``light-speed service'' and ``rigid seating'' got the reviewer
``out within the company's engineered 7.5 minutes per table.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RATING THE BEDROOMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For readers ready to snuggle up on the night before Christmas,
Natural Home magazine, mined for Personals by  &UR; Gabriel Olszewski &LR; ,
provides these tips for safe sleeping:
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the flow of electricity to the bedroom, using some kind
of master switch; remove electrical devices from the bedroom, or at
least unplug them and place at least three yards from the bed;
eschew mattresses with metal springs; avoid beds with metal frames;
don't use electric blankets; if you have a carpet, let it be of
natural fiber; don't sleep in a water bed; avoid ionization-type
smoke detectors; have nothing plastic in the room; don't have
synthetic pillows; say so long to synthetic wallpaper; open a
window; don't place your bed near a refrigerator (now that one
really hurts), even if it's on the other side of a wall; don't
sleep directly over a garage.
</P>
<P>
   And to all a good night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The high-and-mighty New York Times has traditionally looked
down its nose at the Daily News, but former Times editor and op-ed
columnist  &UR; Abe Rosenthal &LR;  is talking to New York Daily News owner
 &UR; Mort Zuckerman &LR;  about becoming a columnist for the tabloid,
reports Mediagossip.com. Rosenthal was unhappy to be retired from
his Times duties recently.
</P>
<P>
   - The newly published ``Quomodo Invidiosulus Nomine Grinchus
Christi Natalem Abrogaverit'' (Bolchazy-Carducci; $16.95) is  &UR; Dr.
Seuss &LR; ' ``How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' in Latin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `` `Oh, but it's the thought that counts!' says Goody-Two-Shoes.
... But if that really were true, we'd be able to think fondly of
each other and leave it at that, instead of having to actually come
up with a present.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &LR;   &LR; From the Curmudgeon's Home Companion, a ``monthly guide to
reality and good food'' produced by  &UR; Dan Goldberg  &LR; in Yountville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHEN-MASSACRE-BOS &LR;      12-23 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHEN-MASSACRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS EMERGE OF MASSACRE OF CHECHEN VILLAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND DMITRY SHALGANOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Russia's commanders Thursday said the end of
its war against separatist militants in Chechnya was near, even as
grim details emerged of an alleged massacre by Russian troops and a
top US diplomat accused Moscow of treating civilians as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   What that means for the fate of tens of thousands of civilians
trapped in rebel-held territory in the breakaway North Caucasus
republic remained unclear. Russia says it is restoring heat, light,
and order to the parts of the strife-torn region it has recaptured,
while Chechens fleeing the fighting speak of looting and summary
executions of defenseless civilians by drunken Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The worst reports so far have come from Alkhan-Yurt, a small
village on the southwest outskirts of the besieged capital, Grozny.
There, refugees and human rights groups say, Russian troops went on
a rampage and killed as many as 41 civilians after capturing the
town in heavy fighting earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Russia first denied that anything untoward had taken place, but
it has now opened an investigation. Military sources said the
commander of the troops involved, Major General Vladimir Shamanov,
had been reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the massacre were corroborated Thursday by leaders of
the loyalist Chechen regime handpicked by Moscow. Malik Saidulayev,
the head of the pro-Moscow Chechen State Council, said drunken
Russian soldiers of the 15th Battalion of the 58th Army had
massacred 23 village residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found some stores of cognac and vodka. . . Soldiers
entered homes, and if they saw that a person was alone . . . they
would kill him,'' Saidulayev told a Moscow radio station.
Saidulayev, who said he had pictures and videos of the massacre,
said only some of the village's houses had been damaged in the
fighting for Alkhn-Yurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest were burned by the troops, who set them ablaze after
looting them,'' Saidulayev said.
</P>
<P>
   Saidulayev, who has spent the last three years in Moscow, is
originally from Alkhan-Yurt, but he is no darling of the
separatists. When he was appointed in September, rebel sympathizers
in Alkhan-Yurt reportedly blew up his house there.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moscow's chief civilian envoy to Chechnya, Deputy Prime
Minister Nikolai Koshman, said rebels were to blame for the events
in Alkhan-Yurt. He said residents had told troops there were no
rebels in the village, but advancing soldiers were met with
grenades and gunfire fired from homes, forcing the troops to return
fire.
</P>
<P>
   But in an amateur video made during a visit to Alkhan-Yurt and
shown to reporters last week, Koshman was shown inspecting the
ruins of the village and upbraiding Russian officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be held personally responsible for this,'' he tells one
officer in the video, whose contents were first reported by the
BBC. ``I've never seen anything like it anywhere in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers in Mozdok said General Shamanov could be soon removed
because of his troops' actions; last week, a commission of superior
officers reprimanded him, citing the looting by his troops. Among
other things, military sources said investigators found that troops
had taken numerous rugs from Chechen homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow Thursday, US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
met with with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and said later
that Russia had broken international norms by indiscriminately
targetting civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens, Talbott said, ``don't want to see themselves treated
as terrorists and enemies, not to mention victims of indiscriminate
killing and driving people from their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has shaken off criticism from the West, saying the war in
Chechnya is an internal matter. Officials say foreigners fail to
understand the wave of terror that Moscow says was generated by
hundreds of kidnappings and general lawlessness that marked the
region's three years of de facto independence.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops entered Chechnya after Islamic militants invaded
the neighboring Russian republic of Dagestan and Moscow and other
cities were hit by a wave of deadly apartment bombings, which
Moscow blamed on Chechen rebels. The separatists have denied
responsibility for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military, out to avenge its defeat in its 1994-1996
war against Chechnya, has waged a relentless and savage assault
that has enjoyed a wave of popular support in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, whose leadership of the Chechen
campaign has won him a 70 percent popularity rating in polls, told
a government meeting Thursday that Russian forces were meeting only
``pockets of resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the territory of Chechnya is now controlled by the
federal forces,'' Putin declared.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of Russian forces in Chechnya, Colonel General
Viktor Kazantsev, predicted in an interview published in the
military paper Krasnaya Zvezda that the war would end in ``two or
three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Russian forces launched a furious air and artillery
attack on Grozny, despite having promised to keep open ``safe
corridors'' for the estimated 8,000 to 45,000 civilians believed to
be still trapped in the capital. Thousands more remained caught in
the foothills to the south, where the only escape corridor, a road
through the high Caucasus mountains into Georgia, was closed by
Russian paratroopers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees said Thursday
that her office would investigate claims by refugees and rights
groups that refugees were being forced to return to a war zone.
Foreign aid workers have avoided the North Caucasus after hundreds
of people were kidnapped for ransom after Russian troops withdrew
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the troops are back, and, Moscow says, they are finding and
freeing hostages held by Chechen captors. This month, troops sent
home a 12-year-old girl who had been kidnapped from a neighboring
region and kept in a basement in Chechnya for months.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, such stories provide ample justification for what
Russian are doing. But in the Caucasus, Chechen civilians fear what
will happen to them if they return home, and stories like
Alkhan-Yurt do not make it any easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Filipov reported from Moscow; Shalganov reported from Mozdok.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
