<HEADLINE>
UN, WOMAN AT ODDS OVER $700,000 DEPOSIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Susan Madakor lives in a housing project in Brooklyn.
Two years ago, as mysterious wire transfers started depositing the
first of $700,000 into her bank account, it seemed as though her
dreams would finally be realized.
</P>
<P>
   Madakor says she spent more than a third of the money to pay off
debts and open a laundromat.
</P>
<P>
   Then the money stopped a month ago. She tried to close the
account but found it blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Bank and the United Nations discovered that 13
foreign governments had for two years wired money into Madakor's
account instead of into the UN Environment Program's account, which
differs from hers by a single digit.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary contributions to help clean up the Earth instead
went to Madakor.
</P>
<P>
   The bank immediately froze the $435,000 she had left in various
accounts and told her to return the rest.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Madakor filed a lawsuit in New York State Supreme
Court, alleging that she won the money in an ``international
lottery'' but never received notice of her winnings. She wants
Chase to unfreeze the funds and pay her damages.
</P>
<P>
   Her suddenly deflated lifestyle has left her with bounced checks
and unpaid food and medicine bills, the suit says. A court hearing
is set for Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The money was transferred in amounts ranging from $12 to ``six
figures,'' said Ken Herz, a Chase spokesman. ``I don't think if you
win a European lottery you get a wire of $12.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Quiblier, a spokesman for the environment program, said
the money was not considered missing because the program is
voluntary and funds are deposited sporadically. Most of the
program's money comes from the regular UN budget, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she tried to close out an account we questioned her and
we weren't satisfied with her responses and we froze the money,''
Herz said. ``It's not her money, it belongs to the United
Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``This lady has spent between $250,000 and $350,000 of
the United Nations' money, yet she wants to keep the rest and seek
damages from us. As far as we're concerned, the $700,000 was the
best thing that ever happened to her and I don't see how it's
damaged her.''
</P>
<P>
   Herz also challenged Madakor's claim about how she spent the
money. ``I don't know about the laundromat but there were many
other things _ it wasn't all on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Madakor did not respond to a phone message left at her home
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
