<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCAVE-CHEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR POPS SUNKEN CHEST BACK INTO SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A twist of the wrist by two surgeons helped give
13-year-old Patrick Delaney a new look to his formerly sunken chest
last Tuesday in a dramatic demonstration of minimally invasive
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts General Hospital surgeons had inserted a bowed
metal bar from one side of Delaney's chest to the other, through
small incisions under each arm.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if turning a crank, the doctors rotated the rod so that
its arched shape pointed upward, pushing the boy's concave chest
wall outward and giving it a normal contour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those jaw-dropping things,'' said Dr. Daniel
Doody, the MGH pediatric surgeon who performed what appears to be
the first such procedure in Massachusetts. ``Everybody in the
operating room said, `Oh, my goodness!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the standard, invasive operation that involves
cutting the ribs apart from the breast bone and rebuilding the
chest from inside, the new procedure was like popping a dent out of
a car door panel. The ribs can be moved like this because they are
attached to the breast bone at the front and the spine at the back
by flexible cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, Patrick, who was born with what's called
``funnel chest'' or more properly, ``pectus excavatum,'' was being
weaned from pain medications. He hoped to come home Friday, his
third postoperative day. The metal piece, called a strut, that is
supporting the front of his chest will stay there, sewed in place,
for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick's nurse, Anita St. John, has taken care of many children
following the standard operation. This innovation, called the Nuss
procedure after the Virginia surgeon who developed it, ``makes just
an incredible difference'' in recovery time, she said, judging by
Patrick's rapid improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already been up and walking _ it usually takes a week or
so before they're really walking on their own,'' she said. And his
once-indented chest ``looks completely normal'' without the large
incision scars from the standard operation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 in 1,000 children are born with a bowed-in chest, said
Doody, the surgeon, and Patrick's was moderate to severe. The boy
said it was like having a soup bowl in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Many children don't need surgery, but in some patients, like
Patrick, the bent-in ribs actually crowd the heart and lungs. ``I
couldn't run for two minutes, I couldn't ride my bike as fast or as
far as my friends, and I couldn't keep up with my friends in
sports,'' Patrick said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The standard method of repair involves, first, making a
``nipple-to-nipple'' lateral incision, said Doody, and then lifting
the chest and abdominal muscles away from the ribs. The ribs are
attached to the sternum, or breastbone, by tough but flexible
cartilage, and to reshape the chest, the surgeon removes the
cartilage, freeing the ribs from the sternum.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the sternum is lifted up and held in place by sutures,
while the ribs are positioned so that they will reattach themselves
over a period of months. The operation can cause a lot of bleeding,
though transfusions are rarely needed.
</P>
<P>
   The new procedure was actually invented about 10 years ago by
Dr. Donald Nuss, a surgeon at Children's Hospital of The King's
Daughters in Norfolk, Va. He didn't discuss it much publicly, but
in 1997 published his accumulated results, drawing a lot of
attention. Doody and his partner, Dr. Daniel Ryan, visited Nuss in
September and learned the procedure from him.
</P>
<P>
   In fixing Patrick's chest, the surgeons first chose a rod of the
right size, 13 inches long, and bent it to fit what would be the
normal curve of his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The small incisions under his arms allowed the surgeons, looking
inside the chest with a video-equipped instrument, to tunnel
through the chest tissue, bypassing the heart and lungs, clear to
the other side.
</P>
<P>
   A long piece of tape (the same kind used to tie babies'
umbilical cords) was passed through the tunnel and then was used to
pull the metal bar through the same space until both ends of the
bar protruded on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Then Doody and Ryan, using handles attached to the bar, rotated
it 180 degrees in one smooth motion, pushing the chest up so that
it formed a normal curvature.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing it, I was impressed,'' said Doody. ``After doing
it, I was even more impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so every surgeon who repairs chest deformities, however. Dr.
Robert Shamberger, a pediatric surgeon at Children's Hospital who
performs most of the pectus excavatum repairs there, said, ``We are
awaiting further support that it's associated with less
complications and optimal results.''
</P>
<P>
   Shamberger said the conventional operation really isn't that
traumatic and patients are out of the hospital in three or four
days. Some surgeons have adopted the Nuss procedure but then
dropped it after complications occurred, Shamberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Doody, however, remains enthusiastic after carrying out
Patrick's repair. ``He's already better'' than other young patients
who've had the standard operation,'' the surgeon said. ``He's way
ahead of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
