<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHRISTMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC CHARITY HELPS POOR PALESTINIAN FAMILY IN BETHLEHEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIT JALLA, West Bank _ Up a dusty gravel path not far from the
lighted square and gilded grotto that mark the traditional
birthplace of Jesus, a plastic Christmas tree, small and bare,
graces a corner of the Masou family's living room.
</P>
<P>
   No ornaments hang from the tree, no presents lie underneath it
and none of the five children in the Palestinian family expects any
to appear by Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Like many among Bethlehem's Christian community, the Masous are
poor. Their living room is cold, chilled by a steady winter wind
that breezes through windows that the family hasn't yet been able
to afford to cover with glass.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this Christmas, they tell a visitor, is the best one yet.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, the seven family members lived together
in one room in a relative's small house next door, while the
father, a house painter, slowly built his own home.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Caritas, the Roman Catholic Church's charity,
they put enough finishing touches on the house to move in just the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so cramped before, we never felt like it was
Christmas,'' said Ibtisam Masou, the family's 33-year-old mother.
``I couldn't relax. The kids were always fighting. Now we can do
what we want. We're comfortable here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Caritas gave no-interest loans of about $2,000 to 50
needy Christian families in the Bethlehem area. It's not much, but
the money helps to ease the poverty of Bethlehem's vanishing
Christian population and thus, Christian leaders hope, stem the
tide of emigration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, the town of Jesus' birth was 90 percent Christian,
according to officials. Today, just 35 percent of its 30,000 people
are Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13,000 inhabitants in neighboring Beit Jalla, the
Bethlehem suburb where the Masous live, the Christian population
stands at 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most live in hilly communities that flank either side of
Bethlehem, along cramped and narrow alleys that the tourists rarely
see. Some survive by carving Christian figurines out of olive wood
to sell in souvenir shops.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Munir Masou, work odd jobs in construction and
carpentry in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Few make more than $1,000 a month, and that's where the
charities come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian community doesn't receive much help so we try to
fill in the gap,'' said Edward Dabdoub, the administrative director
of Caritas. ``We don't like to be too public about it. We could
never fulfill the demand. But we do help an average of 45 families
a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Masou family's new house is small and unfinished,
they now have the relative luxury of living in three bedrooms,
instead of one, a necessity now that the eldest daughter, Navine,
has turned 12.
</P>
<P>
   With the younger children sleeping in one room and the parents
in another, Navine has a room all her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold, but I'm not afraid to sleep alone anymore,'' she
said. ``I can move more freely here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the house seems to have helped ease the children's
disappointment over a Christmas likely spent without presents.
Navine wants a mystery book, Nasri and Amir, boys aged 11 and 10,
want remote-controlled toy cars, and 3-year-old Mary would like
some chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   But the children seem to understand that their parents are
struggling just to pay back loans for their new house and cannot
afford to put any presents under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought his father would bring him a toy car, Nasri
shrugged. ``I didn't ask for anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the children have set their sights on the celebrations
set here for Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Only 3 percent of West Bank Palestinians are Christians. Most,
like the Masou family, are Greek Orthodox, which means they mark
Christmas on Jan. 7, according to the Eastern calendar.
</P>
<P>
   But the big night for everyone here is still Friday, when
leaders of all the Christian denominations will gather at Manger
Square and choirs from around the world will sing. That's when
Nasri and Amir will join others in their Boy Scout troop to parade
along the streets of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   By spring, the Masous hope to buy glass windows for the house.
The first loan from Caritas was spent putting tiles on the floor,
painting the walls and building the window frames, which made the
place livable.
</P>
<P>
   The family has applied for another loan of $1,000 to buy glass
panes, however, Caritas' administrators have not yet approved the
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I put presents under the tree, but not this year,''
said Ibtisam Masou, whose long brown hair tied in a ponytail makes
her look even younger than her 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year will be better,'' she said. ``I'll take the kids
and go to church. Then my family will come here to visit. It will
be nice because we'll have room.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
