<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR SUSPECT IN OFFICER'S SHOOTING WIDENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hunt for the alleged killer of a popular Holyoke, Mass.
police officer spilled into neighboring states Thursday as scores
of police combed the old mill city for the second day.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls continued to pour into Holyoke police
headquarters with sightings of the suspect, 27-year-old Eddie
Morales, and in Lawrence, where he previously lived. Morales had
also lived in Boston, about 80 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   State police manned roadblocks around Holyoke during the early
morning hours, said Sergeant George Girard.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who, officials said, has an extensive record of drug
arrests, allegedly pumped five bullets into Patrolman John A.
DiNapoli as the plainsclothes officer chased Morales in an unmarked
car Wednesday around 9 a.m. DiNapoli, 52, had volunteered to help
break up a fight. Bullets hit him in the heart, abdomen, shoulder
and arm _ he died at 9:24 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation continues and the search continues,'' said
Patrol Officer Jane Deshais. ``We are hearing of sightings
everywhere, and every single one of them is being followed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Renaudette, a bartender, said she and her son spotted
Morales getting off Interstate 391 near High Street in Holyoke on
Wednesday at about 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was driving and he looked straight over at me. There's
another man with him in the passenger seat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a press briefing, the city's leading Latino
religious leaders, the Rev. Roberto Sierra and the Rev. Miguel
Cruz, said they were establishing two 24-hour hotlines to take
calls about Morales' whereabouts. They particularly urged Morales'
relatives and friends, perhaps too timid to call police, to call
the hotlines instead.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke has seen its share of problems between police and
Hispanics, including high arrest rates and accusations of
insensitivity by some Latinos against law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relations between Latinos and police have not been at their
best and now this situation strains something that is already
tense,'' said Betty Medina Lichstenstein, director of a Latino
family agency in Holyoke and a former School Committee member.
``Right now, we are trying to help this community move forward as
one, not as a white, a black, and a brown community. We are asking
everyone to please assist us in getting this man arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the magnitude of the crime, Lichtenstein said some in this
city of 45,000 _ half of whom are believed to be Latino _ fear that
Morales on the loose may not come out alive if he resists capture.
She urged him to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli, a 21-year veteran of the force, was on his way back
from dropping another officer off at a courthouse about 9 a.m.
Wednesday when he volunteered to answer a call to break up an
argument between two men on a street corner. He was still in his
cruiser when he was shot several times.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the search for possible leads extended into
Connecticut, about a half-hour drive south from Holyoke, and into
New Hampshire, just north of Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
