<SLUG> BC-INDEXES-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORRIS COLUMN: THE BEAR-BULL MARKET _ AS INDEXES SOAR, MOST STOCKS
FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a tale of two economies and of the intertwined stock
markets that track them and are sending out wildly confusing
messages. One market is in a speculative blowoff; the other may be
in a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The more exciting of the economies is the new one, the
Internet-driven high-technology model that has captivated
investors. That is the economy that has caused the Nasdaq composite
index to leap 48 percent in 10 weeks. Companies in that market are
showered with capital, and new issues routinely double in price on
the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   But the other economy _ the old non-Internet one that still
accounts for most economic activity _ is starting to slow, and many
of the stocks in it are weak. Soaring tech stocks have pushed the
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks up more than 18 percent in
1999, but most of the stocks in the index have gone down. On both
the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, two-thirds of the stocks
are down at least 20 percent from their peaks.
</P>
<P>
   The old economy's stock market is reacting to the economic
forces that usually affect markets. Interest rates are up, and the
Federal Reserve is hinting that more increases lie ahead. Oil
prices have doubled, and wage pressures are growing.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar may be vulnerable, with the trade deficit at an
unprecedented level. If it weren't for the dominance of new economy
stocks in market indexes, analysts might be asking whether the
market's weakness was sending a recession warning.
</P>
<P>
   But the new economy stocks are in a Millennium Melt-Up. Doug
Kass, a hedge fund manager, reports that 57 of this year's new
issues now rank among the 200 largest technology companies in the
country, as measured by market capitalization. Most of them have
little if any revenues, no profits and soaring share prices. Their
investors won't be bothered if the Fed raises interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
   What would bother them? Some stocks will collapse when it
becomes clear that their business models are not working. That
could happen to some e-retailers when Christmas-season results are
in. But for most new economy stocks, such a verdict is years away.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those business models, however, rely on ready access to
cheap capital to finance years of losses before the (hoped-for)
bonanza arrives. A change in investor psychology could conceivably
cause some companies that would have succeeded to fold up because
of lack of capital. But there is no indication that will happen
soon.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves us with two stock markets in one. One has many
stocks that seem fairly, or even cheaply, valued by traditional
valuation measures. The other is completely oblivious to such
measures. ``There is,'' says Leon Cooperman, a hedge fund manager,
``an unbridled willingness to speculate, but no willingness to
speculate on value.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed may come in for harsh criticism if the new economy bull
market ends badly. Many billions of dollars may be lost if most of
today's young stars fade into obscurity rather than shoot into
prominence in the real economy, where revenues and profits are
important.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those losses will damage the overall economy, just as
the profits from soaring stock prices have helped to pump up
consumer spending. Then the critics will want to know why the Fed
did not slow the speculation before it got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear what the Fed could have done, or can do now.
Stock markets can take on a life of their own, and the new economy
market has done that. It may be that all the Fed can do is watch
and worry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
