<HEADLINE>
MALI'S PRESENT IS POOR. CAN IT BUILD A FUTURE ON THE PAST?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JENNE-JENO, Mali _ Standing at the bottom of a 10-foot-deep pit,
in a field where the only other activity came from a nomadic
herdsman urging his cows to munch on yellowing shrub, the American
archaeologist and his African students were surrounded by
tantalizing clues to life here in the oldest African city south of
the Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   A brownish vase lay buried on the pit's floor with its rim
protruding, not far from a pot with a lid. The side of a small red
urn jutted out of a wall. And embedded in a wall at the center of
the pit was the great find of this dig: a big brown urn, perhaps as
old as a millennium, that the archaeologists had sliced in half,
top-down like a pear, to reveal skeletal remains.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of men hoisted the big urn onto a stretcher and
carried it with some urgency, as if it were a patient not beyond
resuscitation, to a Land Rover nearby. The American, Roderick J.
McIntosh, held on to the pot with both hands, trudging with visible
effort under the sun on a field littered with countless pottery
shards and the occasional protruding vase rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of sites like this in Mali,'' said
McIntosh, an archaeologist at Rice University, who has been
excavating sites in this West African country since 1977. ``Next to
Egypt, Mali has the richest deposit of artifacts in Africa. There
are parts of the Sahara here you can't set foot on and not crunch
something underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wealth of artifacts, little is known of the ancient
history of Mali, or the rest of sub-Saharan Africa, compared with
other areas of the world. In the landlocked territory now occupied
by Mali, great empires _ with names like Ghana, Mali, Songhai _
rose and fell almost silently.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim Arabs crossed the Sahara in the 11th century, and the
texts of Islamic historians then bring some light to life here.
Cities with fabled names like Timbuktu and Djenne, a couple of
miles from here, grew into important centers of Islamic culture and
learning.
</P>
<P>
   The great mosque in Djenne, which stands as the largest
mud-brick building in the world, with a facade that thousands of
townspeople help refresh after every rainy season, was restored
early this century. Its model, which was built on the same site in
the 11th century, was known as far as Europe.
</P>
<P>
   What was here, though, before Islam? The long held, if
simplified, view was that Islam brought the features of
civilization to West Africa: cities, trade, commerce, organized
political structures, professions. But research in the last two
decades, whether in the land of the Yoruba in southwest Nigeria, or
here in the Niger River basin of Mali, strongly suggests that some
of those developments preceded the religion's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nothing much survives of Jenne-Jeno except its ruins. And
even though McIntosh's research suggests that the city died around
the 12th century, for reasons that remain unclear, people in the
area seemed aware that a place called Jenne-Jeno once existed just
outside Djenne.
</P>
<P>
   Jenne-Jeno was surrounded by a 1.3-mile wall that was 12 feet
thick at its base, McIntosh said, standing among the remains of the
structure. From the artifacts he has dug up over the years, he
surmises that masons, blacksmiths, fishermen and weavers lived
together in a sign that urban life permitted divisions of labor.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the discovery of similar possessions and tools in
most houses suggests that the inhabitants enjoyed comparable social
status, and were not ruled by a despot _ the political structure
that was widely believed to have produced the beginning of urban
living in West Africa. The unearthing of materials like gold and
copper, which are not found in the region, point to long-distance
trade and commerce well before Arabs established the trans-Saharan
trade routes in the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
   Radiocarbon dating of scores of relics showed that those found
deepest in the soil went back to 250 years before Jesus, making
Jenne-Jeno the oldest known city in sub-Saharan Africa. At its
height, McIntosh estimated, more than 15,000 people lived in the
city of 68 to 85 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have been Chinese cities bigger than that, but not
by much,'' he said. ``And only a handful of European cities would
have been of that size.''
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts go up to the 12th century and Jenne-Jeno's
mysterious death. Did the increase in trade bring diseases that
wiped out its inhabitants?
</P>
<P>
   Boubacar H. Diaby, an archaeologist and head of Mali's ministry
of culture and tourism division in Djenne, says the absence of
Islamic relics in Jenne-Jeno suggests that its inhabitants
converted to Islam and moved to Djenne.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the findings, you can tell that they precede the
arrival of Islam,'' Diaby said. ``For example, people are buried in
urns sitting up, not lying down in the Islamic way. It's possible
that the people of Jenne-Jeno left this animist city, but kept it
untouched because of their ancestral ties to it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some questions may never be answered. Although a preservation
campaign by Diaby has stopped looting around Jenne-Jeno in the last
decade, illegal digging continues in Mali. The site here bears the
scars of looters: crudely dug holes that have created depressions
where water has accumulated and grass now grows, effectively making
it impossible for archaeologists to study the area.
</P>
<P>
   For years, looters fed African art dealers in Paris and Brussels
with Malian artifacts, especially prized statuettes with human or
animal shapes that sold for thousands of dollars. A five-year
campaign with the strong endorsement of President Alpha O. Konare,
an archaeologist by training who dug alongside McIntosh in
Jenne-Jeno in 1977, has slowed the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term goal, Diaby said, is to use Mali's cultural legacy
to develop tourism. It is a daunting task in one of the world's
poorest nations. Roads are bad; gas stations few; Djenne, which
becomes an island in the rainy season when the Bani River floods,
does not even have a bridge for cars. From independence in 1960 to
the early 1990s, socialist or military governments ruled this
country of 10 million people, and kept it closed off to the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Diaby pointed to the example of another West African country,
Ghana, where tourism was nonexistent until several years ago. Using
its critical role in the history of the trans-Atlantic slave trade,
Ghana has made tourism one of its leading industries.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Mali, Diaby said, developing tourism is something
of a race against the clock, against indifference, erosion and
looting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's hard to tell a poor peasant that he shouldn't dig
because it will preserve his cultural identity,'' Diaby said,
standing not too far from a pit where Malian students would find a
pot an hour later, ``and that sometime in the future his culture, a
place like Jenne-Jeno, might bring development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
