<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHERE WERE YOU IN 1002? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe a millennium is too big a thought. There's a lot of
resistance to this celebration. If we were just turning over a
century, people might have found it easier to wrap their minds
around the whole concept. Or they could be afraid that if they
engage in a conversation about the last 1,000 years, somebody will
ask for their opinion of the Song dynasty or the St. Bryce's Day
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   And of course we're being deflected by critics who complain that
the real turn of the millennium won't happen until Jan. 1, 2001.
(Note to the 2001 purists: It doesn't matter. The whole thing is
arbitrary, and we're in it for the zeroes.)
</P>
<P>
   This great, if totally artificial, event has at least one
important story to tell us. It's that no people has a lock on
history. The nations and ethnic groups that look as if they're on
top now were definitely somewhere else 1,000 years ago, and as time
goes on, the wheel will turn again.
</P>
<P>
   The term Dark Ages has gone out of fashion, but I think it's
fair to say that 1,000 years ago Western Europe was evolutionally
challenged. Since the fall of the Roman Empire, things had been
slipping backward.
</P>
<P>
   The West had lost the Greek classics and, if the squabbling of
two 11th-century French correspondents can be believed, the
mathematicians had forgotten what the interior angle of a triangle
looked like. Most people lived in feudal villages, eating what they
grew and producing little else.
</P>
<P>
   Rome was a semi-rural tourist trap, surviving off the pilgrims.
Genoa had declined to a fishing village. England was governed by a
king named Ethelred the Unready; 'nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Cordoba, the Caliph Hakam II had a library of
400,000 manuscripts and supported 27 advanced public schools for
poor but promising students. Muslims, Christians and Jews lived
together more or less amicably. Food was abundant and cheap. Even
the common folk ate meat, fish and fresh fruit at a time when the
famine-racked peasants to the north were eating each other.
</P>
<P>
   Constantinople was the shopping center of the universe. You
entered the city through a gold-plated gate and walked along
streets lined with colonnades to protect pedestrians from the
elements. The streets were paved, lighted at night and policed
around the clock, more amenable to pedestrians than London in the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle East, Baghdad was famous for its culture, wealth
and religious tolerance _ one of the rare places where a poet could
make a good living. ``People immigrate to it from all countries,
both near and far, and everywhere there are men who have preferred
it to their own country,'' reported a 10th-century visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Kumbi Saleh, the capital of Ghana, was another mecca for
travelers and traders. The king could raise an army of 200,000 for
battle, and visitors to his palace said he was the richest monarch
in the world. (It might have been the 30-pound gold nugget he used
to tether his horse.) At night the streets were filled with dancing
and singing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the visitors to these cities were Jewish
merchant-adventurers who were almost the only navigators willing to
sail the commercial routes from China to Africa to England. At a
time when the world was torn between Christian and Muslim, being
Jewish seemed like a fairly safe, neutral position.
</P>
<P>
   That was at least the thinking of the Khazars, a tribe of nomads
who lived along the Volga River. Deciding that paganism was passe,
the Khazars held a communal debate to choose the most promising
theological direction. They decided to all become Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   We can look back now and realize that Constantinople's culture
had begun to atrophy, and that soon Venice, a little marsh-bound
city with visions of grandeur, would begin stealing away its trade.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the 11th century, Cordoba's glory days were
over. Baghdad would be leveled by the Mongols in the 13th century.
China, which had been so far ahead of Europe on almost every front
in 1000, soon began to slow down and become static.
</P>
<P>
   We don't often contemplate the inevitability of our own
civilization's decline, and really there's not much point. We can
no more stop history than the Indians could turn back the
Mayflower. But we can use this moment to remind ourselves that it's
wise to honor the cultures you pass on the way up, since you're
likely to see them again on the way down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
