<SLUG> BC-FBI-INDICTMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY CONTINUES PROBE IN FBI-MOB CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The federal grand jury that charged retired FBI Special
Agent John J. Connolly Jr. with committing crimes to protect prized
informant-gangsters James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen ``The
Rifleman'' Flemmi is investigating more allegations of FBI
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   A number of current and retired agents have been called in from
around the country to appear before the grand jury in US District
Court in Worcester over the past few months and more agents are
scheduled to testify in the coming weeks, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern declined to comment on the probe,
other than to say that a task force of out-of-town FBI agents
formed two years ago to scrutinize the FBI's handling of Bulger and
Flemmi is continuing its work.
</P>
<P>
   But sources familiar with the investigation say it is hampered
by the passage of time. While some agents have admitted they failed
to pursue tips that Bulger and Flemmi were involved in drug dealing
or extortion, it happened so many years ago that the five-year
statute of limitations on most federal crimes has run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the evidence is old,'' said one source familiar with
the investigation, noting that Bulger, 70, has been a fugitive
since his indictment in January 1995 on racketeering charges and
Flemmi, 65, has been jailed since then while awaiting trial in that
case.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, 59, was charged Wednesday in a five-count racketeering
indictment with Bulger and Flemmi just as the statute of
limitations was about to run out on the most recent alleged crime:
that Connolly tipped off Bulger, Flemmi, and New England Mafia boss
Francis ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme on the eve of their January 1995
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Boston attorney R. Robert Popeo, who represents Connolly, said
it is obvious that Salemme, who pleaded guilty on Dec. 9 to
racketeering charges, testified against his client before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   The Connolly indictment alleges that he warned Salemme during a
meeting in early 1994 that he was under investigation by a grand
jury and promised to alert him, through Flemmi, when he was about
to be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme ``will tell them anything they want to hear,'' said
Popeo, noting that Bulger and Flemmi had provided the FBI with
information about the criminal activities of Salemme and other
mobsters for years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it was Connolly who arrested Salemme in New York City in
the early 1970s when he was wanted for attempted murder in
Massachusetts for maiming an attorney by blowing up his car.
Salemme served 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you have Bulger and Flemmi as the sources of information
that brings down organized crime,'' said Popeo. Now, he said, the
people they informed on, like Salemme, are being allowed to testify
against agents like Connolly. ``It's hardly objective evidence,''
Popeo said.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly is charged with protecting Bulger and Flemmi beginning
in 1975, when he first cultivated Bulger as an FBI informant, and
continuing through 1995. He allegedly tipped them off to
investigations and falsified FBI reports to cover up their
involvement in extortion, loansharking, bookmaking, and drug
dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, who retired from the FBI in December 1990 after 22
years, is also accused of funneling payoffs totaling $7,000 from
Bulger and Flemmi to his former FBI supervisor, John Morris, during
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It was Morris, who was granted immunity from prosecution, who
offered some of the most damning testimony against Connolly during
hearings in federal court last year that unmasked the FBI's
relationship with Bulger and Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   Morris admitted pocketing $7,000 in payoffs from Bulger and
Flemmi and claimed Connolly delivered two payments of $1,000 each.
He also claimed that he and Connolly tipped off Bulger and Flemmi
to investigations. But Flemmi testified that the money was paid
directly to Morris and that Morris was the one who warned him of
the indictment five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several agents admitted during the hearings that they failed to
pursue tips against Bulger after Connolly assured them they were
not true and reminded them that Bulger was a valuable informant.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Kenneth Fishman, who represents Flemmi, accused
prosecutors Thursday of a ``whitewash'' for indicting Connolly for
conduct that he contended was blessed by his superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is hoping that the public will conclude there
is one bad apple in the FBI, rather than acknowledge that these
relationships were approved at the highest levels of the FBI and
the Justice Department,'' Fishman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
