<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: GO-AHEAD FOR D'ALEMA
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema narrowly received agreement from
the lower house of Parliament to start a new administration. The
vote was 310-287, with 18 abstentions. His new center-left
coalition is smaller, but perhaps more cohesive, than the one he
started out with 14 months ago. ``It worries me that my government
is born of a slimmer majority,'' D'Alema told the legislature.
``But it is better than continuing to live with constant
bickering.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PRISONER FURLOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Some 335 prisoners, mostly convicted terrorists and murderers,
were sent home for Christmas from prisons around Northern Ireland.
As a sign of confidence in the region's efforts to establish peace,
the Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, allowed eight
prisoners not eligible for the usual parole program to go home as
well. The prisoners are to return in 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: LIBEL LAW REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would study ways of reforming its libel
laws after it turned out that a former Conservative trade minister
had raised more than $640,000 from supporters in order to bring a
libel action against Mohamed Al Fayed, the owner of Harrods. The
ex-minister, Neil Hamilton, lost the case and incurred more than
$1.6 million in legal costs. One of the concerns raised by the case
is that Hamilton's backers are now liable to pay a further share of
the overall legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUES PLANNED DOUBLE ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said a second van bomb belonging to the Basque
separatist group ETA was timed to explode at the same time as
another van bomb discovered earlier. Both vehicles were on their
way to Madrid when they were found by the police. Interior Minister
Jaime Mayor Oreja said both devices were set to go off at 7:56
p.m., although the exact date and locations are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: ELECTION DATE
</P>
<P>
   The industry minister and government spokesman, Josep Pique,
said general elections would probably be held next March 12. The
final decision on the vote, which must be held by May, is up to
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar and will be announced in
mid-January. After four years in power, Aznar's center-right
Popular Party leads the main opposition Socialist Party in opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: CORSICAN CEASE-FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Four of the eight guerrilla groups demanding independence for
Corsica declared an open-ended halt to violence, saying Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin's meeting with 28 Corsican elected
representatives on Dec. 13 had opened the way to peace. The biggest
armed faction, the National Front for the Liberation of
Corsica-Historic Wing, is among those supporting the truce, the
eighth in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   NICARAGUA: ISLAND DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   Raising the stakes in a three-way dispute over a Caribbean
island, Nicaragua has ordered the expulsion of two Colombian
military attaches, with President Arnoldo Aleman accusing Colombia
of ``an act of aggression against our sovereignty.'' The action
came a day after a new treaty went into effect in which Colombia
and Honduras divided up some 50,000 square miles of Caribbean
waters, believed to be rich in oil and gas, near San Andres Island,
claimed by Nicaragua but under Colombian control. Earlier,
Nicaragua put new tariffs on Honduran goods and placed its army on
alert.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ARCHAEOLOGICAL OUTRAGE
</P>
<P>
   Entrepeneurs who were to stage a New Year's Eve rock concert at
Teotihuacan, the site of pre-Columbian pyramids north of Mexico
City, used heavy earth-moving equipment to flatten some of the
grounds in order to accommodate 200,000 people. Stunned
archaeological authorities ordered the bulldozers out, canceled the
concert, and are now estimating the damage to the site, the
newspaper La Jornada reported.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: DEPUTY TAPPED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said that if at some point he
decides to step down as Asia's longest-serving elected leader, his
deputy, Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, would succeed him. Mahathir named
Abdullah as deputy prime minister last January, replacing Anwar
Ibrahim, his longtime heir apparent, whom he fired two years ago
and who is now on trial for sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GOLAN DIVIDEND
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak, laying the groundwork of his public
campaign to defend a possible withdrawal from the Golan Heights,
said peace treaties with Syria and Lebanon could lead to reduced
military service requirements. Most men now serve three years in
the army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
