<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR-END BUYING LIFTS MARKET INDEXES TO NEW HIGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A year-end buying spree drove the three main stock
gauges to new peaks Thursday, with the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index surging briefly above the 4,000 mark before falling
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the market exploding to the upside,'' said Daniel
C. Mathisson, a senior trader at D.E. Shaw, citing pressure by
institutions to hold winning stocks for year-end reports and a
general preholiday euphoria that has prevailed in late December for
most of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also pointed to tax strategies, with investors tending
to defer sales of winning stocks until after the new year, when
capital gains taxes will not be due until April 2001. At the same
time, losing stocks were being unloaded to generate deductions for
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 202.16 points, or 1.8
percent, to 11,405.76, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
rose 22.21 points, or 1.6 percent, to 1,458.34. The Nasdaq, which
climbed 32.14 points, or 0.8 percent, to 3,969.44, is now up 81
percent for the year, the biggest jump for any major index since
the Dow soared 81.7 percent in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a major milestone,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief
strategist at Edward Jones in St. Louis. ``But it also should serve
as a warning to investors not to get carried away with technology
stocks and to maintain balance in their portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most recent sessions, advancing stocks substantially
outnumbered declining ones, cheering analysts who have long worried
about poor breadth, with a relative handful of technology issues
accounting for the bulk of gains as market gauges surged into
uncharted territory.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's breadth was the best since late October as 1,932 New
York Stock Exchange issues rose and 1,155 fell. But new lows
continued to outnumber new highs, by 248 to 108.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty is that there's more winners,'' said David G.
Sowerby, a strategist at Loomis Sayles in Detroit. ``The breadth is
looking delightful.''
</P>
<P>
   Sowerby also said that another factor contributing to the rally
was institutions and investors who might have otherwise bought
stocks next week, perhaps those depressed by tax-selling, did so
Thursday to avoid having their transactions caught up in possible
problems related to turn-of the-year computer glitches. Buyers have
three business days to pay for stock.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the New York Stock Exchange moderated to 728.6
million shares from 844.2 million as many traders and investors
left work early because of the approach of the Christmas holidays.
The markets are closed Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Internet stocks were prominent nonparticipants in the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com and eBay, reported to be the two most popular
shopping sites last week, slumped 7 11/16, to 90, and 7 3/16, to
142 5/16, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But telecommunications and other high-technology stocks were
among the biggest gainers. MCI Worldcom, up 4{, to 81, was the
biggest contributor to the advance of the S&AMP;P 500 while
Hewlett-Packard, up 5 11/16, to 112|, paced the rise in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 Dow components, 25 advanced, nine of them by more than
2 points as basic industry issues like Alcoa, up 2 9/16, to 79[,
and International Paper, up 2\, to 55 13/16, joined financial, drug
and other groups in posting big gains.
</P>
<P>
   Another reflection of the broad nature of the advance was a 1.33
percent climb in the Wilshire 5000 index, which covers nearly every
American public company.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers, up 3{, to 66 11/16, paced the drug group, with
Merck, Schering-Plough and Warner-Lambert each climbing more than 2
points.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel was another of the high-technology winners, leaping 8
7/16, to 105, aided by a PaineWebber report that it stood to
benefit from a reauctioning of wireless licenses. Novell jumped 7\,
to 34 5/16, after a Fahnestock official named it a favorite stock,
likely to grow 35 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Weis Markets, which has been strong lately because a family
dispute has raised speculation about a possible sale, rose 1 7/16,
to 42~, after it authorized an adviser to explore all options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
