<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANKS-VENTURE-CAPITAL     12-23 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING WINDFALLS, BIG BANKS FINANCE START-UPS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For venture capitalists, it has never been easier to get rich.
Now even big banks are catching on to the potential profits in
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, major commercial banks like Chase Manhattan Corp.
have tripled the money they devote to venture capital, the
high-risk, high-return world of financing companies before they go
public. Overall, they'll spend more than $4 billion this year, and
their investments are rising every quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For banks, the appeal of venture capital is obvious. Chase and
its kin are happy to get 8 percent interest on a typical loan. By
contrast, the average venture capital investment in a new company
almost doubled this year. And bank stocks have weakened this year,
while stocks in publicly traded venture capital companies have
soared.
</P>
<P>
   But as banks move deeper into venture capital, they face some
risks of their own. A few banks, notably Chase and Wells Fargo,
have had successful venture units for years; others have little
experience with the hyper-competition of Silicon Valley. Skeptics,
recalling fiascoes like the bust in high-yield bonds of the early
1990s, note that commercial banks have a bad habit of finding
trends just as they peak.
</P>
<P>
   Yet banks have further reasons to jump into venture capital.
Accounting rules give financial institutions flexibility about when
they choose to recognize venture capital profits. Some analysts
worry that banks will apply that power to set aside ``honey pots''
of unrealized profits on successful venture capital investments.
Banks could then take those profits in difficult quarters to hide
problems in other divisions from investors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Charles Peabody, an analyst for Mitchell
Securities, noted that J.P. Morgan recorded a pre-tax gain of $255
million, or 83 cents a share after taxes, on its venture capital
portfolio in the quarter ended Sept. 30. Companies can realize
gains on shares of nonpublic companies when they sell the
investments at a profit, but what was notable in this case was that
the bank did not even sell its stakes. It simply reappraised them
upward.
</P>
<P>
   That raise let the bank handily beat analyst estimates of its
profit for the quarter by 7 cents a share, Peabody said. Peabody
has a ``sell'' rating on Morgan stock, which has risen 20 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said that the write-up was proper and consistent with
accounting rules, which require the bank to measure the fair value
of its investments each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the potential pitfalls, banks are increasingly
enthusiastic about venture capital, particularly in new companies
with strong prospects in fields like healthcare and technology.
Traditionally, venture capitalists count on a few big winners to
pay for lots of failed investments. This year, the winners are
bigger than ever, thanks to the raging market in technology stocks,
which has allowed even unprofitable companies to sell shares to the
public at enormous valuations.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1999, venture capital funds that invest in
early-stage companies are expected to post returns of 85 percent,
according to the National Venture Capital Association, compared to
a 15 percent gain so far this year in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. During the last five years, early-stage venture
investments have risen 45 percent annually, compared to a 28
percent yearly gain for the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to be a growing business,'' said Ron
Mandle, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., a New York
investment firm. ``Chase and some of the other banks are increasing
the amount of investments that they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Big banks have long had private equity divisions that put up
capital for deals too complex or risky for individual shareholders
to finance. But the stepped-up venture financing reverses trends
earlier in the decade, when following years of subpar venture
capital returns, banks largely abandoned the market to focus on
providing equity for management and leveraged buyouts.
</P>
<P>
   That decision has proven costly. During the last five years, the
return on capital devoted to buyouts has averaged just 17 percent
annually, less than half the returns for early-stage venture
financing. And the gap is widening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buyout game has played its course,'' said John Watkins, a
managing director at J.P. Morgan Capital.
</P>
<P>
   So banks, which in retrospect scaled back their venture
financing at exactly the wrong time, are racing back into the
business. They are being led by Chase and Wells Fargo, two banks
reaping benefits today from their decisions not to abandon venture
capital completely in the lean years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Through its Chase Capital Partners subsidiary, Chase provided
almost $2 billion in venture and buyout funding in 1999, including
$800 million for investments in technology, telecommunications, and
media companies. Overall, Chase's portfolio includes investments of
$7 billion in more than 500 companies, according to Jeffrey Walker,
a Chase Capital managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were investors in the beginning of the Internet,
particularly on the East Coast, where content providers rather than
technology companies are dominant,'' Walker said. ``We're the
largest Internet investors in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase's winners include investments in StarMedia Networks, an
Internet portal that focuses on Spanish and Portuguese speakers,
and Geocities, a community Web site Yahoo bought in May for $3.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio is only a tiny fraction of Chase Manhattan's total
assets of $370 billion, but it has had an outsized impact on
Chase's bottom line this year. In total, Chase Capital Partners
contributed $952 million to the bank's profit in the first nine
months of 1999, 17 percent of its pre-tax income during that span.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, Wells has been the biggest winner. The bank's
Norwest Venture Partners subsidiary earned $550 million on a $12
million investment in the Cerent Corp., a tiny networking equipment
start-up, when Cisco Systems bought Cerent for $7 billion earlier
this year. For all of 1999, Wells Fargo will earn roughly $1.2
billion from its private equity division, more than a fifth of the
bank's total pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
   Successes like that have fueled Wells' commitment to the venture
business, said John Whaley, a Norwest Venture partner. The company
nearly doubled its venture financing to $450 million this year,
from $230 million in 1998, and Whaley said he has had no problem
finding places to invest the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of competition, but there's also a
tremendous amount of new business development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins of Morgan said his firm shares that view. Morgan will
invest almost $500 million in telecommunications and technology
startups this year, nearly triple its investment three years ago,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology, telecom, and the Internet are undergoing
fundamental change and are really attractive for private equity,''
Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he thinks Morgan's reputation and worldwide reach
will be increasingly attractive for start-up companies choosing a
venture capital partner. ``We bring a window into a large global
firm that has contacts all over the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Isaak Karaev, the chief executive of Multex.com, a financial
services company that was financed in part by Chase Capital and
went public earlier this year, said that Multex's relationship with
the Chase venture capitalists opened doors throughout the bank. As
a result, ``Chase became one of our reasonably large customers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some big banks remain wary of venture capital. Despite its name,
Citicorp Venture Capital is largely a provider of buyout financing
for bigger, older companies, and Richard Cashin, its president,
said that his firm has no plans to change.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, traditional independent venture capital firms aren't
exactly quaking at the thought of banks entering their turf. Walter
Kortschak, the managing partner of Summit Partners, a Silicon
Valley venture firm that has invested about $3 billion in
technology start-ups, said he doesn't see banks as serious
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For now, analysts seem to share that view. They have been
relatively conservative in valuing banks' venture gains, figuring
that the profits are too unpredictable to count on indefinitely.
``If there are huge windfalls, I would tend to discount them,''
Mandle said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That course might be wise. If the boom-and-bust history of
venture capital is any indication, the gains will not continue
forever. Total investment from banks, independent venture capital
firms, corporations like Intel and wealthy individuals is expected
to double to $38 billion in 1999, according to the National Venture
Capital Association. More than half that money, $20 billion, will
go to Internet-related companies, triple the 1998 figure and a
tenfold rise from the level three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the flood of money has not hurt returns. But Whaley
warned that new venture capitalists looking for riches _ banks or
anyone else _ might be disappointed. ``It's tough to get into it
overnight, if that's what people are thinking,'' he said. A
windfall like Wells Fargo's on Cerent, he added, ``is the
culmination of many years in the business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
