<HEADLINE>
BUYING BINGE DRIVES NASDAQ INDEX OVER 4000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holiday weekend started early on Wall Street Thursday as the
Nasdaq composite index briefly topped 4000 for the first time, less
than two months after passing the 3000 mark. The Dow Jones
industrial average, meanwhle, jingled past its August high to close
up 200 at a record 11,405.76.
</P>
<P>
   The buying binge was driven by computer hardware and Internet
stocks that hit record highs on the last day of trading before
Christmas (the stock and bond markets are closed Friday). On the
New York Stock Exchange, technology advances were also buoyed by
gains in pharmaceutical and oil stocks along with financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had rallies before at this time of the year, but the
current speculative frenzy is more extreme than anything we have
seen in this century,'' said Thoms O'Neill, chief investment
officer at Fleet Bank. ``What is concerning is the level of
financial participation by the public in speculative stocks to the
point that when the downturn comes, a lot of investors will be
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and others see investors scrambling to own Internet
stocks _ from infrastructure software firms to electronic commerce
``dot-com'' companies _ so they will not be left out of the
Internet economic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Casting aside traditional investment yardsticks of profitablity,
return on assets, and other financial measurements, investors
pushed up tech issues to record levels _ even abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The overseas buying binge toppled market indicators in London,
Paris, and Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest gain was in the United States on the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite, which hit 4001.63 shortly after
noon _ just 36 trading sessions after it reached 3000 _ before
closing at 3969.50 for a gain of 32.14 points, or 0.8 percent. Even
with the late-afternoon dip, the Nasdaq index has soared 81 percent
this year, with just a week of trading remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This milestone is nice to watch, but it is not something to
get overly hyperactive about,'' cautioned Richard Babson, president
of Babson-United Investment Advisors Inc. in Watertown. ``None of
these statistics are startling.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors also pushed up Big Board issues as the Dow surged
202.16 points _ a 1.8 percent increase _ to close at a record
11,405.76. The previous record, set Aug. 25, was 11,326.04.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index climbed 22.21 points or 1.6
percent, to a new high of 1458.34. The S&AMP;P has gained more than 18
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the hefty gains in stocks led all three indexes _
Nasdaq, Dow, and the S&AMP;P _ to rise 1 percent in the first 10
minutes of trading, reaching their highs in the afternoon before
Nasdaq retreated in the last half-hour of trading, mostly from
Internet retailers Amazon.com Inc. and Yahoo! Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these indexes show how technology plays an increasingly
important role in the US economcy,'' said Peter Bennett, head of
equities for State Street Research. ``And with improving economies
in Europe, significant growth in Asia beginning with the recovery
in Japan, and the bottoming out in South America, we should see
continuing improvements next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond tech stocks, pharmaceutical issues also rebounded with
Bristol-Myers Squibb, up 3 1/2 to 66 11/16, and Warner-Lambert, up
2 3/16 to 85 1/8, leading the way. Even smaller drug companies
benefited as the American Stock Exchange's pharmaceutical index
gained 2.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the record-breaking results reflected the past. Since
1989, US stock markets have gained on eight of the 11 last trading
sessions before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Volume, however, was off on all the exchanges as many traders
got a head start on their three-day holiday weekend. Still, 727
million shares changed hands on the New York Stock Exchange by the
4 p.m. close, 19 percent below the three-month daily average of 906
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
