<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS WARN OF SUSPICIOUS HOLIDAY PARCELS FROM GERMANY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
(Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alerted to the possibility of mail bombs from
Germany, federal officials began screening holiday parcels Thursday
and renewed warnings that terrorists _ both foreign and domestic _
might be targeting Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two of the three people arrested recently at U.S.
border crossings have been linked to international terrorist
organizations in Algeria and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, the Postal Inspection Service began X-ray
examinations of all parcels and first-class mail from Frankfurt,
Germany, after receiving a mail-bomb alert from the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued at 2 a.m. Thursday in Washington, the FBI
reported that ``unsubstantiated information'' had been received
saying ``that individuals may be planning to send bombs in small
parcels to addresses in the United States'' from Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Except to say that airlines _ along with state and local
authorities _ were notified once the tips had been received, bureau
officials declined to provide any other details about the
information or its sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of an abundance of caution, the public is being promptly
alerted to this information,'' the FBI statement said.
``Questionable packages should not be handled and local authorities
should be notified.''
</P>
<P>
   Postal Inspector Dan Mihalko said anyone receiving an unexpected
parcel from Frankfurt should exercise caution, especially if there
is no return address. ``If you receive something that in your mind
is suspicious, something that you're not familiar with, don't open
it. Call the professionals _ the postal service and the police,''
Mihalko advised.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to screening packages at 11 U.S. facilities that
process mail received directly from Frankfurt, postal and aviation
officials are working with airlines to examine any mail over 16
ounces before it leaves Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to cover it at both ends,'' Mihalko said.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent threats of violence _ from international terrorists
and home-grown extremists _ have prompted officials to increase
security and heighten public awareness while walking a fine line to
avoid a panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that at the millennium, a lot of people who may even
be a little crazy by our standards, or may have a political point
to make, may try to take advantage of it,'' President Clinton said
late Thursday on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see something that's suspicious, you should report it,
just to make sure that we do everything we possibly can to maximize
our protection,'' the president said. ``But I wouldn't just hunker
down until it was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, security has been stepped up at airports, seaports
and the Post Office in the wake of warnings this week from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking aggressive steps to use all the technology and
tactics that we have available,'' said John Babb, director of field
operations for the U.S. Customs Service's East Texas office.
</P>
<P>
   An extra 600 Customs agents have been assigned to ports of entry
around the country. In Houston, additional agents have been
assigned to Bush Intercontinental Airport, the Port of Houston and
to mail-processing centers.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's alert focusing on the Frankfurt area, Babb said,
``we're paying particular attention to (flights from) that part of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett Johnson, assistant inspector in charge of the local
office of the U.S. Postal Inspection Service, said most mail
arriving in Houston already has been screened, so his agents are
concentrating on the small number of parcels coming by foreign
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for anything that might have missed the regular
routing process,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to warning about possible anti-American attacks by
foreign militants, U.S. officials have alerted local law
enforcement about evidence that domestic hate groups and religious
extremists are preparing for year-end violence.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI report in late October said members of militias and
racist groups, such as Aryan Nations, Christian Identity and
Odinism, have begun stockpiling weapons, food, clothing and money,
and have been surveying potential targets for attack.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a federal magistrate ordered a Canadian woman and
an Algerian national to be held without bond. The pair _ Lucia
Garofalo, 35, and Bouabide Chamchi, 20 _ were arrested Sunday at a
checkpoint as they tried to enter Vermont from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo is charged with trying to smuggle Chamchi into the
United States. Chamchi was charged with violating immigration rules
and possession of a false French passport.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents produced at a detention hearing in Burlington,
Vt., indicated that the car and cell phone used by Garofalo have
been traced to Brahim Mahdi, a member of the Algerian Islamic
League, a group of militants suspected of terrorist activities in
Europe and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   During an inspection, Vermont border officials found a false
French passport in Chamchi's coat belonging to him. He denied any
knowledge of the passport. Garofalo, according to investigators,
said she had given the passport to Chamchi.
</P>
<P>
   Two explosives-sniffing dogs also detected possible traces of
explosives during an inspection of Garofalo's vehicle. No
explosives were found and authorities said subsequent tests turned
up nothing else to indicate explosives were carried in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Mahdi, 34, denied any connection to terrorism and told The
Associated Press from his Montreal home that he had never heard of
the Algerian Islamic League.
</P>
<P>
   He said Garofalo was a friend and that he knew of no links
between her and terrorism. The car was registered in his name
because she has bad credit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities stressed there was no evidence linking Garofalo or
Chamchi to another Algerian who was apprehended Dec. 14 in Port
Angeles, Wash, about 60 miles northwest of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ressam, 32, has pleaded not guilty to charges of trying to
smuggle bomb ingredients and timing devices into the United States.
When he was arrested driving a rental car off a ferry from
Victoria, British Columbia, Ressam also allegedly was carrying two
false passports.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, The Associated Press reported that the Canadian
Security and Intelligence Service has told U.S. officials that
Ressam was trained in the early 1990s in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in France, Canada and the United States are trying
to determine whether Ressam has any ties to the international
Islamic terrorist network blamed in last year's bombings of U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. The group is headed by
anti-American Islamic militant Osama bin Laden, who is based in
Afghanistan and has issued a call for attacks against Americans
during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Canada and the United States are continuing their
search for Abdel Majid Dahoumane, an Algerian who shared a
Vancouver hotel room with Ressam for three weeks before he tried to
enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that French authorities had been
searching for Ressam and are still looking for his former roommate,
a dual Bosnian-Algerian national named Said Atmani, on suspicion of
links to a group of Islamic radicals who carried out attacks in
northern France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reporter Joe Stinebaker contributed to this story from Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
