<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PARDONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PARDONS PORT CHICAGO 50 SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton issued a pardon Thursday to
Freddie Meeks, one of the last survivors of the Port Chicago 50, a
group of black sailors whose convictions on mutiny charges during
World War II became a civil rights cause and helped spur
integration of the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   After a huge accidental explosion killed 320 men, sank two Navy
vessels and flattened the docks at Port Chicago north of San
Francisco in 1944, Meeks and 49 others refused to go back to their
jobs loading ammunition aboard ships.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 black stevedores believed that the dangers of their work
had been downplayed by the then-segregated Navy because the
enlisted members of the loading crews were all black. Meeks and
others asked for combat duty instead, but they were prosecuted for
mutiny, convicted, and jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, 80, who lives in Los Angeles and is in frail health after
suffering a stroke this fall, was informed of the pardon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had a good president and I figured he would do the
right thing, and he did the right thing,'' Meeks told the
Associated Press. ``I appreciate it very much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, he's happy,'' added his wife, Eleanor Meeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy, as recently as 1994, had refused to expunge the
convictions. William J. Perry, who was then defense secretary, told
Congress that ``sailors are required to obey the orders of their
superiors, even if those orders subject them to life-threatening
danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Loading ammunition onto ships was an essential part of the war
effort, the Navy said, and was no more dangerous than combat. Since
a Marine ordered to move forward to attack a machine-gun nest did
not have the right to question orders, the Navy argued, then
neither should an ammunition handler.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also gave presidential pardons to 36 other Americans
Thursday in a traditional Christmas-season practice, using a power
granted him by the Constitution. But Meeks was the only one of
three surviving mutineers to file an official request with the
White House, said Brian Busey, a Washington-based attorney who
represented Meeks at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   Because the servicemen were convicted and served time in prison
so long ago, the action Thursday was largely symbolic. Jack
Crittenden, another of the Port Chicago 50, declined to join Meeks
and told reporters that a pardon would be an empty gesture. A third
survivor, Busey said, is thought to be living in South Carolina and
did not petition the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The July 17, 1944, explosion of more than 3 million pounds of
ammunition obliterated Port Chicago, on the Sacramento River.
Windows were shattered in San Francisco, more than 30 miles away.
Most of the 320 men killed were black sailors who had been given no
special training in handling explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Though their white officers were given 30 days leave to recover
from the emotional toll of the disaster, the black enlisted men
were dispatched to the docks to collect the bodies and body parts
of the dead, Busey said.
</P>
<P>
   Scarred by the grisly duty and frightened by the destructive
power of the blast, more than 200 black seamen refused to go back
to work when ordered three weeks later to resume loading
ammunition. Three-fourths of them relented after the Navy
threatened to shoot them as mutineers, but 50 remained steadfast.
Instead of being charged with the lesser offense of disobeying
orders, they were court-martialed for mutiny, convicted by an
all-white panel, and sentenced to 15 years at hard labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us, `You know you could be shot.' But we made up our
mind _ you go back you might be blown to pieces _ so we didn't go
back,'' Meeks recalled. He served 18 months in prison before his
sentence was commuted in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe the prosecution and conviction was improper
and racially tinged . . . and replete with a lot of evidence this
would never have happened if they were white sailors,'' Busey said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights community agreed. Thurgood Marshall, a young
black counsel for the NAACP who would later serve on the US Supreme
Court, represented the seamen in their appeals process. Eleanor
Roosevelt interceded on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Chicago story was told last spring in an NBC-TV movie.
Led by Representative George Miller and Senator Barbara Boxer, both
Democrats from California, 35 members of Congress asked Clinton in
the fall to grant Weeks a pardon. The NAACP, at its convention last
summer, passed a resolution calling on Clinton to pardon the Port
Chicago survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
