<HEADLINE>
PACKAGES FROM GERMANY TO GET X-RAY TREATMENT, US SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to an FBI warning of a possible
terrorist threat, the US Postal Service will X-ray every package
and parcel arriving from Frankfurt to check for bombs, government
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of an abundance of caution,'' the public is urged not to
open any parcel from Frankfurt if the sender is unknown or the
package is not expected, the FBI said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the FBI nor the Postal Service would discuss how the
threat of a mail bomb was discovered, who might be behind it, or
why the German city is believed to be the origin of a possible
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI statement said the threat that ``individuals'' might
post a bomb to a US address were ``unsubstantiated.'' But
government officials _ even while urging Americans not to panic _
are on high alert following the recent arrests of several
suspicious people entering the country.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement fueled fears that a terrorist group might use
the occasion of the millennium to mount an attack against Americans
at home or abroad. Airport and border security already have been
tightened.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's capital slows down for a holiday rest,
government agencies, ranging from the FBI to the Postal Service,
the Federal Emergency Management Agency, and the Federal Aviation
Administration, are in high gear, preparing for possible computer
glitches or a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton and members of his administration appealed
for calm as well as caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to the American people would be to go about their
business and do what they would intend to do at the holiday season,
but to be a little more aware of people and places,'' Clinton said
on ``Larry King Live'' on CNN Thursday night. ``If you have a hunch
about something, if you see something that's suspicious, you should
report it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were me, I would not . . . refrain from activities,''
the president said. ``I'm going to go out and do my Christmas
shopping. I wouldn't just hunker down until it was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bethel, spokesman for the Postal Service's inspection
division, said parcels from Frankfurt would be X-rayed, but he
would not say what other protective measures would be taken because
he did not want to ``tip off'' potential terrorists. Mail from
Frankfurt comes into 10 airports around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the American people not be traumatized
over this,'' Bethel said. ``We want people to be alert to this, but
we don't want any panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``if you're not expecting anything from Frankfurt, bells
and whistles should go off,'' Bethel said, and the package should
be immediately turned over to the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has issued a ``worldwide caution'' to
Americans, urging them to be on the lookout for trouble, especially
if they are in large groups.
</P>
<P>
   The department does not have any specific information on any
particular country or city where a potential attack is suspected,
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House-sponsored ``America's Millennium'' celebration,
expected to draw many thousands of people on The Mall, will go
ahead as scheduled, with both the president and Hillary Rodham
Clinton present.
</P>
<P>
   At no time did Clinton consider changing his New Year's plans or
staying out of the public crowd to protect himself from a possible
terrorist threat, said White House spokeswoman Nanda Chitre.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of a domestic attack was heightened Dec. 14 when an
Algerian man, Ahmed Ressam, was discovered entering Washington
state with bomb-making materials. Lucia Garofalo, one of two people
arrested earlier this week at the Vermont-Canadian border, has
connections to an international group that has allegedly sponsored
terrorist activities in Algeria and Europe, prosecutors charged
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on Algeria said they did not recognize the name of the
organization, the Algerian Islamic League. The league could be a
splinter group of a terrorist organization, the analysts said. It
is also possible that the name of the group was mistranslated, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria has been the site of terrorist and counter-terrorist
violence since the early 1990s, when the secular government,
unwilling to hand over power to the Islamic Salvation Front,
canceled the national election.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a variety of Islamic groups, some of them engaged in
violence, have fought against the government. About 100,000
civilians have died in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The largest group, the Armed Islamic Group, or GIA for its
French language acronym, is considered a terrorist organization by
the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the group has attacked targets in Algeria and France.
France colonized Algeria, and Algerian Muslims perceive France to
be supportive of the secular Algerian government, said Gavin
Cameron, senior research associate at the Monterey Institute of
International Studies in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if the United States was a target,''
Cameron said, ``but the GIA, this year in particular, has become
much less predictable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
