<HEADLINE>
CELTICS ACTIVATE FORTSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Behind closed doors at the Celtics' workout facility in
Waltham, the sight of Danny Fortson chasing after a loose ball
frightened general manager Chris Wallace. The 6-foot-7-inch,
260-pound forward was 20 feet away, but Wallace sprinted from his
courtside vantage point and out of harm's way. One player Wallace
did not want to collide with was Fortson.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of that preseason practice has stuck with Wallace the
last couple months. The moment reinforced the prediction that
Fortson would be an important part of the Celtics' 1999-2000
campaign. Wallace knew the forward's tenacity and toughness, not to
mention rebounding skill, would greatly benefit Boston. But the
general manager did not know it would be at least 25 games before
Fortson made a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Celtics activated Fortson from the injured list.
To make room on the roster, Jamel Thomas was placed on waivers.
Fortson hasn't played this season after suffering a stress fracture
in his right foot Oct. 20. With Paul Pierce still nursing a
sprained left ankle and a rigorous West Coast trip ahead, Fortson's
return comes at an important time for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited because we've had a long wait,'' said
Wallace. ``When you make a deal such as the major one we did in the
offseason, you've got this guy penciled in to hopefully give you
consistent contributions. That's what you're looking for. You put
your roster up on the board and you have this guy there. But we've
not had him for 25 games. We really want to see what we've got
here. We think Danny will pay dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   The GM noted that Fortson was ``the key ingredient'' in Boston's
Augus with Denver. In exchange for Ron Mercer, Popeye Jones,
and Dwayne Schintzius, the Celtics received Fortson, Eric
Washington, Eric Williams, and a No. 1 draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive rebounding statistics Fortson accumulated during
his second year in the NBA attracted the Celtics. He averaged a
double-double (11.0 points and 11.6 rebounds per game) and ranked
fourth in the league in rebounding. He led his peers in rebounds
per 48 minutes (19.7) and offensive rebounds per game (4.2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been watching Danny play since high school,'' said
Wallace. ``He has never backed down to any challenge. He played in
what is considered a toughness/work-oriented program at the
University of Cincinnati. And in just his second season in the NBA,
he was way up on the charts in several different rebounding
categories. He doesn't have great size, in terms of his height. So
in order to be a great rebounder at that level, you have to have
some toughness. During pratice, he was a sight to behold sometimes.
Early on, he was just dominant, particularly on the offense boards
in our practice sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also lauds the rebounder's strength, knack for
positioning, and ability to get to the ball. What Fortson lacks in
height, he makes up with a wide body and rugged determination.
Wallace does not have a timetable of expectations for Fortson, and
coach Rick Pitino will keep it simple as the forward refamiliarizes
himself with plays in game situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really know the plays as well as he should,'' said
Pitino. ``When he does play we will limit him to three or four
different things and not complicate things too much.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino fully expects Fortson to be prepared to rebound. Even
though the Celtics have performed reasonably well on the glass
without Fortson, Wallace knows that against teams with strong,
physical frontcourts, Boston can use a wide-bodied rebounder. In
its recent loss to the Lakers, where it was overmatched by
Shaquille O'Neal, a strong presence on the glass was missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got some real NBA-level characteristics and you're
willing to work hard and be unselfish, you can fit into any
system,'' said Wallace. ``And Danny will certainly be able to fit
into ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Thomas only spent 10 days with the team, he will
forever be part of Celtic lore. Late in the Celtics' 98-81 win over
Atlanta Wednesday, Thomas put home a fast-break dunk to register
the final basket ever scored on the parquet floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics already have one All-Star. Ed Lacerte, who is in his
13th season on the job, was selected to be trainer for the East
All-Star team for the annual game Feb. 13 in Oakland. Golden
State's Tom Abdenour will take care of the West squad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
