<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     12-23 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TED SHOULD JUST FIRE THE BIGOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBN-ROCKER) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's the perverse part. John Rocker would feel right at home
in Shea and Yankee stadiums, beating up on opposing fans, shouting
all kinds of vile things, often with racial connotations.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker is not alone. Other bullies and bigots lurk behind
microphones on talk radio, dropping shaded messages of ``us'' and
``them.'' Just flip the dial. The ``Beirut'' that Rocker mentioned
is a white code word for a neighborhood of color.
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody really think Rocker just made it up on the spot,
while aiming his expensive automobile at breakneck speed through
Atlanta's tangled roadways (and spitting into toll boxes)? It's not
steroids or greenies, nothing that simple. It's a deep-seated
hatred of the other.
</P>
<P>
   In this holiday season it is a rather sad chore to discuss the
bigotry incarnate in one relief pitcher, but John Rocker left us no
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is a muscle-twitching, wide-eyed specimen who happens to
fling a baseball at high speed. He prattled to a Sports Illustrated
reporter this week that he hates a good deal of the populace of New
York, particularly anybody not exactly like him _ people with
purple hair, gays, unwed mothers, whatever. Most of all, he hates
foreigners, his definition most obviously including
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   New York, however, is only a convenient symbol for what really
bothers a lot of Americans about their country. When they say ``New
York,'' they really mean diverse, different, new. People who live
30 miles out of the city talk the same way, sometimes in the
ballpark. Rocker must also abhor much of the city in which (for the
moment) he earns his living. How barren would Atlanta be without
soul food at Son's, Indian food at Haveli's, Caribbean food at
Bridgetown and even the new Vietnamese pho shops? Rocker barrels
contemptuously past all of it, out beyond the 'burbs, to where he
feels in the majority again.
</P>
<P>
   His parents and his neighbors and officials from his private,
religion-based high school in Macon, Ga., are saying they are
saddened and shocked at his words. They say this is not the John
Rocker they know, but it stands to reason that Rocker did not just
pick up his bile from one ugly segment on talk radio. His prejudice
comes from deep in the heart of a national schism, people who think
the borders should have been closed the day after their own
ancestors arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has since issued an apology whose coherence and maturity
make it impossible to have been written by him. The ghostwritten
mea culpa will not work. He said it, now he has to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   The community must also deal with him because he represents the
city every time he puts the cap with the A on his thick skull.
Atlanta is a city of careful good will, exemplified by Braves fans'
allowing Yankees fans to celebrate during the first two games of
the World Series. Official Atlanta, black and white, must back far
away from John Rocker and his vicious sense of disenfranchisement,
which is no small factor in rural America.
</P>
<P>
   There is some doubt whether baseball can do much with Rocker. It
suspended Marge Schott for praising Hitler, but she was an owner
whereas Rocker is just a lug with a fastball. There is probably
some ``conduct detrimental to baseball'' clause that even his union
(which defended Roberto Alomar when he spat at an umpire) cannot
totally ignore.
</P>
<P>
   So baseball may fine Rocker a few thousand and may suspend him
for a few games, but he must still dress in a room with decent
people named Maddux and Smoltz and Jordan and Lopez. The black and
Hispanic players must know how he really feels about them. They
don't check their instincts at the clubhouse door.
</P>
<P>
   If the players took a vote, they'd probably opt for firing him
right now. Rocker throws hard, but he admits he is not exactly into
the subtlety of the game. Now he could get any of his teammates
skulled at any moment from the psychological assassins already
present in New York grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner has built his CNN empire on a quirky message of
universal brotherhood. He was reaching out to the Soviet Union and
preaching environmentalism early in the '80s. More than any other
owner in sports, Turner has the moxie to just fire this rube.
(Besides, some team will pick Rocker up. Pitching is pitching.)
Turner should do it right away, as a gesture to peace on earth, a
gesture that bigotry is bad form in every season, particularly the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Then the rest of us can examine our radios, our televisions, our
papers, our Internet sites, our companions, our souls, and ask if
John Rocker acted alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
