<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7938 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEAD-MOTHER-BOS &LR;      12-23 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DETAILS EMERGE IN CASE OF CHILD WHO TOLD TEACHER MOTHER DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. _ The School Committee said Thursday the staff at
the Kiley School acted properly after seven-year-old Lydia Hanson
came to school saying her mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff acted in a manner that was appropriate under the
circumstances,'' the committee concluded in a unanimous vote taken
Monday and released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Written testimony from a teacher and a guidance counselor,
obtained by the Salem Evening News, painted a first-hand portrait
of what happened, contradicting some details previously offered by
family members and school officials.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was investigating why the teacher and the guidance
counselor allowed Lydia to take the school bus home, where she
spent a night in the arms of her mother's dead body.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some previous reports, Lydia's teacher, 57-year-old
Janet Makar, said in her testimony that she never asked Lydia if
her mother was in fact dead.
</P>
<P>
   Makar's statement describes the events of Dec. 9 beginning at
8:35 a.m., when her first-graders lined up outside to enter the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of children came to me and said, `Mrs. Makar, Lydia
said her mother died,' '' Maker wrote in her statement. ``I
approached Lydia and said, `We don't say things like that,' ''
wrote Makar, a teacher of 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   A school department source previously said Makar had asked Lydia
why she told her classmates her mother was dead. The source said
the girl had not responded, after which Makar raised the matter
with a guidance counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia's mother Kimberly Hanson, 33, had died that day,
apparently of an enlarged heart. Hanson, a single parent, was
diabetic and, at 5 feet 10 inches, weighed about 200 pounds because
of her illness, said Lydia's grandmother, Sharon Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker blamed Makar for chastising Lydia, whom she called a
``timid and shy'' child. Had the teacher been gentler, Tucker said,
perhaps she would have discovered the truth, sparing Lydia the
trauma of a solitary night with her dead mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lydia is approached by an adult and they're talking firmly,
she'll shut down. She won't talk,'' Tucker said. ``The teacher had
her in class since September. She should know how she is.''
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Makar descr otherwise normal day. The
first-graders, she wrote, completed math assignments, a vocabulary
drill and group reading. Makar ``introduced the letter `Y.' '' The
children ate snack and lunch and played at recess.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia ``didn't cry. She didn't daydream or look spacey. She did
her work and showed no frustration,'' wrote Makar.
</P>
<P>
   When Makar consulted a guidance counselor, Jennifer Colt, about
the girl's odd remarks about her mother, Makar suggested ``maybe
they could have had an argument that morning about something like
what to wear,'' according to Colt's statement.
</P>
<P>
   After Makar described Lydia's ordinary demeanor, Colt asked,
``What do you think?'' Makar wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't know,' and I used body language and shrugged
my shoulder,'' wrote Makar.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher and the guidance counselor apparently satisfied
themselves that nothing was seriously amiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished my conversation with Mrs. Makar, deciding that
according to her observations, that she had appropriately
intervened and monitored the child,'' Colt said. ``The statements
that she made led me to believe that this child was fine. She did
not request that I speak with the child, nor did she relate to me
the need for further follow-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lydia's grandmother expressed frustration that two staff members
never questioned Lydia directly or attempted to contact her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked backwards on this,'' Tucker said. ``They took the
time to monitor her all day and they didn't take the time to pick
up the phone and call the police _ even the Peabody Police said
that's what they're there for.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Mayor Peter Torigian, who chairs the school committee,
said ``hindsight is 20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   `You're in the midst of a hectic day with 450 students in a
school, and some things can slip through the cracks,'' Torigian
said. ``I don't call it a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Adults unfamiliar with young children have no idea how tough a
job teachers have deciphering the truth behind what kids say, said
Kerry Costello, a psychologist in the Andover public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come out with some outrageous stories,'' Costello said.
``If you believed everything you heard in the course of a day with
little kids, you'd never get any teaching done.''
</P>
<P>
   Although first-graders rarely say their parents have died, they
may imagine the deaths of pets or grandparents they see
infrequently, said Costello.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can go on and on. You ask, `Is it really true your dog died
last night?' And it turns out they don't even have a dog,'' she
said. ``You're always walking a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Maryellen Cunnion, assistant professor of education
at Simmons College, such a serious statement is worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a worrisome thing for a child to say something like
that,'' Cunnion said. ``I don't want to second-guess this woman,
but I'd err on the side of caution. At least pursue it with a phone
call home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
