<HEADLINE>
TERROR SUSPECT LIVED OUTSIDE OF BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston's most solid link to world terrorism to emerge
in the jittery days before the dawn of a new millenium was known to
his neighbors as a taxi driver with regular visitors who drove with
Quebec plates.
</P>
<P>
   Raed Hajazi is one of three people still at large from a
terrorist ring tied to Osama bin Laden that allegedly plotted the
bombing of Christian holy sites in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen other alleged members of the ring were arrested last
week in Jordan, but Hajazi escaped. He has not been linked by law
enforcement officials to any of the other Middle Easterners who
have recently been apprehended in Canadian border crossings on
suspicion of terrorist links.
</P>
<P>
   Althought Hajazi hasn't lived in suburban Everett in two years,
he still has a valid Massachusetts driving license. The FBI's
counter-terrorism squad has been on alert for any sign he has
returned, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents went door to door in Hajazi's old neighorhood two
weeks ago, showing residents a photo of the suspected terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Li said he recognized Hajazi as his downstairs neighbor
in a two-family house, where the taxi driver lived with two younger
men Li thought might have been students. More than a year ago, all
three men moved out and left no forwarding address, Li said.
</P>
<P>
   Hajazi's driving license lists a birthdate that would make him
21-years-old. But Li said he thought Hajazi was as much as a decade
older than that.
</P>
<P>
   It was the bombing scheme Hajazi is linked to that prompted US
officials to issue warnings to all Americans traveling abroad over
the holidays to possible terrorist attacks. Security at airports
and other travel points has been tightened in the wake of those
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian security forces arrested 11 Jordanian nationals, an
Iraqi and an Algerian who are suspected of planning terrorist
attacks in the Hashemite kingdom. Jordanian authorities said the
ring was funded by Omar Abu Omar, known as a close associate of bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Everett neighborhood where Hajazi rented an apartment
two years ago, he hardly cast a shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Li's wife, Be Trin, said she vaguely remembers seeing Hajazi
around their Appleton Street two-family. But she remembers the note
FBI agents left on their door two weeks ago _ before the arrests in
Jordan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
