<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SURVEILLANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH BORDER SURVEILLANCE URGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent arrests of three suspected terrorists at the
Vermont-Canada border show the need for a computerized system that
would track foreigners moving through the United States, say
supporters of such a program.
</P>
<P>
   The system, opposed by much of the New England congressional
delegation, would require border officials to check documents of
all non-residents entering and leaving the United States, and
create a new computerized system to track foreigners traveling
through the country.
</P>
<P>
   Authorized by a measure passed by Congress in 1996, the system
was scheduled to be up and running this October. But intense
opposition from border state congressmen, including Vermont Senator
Patrick Leahy and New Hampshire Senator Judd Gregg, has delayed the
plans until March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure say it would tighten US borders
against drug traffickers and the growing threat of terrorism. They
argue the recent border arrests, which have heightened terrorism
fears around the country, underscore the need for better monitoring
of who is entering and leaving the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best wake-up call we're going to get,'' said Allen
Kay, a spokesman for Republican Representative Lamar Smith of
Texas, the measure's chief proponent.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, border agents in Vermont arrested an Algerian man and
a Canadian woman, both believed to have ties to terrorist groups,
as they were entering the United States. Last week, agents arrested
another Algerian man who entered Washington state with a load of
bomb-making materials in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the suspects, Kay said: ``We don't know if they
have entered the US before. How any times have they entered? When
did they leave previously? That kind of information is invaluable
to investigators and to prosecutors and is a significant deterrent.
Right now we don't have any of those tools.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the measure _ known as ``Section 110,'' its
location within a broad 1996 immigration law _ argue the measure
will cause massive disruptions in trade and tourism, including huge
traffic jams at the border. The White House and the US Chamber of
Commerce have said they oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also say the measure was designed to help ensure
foreigners do not overstay their visas in the United States and
would do little to deter terrorists or drug traffickers. The text
of the law, they note, clearly focuses on tracking immigrants with
visas and identifying those ``who remain in the United States
beyond the period authorized by the attorney general.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
