<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FOR CREW AND GIULIANI, THE DIVORCE IS FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-CREW-EDUC) 
(sw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As recently as last week, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was
grudgingly content to leave the fate of his former friend, Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew, in the hands of the seven members of the
city's Board of Education. After all, the mayor is on the verge of
declaring his candidacy for the Senate. He needs stability, not
complication.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, people close to the issue say, Giuliani
became fed up with the long-playing Rudy Crew psychodrama, and let
it be known that the chancellor's ouster would make a fine
Christmas present. The telling detail behind the mayor's decision
came when his two appointees to the board and a third ally suddenly
called for an emergency meeting to discuss the vexing matter of
whether to extend Crew's contract.
</P>
<P>
   So there was little need to hold one's breath when school board
members emerged from a closed-door meeting on Thursday afternoon.
By a 4-3 vote, Crew had essentially been fired. And the Giuliani
administration had spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that the outcome of this vote occurred because
this was precisely what the mayor wanted,'' said Steven Sanders,
chairman of the State Assembly's Education Committee and a
Manhattan Democrat. ``At this point it is ridiculous to assert that
the mayor does not control the Board of Education. He always did.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined public comment on the end of
Crew's tenure. As for Giuliani, he was coy in the hours before the
vote, acknowledging that he had been talking ``for some time'' with
board members, and sidestepping a question about the chancellor's
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the vote, he was a tad more generous. ``In
light of all of the facts I believe the board made the right
decision,'' he said, adding, ``Rudy Crew did a good job in a system
that is not accountable or properly organized, and needs to be
thoroughly reformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday night, in an impromptu discussion with
reporters in City Hall, the mayor said that he talked with the four
members who eventually voted to end Crew's contract, and that they
had already made up their minds. When told that school board
chairman William Thompson said that the mayor's fingerprints were
all over the ouster, Giuliani joked, ``I'll have to check my
fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the complex emotions that have surrounded the
Crew-Giuliani relationship, the mayor might as welsaid:
``The divorce is final.''
</P>
<P>
   After orchestrating the removal of Ramon Cortines as chancellor
in 1995, Giuliani endorsed Crew, an educator from Washington state,
as just the person to rein in a massive, out-of-control school
system. Before long, the two men had become confidants who
discussed personal matters as easily as they did matters of
education. Their friendship surprised acquaintances, given
Giuliani's brusqueness and Crew's acute sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of misunderstandings, miscommunications and basic
philosophical disagreements led to a very public unraveling of that
friendship over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Crew publicly threatened to resign if the mayor
successfully lobbied the school board to begin a pilot program for
school vouchers, in which tax money would be used to send
disadvantaged students to private schools. The mayor thought Crew
had gone from A to Z too quickly; the chancellor thought the mayor
was playing politics at his expense.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, every action prompted a reaction that smacked of
hurt and distrust. The mayor suggested that the school system
should be blown up; the chancellor responded with a letter to city
leaders and educators that criticized the mayor's ``unfortunate
remarks'' as ``destructive rhetoric.'' The mayor's allies on the
board rejected the chancellor's capital budget package; the
chancellor was photographed laughing it up with Hillary Rodham
Clinton, the mayor's expected opponent in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   For a few months the dispute disappeared amid the daily travails
of City Hall. But it resurfaced this fall when the school board had
to decide whether to renew Crew's contract by the end of the year.
And the misunderstandings continued.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the administration said that two weeks ago
the mayor had effectively signed off on a deal in which Crew would
get a one-year contract extension, which a majority of the school
board was leaning toward approving.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the mayor's estimation, Crew acquitted himself
poorly on several occasions _ from suddenly pushing for a
multi-year contract to ridiculing a critic on the City Council as
``too short'' to pass judgment on his performance. And there
remained lingering questions about the chancellor's desire to
remain in New York; he had a standing job offer in Seattle, where
his children from a former marriage live.
</P>
<P>
   Now, critics will likely argue that a mayor powerful enough to
remove a chancellor must accept some responsibility for a school
system that seems to have more success in garnering headlines for
scandal than in raising the reading and math scores of its
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's going to take a political hit,'' an adviser to
Giuliani said, ``but in the long run it's good for the school
system because Crew doesn't want to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday afternoon, the political martyrdom of Crew had
begun. City Council Speaker Peter F. Vallone and Public Advocate
Mark Green, Democrats both, decried the school board's actions.
Then came a prepared statement by Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's
spokesman, e-mailed to reporters throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Dr. Crew learned what happens when you disagree with
Rudy Giuliani,'' Wolfson said. ``Rudy Crew stood up to the mayor by
opposing his voucher scheme and paid the price. He deserved
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
