<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGALFEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DENIES PLAN TO SEEK LEGAL FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: no byline) 
(pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has denied that he would ask the
government to reimburse him for legal fees arising out of inquiries
by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel who investigated the
Whitewater land deals and the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Larry King of CNN, recorded on Wednesday
and broadcast Thursday night, Clinton said an article last week in
The Washington Post that said he was strongly leaning toward
seeking reimbursement ``is not true.'' He said he believed that the
article had been ``leaked from the independent counsel's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Independent Counsel Act, individuals who are targets
of investigations but who are not indicted may apply to the federal
court here for reimbursement of legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he believed ``I may be entitled to it, but my
instinct is not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been fortunate: ``I've had this legal defense
fund. People have helped me pay for my legal fees.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense fund is known to have raised more than $6 million.
The Clintons' legal bills are believed to total well over $10
million, though about half that amount has already been paid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TERRORISM-SUSPECTS-BO     12-23 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-SUSPECTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS CITE WOMAN'S LINK TO ALGERIAN TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Maryanne Campmann is cq;   i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ The Canadian woman arrested Sunday at a
Vermont border crossing is linked to a radical Algerian group
believed to ship arms to terrorist groups, prosecutors told a
federal judge Thursday at a detention hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The government's allegation that Lucia Garofalo, 35, of
Montreal, is connected to a key member of the Algerian Islamic
League heightened concerns that Garofalo and Algerian extremists
based in Canada might have transported explosives into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo was ordered held until Dec. 30 so investigators can
pursue other leads that might tie her to international terrorist
organizations. She and Buoabide Chamchi, an Algerian national
arrested with her, so far have been charged only with immigration
and passport violations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said that the car Garofalo was driving was
registered to Brahim Mahdi, an Algerian national living in Canada
whom prosecutors identified as a ``primary member'' of the Algerian
Islamic League. In addition, they said, Mahdi bought the cell phone
she was using.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Algerian Islamic League, Mourad Dhina, is
connected to groups that have committed terrorist acts in Europe
and Algeria, according to Assistant US Attorney Tristram J. Coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Dhina, a physicist who now lives in Switzerland, is reported to
be an international arms dealer ``actively involved in the shipment
of arms to terrorist organizations,'' Coffin told US Magistrate
Judge Jerome J. Neidermeier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly troubling is the connection between the
defendants and persons affiliated with known Algerian extremist or
terrorist organizations and sympathizers,'' US Attorney Charles R.
Tetzlaff told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the possible ramifications for national security,
this is far from an ordinary detention case.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamchi was ordered detained until a probable cause hearing Jan.
6. Niedermeier ruled that Chamchi, 20, who has been living in
Canada under temporary refugee status, poses too great a risk of
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo, who officials said listed $8 in assets but travels
extensively in Europe and the Middle East, told US Customs
officials on recent attempts to enter the United States that she
was traveling to Boston. Tetzlaff declined to say what efforts
investigators are making to track Garofalo's connections in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public can rest assured that the government is
investigating this case in a very thorough and extensive manner,''
Tetzlaff said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garofalo's court-appointed attorney, Maryanne Campmann, said
the case appeared to be ``ethnic profiling,'' based on her client's
statement that she has an Algerian husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that much of this case is based on assumptions and
innuendo,'' Campmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's arrest followed a series of attempted border
crossings.
</P>
<P>
   She successfully entered the United States, with two men that
officials described as ``Middle Eastern'' in appearance, on Dec. 6
at Pittsburg, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   At the remote crossing, controlled by only a camera and two-way
speaker at the time, Garofalo said she was heading to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to Canada through Stanstead, Quebec, on Dec. 12,
this time with a self-described Algerian national and another
person identified as her son. On Dec. 15, once again using the same
car, she retreated from the US border at Pittsburg, after guards
instructed her through a loudspeaker to report to an inspection
station. A Pakistani-born Canadian traveling with her said he did
not have identification papers.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Chamchi produced an apparently altered French
passport when he and Garofalo were stopped at the remote border
crossing in Beecher Falls, Vt. The pair said they had accidentally
entered Vermont while seeking a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   After questions were raised about the passport and the
circuitous route that the pair had taken from Montreal, two dogs
trained in explosives detection alerted officials to the right rear
panel of the 2000 model Neon that Garofalo was driving.
</P>
<P>
   FBI analysis of the substances found there did not yield any
evidence of explosives or ``explosive precursors,'' Coffin said. A
test for nitrates, often used in explosives, has not been
completed, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities previously had said that trace amounts of explosives
might have been found in the car. Tetzlaff declined Thursday to
identify the substances sent to the FBI lab in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Chamchi, who has been arrested at least twice in Canada for
stealing and breaking into motor vehicles, is said by Canadian
intelligence sources to be linked to Algerian radicals living in
Montreal who help finance terrorist acts through crime.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ressam, the Algerian arrested in Washington state last
week with bomb-making material in his car, also lived in Montreal
and had ties to the criminal group, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said their evidence indicates the case might
be much more than smuggling illegal immigrants across the border.
Neidermeier said the case ``is either a run-of-the-mill
alien-smuggling case or something more serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffin said the account on the cell phone Garofalo was using was
activated by Mahdi on July 29 and, four days later, transferred to
Garofalo. Preliminary analysis shows many international calls,
including countries in the Middle East and Canada, the attorney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's husband, Yasim Rachek, is an Algerian national
deported from Canada in 1993 for using a fake French passport.
Rachek, now living in Italy, was arrested in London in 1996 for
using a fake Greek passport with a substituted picture, Coffin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo, a Canadian native who receives welfare and has three
children, has in-laws residing in Algeria from a previous marriage,
her attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   US investigators are working with Canadian authorities to
determine if Garofalo is linked to a 1992 theft and sale of
dynamite in Ontario. A phone number connected to Garofalo was
called several times in January 1992 from a telephone used by a
person being investigated in the heist.
</P>
<P>
   US attorneys produced little background on Chamchi. Coffin said
Canadian immigration officials reported that he entered that
country in June 1997 as a stowaway, contradicting Chamchi's
assertions that he had been living in Canada for 3 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chamchi told US law enforcement officials that he worked full
time, Coffin said, but he could not remember the name of the
company. A default warrant for his arrest is outstanding in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   If a link to Dhina, the director of the Algerian Islamic League,
can be shown, the possibility of a terrorist conspiracy would be
heightened. Dhina, who has worked for the European Center of
Nuclear Research, fled his native Algeria for Europe a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dhina, also known as Sheik Ahmar, is believed to have been the
main go-between in Europe for Kamareddine Kerbane, the coordinator
of the Islamic fundamentalists' foreign networks. Dhina fled France
for Switzerland in 1995 after police raided his home.
</P>
<P>
   Dhina is believed to have provided much of the equipment
deployed in a car-bomb campaign in Algeria in 1994. He also has
made extensive use of the Internet and other modern computer
technology in his arms-purchasing efforts, according to Swiss media
reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
