A7947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADE24-CO     12-23 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal with Padres simmered until done
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A watched phone never rings. Out in San Diego, Kevin
Towers watched anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Gerald Williams was going to Tampa Bay and
(Fernando) Vina going to St. Louis, I had a feeling the phone would
ring,'' the Padres' general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Which it soon did. One call led to one of the biggest trades of
the winter. Because Braves GM John Schuerholz had explored the
possibilities of a similar deal with Towers just the week before
during the winter meetings, barely 48 hours passed between the
free-agent exodus of Williams and the six-man trade the Braves
formalized Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In giving up second baseman Bret Boone and left fielder-first
baseman Ryan Klesko, the Braves became a predominantly right-handed
hitting team with less power. In gaining second baseman Quilvio
Veras, outfielder Reggie Sanders and first baseman Wally Joyner,
the seven-time division champions emerged a more resourceful
offensive team. It could be their best defensive team. It is surely
a different team from what went before, in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our run-creation and run-production capability is
better,'' Schuerholz said. ``Our team is going to be speedier, a
little more athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive impact should be felt immediately. On-base
percentages recorded by the Braves' leadoff (.318) and No. 2
hitters (.312) both ranked 15th among 16 National League teams last
season. The switch-hitting Veras ran up a .377 on-base average in
1999 (sixth among NL leadoff hitters), while the right-handed
hitting Sanders, appearing primarily third in the Padres' order,
scored a career-high 92 runs, tied a career-high with 36 steals and
recorded his second-best year in eight full major-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have their downsides. Sanders, dealt to his third
team within 10 months, was almost run out of Cincinnati in 1998
after a steadily declining performance. Veras' durability has been
questioned through his five-year career, and he lately developed an
overly deliberate throwing habit that alarmed the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy's got a Gold Glove and, not to knock Quilvio, but he
doesn't have those merits and honors,'' Towers said. ``Bret's got
more range left and right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams' defection as the club's only viable leadoff man
forced Schuerholz's hand. And if the Braves needed a final push, it
came from incoming batting coach Merv Rettenmund, who spent his
past nine seasons in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very, very strong on the acquisition of these three
guys,'' Schuerholz said. ``He especially likes the job Sanders and
Veras did. And of course, Wally Joyner played with a broken
shoulder for most of last year.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Joyner is the most intriguing aspect of the deal.
Limited to just 110 games and 323 at-bats by a fractured left
shoulder, Joyner's production (.248-5-43) was the lowest of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Joyner turns 38 on June 16, the Braves still regard
him as one of the league's reigning clutch hitters. Over the five
seasons before 1999, Joyner hit .344 with runners in scoring
position. Even during his MVP campaign last summer, Chipper Jones
managed just .308 in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   If Andres Galarraga is not prepared for full-time service,
Joyner becomes the left-handed bat for the middle of the order. If
Galarraga can resume his place at first, Joyner becomes a critical
late-inning reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a part-time player and sharing time with Andres,''
Joyner said, ``might be the best for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
