<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-PARDONS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PARDONS FORMER SAILOR FOR ROLE IN PORT CHICAGO MUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moved in `a' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton pardoned an 80-year-old former sailor
Thursday, forgiving a World War II conviction for mutiny that had
become a reminder of the history of segregation in the armed
services.
</P>
<P>
   The former serviceman, Freddie Meeks, is one of the few
survivors of a group of 50 black sailors who were convicted of
mutiny because they refused to resume loading ammunition onto ships
at a California port after an explosion there killed 320 men on
July 17, 1944. Most of those who died were members of black work
crews, and the 50 who refused to resume the loading said blacks had
been forced to do dangerous and menial tasks by white officers who
ignored the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson is we stood up for our rights,'' Meeks said
Thursday at his Los Angeles home after learning of the pardon. ``We
stood up to get the same rights the whites had. We all should have
been treated the same, because we were all in the Navy and were
going to fight for the same purpose. But they thought we should do
the dirty work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christmastime pardon was among 37 that Clinton granted
Thursday. But none of the others proceeded from anything nearly so
sweeping as the role that the mutiny at Port Chicago, just north of
San Francisco, played in American race history.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a century ago the story of the Port Chicago
explosion and the subsequent refusal of the 50 black sailors to
follow orders became one inspiration for a civil rights movement
just beginning to stir. Big-city black newspapers in particular
closely followed the 50 as they were court-martialed, found guilty
of mutiny by an all-white panel and imprisoned. Long before he
became a Supreme Court justice, Thurgood Marshall handled an
unsuccessful appeal of the convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Chicago incident and the focus it beamed on segregation
in the Navy, some historians say, influenced President Harry S.
Truman's order formally desegregating the military in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless Meeks' application for a pardon presented a
difficult choice for Clinton, because the federal government had
been divided over the case in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   At a memorial it opened at the site of the explosion in 1994,
the National Park Service distributes literature describing the
risks faced by the black sailors. One brochure acknowledges that
for many Americans, the events at Port Chicago ``became a symbol of
what was wrong with American society.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Navy reviewed the case in 1994, it declined to
expunge the convictions. ``Sailors are required to obey the orders
of their superiors,'' said William Perry, then secretary of
defense, ``even if those orders subject them to life-threatening
danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, a seaman 2nd class, was sentenced to 15 years in prison.
But, like many of the others, he was released after serving 17
months. The men then rejoined regular Navy units and, except for
those who committed later offenses, were eventually discharged
``under honorable conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, the story of the Port Chicago incident faded
in memories. And some of the men, like Meeks, said they did nothing
to draw attention to what they felt was the shame of having been
branded mutineers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the 1980s the Port Chicago story was rediscovered.
Scholars and journalists sought out some of the aging sailors. The
National Park Service began work on a memorial to the 320 men
killed in the explosion. Of those, 202 were black. This March a
television movie told the story of the Port Chicago sailors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Congress directed the Pentagon to review the case. But
the Navy concluded ``the convictions were not tainted by racial
prejudice'' and declined to expunge the convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Port Chicago sailors were dead by the time the law
firm of Morrison &AMP; Foerster filed a petition seeking a pardon for
Meeks last June. The lawyers said Meeks was the only one of perhaps
three surviving Port Chicago sailor who wanted to ask for a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers read through old files on the case, including the
testimony of the 50 convicted mutineers.
</P>
<P>
   Working in what Meeks said was an effort to clear the historical
record, the lawyers retold the Port Chicago story in their petition
seeking the pardon. They described the black sailors' accounts of
handling tons of explosives in tight quarters with little training.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers of 1999 recounted the 55-year old testimony of the
sailors. ``I am willing to be governed by the laws of the Navy and
do anything to help my country win this war,'' Meeks had testified
in 1944. ``I will go to the front if necessary, but I am afraid to
load ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he said the pardon would be important for young
blacks who are going into the military because it showed Clinton
was interested in correcting the record of segregation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been suffering from severe health problems in
recent years, Meeks said he had believed he would live long enough
to enjoy the symbolic victory of the pardon. ``I knew God was
keeping me around for something to see,'' he said. ``But I am just
sorry so many of the others are not around to see it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meeks added that he was focusing, on a victory that, while
mostly symbolic, was sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon was issued in his name alone. But he seemed to want
to share it with 49 other men. ``It makes a big difference to know
the president gave us a pardon,'' he said. ``We've been waiting a
long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
