<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-TRAVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELERS APPARENTLY UNFAZED BY ARRESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RACHEL MULLIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The high-profile border arrests this week in Washington
state and Vermont, and cautious statements from government
officials suggesting the possibility of terrorist attacks in the
United States, have not put a damper on holiday travel plans in the
Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   While some travel agencies and hotels said customers have voiced
concerns over the threat of terrorism or Y2K glitches, most people
have not canceled their plans to travel to or from the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had no cancellations to speak of,'' said Dawn Curtis,
spokeswoman for the Seaport Hotel. ``Most of the hotel's guests
will be those working in the city over the holiday. For us, it's
not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Michaels, a travel agent at Longwood Travel in Boston,
said people have ``no real concern, but are voicing the awareness
that something might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels said travelers have not been influenced by recent media
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think the media hype is overblown . . . I don't think
people are panicking,'' she said. She added that her agency had
customers leave Thursday on international trips without expressing
any worries at all.
</P>
<P>
   John Moore, director of operations for the Marriott Long Wharf,
said that the threat of terrorism ``sure is alarming, but has not
had any affect on us. We're looking forward to a busy New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Robinson, a travel agent at Liberty Travel, said that
her customers are talking about the possibility of terrorism and
paying attention to new developments, but no one has taken steps to
cancel their travel arrangements.``I don't think people are that
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Vannasse, owner of Beacon Hill Travel and the spokesman for
the New England chapter of the American Society of Travel Agents,
said that he recently sold a holiday trip to Egypt for a family of
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I closed some deals Thursday, I was sort of amused that
people would even do it, based on what we heard in the press. But
that doesn't deter people,'' Vannasse said. ``People will not be
suppressed in their desire to learn, and that's what travel's
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
