<SLUG> BC-NCAA-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHEARING SOUGHT ON ELIGIBILITY RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers for four African-American athletes who sued the National
Collegiate Athletic Association over the minimum test score
requirement for athletic scholarships said Thursday that they would
ask the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to rehear their arguments
and promised to pursue legal remedies, if necessary, all the way to
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in a 2-1 opinion, the judges reversed a lower
court decision that struck down the eligibility requirement, ruling
that it was unfair to African-Americans. The decision did not
address the merits of the case _ that the African-American
student-athletes are unfairly affected by the initial-eligibility
rule as determined by test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the court said that college sports' governing body did
not directly receive federal funding and did not have to conform
with Title VI of the 1964 Civil Rights Act, which forbids
discrimination on the basis of race, color or national origin.
Because of that, they said, it was not necessary to address other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle is far from over,'' said Adele P. Kimmel, a staff
lawyer for the Washington-based Trial Lawyers for Public Justice.
``We will ask them to rehear it. If necessary we'll ask the entire
court to hear arguments. I'm certain that no matter what the
decision, both sides will want to take it to the Supreme Court.
This is that important.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Judge Ronald I. Buckwalter held that the NCAA's
Scholastic Assessment Tests and American College Test minimum score
requirement _ 820 on the former or 16 on the latter _ ``has an
unjustified disparate impact against African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was originally brought by two African-American
students, Tai Kwan Cureton and Leatrice Shaw. Both graduated from
Simon Gratz High School in Philadelphia in June 1996, and both
excelled in track. But despite earning academic honors, they did
not do well on the Scholastic Assessment Tests and could not get
athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The suit took aim at the standards, called Proposition 16, which
dictates initial eligibility for freshmen in the NCAA's 302
Division I schools. The standards include a core group of high
school courses and a minimum grade-point average in that core.
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter cited the NCAA's own research showing that the
practice harmed African-American students' chances of being
declared academically eligible and that the organization's goal of
improving graduation rates _ could be achieved by other methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of this ruling is that the association's
initial-eligibility bylaws remain in effect, and two more important
jurisdictional questions have been answered with regard to the
application of federal law to the NCAA,'' said Graham B. Spanier,
chairman of the NCAA Division I board of directors and the
president of Penn State University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
