<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-UPS-UPS_SFCHRON &LR;      12-23 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-UPS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Tailing's Holiday Helpers  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The ``e'' drops out of e-commerce around 1 a.m. as thousands and
thousands of packages arrive at the United Parcel Service
processing center in South San Francisco.
<P>
   Although volume at this and other UPS facilities nationwide
peaked earlier, the machinery will remain at full throttle all day
today as the country's largest delivery service gives Santa a final
assist in getting presents beneath trees in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, UPS moved more than 307 million packages globally
between Thanksgiving and Christmas, including as much as 55 percent
of all online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   This year, company officials say the total will surely be
greater, with the Internet once again accounting for a major
percentage of holiday shipments.
</P>
<P>
   UPS handles the bulk of traffic for such prominent e-tailers as
Amazon.com, Gateway, Dell Computer and Land's End.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, it seems like I'm delivering more and more
computers,'' said Bob Koga, who has been a UPS driver for 26 years.
``And I know people will use those computers to buy even more
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   VNo wonder analysts are so starry-eyed about the future of
e-commerce _ and the projections are indeed stratospheric. For just
about every PC that arrives for the holidays this year, an
exponentially greater number of online purchases will be made by
next year at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Gateway alone we're moving somewhere in the neighborhood
of 300,000 packages a week,'' said Steve Holmes, a UPS spokesman at
the company's head office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not most, of those packages, as with the vast majority
of e-commerce shipments, fall into the business-to-business
category. But that changes as the holiday season kicks into high
gear and the familiar brown UPS vans stream into residential
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The sun has yet to rise, and an early morning chill fills the
hangar-sized processing center as sorters pluck packages spilling
off the conveyor belts.
</P>
<P>
   Each package has arrived by tractor-trailer truck from Oakland
airport and other hubs. The sorters quickly determine the final
destination and place the packages into color-coded bins that
shuttle on tracks around the loading bay.
</P>
<P>
   Loaders at the backs of open vans reach into the bins _ red for
Pacifica, green for Daly City _ and place each parcel into the
appropriate vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Early deliveries are placed near the front of the van, later
deliveries near the rear.
</P>
<P>
   It's a finely tuned system, which, when working correctly,
allows drivers to make as many as 270 stops and deliver more than
300 individual packages each day during the peak season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very intense,'' said Sunny Chan, a driver who has been
with UPS for 15 years. ``This week, I'll be making about 30 stops
an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   A glance inside just one truck reveals a virtual who's who of
online retailing. Cow-patterned Gateway boxes, books from Amazon
and Barnes &AMP; Noble, goodies for critters from Pets.com _ the
parcels are stacked all the way to the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   UPS estimates that its busiest single day this year fell on
December 17 as some 18 million packages were shipped worldwide. But
drivers at the South San Francisco facility said they were making
more deliveries on Monday and Tuesday of this week.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity illustrates the slippery nature of e-commerce
statistics. The simple fact is that nobody really knows how much
stuff is being purchased online, or when, or at what price.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the ``experts'' don't try. Forrester Research, the
Cambridge, Mass., consulting firm that specializes in Internet
trends, estimates that online shopping this holiday season will
total $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Its New York rival, Jupiter Communications, places this figure
at $6 billion, while the Gartner Group's Dataquest unit projects
$8.6 billion in online gift purchases.
</P>
<P>
   At the high end of the crystal-ball gazing, consulting giant
Ernst &AMP; Young says this season's shopping spree on the Net will
rack up as much as $15 billion in sales, or nearly four times as
much as Forrester's best guess.
</P>
<P>
   Every organization crunches the numbers differently, so analysts
at each defend their predictions by stressing that Internet-related
projections are an inexact science and that their goal is to
provide a broad view of online activity as opposed to hard and cold
facts.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Glen Ramos, a sorter at the UPS facility, and he'll be
happy to explain specifically how e-commerce is changing the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Internet, we worked five or six hours a night,'' he
said while transferring packages from the conveyor belt into
constantly moving bins. ``Now it's six or seven hours. The volume
is much heavier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos has been arriving at work in recent weeks at 1 a.m. During
nonpeak times he usually starts around 4 a.m. He goes pretty much
nonstop channeling packages toward the right delivery vans, and
then, after the vans roll for the day, Ramos heads off to his
second job with an insurance firm.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, UPS says it has no problem with night workers
holding day jobs as well. In fact, the company will do just about
anything it can to keep employees happy. It can't afford to lose
them.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the crush of the holidays, UPS has to hire more than
90,000 seasonal workers, mostly high school and college students
looking to score some extra cash during winter vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people, `If you can get to work, I can make you
successful,''' said Dave Jensen, the ``preload primary
coordinator'' who oversees part-timers shifting parcels between
conveyor belts.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the most intellectually demanding work, but Jensen
noted that a lapse in concentration can send a package bound for
San Francisco on its way to San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Such mishaps can be among the myriad reasons an item ordered
online may take an inordinately long time to reach a buyer's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The popular conception of e-commerce is one of bright, shiny
information technology fostering sales that are untouched by human
hands. But the reality, more often than not, is a yawning, sleepy
teenager tossing boxes onto belts.
</P>
<P>
   To help expedite things, UPS posts its own employees at the
shipping facilities of major customers. At Amazon's warehouses, for
example, UPS loaders will ensure that parcels make it onto the
right trucks bound for the correct hub.
</P>
<P>
   The sun is up at last and the morning bright and clear in South
San Francisco as the final packages are loaded onto some
approximately  &LR; 200 vans waiting to begin their rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're almost there,'' Ed Lynch, manager of the portion of the
processing hub serving the Peninsula, told a gathering of drivers.
``Keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Hicks, the only woman driving a van (or working at the
facility, for that matter), joined her colleagues in expressing
relief that the peak season is almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really heavy, especially with the Internet shopping,''
she said. ``It's pretty crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the drivers climbed aboard their vehicles, started
their engines, and a long convoy of brown vans poured onto the
street, jingling all the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
