r f BC-COOK-COOK_SFCHRON &LR;      12-23 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOK-COOK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Not All Internet Startups' Draw Venture Cash  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
So there are dot-com firms that don't have massive amounts of money
thrown at them.
<P>
   CookExpress, a year-old San Francisco company that delivers
semi-prepared ingredients for gourmet dinners, shut down its site
yesterday during one of its peak times of the year, citing
financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to www.cookexpress.com who type in their ZIP codes to
receive a menu see this message:
</P>
<P>
   ``CookExpress.com has suspended service until further notice. We
hope to reopen for business the beginning of the year, after we
have completed a key round of funding. We would like to thank you
for your ongoing support and apologize for any inconvenience this
may have caused you.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they simply ran out of money.
</P>
<P>
   The firm didn't fail to meet sales goals, said founder Darby
Williams. But it has had trouble luring investors who believed in
the potential for selling gourmet-quality food over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CookExpress, whose ``kits'' arrived as fresh ingredients,
measured, prepackaged and ready to cook, isn't cheap. Entrees range
from $14.95 to $21.95 and delivery is $4.95 per order for orders
under $60.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had a problem executing on our strategy, it's just
a matter of the capital to take us to the next step,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has raised roughly $3.5million through two rounds of
funding in the past 18 months and is now looking for another round
worth about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shutdown, Williams said CookExpress' customers
haven't turned against the company and ``will be there waiting for
us to relaunch.''
</P>
<P>
   But others aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't help in building the brand,'' said Allen Bonde,
director of the market research arm of Extraprise, a Boston
e-commerce consulting firm. ``I don't know how much money they're
spending driving people to the site, but they're basically pouring
that revenue down the drain. Plus the negative impression of
consumers trying (to use the site) and saying `I'll never go there
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Each week, the dot-com world seems to defy common sense,
offering up another record-setting IPO or stock price. But failures
aren't uncommon, said Tamar Zemel, corporate communications
director at VentureOne, a venture capital research firm in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that weird,'' she said, noting that VentureOne
doesn't track firms that don't meet funding goals or go out of
business. ``How many investments go bad? There are plenty of
companies that don't make it. It's possible (CookExpress) will get
their round, and it's possible that they will not.''
</P>
<P>
   CookExpress, along with online grocery sellers Webvan.com and
Peapod.com, has been the subject of scores of articles regarding
the expected growth of Internet food shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded by Williams, an ex-Microsoft executive,
launched its site in January 1999 and counts among its board
members Bay Area culinary guru Bradley Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   Although Internet food and beverage sales were a modest $235
million last year, Forrester Research predicts they will double
annually, hitting $5 billion in 2002 and $10.8 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
