<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER-CHILD24-CO     12-23 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-CHILD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The two faces of John Rocker
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARNER ROBINS, Ga. _ It was a wonderful Christmas story. An
8-year-old boy, who has spent most of his life indoors because of a
condition that robbed him of an immune system, is asked if he has a
special wish.
</P>
<P>
   He wishes he could play baseball. So some nice people who live
in Middle Georgia arrange for Ben Fuller to play ball with a couple
of home-grown major-leaguers. John Rocker of nearby Macon and the
Atlanta Braves would pitch. Mark Johnson, who still lives in town
and catches for the Chicago White Sox, would be behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The wish came true last weekend at the local high school
baseball diamond.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Ben Fuller's mom wonders. Did the real John Rocker show
up? Or was the whole thing a fairy tale that ought to be remembered
with, ``Once upon a time ...''
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker, who exposes himself with disparaging comments in
this week's Sports Illustrated, even seems in the article to be
unkind to children. While driving to a school for the
learning-disabled, Rocker was asked if he enjoys speaking to
children. ``No,'' he said, ``not really.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment hurt Ben's mother, Jean Langston, more than
Rocker's slurs against nearly every ethnic group on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' Langston said. ``I can't see a person
who would give up part of his Saturday to pitch to a little boy he
didn't know being so mean-spirited. But I will never let Ben or my
other children know what he said. I'm not sure that Ben would even
want to bat against him, if he knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she will try not to let Rocker's controversial opinions
ruin the memory of last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the big day, Rocker had sent Ben a Braves shirt.
He autographed a sleeve. Rocker, his parents and his girlfriend
arrived at Langston's home to drive in a police-escorted caravan
down Russell Parkway. Only about 50 friends and relatives watched
Ben's wish come true, but Jake Rocker was happy that they could see
this soft side of his son. The senior Rocker said he regretted that
John would have to leave after a few pitches to attend a relative's
funeral in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   ``John doesn't like to disappoint anyone,'' Jake said. ``He'd
like for there to be four of him and 48 hours of every day.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it began, Rocker lobbing left-handed pitches to Ben,
who'd never hit a baseball in his life. Ben had swung at a tennis
ball in his yard the few times he had ventured out, wearing a mask
that keeps him from germs.
</P>
<P>
   After fouling off a number of Rocker's first 15 pitches, it
happened. Ben hit a sharp liner past first base. The crowd of 50
screamed like 50,000. ``Go, Ben,'' Langston yelled.
</P>
<P>
   He stole second _ never mind that there weren't any fielders _
while his brother, Hiram, was batting. He raced all the way home
from second. A youngster handed Langston the ball. ``Ben's first
hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next time up, he got another hit and Rocker chased him down the
first base line, laughing. And then another hit, and another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Ben said. ``Really fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling for me,'' Rocker said. ``It's important to
do stuff like this for kids. I'm sure Ben never expected me and
Mark to come out and give him a treat like this. Who knows, maybe
it will make a difference in his illness and it'll turn him around
and he'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Langston is a 34-year-old single mother going through a second
divorce. She had to give up a good job as a dental assistant to
care for her four boys. Three of them have serious conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ben, who will be 9 in January, is a ``bubble boy,'' born without
an immune system. It is risky for him to leave an antiseptic
environment; a common cold could be fatal. This week, Langston had
to send Ben to his nurse's home in Atlanta while she battled
bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   Hiram, 13, has a heart condition. Lance, 11, recently had a
three-pound tumor removed from his brain and experiences violent
siezures. Preston, 7, is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has had a lot of hardship, but I'm a very happy
person, believe in God a lot, and I lean completely on the Bible,''
Langston said. A turning point for Ben came last fall, when doctors
at Duke University told his mother that a bone marrow transplant
would be too risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to choose,'' Jean said. ``Was I going to keep him in
the house until he's 18 (a fatal turning point for those with his
condition) or did I want to try and let him get out a little bit.
If you think of David, the bubble baby in the '70s, his mom kept
him in that bubble until he was 18. He left the bubble and died
within days. So what is my purpose in not giving Ben a little life?
This is life. Me, my family, my friends and the doctors decided
together, `Let him go.' If it's one year or one month, give him
that glory.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd already tried to treat Ben like something of a normal kid.
He collects baseball cards, plastic horses and plastic and glass
angels. He has more angels than he can count. Country singer Shania
Twain heard about Ben from her doctor. She's been calling him the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball outing was arranged by Steve Rogers, a local Air
National Guard cop who has developed one fund-raiser after another
for Middle Georgians in need.
</P>
<P>
   When Rogers asked Ben if he could have a wish come true, what
would it be, he replied, ``Well, I already know Shania Twain. I
guess if I could have any wish in the world I'd like to play
baseball.'' He's only been allowed outside to play without a mask
the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Ben, you're going to get to play ball with one of
the Braves and someone from the White Sox,''' his mother said. ``He
goes, `Why?' Then he asked me, `Am I gonna play 'cause I'm gonna
die?' I said, `No, Ben, no. You're going to play because you want
to play.' He doesn't talk of it much and he's not afraid of it, but
he knows the illness.'' Which makes what has become of John
Rocker's image all the more perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   It has put Rogers, a friend of the pitcher for only the past
several months, on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John's boat is the Titantic, I won't jump,'' Rogers said.
``I won't leave him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Rogers called Jim Schultz, the Braves'
public-relations man, and offered to do anything on Rocker's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to stand in front of a thousand microphones and
defend John Rocker, I'd do it,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a 25-year-old kid who was shooting from the hip,''
Rogers said. ``Yesterday, when the story broke, he was in a charity
benefit for Nicaraguan relief. Is that a racist? When he played for
the Macon Braves, he had Andruw Jones living at his house for 18
months. Is that a racist?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other people have done more serious things and gotten
past them,'' he said. ``John's a good person. His heart is good.
``This is the season for forgiveness and love and coming
together,'' Rogers said, ``not for crucifixion.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
