<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-TRENDS-ART     12-23 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-TRENDS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPING IS UP, BUT PROFITS ARE LAGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online holiday shopping is increasingly gnawing at the business
of traditional retailers this year, with preliminary indications
that seasonal Internet sales may nearly triple from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Visa, which represents about half the nation's credit card
spending, estimates that Internet shoppers using its cards will
have spent $1.47 billion this November and December, 179 percent
more than in those months last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the overall retail market, that figure is still small _ 1.79
percent of Visa's total retail sales, up from 0.76 percent last
November and December. And with the economy buoyant and retail
sales expected to rise by 6 percent overall this holiday season,
the big store chains have yet to see the Internet take a
substantial bite out of their sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall trends may mask a more troublesome phenomenon
for those retailers, experts say, as stores find that their best
customers are the quickest to move online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retailers are feeling the pain because the fattest part of
their market is moving online,'' said Mel Bergstein, chief
executive of Diamond Technology Partners, a Chicago consulting
firm. ``The guys online don't buy the $10 gifts. They're the big
spenders.''
</P>
<P>
   And this year there are more of them. A New York Times/CBS News
poll of 1,026 adults Dec. 17-19 found that 17 percent had bought
gifts over the Internet this holiday season or planned to do so,
compared with 7 percent who said they had done so last year.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in Internet holiday spending reflected in the Visa
data is at the high end of industry forecasts. Various analysts had
predicted online holiday sales would be up from 61 percent to 219
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   American Express said its online retail sales had increased
roughly 200 percent from last year's holiday season, although it
would not provide precise numbers. (MasterCard said it did not
track online sales.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sales were bound to increase given the blitz of
television advertising by Internet stores over the last month, many
offering deep discounts and free shipping. And some wonder whether
the rapid growth might taper off, were Wall Street to demand that
Internet companies ever turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to give away stuff for free,'' said Toby Lenk, the
chief executive of eToys, one of the fastest growing Internet
stores. ``A lot of dot-com start-ups and wanabees are spending more
in advertising than they are taking in sales, and they are
discounting heavily. You've got to question the viability of that
business model.''
</P>
<P>
   To others, though, the rapid growth in Internet shopping this
holiday season reinforces the predictions that the share of online
shopping will continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen so far is the tip of the iceberg,'' said
Gerry Sweeney, a vice president of Visa's electronic commerce unit.
``By 2003, we believe that 10 percent of our volume will come from
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   With that potential threat, this year many of the best-known
names from the country's malls and mailboxes have opened up major
stores on the Internet as well.
</P>
<P>
   And early measures show that some of the traditional players
have attracted quite a lot of traffic, with their well-known brands
and the convenient potential of returning unwanted items to their
stores. Surveys show that Toys ``R'' Us, KBKids, the Gap, Costco,
Wal-Mart Stores, and Lands' End along with Barnes &AMP; Noble, already
a Web veteran, appear to have significant growth in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some evidence that while many traditional retailers
are attracting visitors to their Web sites, the Internet-only
stores are doing a better job of making sales.
</P>
<P>
   Next Card, a credit card company, notes that based on its tally
of sales, a greater percentage of the people who visit eToys, an
Internet-only toy store, make purchases than visitors to
Toysrus.com. And the average purchase is $65 for eToys and $45 for
Toysrus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Toysrus has attracted far more sales than it can
handle. On Wednesday it said it would give $100 gift certificates
to a group of customers who might not receive their toys by
Christmas. It declined to say how many customers were affected.
Toysrus was hardly alone. eToys and KBKids were among the toy
stores that left some parents giftless.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the problems faced by the online toy companies spoiled
what many people said was otherwise a very satisfying experience
shopping on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times/CBS News poll found that of those who shopped
for gifts online, 62 percent said the experience was better than
shopping in a store; 25 percent said it was the same, and 8 percent
said it was worse than a store. The online shoppers cited the
convenience, lack of crowds and the speed of shopping as the main
benefits over traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys are the perfect category for online shopping,'' said
Katherine Borsecnik, a senior vice president at America Online, on
which toys and other children's merchandise has been the top
selling category this holiday season. ``No one likes to go to a toy
store between Dec. 15 and Christmas, and a Pokemon from an Internet
site is no different than a Pokemon from a Toys `R' Us store.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the online sales are not just at the expense of
retail stores. While traditional mail-order catalog sales are still
greater than Internet sales, the catalog business is growing
slowly, and some merchants are reporting tough going. Lands' End,
for example, said its sales fell by 18 percent in the first five
weeks of the fourth quarter, a much bigger drop than expected.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the rise in online buying is proving a boon to
the delivery business. The Postal Service says that Priority Mail
shipments are up 8 percent this holiday season, largely because of
Internet businesses. It has had to charter an addition 100
airplanes mainly to serve customers with major online operations,
like Amazon.com, eToys, QVC, Lands' End, and a few others, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express says its volume is up about 20 percent this
holiday season, in part because of electronic commerce. United
Parcel Service says that Internet companies are driving a volume
increase and that many of its biggest customers are now online
stores, but it declined to give specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Studies of Web surfing behavior show that visitors to shopping
sites peaked the week ended Dec. 13. Media Metrix, a New York
research firm, estimates that the online shopping audience declined
by 6 percent in the week ending Dec. 20 from the previous week. But
traffic increased at some sites offering gifts that do not require
packages to be shipped, like Enews.com, which sells magazine
subscriptions, and Americangreetings.com, which offers e-mail
greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Putting an overall dollar figure on holiday e-commerce is far
from a science. Since Visa represents about 54 percent of card
spending in the country, its data suggest that about $3 billion is
being spent on online retail purchases in the last two months of
the year. But Visa cautions that the numbers may slightly
underestimate sales levels because some merchants with both
traditional and online business may not be identifying Internet
sales separately. And while nearly all purchases from online stores
are made by credit card, many buyers on person-to-person auction
sites like Ebay, are made by check.
</P>
<P>
   Market research firms have been predicting online sales for the
holiday season as high as $6 billion to $9.5 billion, but their
methodologies and definitions may vary significantly from those of
Visa. Many rely on surveys of consumers and merchants rather than
actual transaction records. The National Retail Federation
estimates that total retail sales over the holiday season will be
$185 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
