<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7965 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER24-COX     12-23 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The other guy: Rocker's
 &HT;    volatility surfaced down stretch
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago this month, John Rocker was banished to
Puerto Rico, wondering if the baseball thing would ever work out.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year minor leaguer who had only made it to Class AA a few
months before, Rocker had been shipped off to the Puerto Rican
winter league to test his stuff as a potential closer. Ignored on
all the prospect lists, he was just another hot-rod arm with a
vague affiliation with the strike zone; the Braves had sent him to
the bullpen because they had run out of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   And then one afternoon with a game on the line, Rocker was
called in to face Juan Gonzalez, hero to all the island and pure
murder on left-handed pitching. For reasons he has never been able
to clarify, Rocker determined he would sprint to the mound, where
he promptly struck out Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said to myself, `This can work,''' Rocker said. It became
a trademark, soon joined by a Goldberg T-shirt and a mound act so
packed with flinches and winces, he flits around like Rodney
Dangerfield on speed.
</P>
<P>
   And he also became nearly unhittable. Steeled by the Puerto
Rican winter, Rocker just needed one break, which came in the form
of Mark Wohlers' back strain two months into the 1998 season. What
has happened since, accelerated by Kerry Ligtenberg's elbow injury
last spring, is one of the joys of the Braves' player development
department.
</P>
<P>
   Forty saves in 49 career opportunities, 146 strikeouts in 110
1/3 innings, 13 career playoff innings without an earned run. And
for now, the Braves want to be as far from him as they can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``He happens to be an employee of ours. He works for us,''
general manager John Schuerholz said. ``He wears the name of our
company on his uniform. But in no way do the comments and the
attitudes and the feelings that he expressed represent those of the
Atlanta Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's one-man siege upon political correctness, as reported
in this week's Sports Illustrated, has laid open an unseen aspect
of his character, a fairly unknown commodity until the later
stretches of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he has ``no place in my heart'' for Rocker's comments,
Hank Aaron, the most storied player to wear a Braves uniform said,
``I'm sick and disgusted about the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Was Rocker somehow transmuted this season into
the crowd-baiting loon who sparred with all Shea Stadium last fall?
No. Rocker was always loose. He hit the Braves clubhouse trailing
stories of the times he had bitten into baseballs that would not
behave in the bullpen, of challenging catchers to throw balls into
his chest when his control wavered in side sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But there were a pair of incidents last season that hinted at
Rocker's deep irascibility. On June 29 in Montreal, he produced the
worst performance of his major-league career, allowing five runs in
two-thirds of the ninth inning in a 6-5 loss. Vladimir Guerrero
ended it with a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers might drop the memory _ an almost mandatory
ability for relievers _ but Rocker was still so livid 45 minutes
after the fact, he wound up in a bitter tirade against the Expos,
one of the game's worst teams last season. His comments had most
Braves shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how a team that's 28 games under .500 can sit on
every pitch like they knew what's coming,'' Rocker fumed that
night. ``If they're that good, why aren't they at least a .500
team? It amazes me.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly made Rocker the first pitcher who has had trouble
absorbing defeat, but a September incident stunned the club. Rocker
had saved a Sept. 5 game against Arizona, striking out Kelly
Stinnett for the 27th out and what should have been a 5-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   But catcher Eddie Perez dropped the third strike, first baseman
Randall Simon forgot to cover first, Perez threw the ball away and
the Diamondbacks wound up scoring three runs and winning 7-5. Simon
confessed to his error, but Rocker singled him out to the media
afterward, bad form in any clubhouse, especially with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Within three weeks, Rocker had begun taunting Mets fans at Shea
Stadium and what followed is highlight-reel history. It hardly
presaged what happened this week, but in retrospect, it describes a
man who, rather than avoid confrontations, rushes straight to them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
