<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online Holiday Shopping Cuts Into Traditional Sales
</P>
<P>
   Online holiday shopping is increasingly cutting into the
business of traditional retailers this year, with preliminary
indications that seasonal Internet sales may nearly triple from
last year. Visa estimates that Internet shoppers using its cards
will have spent $1.47 billion this November and December, 179
percent more than in those months last year. In the overall retail
market, that figure is still small _ 1.74 percent of Visa's retail
sales _ but it signals troublesome phenomenon for traditional
retailers, experts say. Stores are finding that their best
customers are the quickest to move online.
</P>
<P>
   GM President Upbeat About 1999
</P>
<P>
   The president of General Motors, G. Richard Wagoner, gave an
upbeat assessment of 1999, praising the company's strong profits,
peaceful labor relations, Internet business initiatives, increased
unit sales and new models. But Wall Street analysts have had
growing concerns about GM's slide in market share.
</P>
<P>
   Fed Was Unanimous on Lifting Rates
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's policy-making committee was unanimous in
its decision to raise interest rates at its meeting on Nov. 16 and
expressed a desire to act well before any Year 2000 computer
problems, according to minutes of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Investor in Czech TV Battle
</P>
<P>
   A legal battle over Eastern Europe's most successful television
station has turned Ronald Lauder, an heir to the American cosmetics
giant Estee Lauder, against the government of the Czech Republic
and threatens to taint the nation's broader business reputation.
Lauder has begun an arbitration case, contending that the Czech
authorities have failed to protect his investment in TV Nova,
violating a treaty on mutual investment protection.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Steps Up Plans in Japan
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, the parent of
the Nasdaq stock market, is speeding up its plans for an electronic
stock market in Japan that will promote cross-trading of United
States and Japanese stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Spending Rose 0.5 Percent in November
</P>
<P>
   Consumers accelerated their spending 0.5 percent in November,
pushing the economy closer to a record expansion. Another report
showed that factory orders for big-ticket durable goods increased
1.2 percent after two months of declines.
</P>
<P>
   Europe Wins Ruling in Steel Case
</P>
<P>
   A World Trade Organization dispute panel sided with the European
Union in a challenge to American duties imposed to counter state
subsidies for British-produced steel, a day after a separate panel
ruled in favor of the United States in a dispute over banana
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol to Leave `This Week' on ABC
</P>
<P>
   In the first move of a promised makeover of ``This Week,'' the
troubled ABC Sunday morning political discussion show, the network
has parted company with the conservative commentator William
Kristol, a member of the program's weekly roster of pundits.
Kristol, whose current contract ends on Jan. 1, said he declined
ABC's offer of a short-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   When the Classroom Is a Mall
</P>
<P>
   If retail is war, then the students of Providence Place Academy
in Rhode Island are the first cadets to have their boot camp on the
field of battle. The academy, an alternative public high school
oriented toward business training, may be the nation's first
vocational high school to be based in a working mall.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Closed for Christmas
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets, government offices and banks are closed
Friday in observance of Christmas. They will reopen on Monday. Many
foreign exchanges will close early Friday and remain closed on
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
