<HEADLINE>
TRADE PANEL RULES AGAINST U.S. PENALTY ON SUBSIDIZED STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A World Trade Organization dispute panel sided with the
European Union on Thursday in a challenge to American duties
imposed to counter state subsidies for British-produced steel. If
upheld, the ruling could prevent the United States from levying
penalties on products made by state-owned companies that are later
privatized.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, though, in a broader case, a separate WTO panel
ruled in favor of the United States, finding that although part of
a 1974 U.S. trade law permitting the use of sanctions was contrary
to current international rules, the law had so far been carried out
in a way that conformed with WTO requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling, which declared American steel duties contrary
to global trade rules, comes at a time that the country's steel
industry is struggling to limit imports.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the U.S. trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, quickly said that it would appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly disagree with the panel's reasoning,'' said Thomas
Tripp, its spokesman. ``A mere change in ownership doesn't render a
company's production unsubsidized.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue are American import duties imposed from 1994 to 1996 on
leaded bars produced by British Steel Corp. _ since merged into
Corus Group _ which received an estimated $14 billion in government
assistance. The 15-member European Union, backed by Brazil and
Mexico, argued that the United States had erred by imposing
countervailing duties on British-produced steel because of the
benefits gained from subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States maintained that a company receiving such
government aid gained an unfair advantage for its products that
continued into any new ownership situation.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, in a 47-page ruling, said Washington failed to show
that the subsidies ``had been bestowed directly or indirectly on
the production of those imports'' where the duties had been levied.
It suggested that American officials ``take all appropriate
steps,'' including changes in administrative practices, to prevent
such violations from reoccuring.
</P>
<P>
   The American Iron and Steel Institute, whose officials were not
available for comment, filed friend-of-the-court papers arguing
that huge subsidies for British Steel permitted it to ``buy
equipment and facilities that the market could not justify, train
workers who could not have been trained without subsidies, lower
debt, or otherwise artificially benefit its production.''
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of cash between 1977 and 1986 ``literally kept
steel-making afloat'' in Britain, with serious consequences for
other countries' manufacturers, the institute declared.
</P>
<P>
   Any appeal of Thursday's decision must be made within 60 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
