<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-WORKERS-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE INDUSTRY ADOPTS WORK RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CRUISE-WORKERS) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cruise ship industry Thursday released voluntary guidelines
setting forth the rights of crew members to fair treatment,
including pledges to provide clean quarters, competitive pay and
the right of seafarers to voice complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines were adopted by the International Council of
Cruise Lines, the trade group in Washington that represents the 17
foreign-owned major cruise lines operating in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia A. Colenda, the council president, said in a statement
that most of the guidelines reflected practices already in place
and that they extended beyond the requirements set by agencies that
regulate the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines were approved after questions were raised by The
New York Times about workplace conditions on cruise ships. Bridget
Ann Serchak, the group's spokeswoman, said the issue had been under
consideration since summer. Earlier this year, the council adopted
guidelines requiring that shipboard crime be reported to proper
authorities and that cruise lines improve compliance with
environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   The code for crew members calls on cruise lines to comply with
international regulations on labor practices, pay wages equal to or
exceeding those in the nations from which crew members are
recruited and provide them with free medical care and room and
board in clean, well-maintained quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The code also says that the workplace will be safe, that
employees should be at least 18 years old, and that crew members
cannot be subjected to physical, sexual or verbal harassment. In
addition, it says, seafarers have the right to voice complaints
without fear of retaliation. The new code is be made available to
all crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise council also released a set of guidelines governing
gambling aboard ships that it said were designed to ensure fair and
professional gaming for customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
