<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-INDUSTRY-ART-     12-23 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-INDUSTRY-ART-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED CHANGE IN TAX LAW SENDS GERMANY'S STOCK MARKET SOARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a move that sent Germany's stock market
soaring, the government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder endorsed
plans Thursday to untangle the web of cross-ownership in German
companies that have defined their structure since the end of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which came as a big and pleasant surprise to
business executives and investors, would allow banks and insurers
to sell their huge industrial shareholdings without paying a tax on
the profits, unleashing tens of billions of dollars into the German
economy.
</P>
<P>
   That tax, currently at 50 percent, is among the highest in the
world, and it has effectively prevented such share sales in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Executives cautioned that the proposed change has a long way to
go before becoming law, partly because it is unclear if the
chancellor's Social Democratic Party, senior partner in the
governing coalition, will fully support it or give in to pressure
from its left wing.
</P>
<P>
   But if the proposal does become law, it would strike at the very
heart of the corporate structure in Germany, Europe's largest
economy _ a structure, that has been built around cross-ownership
between banks, insurers and industrial conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   This is an important reason why, for example, Deutsche Bank, the
country's biggest, has been a major shareholder in DaimlerChrysler,
the biggest automaker, and why Allianz AG, Germany's leading
insurer, is a longtime shareholder in 17 of the 30 big companies in
the benchmark DAX stock index.
</P>
<P>
   The present system contributed mightily to Germany's postwar
economic boom, but it has also bred what critics see as cronyism,
rigidity and arrogance toward smaller stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and insurers have long wanted to prune such industrial
stockholdings and reinvest the proceeds in their core businesses.
But they faced billions of marks in capital-gains taxes if they did
so.
</P>
<P>
   German political leaders have chafed at the power of financial
institutions, but did not want to be accused of handing out big
corporate tax breaks. Yet Thursday, government officials said that
was what they planned to do. ``This change will give an important
boost to the modernization and restructuring of industry,'' the
Finance Ministry said in a brief statement.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks here soared on the news, particularly those of banks and
insurers. The DAX index rose 4.46 percent, the biggest one-day gain
in more than nine months. Shares of Munich Re AG, one of the
world's biggest insurers, soared almost 17 percent, to 255 euros.
Deutsche Bank stock jumped 15 percent to 81.4 euros. Allianz, the
biggest direct insurer, rose 12 percent, to 336.51 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Callow, chief European economist at Credit Suisse First
Boston, said the proposed changes went ``to the heart of the way in
which the German economy is financed and structured and owned''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are really seeing,'' he added, ``is a key turning
point, away from the post-1945 methods of financing the German
economy to a more Anglo-Saxon approach based on widespread
shareholder ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest banks and insurers hold more than $150
billion of ``hidden reserves,'' shares in companies that were
acquired over many decades.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's portfolio is worth about $22 billion. It
includes 12 percent of DaimlerChrysler and about 7 percent of
Allianz.
</P>
<P>
   Allianz has a $30 billion portfolio, which includes major stakes
in two other big German financial institutions, Dresdner Bank and
Bayerische Hypo-Vereinsbank.
</P>
<P>
   German banks and insurers have wanted to prune these holdings
for years, so they could move their money into faster-growing
companies, but have been deterred by the prospect of taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives and industry analysts remained skeptical about
the government's plans. Schroeder has come under attack from the
left wing of his party on other matters, and has shifted between a
pro-business pragmatism and the Social Democrats' more traditional
left-wing positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would still be skeptical,'' one executive said. ``But if it
is true, it is a very positive thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives were equally surprised by the government's way of
disclosing the plan. It was buried in a much broader tax reform
plan introduced on Tuesday, not even mentioned until banks and
insurers started asking questions Thursday. The government offered
no explanation for why it did not announce the proposed change more
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the proposal, if adopted, would unleash tens
of billions of dollars worth of stock for re-investment. They also
said it would probably accelerate an already-blistering pace of
mergers and acquisitions in Europe, where economic integration and
the single currency have been reducing barriers to corporate
takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should this proposal be put into effect, it would be positive
for the economy,'' said Diethard Breipohl, chief financial officer
of Allianz. ``A restructuring of the German corporate landscape
would be possible, leading to more growth and employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Allianz is already gearing up for an overhaul of its holdings.
This fall, it hired the head of Goldman Sachs' Frankfurt office,
Paul Achleitner, as its new chief financial officer. Achleitner,
who was been in the middle of Germany's biggest mergers, has been
given the responsibility of streamlining Allianz's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, which has been a pillar of the old system, is
also poised for restructuring. More than a year ago, it put all its
stockholdings into a separate new subsidiary, DB Investor, with a
goal of managing the portfolio much more actively.
</P>
<P>
   But such efforts have been constrained by the tax liability, and
the matter appeared to be in political deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Detlev Rahmsdorf, a spokesman for Deutsche Bank, said the new
proposal, if it became law, would be a breakthrough. ``From an
economic standpoint,'' he said, ``it means that capital allocation
would be much more improved and much more dynamic. The links
between banks and big corporations will become looser, that's for
sure. Everything will be judged and every deal will be decided on
its own economic merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's own experience provides vivid examples of the
old system's weaknesses. Like other big German banks, it has been
the lead lender to many of the biggest companies. When things went
sour, it stepped in with financial help, often exchanging its old
debt for new equity.
</P>
<P>
   But Deutsche Bank lost heavily in the early 1990s, when it was
forced to help bail out Metallgesellschaft AG, a conglomerate that
ran up billions in losses in commodity trading.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank also led a rescue attempt for Philipp Holzmann AG,
a huge but troubled construction company, in which it owns a 15
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann received a bailout in 1997, and one of Deutsche Bank's
board members became chairman of Holzmann's supervisory board. But
Holzmann again got into deep trouble, and Deutsche Bank was stuck
with several billion marks in loans as well as potentially
worthless stock.
</P>
<P>
   After Schroeder volunteered government guarantees and loans,
Deutsche Bank was able to corral other lenders into a new bailout
for Holzmann totaling $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Reich, head of equity research at Metzler Bank in
Frankfurt, said the tax proposal could increase earnings at the
biggest banks and insurers by 10 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really would be a revolution,'' he said. ``Germany as a
closed shop wouldn't exist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich said the Finance Ministry appeared to be serious. He
cautioned that the proposal had not yet been put in full legal
language, let alone passed by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But he said government officials had provided detailed technical
reasoning on how the proposal could be melded with existing law.
``They all said that this is what they want to do,'' Reich said,
``and that there is nothing that should dilute the plan from their
point of view.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
