<SLUG> BC-ABC-KRISTOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE PANEL MEMBER LEAVING `THIS WEEK' PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first move of a promised makeover of ``This Week,'' the
troubled ABC Sunday morning political discussion show, the network
has parted company with the conservative commentator William
Kristol, a member of the program's weekly roster of pundits.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Murphy, the vice president for communications at ABC
News, said the network had decided not to offer Kristol a new
long-term contract. His current contract ends on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep Bill, but only on a short-term deal,'' Ms.
Murphy said. ``That was not what he wanted. We did not want to
stand in his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said he declined the ABC offer. ``I had three good years
on the show,'' he said. ``I feel like I worked hard and made a good
contribution. I like the people very much. I have no complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings for ``This Week,'' which for years was the dominant
Sunday morning network talk show, have been in a deep slide over
the last year. ``This Week'' is now well behind the network leader,
``Meet the Press'' on NBC, and more recently has begun to fall
behind ``Face the Nation'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could hardly be worse as the shows enter an election
year, when there is additional focus on them as they try to book
the prospective presidential candidates as guests. ``Meet The
Press'' and its anchor, Tim Russert, have scored several booking
coups in recent weeks, including the first extended interview with
George W. Bush and last week's news-making debate between Al Gore
and Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a decision to fix the show,'' Ms. Murphy said.
``It was a step along the way. In no way did anybody think he was
the problem with the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said he was gratified Thursday by the number of calls he
had received from other networks and cable outlets. ``I heard from
every other network and all the cable news channels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said he had not committed himself to any other program,
though he works for The Weekly Standard magazine, which is owned by
Rupert Murdoch. Murdoch's News Corp. also owns the Fox network,
which has its own program, ``News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kristol said he did expect to land somewhere else soon,
adding a self-deprecating prediction, ``I don't think the American
public will be suffering from being deprived of my views.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
