<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS ACTIONS NEED THE RIGHT ELEMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Class-action lawsuits are one of the ways employees
can recover damages if their civil rights have been violated. There
are lawyers who will take the cases and front the expenses, which
can be thousands of dollars, to win big discrimination verdicts
involving hundreds of employees.
</P>
<P>
   However, that ability to certify a class of people _ a group
that has faced systematic discrimination that is typical in a race,
sex or national-origin lawsuit _ is getting more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans ruled
in a case involving Venezuela's state-owned Citgo Petroleum Corp.
that mental anguish and other compensatory damages can't be grouped
together in a class action.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that mental anguish is inherently individual, so
a general class-action ruling on compensatory damages isn't
feasible _ even though all the employees in the group may have
experienced discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which is known as the Allison decision, after Citgo
employee James E. Allison, has thrown a wrench into the strategy
used by plantiff's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, David Berg, the well-known criminal and civil
trial lawyer, has filed a race discrimination class action against
GC Services, a Houston-based debt collection agency and phone
servicing center. To get around the Allison decision, Berg is
asking the court for front pay, back pay and punitive damages. The
company has 6,400 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Back pay is compensation for lost wages between the time of
termination and the time of trial. Front pay is typically an
alternative to reinstatement and is money intended to minimize the
effect of discrimination in the future. It may take someone who has
been unlawfully fired awhile to get back to his former income
level.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of employees involved, front and back pay still
is worth several million dollars, Berg said. Individual employees
could then file their own lawsuits for mental anguish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PROVING DISCRIMINATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Berg argued before U.S. Magistrate Judge
Calvin Botley that GC Services systematically refuses to hire
blacks as managers and that the case should be certified as a class
action. Botley is expected to rule later this year or early next
year on whether the case will be certified for class status.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that while 48 percent of the employees are minorities,
only 2 percent are above the level of assistant manager. (However,
GC Services hired a black executive earlier this month, Berg said.)
And Berg said company officials repeatedly told hiring managers in
Atlanta to hire only white employees.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence appears strong: The former head of the Atlanta
office testified at the hearing in front of Botley that he was
instructed many times to hire just white employees.
</P>
<P>
   GC Services, which is owned by Jerold B. Katz, is a big company.
Berg said the company's annual revenues are at least $7.5 billion.
And the company, whose clients include American Express, MCI and
the IRS, has hired Daryl Bristow, the famous trial lawyer from
Baker &AMP; Botts, to launch its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bristow argues that Berg can't make an end run around Allison
like he is trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   It was tried in a case in West Texas, Bristow said, and it
didn't work then. And, he said good lawyers will take individual
cases that may be worth $100,000 or $50,000 or even $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``they may not attract a David Berg who doesn't want to
touch something for less than $1 million an hour,'' Bristow said in
his Oklahoma drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Bristow disputes the allegations of race discrimination at GC
Services and said there was no central hiring authority that
directed race-based hiring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GAINING PERSPECTIVE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Berg storms ahead, the Allison decision has made
employment lawyers reluctant to take on class-action cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many cases are worth trying over front pay?'' asked Larkin
Eakin Jr., who represented 600 black Pennzoil employees in a race
discrimination case that was settled earlier this year for $6.75
million.
</P>
<P>
   Eakin believes the U.S. Supreme Court eventually will weigh in
because other federal circuit courts have allowed class-action
verdicts that included mental anguish. However, Eakin isn't looking
for a test case anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a hot issue, he said, and the high court probably will
wait for more circuits to rule. A more interesting question, he
said, is whether a class member can sue later for mental anguish
and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
