<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-NYT &LR;      12-23 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMARKS COULD HURT ROCKER MOST OF ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
(th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Rocker's remarks about New York Mets fans and New York
residents in general, as reported in Sports Illustrated this week,
have put his future as the Atlanta Braves' closer in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks, which were also ethnically and racially offensive
in tone, have ignited a firestorm of protest and condemnation of
Rocker from his teammates and residents of Atlanta, and may make it
impossible for the Braves to keep him on the team.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the very fans whom Rocker clearly dislikes so much
could well be cheering him next season if the Mets overtake a
Braves team weakened by the loss of their top reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schultz, the Braves' public relations director, said the
Braves offices were ``swamped'' with calls on Wednesday. The
offices were closed Thursday at the start of the team's annual
holiday vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most were very, very negative,'' Schultz said. ``We had people
calling and identifying themselves as gay or Spanish or
Asian-American. Half a dozen or so threatened to cancel their
season tickets. A lot of people said they'd never watch a Braves
game on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine, one of the Braves' veteran starting pitchers, and
Brian Jordan, their right fielder, criticized Rocker on Atlanta
talk shows. Leo Mazzone, the Braves pitching coach, said he should
be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron, the club's senior vice president, said he was
sickened by Rocker's remarks and questioned how Rocker could remain
in baseball, not just with the Braves. About 15 people protested
outside Turner Field on Thursday, urging the Braves to dump the
25-year-old reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell of Atlanta tried to distance Rocker and his
comments from the city and the team when he said ``we regard
ourselves as a city of great tolerance. This is the birthplace of
Dr. King; the civil rights movement sprang from the loins of
Atlanta.'' He called it more of a ``personal tragedy'' for Rocker
that was ``largely the product of ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have said they will address the issue when their
executives return from vacation after the start of the new year.
They plan to meet with Rocker, discuss the dilemma and decide on a
course of action.
</P>
<P>
   Not that most of the protesters care, but from a baseball
standpoint, the situation could prove extremely troublesome for the
Braves. If the Braves have had one problem through their dominance
of the National League in the 1990s, it has been their inability to
come up with a consistent closer.
</P>
<P>
   They thought they finally had one in Mark Wohlers, a young
hard-throwing right-hander, who gained 25 saves in 1995, 39 in 96
and 33 in 97. But then Wohlers inexplicably lost his ability to
throw strikes and wild-pitched himself out of the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Wohlers, the Braves tried Kerry Ligtenberg, a rookie
right-hander, who secured saves in 30 of 34 save situations in
1998. He was the first National League rookie with 30 saves in a
dozen years. But Ligtenberg did not have a chance to add to that
success last season. In spring training he tore the medial
collateral ligament in his right elbow and underwent ``Tommy John''
ligament transplant surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Braves came up with Rocker, a left-hander in his
second season with the team. He was eager and he capitalized on the
opportunity he received. He earned 38 saves, one short of Wohlers'
club record of 39, including three against the Mets in a critical
September series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
