<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CREW-EDUC-ART-NYT &LR;      12-23 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD OF EDUCATION VOTES AGAINST RENEWING SCHOOL CHANCELLOR'S
CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)   (See also NY-CREW-MAYOR) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT20, NYT21 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After weeks of complaining that Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew had lost his focus and slipped into deep ambivalence
about his job, the New York City Board of Education voted 4-3 on
Thursday to end Crew's tenure when his contract expires next June.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Crew said he was so disgusted by the board's action
that he might leave sooner, raising the possibility that the
nation's largest school system, with 1.1. million children, would
be left rudderless at a time when it is under enormous pressure to
introduce tough new graduation standards and raise test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The votes to oust Crew were cast by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
three allies on the board and by Terri Thomson, the Queens member
who in recent months has acted as the swing vote.
</P>
<P>
   Those members said after the vote that they had been
particularly troubled by Crew's behavior in recent weeks. They
cited his persistent refusal to reveal whether he wanted to stay
on, his shrugging off a state report charging widespread attendance
fraud, and his jibe last week that a city councilman was ``too
short'' to criticize him.
</P>
<P>
   But a supporter of Crew, William C. Thompson, the board
president, said after the vote that ``the mayor's fingerprints are
on this'' and that it was ``a recipe for disaster for this school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   For Crew, Thursday's vote, which took place 10 minutes into a
closed board meeting that lasted less than an hour, ended a
four-year tenure marked by several major accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Crew persuaded the state Legislature to curtail the power of the
city's 32 local school boards, giving the chancellor more say over
the appointment of local superintendents, ended the automatic
promotion of failing students and helped negotiate a deal to end
lifelong job protection for principals.
</P>
<P>
   But standardized test scores have largely remained flat under
Crew's leadership, and New York City still lags behind the rest of
the state on graduation rates, spending per pupil and the
percentage of students taking and passing tough new Regents tests.
</P>
<P>
   Crew benefited from strong political support for much of his
tenure, but his close relationship with Giuliani deteriorated last
April after he fiercely and successfully resisted the mayor's plan
to experiment with school vouchers. In May, Giuliani infuriated
Crew again by persuading a majority of board members to reject the
chancellor's $11 billion school construction plan, handing Crew his
first defeat by the board since it hired him in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Crew kept a low profile on Thursday, staying inside his home in
Brooklyn Heights with his four grown children, who were visiting
for the holidays. He issued a long, at times emotional statement
that did not address the vote at all, but alluded to his battle
with Giuliani over vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Crew said that he had realized last spring
that ``it might be impossible to restore the solidarity that marked
my first three years as chancellor.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has not publicly criticized Crew in recent months, but
he has frequently complained that the school system is a failure
and has refused to say whether Crew should remain on the job. But
one person close to the Giuliani administration said on Thursday
that the mayor had planned to support a yearlong extension for Crew
because Giuliani was presumably running for the Senate next year,
and he did not want to face the political repercussions of ousting
a popular black chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   But the person close to the administration, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said that Giuliani's anger at Crew boiled
over this week after Crew made a last-minute request for a raise
and a pension supplement. Crew already makes $245,000 a year,
compared with $195,000 for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The board members voting not to renew Crew's contract were Ms.
Thomson, Deputy Mayor Ninfa Segarra, Jerry Cammarata of Staten
Island and Irene H. Impellizeri of Brooklyn. Voting for him were
William Thompson, of Brooklyn, Dr. Irving S. Hamer Jr. of Manhattan
and Dr. Sandra E. Lerner of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The board had a deadline of Jan. 1 to tell Crew whether they
wanted to extend his contract, but William Thompson and the other
members said in recent weeks that they needed to know whether Crew
truly wanted to stay before making a decision. Early last week,
Crew finally told Thompson that he wanted to stay for two or even
three years, and he asked Thompson to work out the details of a new
contract with his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Crew's aides said that when he asked for the extension, he also
requested a pension supplement worth twice his annual salary, or
nearly $500,000. Ms. Segarra, one of Giuliani's two appointees to
the board and one of Crew's harshest critics, said after the vote
on Thursday that the chancellor had also requested a raise and that
those last-minute demands were ``the straw that broke the camel's
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
