<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-9     12-23 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-910&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN STARTS FIGHT THROUGH HEDGEROWS OF REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Mass., W. Va., Texas, N.C., N.H.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYSONS CORNER, Va. _ Pat Buchanan styles himself lately as
``that troll still waiting out there under the bridge,'' hoping for
political magic to strike his impish presidential candidacy as a
Reform Party insurgent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this troll's campaign along the third-party route is
hardly that lyrical. It is an arduous slog, state by state, into
the arcane thicket of a party whose organizations in 21 states are
the withered branches from the moneyed taproot of Ross Perot. Each
has its own cadre of political mavericks often wary of an intruder
like Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Buchanan field workers are finding rules and
meetings of the Reform Party suddenly being altered at the approach
of his organizers. Buchanan strategists say they have found no sign
of organized opposition in the states where the actual nomination
must be won, despite all the aggressive sound bites and media
coverage of his chief antagonists, Donald Trump and Gov. Jesse
Ventura of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new universe, as basic a form of politics as
anything I've ever seen in 20 years in the business,'' said Bay
Buchanan, the candidate's sister and field general. ``That's what
so refreshing about it: Guys trying to outwit you in numbers you
can deal with, not the Bush machine pumping in millions and buying
support by the busload.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, this is the sort of campaign where one canny Buchanan
opponent, outnumbered at a meeting, drove off and returned with
carloads of homeless people newly enrolled as Reform stalwarts.
``We countered that by going to our people _ a bunch of Catholic
parishioners we found building a new rectory for their pastor,''
said Tim Haley, Buchanan's political director, who insisted that
anxiety within the party about Buchanan seemed to be easing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a stealth campaign _ very stealthy,'' Buchanan said
of the opposition as he employed Perot's past specialist in state
election laws, Matt Sawyer, a lawyer from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With the Reform Party already on the ballot in 21 states,
Buchanan's task, carried out in the shadow of the major parties'
cycle of primary contests, is to impress Reform loyalists by
organizing the other 29 states for his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, he is about to launch a painstaking petition
campaign to gather 800,000 certified signatures across those 29
states, a six-month drive that will cost more than $2 million for
the hiring of professional canvassers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 21 states where the Reform Party is already on the
ballet, Buchanan operatives are trying to put their people in
power. But they are finding that each state has its own peculiar
set of abstruse, often shifting regulations for a candidate's
entry, leaving even a gifted troll facing a national political game
of Chutes and Ladders.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times we hear about a state meeting but they've changed the
rules by the time we arrive,'' said Ms. Buchanan, who has a network
tracking the obscure doings of Reform organizations. ``They'll say
the meeting's at 11, but it's really at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's human nature, the instinct for
self-preservation,'' she said, grateful for the tricks that she
learned from such masters as Lee Atwater, a former strategist of
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you finally pinpoint there's a meeting and find out in
which hotel, you make sure to call the hotel to double-check and
you ask what the capacity of the meeting room is,'' she said,
explaining a time-honored tactic. ``Then you know how many people
to have there to dominate the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley is working from assorted state rule books bristling with
restrictions. In Massachusetts, he cautions, an entire roster of
legitimate petitioners can be rejected if someone has
absent-mindedly put check marks on the document pages. He now knows
that each Reform signatory in West Virginia must be formally told
not to partake in anyone else's campaign or the entire petition
roster fails. Texas and North Carolina are the toughest challenges,
needing more than 50,000 certified signatures.
</P>
<P>
   In one skirmish, the New Hampshire Reform leaders suddenly
canceled an organizing meeting as Buchanan supporters approached,
rescheduling the gathering two weeks later but creating a rule that
attendees must be in the party at least a month to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the creation of a larger rival Granite State
Reform Party by Buchanan's ``pitchfork brigade,'' loyalists from
his Republican primary runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our best not to intimidate,'' Haley added,
emphasizing that he talks not of a party putsch but of a
professional operation dedicated to bolstering cooperative state
leaders. ``I think they're less squeamish after we leave,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of progress included success by Buchanan supporters in
shifting the meeting of Texas Reformers from Dallas, the party
hotbed, to Houston, where there are more Buchanan supporters. Even
more encouraging, Ventura supporters were rebuffed in Minnesota
when they tried to introduce a one-year party membership
requirement to derail the Buchanan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as they decipher each twist and turn, the Buchanan
organizers know they must endure the ultimate Catch-22 in the
national Reform Party's complex set of convention rules next
August. It is the rule that allows two-thirds of the 590 delegates
to suddenly introduce an 11th-hour candidate on the floor despite
the results of all the preceding months of caucus and primary
struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that crazy,'' Ms. Buchanan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other strategists say the antidote lies in the two ways Buchanan
can get his delegates into the convention hall: either as formal
Reform Party representatives more susceptible to the intrigues of
party leaders, or as independent delegates committed to Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation is that Buchanan forces will organize perhaps
four of the 29 targeted states within the Reform Party, while
protecting their strength within the other 25 states by organizing
as independent delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is a wild-card party procedure by which
anyone in the nation can enroll and vote _ by e-mail message, fax,
the manner is not fully clear _ in choosing the nominee. This will
require a full-court alert for the more than 100,000 ``pitchfork
brigadeers'' on the Buchanan list of supporters from past
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frightening,'' Ms. Buchanan admitted in summarizing the
hairpin turnings of the Reform route. ``But so far, we don't find
anyone else on the road out there,'' she said of her brother's
intended path from troll to nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
