<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS HASTENED FOR START OF TRADING IN NASDAQ JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers is speeding up
its plans for an electronic stock market in Japan that will promote
cross-trading of United States and Japanese stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement planned for Friday, Nasdaq Japan, a
partnership between the NASD and Softbank Corp. of Japan, will
describe a deal that could result in some new Japanese stocks being
traded in the United States as early as next September. Previously,
Nasdaq Japan was not expected to be open for trading until the
fourth quarter of 2000 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the Osaka Securities Exchange will provide
Nasdaq Japan with back-office services like clearing and settling
of trades, as well as surveillance of suspicious or unusual trading
activity. In return, Osaka will get a share of the profits
generated from trading on Nasdaq Japan, although Osaka has not
decided whether to buy a stake in the exchange. This agreement will
speed up the introduction of Nasdaq Japan by allowing trading to
begin on Osaka's current computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NASD, the parent of the Nasdaq market in the
United States, will build a computer platform that will link Nasdaq
Japan to the original Nasdaq market, as well as a planned Nasdaq
Europe. The Japan-U.S. connection will represent the first concrete
part of an ambitious NASD plan for a single 24-hour global stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the association hopes to interlink ``pools of
liquidity, so U.S. companies can be exposed to pools of investors
outside the U.S. and non-U.S. companies can be exposed to investors
in the U.S.,'' Frank G. Zarb, the chairman of the association,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan will open in stages. The first stocks to be traded
on the new market will be Japanese initial public offerings. By
September 2000, U.S. investors will be able to trade Japanese
public offerings that meet listing standards on the original
Nasdaq. By the end of 2000, big U.S. Nasdaq companies like
Microsoft and Intel will be available for Japanese investors to
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's move toward 24-hour trading is proceeding even though
the NASD, and regulators have not fully resolved the vital issue of
when companies will disclose important information like earnings
releases and takeovers to investors in a world of continuous
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, companies have made major announcements before or
after the close of trading so that all interested investors and
analysts are apprised of the news before trading resumes in their
stocks. But Zarb acknowledged that the NASD remained unsure what
model would replace that system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
