<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-RUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOT OF THE ONE THE BABE `CALLED' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Wyo.)  (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Warp attended one major league baseball game in his life,
and it was Game 3 of the 1932 World Series. Warp was a businessman
living in Chicago who loved collecting artifacts of the past and
filming his experiences to show to his family back in Nebraska. So
he toted his 16-millimeter camera to Wrigley Field that Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Nice choice.
</P>
<P>
   Warp wasn't an artiste, but in his jiggly style, he filmed one
of baseball's legendary sequences: Babe Ruth gesturing in a way
that made some witnesses believe he was pointing to a spot in the
outfield where he would slug a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth then hammered a solo shot off the Cubs' Charlie Root that
the film shows, for the first time, landing in faraway center
field. Then, Ruth rounds the bases, making mocking gestures to the
bench jockeys on the Cubs who were riding him mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ruth actually called his shot has been a subject of
debate for more than six decades. And now, as millennium lists have
proliferated, the spotlight has been shined on the century's great
moments in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he made a gesture, to indicate `I'm going to hit
one,''' Robert Creamer, the author of ``Babe,'' considered the
definitive Ruth biography, said Thursday. ``But he did that a lot.
It doesn't matter if he's pointing to a spot. He did something. He
challenged them. He gestured. He stuck it to the Cubs and he loved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Warp's film took its place among the many reels of family
doings, and few members of the large Warp clan, who assembled at
annual reunions in Minden, Neb., gave much thought to the
significance of the ancient footage, James Jacobs, Warp's
great-great-nephew, said.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1993 reunion, a relative videotaped the films as they
were projected on a meeting room wall in a motel owned by Warp. The
old man was then in his 90s, yet he provided detailed
extemporaneous narration of 30 years of celluloid family history.
Jacobs was enchanted to see his grandfather, at age 8 or 9, goofing
for the camera as he walked off the porch of a house with 30 or 40
other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ruth footage was played for the family, Jacobs said
Thursday, ``You could hear Harold say, `This is Wrigley Field,
there's Lou Gehrig, there's Babe Ruth.' But he wasn't a big fan.''
In 1994, Warp died.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Jacobs' great-aunt, knowing that Jacobs worked at
a television station, asked him to edit the tape in a professional
manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could tell the family history like Harold,'' Jacobs
said.
</P>
<P>
   But each time Jacobs watched the tape, the more he realized he
had a historic artifact. He researched the incident and wondered if
his great-great-uncle's film had solved the ``called shot''
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs felt the film should be in the Baseball Hall of Fame. He
showed it to members of the Society for American Baseball Research,
who did not doubt its authenticity. Ruth played only two games in
Wrigley Field with the Yankees, and the film clearly showed Ruth
swatting a home run at the ballpark. Jacobs gave a copy of his tape
to a society member who works at the Hall of Fame. But Jacobs still
had no deal.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Jacobs did not own the film and felt
reluctant to give it to anyone without the approval of Warp's son,
his third cousin, who is also named Harold but is nicknamed Skip.
</P>
<P>
   Despite letters and calls, Jacobs said, he got little feedback
from Skip Warp. ``I was frustrated,'' said Jacobs, who lives in
Cheyenne, Wyo. ``I knew he was very busy and this wasn't that
important to him. I told him about the people I was talking to. I
was trying to convince him this is a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jacobs' luck began to change. Online at ESPN.com, he
read a request for unusual footage and home movies from ESPN's
``Sports Century'' series, which was down to its last four
biographies of the century's top 50 North American athletes _ Ruth,
Muhammad Ali, Jim Brown and Michael Jordan. The final order will
not be known until Sunday's finale at 5 p.m. EST on ABC, when Nos.
1 and 2 will be named. ESPN will carry Nos. 3 and 4 Friday night at
10.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' first e-mail to ESPN was ignored. A second one, routed
through a co-worker's friend at ESPN, found Mark Shapiro, the
series' coordinating producer. ``I called him at 11 o'clock Tuesday
night and told him I'd have a courier at his house in 45 minutes,''
said Shapiro, who subsequently made a deal with Skip Warp.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Jacobs spoke to his cousin. ``His feedback was
positive, but I don't know if he was thrilled that I went ahead
without him,'' Jacobs said. ``But he realized the film belongs
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Century'' was the perfect place because of the quality
of its programs and its reputation for archival research. The Ruth
biography was not completed and Shapiro had already planned to open
it with a look at the ``called shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said, ``For a guy who's so mythic, we went with the
moment that symbolized that the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro already had another 16-millimeter amateur movie of the
home run taken by Matt Kandle Sr., which surfaced in 1994. A fan
blocked Kandle's view as Ruth rounded third base, so the Warp
footage completes the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the home movies provide telling evidence that Ruth's
gestures were directed at the Cubs' dugout, not to the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not pointing to the outfield,'' Shapiro said. ``He's
turning left and yelling at the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ruth might have gestured and boasted to Charlie Grimm's
Cubs that he would hit a home run. He had already hit one that day.
</P>
<P>
   And the legend lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
