<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8006 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-TRADE-HNS &LR;      12-23 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Before leaving for the winter meetings in early December, Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker classified any player not under
contract beyond the 2000 season as a ``trade possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In the span of eight days, possibilities have become realities.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros unloaded two more high-priced veterans Thursday,
shipping Cy Young Award runner-up Mike Hampton and right fielder
Derek Bell to the New York Mets for center fielder Roger Cedeno,
righthander Octavio Dotel and minor-league lefthander Kyle Kessel.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, the Astros traded center fielder Carl Everett to the
Boston Red Sox for two minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   All three ex-Astros _ Hampton, Bell and Everett _ were set to
become free agents after the 2000 season, and each will command
salaries of at least $5 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing they would lose Hampton, the lefthander who led the
National League with 22 wins in 1999, to free agency, Hunsicker
said the Astros decided to trade now rather than run the risk of
losing him later without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind there was a lot of interest in Mike, but we
certainly weren't in the mode to just trade him for the sake of
trading him,'' Hunsicker said. ``If we were going to trade him, it
had to make sense from a baseball standpoint. We certainly needed
to receive something back valuable enough to make it work from a
baseball standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, 25, will move into the starting center-field spot
vacated by Everett and may solve the Astros' search for a No. 2
hitter. His acquisition will allow Richard Hidalgo, coming off knee
surgery, to replace Bell in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, a switch hitter, hit .313 with 36 RBIs in 1999, his
first full season in the majors after spending parts of four
seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers. He made $487,500 last season
and is eligible for salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has world-class speed,'' Hunsicker said of Cedeno,
who was second in the National League with 66 stolen bases. ``He's
among the fastest in the majors. It gives (Hidalgo) an opportunity
to get back in the groove instead of tracking down balls in the
massive center field that we'll have in the new ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel, 24, is a highly regarded prospect who is expected to move
into the starting rotation, likely as the No. 4 or 5 man. In his
first shot at the majors in 1999, he was 8-3 with a 5.38 ERA in 14
starts and five relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   He made the league minimum of $270,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets offered Cedeno and Dotel to Seattle earlier this month
in talks involving Ken Griffey Jr. The proposed deal collapsed when
Griffey told the Mariners he would exercise his right to block all
deals except one that would send him to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``As opposed to the Carl Everett trade that was focused on the
future, we wanted to make sure if we were going to trade Hampton,
we got some talent back, players to help us compete and win in the
year 2000,'' Hunsicker said. ``I really believe we accomplished
that with this trade. They are major-league-ready players.''
</P>
<P>
   And they come at a considerably lower price.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have made no secret of their intent to try to pare a
player payroll that reached $56 million in 1999. By trading
Hampton, Bell and Everett, they will save approximately $16 million
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros indicated they may attempt to sign a free-agent
pitcher with the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things this trade does give us is some flexibility
budget-wise,'' Hunsicker said. ``We've gone from a position where
we were pushing up against a limit _ and quite frankly over where
we wanted to be _ to one where we can now do some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who will earn $5.75 million this season and be eligible
for free agency following the 2000 season, was 22-4 with a 2.90 ERA
in 1999, finishing second to Arizona's Randy Johnson in voting for
the NL Cy Young Award. Down the stretch, Hampton won 11 straight
decisions to help lead the Astros to a third straight NL Central
Division title.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Astros on Dec. 15 he was not interested in
discussing a contract extension and would test the free-agent
market a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``His representative called and indicated he would rather play
out the final year and explore the market,'' Hunsicker said. ``That
hit us between the eyes. I was shocked and didn't see it coming. In
my mind, that forced our hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were more than glad to acquire Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard Mike  was available, I thought
it was a ploy to get a lot of offers of players going to Houston,''
Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He's one of the best offensive
players hitting in the ninth spot in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Bell, 31, was less of a surprise. The Astros
have openly shopped him for the past two seasons, finding little
interest because of Bell's high price tag and sporadic play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided internally that we were not going retain him past
the 2000 season,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell lost his starting job during the final week of the season
after hitting .236 with 12 homers and 66 RBIs. A year earlier, Bell
hit .314 with a career-high 22 homers and 108 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play hard and make them wish they hadn't traded
me,'' said Bell, who will make $5 million in 2000. ``I'm going to
make Houston eat its words.''
</P>
<P>
   After trading Hampton, one of the most popular Astros, and
Everett for younger talent, Hunsicker expects the initial public
view to be unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reiterated many times that the key to the success of
this franchise is the continuation of blending veteran players with
young players,'' Hunsicker said. ``With salaries escalating to the
levels they currently are for premium players, clubs are looking at
situations where you only have a handful of real premium players
and you're going to be even more dependent on the young people
coming up, either through your system or via trades.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
