<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DAVIES-3TAKES-NY     12-23 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PATON DAVIES, 91, DIPLOMAT WHO RAN AFOUL OF MCCARTHY OVER
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.Y., N.C., La., Pa., China, Russia, Peru, Spain)  (EDS: An abridged version, OBIT-DAVIES-ABRIDGED, will also be
filed) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Paton Davies, a leading diplomat who was among the ``old
China hands'' driven from the State Department after Sen. Joseph
McCarthy questioned their loyalty and labeled them Communist
sympathizers in the 1950s, died Thursday at his home in Asheville,
N.C. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and about a dozen of the country's most eminent China
scholars and diplomats found themselves accused of having ``lost
China'' after Mao Tse-tung's Communist forces defeated Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalists, which were supported by the American
government, in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   In his attacks, McCarthy was echoing the indignant arguments of
the China lobby, as the powerful American backers of Chiang
Kai-shek were known. Among those accused of ``selling out'' Chiang
were several diplomats, including Oliver Edmund Clubb, John Carter
Vincent and John Stewart Service, and academics like Owen Lattimore
and John King Fairbank.
</P>
<P>
   But of all those Americans whose careers were blighted in the
hunt for scapegoats, Davies may be one of the most poignant
examples. He was a decorated hero of World War II destined,
according to his superiors, for high rank in the State Department.
He was regarded as a tough foe of Stalinism whose World War II
reports from China were much concerned with the threat of Soviet
domination. In 1950 he had even proposed that the United States,
with its superiority in nuclear weapons, engage in a ``preventive
showdown'' with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Nov. 5, 1954, Secretary of State John Foster Dulles
dismissed him from the Foreign Service, maintaining that Davies had
``demonstrated a lack of judgment, discretion and reliability.''
According to ``The China Hands,'' a book by E.J. Kahn published in
1972, Davies was then told that if he ever needed a recommendation
for a new job, the secretary of state would be happy to provide
one.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal took place four years after McCarthy began his
pursuit of the State Department's Far Eastern division, describing
it in a Senate speech as the home base of ``individuals who are
loyal to the ideals and designs of Communism rather than those of
the free, God-fearing half of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped up his accusations that the Eisenhower
administration was sheltering Communist sympathizers, McCarthy
first asserted that he had a list of 205 State Department policy
shapers who were ``known to the secretary of state as being members
of the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he mentioned a list of 57 names, and a list of 81. Pressed
to identify anyone, he declared that Lattimore, a Johns Hopkins
University professor who specialized in Mongolian studies and had
no official ties to the State Department, was ``the top Russian spy
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davies and his colleagues were accused, it was noted that
many were named John, which gave rise to a bitter riddle: Who was
responsible for losing China? John S. Service, John Carter Vincent,
John Paton Davies and John Kai-shek.
</P>
<P>
   In hearings that lasted for years, several of the China hands,
including Davies, Service and Vincent, were accused by Gen. Patrick
J. Hurley, Roosevelt's special envoy and then ambassador to China
in 1944-45, of sabotaging his efforts to prevent the collapse of
the Nationalist government. Among other things, they were attacked
for having known and met with Chinese Communist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the case against Davies arose from his role in the
Tawny Pipit Affair. The tawny pipit, a bird that sings loudly in
flight, was the code name for a covert intelligence-gathering
operation contemplated after the fall of the Chinese Nationalist
government in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   After the lowering of the Bamboo Curtain when the Communists
took over, Davies was delegated by George Kennan, director of
policy planning in the State Department, to attend a meeting with
Defense and Central Intelligence representativays to obtain
intelligence from China. Davies suggested that approaches be made
to half a dozen Americans friendly with the Chinese Communist
leaders, with an eye toward enlisting them as double agents.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was never pursued, but in 1952 Davies' critics
contended that he had been trying to infiltrate the U.S.
intelligence network with Communist sympathizers so they might
eventually subvert their country in support of China.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by a Senate subcommittee on internal security,
Davies parried questions while adhering to his understanding that
anything involving the CIA had to be kept secret. Later,
subcommittee members tried to charge Davies with perjury on the
basis of his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Kennan, who had worked with Davies in Moscow, strongly defended
him. In his ``Memoirs 1950-1963,'' Kennan noted that Davies had
originally run afoul of Hurley by trying to warn him against Soviet
perfidy, and largely as a result of the general's charges had
suffered ``years of harassment and humiliation.'' This, Kennan
said, reflected ``the nightmarish quality'' of that time, and he
described Davies as ``a man of broad, sophisticated and skeptical
political understanding, without an ounce of pro-Communist
sympathies, and second to no one in his devotion to the interests
of our government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
