r f BC-SWISSAIR-PALMDALE-LAD     12-23 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-PALMDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS AIRCRAFT DEAL TO CREATE 6,000 JOBS IN PALMDALE REGION OVER 5
YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dominic Berbeo  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A deal to bring a major Swiss aircraft
maintenance facility to Palmdale Regional Airport north of Los
Angeles will create 6,000 jobs for the region in the next five
years, representing the biggest foreign investment of the 1990s in
California and a comeback for the local economy, California Gov.
Gray Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is another indication that California is back,''
Davis said Thursday at a news conference at Los Angeles
International Airport where the agreement was officially announced.
``This is a phenomenal day for California and a phenomenal day for
the Antelope Valley (region). We expect this project to generate $1
billion in state tax revenues over the next 20 years, and that's a
conservative figure.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the jobs created at SR Technics, a subsidiary of
Swissair, are expected to average $50,000 per year in salary, and
would likely go to local residents left unemployed by the massive
downsizing in the aerospace industry over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives from the state include $79 million in tax subsidies,
Davis said, in return for the Swiss company hiring locally for the
facility which is expected to open in June.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 jobs are expected by the time the facility opens,
with another 5,000 jobs by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the next five years, SR Technics President Hans
Ulrich Beyeler said the facility has a total job capacity of 7,000
positions, and the company hopes to fill at least that many in the
next decade, becoming the largest employer in the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just another facility,'' Beyeler said. ``This is a
building block in our long-term global strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft maintenance and restoration facility will be
located on Site 9 of the airport, land being leased by Los Angeles
World Airports to Boeing Corp. where military aircraft were built
during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was also a key player in the deal, agreeing to contract
with SR Technics to convert 57 DC-10 passenger jets to MD-10 cargo
freighters at the Palmdale site.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is part of an ongoing effort by Los Angeles to lure
commercial air carriers and commuter airlines to the airport, city
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is a major milestone in my long-standing
commitment to a regional solution to meet our ever-growing air
transportation needs,'' Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan said in a
written statement Thursday. ``It follows the joint cooperation
initiative Los Angeles has with the city of Palmdale.''
</P>
<P>
   John Agoglia, president of the Los Angeles Airport Commission,
said the new facility will also help in the negotiations to bring
high-speed rail transportation to Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it definitely shows the airport to be a marketable
asset, and will play a vital role in bringing better public
transportation to the area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Los Angeles will also contribute improvements to the
site, said Deputy Mayor Rocky Delgadillo, including a $12.5 million
fire sprinkler system for the two main hangars on the site.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, a longtime supporter of
increasing activity at Palmdale to relieve some of the traffic at
LAX, praised the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is living proof, as I've contended for years,'' she said,
``that with some serious marketing efforts, Palmdale Airport can
really take off.''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Contreras, the head of the local AFL-CIO, said the county
was in dire need of the influx of new jobs, most of which will be
held by union members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have an agreement yet, but we're going to make sure
the jobs are union,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
