<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DAVIES-2NDTAKE-N     12-23 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: our government.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like several other American figures in the Chinese drama, John
Paton Davies Jr. was born in China _ in Kiating, Sichuan province,
on April 6, 1908. His parents were Baptist missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years at the University of Wisconsin, another at
Yenching University outside Beijing and a fourth at Columbia, where
he graduated in 1931. He joined the Foreign Service and returned to
China the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Stationed successively in Kunming, Beijing, Mukden and Hankou,
Davies spent the next decade observing the advance of the Japanese
armies into China, protecting U.S. interests and eventually
evacuating U.S. civilians. In Hankou, then the Nationalists'
capital, he met the leading Communists, witnessed the rout of the
Nationalist forces by the Japanese and saw atrocities committed by
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   When Japan attacked Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, Davies was in
Washington, on the State Department's China desk. He seized an
opportunity to join the staff of Gen. Joseph Stilwell, who had just
been named commander of the China-Burma-India theater.
</P>
<P>
   Stilwell's forces suffered defeat in Burma; after leading a
painful retreat, Stilwell was given responsibility for organizing
the defense of India and China. Davies served as his chief
diplomatic aide, political adviser, interpreter, sometime press
spokesman and Dutch uncle (occasionally warning the tough soldier,
known as Vinegar Joe, to restrain his candor and optimism).
</P>
<P>
   Tensions quickly developed between the Americans and the Chiang
government, then based in Chongqing. In his reports, Davies
expressed fear that China was headed toward a civil war that the
Communists would win, and that American support of Chiang against
Mao would drive the Chinese Communists toward the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Long afterward, he said he had mistaken the Communists' evident
popularity with the idea that their ascent to power had something
to do with democracy. He also said he had underestimated the grip
of Maoist ideology in theorizing that the Communists would be open
to American investment. In essence something like this did happen,
but it took another three decades.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, 1943, Davies was on a C-46 transport flying to China
from India when an engine failed and all aboard were ordered to
jump.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sevareid, who was aboard as a radio correspondent,
recounted the story: none of the 17 passengers had ever used a
parachute, and all hesitated. Davies, as the senior official,
jumped first, his attache case stuffed inside his shirt. It took a
month for the group to walk out of the jungle, and according to
Sevareid it was Davies who rallied them when it seemed impossible
to go on. At one point, Sevareid said, Davies gave him his last cup
of water. Davies received the Medal of Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In summer 1944, an observation group called the Dixie Mission
was sent to the Communist headquarters at Yenan after prodding by
Davies and the U.S. Army. The mission confirmed reports of
Communist strength in the north. Davies made several trips there
and passed along two offers from Mao, one to visit the United
States to discuss further ties and the other to cooperate with a
contemplated U.S. landing on the Japanese-held coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not now abandon Chiang Kai-shek,'' Davies wrote in a
memo on Nov. 15, 1944, ``but we must be realistic. We must not
indefinitely underwrite a politically bankrupt regime. We must make
a determined effort to capture politically the Chinese Communists
rather than allow them to go by default wholly to the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley, who at the time accepted Stalin's assurances of support
for Chiang and of disdain for the Chinese Communists, now began to
denounce Davies and his colleagues, saying their criticism of the
Nationalists was meant to undermine his attempt to unify the
various Chinese military forces against the Japanese. Arriving in
Yenan in November 1944, he sent Davies back to Chongqing. Davies
was relieved to obtain a transfer to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow in
January 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley gained the Communists' assent to a coalition with the
Nationalists, but Chiang rejected it, proposing one unacceptable to
the Communists. In August 1945 the Japanese surrendered, and the
opposing Chinese armies raced to take over their sectors in a civil
war in which the United States backed the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
