<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DAVIES-3RDTAKE-N     12-23 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: losing side.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurley returned to Washington and resigned as ambassador in
November 1945, blaming the China hands, including Davies, for the
failure of his mission. The hunt for those who ``lost China'' was
well under way.
</P>
<P>
   The first victim was Service. The FBI arrested him, accusing him
of espionage in providing classified reports on China to a small
magazine called Amerasia, but he was cleared by a grand jury. He
was then accused of disloyalty on nine more occasions before
finally being dismissed on the ground of ``reasonable doubt'' of
his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   At the embassy in Moscow, where Davies had been promoted to
first secretary, echoes of Hurley's charges aroused indignant
rebuttals from Ambassador Averell Harriman and Kennan. Secretary of
State James F. Byrnes, on a visit, jestingly asked a Soviet leader
to be nice to Davies because Hurley was calling him a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   From 1947 to 1951, Davies served on the State Department's
policy planning staff, under Kennan. He foresaw the French defeat
in Indochina and urged that the United States avoid getting
involved. Like Kennan he remained suspicious of Moscow, and in one
paper called for a ``preventive showdown'' while the United States
still had a monopoly on atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
   He was nevertheless a major target of the China lobby, one of
whose stalwarts was another son of missionaries to China, Henry
Luce, founder and publisher of Time magazine. When Time accused
Davies of undercutting Gen. Douglas MacArthur by warning of Chinese
intervention in Korea, Kennan wrote an angry rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to Germany in 1951, Davies was called home in the next
year to testify about the Tawny Pipit Affair. He was cleared of a
Senate subcommittee's perjury charge but was transferred to Lima,
Peru, where he served as charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
   Still McCarthy hammered away at him and at Tawny Pipit until, in
late 1954, a special security board ruled that while Davies'
loyalty could not be questioned, his employment was ``not clearly
consistent with the interests of the national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies was informally invited to resign, which would have
assured him a pension. He refused. Dulles summoned him and, in a
few words, told him he had been dismissed. It was then that the
secretary offered to provide a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said nothing, although he later termed the offer
``bizarre,'' because he had been found lacking ``in judgment,
discretion and reliability.'' In a statement he said: ``There has
been enough recrimination. I am not prepared to add to it and
thereby detract from the strength of my country in its mortal
struggle with the Communist enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to his family in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   In India in 1942, he had married Patricia Grady, a correspondent
for The Washington Post and the daughter of Henry F. Grady, the
first American ambassador to India. She survives, as do their seven
children: Sasha, of White Plains, N.Y.; Tiki, of Washington; John
G., of Baton Rouge, Louisiana; Susan, of Chatham, N.Y.; Jennifer,
of Seattle; Deborah, of London, and Megan, of New Orleans. Also
surviving are a brother, Donald, of State College, Pa., and 11
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had no experience in the woodworking trade, Davies
set up a shop in Lima to design and make furniture. It succeeded,
modestly. He also wrote a weekly column for a local newspaper, and
worked his writings into a book published in 1964, ``Foreign and
Other Affairs.'' In it he took a tough view of American policy in
Latin America, suggesting that Washington show more willingness to
support strong governments.
</P>
<P>
   About this time Davies returned to Washington to, as he put it,
raise his children in a democratic American climate. Friends began
a quiet effort to obtain his official rehabilitation, but it was
not until 1969 that he was granted a government security clearance
to work on a research project on Latin America at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. Even this action was not formally
announced by the State Department, though he did obtain a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and his family then lived for several years in Malaga,
Spain. He and his wife settled in Asheville, N.C., when their
children began attending college.His second book, ``Dragon by the
Tail,'' was both a memoir and a history of Chinese-American
relations from 1931 to 1945. It appeared in 1972, as the Nixon
administration's involvement with China was renewing American
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Davies concluded the book with this thought: ``The truth of the
matter is that China has been since the fall of the Empire a huge
and seductive practical joke. The Western businessmen, missionaries
and educators who had tried to modernize and Christianize it
failed. The Japanese militarists who tried to conquer it failed.
The American government, which tried to democratize and unify it,
failed. The Soviet rulers who tried to insinuate control over it
failed. Chiang failed. Mao failed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Davies, along with Fairbank and Service, was invited to
testify before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Its
chairman, William Fulbright, welcomed them by saying: ``It is a
very strange turn of fate that you gentlemen, who reported honestly
about conditions, were so persecuted because you were honest about
it. This is a strange thing to occur in what is called a civilized
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, while Davies was still living in Spain, the
American Foreign Service Association held a luncheon at the State
Department in honor of the old China hands. Davies was among those
invited, but he stayed home. He told friends it would have been a
long way to go for lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
