<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TERROR-VOICES-NYT &LR;      12-23 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK IS GROUND ZERO, ALL AGREE, BUT FOR FESTIVITY OR FEAR?
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three generations of the Errico family were making
their way through Times Square on Thursday, craning their necks at
the panorama of neon and disagreeing about whether the gridlocked
triangle was tourist heaven or ground zero for possible terrorist
activity on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The children, riding on their fathers' shoulders, were too young
to have understood the drumbeat of cautionary announcements from
government and law enforcement officials in recent days. Their
fathers _ one a real estate broker from Colorado, the other an
engineer from Maine _ were brashly confident that those warnings
were needless overkill.
</P>
<P>
   But the grandfather, a retiree from Westchester County, N.Y.,
was edgy as the new millennium approached, and edgier still each
time the president, the State Department, the mayor of New York
City or its police chief urged revelers to pay special attention in
public places.
</P>
<P>
   ``By playing it up,'' said the grandfather, Bob Errico,
``they're only scaring people more and giving ideas to the people
who are cuckoo.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the Errico family, there is no consensus in New York, or
in the nation, about whether this New Year's Eve will be just
another midnight gala or a millennial nightmare. But a few things
are clear: In New York and its suburbs there is substantial concern
about the potential for outbreaks of terrorism, particularly at the
traditional celebration in Times Square. Outside New York, by
contrast, people are generally confident that any trouble will take
place too far away to immediately affect their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But in and around New York, even those who were complacent a
week ago found themselves increasingly unnerved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I nervous? Honestly, yes,'' said John Garabieta, a
filmmaker from Rye, N.Y., who is planning to attend a New Year's
Eve party at a Times Square skyscraper. ``It started a few days
ago, when I kept reading things and hearing things on the news.
Everyone's pretending it's not a big deal, but then again they're
making it a big deal. So where I wasn't worried about it before, I
am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the nervousness more palpable _ or the government
warnings more appreciated _ than at the World Trade Center, where a
1993 terrorist bombing is seared in the memories of witnesses and
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there whose only purpose is to hurt us,''
said Faye Black, an administrative assistant who has worked in the
downtown towers for a decade. ``Officials are not scaring people;
they're giving us the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Catanzaro, a longtime temporary worker there, shuddered at
the memory of ``the helicopters, the smoke, the ambulances'' on the
day of the fatal attack. That dreadful day, she said, was ``a
wake-up call that we live in a city that's a target. There are a
lot of fanatics out there who will take advantage of the
celebration going on in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In cities or hamlets removed from New York, the epicenter of the
celebration and round-the-clock live television coverage, people
said they felt safer, certain that terrorists would choose a site
that guaranteed them maximum visibility.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, at Faneuil Hall Marketplace, Heather Midgley Douglas
said she thought that ``something is going to happen,'' but not in
her backyard. ``I definitely wouldn't be caught dead in New York in
Times Square,'' she said. ``That would be too good a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment was similar in the town square of tiny Holly Springs,
Miss. ``You hit a town like this and you're just wiping out a bunch
of hicks,'' said Tina Rhea, whose aunt owns Nadine's City Cafe,
which buzzed with holiday chatter. ``If you're a terrorist and want
to make a statement and you blow a small town like ththe
map, who cares? I mean, what do we have to offer the world besides
good sweet tea and great sweet potato pie?''
</P>
<P>
   Steven E. Roberts, the police chief of Westbrook, Maine, just
north of Portland, was also counting on quiet in his little corner
of the world. But on Thursday, he was sampling the holiday
excitement in Times Square with his wife, daughter and
mother-in-law. Roberts gave a rousing defense of the escalating
warnings coming from New York City officials as the big day
approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't business as usual,'' he said, noting that
terrorists ``would get the biggest bang for the buck'' by striking
Times Square. ``This is a unique situation and people can't be
complacent. A healthy degree of fear is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts added that city officials face a dilemma. They must
reassure would-be partygoers to boost attendance in Times Square
and also remind people that their safety cannot be guaranteed.
``Cops call it `cover your butt,''' he said of the double message.
``But people must make a conscious decision to take a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary citizens, without law enforcement experience,
worried that all the talk of terrorism would increase its
likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every nut watching TV, anybody with a screw loose thinking,
`This could be my claim to fame,' I'm more worried about them than
the actual terrorists,'' said Ivy Herman, a television producer who
was waiting for colleagues in Manhattan's Grand Central Terminal
for their annual holiday lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herman, like many other people interviewed in the New York
metropolitan area, also doubted the motives of officials issuing
daily warnings. Their goal, she guessed, was to avoid criticism.
``So some family from Wisconsin doesn't say to the mayor, `You said
it would be all right.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
