<HEADLINE>
BEANIE BABIES SUCCESSOR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Pokemon rules the mall this Christmas, the Beanie
Babies market hasn't exactly gone soft. &QL; 
Still, the maker of the squishy collectibles has decreed that the
line ends at 264 _ the total of cuddly characters issued since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Beanie Babies collectors and retailers are
watching the World Wide Web for word of the Beanies' successor,
sure to be a hot commodity by Christmas 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a cryptic Internet posting Aug. 31, Beanie boss H. Ty Warner
announced that production would cease at the end The news was met
with disbelief and raging rumors among fans, but it was confirmed
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ty Inc.'s official Web site (www.ty.com) carried this
note, signed by Warner: ``A VERY IMPORTANT GLOBAL NEWSFLASH WILL BE
MADE ON DE CEMBER 24, 1999. EXPECT THE UNEX PECTED!!!''
</P>
<P>
   A mysterious character even to toy-industry experts, Warner
birthed the Beanie Babies in 1993 and has masterfully manipulated
the little dolls into a huge industry. Though conceived as a soft
plaything for toddlers, they quickly became a hot commodity among
collectors and a business worth hundreds of millions, if not
billions, of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Based in suburban Chicago, Ty Inc. is a privately held company,
so precise sales figures aren't available. Multiple phone calls
from The Arizona Republic were unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no estimate, because he's been so guarded on
everything,'' said Mary Beth Sobo lewski, editor of Mary Beth's
Bean Bag World Monthly magazine, a favorite independent information
source among collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside observers can only guess at the Beanies' sales figures.
For example, Sobolewski assumes that a Princess Diana tribute doll
sold 21 million copies, because Ty Inc. donated that many dollars _
$1 per doll _ to a charity fund in Diana's name.
</P>
<P>
   Another popularity indicator: Ac cording to one published
source, a McDonald's co-promotion moved more than 240 million
miniature (or Teenie) Babies in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Each baby carries a heart-shaped name tag, complete with ``birth
date'' and poem. Hallmark and Nordstrom stores sell them, but Ty
has otherwise generally limited dis tribution to smaller toy shops
and specialty stores. Every Beanie re leased is eventually
``retired,'' cap ping supply and feeding demand.
</P>
<P>
   The Beanies phenomenon pre dated the dawn of e trade, but Web
sites such as eBay quickly arose to connect collectors in real
time. (Ty's Web site, font of all official Beanie news, claims more
than 3.4 billion hits, or viewer visits.) Rare retiree Beanies,
originally sold for $5, routinely trade at e-auction for four
figures.
</P>
<P>
   On the resale market, about 20 percent of the 264 character
dolls are worth $1,000 or more, Sobo lewski said, adding that
interest in Beanie Babies peaked in the sum mer of 1998 and had
been waning slightly before the retirement an nouncement.
</P>
<P>
   The impending production shut down has prompted many fans to
fill holes in their collections, Sobo lewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, I think your older, more valuable Beanies
that weren't out very long will become more and more valuable,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Later issues ``will hover in the $10, $15, $20 range'' on the
resale market because they were manu factured in greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent collectibles show at Chris-Town Mall in central
Phoenix, Leslie Billings, 36, bought a black Beanie Baby bear named
The End _ issued Aug. 31, to commemorate the production shutdown
announce ment.
</P>
<P>
   Billings, who estimated her Beanie Babies collection at 175,
said she's not a speculative collec tor, but she does track her
menag erie's market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we needed something, they'd get sold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Billings purchased The End from dealer Mark Cunningham, who said
collectors ``are being more selec tive, weighing the long-term
value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody thinks they're going to get rich, they're out of
their minds,'' Cunningham added.
</P>
<P>
   Most Beanies followers expect Friday's announcement to reveal
Ty's next set of critters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what's rumors and what's not,'' said Linda
Burner, co-owner of Bears &AMP; More in Glendale, adding that the
Beanies' forced retirement hasn't had much impact on her business,
which remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had 15 ladies waiting for me to open my store this
morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sobolewski speculated that Ty's next set of collectible dolls is
likely to be smaller in size than Beanies (to maximize shelf space)
but will be stitched from a Ty-patented material called Tylon.
</P>
<P>
   And ``it'll definitely be coun terfeit-proof,'' perhaps by way
of holographic label stamp, she said. Burner said Warner is ``going
to the top end of plush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People want very limited things,'' she said. ``I have a
feeling he's going to come out with some thing limited.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, ``Nobody knows,'' Cun ningham said, adding that Warner
isn't likely to abandon one of the most lucrative marketing phenom
ena of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't walk away from a $1 billion-a-year business.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
