<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX     12-23 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Your card is in the mail!
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ This year, I just didn't feel up to it.
</P>
<P>
   The stress. The expectation. The last-minute scrambling. The
nagging fear that you're forgetting someone.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Christmas card list.
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't shopping that stresses me out. I'm a reluctant _
and therefore efficient _ shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Christmas cards have always been my big holiday
production. When I was single, the Christmas card factory cranked
up the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   I devoted night after night to long, heartfelt letters to
faraway friends explaining how much I'd been thinking of them _
even if I had somehow forgotten to write or call them during the
entire preceding year.
</P>
<P>
   And the funny thing was . . . I meant it. Friends stay in your
heart, whether or not you're in constant communication. You may
think of someone once a week, yet manage to get in touch only once
or twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   The list doubled when I married Jim. Then we had the kids . . .
the long, heartfelt letters dwindled to a few heartfelt paragraphs,
or the scrawled _ and habitually broken _ promise: ``Will write
after the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, we were lucky to get heartfelt stamped names in return.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I couldn't resort to form letters, much as I enjoyed
reading them myself. There was this family we dubbed ``The Perfect
Family,'' you see, and the arrival of their annual Christmas
letter, with its enumeration of all their perfections, was much
anticipated. What could we boast of? Getting our daughter
potty-trained at 4?
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas card list became as ponderous as Jacob Marley's
chain, and still, the compulsion persisted. I never felt ready
until that last card had been mailed out, that last envelope
sealed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, I greeted the Christmas cards _ not with the usual
delight, but with a sense of dread: ``Oh, no! Another one I'll have
to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked myself: ``Why not just let it go this year? Other people
do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, so, it came to pass that, Sunday night _ five days before
Christmas Eve _ not a single missive had been mailed.
</P>
<P>
   I looked forlorn at the overstuffed basket of Christmas cards,
the form letters I hadn't yet read. I noticed a real letter in the
basket _ 10 pages! _ from a friend of Jim's we hadn't heard from in
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly apologize for being out of touch for so long,'' she
wrote. ``You know how it goes _ you don't write . . . so you feel
bad . . . so you don't write . . . and you feel WORSE . . . There
were some mitigating circumstances, but I can only say I do value
you and your friendship, and I hope you forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   The mitigating circumstances turned out to be the deaths of her
parents, two years in a row, and she hadn't had the heart to send
out Christmas letters.
</P>
<P>
   No apologies were necessary, of course, but she felt they were.
That's the beauty of Christmas cards _ you can call, write, sneak
into town, re-enter your friends' lives without embarrassment. You
are officially ``in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   I rummaged through the neglected basket and kids' pictures fell
out like confetti. The short notes sparked with affection,
encircling me in their warmth like the lights stringing our
Christmas tree. They told of new babies, new jobs, new homes _
short notes linking friends from year to year, milestone to
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   I took out the boxes of cards and checked off the first name on
the official list: Eric Ash. ``Love you, cousin. Will write after
Christmas.'' Check.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
