<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MALL-SCHOOLS-ART-NYT &LR;      12-23 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-SCHOOLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALL SCHOOL TRIES READING, WRITING AND RETAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT26,27 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ If retail is war, then the students of
Providence Place Academy are the first cadets in the country to
have their boot camp on the field of battle.
</P>
<P>
   The academy, a fledgling alternative public high school oriented
toward business training, may be the first vocational high school
in the nation to be based in a working mall. Classrooms have yet to
be moved to the gigantic new Providence Place mall in the heart of
this reviving city, but the academy's initial 14 students, as
afternoon interns, are seeing their first combat just as the
fighting is fiercest: Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can handle this, they can handle anything,'' Jo-Ann
Ward, the school's curriculum-design specialist, said. ``The rest
will be a walk in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy's administrators have been tested as well in the
debate that has arisen over the school's creation.
</P>
<P>
   With Nordstrom and more than 100 other stores and restaurants,
Providence Place, which opened in August, is a giant deal here,
tangible proof that the tired old industrial city has new life. A
highway traveler who suddenly sees the mall looming above an
overpass might think he had just entered the city of Filene's.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Vincent A. Cianci Jr. provided much of the motivational
force behind the mall and was instrumental in the conception of
Providence Place Academy as well in discussions with city, school
and chamber of commerce officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the school's link to the mall is so unusual it has met with
resistance, said Paul Gounaris, director of the ``school to
career'' programs in the Providence school system. There have been
complaints from school committee members that it will be too
expensive, and criticism from opponents that it will simply funnel
students into dead-end cashier jobs they could have had anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One letter to The Providence Journal argued that the students
would be better served by interning at high-tech companies. Another
said: ``This school is recruiting our most precious assets: our
children. They are training them to serve the `white elite' in
menial jobs such as sales clerks, maids, food servers, and
janitors. Is it just another coincidence that the majority of the
students are poor and minority kids?''
</P>
<P>
   The second letter-writer was partly right. Most of the 14
afternoon interns, all juniors, are black, Asian or Hispanic, and
the program, which began in November, does have them ringing up
sales, stocking shelves, greeting customers and busing tables. (An
hour and a half of their labor is considered their internship, and
if they work longer, which most do, they are paid.)
</P>
<P>
   But the whole thrust of the school, its founders say, is to help
the students parlay their work experiences into learning and into
aspirations that can make the difference between success and
failure in the real world. The idea, they say, is to use the mall
as a great textbook, per a City Council resolution saying that the
mall should function in part as an educational setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many of them will end up working in retail for
most of their lives,'' said Bernard Lough, the school's principal.
``They're using the skills they learn to broaden their horizons.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, among a half dozen students interviewed, there seemed to
be no stampede toward careers at Sak's Fifth Avenue. Rather, they
were full of the revelations of that first venture into the serious
working world: how to tie a tie, how so many things must be done
just perfectly, even how personal tribulations must be kept at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you have troubles in your house, you have to always
have a smile on your face,'' said Ana Hernandez, an intern at
Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   That is the less formal learning that goes on at the academy.
The juniors also take a full academic course load in the mornings
and, perhaps most important, will be linking their work experiences
to the traditional ``three R's'' with requirements like keeping a
workday log that must be grammatically correct.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, Gounaris said, the students will practice
analytical, research and communications skills: figuring out what
their store's market is, for example, researching the potential of
that market and giving an oral presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The academy is to move into its mall classrooms by late spring
and is scheduled to expand to 100 students next fall.
Administrators say there were many more applicants for the program
than there were slots. Its focus on learning by experience fits
into a broader movement intended to shift schools in that
direction, Gounaris said, as well as fitting into a growing
tendency for businesses to enter partnerships with schools. The
academy was created in conjunction with the mall's developers,
Commonwealth Development Group, and with Johnson &AMP; Wales, a
Providence university that includes a well-known culinary college
among its divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Wales is providing classroom space and its students
are serving as mentors. The mall, aside from providing the venues
where the students try their working wings, is giving them a kiosk
at which they can sell their own wares. The students are planning
to publish a children's book called ``Hair-o'' about a little
Jamaican boy whose long dreadlocks have magical powers.
</P>
<P>
   The stores seem happy with their roles as educators, although
there has been little time to teach the finer points of Retail 101
during the Christmas rush, school officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Almeida, manager of the Godiva chocolate store, said that
her intern, Saveth Som, had learned what a Christmas crush was all
about. ``She's either going to love retail after this or hate it,''
Ms. Almeida said. ``There's no gray in retail.''
</P>
<P>
   It is love for Jairo Garcia, the intern in Restoration Hardware.
Still, Garcia said, ``I want to be a pilot and have my own
airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they love or hate their jobs, Providence Place interns
had better not act like those teen-agers who ``hang'' at the mall
merely to wile away their time. The difference between the interns
and their peers, Ms. Ward said, is, ``Ours don't hang.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
