<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 FIVE QUESTIONS FOR jIM STRUPP: THINKING SMALLER ABOUT BEER  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What does Platinum Holdings see in the also-rans of
the beer business?
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, Platinum, a little-known New York investment
company, announced a deal to acquire the brewing operations of the
Genessee Corp. of Rochester. Platinum will add Genessee to its City
Brewing unit, which last July acquired the former G. Heileman
brewery in La Crosse, Wis., which most recently was used to make
Stroh's beer. Terms of the Genessee deal were not disclosed; the
price tag on Heileman was $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a business ever more dominated by Anheuser-Busch, the Miller
Brewing unit of Phillip Morris and Adolph Coors, which together
have 80 percent of the market, Genessee was in fifth place, at
$103.3 million in sales. That put it far behind the No. 4, Pabst
Brewing, which has been buying up other second-tier brands.
Analysts saw little chance Genessee could stay independent.
</P>
<P>
   Other midsized breweries have been crushed between the vice jaws
of the mass market beers on one side and the more expensive imports
and microbrewery products on the other. But Jim Strupp, chairman of
both Platinum and City Brewing, sees an opportunity. After slashing
payrolls at the La Crosse plant, City Brewing introduced two beers
marketed for regional appeal last week, with others in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Strupp took time last week to discuss a strategy that holds
obvious risks. Here are excerpts from the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELLEN ALMER
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why move into beer now, when the giants dominate the market
and many midsized breweries are foundering?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, number one, we don't want to take on the giants. We
think there's an opportunity for a small regional brewery to be
successful, if the costs are very competitive and if we focus on
niche marketing.
</P>
<P>
   We don't try to spread ourselves too thin. We're not going to
compete with Miller or Budweiser; we're not trying to be all things
to all people. Rolling Rock is a success, and a good example of
what we're doing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why would consumers choose your brew over a beer like
Budweiser that might be a bit cheaper or more heavily promoted? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, it's very good beer. We just introduced City
Lager and City Light to rave reviews here in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   We believe people will support a good local beer because it
comes from here. In La Crosse, we've kept the brewery open. These
are premium local beers, made by the people who live here. There's
a big demand.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the bottom-line advantages of limiting yourself to a
regional approach? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Obviously, your distribution costs are much less. Our costs
are one-eighth what Stroh's were.
</P>
<P>
   And your chances are greater for your brewery to be identified
with an area. People are familiar with it (the La Crosse plant)
because it's been here for 140 years, and it's got a long tradition
_ it's part of the heritage in Wisconsin. I'm from La Crosse, I
went to college in Milwaukee, and I'm familiar with the beer in the
area, and the work force _ they're very hard-working people.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe County (N.Y.) is the same. It's a good region, and
Genessee is a great name.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have said you hope to pare down overhead at Genessee, and
step up production from 1.6 million barrels a year to 3 million.
How will you do both at the same time? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You cut out corporate staffs. And you work with the labor
unions in terms of simplifying labor contracts, which is what we
did in La Crosse.
</P>
<P>
   We went from 26 labor classifications to one, so now people can
do more than one job, they have multiple skills, and you have fewer
workers. The employees benefit on the other end: They get gain
sharing, stock appreciation rights, 401(k)'s.
</P>
<P>
   Plus the typical unions knew if we weren't successful, all the
jobs would go away.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where will future growth come from _ acquisitions of more
regional breweries? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Possibly, depending on what's available. Plus we'll do a lot
of contract work for other (beer) companies.
</P>
<P>
   We're also in the water and fruit juice business. And in La
Crosse, we're putting in an ethanol plant _ it comes right out of
the brewery. You just run the corn through some similar processes
as the beer, then you add some distillation, blend it off and sell
it. Our investment costs are one-fifth of what they'd be if we
started from scratch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
