u a BC-OBIT-LANDOWSKI-NYT &LR;      12-23 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LANDOWSKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCEL LANDOWSKI, 84, A FORCE IN CLASSICAL MUSIC IN FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Marcel Landowski, a prominent French composer and
conductor who defended the virtues of classical music against what
he called avant-garde ``over-experimentation,'' died Wednesday in a
Paris hospital. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Landowski was a prolific composer, with 150 works to his name
ranging from symphonies and operas to film soundtracks. But he was
just as well known in France as a promoter of music education in
schools and as the driving force behind the creation of several
regional orchestras and the Orchestre de Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to other renowned postwar conductors, however, he
was never formally associated with a major orchestra. Rather, his
career was built around posts in education and government, most
important among them the job of first director of music, dance and
lyrical arts in the Culture Ministry in the early 1970s, under the
leadership of Andre Malraux.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Pont l'Abbe in Brittany on Feb. 18, 1915, Landowski was
raised in a family of artists. His great-grandfather, Henri
Vieuxtemps, was a famous violinist; his father, Paul, was a
prominent sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, he studied at the National Conservatory of Music
and, while still in his early 20s, began composing.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he became director of the conservatory of music in
Boulogne-sur-Seine in 1960, he was well established as a composer
through a broad range of orchestral and instrumental works, ballets
and operas. In the decades that followed, his pace of composing
slowed as he dedicated more time to administrative posts, among
them director of music at the Comedie Francaise and later cultural
director for the Paris city government.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the late 1970s, Landowski was increasingly
overshadowed by the modernist composer and conductor Pierre Boulez,
who benefited from enormous government support for his Institute of
Research and Coordination of Acoustic Music. And it was apparently
Boulez whom Landowski had in mind when he lamented that
``experimentation has become, for some, the goal of art.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ministries of Foreign Affairs and Culture, in a statement,
described Landowski as ``open to the language of the 20th century
and impervious to the avant-garde, which he challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Landowski is survived by his wife, Jacqueline, a former pianist;
a son, Marc; and two daughters, Anne and Manon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
