<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-TRADE-HNS &LR;      12-23 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
With two shopping days left before Christmas, the Astros on
Thursday executed one of the season's most surprising transactions
by trading their best pitcher, Mike Hampton, and one of their
highest-paid outfielders, Derek Bell, to the New York Mets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In return, the Astros will receive center fielder Roger Cedeno
and righthanded pitcher Octavio Dotel _ who both did what Hampton
and Bell could not do last year, which was to play prominent roles
in a dramatic playoff-game win over the Atlanta Braves _ along with
minor-league lefthander Kyle Kessel.
</P>
<P>
   They also, in conjunction with the recent trade to the Boston
Red Sox of center fielder Carl Everett, will trim almost $16
million in payroll costs for the 2000 season _ which happens to be
roughly the amount of money the Astros say they lost during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks. The trade leaves the Astros without a
lefthanded starting pitcher. It also costs them one of their most
popular players at a time when they need every shred of popularity
to sell seats at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   But with Hampton eligible for free agency after next season and
unwilling to discuss a long-term contract extension, the Astros
felt they had to make a deal _ albeit with no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great respect for what Mike Hampton has done for this
organization, and it doesn't get us anywhere to quarrel about the
decision not to sit down and negotiate an extension,'' said Astros
president Tal Smith. ``That's his right, and it's incumbent on us
as an organization to react and do what is in the best interests of
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said he understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My time in Houston was great,'' he said. ``The fans looked out
for me and backed me all the way. There are no hard feelings, and
there's not one bad thing I can say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy wants to test the market or if a guy is not
comfortable with his situation, it's his right to test it, and in
turn it's the club's right to do what is best for them to ensure
they get something in return. That is the case with both teams'
situations today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, the veteran outfielder who last year suffered through his
least productive season with the Astros, was less charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I had an off year in my career, everybody
turned their back on me.'' he said. ``I'm going to try to turn it
around on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's departure marks the second straight year the team has
lost its most prominent pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, late-season acquisition Randy Johnson left to sign a
lucrative free-agent deal with the Arizona Diamondbacks. The
possibility of losing Hampton, 27, who was 22-4 in 1999, after the
2000 season spurred general manager Gerry Hunsicker to action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the season was over, I expressed an interest to
Mike through his agent that we were interested in sitting down and
exploring a contract extension, and they did not seem real
motivated at the time,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   The parties met about a month ago in Florida, and Hampton's
agent called Hunsicker a day later to say Hampton would play out
his contract and test the free-agent waters for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of hit us between the eyes,'' Hunsicker said. ``I
certainly didn't see it coming. I guess as much as anything, he
forced our hand in this particular situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker then began what he described as ``a number of serious
discussions with a number of clubs,'' culminating in the
announcement of Thursday's trade.
</P>
<P>
   In return for Hampton and Bell, the Astros receive two young
players who had high-profile roles in perhaps the best game of the
1999 season _ the Mets' 15-inning win over the Braves in Game 5 of
the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel was the winning pitcher in that game despite giving up a
run in the 15th, and Cedeno, who stole 66 bases last season, was
the pinch runner who scored from third on Robin Ventura's dramatic
game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of fit, this trade is almost perfect,'' said Astros
manager Larry Dierker. ``Dotel fits as a starter, based on what he
did last year and Cedeno is a real burner to cover more ground in
center field and is an ideal No. 2 hitter behind (Craig) Biggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno said, ``I liked the team in New York, but I think things
happen for a good reason. This is perfect for me. This is an
opportunity, and I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel, a former Texas A&AMP;M basketball player, suffered a
shoulder injury in 1998 and had arthroscopic surgery last January.
He is expected to pitch in the Astros' minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   Shedding almost $16 million in salaries _ $5.75 million for
Hampton, $5 million for Bell and a projected $4.8 million for
Everett, who was eligible for arbitration _ also allows the Astros
some financial wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from a position where we were pushing up against a
limit and, quite frankly, were over where we wanted to be, to a
position where we have flexibility to add somebody before the
season or pick somebody up at the trading deadline,'' Hunsicker
said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a game that is as much dollars and cents as hits and
runs, they also are in position to edge into the black next season,
said Astros executive vice president Bob McClaren.
</P>
<P>
   McClaren said the Astros lost $16.5 million in 1999 on revenues
of $89 million with a player payroll of $56 million. With the move
to Enron Field, McClaren said the Astros expect revenues to total
$120 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to make the Astros a stable, financially secure
organization,'' McClaren said. ``(Owner Drayton McLane Jr.) has
been subsidizing it for several years, and the plan is to get away
from subsidies and go forward. We think a little tweaking now can
save us from having to make bigger moves in years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
