<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KOBE-LADN     12-23 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KOBE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE SILENCES CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ From the NBA's Department of Unassailable Hypotheses
(D.U.H.) comes this news flash: !ital!The Lakers are a better team
with Kobe Bryant!off!.
</P>
<P>
   Seems obvious enough. Hardly seems worth arguing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for much of the past two seasons, critics ranging from
Bryant's own teammates to barstool prophets have posited otherwise:
That Bryant is too undisciplined, too selfish, to make anyone
around him better. That for all his talents, he's more disruptive
to his own team than the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   There was even speculation that Bryant's return to the Lakers
lineup, after a seven-week layoff due to injury, would mess with
the team's chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds rather ludicrous right now.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bryant's return from the injured list Dec. 1, the Lakers
have won 11 out of 12 games. Their scoring is up. Rebounding is up.
Blocked shots and steals, both up.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is averaging 22.8 points, 4.9 rebounds and, yes, 4.2
assists. And as for the presumed delicate balance among the Lakers'
elite triad of Bryant, Shaquille O'Neal and Glen Rice, things are
OK there too. Twice on the Lakers' recent road trip, all three
players scored 20-plus points in the same game. The scoring
emphasis shifts nightly, but all three have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the Lakers are finally a three-star show, not a
three-ring circus?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was concerned about it,'' coach Phil Jackson said
flatly.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Jackson's egalitarian triangle offense has taken care
of some of the ball-distribution issues. But the maturation of the
21-year-old Bryant might be the biggest factor in turning the
Lakers from the disjointed crew of last season into the juggernaut
of the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great,'' said Jackson, ``way more mature than I ever
could have imagined a 21-year-old kid to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the Lakers' recent road trip, when Bryant's occasional
freelancing furrowed Jackson's professorial brow, he showed just
how much he's grown. Against the Minnesota Timberwolves, Bryant
dished out a career-high 12 assists to go with 28 points. He's more
than compensating for occasional fits of wildness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times Kobe will take his own lead out there and I
understand that,'' Jackson said. ``I understand that he's got to be
able to read on his own, and that's very important. That's why
(Ron) Harper's out there with him, because (Harper)'s got a cool
hand, he knows what I want, and he knows how to organize the
offense in ways that are subtle and are purposeful.''
</P>
<P>
   And credit Bryant's seven-week study session for some of the
progress. While Bryant rehabbed a broken right hand, he observed
from the bench, learning the subtleties of the triangle offense,
consulting constantly with the assistant coaches and Jackson. When
he finally re-entered the lineup, the transition was nearly
seamless.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates, I feel pretty comfortable with them,'' Bryant
said. ``I know where they like things and what their timing is,
what their rhythm is. It's just a matter of becoming more of a
general of this offense and setting things up and when to set them
up, and kind of line the defense up and knock them down. That's
just going to come as we play more and more together.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that there weren't enough balls to go around
</P>
<P>
   a concern since Rice arrived via trade in March has subsided for
now. Bryant, O'Neal and Rice are one of the top scoring trios in
the NBA, averaging a combined 67 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three guys have found a way to be successful
offensively,'' guard Derek Fisher said. ``I think you have to give
credit to those three guys, as well as our offensive execution and
sharing the ball out there. We're trying not to dominate the
basketball to any one or two guys and give everybody a chance to
get some touches and some shots. We've been able to do that for the
most part.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some bumps. A one-on-one duel with Toronto's
Vince Carter on Sunday showed Bryant is still prone to playing
showman at times. But Jackson has given Bryant enough freedom to
succeed or fail on his own, with only an occasional benching or
long chat to straighten him out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a style Bryant appreciates, and is benefiting from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil is a different kind of coach, because in the past coaches
might have took me out of the game,'' Bryant said after the victory
at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil said something to me at the airport, he said something to
me at halftime, and that's it. From then on out, if I mess up, I
know that I messed up right there. So I said, `OK, hold on, gotta
step back.' Some guys don't let you learn on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   The tough part for Bryant is those lessons are learned under the
glare of a national spotlight that has followed his every move
since he entered the league as a much-hyped 18-year-old. His
mistakes are often more exaggerated than his successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think people are watching very, very closely. I think
they have been since I've been in the league,'' he said.
``Everybody's watching under a microscope, seeing what's going on
and trying to dissect things, pick things apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is not entirely immune to the criticism, especially when
it comes within the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me at the moment, but then when we sit down and
watch film, it won't be as bad as portrayed. It might be one or two
times when (one-on-one play) will take place, but it wouldn't be as
bad as previously thought. So you just eliminate those couple
times, that's it. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to (tick) people off. I think y'all should know
that by now. I just go out there and do my job. Something goes
wrong, it goes wrong and I can live with that. But for the most
part I'm just out there playing, trying to put W's up in the
column.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, an NBA-best 22-5 record, more than suggests he's
succeeding. The Lakers better with Bryant? Duh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
