<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSCRASH-FOLLOW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SPEED CITED AS POSSIBLE CAUSE IN FATAL TOUR BUS CRASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas) 
 
(Eds.: See optional ending) 
(Eds.: A tilde is needed over first n in Canon City) 
 
By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
and ERIC BERGER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANON CITY, Colo. _ Excessive speed, the driver's health and the
design of the tour bus are being cited as possible critical
elements in the Tuesday crash that killed three Houstonians and
injured dozens.
</P>
<P>
   An official cause of the accident has not been determined, but
officials inspecting the scene and the bus said there were signs
the vehicle carrying 57 passengers from two youth church groups
back from a ski vacation was going too fast down the icy road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it was excessive speed, given the conditions,'' said
R.P. Quintana, an accident reconstruction investigator with the
Colorado State Patrol. Quintana added that extensive testing of the
brake and electronic systems shows ``the bus was mechanically
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither state nor federal investigators would estimate the
vehicle's speed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Medical officials said the 72-year-old bus driver, Robert Gene
Hawthorn, who died in the accident, had severe heart disease and
it's possible he had a heart attack during the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of trauma to his body in the accident was not real
extensive,'' Deputy County Coroner Bill Holt said. ``We're still
weighing all of the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado state troopers, however, say there is no evidence
Hawthorn's medical or physical condition had anything to do with
the accident, and that he died of massive head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   No alcohol or drugs were found in Hawthorn's system, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also noted that several of the injuries and at
least two of the deaths appear to have resulted from the victims
being thrown from the bus when its roof collapsed and split open
after rolling over.
</P>
<P>
   There are no federal standards on tour buses concerning safety
during rollovers, said Larry L. Yohe, an investigator with the
National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 36 motorcoach accidents it investigated between 1968 and
1997, nearly two out of every three fatalities occurred during
rollovers, the government agency reported in a study released in
September. In those rollover accidents, 38 percent of those killed
were ejected from the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has been concerned about motorcoach window strength and
the ejection of passengers during rollovers for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Larger windows, and therefore fewer vertical supports, have
become increasingly popular in the tourism industry. There is no
maximum window size in tour buses in the federal motor vehicle
safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   After the NTSB made recommendations to study the impact of
increasingly larger windows in tour buses on its overall structural
strength in 1973, the Federal Highwaistration said it found
merit in the request but lacked the funds to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   According to its recent report, the NTSB has since urged the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to study the effect
of larger windows on roof strength, and to design requirements that
newly manufactured buses would have to meet in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have recommended to the Department of Transportation to
come up with standards and do a better job of keeping occupants in
their seats'' during tour bus rollover accidents, Yohe said.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB, however, still believes school buses and motorcoaches
are two of the safest ways to travel in the United States. On
average, nine school bus and four motorcoach passengers are killed
in crashes each year, according to the agency. In 1998, more than
41,000 people were killed in U.S. highway crashes in other
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators of Tuesday's accident said they will continue to
look into several factors, including Hawthorn's health.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn and the two other fatalities, Christopher M. Scarberry,
17, and Kevin Matthew Donat, 16, both of Houston, were memorialized
Thursday night at Houston's Windwood Presbyterian Church, which the
teens attended and which co-sponsored the skiing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight passengers remained hospitalized in three Colorado
hospitals Thursday, four in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred on ``Eight-Mile Hill,'' descending the
east side of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is a particularly dangerous stretch of
road,'' said Maj. Ron Adams of the Colorado State Patrol. ``It's
wide, and it has passing lanes built in.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the eastbound bus failed to make a curve to
the right, crossed two lanes of oncoming traffic and tumbled down
an embankment on the far side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   The distance the bus traveled across the highway is a major
reason investigators believe excessive speed was a factor, Quintana
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though no one knows the vehicle's speed, he said, passengers
have told investigators the driver was going so fast as to make
them uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal and five state investigators Thursday tested the
brakes and other equipment on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone on the bus was thrown out as it tumbled and the
roof split open, Quintana said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn and one of the teens killed was ejected, he said, while
the other fatality was trapped inside the bus. The vehicle landed
on one of the teens, whom Quintana did not name.
</P>
<P>
   Yohe said he would not comment on the role the ejections might
have played in the deaths on the bus, which has been transported to
an airport hangar just east of Canon City for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at it and judge for yourself,'' Yohe said, as
he sat in the driver's seat examining the control panel.
</P>
<P>
   The roof has collapsed and been peeled to the side, so half the
seats are exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Seat belts are also not required on tour buses, though some
members of Congress recently called for such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senators, including Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas, recently
called for creation of a federal oversight agency to regulate buses
and trucks. The move followed a tour bus accident in Louisiana on
Mother's Day that killed 22 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   That accident was caused by a driver who, according to later
medical reports, was high on marijuana and dizzy from Benadryl. The
driver was also suffering from congestive heart failure and bad
kidneys. and had gotten out of the hospital less than eight hours
before reporting to work that morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
