<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CZECH-LAUDER-720&AMP;ADD-     12-23 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-LAUDER-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN FIGHTS FOR CONTROL OF PRAGUE TV STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LADKA BAUEROVA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ A vicious legal battle over Eastern
Europe's most successful television station has turned an important
American investor against the government of the Czech Republic and
now threatens to taint the country's reputation in the business
world.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Lauder, an heir to the Estee Lauder cosmetics giant, has
begun an arbitration case in which he contends that the Czech
authorities failed to protect his investment in the highly
profitable TV Nova, violating a 1991 treaty on mutual investment
protection. In full-page newspaper advertisements, Lauder has
warned investors against entering the Czech market.
</P>
<P>
   Lauder has requested compensation for lost profit and for the
calamitous devaluation of shares in his company, CME, whose stock
has fallen to less than $2 a share from $30 in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He says the loss is a result of unfair treatment by Czech
authorities. If the appointed arbitrators fail to negotiate a
settlement by mid-2000, the parties are expected to go to court.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has alarmed the Czech government, which wants to
join the European Union and has only recently become a full member
of NATO. With its economy stagnating, the Czech Republic depends
heavily on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We invested $60 million to $80 million into this country
because we believed the contracts would be upheld. I was extremely
shocked when it didn't happen,'' Lauder said in a recent telephone
interview. ``Our station was hijacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The hijacker, Lauder says, is Vladimir Zelezny, the influential
general director of TV Nova. Zelezny maintains close relations with
Czech political circles. He has been seen associating with the
country's political leaders, including Prime Minister Milos Zeman
and the speaker of the house, Vaclav Klaus. With a 50 percent
market share, TV Nova is by far the most powerful opinion maker in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Zelezny, the majority shareholder of the license-holding
company, severed all ties with Lauder's service company after he
was fired for suspected fraud and mismanagement. Zelezny says he is
innocent of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech authorities, Lauder says, have been either ignoring
his appeals or siding with Zelezny. So when the prime minister
visited the United States last month, he was welcomed by Lauder's
newspaper ads that were headlined ``Think Twice Before You Invest
in the Czech Republic.'' The text told readers that the Czech
Republic abused foreign investors and asserted that ``Czech
business, regulatory and legal practices fall woefully short of
international standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying for several months to talk to them about this
issue and they wouldn't speak to me,'' Lauder said in describing
his efforts to negotiate with the Czech officials. ``I had no other
way but to put an ad in the papers and warn other investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has become more serious than the government had
expected. Last month, the Czech minister of foreign affairs, Jan
Kavan, discussed the situation with the U.S. secretary of state,
Madeleine Albright, who warned against its possible negative effect
on American investor trust.
</P>
<P>
   Several influential members of Congress in Washington have
requested hearings into the TV Nova case and written to the Czech
prime minister, expressing their concern.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech government is trying to find a way to avert a court
battle with Lauder, who said he was willing to drop the case in
exchange for regaining TV Nova or another Czech television license.
</P>
<P>
   The finance minister has been mediating talks about the possible
sale of the other Czech commercial TV station, called TV Prima, to
Lauder. So far the negotiations have made little progress.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign investors have expressed concern about the effect
of the case on the investment reputation of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If CME wins the arbitration and continues to have difficulties
in the Czech court system, almost undoubtedly investors will
carefully consider that fact,'' said Michael Sonenshine, a senior
analyst at ING Barings in London.
</P>
<P>
   He said the dispute highlighted shortcomings in the Czech legal
and regulatory environment. ``There are gaping holes in the law,
the court process takes an incredibly long time, and laws are
vaguely worded, which makes their interpretation difficult,''
Sonenshine said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trouble began last April when Lauder's company fired
Zelezny, then the general director of its Czech subsidiary, saying
he had defrauded and mismanaged the business. Zelezny fired right
back.
</P>
<P>
   As a majority shareholder of CET 21, the company that owns the
broadcasting license, he threatened to sever all cooperation with
Lauder's company and find another service provider. He fulfilled
that threat in August, defying Lauder's claim that the relationship
between CET 21 and Lauder's company was exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Practically overnight, Zelezny cut off Lauder's company from
Czech advertising revenue, moved with his new business partners to
empty film studios on the outskirts of Prague, and began
broadcasting from there.
</P>
<P>
   None of the evidence Lauder's company has so far presented to
courts and police has stopped Zelezny from continuing to broadcast
and collect TV Nova's advertising revenue. He has refused to obey a
preliminary order issued on Nov. 10 by the International
Arbitration Tribunal in Stockholm, which instructed him to break
with all his current business partners and restore TV Nova's
previous relationship with Lauder's company until a final decision
is reached.
</P>
<P>
   For Lauder's company, the loss of TV Nova has come at the worst
possible time. Its other TV stations in Slovenia, Slovakia, Ukraine
and Romania are all losing money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the company withdrew from Germany after failing to
capture any significant part of the market. The company also sold
its stake in the Polish station TVN after a dispute with the local
partner, and failed to win a TV license in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his new office overlooking Prague's film studios,
Zelezny was unapologetic in a recent interview. He called Lauder an
arrogant figure who thought he could buy everything with his money.
``But not this time,'' he said, shaking his head vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to cover up for his poor business skills by
blaming the Czech Republic,'' said Zelezny. ``It's a classic case
where an American businessman gets in trouble and then says, `You
know, it's the locals; it's a banana republic where law doesn't
mean anything.' But if you can't do business, don't blame others
for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
