<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-MARKETSHARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS OFFICIAL GIVES UPBEAT REVIEW OF YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the hottest auto market on record winds to a close, a General
Motors executive gave an upbeat assessment of 1999 Thursday, a year
in which his company has earned record profits even as its market
share has declined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G. Richard Wagoner, president of GM, cited as successes the
company's strong profits, peaceful labor relations, new Internet
business initiatives, increased unit sales and revised models like
the Cadillac DeVille, Pontiac Bonneville, Chevrolet Impala and its
Chevy Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks. ``On balance, we feel
like 1999 was a pretty doggone good year here at General Motors,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street analysts have had growing concerns about the GM
slide in market share. While the company's share has slowly
declined for decades it hit record lows for the last two months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In October, the GM market share was 28 percent, a postwar low
for a nonstrike period. By November, its share sank to 27.1
percent. At its peak in 1962, GM sold 51 percent of the nation's
cars and trucks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Wagoner said the November result was not part of the larger
trend. ``We had a lousy month,'' he said, adding that GM had failed
to quickly match competitors' rebates in certain segments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The market share declines in the first 10 months of the year
came about for a different reason, he said: The company could not
build cars fast enough to meet the exceptionally high consumer
demand during this record sales year. Other large automakers,
including Ford, have also watched their market shares shrink. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner said GM's November results were a temporary setback. ``I
don't think we had an 11-month problem,'' he said. ``We performed
poorly in November, and that caused appropriate reflection. Is it
appropriate to panic based on November? The answer is no.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some Wall Street analysts disputed his interpretation. ``I'm
not sure that November was an aberration,'' David B. Healy, an auto
analyst at Burnham Securities, said. ``I don't really buy the idea
that there was a lack of availability all year long.'' Healy
attributed the GM market share declines to ``the boring product
line.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM had set an internal goal early this year of selling 30 to 32
percent of the cars and trucks in the United States, based on an
expected total market of 15.5 million vehicles, said Steven J.
Harris, GM's vice president for communications. But this year,
automakers are expected to sell more than 17 million vehicles in
the United States. While GM has sold 750,000 more cars and trucks
this year than last year, its percentage of industry sales has only
matched last year's, when a strike shuttered the company for two
months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wagoner seemed more willing than Harry J. Pearce, the GM
vice chairman, to excuse the company's market share declines. Both
men are contenders to replace John F. Smith Jr., the chairman and
chief executive, who is expected to retire soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the November sales were reported, Pearce blamed senior
management for the results, saying, ``We have absolutely not
delivered on our commitment on market share, and that is simply
unacceptable.'' Pearce was unavailable for comment Thursday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner also said Thursday that GM was ``not crazy about'' a
decision by a South Korean government commission to hold an auction
for the auto assets of the Daewoo group. GM has spent nearly two
years negotiating to buy parts of the Korean company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the auction will lead us to pay more than it is
worth,'' Wagoner said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also said GM was considering whether to exercise its option
to buy the portion of Saab that it did not already own. ``We have
the option until the end of January and I don't know if we'll get a
decision reached before then or not,'' he said. He said GM was not
in acquisition talks with any other European automakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
