</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SEEKING JUSTICE IN PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Dec. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half months after the military coup in Pakistan, the
ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, is about to go on trial on
charges of conspiracy, kidnapping and waging war against the state.
If convicted, he could be hanged. But in a real sense, it is
Pakistan that is now on trial. Gen. Pervez Musharraf and the other
military rulers behind the coup have an obligation to ensure that
any former government officials charged with crimes have full
rights to defend themselves. So far the government's performance
has fallen short, particularly in the case of one important former
minister kidnapped by the army last week.
</P>
<P>
   The central case against Sharif and his close aides is that they
tried to dismiss Musharraf as army chief of staff, barring his
plane from landing in Karachi as it was returning from overseas.
The general says that only when he realized his life was in danger
did he carry out the coup. Sharif's lawyers contend that he
dismissed Musharraf to head off a coup.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Pakistan's lively press has been able to cover the
trial preliminaries, reporting on Sharif's arguments and his
complaints about being kept in solitary confinement. The latest
development is a charge that the flight recording system on the
plane supposedly rerouted on Sharif's orders has been erased,
raising suspicions that it was tampered with to destroy evidence
clearing the former prime minister of involvement. It is to the
coup leaders' credit that they have at least allowed these
disclosures to be aired. But nothing can justify the coup. However
unpopular he became, Sharif was Pakistan's duly elected leader. It
would be a grievous mistake to sentence him to death, no matter
what the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In one separate matter, the military rulers' performance has
been ominous. Last week soldiers picked up the former information
minister, Mushahid Hussain, who was under house arrest after the
coup. There is no word on where he is being kept, and the family
fears that he could be beaten or tortured to make him testify
against Sharif. According to some Pakistani press reports, Hussain
has been cleared of criminal activity by General Musharraf's
tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hussain joined the government, he was a prominent and
outspoken journalist. As a critic of the Taliban and other radicals
in Afghanistan he had many enemies, and his supporters say the
military leaders fear that he will mobilize the public against them
if he is released. Since no charge has been lodged against him, he
should be released immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991223.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DAVIES-ABRIDGED-     12-23 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-ABRIDGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PATON DAVIES, 91, DIPLOMAT WHO RAN AFOUL OF MCCARTHY OVER
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: A full-length version, OBIT-DAVIES, has also been filed)  
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Paton Davies, a leading diplomat who was among the ``old
China hands'' driven from the State Department after Sen. Joseph
McCarthy questioned their loyalty in the 1950s, died Thursday at
his home in Asheville, N.C. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and about a dozen of the country's most eminent China
scholars and diplomats found themselves accused of having ``lost
China'' after Mao Tse-tung's Communist forces defeated Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalists in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Among those accused of ``selling out'' Chiang were several
diplomats, including Oliver Edmund Clubb, John Carter Vincent and
John Stewart Service, and academics like Owen Lattimore and John
King Fairbank.
</P>
<P>
   But Davies may be one of the most poignant examples of those
whose careers were blighted in the hunt for scapegoats. He was a
decorated hero of World War II destined, according to his
superiors, for high rank in the State Department. He also was
regarded as a tough foe of Stalinism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Nov. 5, 1954, Secretary of State John Foster Dulles
dismissed him from the Foreign Service, maintaining that Davies had
``demonstrated a lack of judgment, discretion and reliability.''
</P>
<P>
   In hearings that had lasted for years, several of the China
hands, including Davies, Service and Vincent, were accused by Gen.
Patrick J. Hurley, Franklin D. Roosevelt's special envoy and then
ambassador to China (1944-45), of sabotaging his efforts to prevent
the collapse of the Nationalist government.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the case against Davies arose from his role in the
Tawny Pipit Affair. Tawny pipit was the code name for a covert
intelligence-gathering operation contemplated after the fall of the
Chinese Nationalist government in 1949. After the Communists took
over, Davies was delegated by George Kennan, director of policy
planning in the State Department, to attend a meeting on ways to
obtain intelligence from China. Davies suggested that approaches be
made to half a dozen Americans friendly with the Chinese Communist
leaders, with an eye toward enlisting them as double agents. The
idea was never pursued, but in 1952 Davies' critics contended that
he had been trying to infiltrate the U.S. intelligence network with
Communist sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by a Senate subcommittee, Davies parried
questions while adhering to his understanding that anything
involving the CIA had to be kept secret. Later, subcommittee
members tried to charge Davies with perjury on the basis of his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   John Paton Davies Jr. was born in China _ in Kiating, Sichuan
province, on April 6, 1908. His parents were Baptist missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years at the University of Wisconsin, another at
Yenching University outside Beijing and a fourth at Columbia, from
which he graduated in 1931. He joined the Foreign Service and
returned to China the following year. He spent the next decade
observing the advance of the Japanese armies into China and
eventually evacuating U.S. civilians.
</P>
<P>
   When Japan attacked Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, Davies was in
Washington, on the State Department's China desk. He seized an
opportunity to join the staff of Gen. Joseph Stilwell, who had just
been named commander of the China-Burma-India theater. Stilwell's
forces suffered defeat in Burma; after leading a painful retreat,
Stilwell was given responsibility for organizing the defense of
India and China. Davies served as his chief diplomatic aide,
political adviser and interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, 1943, Davies was on a C-46 transport flying to China
from India when an engine failed and all aboard were ordered to
jump. Eric Sevareid, who was aboard as a radio correspondent,
recounted that none of the 17 passengers had ever used a parachute.
Davies, as the senior official, jumped first. It took a month for
the group to walk out of the jungle, and according to Sevareid it
was Davies who rallied them when it seemed impossible to go on.
Davies received the Medal of Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In summer 1944, an observation group was sent to the Communist
headquarters at Yenan after prodding by Davies and the U.S. Army.
The mission confirmed reports of Communist strength in the north.
Hurley now began to denounce Davies and his colleagues, saying
their criticism of the Nationalists was meant to undermine his
attempt to unify the various Chinese military forces against the
Japanese. Davies was relieved to obtain a transfer to the U.S.
Embassy in Moscow in January 1945.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1945 the Japanese surrendered, and the opposing
Chinese armies raced to take over their sectors in a civil war.
Hurley resigned as ambassador in November 1945, blaming the China
hands, including Davies, for the failure of his mission.
</P>
<P>
   From 1947 to 1951, Davies served on the State Department's
policy planning staff, under Kennan.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to Germany in 1951, Davies was called home in the next
year to testify about the Tawny Pipit Affair. He was cleared of a
Senate subcommittee's perjury charge but was transferred to Lima,
Peru, where he served as charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
   Still McCarthy hammered away at him, and in late 1954, a special
security board ruled that while Davies' loyalty could not be
questioned, his employment was ``not clearly consistent with the
interests of the national security.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to his family in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   In India in 1942, he had married Patricia Grady, a correspondent
for The Washington Post. She survives, as do their seven children:
Sasha, of White Plains, N.Y.; Tiki, of Washington; John G., of
Baton Rouge, Louisiana; Susan, of Chatham, N.Y.; Jennifer, of
Seattle; Deborah, of London, and Megan, of New Orleans. Also
surviving are a brother, Donald, of State College, Pa., and 11
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Davies set up a shop in Lima to design and make furniture. He
also wrote a weekly column for a local newspaper, and worked his
writings into a book published in 1964, ``Foreign and Other
Affairs.'' In it he took a tough view of American policy in Latin
America, suggesting that Washington show more willingness to
support strong governments.
</P>
<P>
   About this time Davies returned to Washington. Friends began a
quiet effort to obtain his official rehabilitation, but it was not
until 1969 that he was granted a government security clearance to
work on a research project on Latin America at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and his family then lived for several years in Malaga,
Spain. He and his wife settled in Asheville, N.C., when their
children began attending college. His second book, ``Dragon by the
Tail'' (1972), was both a memoir and a history of Chinese-American
relations from 1931 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Davies, along with Fairbank and Service, was invited to
testify before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Its
chairman, William Fulbright, welcomed them by saying: ``It is a
very strange turn of fate that you gentlemen, who reported honestly
about conditions, were so persecuted because you were honest about
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
