<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ASTHMA-AZR &LR;      12-23 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE THINK THEY'RE ON TRACK OF ANSWER TO ASTHMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Walk into James and Nancy Lee's research lab at the Mayo Clinic
in Scottsdale and you'll see mice, lots of mice.
</P>
<P>
   What you won't see is what makes these mice special: they lack a
gene that's believed to trigger asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wild-type mice,'' James said, ``except for the gene we
believe is important to asthma has been deleted.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one gene of the 20 to 50 suspected to play a role in
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   But if the one gene knocked out in the tan, red-eyed mice is the
key to asthma, the Lees' work could lead to relief for the nation's
17 million asthma sufferers, includ ing the 316,00 who live in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Nancy Lee chants with her fists in the air, ``Asthma
vaccine, asthma vaccine!''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is less optimistic about a vaccine, although he main
tains that all the genetic research going on will lead to
treatments tailored to each patient within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest changes in the next five years will be in
diagnosis,'' he said. ``We'll be able to do genetic testing in the
future when people come into the emergency room with an asthma
attack so they get targeted treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many things in medicine, asthma is an extremely complex
condition. And not all asthma is created equal. Various forms
affect infants, children and adults, and those patients all respond
differently to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking the one gene that's common to all sufferers may be the
key to treatment. The debate is over which gene that is.
</P>
<P>
   The Lees believe the answer is the gene that controls immunoglob
ulin E, or IgE, the antibody that stimulates allergic responses
that lead to chronic airway inflamma tion. It's that inflammation
that constricts the lungs and makes it hard to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Although other researchers are focusing on other genes, the
Lees' work has fans at the University of Arizona College of
Medicine, the Arizona Asthma and Allergy Insti tute and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate answer is in the airway inflammation,'' said the
insti tute's Dr. William Morgan, who also is an associate professor
for the University of Arizona Health Sci ences Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that IgE process gets going, there's a whole lot of media
tors and chemical processes that get going. Ultimately, it's this
IgE response that's the root of all evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Using their backgrounds in mo lecular biology and genetics, the
Lees succeeded in genetically engi neering what they call IgE mice.
They also are able to clone the mice in their lab, which has
received funding from the Arizona Lung Association, the National
Institutes of Health, private foundations and pharmaceutical
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that there's a genetic aspect to
asthma. That's magnified by asthma suffer ers ``self-selecting''
for the ailment by moving to places such as Arizona, for example,
to improve their condition. Asthma sufferers often meet other
asthmatics and end up having children.
</P>
<P>
   The Lees both have asthma, but they married 12 years ago back
East and moved in 1994 to Arizona, where they set up a result lab
at the Mayo Clinic to study asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years ago, the Lees had twins. Their daughter shows
no signs of the ailment, but their son already has a asthmalike
condition in infants known as ``bronchiolitis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lees say males are more susceptible than females to asthma
and that women with asthma tend to pass it on to their sons more
often.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are saddened that their son shares their
ailment, but it gives added urgency to their work and that of their
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid growing up, they didn't do much for you,''
Nancy said. ``No child should have to suffer from asthma in the
same way today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
