<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINETEEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NUMBER 19, THE PARTY IS OVER
 BY MARK JONATHAN DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am the number 19, and my days are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the news, you've seen the future, you've checked
your calendar. The countdown is on, and yours truly, Nineteen, is
being eighty-sixed.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know me best for my recent work in the upper right
hand corner of your checks. It was back in the aughts when that
deal was first inked, thanks to some lazy banker who figured my
full-time position would be a colossal time saver. That move proved
to be the job of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days. I was a prime number in my prime, the most
popular teen in town. 1941, 1963, 1984 . . . the suffix may have
changed each year, but the prefix was set in stone. You could find
me everywhere, on newspapers, year books, tax forms and driver's li
censes. Decade after decade, I was the duke of double digits.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the times they are a-changin', and me a-with 'em. As
the year 2000 approaches, it's dawned upon me that time is no
longer on my side.
</P>
<P>
   I guess all good things must come to an end. Sure, I had a
pretty good run, from 1900 to 1999. With each decade, the 10s would
climb, the ones with them. Some of those years I shared with
perfect strang ers: 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, and that do-nothing 0.
Other years _ well, they were special.
</P>
<P>
   1919 was my favorite, a once-in-a-lifetime tribute that let me
be me. But the 12-month celebration ended with a huge irony when
1920 ar rived; talk about foreshadowing. It wasn't until 1991, when
I had a chance to reflect, that I realized my time was almost up.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as my century of service comes to a close, I bid a fond
fare well to my starring role on the ep ochal scroll. I'd like to
take a second to thank 1 and 9 for their tireless teamwork, for
standing to gether and making me what I am (or, as of 1/1/2000,
was) today.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the single digits are the lucky ones. Most of the
memorable things in life come in smaller quan tities: nine planets,
seven seas, five golden rings. Three guys go into a bar, not 19.
Or, just add a few zeroes, and you're a star with 200 Motels,
10,000 Maniacs and 500,000 Elvis Presley Fans Can't Be Wrong. But
nothing comes in 19,000.
</P>
<P>
   No, I never got picked to be in any cool numerical catch
phrases, like 23-skidoo or Catch-22. I would have liked to have
been remembered as the Magnificent 19, or the Fab Nineteen, or even
the Dirty Nine teen. I never had the cachet of 16 candles, 45 rpm
or Heinz 57. And no one got their kicks on Route 19.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, I wasn't un lucky enough to be unlucky 13,
or Area 51 or Turk 182. I'm proud that Johnny Unitas and Greg ``The
Bull'' Luzinski wore me on their uniforms. And I'm eternally
grateful to Paul Hardcastle's n-n-n-n-nice musical tribute in '85
(or 1985 as I should say).
</P>
<P>
   But as time goes by, I'll be counted out. No one will write me;
no more hot dates. So long, teenage.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to me? Oh, I'll be around. Maybe we'll bump
into each other now and again . . . on a box of Product Me cereal
or, hey, in the echoes of a Steely Dan song. You might take Flight
19, rent Apartment 19, or perhaps pick me on a lottery ticket (go
for it, I'm feelin' lucky!). Most cities have a 19th Street, some
cities have a 19th Arrondissement. And there's always A.D. 19000 _
but don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'll make my regular monthly visits, plus I'll be
back for a yearlong stay in less than a score. Until then . . . try
to miss me, will ya?
</P>
<P>
   Before I turn over the 1900s, I have a few words for my replace
ment, numero 20:
</P>
<P>
   I've seen you looming for the last 100 years, crowding your way
into my spotlight all century long . . . all 20th century long,
that is! (Why is it that MY 100 years are known as YOUR century?)
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Flight Rock, 20 Ques tions, 20,000 Leagues Under The Sea,
20 this, 20th that _ nag, nag, nag. The sight of Hugh Downs will
forever make me cringe.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just in the past few years, the ATM has single-handedly
made you the dominating denomination! And I don't even want to talk
about this whole ``Y2K'' thing; I mean, you must be paying your
publicist a fortune!
</P>
<P>
   And now, the brand new millen nium is here, rubbing you in my
face. They're already printing you on the checks. But don't get too
comfy, 20. The clock never stops ticking, and before you know it,
you'll be dealt 21.
</P>
<P>
   So have fun leading the Napo leonic calendar into the future,
but don't make the same mistake I did. One-hundred years become
history quicker than you think, so live it up while you can.
Cherish the time you're here, and treasure those date books,
postmarks and wonderful, wonderful checks. Time will march on, but
even if you're having a good time, don't let it fly.
</P>
<P>
   I, 19, look back sadly, and regret that I may have taken this
fleeting life for granted. I should have sa vored every moment. But
now that I think of it, I guess hindsight is 20 _ aw, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   (Nineteen is a first-time writer. His new book, Why 2K?, won't
be in stores until next year, much to his chagrin.)
Raised in Phoenix, essayist Mark Jonathan Davis is the founder
ofideatownusa.com, a Los Angeles-based creative content con sulting
service that is already Y3K compli ant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
