<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY BRINGS NICE THOUGHTS ABOUT BAD TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The spirit of the season moves me toward
benevolence, or maybe I've just been weakened by the odor from
Bourbon Street on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   There's something rotten in the Big Easy, and the smell goes
beyond both football teams playing here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no peace on North Texas earth, not with the
Dallas Cowboys being so weak and wobbly. Goodwill toward mankind
does not currently apply to the Chan Gaileys or the Troy Aikmans.
</P>
<P>
   O' come all ye faithful _ except when the Cowboys are 7-7 there
can be no heaven. Or faithful followers either.
</P>
<P>
   But with the mood so ugly back home, why allow football to
totally tarnish such a joyous time of year? Since it's Christmas
Eve, isn't there something good to be said about the Cowboys, at
least temporarily?
</P>
<P>
   Now that you mentioned it, yes, there is. In fact, I just
happened to have made a list, checked it twice, and what follows is
an attempt to be nice.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Cowboys fan, climb down from your machine-gun nest
long enough to be thankful for these gifts:
</P>
<P>
   _ No unlawful flight to avoid prosecution for murder conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   _ No breaking-and-entering arrest for lusting after thy
neighbor. The emphasis here is on no arrests.
</P>
<P>
   _ No failed drug tests, no drug busts, no topless lizards
telling the cops wild stories, no fur coats in the court house, no
90 mph Mercedes wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   _ No amount of expense spared for the guidance and counseling
services of Calvin Hill in the locker room. Hill has raised the
do-right awareness level on what formerly was America's Most Wanted
Team.
</P>
<P>
   _ No Daniel Snyder. Finally, there's an NFL owner who makes us
appreciate Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   _ No problems with Alonzo Spellman, despite rip-jobs from here
when the Cowboys signed him. There was a very sordid past in
Chicago, but since his arrival at Valley Ranch, Spellman has been a
good citizen and good player.
</P>
<P>
   _ No on-the-field attacks on a referee, although Kevin Smith had
a case for one after the bogus pass interference in Sunday's game
against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   _ No more Gunsmoke. Go ahead, barbecue Gailey. Even fire him.
But Chan is a football professional who replaced a national joke.
</P>
<P>
   _ No Randy Moss, but Greg Ellis instead. Moss is a player, and a
touchdown maker. Just the kind of receiver the Cowboys need. But
he's still got punk written all over him. Ellis, as it turned out,
is also a player. And nothing but class.
</P>
<P>
   _ No embarrassing draft busts in two years. Take a bow, Larry
Lacewell. More than any other factor, the Cowboys' current problems
can be directly traced to five previous years of draft disasters.
</P>
<P>
   _ No good news in the NFL on national TV ratings. The league
crowed back in October when ratings surprisingly soared. But since
then, all networks have experienced dramatic plunges. This proves
two things. (1) The fans know bad football when they see it, so
they don't see it as often. (2) The NFL needs the Cowboys to be
good, because after all these years they remain the king of
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   _ No negative goodbyes for Michael Irvin. If his career is
finished, Michael goes out a hero instead of just another name on
the police blotter. Everybody will remember this as a season when
the Cowboys missed him dearly.
</P>
<P>
   No valid excuse from Gailey or anyone else at Valley Ranch,
about the absence of Michael. Last summer in Wichita Falls, Irvin
wasn't even being considered a major contributor to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probably no more Indy Colts on future schedules for at least
three years. This is the team everyone will be wanting to dodge,
but particularly the Cowboys. The Colts, with their young Triplets,
provide a constant reminder of faded glory days at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I've become exhausted with being nice. It was a hard job,
but on Christmas Eve it seemed so appropriate. And truthfully, it
may have been the last chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys play the 2-12 Saints here Friday. They close the
regular season with the 7-7 Giants at Texas Stadium next week. A
loss in one of these games _ and after what was on display against
the Jets, it's certainly possible _ will cause a Rambo version of
the Grinch to descend upon Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   It could become real ugly back home. So just in case this is the
final opportunity, I will say it now. Merry Christmas/Happy
Holidays. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
