<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS' HAND IS FORCED, SO METS DEALT AN ACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the winter meetings in Anaheim, Calif., less than
two weeks ago, the Houston Astros' general manager said his team
was not one of the clubs the New York Mets were badgering in their
efforts to find a front-line starting pitcher or a good-hitting
outfielder. ``They're not going this way,'' Gerry Hunsicker said.
``There's no match.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, the Mets and the Astros made it a match. The Mets
traded Roger Cedeno, the base-stealing outfielder who blossomed
last season, and Octavio Dotel, the young pitcher loaded with
promise, and a minor league pitcher, Kyle Kessel, for Mike Hampton,
who with 22 victories was the National League's No. 1 winner last
season, and Derek Bell, a run-producing outfielder, who suffered
through the least productive season of his career in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, who has not been
outworked by any of his peers the past two off-seasons, pulled off
the deal as neatly as his two middle infielders execute a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this transaction certainly catapults us beyond the
team that won 97 games last year,'' Phillips said, his enthusiasm
for the deal and the team's prospects clearly showing through the
telephone on a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often that you get the opportunity to acquire a No.
1-type starting pitcher,'' he added. ``When you get that
opportunity you have to be aggressive and try to bring him in. We
worked hard the last few days to get him. We've waited for this
opportunity for a long time to acquire a starting pitcher of
Hampton's ilk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were able to acquire Hampton because he had recently
told the Astros that he planned to be a free agent after next
season. That status, of course, is what creates the risk for the
Mets in giving up two good young players to acquire him.
</P>
<P>
   The trade also answered one question. No, the Mets will not
renew their pursuit of Ken Griffey Jr. Cedeno and Dotel were two of
the ingredients the Mariners were considering for Griffey until he
said he would not approve a trade to the Mets. Cedeno and Dotel
were two players everyone sought from the Mets, and now the Astros
have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One absolute in the deal,'' Hunsicker said, ``was I get a
young starting pitcher back who could go into our starting
rotation. Then it was who had the best overall value for us. I
wasn't focused on the outfield, but Cedeno offered a rather
hard-to-find package.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, 27, only three years older than Dotel, had a 22-4
record last year with a 2.90 earned run average, the third best in
the National League. He reeled off 11 consecutive victories leading
to No. 20, and he suffered only one loss after June 24, compiling a
13-1 record in his last 18 starts. He finished second to Randy
Johnson in the voting for the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one competitive nasty pitcher,'' Bobby Valentine, the
Mets' manager, said on the conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who has a $5.75 million salary next season, said it was
premature for him to think about a contract extension with the
Mets. But he said he was excited about the idea of playing for them
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a very exciting city,'' said Hampton, who was born
in Brooksville, Fla. ``I'm from a very small town, a country town,
but I've been able to get out and explore and do some things
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said he was not scared by the thought of playing at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting place to play,'' he said. ``The fans are
really into the game and it gets you pumped up. I go out with an
intensity and New York will probably bring it out in me more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
