<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRIVE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Cowboys' path to playoffs is block by block (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Songs have been written about less emotion than
the roller coaster the Cowboys have endured this week.
</P>
<P>
   Defeat and despair after Sunday's shocking 22-21 loss to the New
York Jets were replaced by renewed hope and optimism when the NFL
announced Tuesday that the Cowboys indeed control their own playoff
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league's intricate tiebreaker system, all the
Cowboys (7-7) need to do to guarantee a playoff spot is win their
final two games, starting with a Christmas Eve battle at the
Superdome against the Saints (2-12).
</P>
<P>
   So never mind that the Cowboys have lost six consecutive road
games and four of their seven losses have come to teams with losing
records. There's no way they will leave the Big Easy, home of sweet
jazz and jumping zydeco, singing the blues, again.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got to go play our best,'' Cowboys running back
Emmitt Smith said. ``If we don't, we'll be right back here on
Monday, singing the same old song with the same old nasty tune.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' emotions likely surged even more when they learned
that the woeful Saints, who have lost five consecutive games and 11
of the past 12, were planning to start fourth-stringer Jake
Delhomme at quarterback, making the first building block in their
playoff pyramid seemingly that much easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also must conclude the season with a victory against
the New York Giants Jan. 2 at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints are first. And not only has Delhomme, a veteran of
NFL Europe, not thrown a pass in the league before, he has yet to
take a snap from an NFL center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been beaten by all kinds of quarterbacks and all kinds
of teams that we're supposed to be better than,'' Smith cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   To scale the pyramid to the playoffs by beating the Saints and
stringing together back-to-back wins with a victory against the
Giants _ and notch their first two-game winning streak since
opening the season 3-0 _ Cowboys coach Chan Gailey must rely on
building blocks that the team has rarely shown in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys must depart from their penalty-plagued
ways. The Cowboys lead the league in penalties and penalty yards.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Cowboys, who rank 24th in the league in third-down
conversions, must find a way to consistently move the chains. They
have converted on just 33 percent of third downs this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys must not only make more big plays, but they must be
able to do it at crucial times, like in the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also can't let the Saints or Giants cripple their
passing game by taking go-to wide receiver Raghib Ismail away.
Tight end David LaFleur, wide receivers Chris Brazzell and Jason
Tucker and cornerback/receiver Deion Sanders must become consistent
factors. Ismail is the only wide receiver to score a touchdown this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to execute,'' Gailey said. ``Doing all that is what I
mean by execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no gimmes in the NFL. Any time you don't play well
you can lose. You better be ready to play or you will get beat,
especially if you are not a dominant team. You can't play subpar
and expect to win. We should know that as much as anybody. If we
don't, then we are not smart.''
</P>
<P>
   And specifically against the Saints, the Cowboys' defense must
return to the foundation that has made them one of the league's top
units _ stopping the run and getting consistent pressure on the
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the Saints will try to use running back Ricky Williams,
the 1998 Heisman Trophy winner from Texas, to take some of the
pressure off of Delhomme. So controlling Williams will be the key.
Once that's done, the Cowboys will look to harass Delhomme
unmercifully into making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, however, are taking nothing for granted against the
Saints. And not just because of the frustrations they've endured so
far in 1999. The Cowboys have vivid memories of a horrifying trip
to New Orleans last season, when the Saints blitzed a heavily
favored Cowboys team into submission in a 22-3 shellacking. Smith
was held to just 6 yards on 15 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Saints' defense is not as stout as it was a year
ago _ New Orleans has allowed at least 30 points in each of its
past five games _ the Cowboys are wary and have prepared all week
for a similar onslaught of blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does not have to be reminded to anybody,'' quarterback
Troy Aikman said. ``Those who were on the football team last year
know what happened when we went there and how disappointing that
was for us. Right now, we know what's in front of us. If we win the
next two ballgames we're in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoff pyramid runs through the Saints. Can the Cowboys
make the climb?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with the energy our team had in practice
this week. I thought it would be a tougher road back,'' Gailey
said. ``But once the news came in that if we win we are in, then it
was like everyone's energy level went up a notch.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
