<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      12-23 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW ORLEANS _ When the Dallas Cowboys face the New Orleans Saints
today, it will be with a bit of a hangover. It wasn't acquired on
Bourbon Street. This is of the five-day variety, a gift from the
New York Jets on Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think there is some hangover effect,'' Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey said. ``And I think any time you have a tough loss, I think
there always is. To be honest with you, if there is not some
hangover effect, you don't have the right people to a certain
degree anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won't soon forget the Jets game. After Washington
and the New York Giants lost Sunday, the Cowboys knew by kickoff a
win would put them in good shape for another NFC East title. They
lost 22-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would probably agree that last week's loss was, for me
anyway, the most frustrating because of the way we lost,''
quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``And also because if we'd have won
that we would have been in the driver's seat in the division. We
had a real opportunity, and we didn't take advantage of that. It's
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the math still works for the Cowboys. Two wins, and they're
in the playoffs, as division champions or as a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't ask for a better opponent today. The Saints (2-12)
have lost their last five and 12 of their last 13. And they'll
start an NFL Europe quarterback who has not thrown a pass in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to play our best,'' Cowboys running back Emmitt
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of room for improvement. Aikman and the Cowboys'
pass offense have dropped to a season-worst 25th in the NFL. Aikman
started the season with a career-best five touchdown passes at
Washington. In the 13 games since, he has thrown only 11. Only nine
teams have thrown fewer. Also, the Cowboys lead the league in
penalties (118) and penalty yards (1,054).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got deeper issues than penalties,'' Smith said.
``We have yet to convert on third-and-short. That's been an issue.
That's been a problem. Then you add that on top of the penalties
and you have what we are right now, 7-7. In my opinion, we haven't
shown that we're a good enough team to overcome those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Smith, who will head to another Pro Bowl in
February, has rushed for 1,165 yards and 10 touchdowns and averages
4.1 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of us having a defensive game like last season are
slim and none,'' said Saints coach Mike Ditka of New Orleans' 22-3
win in which the Cowboys were held to eight yards rushing. ``Not
that we won't try. But the offense has to do their job, and the
defense has to do their job. Yeah, it would be good to stop the
running game, but I don't see that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't seen that happen all season. The Saints, who traded
their entire draft to get Texas running back Ricky Williams, fall
near the bottom of the league in almost every category. The defense
is ranked 21st of the 31 teams. The offense is 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, expected back in the lineup after a four-week absence,
has suffered injuries to his left ankle, right elbow and left big
toe.
</P>
<P>
   But the passing game frustrates Ditka the most. Ditka will try
yet another quarterback this week. Fourth-stringer Jake Delhomme, a
second-year player out of Southwestern Louisiana (now
Louisiana-Lafayette), will be the seventh starting quarterback in
Ditka's three seasons in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday can't get here fast enough,'' Delhomme said. ``It's a
dream come true to play on national TV against the Cowboys. If I go
out and have fun, we're going to have fun, play loose and just let
it go. I'm not looking at this as pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
