<HEADLINE>
KINGS KEEP AN EYE ON OILERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kings held their final practice on Thursday at Iceoplex
before the two-day Christmas break. They will not reassemble until
the morning before Sunday's game against Pacific Division leading
Phoenix, but coach Andy Murray also has his mind on another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are only three points ahead of Edmonton for the eighth and
final playoff spot,'' he said. ``We are taking them very seriously.
They struggled early in the season and we have been struggling.
It's exciting, but it's better when you build yourself a little
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Kings had a 12-point lead on Edmonton, which
faced Northwest Division rival Calgary on Thursday night. The Kings
were 10 points ahead of the Mighty Ducks and eight in front of the
defending Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings and Ducks now are tied for last in the Pacific with 39
points, but both would qualify for the postseason if the season
ended today.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings were outscored 23-8 in a three-game
stretch last week, Phoenix also dropped five of six before routing
the Ducks 8-2 on Wednesday. The Coyotes came into that game after
losing 6-0 to St. Louis at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is consistency,'' said captain Rob
Blake. ``You see how tight everything is. You need to come out
every night with a strong effort. We played better (Wednesday vs.
San Jose) but we still lost. Playing better doesn't mean anything
unless you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the lopsided victory at Anaheim, the Coyotes remain on
shaky ground. They learned Wednesday they will lose veteran second
line left-winger Greg Adams for four weeks after undergoing surgery
for his sinuses.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was named the top player against the Ducks when he had two
goals and one assist.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!All-Star voting:!off! A poor showing the past week plus a
season of injuries will not help the Kings get players into the
Feb.6 All-Star game at Toronto between North American players and
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy Palffy, among the league scoring leaders until missing
four games with a bad back, should make the European squad. But
Michigan-native Bryan Smolinski, who has 33 points in 34 games
including a goal Wednesday, it not even listed in the top 15 on the
North American club. Blake is second in voting (298,466) for North
America. Left winger Luc Robitaille (167,603) is
seventh.!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
