<HEADLINE>
A FIREBRAND WHO SEEMED TO LOSE HIS SPARK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (With NY-CREW-EDUC, NY-CREW-MAYOR) 
(rk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just a year ago, Rudy Crew seemed poised to be the
first chancellor in years to make a lasting difference on New York
City's public schools. From the time he arrived from the
comparatively tiny Tacoma, Wash., embraced by almost everyone in
New York's troubled and politically divided system, he promised
quick results and often seemed to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   He wrested substantial control from corrupt and incompetent
community school boards. He talked about setting higher standards.
He ousted bad principals and took over schools that had abjectly
failed their children, promising to turn them around. He gave hope
that one man could move a huge bureaucracy to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after months of Hamletlike indecision, the one-time
giant came crashing down, after his own board rejected his plea for
public affirmation as symbolized by his request for a long-term
contract, more money and higher benefits. As he fell _ going from
hero to a figure some saw as tragic _ he was publicly excoriated by
some politicians and board members who had once been his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   As word of his ouster became public Thursday, virtually no one _
from parents at the schoolhouse gate to union leaders to academics
and educators _ publicly begged him to stay. In seclusion with his
children in his official town house in Brooklyn Thursday, he stood
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's real sad,'' said Arthur Levine, the president of
Teachers College at Columbia University and a sometime Crew
confidant. ``I'm still a very big fan of his. There aren't a lot of
excellent urban school superintendents in America, and I thought
New York had the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, there are two views of what happened. One
espoused by Crew and his associates is that in standing up for
public education _ opposing the national movement toward school
vouchers and warning of the risks of charter schools _ he became
the target of Gov. George Pataki and, more importantly, of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who controlled a majority of votes on the Board
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The other view is that he came in with a grand vision of taking
control of the city's huge school system, executed it through pure
chutzpah and a network of unions and legislators, then tripped over
the delicate and difficult work of taking his hard-won powers and
improving the schools.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever led to his demise, supporters and detractors all
say that with more political skill and sheer stomach for the fight,
Crew could have salvaged his job. Giuliani, his aides say, was
genuinely torn about Crew, and was looking for signals that the
chancellor was willing to work with him. The mayor had hounded out
a previous chancellor, Ramon Cortines, and a popular police
commissioner, William Bratton, and did not want to be perceived
again as a bully, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My perspective on the fall is that he brought this on
himself,'' said Raymond Domanico, education adviser for the Metro
Industrial Areas Foundation. ``I think to all observers he's been
drifting for a while, and his unwillingness to make a strong
commitment alienated sufficient numbers of the board to lead to his
downfall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
