<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPLE LEAFS TOP DEVILS, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ This habit of losing the second of back-to-back games
has reached epidemic proportions for the New Jersey Devils. They
have played eight such games this season and have lost every one,
and by at least two goals. They suffered their eighth such loss on
Thursday night by 4-1 to the Toronto Maple Leafs, one of the
National Hockey League's elite teams again this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have lost such games even to lowly teams, with last
Sunday's loss to the New York Islanders and to Calgary earlier this
month the most vivid examples. It was after the loss to the
Islanders that several players, but not Coach Robbie Ftorek, said
they had a problem with the second of back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't play back-to-back games,'' Ftorek said tonight when
asked to analyze the reasons for this phenomenon. ``We play one
game at a time. I don't know why you keep beating a dead horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux, Lyle Odelein and Bobby Holik are three of the
players who have said the Devils had addressed the problem in team
meetings and private conversations in small groups. ``We talked
about it the last couple of days,'' Lemieux said before Thursday
night's game. ``Your legs can be going like crazy and you're
working hard, but if your brain is not working, it's all for
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux scored the goal for the Devils (19-12-3-2), who took 32
shots against Curtis Joseph at the Air Canada Center but had only a
handful of quality chances. Holik had five shots at Joseph, four in
the third period when the Devils showed signs of fatigue, perhaps
from beating the Philadelphia Flyers a night earlier in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux has been the most consistent goal scorer in recent games
for the Devils. He took the team lead in goals with 12 when he
opened the scoring on Thursday night with his fifth goal in the
past five games, 8 minutes 23 seconds into the game. Lemieux got
his goal when he skated into the slot and deflected Odelein's shot
from the right point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing O.K. until they scored that short-handed goal,''
Holik said of Igor Korolev's goal, which tied the game with 3:55
left in the first period. ``We played good for 20 minutes and then
we took some penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs (22-11-4-2) also got goals from Nik Antropov,
Jonas Hoglund and Dmitri Khristich for their fifth consecutive
victory. They took 20 shots against Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   There was little Brodeur could do on Antropov's fifth goal of
the season with 7:11 left in the second period, or on Hoglund's
power-play goal just over two minutes later that gave the Maple
Leafs a two-goal lead. Both scorers were wide open when they took
their shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
