<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-RECORDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS SHOW KC OFFICIALS KNEW BRIDGE WAS LIKELY HAZARD IN FLOODING
BEFORE 7 DEATHS IN '98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Months before floodwater swept seven persons
to their deaths off the Prospect Avenue Bridge on Oct. 4, 1998,
Kansas City officials knew the span was a likely hazard during
heavy flooding but did not tell the city's emergency managers,
court records filed Thursday show.
</P>
<P>
   The records, filed in Jackson County Circuit Court as part of a
civil lawsuit against the city, include memos written after the
flood, which killed 11 persons throughout the Kansas City area, and
excerpts from a deposition with the city's emergency management
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The memos suggest that city officials had learned the summer
before the flood that computer models had identified the bridge as
a potential hazard. Deposition excerpts show the city's emergency
management coordinator was not told of the threat ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom at City Hall before the flood was that
channel work completed since 1977 had virtually eliminated the
threat of dangerous flooding along Brush Creek. But even though
preliminary computer modeling challenged that belief, the city did
little to address an immediate threat, lawyers argue.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Smith, who filed the documents on behalf of
families who lost relatives on the bridge, said that, used
properly, the hazard information on the bridge could have saved
seven lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had five minutes and one barricade, that's where they
would have placed it,'' Smith said in an interview. ``This modeling
study showed them exactly where they needed to go. There wasn't any
guesswork. It would have prevented all those people who died on the
bridge from driving on the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the city and its employees, City Manager Bob
Collins declined to comment on Thursday's filings, saying that
neither he nor the city's lawyers had yet reviewed them.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that the city was working hard to correct
existing flood hazards along Brush Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of places that are still floodable,''
Collins said. ``Not all of the improvements were available at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the flood, the city and the Fire Department have moved to
improve emergency planning and eliminate flood hazards along Brush
Creek, including laying plans to remove and replace the Prospect
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In an Oct. 28, 1998, memo to Laurie Spoon-Potter, press aide to
then-Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, Public Works Director Ed Wolf said that
computer modeling had shown the bridge to be at risk during heavy
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This computer modeling has not yet been completed, but
preliminary results which became available this summer did show
that the water level during a major flood event such as the one we
had in 1977 and similar to the one that we had on Oct. 4 would be
over the Prospect Avenue Bridge,'' Wolf wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf noted that the city responded to the threat in summer 1998
by opening negotiations with the state to share the cost of
removing and replacing the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was written in response to questions from constituents
who had called the mayor's office seeking help in recovering from
the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon-Potter, who no longer works for the city, said copies of
Wolf's memo were distributed to staff in the mayor's office to help
them answer questions from the public. She said she did not
distribute it to reporters covering the flood aftermath because
they didn't ask for it. She said she didn't recall reading it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do constituent services, but I probably wouldn't have
read it because my focus was (reporters),'' Spoon-Potter said. ``If
you guys weren't asking for it, I wasn't focusing on it because it
wasn't part of my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hadn't seen the modeling studies Wolf described in
his memo, but had asked the city for them.
</P>
<P>
   One person who said she didn't see the preliminary hazard
reports before the flood was Julie Llorente, the city's emergency
management coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Llorente, who was employed by the Fire Department, said she
first learned of the modeling at her deposition in the civil case
last June.
</P>
<P>
   During the deposition, she acknowledged that such information
could have been valuable had she known it before the flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had you had that information, ma'am, would you have done
anything differently, with regard to your job as the emergency
preparedness coordinator, on Oct. 4, 1998?'' a lawyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe reminded people, the fire chief specifically, that they
thought there might be a problem,'' Llorente replied. ``I don't
really know. It's hard to say what...''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's information you would have liked to have had on Oct. 4,
1998, that (the) Prospect bridge was a dangerous spot?'' the lawyer
followed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would have been good to know that, yes,'' Llorente
said.
</P>
<P>
   That day, the National Weather Service issued a warning of
imminent flash flooding about 3 p.m. Almost 3 inches of rain fell
in the Brush Creek watershed between 7 and 8 p.m. Friends and
relatives of the seven who perished said the victims were swept
from the tops of their cars and into the creek about 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After the flood, articles in The Kansas City Star revealed that
an unplugged radio decoder had crippled an electronic flood-warning
system on Brush Creek, that the city never had budgeted money to
maintain the system and that the city had no contingency plans for
flooding on the creek.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent report by City Auditor Mark Funkhouser spurred
further improvements in the city's emergency planning, including
elevating Llorente to the city manager's office to better
coordinate citywide disaster response.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's filing was a change in strategy for lawyers
representing the families of those killed on the bridge. In an
amended lawsuit, the families argue that by systematically ignoring
the possibility of deadly flooding on Brush Creek, the city
violated their loved ones' constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Such an argument could force the case out of state court and
into federal court. If successful, the move also could remove a
$100,000 cap on damages the city could pay to the families of each
victim.
</P>
<P>
   The families combined now are seeking more than $100 million in
damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-23-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
