<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-23 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-AIRPORT-CLOSING-KAN &LR;      12-23 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-CLOSING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA APPROVES CLOSING OF RICHARDS-GEBAUR AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY and ROBERT CARROLL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The runway lights at Richards-Gebaur Memorial
Airport could go dark Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Thursday granted Kansas
City permission to close the airport to make way for an intermodal
rail hub operated by Kansas City Southern Railway.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council must approve the closing first. Councilwoman
Teresa Loar, chairwoman of the Aviation Committee, said Thursday
that she was confident approval would come early next week, perhaps
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So on the final day of the year, the airport that opened in 1941
and later served 40 years as an Air Force base, is expected to
close to air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Russell Widmar, Kansas City aviation director,
the FAA wrote that Kansas City ``is hereby released from its
obligations to maintain the Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport
property for aeronautical use.''
</P>
<P>
   The approval is based partly on Kansas City's commitment to
study options for a replacement airfield in the area.
</P>
<P>
   City officials praised the FAA's decision. Since well before
voters approved the project in August, officials had been
frustrated by opponents who fought to keep the airport open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time coming, but we are ready to move,'' Loar
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted _ it's what we expected,'' said Phil Brown,
deputy director of the city's Aviation Department.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents were not ready to fold.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McDermott, president of Friends of Richards-Gebaur Airport,
vowed Thursday to continue the fight, perhaps with a lawsuit or
another petition. An earlier petition led to an election in August
in which voters approved the intermodal plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means are we ready to give up,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   His stance did not surprise Loar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few in opposition will continue to try and stop this,''
Loar said. ``But the citizens have voted. The council has voted,
and now the FAA has given approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the new leases held no surprises, but he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In granting approval, FAA officials cited an Aug. 6, 1999,
letter from Mayor Kay Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Barnes told the FAA that the city intended to
proceed with a plan for a replacement airport at or near the
Richards-Gebaur site.
</P>
<P>
   Loar recently said the FAA's approval had been delayed by
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way government works,'' she said. ``And it's slow
going when you have to work with so many agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for Kansas City Southern to operate a
rail-to-truck freight facility at the airport site. Trains from
Mexico would arrive at the intermodal hub, and the goods would be
transported to trucks for delivery elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents called the arrangement was a ``sweetheart deal'' for
Kansas City Southern and said that the city was throwing away a
perfectly good airport. They also said the city's freeway system
would wilt under additional truck traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters countered that the city could not afford not to take
advantage of its location on the so-called ``NAFTA Highway.'' They
contend that the intermodal hub could make Kansas City a major
player in international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's FAA approval came none too soon for supporters.
</P>
<P>
   There was concern that Kansas City Southern might abandon the
plan if FAA approval was delayed much longer. The railroad had made
clear its desire to have a car-handling facility in operation for
Mazda in April.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern official Warren Erdman had said earlier
that the railroad had no date at which it would abandon the
project, but, ``obviously the longer the wait, the less optimistic
you become.''
</P>
<P>
   Erdman could not be reached Thursday for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
