<HEADER>
A8181 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     12-23 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN OF THE COUNTDOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a scale of 1-to-10, the quality and variety of
the media-generated sports-related end of the
year/decade/century/millennium lists we've sifted through in 1999
has been a rather unresounding 5.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the number of lists we actually found interesting
enough to read all the way through.
</P>
<P>
   As much as folks complain about the abundance of them, the
gripes might be better aimed at the lack of inspiration that seems
to drive these lists. With our inherent need to organize and
prioritize, why do most of these lists seem so sanitized?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because they've been group efforts. Publications and TV
networks get input from a huge panel of in-house voters, which may
turn out to be more fair and representative _ and avoid the
embarrassment of things falling through the cracks _ but the
results are without much passion. The Associated Press has been
cranking out sport-by-sport top-athlete lists lately, but their
strange-sized body of ``expert'' voters ends up with strange
compromises.
</P>
<P>
   In making our list of the best lists this year, based on
entertainment and information value plus the ability to make us sit
and think, we're going with this notable five:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Hockey News' 100 Most Colorful People in Hockey: Think of
how this idea could have been carried for any other sport _
baseball might have a top 1,000 list. That's why doing it with a
sport treated so reverentially it's a blast to find those who
rocked the boat and got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Topping this list in the Dec. 24 issue is Eddie ``The
Entertainer'' Shack. Ever heard of him? This part-timer for the
1965-66 Maple Leafs even had a song named for him called ``Clear
The Track, Here Comes Shack'' (not to give any certain Lakers
center any ideas). That song was atop the Toronto Top 40 charts for
nine straight weeks, ahead of anything by the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 is much more familiar _ the Carlson Brothers of the
Johnstown Jets, who inspired the Hansen Brothers of ``Slap Shot.''
The list also has the imagination to include two fictional TV
characters No. 27 (Eddie Lebec, the Jay Thomas character from
``Cheers'' who played goalie for the Boston Bruins) and No. 79
(NBC's Peter Puck), plus former Kings owner Bruce ``Brucie
Bigbucks'' McNall at No. 73.
</P>
<P>
   2. Keith Olbermann's ``Real'' 50 Greatest Athletes of the
Century: Inspired by the haphazard way in which his former
employer, ESPN, did its week-by-week horn-tooting over its
SportsCentury Greatest Athletes project, historian Olbermann
responded with his own compilation for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   First, he announced the guidelines, which ESPN never did. For
example, there are no horses for Olbermann because ``these must be
athletes who compete voluntarily.'' Social impact is considered as
much if not more than pure athletic ability _ ``sheer greatness''
counts the most.
</P>
<P>
   His list included George Mikan, Arthur Ashe, Steffi Graf, Pele,
Pete Maravich and Greg LeMond. ESPN had none of them in its top
100. ESPN's possible Nos. 1 and 2 guys, Muhammad Ali and Michael
Jordan, are Nos. 7 and 6 on Olbermann's list.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Olbermann finished his list by anointing Jackie
Robinson as his No. 1 guy (ESPN had Robinson at No. 15). As
Olbermann wondered: ``How much better might he have been had there
been no color line, or he had not been the first, or if even the
pressure been just a little less... or if he had not pursued his
fifth-best sport?''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann's list can be found online
(http://foxsports.com/columns/olbermann50/) with a special on Fox
Sports Net at 7 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   3. The Sporting News 100 Most Powerful People in Sports for the
20th Century: The Dec. 22 issue, which revealed its annual power
ranking, went another step and challenged itself to do a century
list. Former NFL commissioner Pete Rozelle came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, it also took the time to explain that its
definition of power meant someone who has the capability to effect
significant change _ or prevent significant change. Its subtly
different from ``influence'' and shouldn't be mistaken with
``innovative,'' ``popular,'' ``famous'' or winning championships.
</P>
<P>
   By that, we have people like Branch Rickey (No. 4) preceding
Jackie Robinson (No. 21). And there's Al Davis (No. 31), Howard
Cosell (No. 47), and Don King (No. 49) getting their due as well,
like 'em or not.
</P>
<P>
   4. Sports Illustrated's Top 50 athletes by state vs. USA Today's
Top five athletes state-by-state: Both lists came out this week.
Put 'em side by side, and it's one big mess Rand McNally couldn't
clean up.
</P>
<P>
   In its Dec. 27 year-end double issue, SI has decided that an
athlete should be designated to a state where they first showed
flashes of greatness. USA Today's list, compiled by freelance
writer Lance Gould for Wednesday's edition, stays true to actual
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Which means Granada Hills-reared John Elway is No. 8 on SI's
California poll, but No. 1 in USA Today's Washington poll since
that happened to be the place where his parents lived when he was
born. It also creates wackiness like Joe Louis scoring No. 1 on
SI's Michigan list and Carl Lewis landing No. 1 on SI's New Jersey
list, but USA Today put both of them in Alabama _ Louis (No. 3) and
Lewis (No. 5) behind Hank Aaron and Jesse Owens with Willie Mays in
at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   5. The National Examiner's Top 100 Scandals of the Century: O.J.
Simpson's domestic situation came in second. Tied. With Bill
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. What could have possibly been bigger?
The editors decided it was when Eddie Fisher left Debbie Reynolds
to marry her best friend Elizabeth Taylor in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Egads.
</P>
<P>
   The sports crimes and misdemeanors that were crazy enough to
make this list are impressive _ the Black Sox Scandal (No. 11),
Tonya Harding-Nancy Kerrigan (No. 24), Jim Thorpe stripped of his
Olympic gold medals for having played semi-pro baseball (No. 35),
Marv Albert's sexcapades (No. 36) and Mike Tyson's rape conviction
(No. 98).
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Williams, who recently married Lakers forward Rick Fox,
came in at No. 92. But for much different reasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   _After exhaustive research through memorabilia stores, personal
collections and library files, we've found our Sports Illustrated
cover of the century: July 14, 1969 featuring O.J. Simpson under
the headline ``To Play or Not to Play?: O.J. Cools It In
Hollywood.'' He just won the Heisman Trophy at USC, but was already
holding out from the NFL's Buffalo Bills, who drafted him.
According to Frank Deford's story inside headlined ``Ready If You
Are, O.J.,'' Juice was considering a full-time acting career if the
Bills didn't come up with the bills. Deford writes that Simpson was
acting in ``a new CBS-TV series with the stirring title of `Medical
Center''' as he waited to see if the Bills would meet his demand
for a five-year, $650,000 deal, plus a $500,000 loan. Bills owner
Ralph Wilson countered with a $250,000 deal over five years. Deford
quotes Juice's response: ``I don't like to be pushed.'' &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   _Oliver Stone says you'll never watch football the same after
enduring his much-hyped flick ``Any Given Sunday,'' which came out
Wednesday, but that's ground that NFL Films already covered 20
years ago. The hits, the grunts, the violent body slams _ it's like
one long MTV music video that is definitely a visual and audio
thrill ride for a big screen. But does it make some sort of
statement? Hardly. For as much controversy as it stirred up in its
creative process, there's nothing more here than stylistic
mishmash, trying to get you to believe the Miami Sharks are an NFL
team in the legacy of Lombardi instead of some old USFL team.
Considering Stone plasters his own mug throughout as a TV analyst
(occasionally throwing down some hard liquor and high-fiving the
play-by-play man), the real conspiracy here is how he continues to
make these vanity movies palatable to the public. In this case,
it's the audience participation in trying to identify as many
ex-NFLers and other celebrities as can possibly be crammed into one
movie. Oh, and for a post script: There's not enough Jamie Fox
throwing up. &QL; 
_Our first clue that ESPN's SportsCentury list will be topped by
Muhammad Ali is that ESPN Classic airs the six-part, seven-hour
original production ``The Fights and Times of Muhammad Ali'' on
Christmas Day from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m. ESPN's profile of Nos. 3 and 4
are today from 7-8 p.m., while Nos. 2 and 1 air on an ABC special
Sunday at 5 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
