<SLUG> BC-ASHES-CAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF CAR ADDS TO PAIN OF WIDOW AND HER GRANDCHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Last week Jewel Napier lost her husband to
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   This week she almost lost his cremated remains when a thief
stole her car.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves burned the 1997 Dodge Neon, leaving it a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters found the flaming car Wednesday and extinguished
the blaze. Her husband's remains were not damaged, but Napier now
is left to raise two grandchildren by herself with no car.
</P>
<P>
   She owes more on the car than it is worth, and her husband had
no life insurance when he died, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had been married 20 years. Jim Napier, 57, was
diagnosed with diabetes after a stroke in 1992 and retired early.
</P>
<P>
   He cared for two grandchildren, now ages 7 and 8, when their
mother no longer could. Jewel Napier, 63, held a full-time job as a
housekeeper and nanny as well as baby-sitting jobs on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the primary child-care giver,'' Napier said. ``He did
really well with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But his condition worsened, and he began dialysis in August. He
died unexpectedly in his sleep Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   He had always told his wife he did not want a big funeral. He
just wanted to be cremated. As it turned out, she could not afford
a big funeral anyway.
</P>
<P>
   She had him cremated and took his remains last weekend to
Buckner, where she staged a memorial at a nephew's house. Napier
returned from the trip to her house in the area of 25th Street and
Hardesty Avenue with the cremains in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I left the cremains in the trunk,'' she said.
``I guess I didn't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she planned to bury the cremains in her in-laws' plot
in Excelsior Springs around the time of her husband's birthday in
April.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday morning, the car, with the remains, was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a panic,'' Napier said. ``It was just the thought of
not knowing where his remains were.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday firefighters were called to a burning car at 22nd
Street and Denver Avenue. It was towed to the city's salvage lot,
and police called Napier.
</P>
<P>
   The cremains were intact because the fire had not reached the
trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Napier's financial situation has friends worried. She works as a
housekeeper and nanny for Jackson County Circuit Judge Jay
Daugherty and his wife, Lyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine all these terrible things happening to her all
at once,'' Lyn Daugherty said.
</P>
<P>
   The Daughertys are working through their church to set up a fund
for Napier. The Rev. Robert Cueni at the Country Club Christian
Church is overseeing the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a wonderful person,'' Lyn Daugherty said. ``We call her
Our Jewel. She's always donating things to people even though she
doesn't have much herself. Folks at her church donate clothes for
the grandchildren, and when they're finished with the clothes, she
always tries to recycle them to someone else needy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Napier even donated all of her husband's medical
equipment to a needy woman at church the day after he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always thinking of others, even at this difficult time
in her life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
