u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS     12-23 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS GAIN BRAGGING RIGHTS OVER RANGERS WITH A GAME TO BOAST
ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Although the New York Rangers have not been
very good in recent seasons, their fans could always say that at
least they were better than the New York Islanders. Almost everyone
else in the NH L was better than the Islanders, so why should their
nearest neighbors be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, with about half the capacity crowd at Nassau
Coliseum cheering for each team, the Islanders finally were better
than the Rangers. For the first time in their last nine meetings,
the Islanders emerged with a victory, this one by a score of 4-2.
In the other eight games, the Rangers have seven victories and
there has been one tie.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lapointe scored twice for the Islanders. Jan Hlavac
scored twice for the Rangers, who fired 38 shots on goal, 17 in the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders took their first two-goal lead at 10 minutes 25
seconds of the third period while short-handed when Jorgen Jonsson
scored, wristing a high shot over Rangers goalie Mike Richter after
a pass from Niklas Andersson to put the Islanders up 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The play began up ice when Zdeno Chara, the big Islanders
defenseman, forced the puck off the stick of Theo Fleury, the
smaller right wing of the Rangers. Their individual battle had been
a significant subplot to an interesting match in a building filled
with loud and excited fans.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive in goal for the Islanders was Kevin Weekes, who
seemed nervous early but got sharper as the evening progressed. He
made 36 saves, 17 in the third period, when the Rangers dominated.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a sellout, rare for this building, where current
ownership has slashed payroll while making little attempt to
assemble a team that can compete at the major-league level. Coming
into the game, the Islanders' record of 7-19-5 gave them 19 points,
tied with the expansion Atlanta Thrashers for worst in the 28-team
league.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first game against the Islanders for Rich Pilon, the
Rangers defenseman who moved from Long Island to Manhattan on Dec.
1 in a waiver deal. Pilon, in his 12th season, was honored by a
video presentation on the scoreboard in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some great young guys and they're going to be
great hockey players,'' Pilon said of the Islanders. When someone
asked about the lack of veteran leadership in the Islanders locker
room, Pilon responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my problem. It's the Islanders' problem. I've got
friends over there. They want to win. It puts a lot of pressure on
a couple of guys who shouldn't have that pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the lineup for the Rangers was Valery Kamensky, a right
wing who had played in only nine games this season because of
problems with his right arm. It was his first game since Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Playing goal for the first time as an Islander was Weekes, who
was obtained on Sunday in a multiplayer trade with Vancouver that
sent goalie Felix Potvin to the Canucks. Weekes played twice
against the Rangers earlier this season and won both times.
</P>
<P>
   After two periods, the Islanders held a 3-2 lead. The pace of
play was fast, the action rollicking and rough. The Rangers had the
edge in goaltending over the first 40 minutes, as the Islanders had
better scoring chances. Weekes looked uncertain on several shots,
and Hlavac's second goal came on a strange carom, on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-6-inch Fleury bothered the 6-9 Chara the way a mouse
might torment an elephant. When the NHL's tallest and shortest
players bumped for the fifth or sixth time, late in the second
period, Chara knocked Fleury down with a clean check. Fleury
responded with a two-handed slash.
</P>
<P>
   He got a minor penalty for it and Chara remained on the ice,
kneeling as if in pain. Fleury, apparently suspecting that Chara
was milking the moment, charged toward him, shouting, and had to be
restrained. When he took his seat on the penalty bench, Fleury
threw his gloves against the glass.
</P>
<P>
   The best hit of the period _ and one of the best of the season _
was a hip check thrown by Jamie Rivers of the Islanders against
Eric Lacroix of the Rangers, which flipped him up and over and down
on the ice. An interference penalty was called against Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Lapointe's two goals both took advantage of turnovers at the
blue line by Kim Johnsson of the Rangers. Lapointe scored his first
on a backhand, the second with a forehand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
