r a BC-SANTA-SECRET-KAN &LR;      12-23 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-SECRET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 28 YEARS, MAN REPAYS KINDNESS THAT GOT HIM STARTED AS SECRET
SANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sixty-nine-year-old Jerry Brooks sauntered
through a Kansas City thrift store Thursday seeking warm clothing
for less than 75 cents, which was all the money in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Secret Santa struck.
</P>
<P>
   Dashing through the aisle in a red flannel shirt, Santa pushed a
crisp hundred-dollar bill into Brooks' hand, wished him ``Merry
Christmas,'' and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' mouth fell open. He planned to pay 45 cents for a winter
scarf. Now he could get a heavy coat, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well!'' he exclaimed. ``I don't even know that man. He gave me
$100. God. I can't believe that. Lor-r-r-d have mercy. I don't know
where he came from, but if he doesn't live to be 500, I'll eat my
hat.''
</P>
<P>
   The glow on Secret Santa's face was even brighter, for numerous
reasons. He's celebrating his 20th anniversary of helping others
anonymously. He's giving away more than normal: a whopping $85,000,
including some special gifts planned today.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, before spreading Ben Franklin's face around
Kansas City, Secret Santa repaid a gentleman who rescued Santa from
a dire situation nearly three decades ago. And he repaid him with
more interest than even Uncle Sam charges.
</P>
<P>
   That story begins in 1971 in Houston, Miss., a small county
seat.
</P>
<P>
   The man-who-would-become-Santa was a young salesman then. Every
week, his employer sent him a paycheck, paid rent on a small office
and paid for Young Santa to stay at a local motel. One day, the
employer went out of business but neglected to tell Young Santa.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his motel room for nonpayment, Santa slept in the
car eight nights. He kept waiting for a paycheck that never
arrived. Out of gas and money, Santa turned to a local church for
assistance. But the person who oversaw a fund to help poor people
was gone the day he inquired.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Santa walked into the Dixie Diner, a small
brick cafe around the corner from Walgreens. Having not eaten for
nearly two days, he ordered a huge breakfast, slowly sipped coffee
refills and planned how he could escape without paying. Finally, he
feigned losing his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The owner _ who was the cook, the waiter and the cashier _
lifted a counter top door, walked behind Young Santa's
leather-covered stool, reached toward the floor and acted as if he
had picked up something.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must have dropped this,'' the owner said, handing the
young man $20. Santa's heart was pounding as he paid, left a tip,
raced outside and pushed his car to a gas station before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   As he drove away, Young Santa thought about how fortunate he
was. Suddenly, it occurred to him that no one had dropped that
money. ``Cookie'' behind the counter knew he was in trouble and
helped in a way that allowed him to keep his dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm ever in a position to help other people,'' Santa told
himself, ``that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Santa rode a Greyhound bus to Kansas City,
where he found a sales job and continued living from paycheck to
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   One cold day shortly before Christmas 1979, he pulled up to a
little drive-in restaurant in Independence. The carhop looked so
cold and miserable, Santa decided to give her the change from $20.
Her face glowed.
</P>
<P>
   Santa smiled. He went to his bank and withdrew more money. He
didn't have a lot to give then, but his spree had begun.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Santa, who has become a successful Jackson County
businessman, hands out $50,000 or more during each of his Christmas
campaigns. In Santa's own words, he has become a man ``who gets his
thrills by filling people's pockets with hundred-dollar bills.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's never forgotten the person who got him started.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Santa asked a friend to help locate the Mississippi
diner owner. After learning the man's name, Santa debated a whole
year whether to call _ and how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Retired diner owner Ted Horn baked some cakes last weekend in
anticipation of receiving visitors from Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A Missouri gentleman had called about research he was doing on
Chickasaw County, Miss., where Horn ran a 28-seat diner for two
decades. Today, Horn still awakes at 3:30 a.m., the time he used to
rise to open his Houston-based diner by 4:30 a.m. Now 81, Horn
lives in a modest blond brick ranch home 35 miles to the north in
Tupelo, the birthplace of Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Horn was sitting in his living room with his two children and
his wife when the ``researcher'' walked in Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Horn held in his lap a magazine article about Kansas City's
Secret Santa. The article mentioned Santa receiving help in a
Houston diner. Horn knew it had been his diner.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher took a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm that guy who was there 28 years ago,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   Horn, who had hoped to meet Secret Santa some day, smiled. He
just had.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the diner, about Houston, about how Horn also
used to run a food truck and offered food to people too poor to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Santa pulled two books, a Royals cap and Chiefs cap out of his
gift bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you reckon that twenty-dollar bill is worth today?''
he then asked. ``Do you know how to figure net present value? I had
somebody figure that for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Santa could tell Horn the answer (roughly $120), Horn
gave a response that fit right into Santa's plans: ``To me, that
$20 bill then was probably like $10,000 to you today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny you should say that number,'' Santa said as he pulled
out an envelope thick with $100 bills. ``See what's in that
envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not that much money,'' Horn said. ``You don't owe
me nothing!''
</P>
<P>
   The cash was wrapped by a strip of paper that said, ``$10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good God,'' Horn whispered.
</P>
<P>
   To save Horn from gift taxes, which kick in at $10,000, Santa
pulled out one bill and gave it to Horn's wife, Ruby. That left
Horn with $9,900.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't have to do this,'' Horn said softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to,'' Santa replied, smiling. ``You never know
what one little act of kindness will do for somebody. It can change
their whole life, and it changed mine. When I got out on the road
after getting gas, I figured out what you did....''
</P>
<P>
   Santa's voice broke, and he stopped talking for a moment. The
emotion he had tried to hide was bubbling to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been for you,'' Santa eventually continued, ``I
might have ended up in some jailhouse somewhere, because a hungry
man sometimes will do desperate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching in the living room, Horn's children grew glassy eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this,'' David Horn said. ``For this man to
come down and do this for my father _ it's almost more than we can
bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa offered to take Horn in his red sleigh (a rented Ford
Explorer) for a quick trip to Houston. The diner was right were
Santa remembered. Though a battered neon sign still says ``Dixie
Diner,'' food no longer is served. Instead, patrons receive
haircuts for $5.
</P>
<P>
   They ate lunch at Moore's Restaurant across town, then Santa
began giving out cash. The waitresses and cooks at the restaurant
screamed in joy first. Then Santa visited a laundry, a Sonic and,
finally, the barber working inside the old diner.
</P>
<P>
   Horn watched in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Ruby, has battled cancer, a broken hip and a broken
leg. Now she has Alzheimer's disease. Horn, who will care for her
as long as he can, plans to save the Santa's gift for the day she
must enter a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no nursing home insurance,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kansas City on Thursday, Santa headed out with wads of
$100 in his pockets. His first stop: Nick and Betty's Cafe on
Stadium Drive.
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years, Nick and Betty Nichols were cooking their last
meals and closing for retirement. A new owner will reopen in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Santa had to stop in. After all, Nick used to let him run a tab
at his cafe in 1971, when Santa was a poor salesman. He gave money
to the customers, employees and the Nichols' children, who were
there to savor the cafe's last day.
</P>
<P>
   Waitress Kim Hoy cried when Santa provided $100. Then Santa gave
her two more bills, one for each of her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't handle this,'' Hoy said between sobs. ``This is the
first Christmas without my mom. I wasn't looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa then searched Kansas City streets for other needy people.
He found them standing by an old pickup truck, waiting at bus
stops, walking on a sidewalk, sitting in grocery store parking
lots, buying gas and shopping in that thrift store.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Birdsong, a homeless woman, nearly fainted when Santa gave
her $300 on a Truman Road sidewalk. Her fiance, Cecil Jones,
clutched her around the waist to keep her from falling down. He
also received $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not staying in a (vacant) house tonight,'' Birdsong
said. ``I want to get an apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Two men promised to forward Santa's gift to their church.
</P>
<P>
   Most planned to use their newfound money for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless you!'' retired electrician Ivan Mullen, 71, yelled
after Santa outside Thriftway on Truman Road. Mullen had just
purchased $10 in groceries and needed the money to pay for siding
and porch work on his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you,'' he said in a shaky voice, ``there really is a
God in this world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
