</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA, PLEASE ADD THESE TO YOUR LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Dear Santa: When you're packing up the sleigh with
goodies tonight, there are some people hereabouts who deserve the
best you can send their way. Anything you can do in their behalf
would be greatly appreciated. Please bring:
</P>
<P>
   - Chiefs fans: Victories over Seattle and Oakland, to send them
into the NFL playoffs with a full head of steam.
</P>
<P>
   - Downtown boosters: A sparkplug leader to succeed Nick
Bashkiroff as designated keeper of Stan Durwood's dream for the
Power &AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   - Royals fans: An effective bullpen and a new owner with deep
pockets and an ironclad commitment to keeping major league baseball
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   - Miles Prentice: The thanks of a grateful city for stepping
forward to organize an aspiring Royals ownership group when nobody
else would, and thus forcing the hand of other would-be buyers who
otherwise might have been content to sit on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   - Bill Esrey: A continued presence in Kansas City overseeing
Sprint's local growth, even if his company eventually becomes part
of another corporate empire.
</P>
<P>
   - Bernie Ebbers: The wisdom to keep Sprint's headquarters here
if his MCI WorldCom acquires one of the Kansas City area's
corporate crown jewels.
</P>
<P>
   - Sprint employees: Job security.
</P>
<P>
   - Don Pipes: Blue skies and tailwinds during his well-deserved
retirement after a lifetime of city-managing Overland Park's rise
to its status as one of Kansas' leading cities.
</P>
<P>
   - Local casinos: The respect they deserve for the vitality they
generate for the Kansas City area economy.
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas City's info-tech types: A quiet New Year's weekend with
no disaster to deal with as a result of Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   - Union Station activists: The thanks and congratulations of a
grateful city for pulling off the miraculous rebirth of what's
arguably the city's most venerable landmark.
</P>
<P>
   - Science City: A glitch-free, prosperous new year.
</P>
<P>
   - The hopeless: Hope.
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas taxpayers: A Legislature that shows them some respect.
</P>
<P>
   - Kauffman Stadium: The respect it doesn't get from local
boosters who think an expensive new rounders playground is needed
for downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   - Oz Entertainment: A fair chance to do its thing and develop a
theme park-resort in Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   - The elderly: Caring companionship.
</P>
<P>
   - Overland Park restaurateurs: Surcease from the occasional
harassments of city government's self-appointed smoking police.
</P>
<P>
   - Smokers: The will to quit.
</P>
<P>
   - Merriam officials: Peace in policy pursuits and goodwill
toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas State fans: A bowl full of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   - The truly needy: A helping hand.
</P>
<P>
   - Local workers: Big annual raises and an unemployment rate that
keeps setting records on the downside.
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas City physicians: A Blue Cross//Blue Shield contract
they can live with.
</P>
<P>
   - Golfers everywhere: Fairways, greens and one-putts.
</P>
<P>
   - U.S. Postal Service: The thanks, as usual at this time of
year, of a grateful nation.
</P>
<P>
   - Friends and readers: Health, happiness and best wishes for a
wonderful 2000. Merry Christmas to all, and to all a good night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
